<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS TOP HEAT IN SEASON FINALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Coach Jeff Van Gundy ordered the scoreboards that
circle Madison Square Garden turned off. He wanted to prevent the
Knicks from peeking at their playoff fate, but the crowd had cell
phones and radios and members of the coaching staff had an official
whispering cliff-hanger updates into their ears.
</P>
<P>
   As Van Gundy stalked the sidelines, watching his makeshift team
play against the Heat's makeshift team on Wednesday night, he was
told the fourth-quarter score of the Philadelphia 76ers game
against the Pistons. The Pistons were up, 20 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping the disguise he had worn throughout the day and night,
Van Gundy mumbled a profanity under his breath. Privately, he had
to be pulling for the 76ers, knowing a victory by them assured the
Knicks of a first-round playoff series against the Miami Heat. This
was the team that was built by Pat Riley as a reflection of the
Knicks, a team they matched up well against and a rival that always
pulled out the gritty best from them no matter what the
circumstances. With Patrick Ewing, without Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   This was the team that gave the Knicks the best chance to erase
the turmoil of a disappointing season and prop up the job security
of all involved. The Pacers were trouble if they faced them as the
seventh seed, but where there was Heat, there was hope.
</P>
<P>
   And then destiny made the matchup so. The 76ers rallied, and
poured it on against the Pistons and took the game in overtime. And
so it was done. Just before 10 p.m., before the fourth quarter
began toward the conclusion of a meaningless, 101-88, victory by
the Kncks, the issue had been decided.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had been granted their very secret wish. The
eighth-seeded Knicks will face the top-seeded Heat in the first
round of the National Basketball Association playoffs beginning
with Game 1 Saturday at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A faint echo of ``Beat the Heat'' rang out briefly. And several
fans in the know shouted out warning to the Heat bench: We're
coming to get you. We're coming to get you, Riley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series is beyond everyone's control,'' Riley said after
the final regular-season game was over. ``This is the way it has to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Against a backdrop of two fights in two post-season meetings,
amid the intense nature of the rivalry that dilutes whatever
seeding numbers are assigned, the two will meet in the playoffs for
the third time in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know what intensity this series brings,'' said Larry
Johnson, who has been suspended twice over two years in playoff
games against the Heat. ``I can't say it'll be tense but nothing
like what happened before is going to happen again. I don't think
so. I think the playoffs are a whole new ball game. I think we can
make waves and erase the bad taste of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of these teams know each other so well. What? This is the
third time in three years. To be honest, there are four or five
cats over there that are friends of mine because we've played each
other so much. We're not a typical eighth seed. This is not a
typical one-versus-eight matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   The game that was played on Wednesday night was not a typical
Heat-Knicks game, either. Before the tip, there were motives,
conspiracy theories and intrigue in a scene that played out like a
game of Clue. But by the end of the night, it didn't matter who did
it in the Garden, or by what method.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy preached winning no matter what seeding his team ended
the night with, and he maintained that the integrity of the game
was important. Van Gundy used caution as he went for the victory
with the understanding that if the 76ers had lost, they would find
themselves with the seventh seeding and playing a very physical
Pacers team.
</P>
<P>
   With the Heat already assured of the top seeding in the East and
with the Knicks holding back to prevent key injuries, there was no
Patrick Ewing, no Chris Childs, no Alonzo Mourning, no Tim
Hardaway, no Dan Majerle. As the game wore on, the minutes of Allan
Houston and Larry Johnson were whittled down, too.
</P>
<P>
   In a game with no physical defense at all, where layups were
uncontested and jumpers were made in open space, the Knicks were
led by the 22 points of Marcus Camby and the 11 assists by the
reserve Rick Brunson. The Heat were led by Clarence Weatherspoon's
18 points and 12 by Voshon Lenard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played to win,'' Van Gundy said. ``I don't even look at the
other team. I'm just worried about our team. We went out to win. I
think every time you think you know what to expect, something
different crops up. We know we're going to be a heavy underdog and
we're going to have to go down there and play great.''
</P>
<P>
   Just to know they're going to face the Heat was uplifting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new season now,'' Houston said. ``We can regroup
physically and mentally. We have to pay attention to detail. When
we play well, especially defensively, we can beat anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Miami is number one. And they've earned that. They
were the best team in the East this year. But at the same time, we
know what we're capable of. We know we can play with them. We're
not going down there lacking confidence.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
