<SLUG> BC-BBC-LEHR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMBLE PAYS OFF FOR USC'S LEHR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Justin Lehr's desire for a trip to Omaha almost
got him a ticket to nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Lehr, now the No. 2 pitcher for the 18th-ranked USC baseball
team, would rather peek ahead at what appears to be a rosy future.
</P>
<P>
   But before all that was in place, Lehr took the unorthodox step
of transferring from UC Santa Barbara after his junior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been my dream to play in a College World Series in Omaha,
and I felt this was my best chance,'' Lehr said. ``I think the
transition has gone pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehr isn't speaking only of the transition to a new school. He
also switched positions -- from catcher to pitcher -- figuring it
was his best chance to play at the next level.
</P>
<P>
   All this after having been drafted in the 15th round by the
Detroit Tigers out of West Covina High School and in the 10th round
by the Angels after last season. Both teams wanted him as a catcher
first, although the Angels supposedly looked to turn him into a
closer down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a risky move on his behalf,'' said USC pitching coach
John Savage of Lehr's transfer. ``But there's some good people
here, and he's really taken advantage of the situation better than
anyone I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Lehr has become a major force on the Trojans'
pitching staff, despite the fact that his pitching career at this
level is still in its infancy.
</P>
<P>
   With the regular season winding down, Lehr is 6-1 with a 4.30
ERA and a team-leading 92 innings pitched, after this past
weekend's series against UCLA. He also has three saves, 91
strikeouts and only 35 walks.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to think that, as late as August, Lehr still
wasn't sure he would be a Trojan. The school didn't have a
scholarship to offer.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, USC still was awaiting the decision of third
baseman Sean Burroughs of Long Beach Wilson, who had committed to
the school but also was the first-round pick of the San Diego
Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still waiting to hear about that, when the Angels made
what they said was their final offer three days before,'' Lehr
said. ``I didn't know what I would do.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Lehr would have had his suitors had USC fallen through,
but days later, on the first day of classes, Burroughs signed with
USC and the spot opened. The postscript to this phase of the story
has had its excitement, but it certainly was a busy road getting
there.
</P>
<P>
   Lehr pitched in high school and also saw action on the mound at
UCSB, mostly as a closer or spot starter. Still, in all that time,
pitching never became a full-time passion for the 6-foot-1,
200-pound right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   This past summer, however, all that changed.
</P>
<P>
   Lehr spent time pitching for the Santa Barbara Foresters and
also working with pitching coach Brian York, who is a former major
league scout in his first year at Glendale Community College.
</P>
<P>
   York became aware of Lehr when Lehr played for the Baltimore
Orioles scout team in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the most sought-after catchers coming out,''
York said. ``And even now, he's still a very fine catcher.''
</P>
<P>
   When he isn't pitching for the Trojans, Lehr plays first base
and at designated hitter. Catching is mostly a memory, although he
is an emergency player at the position.
</P>
<P>
   Lehr and York hooked up through pitching coach Jim McDowell,
brother of Jack, and hitting instructor Craig Wallenbrock, one of
York's best friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, (Lehr's) a major league player,'' said York, who met
weekly with Lehr all summer at Chaminade High in West Hills.
</P>
<P>
   But there was plenty of work involved in the transition to
full-time pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we completely created his delivery,'' York said.
``We went through everything we could think of, throwing style,
videotaping from different angles, drills.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehr said his progress has been fast and steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've made a ton of progress, and I've picked up
the experience I need,'' Lehr said. ``It was a stressful situation
to make the decision to pitch all the time or whether I should
sign, but I'm glad the way it's worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Savage said Lehr arrived with a solid foundation and knowledge
of what it takes to be successful on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he already has a good feel how to set batters up and
finish them off,'' said Savage, who also credited Lehr's catching
experience as a plus. ``When he gets it all going, his performance
is pretty dominating.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case last Saturday against UCLA, when Lehr took a
2-0 lead into the ninth inning, only to see the Bruins rally
against the Trojans' bullpen for a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   When Lehr is at his best, he mixes in an 88-91 mph fastball with
a curve, a slider and an extremely effective changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one pitch (the changeup) that a lot of guys have a
tough time getting to be effective,'' Savage said.
</P>
<P>
   York said Lehr's pitching style resembles that of Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has those capabilities,'' York said. ``If he uses all of
his pitches, it makes them all better.''
</P>
<P>
   York is just glad things have worked out for Lehr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't believe how well it's worked out,'' York said.
``He hung in there and went through some emotional stress, which he
handled great . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kinds of things are difficult for a young man. They test
a person's character, and he came through with class, dignity and
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, the rest should be easy. Although it won't be, Lehr
has made it look that way so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
