<HEADLINE>
MISSING WOMAN'S FAMILY WAITS IN FEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. _ For almost 48 hours, Kara Wiese's family
prayed for word that their loved one, the mother of a 6-year-old
boy found wandering in the rubble, had been found.
</P>
<P>
   Then Wednesday night, authorities asked for Wiese's fingerprint
records. Her family feared the worst, especially after hearing
rumors that a woman's body had been found in this semirural
community 30 miles southwest of Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   The search for Wiese began almost immediately after authorities
found her son, Jordan, wandering near his home Monday night in the
ruins of the Southern Hills addition.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan told family members that he and his mother had sought
shelter in the bathroom of their mobile home when a deadly tornado
swept through town.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just ran and got in the bathroom real quick with Jordan,''
said Misty Dickson, who is engaged to Wiese's younger brother,
Dustin. ``Jordan says he put his arms around her and she put hers
around him and they held on real tight.''
</P>
<P>
   High winds ripped the trailer apart, sending both flying. Jordan
landed in a nearby ravine; his mother was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said, `I lost my mama. I couldn't find her,' '' said
Dickson, 21.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, authorities contacted the home of Wiese's
mother, Mary Wiese of El Reno. They asked family members to bring
fingerprints to the Oklahoma medical examiner's office.
</P>
<P>
   As Dustin Wiese made the trip to the medical examiner's office,
Dickson took care of Jordan, who was released from Southwest
Medical Center on Tuesday. The boy suffered a broken rib, and cuts
and bruises on his head, his left eye and his leg, as well as all
over his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said a tire hit him in the back,'' Dickson said. ``He got
pretty torn up, but he's OK. He just needs time to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   The kindergartner has been playing and frequently asks for his
mother, Dickson said. But the adults, although hopeful that Wiese
will be found alive, are realistic, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an emotional roller coaster,'' Dickson said.
</P>
<P>
   While the family was out Wednesday in the Bridge Creek community
where Wiese's mobile home once stood, a sheriff's deputy told them
that Wiese had been found alive and buried in rubble, Dickson said.
The news reached at least one local TV crew. Shortly thereafter,
officials returned and said the report was a mistake. No woman had
been found, they said.
</P>
<P>
   With Wednesday night's phone call, the roller coaster dipped
again, Dickson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want it to be her, because Jordan won't have anything
left _ not a mom, not a house,'' Dickson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson described Wiese as a wonderful mother who doted on
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did everything for Jordan. He had everything he needed.
She just hugged him all the time, said `Jordan, I love you,' woke
up every day and cooked him breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
