<SLUG> BC-VOL-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS GIDDY OVER RATELLE'S SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On any afternoon, a person could walk through the Long Beach
State athletic offices and hear administrators, coaches and
athletes talking up the success of a colleague.
</P>
<P>
   And there has been a lot of success to talk about, from Brian
Gimmillaro's three-time NCAA champion women's volleyball team to
Dave Snow's nationally-ranked baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   But there probably hasn't been a moment in the last five years
that has the department as giddy as Ray Ratelle and his men's
volleyball team making it to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   In the 49er family tree, Ratelle is the patriarch. The
59-year-old has been the men's head coach since 1982, making him
the dean of the staff, as well as a key player in the U.S. men's
national team development for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a colleague about Ratelle and words like gentleman,
professional, respectful, disciplined and humble will fly at you at
spiking speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say we've never felt so good about one person's
success as we do now for Ray,'' Long Beach State athletic director
Bill Shumard said. ``Ray is special around here. There will be more
people wanting him to succeed this weekend than we've ever had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray is what I'd call a throwback. He has a steady hand as a
coach. He's a disciplinarian and believes in strong academics, and
his teams have always been the leaders when it comes to support for
other programs. That has been Ray's signature for his entire
career.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gimmillaro, the word that comes to mind is honorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire him for a lot of reasons,'' Gimmillaro said. ``He's a
gentleman, very smart and aware, very honorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes out of his way to always be professional. In an era in
sports where everyone gives you his opinion whether you've asked
for them or not, where there often is not a lot of respect, that's
pretty special.''
</P>
<P>
   The man himself isn't much for hoopla, even if his name is
well-known and well-regarded around volleyball circles. He's
ecstatic to be in the Final Four, which starts tonight at UCLA with
the 49ers facing Indiana-Purdue-Ft. Wayne, but it won't change his
persona on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always a lot of times when you think you should be
there (in the Final Four) and you don't get there,'' he said. ``So
when you finally do, it makes the moment special.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Ratelle's third trip as the 49ers coach. His 1990 team,
his first conference champion, made it to the NCAA title game,
where it was upset by USC. He avenged that loss the following year
by beating the Trojans in the title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here, I didn't think I'd be here that long,'' said
Ratelle, who was an assistant coach on the 1973 NCAA champion San
Diego State team. ``I was a regular in the 9-to-5 world as a
pharmaceutical salesman and coached on the side, and I thought I'd
eventually give up coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was such a good situation here for me, and things have
gotten a whole lot better in the last 10 years, especially since
(school president) Dr. (Robert) Maxson and Bill Shumard came along.
They recognize volleyball and the job we're doing here, and they've
been appreciative.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how that feels. When we won a title at San
Diego State, it was the first national title in the school's
history, but no one in the athletic department seemed very
impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams Ratelle took to the 1990 and 1991 finals were led by
Brett Winslow and Brent Hilliard, consensus All-Americans most of
their careers at Long Beach State. Hilliard was the 1992 national
player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Ratelle doesn't have a standout star like that on his '99 team,
but it is one of his most experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those years, we had a go-to guy in Hilliard,'' he said. ``This
team is well balanced and the pieces all fit. It plays well
together as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this team because it knows what a struggle it has been
to get this far. It is so difficult to survive in our conference''
the Mountain Pacific Sports Federation, which features USC, UCLA
and every other Southern California standout ``because it's so
deep. Each year, it's an absolute dog fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're experienced. I have the same basic team this year
that I had last year, and they know how quickly things can change
in the sport. Last year, UCLA and Pepperdine were the best teams in
our region, and they returned most of their key people, but neither
made it this far because they ran into hot teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Shumard believes the program has never been stronger because
it's grown together. Alan Knipe, a player on the 1990 and 1991
teams, returned in 1995 as Ratelle's top assistant and has helped
the team's recruiting base. The other assistant is Andy Reed, who
was the head coach at UC Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray believes in the simple things, like work ethic and
preparation,'' Shumard said. ``He's not big on folderol. He's from
the school of doing your job and doing it well, because that's what
you're supposed to do.'
</P>
<P>
   ``For all of the new age thought in sports, it's nice to know
that old stuff still works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
