<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-ARENA-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS ARENA'S DEMISE LIKELY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those involved with Los Angeles' drive to return the NFL to an
upgraded Coliseum may have a potential solution to parking
improvements in Exposition Park: The demolition of the 40-year-old
Los Angeles Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   When the NFL gave their conditional backing to Coliseum last
month, they added the need for 27,000 parking spaces in Exposition
Park to their wish list. Since then, the two groups vying for a
franchise -- Michael Ovitz and the Eli Broad/Ed Roski team -- and
several city officials have stepped up discussion of razing the
arena and building a parking structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sports Arena is the oldest venue in the NBA, which speaks
for itself,'' said L.A. City Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas, who has
championed the New Coliseum idea. ``We could conceivably demolish
it or find a way to adapt it for use in the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm open to anything that makes economic sense and is
compatible with how we want to grow the Coliseum renovation and
Exposition Park.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sports Arena is the home for the NBA's Los Angeles Clippers
and USC basketball, as well as another 100 or so events a year,
ranging from circus shows, ice shows, concerts and religious
gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clippers played their last game at the arena Wednesday
night and will move to the new Staples Center next season. USC
officials are in the early planning stages for on-campus facility
for its basketball and volleyball teams.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Lynch, General Manager of both the Coliseum and Sports
Arena, said the arena, operated by the Coliseum Commission, has
been running in the red for several years. But since the two
facilities are linked budget-wise, Coliseum revenue has made up
arena shortfall. The bond debt on the facility was retired a decade
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facility is supposed to be self-supporting, and it hasn't
been,'' said Lynch. ``We're losing one team and we might lose
another. We've been looking toward booking additional events with
the Clippers leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is pretty obvious that a lot of events that we normally
would book will go to the Staples Center. The commission is
cognizant of the arena's future and the NFL's concerns about
parking.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent proposal presented to the NFL by the Roski/Broad
team included the use of parking lots at USC as park of park
development, but league officials rejected USC's lots as meeting
their conditions. They want 27,000 parking spaces within the
confines of the park as a way of alleviating old concerns about
neighborhood safety.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz and architects from the Rockwellgroup (cq) were planning a
site survey of the Coliseum and park this week. When asked about
how the arena fits into early development plans, Ovitz said ``we're
not counting on it being there.''
</P>
<P>
   The state owns the land where the arena now sits, while the
Coliseum Commission owns the building. Lynch said the state could
approve the lease of the land to a private development group, like
Ovitz or Roski/Broad, pending approval to tear the arena down by
the Coliseum Commission.
</P>
<P>
   There would still be environmental and financial questions to
answer, however, before any wrecking ball could be ordered. While a
three- or four-story parking structure would alleviate parking
concerns, it might create traffic headaches and impact the three
museums that share Exposition Park. Approval would also have to
include agreements on how revenue from a parking structure would be
divided.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, councilman Ridley-Thomas said there has been
conversations among the two groups vying for a franchise about
combining their effort, but that it still is in the preliminary
stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of shuttle diplomacy,'' he said.
``They're trying to figure out if a partnership can be consummated
or if they want to stay on their own. I know Ed and Eli are
receptive to Michael Ovitz participating. They have been quite open
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz this week said he is continuing to work on his own
business plan and stadium model in anticipation of the next round
of NFL meetings, May 25-26 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said L.A. expansion is one of three
issues on the agenda for those meetings. But he doesn't expect the
ownership to select an ownership group or set a franchise fee in
Atlanta. The NFL has set a deadline of Sept. 15 for an L.A. plan to
be in place and approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be more focus on stadium development and
the business plans the expansion committee wants to see,'' he said.
``We've heard talk about the Sports Arena being torn down, but
that's an issue for the Los Angeles groups to determine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
