<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO'S ON FIRST, ANGELS ON TOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Mo Vaughn broke a sweat Wednesday night, and that was
big news for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Playing his first game at first base since opening night,
Vaughn's two-run homer in the fourth inning led the Angels to a 4-1
victory over the Detroit Tigers before 12,676 at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's sprained left ankle still hurts _ he talked to
reporters after Wednesday's game as a tube pumped cortisone into
the ankle _ but being back on the field instead of serving as
designated hitter means a lot to him and the club.
</P>
<P>
   Everything went right for the Angels on a night that must have
been what manager Terry Collins envisioned before an influx of
injuries sent the club into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Steve Sparks (1-3) got his first victory of the
season after allowing one run and three hits in eight innings. Troy
Percival struck out two in a 1-2-3 ninth for his fifth save.
</P>
<P>
   And Darin Erstad, back in left field for the first time since
Vaughn's injury, hit a two-run homer and made a diving catch to rob
Tony Clark of a hit.
</P>
<P>
   But it all started with Vaughn, whose home run off Tigers
starter Jeff Weaver (3-2), turned the game around. Through three
innings, Simi Valley High graduate Weaver didn't allow a hit,
walked only one and struck out five as the Tigers had a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fourth, Randy Velarde singled to open the inning
before Vaughn hit to left field on a 3-2 pitch for his fourth homer
of the year and a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much of a better flow being in the game,'' Vaughn
said. ``You generate blood flow and sweat. I'm surprised I did as
well DH-ing as I did. I was just not into it. Now I feel a part of
the ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings something to the table not many people do,'' Erstad
said of Vaughn. ``He's Mo Vaughn. His reputation precedes him. The
way he flows, the way he moves, the way people feed off him. When
he's not in his element, he's not comfortable. Now he's in his
spot, his normal routine. He's ready to roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, facing Weaver was a challenge for Vaughn and the Angels
Wednesday. Weaver entered the game 3-1 with a 2.45 ERA, his only
loss coming in a 1-0 setback to Pedro Martinez and the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half of the season is like a cloak and dagger,''
Vaughn said. ``You haven't faced these guys and nobody had ever
faced (Weaver). You almost give yourself up in your first at-bat to
see what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite getting the loss, Weaver allowed only two runs and three
hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the victory was Sparks' first of the year, he's
recently been on a roll. In his past three starts, he has allowed
only two earned runs in 202/3 innings. He helped himself in the
second when his fake pick-off attempt toward third got Juan
Encarnacion to break from first.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks threw him out at second.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Sparks allowed only one hit from the third inning
through the eighth. The difference now from his first three starts
(15 earned runs in 141/3 innings) is that his knuckleball is around
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to think early in the year,'' Collins said.
``He had trouble throwing strikes and (the catchers) had trouble
handling it. But the last few times out he's been around the strike
zone. That makes such a big difference. You get guys to swing the
bat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of things (pitching coach) Dick Pole
worked on with me and my mechanics,'' Sparks said. ``He kept me on
line toward home plate, like a little hallway towards home plate.
If you get guys to swing early in the game and you pound the strike
zone early, it makes all my pitches that much better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
