<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSU-FACULTY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIONS SEEK TO FORCE CALIFORNIA COLLEGE FACULTY TO PAY DUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHARLINE CHIANG  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- With Democrats in control in Sacramento, unions
are again seeking state-mandated rules that will force employees at
California State University and University of California campuses,
including faculty, to pay dues whether they join the union or not.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-union faculty members are opposing a so-called ``agency
shop'' bill out of the state Senate that has already passed one
Senate panel and is now headed to appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   Faculty members such as California State University, Northridge,
economics professor Shirley Svorny resent being forced to pay for a
union that they believe does not represent their needs and
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that the union has served the faculty well in
terms of negotiations,'' Svorny said. ``I don't want them to
represent me.''
</P>
<P>
   Union activists say requiring dues from nonmembers who receive
full representation on matters such as contract negotiation and
grievances is only fair.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Meisenhelder, president-elect of the California Faculty
Association and an English professor at California State
University, San Bernardino, compared agency shop to taxation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everybody likes taxes,'' she said. ``But it's not
voluntary. But people do understand that in order to have an
effective government everyone has to pay taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees could appeal for exemptions, Meisenhelder said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require all employees to pay a ``fair share'' of
union due fees. For faculty, that would amount to 85 percent of
total dues. Full membership and voting rights would be granted to
those who pay in full.
</P>
<P>
   The measure promises to more than double the number of employees
paying dues. Right now, only two in five faculty employees in the
two university systems -- or about 7,000 full- and part-time
professors, librarians, counselors and coaches -- choose to join
the California Faculty Association.
</P>
<P>
   Members pay a little less than 1 percent of their gross salary
per year in dues. The union's 1998-99 revenues from dues are about
$3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The entire CSU system has seven unions.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 645, authored by Sen. John Burton, D-San Francisco,
was introduced Feb. 24 and was passed 9-4 April 14 by the Senate's
Education Committee. Efforts to contact Burton on Wednesday were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   However, Burton spokesman Dave Sebeck said Burton is ``a
longtime believer in agency shop and fair share representation.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation has been attempted before only to be vetoed
under previous Republican governors George Deukmejian and Pete
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Although supporters and opponents alike predict the bill will
sail through this time under Democratic leadership, Gov. Gray Davis
has not expressed support for or opposition to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently the governor does not have a position on this
bill,'' said Linda Choi, spokeswoman for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
