<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, May 6.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MASSACRE (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Betrayal is the theme of
the story of Slovinje, a village in Kosovo. Of the 600 homes there,
40 belonged to Serbs and the rest to ethnic Albanians. When the
violence began in the province, the Serbs of Slovinje told their
Albanian neighbors that they had nothing to fear from the army or
paramilitary forces. But last Friday, two mass graves were dug up
in Slovinje, and 16 muddy corpses were laid out in a schoolroom.
The story is incomplete without independent confirmation: In
separate interviews, 17 Kosovar Albanians who had been in Slovinje
on April 15 and 16 told their stories to The New York Times during
the last week. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT13,14) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina) _ At Pristina's main hospital,
Yugoslavia's second biggest, Serbs and Albanian medical workers
feel obligation to stay in the war zone and work. They talk about
how they cope and about the various bomb injuries they see. Some
patients from the bus bombed on a bridge over the weekend are
there, along with some soldier patients. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT30) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ The NATO allies now believe
they will need nearly twice the 28,000 peacekeeping troops they
originally planned to station in Kosovo in a negotiated settlement,
allied and U.S. officials said Wednesday. By Craig R. Whitney with
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ There is intense pressure on
Yitzhak Mordechai, who is running third in polls, to drop out of
the election. If he stays in, he could give victory to Netanyahu,
his arch-enemy. If he drops out and joins with Barak, Netanyahu
could lose in first round. By Deboarh Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-ELECT (Edinburgh) _ Millions of voters in Scotland and
Wales head to the polls on Thursday to elect new assemblies as part
of a historic devolution of power from London promised by British
Prime Minister Tony Blair. Some 4 million Scots are eligible to
cast ballots for the Scottish Parliament, their first chamber for
300 years, while in Wales more than 2 million voters can turn out
to elect the country's first ever elected house. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR (Rdili, Indonesia) _ In East Timor, even
hospitals are not safe havens from fighting. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-SEARCH (Oklahoma City, Okla.) _ As this area recovers from
this week's devastating storm, which has accounted for 38 deaths so
far in the Oklahoma City area, no task has been more gruesome than
the search for the missing. It has been complicated by significant
confusion, with the authorities apparently uncertain about how many
people really have yet to be located. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-POLICE (Oklahoma City) _ Many of the homes that were
destroyed in one neighborhood were owned by police and fire
fighters who are helping others cope with disaster. By Michael
Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ORGAN-DONATION (Washington) _ With demand for human organs
far outstripping supply, and more than 64,000 Americans waiting to
receive new hearts, lungs, livers, pancreases and kidneys,
Pennsylvania is planning to become the first state in the nation to
break a long-held taboo against providing a financial reward for
organ donation. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-HOSPITALS (Boston) _ Normally, the great teaching hospitals
here carry an air of best-in-the-world arrogance. But lately, their
chief executives carry an air of pleading and alarm. With rising
costs and dropping payments, especially Medicare payments, the
special missions of the teaching hospitals give them no immunity to
the great changes sweeping American health care. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT22) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MICROSOFT (New York) _ Two years ago, AT&AMP;T Corp., one of
the world's most venerable companies, appeared a crippled giant.
Today, poised to become the nation's No. 1 cable television company
and to strike a partnership with Microsoft, the computer software
leviathan, AT&AMP;T once again stands astride the communications world.
By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-COMCAST (Undated) _ In what is being widely hailed as savvy
resolution for both sides, AT&AMP;T, which already owns the nation's
second largest cable company, gets MediaOne. But Comcast, which was
also vying for control of MediaOne, walks away with a prize: it
acquires 2 million cable subscribers and gets control over 2
million more. One reason AT&AMP;T and Comcast may have avoided friction
over the deal is that the negotiating was done directly between top
level corporate executives who are seasoned dealmakers in their own
businesses. By Geraldine Fabrikant and Laura M. Holson
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS-ECON (Nablus, West Bank) _ New features of the
Nablus landscape include a Palestinian stock exchange, a modern
television assembly plant and the headquarters of Paltel, the
Mideast's first privately owned phone company. These are
cornerstones of an emerging Palestinian economy, being built with
offshore Palestinian money in expectation of statehood. By William
A. Orme. (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Photo [NYT28) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CADILLAC-LINCOLN (Detroit) _ Here in the Motor City, auto makers
take their annual battles for sales titles pretty seriously.
Perhaps the most fiercely fought feud has been between Cadillac and
Lincoln, as Cadillac struggled to keep its 57-year winning streak
as the nation's best-selling luxury car. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ It may appear to many investors
that the sharp rebound in Brazilian stocks and bonds has passed
them by. The stock market, in local terms, is up 71 percent this
year and is almost back to its last peak in March 1998. Analysts
and money managers, though, say there is still much more to make on
a investment in Brazil. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Big plans to overhaul Social
Security may or may not be dead in Congress this year. But
regardless of what happens, Washington will eventually have to come
up with a way to keep the system from running out of money when the
baby boomers retire next century. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   HEINZ-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Using its flagship condiment as a
battering ram, H.J.Heinz is in the middle of a major campaign to
revamp itself as a zippy, modern corporate behemoth, not the slow,
barely growing behemoth it has long been. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
