<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' ARNOLD BEATS JITTERS, EXPOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Dodgers rookie Jamie Arnold arrived at Olympic
Stadium with no idea what happened to left-hander Carlos Perez's
right knee.
</P>
<P>
   How could he? Even Perez said he doesn't know the answer to how
he was injured. It's a question the Dodgers brass is also asking.
</P>
<P>
   But with Perez out with a swollen knee, manager Davey Johnson
turned to Arnold for what turned into the most memorable night of
his eight-year professional career.
</P>
<P>
   In his first major-league start, Arnold took a no-hitter into
the sixth inning and allowed one hit in 62/3 shutout innings as the
Dodgers beat the Montreal Expos 8-2 on Wednesday to finish their
nine-game road trip with seven wins.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield added a three-run homer in
the third inning and a solo homer in the ninth. It's the first time
Sheffield homered since he hit two April 17 at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more nervous about this start then my first professional
outing,'' said Arnold, whose major-league debut was pitching out of
a bases-loaded, one-out jam against the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here, (Eric Young) asked me if I was starting,''
Arnold said. ``I said I didn't think so. Five minutes later I found
out I was starting and the butterflies began.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Arnold did was call his family in Kissimmee,
Fla., to tell them to watch the game.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing the 25-year-old former first-round pick of the
Braves did was dominate the Expos like this was rookie ball.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he wanted to hold Arnold to 60 pitches.
Astonishingly, Arnold (1-0) threw just 60 pitches in nearly seven
innings. Orlando Cabrera's leadoff single to left in the sixth was
the only hit he allowed. Arnold, a reliever since 1997, walked one
and struck out two.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a non-roster invitee to spring training after
signing a free-agent contract with the Dodgers during the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got great stuff to begin with, but obviously, we needed
someone to step up and he did it,'' Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley
said. ``I was going to try and keep him in the game as long as
possible because I knew he was capable of pitching like this.
That's that we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez will be examined in Los Angeles today by Dodgers team
physician Dr. Ralph Gambardella.
</P>
<P>
   Though Perez couldn't bend his knee and spent most of the
pregame getting treatment, Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone
said he's hopeful Perez will start Tuesday against the Chicago
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   If Perez isn't available, Malone talked before the game about
promoting a starting pitcher from Triple-A Albuquerque. The leading
candidate is right-hander Mike Judd. He's 1-2 with a 5.40 ERA, but
Malone and Johnson said Judd's pitched well lately. In eight career
games with the Dodgers, he has a 12.21 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   However, after watching Arnold dazzle the Expos, Johnson had
another plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over to the other starters and said, `See how easy it
is, fellas,''' Johnson said. ``I think I might look at him to get
another start. I'm dumb, but I'm not stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the Fox Group didn't force Malone to cut the
payroll and deal Dave Mlicki, which sources said occurred, the
Dodgers wouldn't be facing this predicament. They were one of the
few teams overloaded with starting pitchers but now could be in the
market for a fifth starter. And it could be for much more than the
$2.25 million Mlicki makes this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if we had him now, yeah,'' Malone said. ``If
this is a long-term problem, it's definitely worse than we're
hoping for. We're optimistic he'll be able to pitch May 11.''
</P>
</TEXT>
