u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT &LR;      05-06 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS BEAT METS, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The routine had become routine for Bobby Valentine.
When the game stretched into the late innings, he picked up the
phone to the bullpen, summoned one of the Mets' superb relievers
and watched them hold tight to another lead and secure another
victory. Valentine's routine had become very routine and it was
very successful.
</P>
<P>
   But that seamless routine ended abruptly and ended emphatically
on Wednesday night when Jeff Bagwell crushed Armando Benitez's
fastball into the left-field bullpen for a two-run homer that
helped vault the Houston Astros to a 5-4 triumph over the Mets at
Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were four outs away from celebrating a night in which
Bobby Jones was effective and Bobby Bonilla was cheered, but they
faltered in the eighth inning and lost for the second straight
game.
</P>
<P>
   After Bonilla's single started a rally that reached its climax
with Roger Cedeno's single that put the Mets in front, 4-3, in the
seventh, Benitez (0-1) was called upon for the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez walked Bill Spiers then rebounded by getting the next
two batters out. But then he pumped a 91-mile-an-hour fastball that
was chest high, and Bagwell whacked it for a two-run home run, his
eighth homer in the last 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Benitez, who had allowed only two runs in 122/3
innings, had allowed that many in two-thirds of an inning on
Wednesday night. Suddenly, the bullpen that had saved 12 of its
first 13 save opportunities had faltered. Instead, Billy Wagner
struck out the final four Mets to notch his 10th save for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The glamour of the inning was a real good hitter hitting a
ball over the fence,'' Valentine said. ``The story of the inning
was there were four balls thrown to that first hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Benitez, who said he rushed against Spiers and that is why he
walked him on five pitches, also misplaced the fastball to Bagwell.
Now the Mets must watch Benitez a little closer; he sometimes lost
confidence with the Orioles after giving up critical hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``''I tried to throw the ball outside,'' Benitez said. ``I
missed my location and he got it.''
</P>
<P>
   A seemingly relieved Bagwell said: ``I can do that every once in
a while. Benitez is probably going to strike me out more times than
I'm going to hit homers. He's very tough. He's not a treat to
face.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Mets (17-11) finished their homestand with a decent 6-3
record and will journey to Arizona to begin a nine-game road trip
on Friday. But this is a game that should make the Mets ache
because they had a one-run lead at a point in which they have been
dominant, and they had already mishandled some chances at a larger
lead. Mike Piazza hit into a double play with the bases loaded, and
was nabbed off first after a lineout when he did not slide; Edgardo
Alfonzo smacked into another double play with two runners on, and
Rey Ordonez was gunned out at home on a powerful throw by left
fielder Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to forget about this,'' Piazza said.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, Bonilla, whose sacrifice fly in the fourth
had given the Mets a 3-2 lead and earned him a standing ovation,
was cheered a second time after he singled off Jay Powell (2-0) to
open the seventh. The pinch-runner Jermaine Allensworth replaced
Bonilla and later scored on Cedeno's looping single to give the
Mets a 4-3 lead. Earlier, Bonilla had been berated when he made a
lazy throw to second and a blooper that he chugged after had
dropped fair by a foot.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who gave up three earned runs in seven innings while
striking out eight and walking one, could not hold the 3-2 lead for
too long as Tim Bogar doubled with one out in the fifth. One out
later, Craig Biggio rapped a double between Brian McRae and Bonilla
into the right-center-field gap.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, who is wearing a cumbersome brace because of a torn
ligament in his right knee, hobbled after the ball and was about 10
feet away from it when it dropped. While Bonilla would have had to
make a splendid running catch, the Mets had to wonder if a speedy
outfielder like Allensworth would have caught the ball. Later, the
Mets also had to wonder what happened to their bullpen routine last
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, you miss the spot,'' Benitez said. ``You're human.
You know?''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
