A6301 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT &LR;      05-06 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE HELPS YANKS GET BACK ON TRACK WITH WIN OVER TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Andy Pettitte lowers his chin when he stares in
for the sign from the catcher, the bill of his cap dropping as
well, and nearly hiding his eyes from view. His field of vision is
restricted from this angle, his sightline no higher than the first
few rows of the stands behind home plate.
</P>
<P>
   This is his world: Pettitte sees the catcher and his glove and
the hitter, and Wednesday night, he ruled his world, shutting down
the Minnesota Twins in a 5-3 victory on an evening when the New
York Yankees needed to re-establish themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had been guilty of flawed performances that were
repeated, and with Pettitte permitting just five hits over 7 2-3
innings and Tino Martinez driving home two runs, the Yankees'
universe turned right side up, finally.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte had lasted just 3 1-3 innings in his previous start,
against Kansas City last Friday, and his response to that Wednesday
night was typical. Pettitte has had outings of five innings or less
nine times since Aug. 30, 1995, and each time, Pettitte has won his
subsequent outing.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte and Martinez and the core veterans of the Yankees give
this team an unshakable foundation in 1999. No matter how poor the
bench is right now or how little production the Yankees are getting
from their left fielders, regardless of Jorge Posada's deep slump,
the first six hitters in the Yankees' lineup are probably as good
or better than any other 1-to-6 group in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The middle relief is a mess, but if the Yankees have a lead in
the eighth or ninth inning, there is perhaps the best closer in the
game, Mariano Rivera, who got the save Wednesday night. Hideki
Irabu is floundering, but he is surrounded by pitchers who have had
ample success and thrived under pressure, from David Cone to
Pettitte to Orlando Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Even in those times when the Yankees struggle _ and they have
played truly awful baseball at times _ they will win many games
because of that foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee, the rookie left fielder, is hitting well under .200
and has no home runs and two runs batted in, and his poor defense
is being exploited. But the foundation allows the Yankees to keep
Ledee in the big leagues and give him the opportunity to work
through his troubles, rather than demote him to Triple-A; they can
win without contributions from Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   A foundation that includes Joe Girardi as the backup catcher
affords Posada a day or two off to clear his mind, take extra
batting practice and reflect on his recent failures. Posada's slump
eats at him, and the Yankees will be much better whenever he
emerges. But he could flounder all year and the Yankees can win.
</P>
<P>
   Posada didn't play Wednesday night and won't play Thursday, in
the final game of the Yankees' 10-game road trip. Don Zimmer, the
interim manager, wanted Girardi to catch Pettitte Wednesday night
and David Cone on Thursday. Ledee went 0 for 4 with two strikeouts
and a misplay in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees thrashed the Twins anyway and improved their record
to 17-9. They jumped on LaTroy Hawkins, the Minnesota starter, for
two quick runs in the first inning. Luis Sojo dumped a single into
right field and Paul O'Neill followed with a single. Hawkins
retired Bernie Williams with a low curveball, Williams grounding
out to first base and both runners advancing.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling good about his curveball, Hawkins then tried another in
throwing to Martinez _ and the Yankees' first baseman pulled a
double into the right-field corner. Sojo scored, O'Neill followed
and the tone was set. Scott Brosius blasted a solo home run in the
second inning, increasing the Yankees' advantage to 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis beat out an infield single leading off the fourth.
The second baseman always plays deep on the artificial surface
here, and Davis managed to leave a bouncer in front of the Twins'
Todd Walker. It appeared Davis would be stranded, when Ledee
whiffed and Brosius grounded out. But Joe Girardi slapped an
infield single to deep short, and when the throw got past first
baseman Ron Coomer, Davis scored; Girardi came home when Derek
Jeter doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte would have won with much, much less. He rarely pitched
deep into the count. He went to a three-ball count only three times
in the first four innings and whenever he needed a big pitch,
Pettitte would lean back and fire his cut fastball at the hands of
the Twins' hitters, or perhaps a sinking fastball. Pettitte
generated 15 ground-ball outs, including two double plays, and fell
just short of becoming the first Yankee pitcher to throw a complete
game this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
