<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOT-BLOCKING DOWN FOR SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Shaquille O'Neal's usual offensive dominance had him
chasing a scoring title this season, but as the Lakers wrapped up
the 50-game slate, O'Neal also turned in a career-low on the other
end of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's shot-blocking average of 1.69 per game is a block per
game lower than his career mark and by far the lowest for any
season in his seven-year NBA career. He averaged 3.53 as a rookie
and had never averaged fewer than 2.0 per game.
</P>
<P>
   In a year when the Lakers' defense has ranked near the bottom of
the league, O'Neal's shot-blocking decline might simply be a
reflection of his team's struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't for a long time been playing very good defense,''
coach Kurt Rambis said. ``Our transition defense wasn't there _
it's hard to block shots when you're not back on defense.
Regardless of whether it's him or anyone else, teams were getting
opportunities to score. I know his stomach (abdominal strain) has
bothered him intermittently throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're doing our job defensively, we're forcing them to come
into him, which gives him the opportunity to block shots. If our
defensive rotation isn't there, then they're standing outside,
shooting wide-open jumpers. It's pretty tough for someone to block
those shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that O'Neal is too concerned with being 15th in the league
in blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've never seen a big man come in here and dominate me,'' he
said. ``They might score one or two jumpers, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal wouldn't hazard a guess as to the reason for the decline
but said his sore abdomen was not the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to help guards, and all of that. I can't do everything
at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that Miami's Alonzo Mourning, an MVP candidate because of
his defense, averaged 3.91 blocks this season, O'Neal got
sarcastic: ``I guess that's why he's the best big man, and I ain't
(bleep).''
</P>
<P>
   Back to class: With at least two free days before taking on
Houston in the playoffs, Rambis is eager to use the time for
much-needed practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game we play, we break down the tape to show the guys:
Here's some great things that you did, here's some not-so-great
things you did. Here's a guy that was open on this play, you need
to find this guy. It's just a matter of making the players aware of
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis also figures to lengthen both practice time and film
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get guys out there for five hours on the court.
We want to try and make it hard and concise and keep them in the
hour-and-a-half to two-hour range, but we will have much longer
film sessions. Since you have time to focus and concentrate on one
(opponent), you can break down a lot more tape and spend time with
the guys and show them individual things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
