<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6311 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-WILDLIFE-LADN     05-06 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-WILDLIFE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE RAGES OVER WILDLIFE MANAGEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the harbor seal population began to diminish, the U.S. Fish
and Wildlife Service stepped in and made it illegal to hunt, touch
or hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the mountain lion's ranges are severely depleted,
California voters decided -- twice -- that no agency could kill
one.
</P>
<P>
   Another state measure bans the trapping of animals. And the
Department of Fish and Game was set to kill a population of beavers
near Lake Skinner in Riverside County that was threatening the
endangered gnatcatcher until a group of citizens stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of federal and state wildlife and
conservation organizations supporting various causes. But should
these organizations dictate wildlife policy?
</P>
<P>
   The debate over who should manage wildlife has been an issue for
decades. With humans invading even more wildlife space, the issues
have become virtual lightning-rods.
</P>
<P>
   Is it the job of DFG director Robert Hight and the Fish and Game
Commission -- all appointed by the state governor, who is elected
by the people -- to determine what is best for the state's
wildlife? Or is it the job of organizations to determine that
policy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely oppose specialty groups getting involved in
wildlife management,'' said Ed Hover, the California Conservation
Director for the Izaak Walton League. ``That should be in control
of the Department of Fish and Game. What these groups do is a lot
of (political) lobbying. They're thinking of Bambi, dealing with
sentiment.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Mountain Lion Foundation executive Lynn
Sadler says it's not fair for the DFG to run roughshod over these
organizations. Instead, the state should look at other methods of
solving these issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about what to do with mountain lions, beavers or
gnatcatchers,'' she said. ``We're saying that they should try to
find other ways to do things. The agencies are not following the
public's wishes. They've been like a bunch of kids that want their
way. All we're saying is there are different ways to handle things
and a lot of interpretations.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislation protecting endangered species had significant
statewide impact:
</P>
<P>
   Anglers now curse at harbor seals for stealing their catch as
they reel in the fish. The City of San Diego has had to rope off a
portion of its popular Children's Pool beach at La Jolla to protect
the seals from people. Many boaters and anglers up and down the
West Coast consider the animals a menace.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mountain lion initiative was first passed in 1992,
hunters claim that it has ruined the state's deer population,
resulting in fewer in-state hunting license purchases and less
funds to support California's wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   A pack of mountain lions in the Eastern Sierra has almost wiped
out a strain of Sierra Nevada Bighorn Sheep, leading the Department
of Fish and Game to change the listing of the animal from
threatened to endangered. The Sierra Nevada Bighorn Sheep
Interagency Advisory Group says there are fewer than 100 sheep in
the strain and the decline has been attributed primarily to
mountain lion depredation. They are contemplating moving the herd
to Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been more reports of mountain lions attacking
humans throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   After traps were made illegal in last November's election, two
coyotes attacked a San Jose-area hiker. Biologists say the only way
to remove the animals safely is through traps; no other method will
work effectively. The non-native red fox has established residences
in Orange County and biologists suggest the foxes -- which can be
effectively removed with traps -- destroy feeding patterns by other
animals.
</P>
<P>
   Groups that support just one animal include the Mountain Lion
Foundation, California Trout, Ducks Unlimited, Quail Unlimited,
National Wild Turkey Federation, Rocky Mountain Elk Deer Foundation
and Society for the Conservation of Bighorn Sheep.
</P>
<P>
   There are some organizations that support various nature causes:
the Sierra Club, Izaak Walton League, Nature Conservancy, National
Wildlife Federation, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each group is beneficial,'' says Patti Krueger, a biologist
for the Angeles National Forest. ``A group like Quail Unlimited may
be interested in protecting and improving the habitat of quails,
and their work benefits all other species.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, should organizations like Cal Trout, which has sued the
state to create catch-and-release areas, or the Mountain Lion
Foundation, which was behind the mountain lion initiative, pick and
choose policies that fit their organization's mission statement?
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with specialty groups that focus on one animal is
that they may focus on the problems of that animal and overlook the
overall picture,'' Krueger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are extremists everywhere. A wildlife manager has to
look at everything and the fact is there are not enough zoos to
fill the (excess) animals. The fact is the San Diego Zoo can only
take so many beavers and mountain lions.''
</P>
<P>
   Hover is unhappy with the harbor seals decree, saying the seals
have wiped out the Pismo Clam population.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that changing water conditions, pollution and less
fish been a factor, too?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're scavengers -- not sharks,'' the Hacienda Heights
resident says of the seals. ``They overeat and ruin pristine
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to move (sea) otters and the otters weren't part of
the contract,'' said Sadler, who says groups cannot become too
focused on their animal, but must look at the whole picture, too.
``They went right back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The seals have rights, too,'' Dorene Carlson told one
newspaper about the seals occupying La Jolla beaches. ``By leaving
them alone, we're teaching our children to respect other
creatures.''
</P>
<P>
   Krueger says the heart of the matter is the management issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, who is managing the (mountain lion) herd?'' she
said. ``The Department of Fish and Game feels by hunting, it can
manage the herd and they feel they can do that without a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   When wildlife begins preying on humans and pets, Krueger says
wildlife management could be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an animal is consistently in back yards and not utilizing
its habitat, that means it is being pushed into urban areas,''
Krueger says. ``If an animal is completely protected, then you're
lacking the ability to look at the big picture. Wildlife is then
being influenced by people.''
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for controls, the bald eagle and the gray whale
would not have rebounded from the endangered lists, and the
mountain lion and harbor seal might have replaced the eagle and
whale on those lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is,'' Sadler said, ``do we have a Mountain Lion
Foundation to protect only mountain lions, or do we follow our
mission statement to protect all California wildlife, with the
mountain lion as a point of reference from which we look at the
entire (eco-)system?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 0117EDT &QL; 
