<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-ROCKET-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YET ANOTHER SETBACK FOR BOEING'S ROCKET BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The second consecutive failure of The Boeing Co.'s new
Delta 3 rocket was not only a setback for the company's
opportunities in the space business, but a blow to U.S. efforts to
recapture a larger share of the global launch services market,
industry experts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   When the second stage of the Delta 3 misfired about 20 minutes
after launch Tuesday night from Cape Canaveral, Fla., it left an
important Asian communications satellite owned by Loral Orion
stranded in a useless orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers are trying to salvage what they can of the $235
million mission, but Loral CEO Bernard Schwartz said Wednesday the
Orion 3 satellite apparently was a ``total loss.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the second time in eight months, Boeing was forced to
appoint a team of investigators to determine why its powerful new
rocket malfunctioned. The first Delta 3 exploded on its maiden
flight last August, destroying a Galaxy X communications satellite
built by Hughes for PanAmSat Corp.
</P>
<P>
   This was the sixth significant launch failure of either a Boeing
or Lockheed Martin rocket since last August, failures which have
resulted in the loss of several billion dollars worth of military
and commercial satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Half those failures involved Boeing. Two Delta 3 rockets didn't
work, and a Boeing-built motor malfunctioned last month, leaving a
military satellite in a useless orbit after it was launched by a
Lockheed Martin Titan rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a disaster,'' Marco Caceres, a rocket and space
analyst with the Teal Group, said of the string of recent U.S.
mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   The rash of failures is driving commercial customers overseas in
search of more reliable launch vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Air Force Gen. Howell Estes, former commander of the
U.S. Space Command, told Defense Daily on Monday, one day before
the latest Delta 3 failure: ``Right at the time that the commercial
sector is set to take off, we run into this launch problem that
brings things to a screeching halt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orion 3 mission was covered by insurance, including the
estimated $85 million cost of the rocket, so the material loss for
Boeing is insignificant. But as a result of the back-to-back Delta
3 failures, Boeing has lost a significant opportunity to establish
itself in a market that desperately needs more powerful rockets to
launch today's new generation of heavier communication satellites
such as Orion 3, said Caceres.
</P>
<P>
   ``The positive news is that Delta 3 didn't blow up again,''
Caceres said. ``Boeing will figure this out and try again another
day...
</P>
<P>
   ``But a window of opportunity was there for Delta 3 to come in
and make some headway. Now, Boeing is back to where it was. They
have gained no ground on their competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   The principal competitors are the French and U.S. defense giant
Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   In a market once dominated by the United States, France's
Arianespace now launches more than half the world's communications
satellites _ a business that in a few years is expected to be worth
upward of $20 billion annually. U.S. companies have about 30
percent of the market, with the rest divided between Russia and
China.
</P>
<P>
   Delta 3 was expected to bring a good chunk of the commercial
business back to the United States, and to Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Orion 3 mission, Delta 3 was to fly twice more
this year, and at least six times next year.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how the latest failure will affect Boeing's
Delta 3 launch manifest. That will be determined by how quickly
investigators can pinpoint what went wrong with the second stage on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The first stage of the new Delta 3 is very similar to the first
stage of Boeing's reliable workhorse Delta 2. But the second-stage
cryogenic engine is new for the Delta 3 program. Built by Pratt &AMP;
Whitney, it uses uses super-cold liquid oxygen and liquid hydrogen.
</P>
<P>
   The second stage was supposed to ignite twice to place the Orion
3 satellite into an orbit with a high point of 15,969 miles above
the Earth, and a low point of 115 miles. The satellite would then
use its on-board engine to push itself into a permanent orbit
22,300 miles above the Equator.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary indications are that the second burn never occurred,
and the Orion 3 was left in an orbit with a high point of about 862
miles and a low point of 98.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Loral's Schwartz told analysts during a conference
that the satellite apparently was a total loss, Hughes engineers on
Wednesday sent a series of commands to the stranded satellite in an
effort to raise the orbit enough so that sunlight can reach the
craft's solar cells and recharge the batteries.
</P>
<P>
   That will give engineers more time to study possible options to
salvage the mission, said Hughes spokeswoman Fran Slimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said Wednesday the investigation board that will examine
what went wrong with Delta 3 is headed by Dr. Russell Reck,
Boeing's director of engineering technology for Expendable Launch
System in Huntington Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Caceres said he expects the high failure rate of new rockets to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not upgrades. These are new rockets systems,'' he
said. ``Companies today are not going through flight testing
because it's not economically feasible. They want to get into the
market and start making money right away.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Hughes has signed nine customers for Delta 3, including
the Orion 3 and Galaxy X missions, said Slimmer, the Hughes
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   No customers have canceled their orders for Delta 3, Slimmer
said Wednesday. But Boeing has not booked any new orders since the
explosion of Delta 3 last August.
</P>
<P>
   The two remaining Delta 3 flights that had been scheduled for
later this year were to have carried two of the 12 satellites for a
mobile communications system owned by ICO Global Communications of
London.
</P>
<P>
   The first two ICO satellites are to be launched by Russian
Proton rockets. The third and fifth satellites in the ICO
constellation were to have been launched by Delta 3 this year. In
between those two Delta 3 missions, an Atlas rocket is scheduled to
launch the fourth satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ICO spokesman Joe Tedino said in an interview Wednesday that ICO
has not changed its plans to have Boeing launch satellites 3 and 5.
But he did say the company has ``great flexibility'' to change its
plans and book space on another rocket should the need arise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we will be watching closely the information that
comes out of the Boeing investigation,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
