<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS LOSE FINALE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After teaming up on enough grief to require
air-traffic control for circling buzzards, the Clippers and the
Sports Arena called it quits Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ending this relationship as soon as possible was the best excuse
we've heard for not making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So, in a season-ending game with layoff implications, the
Clippers lost most of their cleaning deposit by getting lightly
dusted by the Seattle SuperSonics, 107-105, in front of 15,372.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, the Clippers (9-41) attempted to behave like a
team that didn't mind smashing a few of those precious lottery
Ping-Pong balls. Behind CBA refugees Tyrone Nesby (a career-high 30
points) and Troy Hudson (19 points, 10 assists), the Clippers
provided some drama after trailing by 16 in the fourth quarter. The
Sonics (24-26), who qualify as lottery trainees, were content to
see if the players who didn't play much this season could have
gotten them into the playoffs if they had played more often.
Ex-UCLA star Don MacLean, who was drafted by the Clippers in 1992
but traded before he could suit up, led Seattle with 26 points.
</P>
<P>
   For the home team, emotional impact varied.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, who are moving to the Staples Center when the
paint dries, played with passion, but seemed as sentimentally
involved with leaving their old venue as a family checking out of
Motel 6.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go to star forward Maurice Taylor for possible emotional
relevance. What about it, Mo ... any pangs of nostalgia?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' Taylor, who scored 20 in the finale, said.
</P>
<P>
   OK, but the Clippers are not unanimously thrilled with moving.
Guard Eric Piatkowski, who has spent all five of his pro seasons
playing for the NBA's version of a garage band, does have a soft
spot in his heart for the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought it was a good place to play,'' Piatkowski
said of the Sports Arena, home to the Clippers for 15 seasons and
254 victories in 564 games. ``It's a pretty good place to watch
basketball. I have some good memories here.''
</P>
<P>
   Elgin Baylor, the Clippers vice president of basketball
operations, created positive vibes in the building than anyone
while starring for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are teams that have played in worse arenas than this,''
said Elgin Baylor, the Clippers vice president of basketball
operations, possibly referring to Mel Gibson's Thunderdome crew.
</P>
<P>
   But despite what could be considered a late resurrection, there
haven't been many Clipper teams that struggled as much as this one.
At least the Clips finished this irregular season with a moment or
two to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Nesby, the rookie free agent, checked in with four dunks, with
two of those abetted by lob passes from Hudson. Taylor, who hit a
few bumps on a recent road trip, finished a slick left-to-right
crossover dribble by going Hatfield for a dunk on Seattle rookie
Jelani McCoy. He rocked two more in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Sonics -- seemingly unwilling to go bow to
the getaway-party atmosphere - brought just enough game to avoid
going down in Clipper history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
