<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6317 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-METS-HNS &LR;      05-06 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-METS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ The Astros made a living off some of the best relievers
in the league last season. But even with Jeff Bagwell at the plate
in the eighth inning of Wednesday's game and the Astros trailing by
a run, things didn't look good with Armando Benitez zipping 96-mph
fastballs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At one point, Astros manager Larry Dierker turned to bench coach
Matt Galante and asked, ``What if Benitez could just throw one of
those 91 or 92 mph (pitches) for a strike right now?''
</P>
<P>
   Request granted.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell hit a two-run homer in the eighth inning off Benitez as
the Astros completed an impressive road trip with a 5-4 win over
the New York Mets at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked up (at the radar reading), it was 91,'' Dierker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez (0-1) had allowed just two runs in his first 12 innings
for a Mets bullpen that entered Wednesday as the best in the
majors. Mets relievers were 7-0 with 12 saves and a 2.44 ERA before
Bagwell's home run, his third during the Astros' six-game road
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do that every once in a while,'' said Bagwell, who went
2-for-4 with four RBIs. ``Let me tell you, Benitez is probably
going to strike me out more than I'm going to get a home run off of
him. He's very tough. He's not a treat to face.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros twice rallied in the game, the latter in a two-run
eighth inning. With the Mets leading 4-3, Benitez walked Bill
Spiers to lead off the inning but got the next two hitters before
Bagwell hit a 1-0 line drive over the left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell went 8-for-22 with three home runs and seven RBIs during
the road swing, extending his hitting streak to 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the second time in seven days Benitez blew an
eighth-inning lead. In a game last week, he allowed two runs to San
Diego before the Mets rallied behind Mike Piazza's game-winning
two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to throw a fastball outside,'' Benitez said. ``I
missed my location, and he got it.''
</P>
<P>
   The come-from-behind victory let reliever Jay Powell (2-0) off
the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Powell entered in relief of Sean Bergman in the seventh inning
with the score tied at 3. He surrendered an RBI single to Roger
Cedeo and allowed three hits, walked one and hit a batter in 1
innings.
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros clinging to a one-run lead, Billy Wagner
relieved Powell with two runners on and two outs in the eighth.
Wagner struck out all four batters he faced _ 12 of his 15 pitches
were strikes _ for his 10th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Jay Powell did well,'' Dierker said. ``He's had good
stuff all year, but everything has gone wrong. It's tough for him
because he hasn't had any success, nothing positive or good to look
at.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell has struggled through his first 10 appearances,
particularly with control of his slider. In 10 innings, he has
given up seven runs, 13 hits and six walks.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros gained a measure of revenge against the Mets, taking
two of three during the series at Shea Stadium and going 5-1 on a
road trip that also included a stop in Florida. New York took three
of four games last September in Houston, delaying the Astros'
clinching of a second straight National League Central title.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took it to me and got on me pretty good,'' Wagner said of
home runs he allowed to Brian McRae and Piazza in consecutive games
last September. ``It's an intense game every time we play this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   It also served as validation of how the Astros can pull out a
victory against a tough starter, an even stronger bullpen and a
team considered an early favorite to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just hard to beat,'' Dierker said of the Mets. ``We
never get much more than two or three runs off him (starter Bobby
Jones). They got a lot of hits, and we managed to close off some
rallies and leave some runners on base. You can't always do that,
but we did that tonight. That was the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a few games where we've outhit the other team and
lost. This time, they outhit us (11-8) and we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones went seven innings, allowing five hits and three runs
while striking out a season-high eight.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored twice in the first inning when Craig Biggio
walked and Derek Bell hit a fly ball down the right-field line that
Bobby Bonilla, wearing a brace on his sprained right knee, couldn't
chase down.
</P>
<P>
   It went as a double, and Bagwell followed with a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets answered on Edgardo Alfonzo's RBI double and Piazza's
RBI groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman, coming off a complete game in his last start April 30
at Florida, allowed three runs and eight hits in six innings. It
marked the first time in 10 games an Astros starter did not get a
decision. The starting rotation was 7-2 in those nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla gave the Mets a 3-2 lead in the fourth inning with a
long sacrifice fly, and the Astros responded on Biggio's RBI double
in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' defense played a role in keeping the Mets off the
scoreboard with three double plays, and Richard Hidalgo made a
pinpoint throw from left field to throw out Rey Ordoez at the plate
to end the fourth inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 0124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6318 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     05-06 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DAYS before the big race, D. Wayne Lukas took pride in showing
visitors a pair of small wooden carvings hanging in the shed row of
his barn at Churchill Downs. A gift from a fan, each artwork
displayed the back of a horse and jockey, and on them had been
hand-painted the names of Lukas' two entries in the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is exactly the view I want the other (17) horses to see
at the wire,'' said Lukas, who very nearly got his wish.
Charismatic came barreling up from seventh at the far turn to win,
and Cat Thief wound up third by slightly more than a length.
</P>
<P>
   If a flying Menifee hadn't dodged his way through the field to
wind up second, beaten by a neck, Lukas would have achieved his
improbable, picture-perfect finish. He didn't get his exacta, but a
third victory in five years made a swell consolation prize.
</P>
<P>
   The most active of all Kentucky Derby trainers is not among
those campaigning to limit the field to a more convenient number
than the 19 colts who scrimmaged in last week's classic. No one
promised us a rose garden, but the debate goes on: Is this the best
way to showcase racing's premier event?
</P>
<P>
   The wonder is that there were no spills, no serious injuries to
the horses or the plucky little athletes who must manage them. But
when you fill up the track, form and strategy pretty much take a
holiday. Picking a winner brings back memories of the days when the
child who came closest to guessing the number of jelly beans in a
candy store window could collect a bagful on the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great for Bob Baffert and Nick Zito and me,''
Lukas said of the idea of limiting the field to 15 or fewer.
``We're here every year, sometimes with two or more colts. But what
about the guy who only has one, and his trip is once in a
lifetime?''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas may be moved by motives that are entirely altruistic. The
average field for the 125 Kentucky Derbies is 12 and a fraction,
but the trend is clearly pointing to a full house. In five of the
last eight years, there have been 18 or more starters. And guess
what? Charismatic and Thunder Gulch won from the 16th hole, and
Grindstone from No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The other Lukas champion, the filly Winning Colors, had the 11th
position in a field of 17 in 1988. One of three fillies ever to win
the Derby, Winning Colors did it by taking the lead and holding it
wire-to-wire.
</P>
<P>
   The trick to prevailing in this kind of traffic is to find a
lane and hope for a clean ride. It worked just fine for
Charismatic, who stayed wide early and made his move at the top of
the stretch, with a heady ride from Chris Antley.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert is on record as favoring a limit of 12 to 14 horses. He
had three chances to become the first trainer to win three Derbies
in a row, but General Challenge, his best bet, was clobbered early,
while Prime Timber and the filly Excellent Meeting had to battle to
wind up fourth and fifth. A victory by General Challenge would have
been the first by a gelding in this race in 71 years, but he never
got untracked, plodding across the line behind 10 others. It was a
dreary day for the horse Baffert had talked up all week. Of course,
being a gelding means he isn't looking forward to his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Zito, who trained two Derby winners, Strike the Gold and Go for
Gin, hasn't yet landed hard on the issue. ``It's the Kentucky
Derby,'' he said. ``There is always the luck factor, and with so
many horses it might be even more so. But what are you going to do,
tell someone they can't run their property?''
</P>
<P>
   Luck was not with Zito's entries, Stephen Got Even and Adonis,
who finished 14th and 17th.
</P>
<P>
   The largest field in Derby history was in 1974, the 100th
anniversary of the spectacle, with Cannonade leading a pack of 23.
</P>
<P>
   Another famous mob scene occurred in 1982, when Gato del Sol ran
last for half a mile, then closed fast to win in a crowd of 19. The
bumping and jostling in the first turn may have affected the
outcome of the Derby in 1987, when War nearly went over the inside
rail, and 1994, when Strodes Creek was hindered by Valiant Nature,
who had been sideswiped by another horse.
</P>
<P>
   War staggered home 13th in a field of 17. Strodes Creek, trained
by Charlie Whittingham, finished second to Go for Gin among 14
colts _ what many believe should be the maximum number of starters.
The first 14 ran out of the main gate Saturday, with the extra five
in the auxiliary gate.
</P>
<P>
   The grand design of Baffert wound up in the trash bin when
Aljabr had to be scratched, moving each colt one spot to the left.
Instead of having Prime Timber on the outside of the main gate,
with room to his right, and General Challenge in the auxiliary,
with space to his left, they were crunched side by side and caught
up in the gang fight at the start.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the railbirds mean when they refer to ``racing
luck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
