<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6320 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VICKERS-EXECUTE-AZR &LR;      05-06 2190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICKERS-EXECUTE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT VICKERS, ARIZONA DEATH ROW LEGEND, EXECUTED
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCE, Ariz. _ At 3 p.m. Wednesday the blue curtain opened
inside the death chamber at Arizona State Prison here.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wayne Vickers, Death Row's most infamous resident, popped
his head up like a cobra from the gurney and smiled a gap-toothed
smile at the assembled crowd of officials and witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, everybody,'' he said with the swagger that would
characterize his death as it did his troubled, violent life.
</P>
<P>
   ``See you later.''
</P>
<P>
   He nodded. His microphone was cut off. Still, the watchers
outside the glass could read his lips: ``Time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Vickers, facing death by injection for the 1992 murder of a
fellow Death Row inmate, looked at his aunt, cousin and a woman he
often referred to as his ``soulmate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you. Don't cry,'' his lips said. ``I'm coming home.''
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   His aunt's sobs and the hum of the air conditioner were the only
sounds as the crowd filed out of the small, windowless room. The
blue curtain closed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 41, the man who proclaimed himself ``Banzai Bob'' by carving
the Japanese epithet in a victim's flesh had built himself into a
bloody legend inside Arizona's prison sys tem.
</P>
<P>
   His violence, ingenuity and flair for the dramatic became known
even beyond Arizona when he appeared in a HBO special to show how
one can escape from cuffs and chains.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials took no chances. After Vickers finished his
last meal of two green chili burritos, fries with ketchup, vanilla
ice cream, cream soda and one cigarette, they added a special
thumblock, along with handcuffs and straps, to bind him to the
death gurney.
</P>
<P>
   The longest-serving current in mate on Arizona's Death Row,
Vickers amassed a staggering record of mayhem inside the walls of
the state's correctional system.
</P>
<P>
   He was cited for two murders, 158 other major violations,
assaults on 12 corrections officers and some 20 inmates, numerous
threats and about 40 counts of making weapons.
</P>
<P>
   If he regretted any of it, he never said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1982 killing, Vickers built a firebomb from hair gel and
an ice-cream carton, then used it to torch fellow murderer Wilmar
``Buster`` Holsinger in his cell.
</P>
<P>
   When a guard asked Vickers if Holsinger was dead, Vickers re
sponded, ``He should be. He's on fire.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Banzai Bob'' started out small - small in age, small in crime.
Sometime before his 11th birthday, court records show, he started
steal ing.
</P>
<P>
   His role model was not hard to find. According to court records,
his father, Harold Vickers, took the boy along on several
burglaries. On some occasions, he used Robert's small size to gain
access to his targets.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the elder Vickers ap parently did little in the way
of parenting. Robert Vickers once told a parole officer that his
mother and father divorced when he was barely a year old.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers, who grew up mostly in the Sunnyslope area of Central
Phoenix, lived with a grandmother until he was 4 years old, then
with his father until age 7. Even then, Vickers said, his father
left him with relatives for long periods.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers lived in 18 different foster homes; in one, both Vickers
and his sister were molested by their foster mother, according to
court records.
</P>
<P>
   By sixth grade, he was in custody of the state, and spent time
in juvenile corrections facilities at Fort Grant, Alpine and Adobe
Mountain. It was the end of Vickers' formal education.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers' relationship with his mother, Jennie Thompson, was ap
parently no closer. Once, he said, she literally threw her infant
son into the trash. On another occasion, he said, he and his
sister, Brenda, visited their mother while the chil dren were
living with their father.
</P>
<P>
   When his mother feared that Harold Vickers was not coming to
pick them up, he said, Jennie Thompson turned the children over to
child-welfare workers.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Gray, a Tucson attorney who represented Vickers in his
first murder case, said he once inter viewed Vickers' mother and
``she was totally devoid of any kind of emotional connection with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   In late February, Vickers' mother committed suicide, said
Camilla Strongin, a Corrections Department spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Family members said she left a note saying that she was
responsible for her son's actions.
</P>
<P>
   They said Vickers was never told about his mother's suicide.
Prison officials feared that the infamous Death Row inmate might
kill him self.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers was far from infamous when he entered Arizona's adult
prison system in 1977; in fact, he was a relatively small man doing
small-time crime. After amassing a long record of petty juvenile of
fenses, Vickers was sentenced as an adult to three to nine years
impris onment for grand theft.
</P>
<P>
   After his release from juvenile custody in 1976, he'd moved to
Fresno, Calif., and stayed there just long enough to run up five
warrants for his arrest for burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers came back to the Valley and pulled off 12 burglaries in
13 days, police said.
</P>
<P>
   In one, he pried open the bath room of a Tempe home and stole
$550 of property, including a hand gun and jewelry. He stole $2,000
from another Tempe home that day.
</P>
<P>
   A Tempe police officer, who said that Vickers admitted to 33
Califor nia burglaries, said Vickers, ``be gins every day planning
a burglary much as another individual would attend to a regular
job...If he was out of jail another 100 days he would do another
100 burglaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Vickers escaped from the Tempe jail a few days later, but was
captured and sent to Florence.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Warden Frank Terry, a guard during those days, remembers
that time as being one of extraordi nary violence at the Florence
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was still a teenager, only about 5 feet, 5 inches and
skinny,'' Terry said. ``He had small-man's syndrome and did what he
felt like he had to do to keep the other inmates away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Terry said, there was Vick ers' ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also saw himself as a legendary killer of gigantic propor
tions,'' Terry said, ``who will be remembered forever along the
lines of John Dillinger.''
</P>
<P>
   Vickers wasted little time in prepar ing his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   His first murder was of inmate Frank Ponciano, whom Vickers
sought out as his cellmate because Ponciano had a TV. Angered that
Ponciano did not wake him up for lunch and drank his Kool-aid, Vick
ers killed him, then carved - and misspelled - the Japanese war cry
``Bonzai'' in Ponciano's back.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers burned a cigarette on Ponciano's foot to show a guard he
was dead, then said, ``Get this stinking (expletive) out of my
cell.''
</P>
<P>
   Vickers later told prison psychol ogist Kent Spillman that he
regret ted only one thing about the attack: that he didn't have
enough time to carve a swastika on Ponciano's body.
</P>
<P>
   During his trial for Ponciano's death, Vickers threw a water
pitcher at a prosecutor while his mother was on the stand. He also
fashioned various weapons in his cell and used one to stab a guard.
He later stabbed another. Later, he would attack 10 more.
</P>
<P>
   Like Officer Richard Lockwood. Vickers threw a homemade bomb
which exploded behind him in March 1980. When Lockwood ap proached
him, Vickers kicked him in the groin.
</P>
<P>
   Three months before, Vickers used a ballpoint pen to stab an
officer in the head who was bring ing dinner to his cell. In early
1981, Vickers stabbed yet another officer in the chest with an
8-inch shank while the officer was pouring him a cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers also once escaped from death row and climbed atop the
roof of Cellblock 6 through a shaft with another inmate. Vickers
had man aged to short circuit the electronic locking mechanism on
his cell door and left a dummy in his bed.
</P>
<P>
   Once atop the compound, how ever, the two realized they had no
place to go. The outside fence was too far away. It was too high to
jump to the ground below.
</P>
<P>
   The two then did a striptease for a woman tower guard who
spotted them before they were caught by other officers rushing to
the roof, said corrections officer Jim Robi deau.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Vickers slipped his restraints while in a visitation
area, dashed down a corridor past startled guards while flinging
homemade ``shanks'' at two inmates in their cells.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks before, angered about not promptly receiving a
Christmas gift, Vickers threatened to ``kill a pig before Christ
mas...rolling in their blood squeal ing,'' according to prison
records.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers also celebrated the Christmas season that year by ask
ing a guard for a couple .22 caliber rounds so he and another
inmate he called ``Gypsy'' could kill a third inmate they both
detested.
</P>
<P>
   When the guard responded in the negative, Vickers said, ``It
never hurts to ask.'' It was years since Vickers was permitted
access to any electronic equipment. In the past, he'd made weapons
out of typewriter parts, pop-up stereo antennas, television cables
and even by scratching chips from the wall of his cell.
</P>
<P>
   At a prison hearing last Decem ber, officials waived the
necessity of Vicker's presence because of safety concerns. They
also were relieved this week when Vickers decided not to attend his
Tuesday clemency hearing.
</P>
<P>
   It was a chronic concern. In 1988, a prison memo warned that
guards had seen Vickers starting to work out with weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be advised,'' it said, ``this behavior is usually the start of
a routine prior to his stabbing some one.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, not everyone viewed Vickers as a vicious monster. Gray,
Vickers' former attorney, says he holds the state of Arizona
responsible for Ponciano's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing in (Vickers') juvenile record of violence,''
Gray said. ``Why did the state put a skinny kid thief in the same
cell with a second-degree murderer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did the state also refuse to pay for Bob's mental-health
coun seling when he was transferred to California as a juvenile?''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Spenser, a former inmate who knew Vickers well, said he
definitely needed psychiatric coun seling.
</P>
<P>
   Spenser said Vickers believed that he lived with a pet
alligator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks to him...he sits him on his shoulder. I watched him
with a mirror and he puts that alligator to bed every night at the
foot of the bed,'' Spenser said.
</P>
<P>
   Another inmate, Roy Turrentine, remembers Vickers cutting his
throat with a razor on five occa sions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason that the dude didn't cut himself bad enough to
bleed to death,'' he said, ``was 'cause the only kind of razors we
had out there were the safety razors.''
</P>
<P>
   For sheer brutality, Vickers outdid even himself in his 1982
attack on Holsinger, which also nearly killed a half-dozen other
inmates from smoke inhalation and which forced officials to
evacuate Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers, who was assigned the job of a porter cellblock
attendant, flew into a rage after Holsinger made lewd comments
about a pic ture Vickers was displaying of his 11-year-old niece.
</P>
<P>
   About a minute later, records show, Vickers returned to the
front of Holsinger's cell with his flamma ble concoction. He threw
it in, burning the inmate and igniting a large collection of legal
documents.
</P>
<P>
   later court testimony indicated that Vickers threw a second fire
bomb into Holsinger's cell just make sure.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Vickers asked investi gators, ``Did I do a good
job?...I told them they should have gassed me in December when they
had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time Vickers had demanded death. In a
letter the previous year to then-Gov. Bruce Babbitt, he'd written,
``So what's the hold up fella?
</P>
<P>
   ``If ya don't do it soon, I'm gonna draw more blood than your
cheap mops can absorb. I'm a very impatient person, I never did
like waiting. I've got a date with the devil's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix attorney Ben Cooper said Vickers had toned down con
siderably in the past 10 years and hasn't been charged with any
violent acts. But DOC records indicate two assaults by Vickers
during the period.
</P>
<P>
   Vickers never lost his violent edge, even near the end.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Lopez, a corrections officer who had counseled Vickers on
a daily basis, said Wednesday he was looking in Vickers' cell one
recent morning and angered the con demned man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lopez, I know you're not an evil (expletive) but I'm in an
evil mood,'' Lopez said, recalling the smirk on Vickers' face.
Lopez also said that Vickers had lamented aloud in recent months
that he hadn't assaulted any prison staff members in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   But, always, there was that swag ger.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, Vickers gave a prison officer a weapon resem
bling a crossbow that he had crafted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised you a rubber band gun some day so here it is,''
Vickers wrote to the officer. ``I call this the cell warrior
g-57...it can go THROUGH the human skull and brains, the tip and
shaft.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the neatly hand-written letter, Vickers asked: ``How's
the family?'' &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057, or at
mark.shaffer &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
