<HEADLINE>
JUNIOR PITCHER, TEXAS-ARLINGTON BASEBALL TEAM REDISCOVER SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ To get where he is this season, and to help
get the Texas-Arlington baseball team in the Southland Conference
tournament, Ben Grundhauser had to go back.
</P>
<P>
   He had to try something, anything.
</P>
<P>
   The junior left-handed pitcher was mired in a slump.
</P>
<P>
   His earned-run average held steady near 6.50, and the guy who
had established himself as one of Texas-Arlington's top starters in
fall scrimmages was having trouble getting anybody out.
Texas-Arlington was also off to a poor start, and there was no end
in sight for either.
</P>
<P>
   But look at Grundhauser now. His ERA is 1.94 in his past five
starts.
</P>
<P>
   And look at the Mavericks. They have won 11 of their past 16.
</P>
<P>
   Grundhauser went back to what worked in the fall. As simple as
the whole thing sounds, throwing strikes was the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started getting ahead of hitters and getting the ball over
the plate,'' Grundhauser said. ``Instead of trying to throw the
perfect pitch, I was trying to get people out. The defense has
played great. Everybody, including me, has really gained some
confidence back.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Grundhauser throwing like he did in the fall, he's
doing it consistently in crucial conference games down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   In his past five starts, Grundhauser has three victories and a
no decision. His complete-game victory Saturday against Nicholls
State clinched Texas-Arlington a spot in the SLC postseason
tournament and gave coach Butch McBroom his 800th collegiate
victory.
</P>
<P>
   McBroom said Grundhauser has helped give the entire team a lift.
After a 1-5 start in the SLC, Texas-Arlington finished 14-13 for
fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-Arlington opens the SLC tournament May 15 at 11 a.m.
against Northwestern State in Monroe, La.
</P>
<P>
   Grundhauser might be the starter in that first game, McBroom
said. Coaches will make that decision at the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has given us a go-to guy,'' McBroom said. ``When he goes
out there, the guys expect to win. That's something we didn't have
early in the season. We talked to him a while ago and said, `Do
what you were doing in the fall, because you don't have to do any
more than that.' He started to get back to that, and he has really
pitched well.''
</P>
<P>
   What Grundhauser has done for Texas-Arlington lately is what
coaches expected all along.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks recruited him out of Yavapai (Ariz.) College, and
he played last summer for Texas-Arlington assistant coach Clay
Gould in the Jayhawk League. A solid summer season had coaches
excited about him challenging for a spot in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   A good fall helped solidify his spot in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   But Grundhauser said arm soreness early in the spring season and
a few bad starts hurt his confidence and inflated his ERA, which
now stands at 5.09. His turnaround began against Southeastern
Louisiana on March 20 when he went seven innings, allowed six hits
and one run for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm feels good now, and I'm getting my routine down,''
Grundhauser said. ``I expected better out of myself at first. At
least I was able to turn it around in time and start winning, and
the team was able to turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Grundhauser reversed it by going back to what was working.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a reason Texas-Arlington is in the SLC tournament
after not qualifying last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing as well as anybody in the league right now, and
we have as good a chance as any team to win that tournament,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Darrin Scheid writes about college sports for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 548-5451. E-mail:
sportszone(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
