<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6323 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UIL-TEX     05-06 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UIL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SENATE APPROVES OPENING ASSOCIATION TO PRIVATE SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A bill that would allow private schools to
compete in district events sanctioned by the University
Interscholastic League won preliminary approval in the Senate
yesterday, but a limit was placed on how many schools would be
affected.
</P>
<P>
   If the bill becomes law, only six private schools in Texas, none
in Tarrant County, would be eligible to participate in
public-school districts in athletic and academic competitions
governed by the UIL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh gosh, everyone is amazed,'' said Dallas Jesuit football
coach Bob Wunderlick, whose school would be eligible to compete in
the UIL. ``There are six steps to a bill and we've gotten past
five. Nobody thought we'd get there. The UIL is very much against
it, but we are pleasantly surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires the six schools to adhere to the same
standards that the UIL imposes on public schools, and that the
private schools have at least 500 students and be either all-boy or
all-girl academies.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Armbrister, D-Victoria, author of Senate Bill 266, said he
limited the number of schools covered by the measure in order to
ensure that it would pass.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 29 senators present yesterday, 22 supported the bill. A
final vote to send the bill to the House is expected today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we wanted,'' Dallas Jesuit athletic director
Steve Koch said.
</P>
<P>
   UIL officials have been advised not to comment on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bill said that private schools often are better
funded than public schools and therefore would have access to
superior equipment and facilities and could afford to hire better
coaching staffs.
</P>
<P>
   But Armbrister said the bill is structured to ensure that the
private schools meet the same standards the UIL imposes on public
schools. All the private-school students would have to take the
Texas Assessment of Academic Skills, meet public schools'
attendance standards, and abide by the state's no-pass, no-play
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Private schools will adhere to the same attendance boundaries as
the nearest public school. In Jesuit's case, it would match
attendance zones with Dallas White. Any student-athlete who enrolls
at Jesuit from outside the boundary will be ineligible to
participate in varsity athletics for one year. The same standard
applies to public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Koch said his school would have no problem meeting the criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it makes sense to want to join the UIL,'' said Koch,
whose school has 850 students. ``To play a football game, sometimes
we have to go all the way to El Paso to find a school our size.
That's 1,700 miles round trip. That means the kids miss a lot of
study time. I'll bet we pass 1,700 other high schools along the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The other schools covered by the bill are Houston Strake Jesuit,
St. Thomas School for boys and St. Agnes School for girls; El Paso
Cathedral for boys; and San Antonio Providence High School for
girls.
</P>
<P>
   Before it becomes law, the bill has two more hurdles to pass
before the legislative session ends May 31. The House must pass it
and then Gov. George W. Bush must sign it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The latter is the easy of the two hurdles left,'' Koch said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
