A6327 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COCAINE-ARIZ-AZR &LR;      05-06 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCAINE-ARIZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$500 MILLION IN COCAINE SEIZED NEAR ARIZONA CAPITOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM HERMANN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Phoenix police responding to a burglary call Wednesday
stumbled upon a half-billion dollars worth of Colombian cocaine
about a mile from the State Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure, the biggest in Phoenix police history and one of
the biggest ever in Arizona, carries an ominous message for the
Valley, according to the local chief of the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix has arrived,'' Special Agent Thomas Raffanello said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that the Valley is right up there at the top as a
drug trans-shipment point.''
</P>
<P>
   Three patrol officers discovered about one ton of cocaine _
which police said would be worth about $500 million on the street _
about 4 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a call of a burglary in progress this morning at a
house near 25th Avenue and Buckeye,'' Officer Ritche Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
   The officers went into the back yard and found two men carrying
boxes out of the house, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stopped them, I looked into a box, and thought, `Wow!'''
</P>
<P>
   The two men were arrested for trafficking and booked into a
Maricopa County jail, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When Ramos and Officers John Hobbs and Sean Burton figured out
what they had on their hands _ 997 2.2 pound (1 kilo) bricks of
cocaine _ they called for reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the whole squad there and we got the dope out pretty
quickly,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Phoenix Chief Irwin Bakin said, ``This obviously
raises the question, if this is what we just stumble on, how much
more is out there?
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got the low-hanging fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Drug Enforcement Bureau Lt. Alton Thiele said, ``We
wouldn't have seen anything like this a few years ago. This clearly
illustrates just what kind of a trans-shipment point we have
become.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon most of the bureau's detectives were
weighing and inventorying the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Thiele said it was as yet unclear who was responsible for
importing the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone is going to be very, very angry about this,'' Thiele
said as detectives lugged the cocaine over to scales, weighed it,
then took it to an undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
   The officers found the bricks of cocaine packed in 45 large
cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were packed in Styrofoam, and the boxes looked like they
were ready to be mailed,'' Detective Mike McCullough said.
</P>
<P>
   Raffanello said Phoenix ``just seems to be the new place for
trans-shipment.'' He said cocaine typically is moved by airplane
from Colombia into central Mexico, or by ship from Colombia into
the Yucatan Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it travels by land north to Arizona ports of entry
such as Nogales or Douglas _ just a few hours' drive from the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``And here we have a very big international airport, we have
freeways going east and west,'' Raffanello said. ``It's perfect for
trans-shipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Raffanello, Phoenix Police Chief Harold Hurtt, Maricopa County
Attorney Rick Romley and other local officials recently joined in
asking the federal government to name central Arizona a High
Intensity Drug Trafficking Area.
</P>
<P>
   Such a designation would bring about $5.8 million yearly to fund
a drug-fighting task force and to distribute funds to federal,
state, county and city law agencies to support existing anti-drug
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Raffanello and Hurtt said they want the designation to help them
fight the many drug-trafficking organizations that now call the
Valley home.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, about 10 such organizations existed locally.
Today, Hurtt said, there are about 28.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of National Drug Control Policy has yet to announce
whether central Arizona will receive a HIDTA designation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly could use the support,'' Raffanello said. ``If
we're practically falling over this amount of drugs in a house near
downtown Phoenix, you've got to wonder how much more is out there
for us to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Raffanello said the largest drug find in Arizona history was
5,310 kilograms of cocaine found in a Tucson warehouse in 1996. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 0144EDT &QL; 
