<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6349 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-06 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ There are times, even now when those 3-pointers are
falling as soft and pretty as spring snowflakes in the Rockies,
that Michael Dickerson isn't so sure he's going to thrive or even
survive in this league.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA is an in-your-face place, a world of strutting, crowing
and telling the world that you've got game. It's Allen Iverson
never meeting a shot he didn't like, and it's Kevin Garnett shaking
the backboard with a slam dunk and howling like a wolf in the
night.
</P>
<P>
   It's Stephon Marbury forcing the breakup of a playoff contender,
and it's Kobe Bryant leaping from high school to TV spots and
jumping right over the part about fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   It is into this place that Rockets rookie Dickerson fits about
as neatly as a hip-hop singer in the Mormon Tabernacle Choir. He'd
make a monk seem rowdy, make a library seem like a carnival
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the Rockets closed out the regular season with a 95-88
win over the Nuggets and head into the playoffs, any noise they can
make in the next few weeks will only be louder if Dickerson is a
part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's athletic, he's talented, and he's just learning about all
of the things he can do on the basketball court,'' said Scottie
Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an amazing talent,'' said Charles Barkley. ``And if we're
going to be able to do anything at all in the playoffs, we're going
to have to take full advantage of people like Michael and Scottie.
We know what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers scout sitting courtside at McNichols Arena knows,
too. On back-to-back nights, he has seen Dickerson zap the
Minnesota Timberwolves like the heat in a microwave for 31 points,
then come right back to drill the Nuggets for another 27.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't just a roll Dickerson is on. All of a sudden, he's a
boulder hurtling down the side of a mountain. He connected on five
of six from beyond the 3-point line Wednesday. He pulled up off the
dribble and dropped in sweet jumpers around the key. He got out on
the perimeter to play aggressive defense that forced turnovers, and
he streaked to the other end of the floor to finish off fast breaks
with a couple of dunks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, I'm just feeling good about myself right now,''
Dickerson said. ``The way we're making an effort to get the ball
off the boards and push it up the court in a faster pace definitely
helps me. But all I'm trying to do is fill in the spots where I can
help and make a play if the ball comes to me. I don't know if this
is the real me scoring all these points every night.''
</P>
<P>
   If humility were money, Dickerson would be richer than several
sheiks.
</P>
<P>
   With him, it's not a false front or an aw-shucks manner that
simply covers up for being shy. This is a kid who was an integral
part of a national champion at Arizona, was chosen No. 14 overall
by the Rockets in the 1998 draft, scored in double figures 24 times
this season and yet could still use a confidence boost.
</P>
<P>
   When his shot stopped falling and his offense sagged for several
weeks, the rookie wondered. About what to do to snap out of it.
About whether he would have a long future in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get my doubts at times,'' Dickerson said. ``I miss a few
shots, and I wonder if I should take them. Then I don't take the
shots, and I find that I'm not doing a lot to help the team. I ask
questions. I'm unsure.''
</P>
<P>
   And in those cases, he kneels and prays.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Lord has helped me in so many ways through this season,''
he said. ``I can't tell you the number of times I've gotten down on
my knees and asked for his help, begged for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson has also gotten help from another source _ Eddie
Johnson, who has spent the season on the injured list but still
made his contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing with Scottie, Charles and Hakeem because they
are so special,'' Dickerson said. ``But Eddie is the one who is
teaching me how to be a shooter and a scorer in this league. He
talks to me all the time about the things I have to do. He's the
one who is always saying the things to boost my confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what if you miss two or three or four shots in a row? A
scorer has to take the next one, knowing it will go in. You know,
that's not part of my natural makeup. But Eddie's pushing me, and I
guess it's paying off.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much of this season's focus on the Big Three of the
Rockets, it is probably appropriate that their fate in the playoffs
will rest a great deal in the hands of Dickerson and Cuttino
Mobley, the rookie backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The veterans tell us that it will be rough and tough, you've
got to be strong,'' Dickerson said. ``Actually, I'm kind of
curious.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they know they will open the playoffs against the Lakers at
the Forum, that they will have to claim at least one road win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we were dealt,'' Dickerson said. ``So we deal with
it, and for me and Cuttino we learn in the process. I'm ready. My
confidence is up.''
</P>
<P>
   At just the right time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 0221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
