<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6351 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CELTICS-HORNETS-B     05-06 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-HORNETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS END ON LOSING NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was the shortest season in modern NBA history. It
was also the weirdest. If you can accept those facts, you will have
no problem understanding the Celtics' final loss of the spring
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   On Fan Appreciation Night, an evening when players and coaches
greeted the 16,635 fans at the turnstiles and handed out T-shirts,
the Celtics played their longest home game of the year. It took 58
minutes and two overtimes, but the Hornets finally won, 133-129.
Boston's loss was its 31st in 50 games. Depending on whom you ask,
that was somewhere between six and 10 more losses than a lot of
people expected when the season began exactly three months ago
(M.L. Carr did not say what his projected win total was for Rick
Pitino's team).
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing what could have and should have been is what you might
expect at the end of a season. But no one in green and white was
ready for the performances of Brad Miller and Ricky Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whew, that's tough,'' Ron Mercer said, after being told the
two rookies combined for 64 points off the bench. ``But I'll take
credit for Ricky Davis. I worked out with him during the summer, so
I have to take credit for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't feel badly if you have never heard of Miller and Davis.
Miller is a 6-foot-11-inch center known primarily for playing on
USA Basketball's bronze-medal team that played in the World
Championships at Athens last summer. Davis is a 6-7 teenage forward
(he's 19) known for . . . being a nice guy?
</P>
<P>
   In any case, both players posted up around, jump shot over, and
dunked on the Celtics until each had 32 points. It's a good thing
the Celtics didn't hand out Hornets media guides before the game
because the fans might have collectively flipped between pages 51
and 68, trying to figure out what made Davis and Miller so special.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took them lightly,'' Celtics forward Antoine Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   That is obvious when you look at the stat sheet and check points
off the bench. The Celtics got 45 points from their reserves, 23
from Walker, normally a starter. The Hornets? Try 85 points. Think
of the last time you heard someone say a team got 85 points off the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing was normal about the game. The Celtics appeared to
be finished late in the fourth. That's when Miller got good
position inside and dunked to make it 104-96. The Celtics tied it
at 109 when Paul Pierce made a 24-foot 3-pointer from the corner.
That would be the score going into the first OT.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics were positioned to win at the end of the first
overtime, leading by 3 with 8.1 seconds left. But then another
player who will not appear on an All-Star ballot near you _ Corey
Beck _ made a three to send the game into yet another OT.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't seem familiar until the final minute of the second
overtime. That's when former All-Star Eddie Jones made a terrific
baseline shot _ falling away from the hoop _ to break a 129-all tie
and, essentially, give the Hornets their winning points. The
Celtics got some serious numbers from Pierce (27 points, 9
rebounds, 5 assists), Dana Barros (26 points, 9 assists, 7 rebounds
in 52 minutes) and Mercer (23 points, career-high 10 rebounds). It
wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made some shots and Eddie Jones is a bitch to guard
one-on-one,'' Pitino said.
</P>
<P>
   He could have had the same lament about the team's season, which
seemed to last much longer than 50 games. It was a season in which
talk-radio callers were offended by the coach, a season in which
Kenny Anderson was told not to make a trip to Florida because of
his behavior, a season in which Walker was booed on a Wednesday
night and given a standing ovation two nights later, and a season
in which the eternally optimistic Pitino said it was his least
enjoyable in two and a half decades.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media put us on this high pedestal with the Utah Jazz,''
Walker said after his 23-point, 8-rebound, 7-assist night. ``We're
a young team and it's going to take chemistry to get to Utah's
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah may be a stretch; most fans dreamed of a break-even season.
Every Celtic agreed Wednesday night that it was far from that. They
said they tried hard and were encouraged by their late-season
development. But in the end, they found themselves talking about
losing a game because Brad Miller and Ricky Davis beat them. And
for the fourth consecutive season, they wound up skipping the
postseason and talking about next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
