<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAD END TO SORRY SEASON FOR SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What a place to go down. In Tinseltown. Against
the Clippers. In the seedy old Sports Arena, where Wednesday night
there was a party of all things because the grunge pit is about to
be imploded.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics could not have found a worse place, a worse way to
end their sorry, nutball, playoff-less season _ except that they
showed enough Sonic pride to hold off the typically inept home
team.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a big night out. Even Bill Walton showed up. For one
night, it was almost noble to be an ex-Clipper. And the Sonics had
to be there just to take up space, to try to hold their heads up,
despite the disappointment of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bitter pill,'' coach Paul Westphal said after the
107-105 win.
</P>
<P>
   If there was supposed to be teary sentiment or overtones of
nostalgia over successful Sonic seasons past, you could not find it
among the Sonics. They had a week to digest their postseason-less
plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to watch a playoff game. I could care less who
wins,'' Vin Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no crying in the cramped visitors' locker room, where
Gary Payton munched on sliced melon and Billy Owens checked out his
cell phone and Baker sauntered around in his sweat pants, sipping
on a can of fruit juice.
</P>
<P>
   There was no nostalgia on the faded court of the Sports Arena,
where Payton took turns lambasting Vladimir Stepania and Rashard
Lewis for their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   And there was not much nostalgia in the hearts of most veteran
Sonic players _ Detlef Schrempf, Payton and Hersey Hawkins _ who
have to wonder if there is a way to get back to great expectations
in their basketball lifetimes.
</P>
<P>
   Those three were the only ones left this season from the team
that took Michael Jordan and the Bulls to Game 6 of the 1996 NBA
Finals, and that was what was so weird Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to play in this game,'' Schrempf said before
the final game of the futile season in which the Sonics find
themselves at the biggest crossroads in perhaps a decade.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time the Sonics played games at the end of the
regular season that meant nothing?
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time this team did not believe itself to be a
legitimate contender, if not for the NBA championship then at least
for the Pacific Division title or the Western Conference crown?
</P>
<P>
   The valley is deep that divides '96 and now.
</P>
<P>
   The question is how long might it take for the Sonics to climb
out?
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to shoot the ball better. We need some more help in
the backcourt. We need a stronger inside game both offensively and
defensively. We need to have the core group back in the best shape
of their lives,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Sonics president Wally Walker was talking
about not over-reacting. He called upon 1995 as an example, when he
did not break apart a team that had lost in the first round of the
NBA playoffs. The next year the Sonics went to Game 6 of the
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   But the remaining nucleus of that Sonics contender could break
apart anyway. Asked if he was at all sentimental about putting on
his Sonics' jersey for perhaps the last time, Schrempf shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even want to put it on tonight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fates of Schrempf and Hawkins are a priority issue for the
Sonics this offseason. Schrempf is a player Westphal and the Sonics
are eager to have back. However, Schrempf appears willing to let
the free-agent market come to him, should he decide not to retire.
And if an offer presents itself to go to a contender, especially in
the West, then it would not be a surprise if this stalwart Sonic
takes a one-year deal with the Lakers or San Antonio or Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   If Wednesday was the last time Hawkins suited up in Sonic green
and white, it would be a shame.
</P>
<P>
   The epitome of an NBA professional, Hawkins has been every bit
the heart, soul and conscience of the Sonics since he arrived. But
there is reason to suspect that in the revamping, Hawkins could be
traded, if it was the best way to bring in backcourt help so that
Payton can slide to the off-guard spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very disappointed,'' Hawkins said about his
possible trade.
</P>
<P>
   There are even questions about Baker ... questions he raises
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The power forward who had the worst season of his career will
opt out of his contract this summer. But he refused to say for sure
he will be with the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are my first choice but I have to weigh all my options,''
he said, promising that he is too nice a guy to just be talking
tough for negotiation posturing _ and we have to believe him,
especially because there could be part of Baker that would prefer
to play closer to his parents' home in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Celtics have been scouting me since I was in high
school,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, everyone understood that when the Sonics signed Payton
to that well-deserved, long-term deal, the Sonics would become
Payton's team. But Wednesday night, as we took our last look at the
Sonics during this nutball season, the biggest problem that
appeared to be sprouting is that Payton could be the only player of
consequence left on what looks to be a team in transition.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 0224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0038 </DOCNO>
