<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS RAP RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-RANGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There's nothing wrong with the Red Sox that a little
quality starting pitching won't cure. But the question is: where
will they find some in games Pedro Martinez doesn't pitch?
</P>
<P>
   Veteran righthander Pat Rapp is among those searching for
answers. He recorded only one out Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night and was the
victim of a five-run, first-inning assault as the Texas Rangers
routed the Red Sox, 8-3, before 20,906 at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the third straight for Boston and sixth in eight
games. The Rangers have won five straight on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really felt comfortable out there,'' said Rapp. ``I
couldn't control my fastball. I'd get behind on a guy and every
pitch they hit was hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just haven't done it as a starting staff. Unfortunately,
we're putting a lot of pressure on the bullpen, which we weren't
expected to do this early in the season. Hopefully, we can bounce
back.''
</P>
<P>
   After posting his only victory of the year in his previous start
(at Minnesota), Rapp appeared as though he could help stabilize the
rotation. But he came back with the shortest outing of his career.
Granted, the Texas Rangers are not the Minnesota Twins. Before
Wednesday, the Rangers had scored 21 runs in 18 innings against
Rapp when he was with Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   They added five runs Wednesday, pushing Rapp's career earned run
average against Texas to 12.90. Rapp walked leadoff man Tom
Goodwin, then following a Mark McLemore strikeout, walked Rusty
Greer. Singles by Juan Gonzalez and Rafael Palmeiro gave Texas a
2-0 lead. Ivan Rodriguez then upped the ante with a three-run
homer. Two batters later (Todd Zeile single, Lee Stevens walk),
Rapp was done.
</P>
<P>
   He was replaced by John Wasdin, who was something of a savior to
the Sox bullpen. Wasdin, who was recalled from Pawtucket Tuesday,
gave up two runs over 6 2/3 innings, giving his fellow relievers a
bit of a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough playing catch up,'' said manager Jimy Williams,
``especially when their pitcher (Rick Helling) is throwing well and
they are playing good defense behind him. Rapp pitched good in
Minnesota. But these things happen once in a while. In our case, it
has been in consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasdin picked us up. He gave us a chance to get back into it.
But then their pitching and defense just stopped us. We had a
couple of chances early and couldn't score. Then we ran out of
innings.''
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, Nomar Garciaparra hit his first home run of
the season, a two-run shot into the screen in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp said he has been working on his mechanics, mostly his
delivery, since spring training. It hasn't always been helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've changed a lot of things since spring,'' said Rapp. ``But
it's just hard to take into a game what you learned during the week
when you've only had a week to change something. Tonight, I didn't
take it into the game. I wasn't comfortable out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said he appreciates Rapp's honesty
in what could be a difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not comfortable?,'' said Kerrigan. ``They have a team that
makes you that way. I look at his sheet against them and you find
that Gonzalez is hitting .625, Goodwin .400, Greer .444, McLemore
.500, Pudge Rodriguez .555. I'd feel a little uncomfortable, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat is a very good pitcher. But he still has some delivery
issues. Nothing drastic. Nothing major. He's not as good as he
wants to be with first-pitch strikes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 0224EDT &QL; 
