<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6354 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-06 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESA MUTES CLEVELAND BOO-BIRDS AS M'S ENJOY LATE RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ For Jose Mesa, the boos started well before the
ninth inning Wednesday night, when 42,991 fans dumped jeers on him
in full force.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was expecting that,'' Mariners first baseman David
Segui said. ``He said he was hearing it all night in the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs Field is ``Home of Baseball's Best Fans'' _ it says so on
top of the visitors dugout _ and the Cleveland Indians have sold
out every game there for almost four years. The fans are giddy for
their team, but they come with an edge. In last year's American
League Championship Series, then-Yankee David Wells complained that
fans mocked his late mother as he warmed up in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Wells won that game. And Mesa saved this one, a 6-5 Mariners win
over a team he spent six years with before being traded nine months
after blowing the save in Game 7 of the 1997 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I like that,'' said M's reliever Jose Paniagua, who
set up Mesa with 22/3 shutout innings. ``If fans do that, it makes
me feel stronger. Mesa told me that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa wasn't saying much of anything afterward, making good on a
pregame promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking about Cleveland, or anything else,'' he told a
reporter. ``After I save my 40th game, I'll have a big press
conference. Talk for two hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooperative? Not Wednesday anyway. Confident? Apparently so.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa started the inning by falling behind Kenny Lofton 2-and-0.
But he came back to strike him out on a forkball, a pitch he has
claimed the Indians never would not let him use. He got the next
out when Segui speared a ground ball by Enrique Wilson, making the
catch behind his head on his glove side after the ball took a bad
hop.
</P>
<P>
   A walk to Roberto Alomar followed, but Manny Ramirez lined to
second to end it.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa now is 7-for-7 in save opportunities despite an unsightly
28.93 earned run average in all other games.
</P>
<P>
   M's manager Lou Piniella said he was proud of the way Mesa
handled the environment, but his highest praise was for Paniagua,
who relieved Jeff Fassero (1-3) with the bases loaded and one out
in the sixth. Wilson hit a first-pitch screamer to third baseman
Russ Davis, who caught it and threw to first to double off Lofton.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua, who last pitched on Saturday, sailed through the next
two innings for his longest outing of the year. He now has a 1.04
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he came here for the last two months of last season,''
Piniella said, ``he's been our most reliable pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero worked 51/3 innings and allowed nine hits _ tying him
for the top spot in the AL in that category with teammate Jamie
Moyer. He was aided by defense in the third inning, when center
fielder Ken Griffey Jr. threw out Wilson trying to score on a
sacrifice fly, and again in the fourth, when shortstop Rafael
Bournigal made a diving grab of a liner by David Justice with a
runner on second.
</P>
<P>
   But Fassero, who allowed two homers to Travis Fryman, won for
the first time this season. The M's won for the third time in a row
when he pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``In games that I've pitched, we're 3-4, and two of those losses
definitely could have been wins,'' Fassero said. ``Right now, my
goal is to get the team to .500 in games I pitch and just keep
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners got their runs in typical fashion _ with a trio of
two-run homers, by David Bell and John Mabry in the first inning
and Dan Wilson in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's homer, his ninth of the year, crashed off the front of a
souvenir stand in left field, 421 feet from home plate. He has
never hit 10 balls out of the park in a season; his career-high of
10 was aided by an inside-the-park homer he hit against the M's as
an Indian last April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good up there,'' Bell said. ``I always come back to
what Lou and I talked about as far as taking more pitches. I know
it sounds weird, but when you walk more, you're more aggressive.
Your reactions kind of take over. If it's not a good pitch, you
take it. That's the only thing I can say I feel different.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa's feelings will have to wait for another day. But if it
truly takes until that 40th save, here's a bulletin: he's on pace
for 42.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
