<HEADLINE>
SOURCES SAY POLYNICE STINT OVER WITH SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He was the last player to arrive at the Sports
Arena, and wielded a handful of tickets when he did.
</P>
<P>
   Olden Polynice lives here in the offseason. His ties are strong,
so the center had to accommodate people before the Sonics beat the
Los Angeles Clippers 107-105 Wednesday night in their
regular-season finale.
</P>
<P>
   That Polynice curiously did not play for a second straight game
meant more than giving younger players experience.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Polynice plays host before an NBA game, he will
not be in the Sonics' uniform or locker room. The
Post-Intelligencer has learned the Sonics will not re-sign
Polynice.
</P>
<P>
   Though Polynice gave the Sonics rebounds and energy, his
attitude was often considered detrimental, according to team
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice, who signed a one-year contract with the Sonics before
this season, becomes a free agent July 1. Polynice said he will
pursue a winning situation, not money, in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, I think I did what they asked me to do,''
Polynice said. ``I think I had a pretty good year. I'd like to come
back. But that's a decision they have to make. I wish we could have
made the playoffs and had a better record; then it would have been
a lot easier to make certain decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sentiment within the team is that the Sonics also will pass on
bringing back forward Aaron Williams, whose constant struggles with
plays cost him. The Sonics will try to move forward Don MacLean in
a trade that could land them a solid point guard Gary Payton
trusts.
</P>
<P>
   The team wants to phase Payton in at shooting guard if they can
sign a player who can handle the ball slightly more than half the
game. That would mean bringing Hersey Hawkins off the bench _ a
move Hawkins has already endorsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to flow better at the two,'' Hawkins said of Payton.
</P>
<P>
   There still is a possibility the Sonics could attempt a trade
involving Hawkins to get a quality point guard or front line
player. It would also rid the team's salary cap of the $8.7million
Hawkins has left on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a genius to figure that out,'' said Hawkins,
32. ``When you look at the team, who else can you get something
for. They're not going to get rid of the young guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice, though, will be one of the most noticeable absentee
next season.
</P>
<P>
   No one could ever accuse Poly-nice of not knowing his role. He
adequately filled the Sonics' rebounding void at center with 8.9
boards a game.
</P>
<P>
   But his brutally honest remarks have made him expendable.
Polynice's indiscreet comments also made him difficult to live
with, according to insiders. Polynice never questioned game
strategy but, at times, he publicly wondered about coach Paul
Westphal's communication.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice said it was a matter of ``respect'' when Westphal told
him five minutes before the April 18 game at Phoenix that he would
not start. On other occasions, Polynice was unhappy about his
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when he said things that didn't need to be
said,'' one Sonic player said. ``Sometimes when things happen you
just have to accept it and move on. He wasn't always able to do
that. Sometimes it was a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not unreasonable to believe the Sonics would entrust
rookie Jelani McCoy at center. McCoy turned in aggressive, tough,
sometimes veteran-like performances this season.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Polynice is not a superstar. Therefore, he
was not given much leeway with the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a Charles Barkley, who are very direct and honest,''
Polynice said. ``So why is it that I can't be honest as well?
Because I don't have the status of a Charles Barkley that means I
have to lie? No. If I'm asked a question, I'll answer it as
honestly as I can. I'm not going to please everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to live my life. There's bigger things than this job.
I'm going to retire in a couple of years. If I have to walk around
saying I lied to somebody or I did something I was against, I'm
going to feel worse.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, those who brought Polynice aboard felt he lived up
to his reputation. He is good when things go well. But when things
go sour, the rap on Polynice has been his poor attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice said that is an unfair criticism. ``When I'm
interviewed, I'm not going to talk bad about anybody, knock a
teammate or anything like that,'' Polynice said. ``But if I'm asked
a question about what I see, I'm going to be truthful. People have
to respect that. They may not like it. But they have to respect it.
That's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked of he would disappointed if he did not return to the
Sonics, Polynice flatly said ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a family to support,'' he said. ``What I would regret
not coming back is not being able to right the wrong as a team. ...
Paul is one of the nicest guys you want to meet. I don't envy Paul
and (team president) Wally Walker at all. This season was tough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
