<HEADLINE>
RICE'S BIG NIGHT CARRIES LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ From game one to game 1,464, from the days of West
to the days of Magic to the present, with their legacy framed in
six championship banners on the south wall, the 1999 Lakers paid an
appropriate honor Wednesday to the past and to three glorious
decades at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   In the final regular-season game at the Forum, the Lakers played
near-flawless basketball for a 119-91 rout of the Portland Trail
Blazers _ and in doing so, guaranteed themselves a chance to play
in the venerable arena for a while longer.
</P>
<P>
   The victory secured home-court advantage for their best-of-five,
first-round playoff series which begins Sunday against the Houston
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing was, the Laker with the least time on the Forum
floor seemed to feel the most at home on Wednesday. Glen Rice, his
former shooting woes now a faint memory, hit a
franchise-record-tying eight 3-pointers and made 14 of 20 field
goals to score a season-high 40 points.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before, Rice voiced frustration with his role in the
offense. Suddenly, he (begin ital)was(end ital) the offense. And
feeling understandably chipper about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you go out and play as well as I did tonight and the
crowd responded the way they do, it's definitely uplifting,'' he
said. ``I just have to keep going out there and doing the things
that I did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice's roll started when he hit an 18-foot jumper on the Lakers'
first possession of the night. It was clear his teammates wanted a
more involved Rice as they fed him pass after pass. And Rice repaid
their confidence, scoring 15 first-half points, then exploding for
18 in the third quarter as he made all six 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun. When you have a guy hot like that, you have to
keep milking it,'' he said. ``It was really evident that they were
trying to keep giving the ball to me, and that's what you have to
do when you have a guy hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice's third-quarter 3-fest took a modest Laker lead and turned
it into a 27-point margin by the time the fourth quarter had
arrived. Rice could do no wrong, as even off-balance jumpers made
with an opponent's hand in his face found their way through the
net.
</P>
<P>
   It had the Lakers bench hopping and the fans giving Rice a
standing ovation when he checked out of the game in the fourth. Two
months after arriving in a much-debated trade, Rice had won a
symbolic embrace from the home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying all along that he has to learn to play within
our system and with the guys that we have,'' coach Kurt Rambis
said. ``It's just very nice that it came together for him in the
last game of the regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   Just one more possible headache for opponents who already had to
contend with Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by Rice's hot hand, the Lakers shot 51.3 percent as a
team and thoroughly dominated Portland in every area, holding the
Blazers to 43 percent shooting and outrebounding them 43-38. The
119 points was a season-high, the margin of victory equaled their
largest this season and for the second straight game, the suddenly
selfless Lakers dished out 30 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Only eight days ago, the Lakers hit their season low point,
losing three straight and six in an eight-game span. They were
playing no defense, running the offense with zero precision and
generally looking like a team that had been irreparably damaged by
an overdose of change. That, and Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after closing out the season with four straight wins, all
impressive, the Lakers not only look ready for the playoffs, they
even _ dare we say _ appear ready for a championship run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel good going into the playoffs,'' Bryant said, ``but we
have to continue with the same mindset _ that's the mindset of
improving every game and every day. We have to come in and focus,
forget about this game and forget the last four games and get ready
for Houston.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
