<SLUG> BC-HKN-HULL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPILY, STARS' HULL IS ONE OF THE GUYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The makeshift sign hung in Brett Hull's locker
at the Dr Pepper StarCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Soft Hands
</P>
<P>
   1. Liberally apply baby oil to hands.
</P>
<P>
   2. Rub in thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place baby powder on knob of stick.
</P>
<P>
   4. Shoot between pipes for best results.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull took one look at the jab at his lack of scoring, laughed to
himself, and moved on, disappearing behind the black door of the
Stars' locker room and turning himself into just another hockey
player.
</P>
<P>
   It's a nice sign, he says. Not just the one placed on his stall
by teammates who gigged him for scoring one point in the first
round of the NHL playoffs. The real sign is that he's becoming more
and more a part of the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' said Hull, 34. ``It's nice to just be one of the
guys. That's what I always wanted, to just be a hockey player.''
</P>
<P>
   That might not be possible for the next two weeks because the
Stars take on Hull's former team _ the St. Louis Blues _ in Game 1
of a best-of-seven Western Conference semifinal series at 7 tonight
at Reunion Arena (Fox Sports Net Southwest and ESPN2).
</P>
<P>
   The story line is too juicy _ former hero returns to face the
team that dumped him. Brett Hull, the mouth that roared, goes back
to St. Louis to take on the team he made famous, to play in the
building he basically built.
</P>
<P>
   But Hull isn't buying that. He's still just one cog in the gear
that is the Stars' hockey machine. He left behind the glory days of
St. Louis last summer when the Blues refused to sign him as a free
agent and he cashed in on a three-year, $17 million deal with the
Stars. But in stepping away from the Blues, Hull also left behind
the media frenzy that followed his every move, the 86-goal season
in 1990-91 that spawned thousands of jersey sales and put his
poster on the bedroom wall of many a young fan in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   This guy was as big as Mark McGwire at one time, and now he
wants to just fade into the background? C'mon, Brett, where's the
golden throat?
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is all about `team,''' Hull said. ``There are a lot
of stars, a lot of leaders, there's no one guy, and I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   After being the ``one guy'' for 11 seasons, Hull has found his
relocation to Texas refreshing. He has changed his style, changed
his expectations, changed his image. And the second-round playoff
meeting with the Blues illustrates just how much he has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Dallas Star now,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``We've gone through the transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the first four games of the playoffs, Hull has no goals
and one assist. In St. Louis, they would have been studying his
body chemistry and calling in experts to diagnose his problem. In
Texas, he gets praise for a job well done.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played well in that first series,'' Hitchcock said. ``He
fought hard for his ice and he earned a lot of scoring chances. He
was responsible defensively and he really played within the game
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, that's all that's required of Hull _ the 13th leading
goal-scorer in league history (586) and a lock for the Hall of Fame
someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a different situation for me,'' Hull said. ``The
guys are giving me a little heat because I haven't scored yet. But
the contributions from everybody are more important than the goals
themselves. If a guy like me or Mike Modano isn't doing what
they're supposed to do \Rdefensively\S in the system, everything
breaks down.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull, the $5.5-million checking winger? It has a strange
sound to those who watched him dazzle St. Louis with spectacular
goal-scoring. But it's what the Stars now require of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a checking winger,'' Hitchcock said. ``His first job on
that line \Rwith Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen)\S is to check the
other team's best line. His next job is to help make sure that his
line outscores that line.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Hull would attempt to do that by scoring three
goals while giving up two. Now, he's trying to score one goal while
giving up none. And he's succeeding in the new system. He had 32
goals, including 11 game-winners, and was a plus-19 this season. In
Hitchcock's book, that's more than worth the investment.
</P>
<P>
   In the playoffs, Hull has generated 18 shots and is even in
plus-minus, exactly where the Stars want him to be. Sure, he needs
to score some goals _ that's the second part of his job _ but those
goals have to be a product of playing within the Stars' system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I still see myself as a goal-scorer and the pressure is
always there,'' Hull said. ``But I've been able to temper it now.
Now, I know I can contribute to the team even if I don't score.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Brett, you have to want to score against the Blues, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After going 11 years in St. Louis without advancing past the
second round of the playoffs, that would be a change for the
better.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
