<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORREPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOAT SICK ABOUT FATALITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By John Sturbin c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram When they
red-flagged the VisionAire 500 to a halt at Lowe's Motor Speedway,
and the tragic facts surrounding the deaths of three spectators
began to unfold Saturday night, a cold sweat swept over driver
Billy Boat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I got a sick feeling in my stomach,'' Boat said from his
business in Phoenix the other day. ``For me, it hit a little closer
to home. That's because two of my kids were in the grandstands,
sitting with some friends, and we didn't know where they were. As a
parent, I was glad to see my kids after my wife \RAndrea\S went out
and found them. Because you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Trisha Boat, 12, and Chad, 7, left the racetrack in Concord,
N.C., with their parents Saturday night, when what was supposed to
have been a grand prelude to the 83rd Indianapolis 500 turned
instead into the Pep Boys Indy Racing League's worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Three fans killed. Eight injured by flying debris hurtled over a
catch fence and into the grandstands. Among the victims was a
9-year-old girl who remains in a North Carolina hospital with brain
and lung injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Boat, the parent, still is sick to his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart goes out to the family and the friends of all the
people involved,'' said Boat, the father of four children. ``All
you can do is just pray for the families. It's a helpless
situation. It's something you never, never really get over.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have followed the IRL since its inception are well
aware of founder Tony George's struggles to build the depth and
strength of series teams, to attract the commitment of corporate
America and to capture the interest of oval-track fans. It has been
a well-intentioned but sometimes agonizingly slow process for a
series featuring 200 mph race cars.
</P>
<P>
   And now this, at a facility that never had witnessed a racing
fatality in its 40-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge blow, definitely something the IRL didn't need at
this point. No series needs it,'' said Boat, who has blossomed into
a star in the fledgling IRL. ``But it's not a problem confined to
the IRL. Even NASCAR has to take a look at it, because they're not
immune from parts flying into the grandstands, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's Motor Speedway is, of course, the center of developer
Bruton Smith's Speedway Motorsports Inc., an empire that also
includes Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth. LMS president H.A.
``Humpy'' Wheeler and IRL officials are attempting to recreate the
accident that sent a wheel and suspension parts from a three-car
wreck flying over a 15-foot fence and into the Turn 4 grandstands.
</P>
<P>
   The same painstaking process was undertaken at Michigan Speedway
last July, when three fans were killed and six injured by a wheel
and parts that flew off a Champ Car during a CART FedEx Series
event.
</P>
<P>
   Once its investigation is completed, SMI officials might opt to
uniformly raise the catch fence heights at all its racetracks. Or
there might be no change implemented before the series visits TMS
for the first of two races in June. Because how high is high
enough, and presumably safe enough, for you and the members of your
family?
</P>
<P>
   Or Billy Boat's children?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had the answer, I'd offer my suggestion,'' Boat said. ``I
don't know if there is an answer. But you have to make the fans
feel safe. They are there to have a good time and enjoy the races.
They shouldn't have to worry about their safety.''
SPOTLIGHT ON ... Wallace works overtime on revised Ford Taurus
To mixed reviews among its NASCAR Winston Cup teams, Chevrolet
officials have delayed the debut of the racing version of the 2000
Monte Carlo until the beginning of next season.
</P>
<P>
   That will keep the new Monte Carlo on a level playing field with
the updated 2000 Ford Taurus, which Cup star Rusty Wallace
confirmed is being developed by Penske Racing South.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car is in our shop right now,'' said Wallace, driver of
the No. 2 Miller Lite Ford. ``All it's going to be is a new nose
and new tail. It's not going to be a radical design or anything.
And I don't think you're going to see a performance change.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shocks a lot of people because they say, `Why would you
change a car if you're not going to make it run faster?' The
Chevrolet guys are already saying, `Oh my God, they're coming out
with a bullet.' That's not the case. We're coming out with a car
that has to have a facial change because of the new design of the
2000 Taurus. So, the headlights will look a little bit different
and the taillights will look a little bit different. But trust me,
NASCAR is all over this car, governing everything that gets done on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Monte Carlo was supposed to have made its debut at
Lowe's Motor Speedway this month. But NASCAR officials asked
Chevrolet to make additional aerodynamic changes to the new car's
roof line and rear deck after tests conducted at the
Lockheed-Martin wind tunnel in Marietta, Ga., in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Ritter, general manager of marketing for Chevrolet, said
those changes would have made the new MC uncompetitive.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said NASCAR is simply trying to maintain competitive
balance. Through 10 races, Ford teams have a 70-67 lead over
Chevrolet, which has a 5-4 advantage over Ford in victories.
Pontiac has scored one victory, with John Andretti, and 53 points _
and has three drivers ranked in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want that balance to go away,'' said Wallace, who
has won a race and is seventh in points. ``I think that's one of
the reasons they haven't approved the Monte Carlo to run this year.
I think they want to look at both cars, so when they start the year
2000, they're sure they've got these cars as close as they can.''
QUICK HITS Little E Cup testing Reigning NASCAR Busch Grand
National champion Dale Earnhardt Jr. officially launched his
Winston Cup testing career at Lowe's Motor Speedway Wednesday
before an audience that included 13 television cameras and
approximately 50 journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, the son of seven-time Cup champion Dale Earnhardt, is
scheduled to make his Cup debut May 30 in the Coca-Cola 600. He was
among General Motors drivers participating in a two-day test at the
1.5-mile trioval in Concord, N.C. Little E's team brought two
Chevrolet Monte Carlos to his home track, but one car developed a
malfunction that led to a carburetor fire.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, 24, logged only three laps of practice in the second
car before afternoon showers ended the session after approximately
50 minutes.
CART's Blundell injured CART FedEx Series regular Mark Blundell was
reported in fair condition at St. Louis University Hospital after
suffering apparent head injuries in a crash while testing at
Gateway International Raceway in Madison, Ill., Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Blundell was injured when his No. 18 Motorola
Reynard/Mercedes-Benz spun and crashed into a wall at the 1.27-mile
oval after a gear selection problem.
</P>
<P>
   Blundell was taken to St. Elizabeth Medical Center in Granite
City, Ill., where CAT scans were normal. He was transferred to St.
Louis University Hospital for more tests.
Elliott gets McNews NASCAR's Most Popular Driver is hungry for a
new primary sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elliott's association with McDonald's will end after the
2000 season, with the fast-food retailer opting for a new agreement
with California-based Precision Preparation Inc. PPI owner Cal
Wells III is scheduled to field a NASCAR Busch Grand National team
next season, before eventually graduating to Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   PPI has hired Tim Wardlaw as program manager and Joe Garone, who
recently left Elliott's No. 94 Ford Taurus Cup team, as crew chief.
Wells, who has fielded Toyota's primary engine development team in
the CART FedEx Series since 1995, plans to run Taurus sheet metal
in the BGN series.
Burton tops ballot Winston Cup points-leader Jeff Burton has
captured first-quarter voting for Driver of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Burton collected 10 first-place votes and 102 points from a
panel of 12 motorsports journalists, including this reporter. Jeff
Gordon, the three-time and reigning Cup champion and Driver of the
Year recipient, was second with 48 points. Eight-time NHRA Funny
Car champion John Force, the 1996 award-winner, received the other
first-place votes and was third with 41 points.
Last words ``In a way, I'm certainly pleased to see the Monte Carlo
delayed a little bit. Because I felt like it was going to be better
than what they \RChevrolet\S had, and what they had was pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Martin, offering a Ford driver's view on the rival camp's
2000 Winston Cup car.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
