<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF DISAPPOINTMENT FOR STARS: THEY CAN'T HATE THE BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
DALLAS _ Hate had happened.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And this wasn't a case of somebody juicing the hype. In
describing the relationship between his Stars and the Phoenix
Coyotes, hype-free Ken Hitchcock freely used ``unhealthy hate.''
</P>
<P>
   What a jaw-for-a-jaw playoff series it was gonna be. Even Jeremy
Roenick, wearing a contraption that looked like a bobsledders
helmet, had his mouth wired and ready.
</P>
<P>
   Except in their eagerness to deliver ``Roenick's Revenge,'' upon
the Stars, the talkative prairie mutts had a sudden memory lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Up three games to one in its first-round Stanley Cup series,
Phoenix flat forgot how to beat St. Louis. Not even Roenick making
his dramatic (at least in Phoenix it was considered dramatic)
return for Game 7, could prevent Choke City.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, the Coyotes became NHL poster boys for the
Heimlich maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   As of tonight, the Blues will be showing up at Reunion Arena,
probably as surprised as the Stars that they are actually here.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too late to work up a good case of hate against St. Louis?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way,'' Brett Hull said Wednesday at StarCenter.
``This is a team that's just like us _ a hard working hockey club
without a lot of frills.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he once spent a career bleeding blue, Hull certainly knows
these people. But defensemen Richard Matvichuk showed a grin when
asked if there was any reason to strongly dislike the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give it a couple of shifts on the ice \Rtonight\S,'' he
answered, ``and something will probably turn up.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably.
</P>
<P>
   Round Two of the playoffs presents a classic case of bad
news-good news for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, there was a desire to play Phoenix, which had nothing
to do with the potential for emotional and physical fireworks. The
Blues are more skilled, therefore more dangerous, particularly if
Grant Fuhr is ``on'' in goal. St. Louis' uneven regular season was
caused mainly by inconsistency and injuries involving Fuhr.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Stars' good side is the Blues going seven games with
Phoenix, and then into overtime to win the series in Game 7. Plus,
with Colorado-Detroit considered the premier playoff matchup, the
league office and TV combined to give St. Louis the shortest
possible recovery time from one series to the next.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, of course, haven't played in eight days, which might
bring up concerns of rust, except ...
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've been telling people is although the Edmonton series
will go down as a sweep in the books, I have never been involved in
a tougher one,'' said Hull. ``Every shift was a physical battle.
Those four games were harder on you than any seven-game series I've
experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of rust settling in, there was healing. And until the
Blues came back on Phoenix, this last week was spent preparing for
another physical and mental showdown against the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been the \RDerian\S Hatcher-Roenick series,
but this will be all about Brett and his deep roots in St. Louis,''
said Matvichuk. ``One way or the other, there was going to be a
focal point in this second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Brett will handle that business in the right way, and that
should leave us with just a tough series of hockey to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull, in fact, made a point Wednesday of meeting head-on with
the media horde. ``You can let it be a pain in the butt by trying
to run from it and refusing to talk about it, but why?'' said Hull.
``Why not get all the questions asked and answered to start with,
and then go about your business.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mike Keenan were still in St. Louis as coach-GM, then Hull
would be involved in verbal warfare, but those days are long gone.
Kinda like the Phoenix Coyotes now being history.
</P>
<P>
   Had there been a different Game 7 winner out west Tuesday night,
Matvichuk would never have been describing tonight's opponent as
``a team that plays with heart and class.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Louis will show up for every game and throw everything
they've got at us,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   That means good special teams, particularly on the power play,
and a pair of defensemen in Al MacInnis and Chris Pronger who
perform like ball-handling point guards. Against the Stars' hard
forecheck, MacInnis and Pronger are a perfect duo.
</P>
<P>
   And how could you hate a team where the leading scorer, Pavol
Demitra, shaves his head?
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not Phoenix, but this will be tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Stars in six, as Roenick sits in Phoenix, sucking up his meals
through a straw.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
