<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-TEX </SLUG>
 
BLUES EXPECT KEEPING FOCUS WILL BE THEIR EDGE (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By Jennifer Floyd 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Forget conventional wisdom that says a well-rested
Stars bunch will quickly dispose of a drained bunch from St. Louis
in Round 2 of the NHL playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Blues winger Tony Twist has a varying theory before Game 1
begins at 7 tonight at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   He figures an exhausted Blues crew, less than 48 hours removed
from a Game 7, series-clinching, overtime victory against Phoenix,
has an advantage against a well-rested Stars crew that last played
a game April 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a lot easier to prepare for a hockey game playing
hockey than playing golf,'' Twist said. ``There is a lot to be said
for rest, but there is a lot to be said for never losing focus. I
think coming off a Game 7 like that, the way we did _ Game 7,
overtime, goal OT winner _ I think we're ready. We're focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe just a little tired, too?
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, maybe,'' Twist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were just beat,'' Blues winger Kelly Chase said. ``Any
time the guys on the plane are too tired to play cards, you know
they are tired.''
</P>
<P>
   When Blues center Pierre Turgeon finally ended Game 7 with a
deflection of a Ricard Persson shot, Tuesday was pretty close to
being Wednesday in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday already had arrived in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the only one up in the house at the time,'' Stars winger
Pat Verbeek said of a game that ended at 1 a.m. locally. ``I can't
imagine why.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure a couple of Stars players like Verbeek stayed awake,
propped up on a bunch of pillows with a remote control in one hand
and a icy cool beverage in the other watching Blues players sweat
and fret and hustle just to get to Round 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' invitation already had been extended _ eight days
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We earned the right to have a layoff,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``But it only does us good if we use it. We've got
to play with very strong energy. We've got to play with a lot of
enthusiasm, and we've got to hopefully set the tempo as much as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Blues coach Joel Quenneville also stressed a need to set a tone
early on. And he believes that playing a game so recently benefits
his group in trying to do so.
</P>
<P>
   He said this despite catching a flight from Phoenix that arrived
at D/FW Airport at around 5 a.m., despite few Blues getting more
than six hours sleep, despite only a couple of Blues being up for a
skate a day before a big series begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all of that emotion, I think we just needed some time
away to get our thoughts and change channels,'' Quenneville said.
``I think we got the emotion high right now. Hopefully, that can
help us.''
</P>
<P>
   To rest or not to rest? That seems to be the question.
</P>
<P>
   The answer? Well, that isn't quite clear yet.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, players best prepare for a hockey game by playing a
draining game of hockey. Maybe, players best prepare for a hockey
game by playing a relaxing game of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, both in a case of Blues goalie Grant Fuhr.
</P>
<P>
   ``So does Fuhrsy,'' Chase responded when presented with Twist's
theory that the Stars might be flat from playing a lot of golf.
``He's played golf every day and has been playing a lot of hockey,
and he's been playing great.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
