HELLING HELPS RANGERS QUIET RED SOX (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAULS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates expects a confrontation
someday on the mound with right-hander Rick Helling.
</P>
<P>
   The manager will stroll slowly to the mound, signal the bullpen
for the appropriate reliever and demand the ball from a defiant
Helling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said before that we're going to get in a fight one of
these days when I go to the mound to make a pitching change,''
Oates said. ``I couldn't believe he let go of the ball when I went
to get it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates expected that confrontation during the seventh inning of
the Rangers' 8-3 victory Wednesday night against the Boston Red Sox
at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Oates summoned left-hander Mike Venafro from the bullpen to
replace Helling, who did not want to surrender the ball with the
Rangers' 7-1 lead intact. In fact, the manager's presence stunned
Helling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his decision,'' said Helling, who emphasized his
reverence for the manager's authority. ``I respect that, but it's
frustrating. I thought tonight was a good night to get out there
and throw 120 pitches and build some endurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he doesn't feel comfortable with me out there pitching
with a 7-1 lead. That's the way I looked at it. Just because we've
got eight guys out there in the bullpen doesn't mean he has to use
them. Let us pitch through some of these situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates acknowledged his appreciation for Helling's
competitiveness, but the game dictated a change, the manager said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the time to make the move there,'' Oates said. ``If I
don't, the lead might not be there. He had thrown 100 pitches. How
many more pitches is he going to throw? So, why let him face those
left-handed hitters?''
</P>
<P>
   Helling surrendered a leadoff double to Jose Offerman, but
recorded the seventh inning's first out with a fly ball off the bat
of John Valentin. That brought Reggie Jefferson, Boston's
left-handed-hitting designated hiter, to the plate and Oates from
the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said before that we're going to get in a fight one of
these days when I go to the mound to make a pitching change,''
Oates said. ``I couldn't believe he let go of the ball when I went
to get it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling, who earned his third victory in as many starts, did not
want to leave despite pitching around trouble most of the evening.
However, pitching around trouble served Helling's purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched like it was a 7-0 game,'' he said. ``I threw a lot
of first-pitch fastballs to a good fastball-hitting team. A 7-0
game is different than a 1-0 game. All you want to do is get outs
and get your team off the field as fast as you can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make them hit the ball early in the count. If they hit it,
they hit it. Then, I'll start pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   That plan served Helling (3-3) well after the Rangers' five-run
first and two-run second innings. Catcher Ivan Rodriguez, who drove
in only three runs during the previous 16 games since his
9-runs-batted-in performance April 13 in Seattle, matched that
production with his first-inning at-bat against right-hander Pat
Rapp (1-2).
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's three-run home run highlighted the Rangers'
first-inning explosion, and his second-inning single provided
Helling a seven-run advantage. Helling pitched out of a
first-inning, bases-loaded jam and stranded eight runners through
six innings before eventually being removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind him wanting to pitch and not wanting to come out
of there,'' Oates said. ``I appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates' decision, though, might prompt Helling to alter his
approach the next time the Rangers provide him a comfortable lead
so he can pitch deeper into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not because we're not capable,'' Helling said. ``Maybe
I'll pitch differently the next time. Maybe I'll pitch like it's a
1-0 game, but that's the competitor in me. I want to be out there
all the time.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
