r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TREK-STAR-WARS-PRODUC     05-06 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-STAR-WARS-PRODUCER-RICK-MCCALLUM-ART-ADV17-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN: FLORIDA 
 INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI
</HEADLINE>
  THE SOURCE BEHIND THE FORCE: `STAR WARS' PRODUCER RICK McCALLUM  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., MAY 17, 1999) 
 Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Ray Park as
Darth Maul in ``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Even Darth Vader needed a Grand Moff Tarkin.
 &HT;    Somebody's got to keep the details covered while The Big Guy is
communing with the Force. And for ```Star Wars'' mastermind George
Lucas, that man is Rick McCallum.
 &HT;    McCallum is a longtime Lucasfilm top gun and producer of ``Star
Wars: The Phantom Menace,'' which blasts into theaters on May 19.
His job may not be as eye-catching as some, but it's important.
 &HT;    ``At the end of the day, I am responsible for making sure that
whatever George Lucas wants George Lucas gets, and that he's going
to get it in the most cost-effective, efficient way,'' McCallum
says. ``That allows us to do things our way, but without the huge,
huge risks that a normal big film of this size would have.
 &HT;    ``I make that happen.''
 &HT;    Signing stars and unknowns alike to three-picture deals? No
problem. Overseeing the creation of a staggering 2,000-plus
computer-enhanced shots? Easy. Schlepping 70 tons of equipment and
hundreds of cast and crew from London to Tunisia to Italy and back
again? Not to worry.
 &HT;    ``George gave us the tools and the money to be able to make the
movie we wanted to make,'' the 45-year-old McCallum says by
telephone from Skywalker Ranch in San Rafael, Calif. ``If it
doesn't work, it's nobody else's fault.
 &HT;    ``That's kind of terrifying and, at the same time, very
exhilarating.''
 &HT;    The result of Lucas' largesse is a $115 million sci-fi
extravaganza that many observers predict will be one of the most
lucrative films of all time. The growing buzz has had even McCallum
sitting up and taking notice, ever since the re-release last year
of the spiffed-up versions of the original trilogy.
 &HT;    ``I was amazed by the success of the special editions,'' the
producer says, ``and I could see that there was a real need for
something truly exciting.
 &HT;    ``We don't have that experience in films anymore,'' he adds.
``You have it at rock concerts and basketball or football games,
but you don't get the cultural, collective experience very often in
films anymore.
 &HT;    ``When you do, it's very powerful.''
 &HT;    McCallum promises that this will be no ordinary movie. For one
thing, the story of young Anakin Skywalker _ the future Darth Vader
_ will test its viewers' minds and imaginations, not just their
adrenaline glands.
 &HT;    ``This is primarily the setting up of the whole saga,'' McCallum
says of what is to be the first in a prequel trilogy. ``It's a very
complicated story, in terms of the politics and the nature of the
world that surrounds this event of Anakin being discovered.
 &HT;    ``We also visit three different planets _ Courascan, Tatooine
and a new one called Naboo,'' he says. ``So there is a lot of
information, and every frame of the film is very, very dense with
characters and subplots and creatures.
 &HT;    ``The film will surprise a lot of people,'' he says coyly. ``I
think `The Phantom Menace' is much more complex than people will be
expecting. It has a lot of humor _ more than people would associate
with a film set in the `Star Wars' universe.
 &HT;    ```The Phantom Menace' is just a fun ride,'' he adds. ``It's
meant to be enjoyed. I'm so happy, and I know George is very happy
... We're there. We're so close we can taste it.''
 &HT;    Lucas' frame of mind has been talked about for years. He hadn't
directed a film since ``Star Wars'' (1977), and there were reports
that he hated directing, had some kind of phobia about it and would
never direct again.
 &HT;    Now, however, he is said to have enjoyed ``Phantom Menace'' so
much that he's also planning to direct its sequel.
 &HT;    ``I've been working with George for 10 years,'' McCallum says.
``Ever since I've known him, he's been a consummate filmmaker. He
loves to edit, he loves to photograph. Writing is painful for him _
it's laboriously long for him.
 &HT;    ``I know he enjoyed shooting `The Phantom Menace,' which is why
I know he wants to direct the second one,'' the producer says.
``But I think his real joy comes in post-production, when he edits.
That's what he loves _ he loves to be able to spend the time
manipulating the images.
 &HT;    ``And I think, for him, it's not so much a maturing as a finding
of freedom _ he's finally able to have the technology to tell the
stories he always wanted to tell.''
 &HT;    That's assuming that it's ready in time. As of the end of April,
McCallum and company were racing the clock, putting the final
touches on ``Phantom Menace.'' There was a lot still to be done,
and Lucas' having advanced the film's opening date from its
original May 21 didn't help.
 &HT;    McCallum was confident that they'd finish in time, however. They
had to _ on May 21, he's scheduled to begin pre-production on
``Star Wars: Episode II.''
 -0- 
 NEXT WEEK  
 &HT;    ``Deep Space Nine's'' final episode, ``What You Leave Behind.''
 -0- 
