<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Dreamy Saturdays with Mother
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Mother's Day editors
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Jane Brooking
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   When you're the only girl in a family with five brothers,
finding time for that mother-daughter bonding takes some creative
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Creative thinking must have been one of my mother's specialties.
</P>
<P>
   With six children to raise and a husband long gone, she somehow
managed to stretch both her time and resources so that, looking
back now to our childhood, we could say, ``Yes, we had our
Dreamsville.''
</P>
<P>
   I lived for those Saturday afternoons when Mother had squirreled
away enough coins to send my five brothers to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure the neighbors must have wondered why I didn't go, too.
They couldn't have known that a Saturday afternoon alone with
Mother was my special treat.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, for a purchase totaling the grand sum of $2,
Margrave's Drug Store in Paris, Texas, would deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and I were both avid readers, and we both suffered severe
cases of sweet tooth, so you can guess what our order consisted of.
</P>
<P>
   We'd pile pillows to make our nests at each end of the sofa and
with our feet tucked up and the chocolate bars within easy reach,
we'd devour the true romance magazines that let us glimpse into the
lives of beautiful women and handsome men.
</P>
<P>
   They would, we knew to be a fact, live happily ever after in
their perfect houses with their perfect children.
</P>
<P>
   And if they could, then, some day, so could I.
</P>
<P>
   During my lifetime I've read just about everything from the
world's great classics to the current best sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Not even a box of Godiva chocolates on the side could make them
equal the memory of one Saturday afternoon sharing with my mother
nickel candy bars and 25-cent romance magazines.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jane Brooking makes her home in Gladewater, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville
stories, visit http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
