 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2540 - May 6, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2540 -- May 6, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. WHO NEEDS WAR CORRESPONDENTS? For reasons that often have
little to do with journalism, it can be surprisingly difficult to
maintain a commitment to honest and courageous reporting while
trying to cover certain wars, writes Christiane Amanpour, chief
international correspondent for CNN. (This commentary is adapted
from her address to the Freedom Forum in New York on April 13.)
1,500 words. 2. CAN THE BRAIN BE REPROGRAMMED TO REDUCE PAIN?
Recent research indicates that pain is a much more complex process
than was once thought. For many years, pain was considered a
relatively simple sensation generated by pain receptors in damaged
tissue and sent, more or less unchanged, directly to the brain. New
research, however, indicates that many factors - including our
emotions and intellect - can alter how our nervous systems process
pain. By learning how to manipulate these factors, researchers say,
it may be possible to change the way we experience pain and reduce
its impact on our lives. By Michael McCarthy. From The Lancet News
Service. 1,000 words. 3. THE ONION Celebrating its 11th year on
paper, its third as the Web's leading source of satire, and its
first as an out-of-control pop icon, The Onion may be vulgar,
insensitive, sexist, racist, or even on occasion offensive, but
unlike its Web rivals, it is funny. But for those poor people who
mistake them for real news, Onion stories often have a bitter tang.
By Liesl Schillinger. From Wired magazine. 2,500 words. (N/A
Japan.)
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE : (N/A Australia, New Zealand, Brazil)
</P>
<P>
   A. MORE GAIN, LESS PAIN Mammograms reveal lumps in breasts but
only a painful biopsy can prove if a lump is benign or cancerous. A
new device from the U.S. could avoid the need for many biopsies. By
Kurt Kleiner. 500 words. B. CROSSWORD WIZARD First computers learnt
how to defeat people at chess and now they can even take us on at
solving crossword puzzles - and sometimes win. By Jonathan Beard.
800 words. C. DEATH BY FIRE Did fires lit by the first Australians
finish off the large animals that once roamed that continent?
Sharon Levy investigates a controversial new theory. 3,000 words.
D. CRASH COURSE Crippled combat aircraft should soon stand a better
chance of making it back to base, thanks to a novel neural network
that has just passed its first major test. A software co-pilot can
rapidly learn to fly a damaged plane. E. LOST FOR WORDS Dyslexia
seems to be caused by a breakdown in the way sensory nerves develop
in the fetal brain, reports Julie Clayton. Could the mother's
immune system be to blame? 2,000 words. F. FIRM FORECAST Managing
the ups and downs of everyday life has always been a nightmare for
chiefs of disaster insurance companies and senior stockbrokers.
Now, a generation of virtual humans could put the prediction
business on a sound footing. By John Casti. 3,000 words. 5. BORGES
IN AUSTIN, TEXAS There are countries that can be reflected in
cities which at first sight have nothing to do with them. You place
the city in front of a mirror and suddenly the country just
appears. That's what happens with Austin, the capital of Texas. In
a secret, subliminal sort of way, that city is Argentina. The
similarity probably began in September 1961, when Jorge Luis Borges
was invited by the University of Texas to give a poetry seminar. By
Tomas Eloy Martinez. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
BEYOND AFFIRMATIVE ACTION In the wake of affirmative action,
campuses in California are managing to maintain diversity without
racial set-asides. This will satisfy neither liberals nor
conservatives, but it's looking a lot like the future. By James
Traub. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (8,300 words)
+ edited article available.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
BITTER HARVEST : THE ORGAN SNATCHING URBAN LEGENDS Many urban
legends are harmless, such as stories of microwaved poodles and
giant alligators lurking in sewers. Others, however, can have
serious consequences. The organ-snatching urban legend and its
variants have been taken seriously in some places and caused real
harm. Rumours, urban legends and misinformation can easily lead to
disaster and it serves us all to subject them to sceptical inquiry,
writes Benjamin Radford. From Skeptical Inquirer Magazine. 3,500
words. Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81 I
am interested in story no. ______ from summary 2540 Name :
