<HEADER>
A6542 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV09-C     05-06 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: HOW TO EAT PORK OVER KOSOVO
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 9.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than likely, the folks who edit the newspaper
where these words appear work under a budget for gathering the
news. They usually do not go to their publisher seeking extra funds
each time a news event occurs.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the way the federal government works. When air
war broke out in the Balkans, President Clinton promptly asked
Congress for an emergency grant of $6 billion to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution limits the role of the legislative branch in
the conduct of foreign policy. Still, the founders gave Congress
sole charge of the public purse, thereby offering the legislators a
way to get their oar in, should they be so disposed.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans dislike what they call ``Clinton's war'' with
Yugoslavia so much that they passed a bill last month to block the
use of U.S. ground forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with that negative outlook, it would be only natural
for the House Appropriations Committee to grind down Clinton's $6
billion request. Instead, the panel saw fit to vote $12.9 billion
in ``emergency'' funds.
</P>
<P>
   That action did not sit well with Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin,
the ranking Democrat on the panel, who said: ``Frankly, I find it
mind-boggling that some of the same (Republican) members who
yesterday voted against the operation will today here now vote to
more than double the amount of spending that the president has
asked for to conduct those operations. I think that is
spectacularly inconsistent.''
</P>
<P>
   But Obey knows how the game is played. The federal budget is in
surplus. In part, that's due to tight overall budget caps, which
include Pentagon outlays. House Republicans have pledged to keep
those caps intact. But the ``emergency'' Kosovo money isn't
covered.
</P>
<P>
   And that lets the Republicans out of their box. It lets the
Pentagon generals do an end run around the White House. It lets
their defense industry pals talk up Pentagon wish lists on Capitol
Hill, even as they sign over their fat campaign checks to the
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the way you get, say, two new tank wash parks built
in Germany, at $8 million a pop from taxpayers' wallets, as a
product of the Kosovo ``emergency.'' A spotless Sherman tank here
and there and soon you're talking serious money. All in all, the
House panel would spend $222.5 million more on ``overseas
contingencies'' than Clinton wants.
</P>
<P>
   Says Obey: ``I do not believe that we should be using something
as serious as the war in order to simply make a lot of head room
for somebody's pork.''
</P>
<P>
   Look at the big picture: Since the start of the Persian Gulf
war, which coincided, more or less, with the end of the Cold War,
the nation has spent $3.2 trillion to meet its military needs.
Current estimates call for another $1.8 trillion in U.S. military
spending between 1999 and 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Where has all that money gone? Where will it go?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's not exactly cheap to fly a B-2 a third of the way
around the world, and back again, to drop its 16-bomb payload. Each
such mission costs the taxpayers some $12 million per payload. And
then, of course, the bombers need to be washed after they return to
their U.S. base from the skies over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
