<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's always someone to blame
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As much as Austin preens about being different,
the miserable turnout in Saturday's council elections pretty much
tracked the apathy that greeted local elections statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Texans who stoutly maintain they want to vote on every office
from county surveyor to police chief _ in some communities _ passed
up a chance to cast ballots for mayors as well as school board and
city council members. Not to be outdone by their cousins in Dallas
or San Angelo or Round Rock or San Marcos, Austinites showed that
they could be as apathetic as the rest of them.
</P>
<P>
   However, ladies and gentlemen, I submit that candidates in those
other communities don't have near the panache that Austin
candidates do. Our City Council candidates have a certain
indefinable quality about them that sets them apart and they
maintain that sense of style, even in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   There are many contenders, but I'm naming Place 1 candidate Chad
Crow as winner of the Stylish Loser crown for this year's council
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Previous winners have been those who blamed their loss on people
being happy (so, therefore, only those who were mad at her voted)
and the losing mayoral candidate who congratulated his opponent,
this newspaper, on election night.
</P>
<P>
   Among the things I collect are excuses and alibis. You never
know when you're going to need one, and they are fun to swap. In
any event, Crow had a doozy for not getting into a runoff with
incumbent Daryl Slusher.
</P>
<P>
   In a press release delivered electronically on Monday, Crow had
this to say: ``Crow felt the key to making a runoff relied more on
Marcos DeLeon's success than his own. 'Normally, 28 percent is
enough for a runoff when you've got six people in a particular
race. But we needed Marcos to take quite a few votes from Slusher
and it just didn't happen. It's disappointing but I know he was
working with a very limited budget, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   I've been around the world and to the Tom Green County Fat Stock
Show and Rodeo and I've never seen one like that. It's a Hall of
Famer.
</P>
<P>
   A loser will usually blame the press or society or good weather
or bad weather or endorsements or even say that voters were
misinformed or misled.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely, however, do we find a defeated candidate with the
creativity to shift the blame to another loser. Moreover, Crow
deftly hijacked and modified the standard excuse Democrats deploy
when they lose: ``Low Hispanic turnout.''
</P>
<P>
   My man Chad Crow may not have won the race, but he won the alibi
derby going away.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at agarcia(at)statesman.com
or 445-3667.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
