A6625 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-TOOLS07-COX     05-06 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-TOOLS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How does your garden grow? With the right tools, of course
 &HT;    By Diana Blowers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Many gardeners have a favorite tool. Sometimes
it's the old hoe passed dow n from Grandpa. Other times it's a
newfangled gadget such as the Weasel or Claw. Often it is simply a
quality-made version of an old standby.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are a die-hard gardener or simply sprucing up the
landscape, the tools you use help determine how easy you get the
job done.
</P>
<P>
   Hoes, rakes, spades, shovels, loppers, saws and pruners continue
to be gardening staples. However, garden centers, hardware stores
and tool catalogs are filled with many variations on each one, as
well as with new tools to do old jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Both those who sell them and those who use them tend to agree
that the first tool-buying issue is to buy the highest quality one
you can afford. A high-quality tool will be around to pass on to
the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   The choices are many, but your challenge is to discover that
tool you will soon learn you can't do without. T
</P>
<P>
   Felco pruners
</P>
<P>
   Several good pruners are on the market, but the Felco brand
seems to be the standard by which all others are measured. They
come in several sizes and styles, including left-handed models. A
Felco 7 model features a rotating handle to reduce wrist fatigue.
Regardless of the brand, by-pass pruners, those where the blades
by-pass each other like a pair of scissors, should be used for soft
plant material to avoid crushing the stems. The anvil-type pruners,
those where a blade cuts on a flat plate, should only be used when
only with cutting hard wood.
</P>
<P>
   Fork
</P>
<P>
   Many experts prefer the one-piece construction of aluminum
alloy, which doesn't bend under tough garden use.
</P>
<P>
   Trowel
</P>
<P>
   Considered among the basic staples for most gardeners, along
with the fork. They are used in cultivating small patches of soil
and planting of small plants.
</P>
<P>
   Dibble
</P>
<P>
   You can't find a much simpler tool than the dibble, also called
a dibber. Its sole purpose is to poke holes. The point is plunged
into the ground, the dibble is wiggled around and you have a hole
ready for planting seeds, small seedlings or little bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   Auger
</P>
<P>
   Bulb planting becomes one of the easiest jobs in the garden when
you attach an auger to a household power drill. The resulting hole
is perfect for bulb planting and could also be used for planting
small
</P>
<P>
   plants.
</P>
<P>
   Garden Weasel
</P>
<P>
   The bladed wheels of this tool rotate crosswise, creating a
scissors-like action that breaks up soil and uproots weeds. It
comes with a short and a long handle and the blades are detachable
so the tool can work between rows of varying widths and around
plants in tight places.
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomic rakes, hoes and shovels
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomically designed handles add a new dimension to old garden
standbys. The longer, curved handles allow the user to stay in an
upright position, allowing for proper leverage while reducing
bending and stooping.
</P>
<P>
   Claw
</P>
<P>
   This is a newer tool that many gardeners swear they can't do
without. It can replace the hoe and the shovel as it cultivates
around plants, uproots weeds, digs holes and mixes in fertilizers
or peat moss. All of this is done as the gardener stands upright
and simply makes a half turn of the handle.
</P>
<P>
   Spade
</P>
<P>
   Spades come in a variety of shapes to meet a variety of needs.
This is one of several available with a narrow, long head. Helpful
when digging up plants or planting new ones in an established
perennial bed, it allows the gardener to work in a relatively small
space without disturbing nearby plants.
</P>
<P>
   Hand cultivator
</P>
<P>
   When planting, this two-sided hand tool can be invaluable when
trying to penetrate the hard crust of clay soil. Once the plants
are established, it is helpful in cultivating in spaces too small
for just about any other tool.
</P>
<P>
   Scuffle hoe
</P>
<P>
   This hoe, which resembles the stirrup on a saddle, is also
called an action hoe or an oscillating hoe. Its blade moves back
and forth slightly as the hoe is pushed or pulled. Its sharp,
double-edged blade acts as a cultivator, weeder and edging tool.
The back-and-forth motion cuts both ways, snipping weeds off at the
ground without disturbing the soil or the roots of the surrounding
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
