<HEADER>
A6626 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAIR-JEWELRY07-COX     05-06 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIR-JEWELRY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hair jewelry is a girl's best friend
 &HT;    By Jeanne Claire van Ryzin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Messalina, wife of Roman Emperor Claudius I,
fancied tying her hair in a red or purple band. Queen Elizabeth I
started the Renaissance rage of wearing wigs (she had hundreds _
mostly red-haired) adorned with bright jewels, pearls, and other
ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   English women of the 19th century favored large gilt hair pins
with balloon-like tops to keep their towering hair styles in place.
Combs with gold-beaded edging were popular for decoration. So were
feathers and ostrich plumes. Queen Victoria tolerated these plumes
_ maybe _ but only the white ones. In 1879, she ordered that all
plumes must be worn in full sight lest any offending colored plumes
be hidden amongst a woman's curls.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1910s, dancer Irene Castle (who with her husband and
dance partner, Vernon, popularized the scandalous tango in the
United States) scandalously bobbed her hair. Castle used a headband
to hold her chic, short cut in place. Away with those unwieldy
Victorian hairpins. The flapper era had dawned.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother, much to her (very Catholic) mother's dismay,
bobbed her hair when she was a young woman in the 1920s. But
instead of a headband, my grandmother favored holding her hair back
with barrettes and combs. All the better to dance in.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when my grandmother was well past her flapper years, she
still swept her hair off her face with beautiful barrettes and
combs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a classic look,'' she always said as she scraped the
metal prong of a barrette across my scalp.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother preferred heavy barrettes made of brushed metal
or imitation tortoise shell. And while I loved to finger these when
I explored her scented dresser drawers, I liked tiny plastic
barrettes in primary colors; those didn't hurt and pull.
</P>
<P>
   Barrettes failed me the year I mimicked Olympic gymnast Olga
Korbut in my back yard, so I switched to elastic ponytail holders.
High school in the late 1970s brought a fascination with combs and
barrettes _ jeweled ones, shiny ones, feathered ones. It was a
brief romantic renaissance with 1940s hairstyles (or so I thought)
as I yearned for an elegant adult look.
</P>
<P>
   College began a decade of short hair. Yet the cheap Chinese
lacquer box of my barrettes and combs followed me. It refused to
disappear, surfacing again and again during every move. When my
hair neared shoulder length a few years back, the lacquer box, with
all its contents, magically re-emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, my 3-year-old niece arrived for a visit from New
York. From her plastic backpack she produced a handful of
neon-colored scrunchies. ``I want a ponytail,'' she insisted. I
dutifully swept her soft, fine hair into a ponytail, yet I thought,
how nice a tortoise-shell barrette or comb would be. Or perhaps a
red band, a bright jewel, a white plume.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
