<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6627 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX     05-06 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Backyard remembrance of a devoted climber
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Dog years are a rip-off.
</P>
<P>
   Seven to one human year? Six to one? However it shakes down,
it's unfair. Dogs spend so much of their time waiting against the
human clock. For overtime worked, they should get at least time and
a half.
</P>
<P>
   I'll tell you what else is unfair _ that someone has to be the
adult when a pet dies. Someone has to do the pronouncing, and the
arrangements, and must soothe a young mourner, when that someone
would rather have his own hair ruffled, have refuge in a mom's
apron, have Flower back. Unfair.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea what kind of dog Flower was, part retriever, part
everything. She was a doctor's thesis in forensic pedigree. Heck,
we might be blood relatives.
</P>
<P>
   She got her name from the swoosh of white on her black forehead,
like Bambi's skunk friend.
</P>
<P>
   At 11, she was old by dog years, an injustice sufficient unto
itself to make a young man cry. We got her tiny at the Waco Human
Society Animal Shelter. She was a handful even as a spoonful. It
didn't take much growing on her part to demonstrate the house was
too small.
</P>
<P>
   The yard was big. It became hers. And it was almost no time,
maybe 30 seconds there, before she showed off a talent that would
become preoccupation of mine. The dog could climb.
</P>
<P>
   The standard fence or gate did not contain her. And when I used
chicken wire to extend it she would find gaps without fail.
</P>
<P>
   She would never go far, always ending up back on the driveway to
do what she did in back: wait.
</P>
<P>
   For a short time, a chain to the mulberry tree was my grudging
answer. Then another dog entered the picture, a shepherd-mix stray
we named Tramp. He also found the same escape routes. Finally I
subdivided the yard with 6-feet-high fencing. We named it Fort
Flower.
</P>
<P>
   Tramp and Flower were quite a pair. Siblings of circumstance.
Mutt and Mutt.
</P>
<P>
   Suckers that we are, our pet population grew two years ago with
Layla, a collie we rescued in the Denny's parking lot just yards
from death by interstate. She spent two nights waiting to be
claimed at the animal shelter. Not a second more.
</P>
<P>
   Entertaining three dogs from a lawn chair is an art form. The
human body has only two hands. I got adept at the group-pet, my
hands working the crowd like a ginsu chef.
</P>
<P>
   This morning I had only two dogs to stroke. It feels like I have
too many hands.
</P>
<P>
   Son Robert was Flower's contemporary. Both were babies at the
same time. Unfair: Dogs got the jump on running and jumping. Then
it seems that just as the little boy acquires colt legs, the dog is
slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   We buried Flower just outside the fence beside the house. It was
getting dark. Fireflies lent their green lanterns. We mused that
the climber in Flower might have made the leap into one of those
little electric bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   I watched the dogs for signs of mourning. They were beyond
detection. And whatever he felt, a dog's got work to do. Tramp's
job always has been to ward off moonbeams and announce the arrival
of breezes in the bushes. Flower was the sentinel who commonly had
a ratty old rag in her mouth at my appearance, demonstrating her
readiness to protect. Layla keeps June bugs in line and watches the
tree line for squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   After Flower had been laid to rest, I thudded into the lawn
chair for a group stroke. It was brief. Layla noticed a firefly
invading the far reaches of the yard. They both took off.
</P>
<P>
   Good help like this is hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
