<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CAROLINA _ GRAND STRAND, S.C. _ When you think of South
Carolina's Grand Strand, the first place that comes to mind is
booming Myrtle Beach. But we eschew the neon for nature, exploring
the rivers and saltwater marshes that once supported rice
plantations along the fertile coast. We take a cruise on the
Waccamaw River, sail on Winyah Bay, take a Carolina Jeep Safari
tour along the coast and an excursion with Capt. Dick's Saltwater
Marsh Explorer. We stay in nature-based B&AMP;B inns far from the beach
hi-rises. (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MAY, 9.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CAROLINATOUR _ The upper coast of South Carolina, with
its natural charms, beckons to the adventure seeker. ``What we call
nature-based tourism is just outdoor recreation with a new spin on
it,'' says Tim Todd of the 5-year-old South Carolina Nature-Based
Tourism Association. By any name, its a compelling reason to wander
off the usual track, as I did on a recent four-day trip. (Thrasher,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MAY, 9.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SOUTH-PREDISNEY _ Southern Almanac story about ``Dixie
Before Disney,'' new story about tourism in the South. (Auchmutey,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MAY, 9.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-MATERNITY _ Whether you're expecting a millennium baby_or
an heir in a few months _ you can have chic, comfortable,
cool-looking clothes. Just remember, a stylish maternity wardrobe
is not an oxymoron. And Mother's Day, which is Sunday is the
perfect time for expecting women to be gifted with fashionable new
clothes. (MJohnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   EDs: CoxNet has prepared a full color page _ COXNET-SHOP07-PAGE
_ with photos and a column by Austin American Statesman consumer
writer Jane Greig.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-MOTHERSDAY _ Two Moms are selected for a special makeover
for Mother's Day. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MAY, 9.
</P>
<P>
   EXERCISE-CLOTHES _ Bess hilpert has a company that makes
exercise clothing for pregnant women. She used to be an exercise
physiologist for stars in Los Angeles, then became a stay at home
mom, and now does this. she has a patent for the support method in
the clothes, and Nordstrom is launching them on Mother's Day.
(Santos, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SATURDAY, MAY, 8.
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-PILLOWS _ Cynthia Witter doesn't have time to rest on her
laurels _ or her pillows _ now that the hand-painted designs are in
such demand. (Janjigian, Palm Beach Daily News). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   HAIR-JEWELRY _ Messalina, wife of Roman Emperor Claudius I,
fancied tying her hair in a red or purple band. Queen Elizabeth I
started the Renaissance rage of wearing wigs (she had hundreds _
mostly red-haired) adorned with bright jewels, pearls, and other
ornaments. English women of the 19th century favored large gilt
hair pins with balloon-like tops to keep their towering hair styles
in place. Combs with gold-beaded edging were popular for
decoration. So were feathers and ostrich plumes. Queen Victoria
tolerated these plumes _ maybe _but only the white ones. In 1879,
she ordered that all plumes must be worn in full sight lest any
offending colored plumes be hidden amongst a woman's curls. In the
1910s, dancer Irene Castle (who with her husband and dance partner,
Vernon, popularized the scandalous tango in the United States)
scandalously bobbed her hair. Castle used a headband to hold her
chic short cut in place. Away with those unwieldy Victorian
hairpins. The flapper era had dawned. My grandmother, much to her
(very Catholic) mother's dismay, bobbed her hair when she was a
young woman in the 1920s. But instead of a headband, my grandmother
favored holding her hair back with barrettes and combs. All the
better to dance in. (van Ryzin, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   CONTAINER-GARDENS _ Containers are a popular means for gardening
on highrise balconies. But there's more to creating a pretty pot in
high places than buying some tough plants. Extreme heat and wind
can send a pot into terra cotta terror. Here are some tips for
battling heights. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WORKSHOP-FANS _ Ceiling fans are easier to install than ever.
Here's a primer on how to do it yourself. (AHill, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LEEMAY-COLUMN _ Lee May writes about an essential truth of the
indispensable garending tool, the hosepipe: It will always find a
way to frustrate you. (May, Atrlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-TOOLS _ A look at gardening tools that are good to have,
with photos and brief descriptions of each one. Also includes some
catalogs with Web sites, a book and some tips for keeping tools in
good condition. (Dayton Daily News). 40. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0506 _ Film critics have generally liked
``Pushing Tin,'' the romantic comedy about two fiercely competitive
air traffic controllers. It's safe to say most movie critics don't
know diddly about guiding planes from the heavens to terra firma.
Viewers who do _ namely real air traffic controllers _ have a
different spin on the film, and they are not amused. (Garcia,
Austin American-Statesman) Art includes 3-column color photo from
film ``Pushing Tin'' and 6-pica color photo of jet landing at
airport in heavy fog.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   STAR FILE CHESNEY _ This spring country music artist Kenny
Chesney tossed off his hat, put on a Hawaiian shirt, headed for the
Caribbean and produced the biggest song not only of his career, but
of country's Class of '99. ``How Forever Feels,'' a danceable,
cotton-candy tune that has ruled the charts for the past month.
(Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 6-pica color
photo of Kenny Chesney.
</P>
<P>
   STAR WARS SOUND _ When George Lucas' fourth ``Star Wars'' film
debuts May 19, it won't sound at some theaters like any movie
you've ever seen and heard before. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 6-pica color photo of Yoda from
``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   PHANTOM MENACE COUNTDOWN _ A 2-column color graphic ``Countdown
to `Star Wars''' outlining the number of days remaining until ``The
Phantom Menace'' opens. (Staff, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS _ Ernst Lubitsch's beloved 1940 film ``The Shop
Around the Corner'' hits the Internet age in ``You've Got Mail,''
giving director and co-writer Nora Ephron a chance to reunite Tom
Hanks and Meg Ryan in a story ideal for their charms. Also
reviewed, ``Babe: Pig in the City.'' (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 18-pica color photo from the
film ``You've Got Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ After splitting from the British teen-dream group
Take That (``Back for Good''), Robbie Williams set about changing
his image. Also, Eric Benet (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY _ Do people randomly maim and murder because they see
violence in films? No, they murder because they are murderers,
predisposed psychopaths. To suggest that Hollywood is to blame for
the tragedy at Littleton, Colo., is ridiculous. (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman) Art includes 1-column color photo from film
``Natural Born Killers.''
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS/REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-ELECTION _ Review of the dark comedy ``Election'' about a
high school teacher (Matthew Broderick) whose personal spite
involves him in the student council president campaign of a
go-getting senior (Reese Witherspoon). From the director of
``Citizen Ruth.'' Grade: A-. (Murray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 24.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-LOVERS _ Review of ``Lovers of the Arctic Circle,'' about
a man and woman who first met at age 8 and who recount the events
that led them to love. Grade: C+. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
10.
</P>
<P>
   FILMS-MUMMIES _ Universal Pictures has been dying to resurrect
one of its classic horror franchises. The Mummy was the last
Universal monster left from the studio's horror movie heyday in the
1930s and '40s. The latest incarnation opens today, starring
Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz and Arnold Vosloo. Its storyline is
similar to the Karloff original. But the $80 million update's path
to the screen was as slow as the somnambulistic Mummy itself. Plus
a look at the previous mummy movies. (Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MUMMY _ The first big summer film _ ``The Mummy'' _ with
Brendan Fraser. 10. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-MUMMY _ Review of ``The Mummy.'' A remake of the 1932
horror film. Treasure hunters stumble upon an ancient tomb and
unwittingly set loose a 3,000-year-old reign of terror. (Garcia,
Austin Amnerican-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TV-GREATEXPEC _ Review. Great Expectations on Masterpiece
Theatre. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA-COLUMN _ Column: The hype surrounding ``Star Wars.''
(Garcia, Austin Amnerican-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   UHLER-COLUMN _ Video column: May 10 marks the centennial of the
birth of Fred Astaire. A look at some of his best movies. (Uhler,
Austin Amnerican-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Books page for this week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0504 -- The story writer John Taliaferro tells of
Tarzan's creator in ``Tarzan Forever: The Life of Edgar Rice
Burroughs, Creator of Tarzan'' could hardly be filled with more
surprises. Though Edgar Rice Burroughs built a career writing about
a noble apeman swinging through the African jungle, the author
never set foot in Africa. (Morris, Austin American Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FOOTE -- Intimate astonishments jump out _ like fish
breaking the surface of a still, dark lake _ from Horton Foote's
quiet, warm, dignified narrative in ``Farewell: A Memoir of a Texas
Childhood.'' (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NONFICTION PREVIEW -- A preview of forthcoming nonfiction
books for the summer reading season. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS -- Scott Huler offers an amazing look at
NASCAR's appeal in ``A Little Bit Sideways: One Week Inside a
NASCAR Winston Cup Race Team.'' (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SECRETYANKEES _ As it turns out, Miss Pittypat's shocked
words in ``Gone With The Wind'' were an understatement. Union
troops were closing in on the city, and her words suggest Atlanta
was a united city. Not so, says UGA professor Thomas Dyer in a new
book, ``Secret Yankees,'' just published by Johns Hopkins
University and getting some national attention. Yanks'd been here
for years, and actively helped the Union. It's taken two decades of
research, starting with an old diary in the UGA archives, but
Dyer's found that Atlanta was crawling with Union sympathizers and
spies. Historians praise the scholarship because it took a dogged
investigation to find out that Atlanta's population wasn't as
unified as Gone With The Wind has led most folks to believe.
(Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 47. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   YANKEES-EXCERPTS _Excerpts from the diary ``Secret Yankees.'' 10
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Georgia writer Frank Gannon, who contributes
regularly to GQ and The New Yorker, has gotten a six-figure advance
for a book on his family roots in Ireland, Mid-Life Irish; former
AJC sportswriter Ed Hinton has signed a six-figure deal with
Warners to do a book on Daytona stock car racing; Michael
Cunningham, who won the Pulitzer Prize for ``The Hours,'' has had a
great year. He also won the PEN/Faulkner Award for fiction and the
American Library Association Award for fiction. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-PITTS _ National syndicated columnist Leonard Pitts Jr.
talks about his tortured relationship with his abusive father and
how that experience affected his relationship with his own sons and
daughters. In his new book, ``Becoming Dad,'' Pitts describes his
journey from an angry teenager to a father learning from the
mistakes of the past. Pitts also talks about what parents can do to
prevent tragedies such as the massacre in Colorado. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-TRENDS _ A look at the upcoming trends in publishing,
based on the American Booksellers Convention in Los Angeles.
(Morris, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MOTHERS _ Self-help author Harriet Lerner says ``Mothers
are blamed for everything and blame themselves in this society,''
she says. In Dayton recently to promote her new book, The Mother
Dance, (Harper-Collins, $25), Lerner also has authored The Dance of
Anger and The Dance of Intimacy. ``A particular mother can behave
badly, even abominably, but she cannot make her child become a
serial killer or even get straight A's. (Dayton Daily News). 28.
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ Anyone who remembers high school Latin knows
that time flies. Stewart Brand would like to slow it down _ or,
rather, expand our consciousness of it so that we are concerned
less about the end of a millennium and more about what might be
called the eternal present. ``The Clock of the Long Now'' is an
anti-millennial book in the sense that it argues for a
reconsideration of how we understand past, present and future.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MAY, 9.
</P>
