<HEADER>
A6640 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     05-06 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, May 6, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-MULHALL (Mulhall, Okla.) _ In this tiny town of 110
homes 40 miles north of Oklahoma City, only 10 are left standing.
Half the town's elementary school is a heap of plastic chairs and
cinderblocks and the 60,000-gallon tank lies twisted on the
hillside. But Mulhall isn't destined to be a ghost town because of
Monday's mammoth tornado _ residents say they are ready to rebuild.
By MARO ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   WW2-VETS (San Francisco) _ More than a half-century after 830
Americans of Japanese ancestry fought for their country and died on
the battlefields of Europe, the legendary valor of their most
well-known units _ the 100th Battalion and the 442nd Regimental
Combat Team _ are celebrated in books, movies and a national
exhibit at the Smithsonian Institution in Washington. A drive is
now underway to create a CD-ROM preserving the history of those who
died in battle. By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-REDFORD-CABLE (San Francisco) _ Robert Redford is pushing his
new cable TV channel, the Sundance Channel. Redford has a dogged
vision of the Sundance concept _ what is better known these days as
synergy, but what was probably dismissed 20 years ago when he
formed his filmmaker's lab as Redford's Folly. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   TV-PVRS (San Francisco) _ Making the idiot box idiot-proof. That
seems to be the theory behind two new TV set-top boxes that hit the
market last month. Dubbed Personal Video Recorders, or PVRs, the
gizmos are being touted as the next wave in TV viewing, allowing
users to create their own instant replays, commercial-free network
viewing experience and effortless recording of shows for later
watching. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MOM-GIFTS (Undated) _ Listen up, all you whiney, milky,
shopping-averse types still dithering over what to get dear old
Mom, who these days may seem younger than you. All you have to do
is observe what your mother already has and then improve on it,
with a replacement that's better, prettier, more fun,
nicer-smelling, cleverer or just plain newer. By JO MANCUSO.
</P>
<P>
   LESBIAN-MOTHERS (San Francisco) _ ``We did this book as an
implement for social change, so people would celebrate motherhood
of all kinds,'' says photographer Barbara Seyda, of her
award-winning book of photographs and stories, ``Women in Love:
Portraits of Lesbian Mothers and Their Families.'' By JANE GANAHL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ It was like watching a ship being
built in a bottle. A 125,000-pound drill rig was being assembled
inside a 10-story building. Why do it? Because the building _ One
Market _ is a big piece of San Francisco history, built in 1917 by
Southern Pacific Railroad as its headquarters. Sure, you could just
knock it down. You also could live in Atlanta. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Ever since my neighbors gave me
a compost bin as a housewarming present, I have sarcastically
referred to it as ``my pets.'' The term is meant totally as a slur
on me and my un-St. Francis of Assisi relationship to animals, not
on the worms and whatever else slithers around inside the
composting bin. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
