<HEADLINE>
W'S READERS PICK THE WORLD'S CHICEST MEN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature from DNR _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent by mail or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number. Please specify that
you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By The Editors of W 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Who are the most-desired and inspiring men in the fields of
sports, entertainment, politics and the arts? See if you agree with
the coveted picks below:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION: DYLAN McDERMOTT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, about a decade ago, Dylan McDermott had all
the trappings of soon-to-be movie stardom a young 80s hunk could
hope for: coveted roles in big-budget movies, an open door to the
Brat Pack's Hollywood parties and an engagement to ingenue-du-jour
Julia Roberts, just after they starred in ``Steel Magnolias''
together and her career took off.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened: His didn't. Julia moved on to Kiefer
Sutherland _ and superstardom _ and McDermott moved on to less
flashy women _ and humdrum roles.
</P>
<P>
   Well, what a difference a decade can make. Today, on a
television studio lot in Manhattan Beach, the 36-year-old actor has
all the trappings a 90s just-made-it TV star could hope for: a trip
to the Super Bowl on the Fox private jet and a brand new black
Jaguar delivered, VIP-style, to the set to ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   In his dressing room sits a silver-framed shot of him winning
his first Golden Globe this year for Best Actor in a TV Drama, sent
by way of congratulations by Paramount's Sherry Lansing. And at
home in Santa Monica, his beautiful actress wife, Shiva Rose Afshar
and two-year-old daughter, Colette, are making Daddy a great
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott discusses the ups and downs of his career as casually
as if it were someone else's. ``You know why I didn't become a
movie star the first go-round?'' he asks. ``Because I wasn't ready
to be a movie star _ I wasn't really a man yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The role of idealistic, struggling Boston lawyer Bobby Donnell
on ``The Practice'' seems tailor-made for McDermott, finally
showing off his earnestness and intensity _ and leading-man square
jaw and blue eyes. ``Bobby was originally meant to be schlubbier,
less stylish, not too attractive.'' he says. ``But I told them that
even as a Boston criminal attorney, he could buy nice clothes at an
outlet store, and they let me do it.''
</P>
<P>
   McDermott may have been a self-described nerd in high school but
he now gets regular mention as one of Hollywood's best-dressed
actors. ``I think it's because I'm from New York,'' he say, ``and
it is the fashion capital of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERFORMING ARTS: MIKHAIL BARYSHNIKOV &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Mikhail Baryshnikov arrived in the U.S in 1973, he quickly
learned to fuse his classical Russian training with a free-form
pursuit of more experimental, Western modes of dance. Now a
50-year-old U.S. citizen, Baryshnikov still embodies the best of
both worlds: He's a ferociously disciplined dancer and leader of
the White Oak dance troupe, but he's not opposed to tossing back
some vodka and sounding off about the problems of the world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEDIA: MATT LAUER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only recently one of New York's most eligible bachelors,
``Today'' show cohost Matt Lauer, who married Dutch model Annette
Roque in October, is still the man that American women most want to
see across the breakfast table. Generally considered a welcome
relief from the irascible and egocentric Bryant Gumbel (a close
friend and the best man at his wedding), Lauer plies his trade with
a combination of good looks, even temperament and just the right
degree of friendly seriousness required for 8 a.m. His fashion
claim to fame _ dark dress shirts with matching ties _ brought a
runway trend to the streets so quickly that even he had to abandon
it lest he look too, well, Matt Lauer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART: DAVID HOCKNEY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If David Hockney is one of the world's most popular living
painters, it's not just because his work _ with its emphasis on
luminous colors and inviting spaces _ is so pleasing to the eye.
Hockney is also a genuine charmer who has never felt the need to
play the tortured artiste. Still youthful and sprightly at age 60,
the British expat remains enamored with his adopted country _ an
enthusiasm that shows in his work, whether he's painting his two
basset hounds or the Grand Canyon itself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS: TED TURNER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's loud, abrasive and obnoxious, but in many ways, Ted Turner
is the consummate American businessman. The merger of Turner
Broadcasting with Time Warner in 1996 put him near the center of
power in the country's biggest media conglomerate, but he hasn't
stopped there.
</P>
<P>
   In politics and the environment, he has put his considerable
money where his even more considerable mouth is; even the U.S.
government often pales by comparison. While Turner has pledged a
billion dollars to the United Nations, Congress dithers over paying
its international dues. And while the Senate might ponder whether
to buy a 95,000-acre ranch in the middle of the Santa Fe National
Forest, Turner had already snapped up nearly a million acres in New
Mexico for preservation. ``He is the most important American on the
conservation front since Teddy Roosevelt,'' says NBC anchor Tom
Brokaw, who calls Turner ``a mogul of the highest order.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROYALTY: JOHN F KENNEDY JR. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was unwise of us to put him on the ballot alongside
Prince Charles and Albert of Monaco, but ``George'' magazine editor
in chief John F. Kennedy Jr., received more votes than any other
nominee in any category. Of course, there is his pedigree, which is
impeccable. And you certainly have to agree that he married well.
</P>
<P>
   He also continues to manage a good deal of finesse under the
enormous public scrutiny that comes from being JFK's son: the nasty
tabloid headlines when he flunked his bar exam, his lovers' spats
documented with high-powered lenses, the near hysteria surrounding
his mother's death. But just because he looks better in an evening
suit, is that any reason to pick him over the Dalai Lama?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC: LENNY KRAVITZ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although music critics aren't always thrilled with Lenny
Kravitz's derivative brand of 70s-style funk/rock, few would deny
that he looks good in bell-bottoms. Last year, Kravitz released his
fifth album, began his world tour and cut off his famous
dreadlocks. The rocker is also planning a film appearance. Not to
worry, though. He may go Hollywood and he may be shorn, but the
tattoos, the piercings and leather get-ups remain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM: HARRISON FORD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The David Carusos and Ryan Philippes of the world may come and
go, but Harrison Ford _ now in the fourth decade of his career _ is
definitely built to last. The former carpenter's rugged,
regular-guy appeal has helped him become this century's most
dependable action hero: His movies have pulled in an astonishing $2
billion worldwide. As for his unstudied sense of style _ part
