</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS: TED TURNER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's loud, abrasive and obnoxious, but in many ways, Ted Turner
is the consummate American businessman. The merger of Turner
Broadcasting with Time Warner in 1996 put him near the center of
power in the country's biggest media conglomerate, but he hasn't
stopped there.
</P>
<P>
   In politics and the environment, he has put his considerable
money where his even more considerable mouth is; even the U.S.
government often pales by comparison. While Turner has pledged a
billion dollars to the United Nations, Congress dithers over paying
its international dues. And while the Senate might ponder whether
to buy a 95,000-acre ranch in the middle of the Santa Fe National
Forest, Turner had already snapped up nearly a million acres in New
Mexico for preservation. ``He is the most important American on the
conservation front since Teddy Roosevelt,'' says NBC anchor Tom
Brokaw, who calls Turner ``a mogul of the highest order.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROYALTY: JOHN F KENNEDY JR. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was unwise of us to put him on the ballot alongside
Prince Charles and Albert of Monaco, but ``George'' magazine editor
in chief John F. Kennedy Jr., received more votes than any other
nominee in any category. Of course, there is his pedigree, which is
impeccable. And you certainly have to agree that he married well.
</P>
<P>
   He also continues to manage a good deal of finesse under the
enormous public scrutiny that comes from being JFK's son: the nasty
tabloid headlines when he flunked his bar exam, his lovers' spats
documented with high-powered lenses, the near hysteria surrounding
his mother's death. But just because he looks better in an evening
suit, is that any reason to pick him over the Dalai Lama?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC: LENNY KRAVITZ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although music critics aren't always thrilled with Lenny
Kravitz's derivative brand of 70s-style funk/rock, few would deny
