<HEADER>
A6770 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-APACHES-BOS &LR;      05-06 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-APACHES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCIDENTS DIM IMAGE OF APACHES' INVINCIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that two US Apache helicopters have crashed in Albania
without a shot being fired, the question arises: What fate awaits
the other 22 choppers if they cross the Kosovo border and enter the
war?
</P>
<P>
   This concern explains a good part of why the Apaches, also known
as the AH-64As, have been held back for now. Helicopters generally
are vulnerable machines. A good shot at one of its rotary blades
can put the craft out of commission. And the Yugoslav army is
believed to have plenty of shoulder-fired surface-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, Apaches are better protected than most
helicopters. They are somewhat armored, protecting them from
gunfire, though not from missiles. They are also built to absorb
the impact of most crashes, making it less likely that the pilot
dies as a result.
</P>
<P>
   However, in another sense, the Apaches are more vulnerable.
Their mission is to attack enemy tanks and troops, which means they
fly in low. Since that puts them in the line of antiaircraft fire,
they have special instruments that let them fly in very low _
hugging the terrain, popping up above hills or treetops, firing
their weapons, and ducking back down.
</P>
<P>
   But flying so low, especially at night or in unfamiliar
territory, heightens the chance of a crash.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, according to US Army data, Apaches have crashed, on
average, two to three times as often as cargo- and troop-carrying
helicopters _ four crashes per 100,000 hours of flight, compared
with 2.2 for the Ch-47 Chinooks and 1.5 for the UH-60 Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, accidents tend to increase as the Army gears up for
war. In 1991, the year of the Persian Gulf War, Apaches crashed at
a rate of 8.76 per 100,000 hours of flight, more than double the
normal rate.
</P>
<P>
   This year, so far, five Apaches have crashed in 63,000 hours of
flight-time _ which translates to 7.94 per 100,000 hours, again
double the usual rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you mobilize for operations, you fly more hours, more
realistic training missions, lower altitudes, more often at
night,'' an Army officer said Wednesday. ``It's no surprise we're
seeing more accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the Army relies on such delicate machines is a story going
back to the years just after World War II, when the US Air Force
split off from the Army and became an independent branch of the
armed forces. The chiefs of the two services met at Key West, Fla.,
and divvied up the ``roles and missions'' that had been performed
by what used to be called the Army Air Forces.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Key West accord, as it came to be called, the Air
Force got control of combat airplanes and the Army was left with
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force had little interest in buying many planes for the
mission of supporting Army troops on the ground. The atomic bomb
seemed to be the weapon of the future. It seemed best delivered by
air power. So, for the next couple decades, that became the Air
Force's chief preoccupation.
</P>
<P>
   The Army chiefs still saw a role for ground troops, but since
they could not count on the Air Force to provide support from the
air, they built up a huge force of helicopters _ even knowing they
would be less lethal and more vulnerable than low-flying airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   This interservice tension persists. As recently as the Gulf War,
the Air Force's A-10 Thunderbolt attack planes, which had been
built specifically to support ground troops, were not included in
the original war-plan. The US commander, Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf,
had to insist that A-10s be involved. Afterwards, official analyses
showed they destroyed more Iraqi tanks and armored personnel
carriers than any other kind of plane.
</P>
<P>
   The analyses also revealed that the A-10s flew 7,983 combat
sorties in the Gulf War, yet only four of the planes were lost to
enemy fire.
</P>
<P>
   This was fewer than the six US helicopters that were lost during
training exercises in the four months leading up to that war,
before a shot was fired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
