<HEADER>
A6771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-KOSOVO-$ADV09     05-06 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-KOSOVO-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A GENERATION LATER, GERMANY ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE GENOCIDE
ISSUE
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ In the half-century since World War II, Germans have
been taught two maxims: No more war; no more genocide.
</P>
<P>
   With the war in Yugoslavia, these principles are in deep and
unresolved conflict.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since being defeated in World War II, German
forces are engaged in armed military action. An estimated 3,000
German soldiers are in Macedonia as part of a multinational
security force and perhaps as an expeditionary force into Kosovo.
Since the start of the war in late March, 14 Luftwaffe Tornado
warplanes have been flying combat missions over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Riveted by the images of an estimated 1.5 million Kosovar
Albanian refugees forced from their homes -- images that are
hauntingly reminiscent of Nazi purges of Jews and others -- Germans
support doing something.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the German government has been a leader in bringing
humanitarian aid to Kosovar Albanian refugees in Macedonia, and
taken in nearly 10,000 of them to ease the burden on the cash-poor
Macedonian government. And last week(CQ), German officials were out
front in bringing Russia to the table to narrow its differences
with Western allies over a future international force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, still for many Germans it remains unthinkable that any
efforts should involve force.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls reveal this duality: Most Germans favor NATO
airstrikes, but even more oppose a ground invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we should contribute,'' said Ernest Roeger, 68, a
retired Berlin chemical engineer. ``We could build up hospitals,
refugee camps and help the people build up their country afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we should not take military action,'' Roeger said.
``Because of German history and because Germany has already dropped
bombs on Belgrade, there should be no Germans among the soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   This thinking spans the generations. In Dresden, a city
decimated by Allied bombing near the end of World War II,
15-year-old Melanie Eberle pauses from a sundae at a McDonald's to
profess her horror at the thought of Germans taking up arms.
</P>
<P>
   In her view, the military is an emergency assistance force
rather than a fighting force trained to capture objectives and kill
the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would never be justified for us to go into another country
and start shooting people,'' said Melanie, who is the only one
among her half-dozen friends sitting at the table to express a
willingness to join the military.
</P>
<P>
   Ruprecht Polenz, a senior member of the foreign affairs
committee in the German parliament, said Germans view war
differently from other Europeans and Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Germans have come to equate war and doing wrong as the same
thing,'' he said. ``For other nations, war can connote liberation
or coming to the aid of allies, but for Germans, it means having
done wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany is so bereft of a military culture that there are no
medals to honor war heroes. The traditional Iron Crosses -- a medal
won by Adolf Hitler in the World War I -- were abolished.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for many, the presence of German forces represents evidence
that the country is at last part of the mainstream. ``I don't know
very much about the Luftwaffe, but I am thrilled to see them fly,''
said Gebhardt von Moltke, the German ambassador to Britain, who was
a child during the last war. ``It means we have finally been
forgiven and can have equal rights and responsibilities with the
rest of NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   The belief that Germany is fighting now because of its
obligation to NATO as opposed to some national aspiration or
interest seems to ease the concerns of many. ``We're an integral
part of NATO,'' said Matthius Griebel, the director of the Dresden
city museum and a survivor of the 1945 fire-bombing. ``When we have
benefitted from NATO security then we must also take part in an
action such as this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, other Germans remain deeply opposed to the war.
</P>
<P>
   Ilona Rothe of Berlin has formed a group called Mothers Against
the War. She says she has received more than 1,000 phone calls from
people who agree with her assertion that the war must be stopped
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have touched a nerve in Germany,'' she said. ``I hear the
women crying on the telephone for their sons or their husbands.''
</P>
<P>
   Her 24-year-old son is among the German troops in Macedonia --
where they have built and operate the best of all the refugee camps
there. So far, Rothe's son has seen no action. ``I heard an
interview with a Serbian mother, in which she said, 'I want my son,
I don't care about (Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic.' That's
how I feel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhardt Schroeder(CQ), the first German
leader with no personal experience with World War II, acknowledged
the dilemma in a recent magazine interview. But he argued that this
generation of Germans must not be in the position of trying to
explain to later ones why they did nothing to respond to the plight
of the Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to be able to say: We did what was possible and
right,'' Schroeder told Der Spiegel. ``Especially as Germans, our
response must be clear: We must never again allow murder,
expulsions and deportations to be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
