<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6774 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-$ADV0     05-06 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELECTIONS DEMONSTRATE ISRAEL'S TRIBAL DIVISIONS
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-BOX-$ADV09.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Yitzak Soudri's vision of Israel is different from
the one most Americans imagine from afar.
</P>
<P>
   For Soudri, a spokesman for the ultra-religious Shas Party,
Israel is not the mythic Zionist refuge, where pioneers band
together for common survival.
</P>
<P>
   He sees what is often called the ``tribal'' Israel. In that
Israeli reality, Shas and their supporters, the ``Sephardim'' of
Asian and North African descent, battle daily against the
``Ashkenazim'' elites from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to start from the assumption that there's a culture
war in the country,'' Soudri says. ``In the last 15 years, Shas has
been destroying everything (the elites) have tried to create . . .
what we're doing frightens every secular Ashkenazi.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the May 17 elections for parliament and prime minister are
intensifying Israel's battles between the tribes. Tribes that seem
to be growing farther apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are remarkably similar to each other compared to
Israelis,'' says Michael Walzer, who studies Israel for the
Institute for Advanced Studies in Princeton, N.J. ``Among the
(countries) I know, Israel is the most polarized.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's current divisions are no surprise. The country was born
only 50 years ago. It has since been rapidly populated by
immigrants speaking different languages, socialist ideologues
fighting for liberation and ultra-religious Jews seeking biblical
land.
</P>
<P>
   Shas and the other Sephardim, olive-skinned and usually working
class, clash with the fair-haired and wealthier Askenazim.
Ultra-Religious Jews in black suits and fedoras attack secular Jews
in tie-dye. The growing Russian and Arab minorities cluster in
their own ethnic parties seeking influence as tie-breakers among
the bigger players.
</P>
<P>
   The population of 6 million is changing. Religious Jews and
Arabs have large families, so their numbers increase. A million
Soviet immigrants have arrived since 1989. And, Israelis are what
one pollster calls, ``calcified voters.'' Repeatedly, Sephardim and
the religious Jews back right-wingers, while Ashkenazim, secular
Jews and Arabs back left-wingers.
</P>
<P>
   They battle daily in the press, politics and sometimes the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each group thinks they only have to worry about themselves.
Extremism is growing,'' said Orthodox Rabbi Yehuda Gilad, leader of
a small mixed party of religious and secular leaders. ``I think the
majority is sick of this trend.''
</P>
<P>
   But, moderation does not look likely.
</P>
<P>
   The Center Party, formed to bridge cultural and political gaps,
is floundering. Extreme religious parties are flexing their muscle
with street protests. The small, combative Change Party benefits
from the backlash by attacking the religious, their military
exemptions and their use of government money for their schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we were defending the state, somebody stole it from
behind our backs,'' says Change candidate Tommy Lapid.
</P>
<P>
   The major candidates for prime minister, right-wing incumbent
Benjamin Netanyahu and left-wing Labor Party challenger Ehud Barak,
are tuning their appeals to ethnic ears. Sometimes they try to
remind people of the common good, sometimes not.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has publicly apologized for historic mistreatment of the
Sephardim by his Ashkenazim. Both parties run campaign ads with
Russian subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   But, this week, a comedian at a Labor Party rally made fun of
the Sephardim -- calling them ``rabble'' -- and Netanyahu's Likud
Party turned it into a campaign commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu later toured a produce market, reportedly saying,
``these so-called elites, they hate the people. They hate
Sephardim.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sephardim make up about 35 percent of the voters -- more
than the Ashkenazim -- and the parliamentary system increases their
clout.
</P>
<P>
   Since only a majority of parliament can recall a prime minister,
any leader has to build a coalition of several small parties to
stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Amid it all, the country's major issue, relations with it's Arab
neighbors, can be decided almost as a by-product of the tribal
competition.
</P>
<P>
   A prime minister can either find himself hostage to the many
demands of small parties or exploit the competition between them to
steer the country toward solutions with the Arabs -- something most
Israelis support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a lot of leverage,'' said Israeli political
scientist Shmuel(cq) Sandler. ``You can buy them off.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Shas wants more government money for religious
schools and Shas welfare services. The peace process is less
important.
</P>
<P>
   When left-winger Yitzhak Rabin agreed to their demands, they
joined his coalition and helped him ratify the historic Oslo Peace
Accords. In 1996, when Benjamin Netanyahu agreed to their demands,
they bolstered his coalition and helped him bring the Oslo process
to a tense standstill.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Shas finds new competition from other ethnic parties.
</P>
<P>
   The main Russian party is running commercials in Russian
exhorting voters to give it more parliamentary seats than Shas.
</P>
<P>
   With that clout, the ad promises, it will be able to force the
next prime minister to remove the Shas leadership of the
immigration ministry and install a secular Russian in the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to give (the ministry) to us just as a
gesture,'' says Natan Sharansky, leader of the party.
</P>
<P>
   In return for its demands, the Russians would set aside their
hawkish views on the peace process. They backed the dovish Rabin in
1992. Seeking a better deal, they flipped and backed the hawkish
Netanyahu in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But, prime ministers can also find themselves at what many call
the ``blackmail'' of the tribes.
</P>
<P>
   The religious parties, for example, threatened to bring down
Netanyahu's government if he backed proposals to recognize the less
traditional Reform and Conservative forms of Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's predicament is summed up artfully by an animated
political commercial for the left-wing Meretz Party.
</P>
<P>
   It shows an exhausted Netanyahu dancing to a caricature
``Klezmer'' band of notable religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the tribes choose the music and the prime
minister dances.
</P>
<P>
   Even Netanyahu supporters found it amusing. But, given the tense
political climate and Israel's tribal voting habits, few will
change their vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it brought a smile to people's faces,'' said Meretz
parliamentarian Nomi Chazan. ``That's something.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
