<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6775 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BOX-$ADV09-COX     05-06 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BOX-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW ISRAELI ETHNIC AND RELIGIOUS GROUPS VOTED
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-POLITICS-$ADV09.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 9 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The May 17 elections for Israeli prime minister, and
the possible June 1 run-off, are expected to be split along ethnic
and religious lines. That's how elections have long been decided in
what many call Israel's ``tribal'' society.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Jews of European descent, Arabs and secular voters
prefer the left-wing Labor Party while Russian immigrants, Jews of
North African and Asian descent, and religious voters back
right-wing Likud.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at ethnic voting patterns based on research on the
1996 election when the Likud Party's Benjamin Netanyahu narrowly
beat the Labor Party's Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
   ETHNIC GROUPS:
</P>
<P>
   Group: Jews of recent African and Asian descent.
</P>
<P>
   Percent of electorate now: 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vote in 1996: 60 percent supported Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Group: Jews of recent European or American descent.
</P>
<P>
   Percent of electorate now: 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vote in 1996: 70 percent supported Peres.
</P>
<P>
   Group: Immigrants from the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Percent of electorate now: 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vote in 1996: 62 percent supported Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Group: Jews with parents born in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Percent of electorate now: 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vote in 1996: 60 percent voted for Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Group: Arab Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Percentage of electorate now: 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vote in 1996: 95 percent supported Peres.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGIOUS IDENTIFICATION (overlapping with ethnic groups):
</P>
<P>
   Group: Orthodox and Ultra-Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Percent of electorate now: 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vote in 1996: 96 percent supported Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Group: Traditional, though not Orthodox, Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Percent of electorate now: 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vote in 1996: 65 percent for Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Group: Secular Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Percent of electorate now: 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vote in 1996: 63 percent supported Peres.
</P>
<P>
   Group: Arabs (Muslims, Christians).
</P>
<P>
   Percent of electorate now: 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vote in 1996: 95 percent supported Peres.
</P>
<P>
   (same as ethnic Arab group above)
</P>
<P>
   Source: Smith Research Institute, Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
