<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6777 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELTWAY-SISTERS-BOS &LR;      05-06 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELTWAY-SISTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK WOMEN GRAB REINS TO STEER DEMOCRATIC RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not so long ago, Regena Thomas and other members of
the ``Colored Girls Club,'' as the tight-knit group of black female
political operatives call themselves, watched a parade of their
white male counterparts assume key roles in Democratic Party
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   While the ``white guys'' made the big bucks and sat ``at the
right hand of God,'' so to speak, Thomas said, ``we were the ones
who got called the last 30 days of the campaign, when all the money
had been spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this was going to be our lives for the rest of our
days,'' she chuckled. ``But now, here we are at the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   A record number of black women are at the starting gate of
political campaigns this year, taking charge of strategy for the
Democratic Party and one of its presidential candidates. They are
the George Stephanopouloses and James Carvilles for the last
election of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Their brash, self-confident, shoe-leather style of grass-roots
politicking has become an important cachet.
</P>
<P>
   This cadre of women includes Thomas, who was recently elevated
to national campaign director at the Democratic National Committee;
Donna Brazile, who is Vice President Al Gore's new deputy campaign
manager and national political director; and Minyon Moore, who was
promoted to assistant to the president and director of White House
political affairs earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the group are Carlottia Scott, the Democratic National
Committee's new chief of politics, and Alison McLaurin, who at 29
is the youngest member of the informal and loosely organized
Colored Girls Club. Despite her age, McLaurin is the veteran,
having been political director at the Democratic Governors
Association since last June.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of McLaurin, all the women cut their teeth in
national politics on Jesse Jackson's unsuccessful presidential bids
in 1984 and 1988. Collectively they have traveled every state in
the nation as campaign workers, and their combined experience spans
local, state, national and, in some cases, overseas elections.
</P>
<P>
   With recent polls showing that women are leaving the Democratic
Party, these political directors are helping craft a message not
only to bring back women and attract the huge swath of black voters
who are registered and don't vote, but also to reach those in rural
areas and those who are young and alienated from the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``What our being here says is that this is a very important
election, and it is so important that you have to disturb the
comfortable,'' Moore said. ``It has caused people to want to get
back out here and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of these women have been on the political scene for years _
knocking on doors, shaking hands and kissing babies. They say it is
now their turn to be front and center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to contribute to victories in the elections. No
one's doing them any favors,'' said David Bositis, a senior
research associate at the Joint Center for Political and Economic
Studies, a black think tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Political pollster Ron Lester agreed: ``They have paid their
dues.''
</P>
<P>
   After Democrats got their ``butts kicked'' in 1994, as McLaurin
put it, the women weighed in to help the party recover. Thomas, for
example, was dispatched to New Jersey in 1996 to help
then-Representative Robert G. Torricelli campaign for an open
Senate seat, which he won.
</P>
<P>
   Brazile, as a senior political adviser for the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, lead a stealth campaign to reach
black voters in last year's midterm election. Democrats bucked
historical trends for an off-year election, picking up five House
seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``These women played critical roles going into November's
elections, and so they have been and are being rewarded for the
roles that they played,'' said Representative James E. Clyburn, a
South Carolina Democrat and chairman of the Congressional Black
Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   DNC Chairman Roy Romer, a former governor of Colorado, said,
``There was never any pre-planned strategy'' to make political
history by picking black women for the campaign jobs. ``These
decisions were arrived at because the people are competent,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bositis, however, said that taken together, their presence might
benefit Gore if he becomes the presidential nominee. ``It's clear
that they have experience in black politics, and the fact is that
the black vote is going to be important both for the Democrats and
certainly for Al Gore,'' he said. ``Between 55 and 60 percent of
the black population is in the South. ... If Gore takes the South,
it doesn't matter what happens in the rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Brazile, ``We not only know black people, but we know white
people, too, and that makes us very valuable. We will outwork
anybody on the political scene today, other than our candidates,
who we will work to death.''
</P>
<P>
   These women are beneficiaries of the groundwork laid by Fannie
Lou Hamer, a Mississippi voting rights worker who pressed the
Democratic Party in the early 1960s to give African-Americans a
seat at the table. More recently Jackson; the late Ronald Brown,
who was Commerce secretary and the former DNC chairman; and Labor
Secretary Alexis Herman are helping show that blacks know what to
do once they get that seat.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the new roles these women play, rather than being
revolutionary, have evolved in the party, Bositis points out.
</P>
<P>
   After working on the Jackson campaigns, most of the women
ventured into other presidential campaigns, including those of
House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt and former Massachusetts
Governor Michael Dukakis, as well as the campaign of Senator Edward
M. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Jackson's campaigns that ``taught you not to freak
out over the fact that you have less than 48 hours to pull off a
miracle,'' said Brazile.
</P>
<P>
   Their new jobs have forced one change when the club meets for
their frequent Friday night fish fries. Now, instead of cooking the
fish, one of the women brings it already prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Having her ``sisters'' with her, Scott said, ``brings a new
dynamic to the whole of the Democratic Party structure. It's about
us as a collective, as a family, and what we do is bigger than us
as individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Moore: ``We've always had the company of each other. Now we
have the accountability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
