<SLUG> BC-MIT-MOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN BREAKS BARRIERS FOR COLLEGE GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She had seen it a hundred times before. All around Nora Cadena,
girls were getting pregnant and leaving high school.
</P>
<P>
   Or they were having their babies and trying to finish anyway,
dragging their educations out over extra years, against long odds,
and in spite of politicians' caricatures of them as shiftless and
irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   But she was different. She had stayed out of trouble. School had
always been easy for her. And she was going to college.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at 16, she got pregnant, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really disappointed in myself. I couldn't believe it,''
Cadena recalled. ``I said, God wouldn't do this, this can't happen.
I have everything going for myself.' I thought it would all be
over.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't over. Indeed, come September, Cadena will leave
her parents in San Fernando, Calif., and travel with her baby
Chassitty, now 9 months old, to MIT. She will be one of only 10
undergraduate parents out of a student population of almost 5,000,
and one of the few freshmen to bring a child to school with her.
</P>
<P>
   And to attend MIT, she is turning down University of California
at Berkeley, University of Southern California, California Lutheran
University, and possibly Harvard, where she is on the waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   When she unpacks her bags in Cambridge this fall, Cadena already
will be freighted with more responsibilities than most of her
classmates will face for years.
</P>
<P>
   But she will also be armed with many of the advantages with
which the luckiest students arrive at the country's best schools:
strong parents, teachers who refused to write her off, and a large
helping of natural ability.
</P>
<P>
   America has the highest teenage pregnancy rate of all developed
countries _ nearly double that of Britain _ with a million
adolescent girls becoming pregnant each year. And even though US
pregnancy rates have been declining since the early 1990s, the
decreases have barely touched Hispanic teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Cadena, who is Hispanic, saw many of her classmates become
pregnant and leave the school, or stay and ``just get by.''
</P>
<P>
   Many were also battling tough economic situations, as was she.
Most of the community where she lives with her parents, both of
whom lost their jobs earlier this year, live below the poverty
line. One of her teachers told the Los Angeles Times that half of
his 9th graders drop out or return to Mexico each year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as many children from difficult circumstances do with
enough support and smarts, Cadena shone as a student, taking six
advanced-placement courses and managing a 4.284 grade point
average.
</P>
<P>
   But when she got pregnant, the academic success and the strong
family life counted for little. She, too, felt the sting of the
stereotypes, with strangers on the street calling her names.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I'd go out to the store, every time I'm walking
down the street with (Chassitty), people would stare and comment,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said most of the teachers in her school expected her resolve
to slip after the baby was born, but quickly came around. Cadena
took a total of 10 days off for her child's birth, and even came to
school three days after Chassitty was born to pick up an
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Since her parents weren't working, she also took a job at a
discount clothing store, where she worked for 25 hours a week while
raising her baby and continuing her studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I matured really quickly,'' she said. ``I realized the
importance of getting an education, and this is how I'm going to be
able to advance myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But will the persistence that got her to one of the most
academically demanding colleges in the country be enough to help
Cadena survive four years there? She will, after all, be bringing
up her baby alone, thousands of miles from the parents who have
been so vital to her and Chassitty's success so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be difficult,'' she said. ``I'm wondering if
it's all going to catch up with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cadena has friends at MIT already, which is partly why she first
applied there. She is already lining up child care. And MIT has
offered her family housing. She will get by on scholarships and
loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be the first time an 18-year-old has come in as a
parent, but it's unusual,'' said Kathy Simons, MIT Family Resource
Center coadministrator. The institute offers help with medical
care, and flexibility in courseload for parents.
</P>
<P>
   But Cadena's biggest hurdle may be back in California.
Chassitty's father has threatened to sue to keep Cadena from
leaving the state with his child.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gina Ocon, the California mother whose former partner tried
to keep her from attending Harvard with their infant daughter, and
who eventually won the right to attend Harvard, Cadena has had
offers of legal help from several women's advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I have a lot of people helping me,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
