<HEADER>
A6782 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMAZON-EXPLORE-ART-BO     05-06 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-EXPLORE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE TEAM BELIEVES IT'S FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE AMAZON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question does not often occur to your average dad, but for
Ned Strong it became all-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the Amazon begin?
</P>
<P>
   The mighty 4,000-mile river, which runs from the Peruvian Andes
through Brazil to the Atlantic Ocean, holds more water than the
Nile, the Yangtze and the Mississippi together _ a full fifth of
all the world's flowing water.
</P>
<P>
   But it starts _ somewhere _ as a trickle.
</P>
<P>
   Just where has been a matter of some contention for decades. A
few weeks ago, Strong, 46, his 13-year-old son Peter, a hiking
partner, Lew Scotten, altitude specialist Dr. Michael Wiedman,
Strong's brother Don, and National Geographic photographer Zbigniew
Bdzak headed for Peru, on their own search for that place.
</P>
<P>
   They carried with them sophisticated Global Positioning System
(GPS) satellite tracking equipment, camping gear, freeze-dried
dinners and a flag from the New York Explorers Club.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks and 85 cans of tuna later, they are back, armed with a
computer-load of figures which, when synthesized, will settle the
question of where the Amazon begins, once and for all. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of late 20th-century exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Strong's son, Peter, was 9 when his father started talking about
finding the source of the Amazon. The elder Strong had been on a
hiking trip in Ecuador with Scotten, and the two were determined to
follow the river to its beginning. Peter begged to go along back
then, but was told he was too young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took so long for him to set a date to do it that I got to
go,'' said the seventh-grader at Clarke Middle School in Lexington,
Mass. Until this trip, he had been camping with his father in New
Hampshire, and once at Yellowstone, but never anywhere more exotic.
</P>
<P>
   And while the adults had to train for the high altitudes of the
Andes, the 13-year-old long-jumper and 200-meter runner was ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best hiker among us,'' said Ned Strong, who heads
the Latin American Scholars exchange program at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   The team flew into Arequipa, southeast of Lima, then traveled
for two days to get to their base camp. They spent the first week
training for the altitude, then set up camp at the Lloqueta river,
an area where expeditions before theirs have agreed lies the origin
of the Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to determine what was the longest stream of
water that feeds into the Amazon,'' said Ned Strong. ``A lot of
people have gone up into this area, but because of altitude
sickness, they weren't able to do the survey work that we did. And
we were the first group to go up there with a sophisticated GPS
system to chart the exact location.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We went farther than previous expeditions,'' said Wiedman,
calling from Peru. ``And we got measurements they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   For four days, the party mapped each of the tributaries that fed
the River Lloqueta, which itself eventually runs into the Amazon:
the longest one would be the source of the giant river.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, they rose at 6, and followed the brooks toward
the peaks of three mountains, Mount Mismi, Mount Cutiti, and Mount
Quehuisha. At 18,000 feet, there was a surprising amount of
activity, the explorers said: villagers from lower country grazing
their sheep, llamas and alpacas on the grass and mosses up on the
otherwise lunar hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just surprising that such a harsh environment would
support that many plants,'' Ned Strong said.
</P>
<P>
   Every day at 2 p.m. it snowed. And every night, after trout, or
canned tuna, or freeze-dried meals, the group huddled in their
sleeping bags and tents in below-freezing temperatures, asleep by 7
or 8 p.m. Peter used his spare time to rehearse lines from his
school's upcoming production of ``Snow White.'' (He plays the
prince.)
</P>
<P>
   After all of the tributaries had been mapped, the group
celebrated with champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Now the real work, and the controversy, begins.
</P>
<P>
   Many parties have been to River Lloqueta watershed area before.
In 1971, National Geographic writer and photographer Loren McIntyre
found a catchment area just below the peak of Mount Mismi, later
named Lake McIntyre, and for years that was agreed upon as the
source of the Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, a Polish crew headed by Virginia-based adventurer
and environmentalist Piotr Chmielinski named the source at a
different point.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts-based team isn't sure yet where the longest
source will be. They've narrowed it down to two spots _ one close
to Lake McIntyre, and another along a different stream, the river
Ccaccansa, which flows from the top of Mount Cutiti. When the
calculations are finished, the source-point will emerge, they say.
In the end, they may add only yards to McIntyre's original
source-point.
</P>
<P>
   It's a very modern kind of expedition: the kind that ends not in
a huge, startling discovery, but in a cache of information to be
synthesized later. Just about every summit has been reached, every
lost tribe found. All the flags have been stuck.
</P>
<P>
   What's left is the hair-splitting expedition, that which yields
not new, but better, information. And notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why keep climbing Everest, or going across the Atlantic in a
rowboat? In a sense, they're stunts, and you try to outstunt
somebody else and you get your 15 minutes of fame,'' said McIntyre,
who at 82 has grown impatient with the revisionist explorers.
</P>
<P>
   There's a crew on Mount Everest right now trying to establish
its exact height using GPS.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Livingstone's day, it was kind of a romantic situation,''
said McIntyre. ``But there's not much of that kind of thing going
on in the world now. Today you go to the Discovery Channel and
dozens of (expeditions) are going on just to provide adventure
fare.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Strongs feel no less adventuresome than Dr. David
Livingstone, and their findings promise to be no less controversial
than that famous 19th century quest for the source of the Nile,
during which Livingstone disappeared, and over which competing
explorers practically dueled.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon explorers disagree not only on where the source of the
South American river is, but also on how to define it. The river
changes too much to allow for absolute pronouncements on its
origin, said McIntyre. ``The Amazon changes from one moment to the
next,'' he said. ``It's tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   And this latest group is aware that their own findings will also
be a matter of perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to measure from the top of the watershed
permanently in snow and ice, then that would be the source,'' said
Ned Strong. ``If you want to measure from where the water starts,
then that's the source.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll let the debate happen,'' he said. ``We just wanted to
provide the data.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
