<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-MULHALL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIRIT TO REBUILD SURVIVES IN TOWN RAVAGED BY TWISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARO ROBBINS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MULHALL, Okla. _ The elementary school is destroyed. So are the
only store and the water tower.
</P>
<P>
   Among the only assets not touched by the tornado that hit here
Monday are the plucky community spirit and the plaque naming
Mulhall a finalist for the title of Best Small Town in America.
</P>
<P>
   The plaque hung Wednesday in the community center above cold
cuts and other donated relief. The spirit was evident in the
streets as residents and neighbors picked up the debris left by the
storm.
</P>
<P>
   No one died in Mulhall in the category F-4 tornado that left a
swath of death in nearby communities. But no house in this town,
which sits nestled among emerald pastures about 40 miles north of
Oklahoma City, escaped unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Of 110 homes, all but 10 were left uninhabitable or suffered
major damage, according to the volunteer fire department.
</P>
<P>
   About half the of Mulhall-Orlando Elementary School appeared a
heap of plastic chairs and cinderblocks.
</P>
<P>
   The 60,000-gallon tank that held the water supply lay twisted on
the hillside, after having dumped its contents onto a nearby lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Most of town's population of about 200 is retired. The community
dates back to an 1889 land grab and was named for a promoter of
wild-west shows.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not likely anytime soon to become a dusty ghost town.
Many of its residents said Wednesday they found hope and reasons to
rebuild from the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John Pangburn said he hoped the catastrophe would dispel
some of the apathy that has left one of the city council's three
posts vacant. He also said the disaster might help the town obtain
long-anticipated state funding necessary to upgrade an antiquated
water-supply system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may help push (the project) along a little bit faster,''
said Pangburn, who appeared unshaven and carried two cans of spray
paint, as he prepared to go door to door, making sure all local
water valves were off.
</P>
<P>
   Up the hill, the Rev. Troy Withey worked with parishioners to
haul out the chunks of sheetrock and tufts of yellow insulation
left behind when the storm snatched pieces of the First Baptist
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Mulhall's newest inhabitants, Withey and his wife, finished
moving into the parsonage at about 2 p.m. on Monday. The twister
leveled the house about eight hours later. But it didn't take much
longer for Withey to find the silver lining in the dark stormy sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to minister in this town ... It would be hard to do if
I hadn't lost anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chainsaws buzzed on almost every street. Nearby towns sent
municipal work crews to help clear away the torn trees and smashed
homes. Private contractors came on their own, as did college
students and bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pangburn, the town's contingency fund only holds
about $80,000, set aside to match state grants. To supplement the
hamlet's sparse budget, a relief fund for donations has been opened
at the Oklahoma State Bank in nearby Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-day, crisp American flags snapped in the breeze along the
muddy Main Street, where someone had placed them, as if for a
parade.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only sign of business-as-usual was a fresh copy of
the Daily Oklahoman in a muddied newspaper-vending machine outside
the town's only grocery and deli.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Jackie's Farmers Store, a slab of cheese and melted bars
of butter, squashed by the winds, clung to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on soggy snacks and sheetrock, Jackie Pfeiffer talked
about rebuilding. She has considered calling it quits, she said,
during her quiet moments at home alone, in the nearby town of
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The thought, however, evaporates when she returns to the town
that she has served seven days a week for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Said Pfeiffer: ``You know you have to come back after seeing the
rallying of the community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
