<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTALLING CEILING BUTTONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The plaster ceiling in my condo in a 1920 building is
sagging. I bought some ceiling buttons to try to get the ceiling
plaster back up. But I am not sure how to use them. Are they driven
into the lath, the strapping or the joists?
</P>
<P>
   DONALD TURKEWICH, Brighton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can drive screws into the lath which, chances are, is not
sagging. If it is, you have to drive the screws through the lath
and into the strapping, which is nailed at right angles to the
joists.
</P>
<P>
   Before driving the screws, press the plaster ceiling up and
level. Plaster applied to wood lath is pressed between the lath
strips, spreading out a little when it goes through those gaps,
creating a key; that is how the plaster is held in place. Sometimes
these ``keys'' break off and the ceiling sags.
</P>
<P>
   If the ceiling does not push up nice and evenly, it means that
broken plaster has gotten between the ceiling and the lath, and a
fix is impossible; if that happens, that section of plaster must be
removed and new plaster _ or a plasterboard patch _ put in its
place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wood paneling is 35 years old and I thought it needs a
little refurbishing. I sprayed on Old English wood polish. That
stuff smelled to high heaven, a sickening smell. I washed it with
baking soda and water; the odor remained just as strong, and
remained so even after I used Spic and Span and water, then ammonia
and water, then vinegar and water. The wood is now bone dry, with
the odor as intense as ever, and I am desperate. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR DONISI, Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It seems to me that all those treatments did remove the
polish, so it is a mystery as to why the odor remains. There are a
couple of things you can try. 1. Wash with straight white vinegar;
your diluted vinegar wasn't strong enough. 2. Wash with paint
thinner, which has its own smell which should dissipate. 3. Wash
with Natural Magic Odor Blaster, sold in retail, hardware, and
grocery stores, or call 800-376-2442 for locations.
</P>
<P>
   Odor Blaster does not disguise the odor or paralyze the smeller,
but oxidizes the odor. It comes in scents (citrus and herbal) but I
suggest you use the ``natural'' stuff. Goodness knows you don't
need another odor.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, I suggest you sand the paneling very
lightly to roughen it, and apply two coats of a semigloss,
oil-based polyurethane varnish, which should cover the polish odor,
and with plenty of ventilation, eventually will not smell. And lay
off the polish; it does not belong on paneling anyway, in my
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am getting a distinct smell of cigarette smoke in the
living room of my apartment since a smoker moved in below me, and
it migrates to the bedroom as well. I have been in the 25-story
building since it opened in 1963. The maintenance people caulked
along the baseboard, and I think around a pipe coming out of the
floor, which helped a little. The baseboard heater is several
inches above the floor. Is there anything else that I can do?
</P>
<P>
   J. W., Boston
</P>
<P>
   A. Physical blocking is the best thing you can do to keep out
the smoke, and caulking is physical blocking. Have any and all
joints caulked; it may not look so hot but it may help. The joints
that can be caulked are at the top of the baseboard (which I assume
is what was already caulked), between the baseboard and the floor,
around pipes coming through the floor or wall, and possibly around
window casings because the smoke may be coming up through the wall
and into your unit around the window casing. Do this on inside
walls as well as outside ones.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a shoe mold (a quarter-round molding) between the
baseboard and floor. If you have hardwood flooring, there may be a
half-inch open joint under that shoe mold; that is an expansion
joint to allow the wood floor to expand and contract, which is good
because it prevents the floor from warping. But that open joint may
be a perfect conduit for the smoke from below. The best way to
caulk that joint is to remove the shoe mold, caulk the joint
heavily, fill the open joint, and put the shoe mold back on. This
will make a good closure, and be invisible. The caulking is
flexible enough that it will not interfere with the expansion and
contraction.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing to try is to have your neighbor have his unit
caulked between wall and ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Caulking has to be complete and thorough; a lick and a promise
will not do. The more seams and joints and cracks you caulk, the
better off you will be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am replacing a picket fence. What kind of wood should be
used for posts, rails, and pickets? A carpenter said he would make
the pickets and build the fence for a lot less than a professional
fence company. Should the posts be set in gravel or concrete? I
would like to paint or stain the fence.
</P>
<P>
   MARGARET O'CONNELL, Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Ideally, the posts would be pressure-treated lumber, and the
rails and pickets would be white cedar, so you could stain them.
Stain everything with two coats of a solid latex stain. Forget
about paint. You will get no cedar bleed (brown stains bleeding
through the paint) because cedar bleed results from painting or
staining red cedar, and since white cedar has no pigment, no cedar
bleed.
</P>
<P>
   Posts should never be set in concrete. It causes premature
decay, and always put them in earth, with about 6 inches of crushed
stone at the bottom for drainage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
