<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICTURING MOM AS SHE MIGHT HAVE BEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Carol Green's images of the mother she never knew are
haunting. The walls of Le Gamin, a small South End cafe are lined
with more than 70 of Green's photographs, all of them reproductions
of the same portrait of the same delicate face, re-cast again and
again in dozens of glamorous roles.
</P>
<P>
   With these images Green, a Back Bay artist, has invented another
life for her mother, a life that might have been if she hadn't died
at 23, if she'd gone to Hollywood. When Green was growing up in
Jacksonville, Fla., friends and relatives remarked on her late
mother's beauty. ``She was pretty enough to be a movie star, that's
what people always said about her,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Green's mother Sylvia died in 1937, 10 days after giving birth
to her only child. When Green was 6 years old, a cousin told her
that her stepmother was not her biological mother. At that point,
she recalled, she was more shocked to find she had a stepmother
than she was to learn her mother had died. Reared on fairy tales,
she thought all stepmothers must be evil, but her own was a
wonderful, loving woman.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 18 her father gave Green her mother's girlhood
scrapbook, which included a hand-colored photograph, an engagement
portrait which, years later, would inspire what she calls her
``Mother Made For Technicolor'' project. In 1989 Green's children,
Robin and Scott, gave her a Polaroid Spectra System camera. Not
long after, she decided to try photographing her mother's
engagement portrait. ``When that first print popped out of the
camera, there was something about it, the light on her face, that
made me think of a beautiful evocation of a '30s film star.''
</P>
<P>
   Green went on to create more than 300 images of her mother as
the star of dozens of movies, shooting the engagement portrait in
various lights, using props and fabrics to create different effects
evocative of films of the '20s and '30s. In one, ``Natasha,'' she
stares cooly from beneath a furry hat, reminsicent of Garbo in
``Ninotchka.'' In another, ``Honeymoon in Honolulu,'' she's draped
in glittery Christmas decorations, peering from behind tropical
foliage _ a fresh pineapple. In ``Mail-Order Bride'' she wears a
perky orange feathered hat. ``I used to see so many Western movies,
and there was always a mail-order bride getting off the
stagecoach,'' Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the project, Green also wrote a short biography of
her mother's life as a film star. ``I wanted people to really feel
the two possibilities, that if destiny had taken a different turn
she might have been a movie star,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   The biography begins with her selling hats in a department store
where she's ``discovered'' by a Hollywood talent scout, moves to
her screen test, then on to her fabulous fictional career in
movies, her roles in ``Dollface,'' ``The Follies Girl,''
``Tradewinds,'' ``Hometown Girl,'' and many more.
</P>
<P>
   People see all sorts of things in ``Mother Made For
Technocolor,'' Green says. A comment on the evanescent nature of
celebrity. A cinematic blurring of fantasy and reality. A tribute
to her lost mother. A testament to the emotional power exerted by a
lost or missing parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me all the time, was it cathartic? It wasn't at
all,'' Green said. ``It was exciting and interesting, a very
physical labor of love. But I was so caught up in the creation of
it that I felt detached from emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotion caught up with her as she was compiling collages of real
snapshots from her mother's scrapbook, black and white images to
hang alongside ``Mother Made For Technicolor.'' The girl who became
her mother frolicks on the beach with friends, poses with her new
husband on her wedding day. ``That's when I felt some deep sense of
melancholy and loss and mourning,'' Green said. ``Looking at her
real life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
