<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOM-GIFTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T JUST GIVE MOM ANY OLD GIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO MANCUSCO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Listen up, all you whiney, milky,
shopping-averse types still dithering over what to get dear old
Mom, who these days may seem younger than you.
</P>
<P>
   That's the thing _ allow yourself to be sucked into the slick,
brilliantly colored Mother's Day world painted by major retailers
and you'll never locate your mom, who climbs rocks or day-trades or
predicts treacherous plot turns on soap operas _ perhaps all three
in the same day.
</P>
<P>
   No, in Retail Mother's Day Land, moms are awash in 47 flavors of
perfume, pearl jewelry, crystal vases, French terry robes, diaper
bags disguised as totes, candles and really ugly sandals.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you've already shrugged your shoulders and carried one of
those pre-wrapped gifts to the cash-wrap, setting it down like an
unfamiliar totem you hope will appease a vaguely understood deity.
This is for those of you whose minds cannot make the leap from
saute pan to serving platter, from blazer to scarf, from camera to
photo album:
</P>
<P>
   All you have to do is observe what your mother already has and
then improve on it, with a replacement that's better, prettier,
more fun, nicer-smelling, cleverer or just plain newer.
</P>
<P>
   Take the camera illustration. Your mother has a camera. Is it
old, the lens scratched or just not very sharp? Or does Mom
complain that it's too tricky to use, does she have trouble loading
the film? New camera! Or consider the photo album. Are those
``peel-back'' albums from the '70s turning icky? Are overflow
snapshots jumbled in a shoe box? New photo-storage system!
</P>
<P>
   Here is a truly crucial caveat: Don't ``retire'' something with
significant sentimental attachment. Spiffy new recipe cards in a
file might seem thoughtful, but not if Mom treasures cooking from
decades-old, handwritten recipes given her by friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   Look around Mom's abode or play back conversations in your mind:
It could be as simple as a pair of worn slippers that have given
their all. And don't think you must give a single ``significant''
present that costs exactly what you want to spend; opening several
packages is fun at any age.
</P>
<P>
   Mom has a sweet tooth? Treat her to what she wouldn't buy for
herself _ an assortment of Bernard C. chocolates, perhaps, or
something unexpected and nostalgic, like a box of Aplets &AMP; Cotlets.
</P>
<P>
   Mom's a fix-it whiz? What about upgrading some of those tools
she's accumulated? Is she on the cusp of CD-readiness? Maybe a
player _ and CDs of some of her favorite cassette tapes to make the
transition easier.
</P>
<P>
   Electronics and small appliances are excellent prospects but, as
with all gift ideas, you've to gauge _ by insidious interrogation,
if necessary _ whether your gift actually will be welcome. A
designer-hued six-slice toaster might be ultracool, but if Mom has
no call to produce stacks of toast rising like CD towers, your
choice will seem about as personal as, say, a glitzy new answering
machine when Mom has been raving about how much the one she has
helps out on business trips.
</P>
<P>
   The other caveat is to focus on what you and Mom share and stick
with what you know: Give Mom an uninformed gift like bicycle
gloves, a classical flute recording, home-finance software or a
mounted moth and you've presented her with a dilemma instead of
something she can enjoy. But if you have started wine-tasting
together, a set of classic goblets and a bottle of red you both
liked would fall in the ``thoughtful'' category.
</P>
<P>
   And, squirm all you want, therein lies the true secret of
gift-giving: You have to pay attention to the other person.
</P>
<P>
   Contemplate the implications _ there will be a test one week
before Father's Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
