<HEADLINE>
MOTHERS DESERVE HELP, NOT BLAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a private Mother's Day communication. Unless you are a
mother or have had a mother, please go on to some other part of the
paper.
</P>
<P>
   OK, we're alone now. I can talk without having to worry.
</P>
<P>
   This is what I'm brooding about:
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Littleton, parents are once again in the
gunsights. When kids go wrong, everyone's taking aim at mothers and
dads, asking, ``Shouldn't they have known? Shouldn't they have done
something? Shouldn't they have cared more?'' Not a word about the
ways we're undermined, unsupported, and burdened with the full
responsibility, not only for raising kind-hearted, stable children,
but for fighting the powerful forces in this culture that blow our
good intentions to smithereens.
</P>
<P>
   If we're going to be blamed for how our kids turn out, I think
it's time the culture gave us a little help.
</P>
<P>
   Just think of all the stuff parents, (let's face it, mostly
moms), are expected to do these days. In addition to holding down a
job and taking care of a home, we're supposed to be supervising
homework, attending every sporting event in which our kids
participate, taking them to doctor and dentist appointments,
keeping them clean, preparing healthy meals, overseeing
friendships, buying birthday presents, chauffeuring them to
lessons, parties, and after-school dates, purchasing and tending to
their clothing, reading to them, listening to them, stimulating
their minds, meeting with their teachers, explaining sex to them,
making sure we know where they are every moment, on and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   This is more than enough to fill a mother's day.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I don't mind this list. It's filled with nurturing
behavior, the kind that can be accompanied by a hug or a laugh, the
kind that makes you feel you're contributing to your kids' quality
of life. No mother minds spending time having a positive effect on
her children's lives.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, there's a whole new range of expected
maternal behavior that's more like voodoo. Using our special brand
of magic, mothers are expected to ward off a clutch of dangers.
</P>
<P>
   If our kids are little, we're expected to keep informed about
pesticide residues in baby food, poisonous polyvinyl chloride in
plastic toys, and how watching TV is stunting the development of
our children's brains and attention spans.
</P>
<P>
   Notice that no one else in this culture assumes any
responsibility for your child's health and well-being.
</P>
<P>
   When they're preteens, we're supposed to combat the
corporate-sponsored fads that saturate their world, keep them from
playing video games six hours a day, warn them about the dangers of
talking to strangers and roaming the Internet. We've got to keep
the girls from admiring the stick-skinny models in fashion
magazines and the boys from imitating the bullies wrestling on
Saturday night TV, stop them all from eating fast foods, watching
violent or sex-drenched movies, and getting involved with members
of the opposite sex before they're ready. Notice that almost every
force outside the house is working against us.
</P>
<P>
   By the time our kids are teenagers, we're supposed to have
imbued them with ethical and moral principles that are ridiculed on
every TV show they watch. We're supposed to have taught them to use
alcohol wisely although the media glamorizes excess and doesn't
mention the cost in ruined lives. We're supposed to evaluate our
teen's state of mind when we don't even recognize the names of
popular rock groups and can't stand to watch the violent films
Hollywood aims at adolescent males. How can we find out where our
kids go on the Internet when we're still trying to master e-mail?
How can we deny them heavily advertised, expensive toys and
clothing when they're a prerequisite for peer acceptance?
</P>
<P>
   Who's prepared to have an intelligent conversation about
sexually transmitted diseases? Has anyone figured out how to
control what a child is exposed to at friends' houses? Are you
skilled in the art of detecting drug use? Or shoplifting? Or
promiscuity? Answer this one honestly: If your kid came home with a
bag of stuff from the local hardware store and said it was for a
school project, would you recognize the ingredients for a bomb?
</P>
<P>
   Given the roles we're expected to play, we should have trained
for motherhood at the police academy.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since freedom of speech was redefined to include the
freedom to sell anything, the powers-that-be spend millions of
dollars marketing and promoting unhealthy, antisocial, harmful and
dangerous foods, weapons, games, movies, products, attitudes,
images, and ideas. And against this sophisticated, carefully
targeted barrage designed to have maximum impact on children from
the crib up, there's only Good Old Mom and Pop, standing there
yelling, ``stop,'' looking ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an accident. Advertisers know that there's only one
thing between them and children's money: parents. They can get by
you by targeting the kids themselves, not only in commercials, but
in programs and movies that spin off consumer items, and by
invading the schools. They can get around you by encouraging peer
pressure, making sure every other kid has their name imprinted on
T-shirts, sneakers, sheets, and lunch boxes. Or they can go against
you directly, picturing you in the popular culture as a
know-nothing, a behind-the-times dolt, a spoilsport.
</P>
<P>
   You think I'm exaggerating? Take a look at this quote from a
Forbes magazine article: ``We have discovered that these children
can be turned into consumers as readily as anyone else . . . by age
six a child's buying habits can be fully determined for the rest of
their lives. . . . We now have the chance to invest in appropriate
programs which will lock the children into permanent targets of
manufactured goods for the rest of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the ever-growing demands of the workplace continue to
encroach upon family time, making it increasingly difficult for
parents to be the dominant force in building the character of their
children. Is it too much to ask that this country be less willing
to reduce our children's lives to the level of consumer, no matter
what the cost to their souls?
</P>
<P>
   This is the Mother's Day card I'm sending you.
</P>
<P>
   For Mom, who is doing the best she can against all odds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
