<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGING CHEATING'S SEVERITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're playing Chutes 'n Ladders with your 4-year-old niece when
she jumps her cardboad token an extra few spaces. You pretend not
to notice. Then she does it again, this time down a slide, up two
ladders. You can't contain yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a second,'' you sputter. ``Your spin was only a five!
That's cheating!''
</P>
<P>
   To you, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Cheating is one of society's most universally accepted no-nos,
but we tend to make two mistakes in our efforts to convey its
seriousness to children: We overreact to young kids who cheat and
underreact to older ones.
</P>
<P>
   We're quick to jump on a preschooler who cheats and assume it's
purposeful. In fact, it's not fair even to call it cheating, says
clinical psychologist Lawrence Kutner. ``At this age, there's no
malice, no sense of wrongdoing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with a grade-school child who cheats on a test or at sports,
we tend to issue a stern reprimand _ ``Cheating is wrong; don't let
me catch you at it again'' _ and let it go. We should be doing
more, says child psychiatrist Eugene Beresin. At this age, cheating
can be a tip-off to an underlying problem.
</P>
<P>
   In the preschool years, a child is developmentally incredibly
egocentric, able to concentrate on only one thing at a time, and
not yet capable of internalizing rules. When the dice rolls four
and he moves five, he simply thinks he can put the rules aside
because they don't fit his need, at least not at the moment: ``I
want my token to be here now; I'm the center of the universe, so I
put it where I want.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA developmental psychologist Deborah Stipek says this isn't
cheating. ``It's strategic planning,'' she says, ``a kind of
convenient forgetting to fit his needs.''
</P>
<P>
   A child's magical thinking can also sometimes look like
cheating. When Kutner's son was 6, he took a fencing class. Even
though Kutner was there one day to witness his son's ``defeat,''
the boy insisted it hadn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   Beresin says that's because the line between fantasy and reality
is so thin: ``If a child imagines it happening one way, he may be
unable to see that it really didn't.'' Beresin is director of child
and residency training at McLean and Massachusetts General
Hospitals and associate professor at Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a 6-year-old's insistence that he won or a
preschooler's manipulation of a board game, the flouting of rules
is rarely motivated by competitiveness. More likely, it's a need to
accomplish. When you ask her why she moved her token ahead, for
instance, she might say, ``I wanted to get to the end,'' or ``I
wanted to catch up with you.''
</P>
<P>
   When her own daughter was 4, Stipek can remember her saying,
``Mommy, why don't you go twice, too? That way, we both can win!''
Stipek recalls being delighted at her daughter's suggestion and
taking her up on the offer. Unfortunately, that's a move many of us
would resist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell parents to make light of a 4-year-old's `cheating,' ''
says child psychologist and parent educator Lawrence Balter of New
York University. Use humor: ``I guess you really want to win
today!'' ``Once in a while can I win, please!?'' and definitely
don't punish, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Between 5 and 7, a child begins to move along the continuum to
understanding that breaking rules is cheating. Now Balter suggests
gentle reminders that these aren't the real rules: ``I guess we can
play with your rules this time. It also helps to provide a reality
check: ``You know, if you were playing with your friends, they
might not like this.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they would probably hate it.
</P>
<P>
   A school-age child who cheats with friends or siblings may do it
initially because he thinks he needs an edge to gain approval. Once
he is found out, there's such a negative reaction that he won't do
it again. The child who persists not only doesn't feel good about
himself, but actually sabotages himself.
</P>
<P>
   Beresin says, ``The more he cheats to gain the perceived edge,
the more trouble he gets in with his friends, the more self-esteem
plummets, the more desperate his measures get and the angrier the
peer sanction. Now he's in so deep he can't get out without
professional help.''
</P>
<P>
   How we respond to school-age cheating sends several messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a first-grader cuts in line, every child in class sees it
as cheating,'' says Stipek. ``If the teacher harshly tells the
cutter to go to the end of the line, she reinforces the notion for
everyone that this is an externally imposed rule you follow to
avoid punishment. But if she says, `How would you feel if you stood
in line patiently and someone cut in front of you?' she's helping
all of them understand the value of the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the approach to emulate, says Stipek, because seeing the
value and fairness of a rule is what enables a child to adopt it as
her own and not want to cheat.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, children are more likely to cheat at school when
parents consistently ask, ``How did you do on the test?'' The
message they get is that performance is what counts, not learning,
so when there's an opportunity to cheat to enhance a grade, they
see no reason not to take it. Stipek, a researcher and director of
the laboratory elementary school at UCLA, fears that the increased
emphasis on standardized tests in American schools could
inadvertently lead to more cheating among children.
</P>
<P>
   Beresin calls academic cheating a cry for help.
</P>
<P>
   Kutner agrees: ``Assume that the child who cheats on a test,
even once, does it because he sees cheating as the best solution to
a problem. Our job is to figure out what the problem is.'' Kutner
is author of ``Toddlers and Preschoolers'' and ``Your School Age
Child'' (both Morrow).
</P>
<P>
   There are several possibilities. At one end of the continuum is
a child who is a good student and can do the work but feels
unprepared this particular day. ``This won't be a chronic
cheater,'' says Beresin, but the situation deserves examination of
the pressures the child feels and ways to keep them in check.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme is a child with severe, multifaceted
problems that could include an undiagnosed learning disability, an
emotional disorder, or both. In between, there's a range of
possibilities, from mild LD to a family problem. It's not unusual,
for instance, for a child whose parents are getting divorced to
cheat, hoping they will find out and be distracted enough to focus
on him instead of on the divorce. ``In his mind, it's a way to
bring them all back together,'' says Kutner.
</P>
<P>
   Most typically, the cause of cheating is some variation of being
unable to do the work. ``Cheating is a way to keep up with the
class,'' says Beresin. Some kids are so adept at it that they go
years without detection. Whenever it is discovered, a conference
with teachers and an evaluation may be in order.
</P>
<P>
   Beresin recommends consequences for academic cheating that are
direct _ rewriting a paper, writing an extra one, retaking a test _
and constructive: helping a child organize himself better to study
for a test or to do homework, perhaps educational testing or a
tutor. Whatever it is, says Beresin, the message needs to be clear:
We value learning for its own sake.
</P>
<P>
   Stipek warns against overly harsh consequences _ ``A month of no
phone doesn't make much sense, but maybe no calls until homework is
done'' _ and against imposing consequences without exploring what's
behind the cheating. Kutner poses a series of questions parents can
ask:
</P>
<P>
   --Is she struggling to do the work?
</P>
<P>
   --Is this a highly competitive class/school/family?
</P>
<P>
   --What pressures is she feeling?
</P>
<P>
   --What's going on in the family/community?
</P>
<P>
   --Has there been a change in friendship groups?
</P>
<P>
   --Is there a medical problem?
</P>
<P>
   Not to be minimized is the role our behavior serves as a model
for our children. The recently uncovered practice in some
Boston-area schools of adults' purposefully misreporting scholastic
game scores does not go unnoticed by children, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it may have been done to spare the feelings of
youngsters on a badly losing team, ``there's no two ways about it
for kids,'' says Kutner. ``They see it as cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT: When you and your teenager can't stand being in
the same room with each other, let alone talk to each other, try
communicating via e-mail. Even though you live in the same house
and the idea sounds counterproductive, anecdotal reports are that
it works wonders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz's first book, ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell), is now
available in bookstores. She welcomes letters and comments via
e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
