<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A BETTER BLADDER, DRINK SOME MORE WATER  
 SEXUAL WOES, TREATMENT OF CERVICAL CANCER LINKED  
 ADDITION TO PAP SMEAR URGED TO LESSEN WORRIES  
 NEEDLE BIOPSIES BACKED AS SURGICAL ALTERNATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For a better bladder, drink some more water
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Common sense might seem to suggest that drinking a lot of water
would keep your bladder healthier, by diluting bad stuff and
flushing it out of your system. Now Harvard University researchers
have a study showing common sense is right.
</P>
<P>
   Men who drink at least five pints of water and other liquids
each day cut their risk of two common types of bladder cancer by 49
percent compared to men whose daily fluid intake was 40 ounces or
less, according to a study in the current New England Journal of
Medicine. Bladder cancer, which is most common in smokers, is the
fourth leading type of cancer among US men, who contract it at four
times the rate of women.
</P>
<P>
   A team led by Dr. Dominique S. Michaud of the Harvard School of
Public Health studied 47,909 American men who participated over 10
years in the Health Professionals Follow-Up Study.
</P>
<P>
   Factoring out several other things that affect cancer rates _
including smoking, geography, and eating fruits and vegetables _
Michaud's team found the risk of developing cancer dropped in
direct proportion to daily fluid intake. Drinking water had the
clearest link to reducing bladder cancer, but milk, juices, coffee,
and even alcoholic beverages in daily fluid intake also helped.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have not concluded why drinking liquids helps
prevent bladder cancers. But a commonly accepted theory is that it
dilutes carcinogens in urine and encourages frequent urination,
which reduces exposure to the cancer-causing substances. The study
reiterates that the best way to reduce the risk of bladder cancer
is to quit smoking. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Sexual woes, treatment of cervical cancer linked &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Treatments for cervical cancer caused sexual problems for one in
four Swedish women, but not to the point of affecting their ability
to have an orgasm, a study in the current New England Journal
found. The authors, led by Dr. Karin Bergmark of Stockholm's
Karolinska Institute, said the study indicates physicians may need
to do a better job counseling women being treated for cervical
cancer about the possible impact on sexual function and develop
surgical techniques that reduce these problems.
</P>
<P>
   A questionnaire distributed to 256 women who had undergone
treatments, chiefly hysterectomies and removal of pelvic lymph
tissue, found about 26 percent later complained of ``moderate or
much distress'' over changes to their vagina, including loss of
elasticity, pain during sex, and inability to lubricate. This
compared to 8 percent in a control group of 350 women without
cancer. However, they found that ``the frequency of orgasms and
orgasmic pleasure was similar in the two groups.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Addition to Pap smear urged to lessen worries
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In more news relating to cervical cancer this week, a study in
the Journal of the American Medical Association found that adding a
second test to the common Pap smear can eliminate the need for
follow-up Pap smears in hundreds of thousands of women.
</P>
<P>
   Subjecting a Pap smear sample to a simultaneous second test for
the papilloma virus that causes most cervical cancer can find
virtually all cases of cancer or latent cancer, without requiring
women to wait anxiously for several weeks or months for a second
Pap smear or other test.
</P>
<P>
   About a quarter of women having the test will, at some time in
their lives, get an uncertain result called ASCUS, indicating they
need a follow-up test, according to study leader Michele Manos, a
Kaiser Permanente researcher. In women who got an ASCUS report from
the Pap smear, which had been subjected to the second test and did
not show the papilloma virus, researchers could be ``99 percent
certain'' the women did not have cancer, Manos said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Needle biopsies backed as surgical alternative
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other medical news: Brigham and Women's Hospital researchers
led by radiologist Dr. Jack E. Meyer reported in JAMA that
large-core needle biopsies of malignant breast tissue are a safe,
effective, and easier alternative to having tissue samples taken by
surgically opening the breast . . . Researcher Matthias A. Hediger
of the Brigham and colleagues report in the current Nature they
have found a gene that aids in absorbing vitamin C, which could
lead to treatments for diseases related to poor absorption of the
vitamin . . . Arsenic trioxide, commonly used in Chinese medicine,
showed considerable promise in lab tests in treating a variety of
lymphatic cancers by reducing cell growth, according to a study in
Wednesday's Journal of the National Cancer Institute by Shanghai
and Mount Sinai School of Medicine researchers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
