<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBERTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR MINES MEXICAN ROOTS FOR SUBJECT MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
 RIOS-BOOK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Poet Alberto Rios grew up multilingual.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first language was (begin ital) everything (end ital),'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   With a Mexican father and a British mother, the boy Alberto used
everything within his grasp to communicate _ words, gestures,
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Multilingualism has served him well as a writer, teaching him
that everything has more than one name. Critics have said he writes
in Spanish that looks like English: English words, Spanish syntax.
</P>
<P>
   The emotion is uniquely Rios.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a quirk of my upbringing and how I've come to see
things,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Rios, a regents professor at Arizona State University who
teaches creative writing and Latin American literature, has just
published a new collection of short stories, ``The Curtain of
Trees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Curtain of Trees'' draws from his heritage in a family of
storytellers. Much of the Rios clan came from northern Sonora,
Mexico, and many were involved in the Mexican Revolution early in
this century.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Obregon Rios, born in Nogales, Ariz., was himself named
for Mexican revolutionary general Alvaro Obregon, who served four
years as president of Mexico before being assassinated in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   Rios's characters come from those Sonoran roots. Family history
fell into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This book wrote itself,'' he says. ``It came out of my body,
out of my brain.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories are rich in details of the time period, a common
thread in his literature. So authentically historic are his
stories, in fact, that some are studied in anthropology classes.
</P>
<P>
   But Rios' family was not locked only in tales of past
adventures. They also embraced contemporary culture. He recalls one
afternoon when his great aunts thrilled to a recording by crooner
Engelbert Humperdinck.
</P>
<P>
   He laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of that moment _ how do you get from the Mexican
Revolution to Engelbert Humperdinck?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is somewhere between the pages of ``Curtain of
Trees,'' which comes out this month and already has earned praise
from ``Publishers Weekly''.
</P>
<P>
   Next fall, Rios will publish a memoir, ``Capirotada: A Nogales
Memoir.'' Its title refers to a Mexican bread pudding that
encompasses myriad ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a metaphor for how we try to make things better,'' he
says. ``It's a confusion. My life has been a confusion of good
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The good things have been coming for some time. Rios, 46, is the
author of seven books and chapbooks of poetry, and two collections
of short stories. He has won the Arizona Governor's Award, the Walt
Whitman Award, the Western States Book Award for Fiction and five
Pushcart Prizes in poetry and fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Rios' success in prose might come as a surprise to those who
consider him primarily a poet. But all his writing springs from the
same well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a poet,'' he says. ``I think of all my work as poetry. I
write prose to teach me how to be a better poet.''
</P>
<P>
   His themes also have a common focus. Rios says his 13-year-old
son, Joaquin, teases him that his next book will be about Nogales
in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin is not psychic. He is a bright boy who knows his father
well. Much of Rios' work dwells on Nogales in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   He writes, he says, about ``the people who are me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my anchor. You need not look far away. You need only
look closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Writers are admonished to write what they know, he notes, and
``that's enough for a lifetime.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
