<HEADLINE>
MEETING OVERDUE FOR VETERANS ZENGA, NICHOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRAMINGHAM, Mass. _ The low-ceilinged locker room at
5,600-capacity Bowditch Field was an incongruous place for Walter
Zenga and Steve Nichol to cross paths. They had played for nearly
20 years with clubs in Europe, with their national teams, but had
never met before the Revolution and Boston Bulldogs faced each
other in an exhibition Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we knew about each other, but we didn't know each
other,'' Nichol said after conversing with Revolution player-coach
Zenga and assistant coach Giuseppe Galderisi.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga and Galderisi have kept high profiles since arriving in
the United States, but so far Nichol has remained virtually
anonymous. But it should be known that Nichol's accomplishments
more than rival the Italians'.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Nichol not only won a European Champions Cup title with
Liverpool, he won in Rome in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a long time ago,'' Nichol said. ``Most of the guys
I'm playing with now are a bit too young to remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Nichol probably has not received the proper respect
since arriving as a player-assistant coach with the Bulldogs. About
10 minutes into his first game, he suffered an ankle injury after
clashing with a Connecticut foe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I was assassinated,'' Nichol said. ``But that's
life. It was a tackle and that is part of the game. Next time you
just have to be a bit quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Nichol been able to take the time to display his
credentials, the opponents might have given him some room. He was a
part of the Liverpool dynasty, played in two European Champions Cup
finals, at the Mexico '86 World Cup with Scotland. There was glory
in the penalty-kick defeat of AS Roma in 1984, the tragedies of
Heysel Stadium '85 and Hillsborough in the 1989 FA Cup semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Heysel disaster led to the banning of English teams
from European competitions, and made a meeting with the likes of
Galderisi and Zenga less likely.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they all have arrived in the United States to provide
guidance to young teams desperately in need of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not every player wants to coach,'' Nichol said. ``The majority
of guys who played at the highest level get disillusioned when they
go down to a lower level. But as a player, this is where you start.
So why should it be any different for a coach?''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs began as the Worcester Wildfire, but after two
losing seasons and low attendance, they moved closer to Boston.
They are both in competition and in cooperation with the
Revolution, as a developmental team as well as a sparring partner.
</P>
<P>
   Nichol's first view of an MLS team was Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too soon for me to judge the level of play here,'' Nichol
said. ``I didn't know what to expect, so I've been taking it as it
comes. But I'm treating it as I would if this were the Premier
League, trying to make it a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good opportunity for me because I can both play and
coach, plus get a sample of what America is like. I don't know how
long I'm going to be here, so I want to make the most of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
