<SLUG> BC-LESBIAN-MOTHERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK OFFERS A DIFFERENT PORTRAIT OF MOTHERHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GANAHL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Photographer Barbara Seyda wrote her
award-winning book on lesbian mothers as an implement for social
change, but also to celebrate ``motherhood of all kinds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I first thought of it at a 1993 Thanksgiving dinner, with
several lesbian friends and their children,'' said Seyda, the
co-author of ``Women in Love: Portraits of Lesbian Mothers and
Their Families'' (Bulfinch Press). ``It was like a post-modern
Norman Rockwell painting, with all ages and ethnicities. And I
realized these are faces you never see in the mainstream media or
in parenting magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   Seyda, a lesbian, knows whereof she speaks. The photojournalist,
speaking by telephone from her home in Arizona, first tried to make
a magazine article out of the photos she had taken _ of a
collection of same-sex families _ only to have a publication kill
it at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first they tried to get me to take a different angle _ like
talk about how screwed up the kids were from this lifestyle,'' she
said. ``But they weren't. Most seemed very happy. When I made it
clear I wasn't going to alter my story, they killed it.''
</P>
<P>
   When she tried to sell publishers on the idea of a book on the
subject, none, as she put it, ``would touch it with a 10-foot
pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Seyda did not give up. She and her partner and co-author, Diana
Herrera, an acupuncturist, instead went about seeking donations to
publish the book themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It took two years, but by the end of 1997 they had collected
$85,000 from investors and donors and traveled the country
photographing and interviewing lesbian mothers and their children.
``We slept on couches. People gave us gas money, made us dinner. We
were welcomed everywhere in the community. There was a lot of
belief in what we were trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The results were worth the effort. A highly attended photo
exhibit was held last year at San Francisco Main Library, and just
last weekend Seyda and Herrera picked up an award in Los Angeles
from Lambda, the national gay rights organization, for best
photography/visual arts book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful to be acknowledged by my peers,'' Seyda said.
</P>
<P>
   To her, acknowledgment and acceptance of the lesbian family unit
are overdue. ``There are around 10 million lesbian mothers out
there,'' she said, ``and around 60 to 70 percent of all lesbian
couples will have children. What we're witnessing is an incredible
evolution of women's consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   There were only a few hitches in the project, not the least of
which was getting teen-agers to talk about their families. ``That
was tough, but I think that would be normal with any teen-agers,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the children we interviewed said they knew that if
their mothers were happy, they'd be happier, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Seyda is completing a project documenting stories and portraits
of homeless people, called ``Desert Nomads: A Celebration of
Survival.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Another difficult story, but another that deserves to be
told,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
