A6811 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-OPENYOUREYES-TEX     05-06 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-OPENYOUREYES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY BECOMES A BEAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Open your eyes,'' murmurs a voice. For Cesar, the slightly
morose, self-involved protagonist of ``Open your Eyes,'' even when
he's got the world on a string, still it ain't got that swing.
</P>
<P>
   Slipping in and out of affairs as easily as he jumps from one
car to another, Cesar looks a little glum, his eyebrows poised over
his dimpled face like question marks. In playing him, Eduardo
Noriega is an aware enough actor to understand that a little bit of
misery around the edges is more than enough to give the slick
wizardry of ``Open Your Eyes'' a touch of tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a European aspect, but he looks to be the tiniest bit
ashamed of leading a life that appears to have been Xeroxed from a
1969 issue of Playboy. He's rich, effortlessly charming and chooses
to never sleep with the same woman twice.
</P>
<P>
   And one of those women _ his latest conquest, Nuria (Najwa
Nimri), a catlike beauty with confident hips and a dark, sensuous
helmet of short hair _ is stalking him. She doesn't confuse their
night of passion with love, but she's not ready to give him up,
either.
</P>
<P>
   But there's something remote about Cesar. Even though he's
surrounded with the kind of lifestyle that probably only R. Kelly
knows on such an intimate basis, he's lonely. But the picture
doesn't play that up. Rather, it's in his performance. That is,
until at his birthday party he meets Sofia (Penelope Cruz), the
woman who his best friend has just started to date.
</P>
<P>
   Using Sofia as a way to keep away from his stalker, his
flirtation with her actually takes on a romantic constancy that, if
you'll pardon the expression, opens his eyes. He runs off with his
new love and they spend a night together, but it's an evening of
friendly intimacy that doesn't involve sex. When he emerges in the
morning, his ex, Nuria, offers to drive him home. She swallows a
handful of pills and drives off the road. She's left dead, and his
face is a mass of misshapen scar tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cruise has already bought the American remake rights to
``Open Your Eyes.'' That seems a little strange, because the movie
appears to be set in the Spanish-language version of Metropolis, a
verdant urban sprawl that suggests not a hint of the flavor of the
culture in which it was filmed. If it were dubbed into English, you
could almost mistake it for an American movie.
</P>
<P>
   And, ``Open Your Eyes'' is set in what is on its way to (slowly)
becoming a subgenre: the don't-trust-your-eyes school of
filmmaking, like ``The Matrix'' and last fall's ``What Dreams May
Come.'' After the accident, we're plunged into a series of scenes
that makes us wonder if Cesar is crazy _ sometimes he wanders the
streets totally unscarred, as if nothing has happened. He has been
jailed, because he may have murdered his ex. And his psychiatrist
is determined to get to the truth, shake away the delusions and at
least heal his patient spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   With his loose swagger and head on a constant pivot _ he's
always looking around for something more interesting than what's
going on around him _ Eduardo Noriega has a self-possessed fluidity
that makes him seem older than his years. His performance _ as well
as the even, cool direction of Alejandro Amenabar _ contradicts the
low-tech, science-fiction feel that ``Open Your Eyes'' develops (it
starts to feel a little like Jean-Luc Godard's ``Alphaville'').
Their efforts make this one of the most uniquely entertaining
movies of the year. Its melancholy lingers long after you've walked
away from the theater.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Open Your Eyes''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Alejandro Amenabar
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Eduardo Noriega, Penelope Cruz
</P>
<P>
   Length: 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ nudity, adult language and situations, and violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
