A6814 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     05-06 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STELLAR '99 PUTS WINDSOR FUND BACK IN FASHION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the old clothes in your closet, Charles Freeman has finally
come back in fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel validated here,'' said Freeman, in an interview
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, Freeman has managed the money in
Vanguard's Windsor fund, one of America's best-known mutual funds.
Freeman himself works for Boston-based Wellington Management.
Freeman had a strong 1996, a so-so 1997 and a perfectly awful 1998.
In a year when the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index climbed 28 percent,
Windsor returned less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors noticed and began withdrawing money from the fund.
Vanguard noticed too. In March the mutual-fund giant said it was
bringing in new managers from Sanford C. Bernstein to help Freeman
run the fund. Vanguard said its action wasn't a response to
Windsor's poor performance, but to the rest of the world it looked
as if Freeman had gotten the hook.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the manager may have yanked Freeman too early.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, Windsor was up 18.4 percent for the year,
compared with 8.8 percent for the S&AMP;P 500 Index. So far this year
the $18 billion Windsor fund has the best performance among the
nation's 30 largest mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   What explains the dramatic turnaround?
</P>
<P>
   It's the economy, stupid. In this case, the world economy.
Windsor got hammered in 1997 and 1998 when Asia, then Russia, then
Brazil, ran into trouble. The bad news hurt the world economy and
sent investors scrambling for safety.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman owned commodity companies when the price of commodities
was tumbling; he owned mid-cap stocks when large-cap stocks were in
vogue; and he owned virtually no technology stocks when investors
could not get enough Microsoft and Dell.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Freeman stuck to his guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest enemy you face in a period like that is the market
saying you are wrong,'' he says. ``What you do is check your cards
and think about what you own. We felt we had unappreciated value in
our portfolio that would be recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   For that value to be recognized, however, Freeman needed some
recovery in the world economy. In an interview last fall, he
predicted such a recovery would begin in the next year, that the
recovery would cause the stock market to broaden out, and that
long-neglected stocks would come back into favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a classic turning point,'' he said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Within the last few months, the economic news has
been better than expected. Brazil isn't falling into a deep
recession. Parts of Asia have begun to recover. And the already
strong American economy has been stronger than anyone predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of strength have boosted commodity prices. Oil has
gone from $12 a barrel to $19 a barrel. The price of metals and
agricultural products has climbed as well.
</P>
<P>
   The shift has triggered a major runup in the stock prices of
industries Freeman has owned all along _ energy, paper, chemicals,
and farm equipment. Bank stocks have come back too. So have
hospitals and health maintenance organizations. Freeman owns all of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, he doesn't own the stocks that have lost
their luster _ the technology giants or the big consumer companies
like Coke, Gillette, or Procter &AMP; Gamble. In effect, the whole
market has rotated around, and for the moment, Freeman is standing
on top.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is impressed. While conceding that cyclical stocks
were ready for a rebound, Ned Riley thinks the euphoria about the
stocks isn't justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this rally has extended too far,'' says Riley, chief
investment officer of BankBoston. Others worry that a sustained
rebound in commodity prices would spark inflation fears, which, in
turn, could send the whole stock market tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman isn't too worried. He believes many of the stocks he
owns ``still have legs.'' He expects the world economy to improve
this year and next, but he doesn't look for growth so robust that
it would ignite inflation.
</P>
<P>
   And how does he feel about Vanguard's move to split up the fund
and bring in new managers?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to ask Vanguard about that,'' he says
diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
   A Vanguard spokesman says the Bernstein team will take over a
piece of the fund in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it will bring added diversity to the portfolio,''
says the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will. But in a business where timing is everything,
Freeman might have been in a stronger position if the stock market
had decided to rotate just a few months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
