<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOPURE-IPO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOPURE BANKS ON ITS BLOOD SUBSTITUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We drink milk. We eat filet mignon. So why not purify cow's
blood and inject it in humans?
</P>
<P>
   Biopure Corp. already stood out among the few biotechnology
companies in the decade-long marathon to be first to win the US
Food and Drug Administration's approval for a human-blood
substitute. The tiny Cambridge, Mass. firm has a medical celebrity
on its board, former surgeon general C. Everett Koop, touting a
safe substitute as destined to be among the ``top 10 advances'' in
modern medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Biopure is alone in having FDA permission to sell a blood
substitute to veterinarians for use in treating dogs. And now it's
a frontrunner in developing a more pure product for use in humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've also seen it used in cats successfully,'' Dr. Robert
Murtaugh, director of critical care at the Dove Lewis Emergency
Animal Hospital in Portland, Ore., said about the veterinary
product. It's ``revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   To stay ahead in the human-blood market, Biopure and cofounder
Carl Rausch, the company's chief scientist, are at a critical stage
in testing their therapeutic, which analysts say could one day be a
multimillion-dollar industry. Biopure has the daunting challenge of
convincing not only regulators but also investors _ and a wary
public _ that the idea of using bovine blood in humans will fly.
</P>
<P>
   Although faux blood is not a perfect substitute for the real
thing, it could be important in supplementing blood-bank supplies.
Substitutes don't need to be matched with a patient's blood type,
giving them a variety of medical uses, such as during surgeries or
emergencies when the real thing is unsafe or in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   But memories of the breakout of ``mad cow disease'' in the
United Kingdom two years ago won't help Biopure's cause, despite
meticulous care taken by the company to protect its Pennsylvania
herd until the cattle are slaughtered and their blood collected for
processing.
</P>
<P>
   Qualms about using substances from other species ``would
certainly be one reason why most people, given a choice between cow
blood and human blood, would take human blood,'' said George Annas,
professor of health law at Boston University's School of Public
Health. ``It's like genetically modified food. There's no evidence
it hurts anybody, but if you label it nobody eats it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Biopure can think about marketing its blood, the company
needs an infusion of cash to pay for costly clinical trials
required by FDA to gain the agency's approval. Biopure is expected
to file, possibly within days, for its first public sale of stock.
</P>
<P>
   If Biopure does sell stock in coming weeks, it would be entering
a market dazzled by Internet stocks and inhospitable to fledgling
biotech firms. Not a single biotech company has done an initial
public offering this year.
</P>
<P>
   A Biopure deal would be ``a bellwether biotech offering,'' said
Peter Feinstein, a consultant with Feinstein Kean Partners Inc. in
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Biopure's spokesman, Doug Sayles, declined comment on the
company's plans. As of Wednesday, it had not filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Cristina Fernandez, president of Schooner Capital, a venture
capital firm backing Biopure, said in a voice-mail message last
week, ``I'm not going to be able to talk to you about the company
until after the'' initial public offering. She did not return a
call seeking further comment.
</P>
<P>
   On a purely scientific level, competition to find a human blood
substitute is intense.
</P>
<P>
   FDA requirements for a therapeutic with so many applications are
stringent, and Northfield Laboratories Inc. is breathing down
Biopure's neck.
</P>
<P>
   Northfield, like Biopure, is in phase III _ or final _ clinical
trials. And both are shooting for FDA approval to begin selling
their product next year.
</P>
<P>
   Northfield's chief executive, Richard Dewoskin, said in a
telephone interview last week that his company's product, PolyHeme,
has the advantage that it can be administered in larger doses than
Biopure's product, Hemopure.
</P>
<P>
   Northfield is using up to 20 units in clinical trials, while
Biopure is approved for only 10 units.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supposed you're injured in an auto accident and you're
bleeding badly _ you could go into shock and die in minutes,''
DeWoskin explained. PolyHeme could be pumped ``in the patient until
they have no blood left _ that's what it is for.''
</P>
<P>
   Northfield's product is made from human _ not bovine _
hemoglobin. New Jersey-based Enzon Inc. is the only other company
developing a bovine-derived substitute, but its product is in early
stages of research.
</P>
<P>
   Biopure touts Hemopure as being highly efficient in carrying
oxygen, so large amounts aren't as crucial. And the company has the
advantage of already having proved a veterinary blood product as
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works,'' Rausch said in an interview in February. ``No
question it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Last August, Biopure announced it would launch phase III trials
on 640 American patients for orthopedic surgery. In November, the
company reported to the American Heart Association that Hemopure
reduced the need for transfusions in cardiac-surgery patients
during second-phase trials. Biopure said it has also tested its
blood on in human patients in Guatemala and Europe, with success.
</P>
<P>
   The search for a blood substitute gained steam in the early
1980s as a way to prevent transfusions, which carried new risks of
transmitting infectious diseases, namely HIV and hepatitis. There
are more than 12 million transfusions a year in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen-carrying blood substitutes may one day minimize
transfusions by creating a ``bridge'' until the body regenerates
its own red blood cells, physicians say. And Biopure said Hemopure
can be stored, at room temperature, in ambulances or on hospital
shelves for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``The regulatory hurdles are going to be pretty
formidable,'' said Katherine Martinelli, a medical technology
analyst for Merrill Lynch in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   On top of regulatory hurdles are the financial ones.
Biotechnology companies typically are strapped, because they
consume vast quantities of cash, especially in costly clinical
trials, which can run at $10 million apiece or more.
</P>
<P>
   Northfield, for example, lost $5.8 million last year but has
raised cash in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about Biopure's financial status, since the
company is private.
</P>
<P>
   Biopure said it had $2 million in revenue last year, about half
from the sale of animal-blood substitute. The last time on record
that Biopure received any funds was in December 1997 when $50
million was raised from venture capital investments.
</P>
<P>
   But Biopure needs money to fund clinical trials, Rausch said in
the interview. And Northfield and Biopure are close in the race.
Northfield may have a slight lead in its third-stage trials,
analysts say, but Biopure has shown that a similar product works
for animals.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Harvey Klein, chief of transfusion medicine at the
Warren G. Magnuson Clinic at the National Institutes of Health, who
has consulted to Biopure, said that although the company has ``a
good technique'' for turning bovine blood into a blood-substitute
for humans, there are always ``unknown'' toxicities, which may not
come to light even in the best-designed, most extensive clinical
trials.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the race, Baxter International, was forced to
abandon its trials last March after researchers, during the third
phase of testing, found that use of its product caused ``an
increased mortality compared to those in the control group'' on
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Baxter has fallen behind in the race. The Chicago company is now
pursuing a blood substitute based on a new technology developed by
a small biotech company, Somatogen, that Baxter acquired last year.
But, Baxter has fallen behind _ ``we're talking 2004,'' Martinelli
said.
</P>
<P>
   Biopure's secret formula for its blood substitute is based on a
purification process using chromatography and designed by Rausch, a
chemical engineer by training, and the company's other scientists.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Rausch was one of four founders of Biopure, which grew
out of their joint research at the enzyme research center at Tufts
University. His partners are the center's ex-director, Bing Wong;
physician Edward Jacobs of Massachusetts General Hospital; and a
former Gulf &AMP; Western Industries founder, Jim Judelson.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade after starting their research, Rausch said,
Biopure ``is a company with a real product.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
