<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6820 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DREAMLIFE-TEX     05-06 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DREAMLIFE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TRUE TO LIFE AS YOUR GAL-PALS GET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Dreamlife of Angels'' caused quite a stir at the 1998
Cannes Film Festival, where its stars shared the Best Actress
award. Although the movie has taken almost a year to get a release
in America, it's well worth the wait. It's a detailed examination
of two young women floating through a period of disconnectedness.
Although they turn to each other to fill empty spaces in their
lives, neither can answer the big questions they have.
</P>
<P>
   The stars seem to have been matched as if they were right out of
a road-picture buddy comedy, and their relationship sounds a little
pat. Isa (Elodie Bouchez) is a natural sweetpea, and her sunny
outlook helps her sail through life as if she has a lucky charm
bracelet hidden in her backpack. Her pal, Marie (Natacha Regnier)
is her polar opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Storm clouds brew behind her eyes, and her dark temperament
masks a deep-seated desperation. This bent toward misery attracts
her to the wrong kind of guy, like the nightclub owner with a cold,
mean streak; he treats her like sewage. But first-time director
Erick Zonca doesn't play up the cheap melodrama, which would make
``Dreamlife'' a satisfying piece on its own: ``When Bad Things
Happen to Pouty People.'' Instead, he focuses on the minor details
of how the young women get through each day, and builds the movie
into a novelistic piece of observation.
</P>
<P>
   Marie can't seem to help herself. And ``Dreamlife'' makes no
excuses for her, nor does it try to offer a big explanation as to
why these women have fallen in together. It just follows them
through a period with no big drama, and the collection of anecdotes
_ minor flirtations, wasting their days squabbling over nothing _
isn't emphasized with grandiose technique.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, ``Dreamlife'' suggests the kind of foreign film we
don't see much of anymore. It's an empathetic glimpse into the
lives of people whom American movies would be nervous to depict,
because there's not enough conflict in their lives. And the lack of
contrivance would be confused with an absence of drama, because not
much happens. It's said that the first cut of ``Dreamlife'' ran
close to four hours, and if that's the case, Zonca has made
judicious cuts. The drama here cuts close to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Dreamlife of Angels,'' in French with subtitles
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Erick Zonca
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Elodie Bouchez, Natacha Regnier
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ sexuality, adult language and situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
