<P>
   The New York Times plans 3 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Bonn, Germany) _ Russia and the Western powers
agreed Thursday on a common approach to seeking peace for Kosovo,
including terms for an armed international force to secure the
return of refugees. ``The Russians have accepted the proposition
there needs to be a security presence on the ground in Kosovo,''
Sandy Berger, the U.S. national security adviser, says. Foreign
ministers of the Group of Eight countries meeting outside Bonn
settled on a seven-point plan to be endorsed by the U.N. Security
Council, German officials said. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the Kosovo plan,
looking a how the U.S. is seeking a diplomatic solution that would
save face, what demands will the U.S. and NATO compromise on and
where this NATO-Russian agreement leaves Slobodan Milosevic, the
Yugoslav president. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Ingelheim, Germany) _ President Clinton's day:
He met with Kosovo refugees and promised that Milosevic ``will not
succeed in erasing your presence from the land of your parents and
grandparents.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments from NATO headquarters:
the allies are to give a detailed briefing on what has been done to
Serbian forces in Kosovo. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congressional debate continues on
Kosovo spending. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Tirana, Albania) _ Macedonia closes its border
with Kosovo, saying it will take in only as many refugees as leave.
There is talk of busing many refugees from Macedonia into Albania,
which raises the question of how the Albanians can cope with such a
moved. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Tirana, Albania) _ A key separatist leader, Jakub
Krasniqi, says the KLA rebels will never agree to be disarmed,
insists on Kosovo independence and demands an explanation of
controversial statements made by Ibrahim Rugova, a moderate ethnic
Albanian leader. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-RUGOVA (Rome) _ The moderate leader Ibrahim Rugova holds a
press conference with Massimo D'Alema, the Italian prime minister.
By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Fort Dix, N.J.) _ Developments on the
Kosovar refugees brought to the U.S. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, stories on the social and
economic impact of the NATO attacks on Montenegro; the growing
prominence of Robin Cook, the British foreign secretary, and on the
plight of displaced Albanians who remain inside Kosovo, thought to
number 300,000.
