<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-ROBOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I WANTED A ROBOT, BUT GOT DISPOSABLE DIAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 1999. Where is my robot, dammit?
</P>
<P>
   I grew up watching ``The Jetsons'' and believing the promise of
science that someday, in the kitchen of my future, would stand an
automated matron in an apron, scrubbing pots and pans and mixing
martinis at the push of a button.
</P>
<P>
   But here it is, 30 years later, and the closest I'm going to get
to a Rosie of my own is if I hotwire the blender to the dishwasher,
toss in a cocktail onion, and press ``pulse.''
</P>
<P>
   Futurists from Walt Disney to World's Fair hawkers had some
interesting ideas about how technology was going to revolutionize
our lives by this point, but so far, many of those predictions have
fallen short.
</P>
<P>
   If their dreams did come true, we'd be buying gyrocopters on
clearance at Wal-Mart by now, and time-travel machines would be
given away free with time-share offers. Michael Jackson most
certainly would have gone for the icy cryogenic chamber instead of
the breathy hyperbaric.
</P>
<P>
   And homes, not ``Bay Watch'' actresses, would be made entirely
of plastic, although Monsanto's motto would still apply: ``Hardly a
natural material appears anywhere!''
</P>
<P>
   At the 1962 World's Fair in Seattle, spectators munched cotton
candy and mused about a 21st century where disposable clothing
would be all the rage, man-made lightning would fire up the skies,
and school buildings would have walls formed by jets of air and
floating roofs that would shift to the angle of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Just what was in that cotton candy, anyway? Oh, yeah _ it
was the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Still, let's examine how close they got: Diapers are disposable,
but lightning remains an act of God (although sparks can certainly
be created by the right man), and schools do have shifting walls,
but it's called decay.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens were an easy and popular target for futurists, who
enjoyed wowing women with tantalizing gadgets to make the
``housewife's'' life that much easier, like solar ovens,
thermo-electric refrigerators, talking toasters, cordless waffle
irons, and disposable dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to a man to conceive the paper plate, but have no
inkling of the nascent feminist movement. Or of takeout, for
heaven's sake.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, there were some things the prognosticators got right
over the years. They accurately surmised we'd be living in the
suburbs watching televisions and using super highways to get to
work, where we would be dependent on fax machines.
</P>
<P>
   Even more things, though, were only a little bit right or the
result of wishful thinking: Videophones were unveiled at the 1964
World's Fair, but we're guessing that Bill Gates was too young then
to monopolize the idea and sell them with a Rolling Stones theme
song.
</P>
<P>
   Cars, they said, would be air conditioned, but also
teardrop-shaped, float on air, and cost only $200. Clearly, they
were really talking about sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of cars, the General Motors exhibit at the 1939 World's
Fair displayed a city with tall, curving towers ringed by expanses
of greenery. At the base of the towers, highways met in massive
intersections more than 20 lanes wide. No pedestrians were in
sight. The Big Dig run amok?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the allure of exhibits called Town of Tomorrow, Soda
Fountain of the Future, and World of the Day after Tomorrow, the
biggest buzz was always around the robot.
</P>
<P>
   It would have had the most immediate and long-lasting impact on
improving everyday life. Enthralled spectators envisioned the joys
of programming a machine to cook dinner, walk the dog, iron the
clothes, and mow the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years later, we're still rooting for a robot and for the
same basic reasons. But today, we'd give it different jobs. Like
program it to find loopholes in the tax laws. Teach it to surf the
Net for cheap airfares.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and one more: Program the VCR to record those good ol'
Jetsons' reruns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Staff reporter Doreen Iudica Vigue covers education for the
Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
