A6827 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      05-06 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-STAKES RACE TO REPLACE KALB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was all smiles Tuesday as the brothers Kalb (veteran
journalists Marvin and Bernie) marked the end of Marvin's 12 years
as director of Harvard's Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press,
Politics and Public Policy with a ``brown bag'' lunch featuring a
light menu of media conversation and fraternal reminiscences.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, however, the high-stakes race to land a big
fish to succeed Kalb _ who leaves at the end of June for
Shorenstein's Washington office _ is getting deadly serious. In an
era when press scrutiny has become a huge growth industry,
Shorenstein's reputation as one of the nation's most influential
think tanks _ capable of attracting visiting scholars and
celebrities _ is at stake in the selection of the director who will
follow the man who put it on the map.
</P>
<P>
   No one at Harvard is saying anything officially and the
situation appears fluid. But several contenders have reportedly
emerged as major candidates: Ken Bode, the dean of Northwestern's
prestigious Medill School of Journalism; media critic Alex Jones,
who shares the Eugene Patterson chair in journalism at Duke
University with his wife, Susan Tifft; Newsweek assistant managing
editor and Washington pundit Evan Thomas; and former NBC News
president turned editor and co-owner of The (Ames, Iowa) Daily
Tribune, Michael Gartner.
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate potentially in the mix is Ed Fouhy, the former
network newsman and director of the Pew Center for Civic Journalism
who now edits an online news service dealing with major issues
facing the states.
</P>
<P>
   A number of names _ from ABC's Ted Koppel to CNN's Jeff
Greenfield to former White House press secretary Mike McCurry _ had
reportedly been bandied around to succeed Kalb before the selection
process got more pragmatic. And no one is ruling out the idea that
new contenders could emerge before a final decision is made
sometime in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought all along that . . . the date was not the driving
factor here. The fit with the person and the position will be the
key,'' said Thomas Patterson, the Bradlee Professor of Government
and the Press and co-chair of the faculty search committee, who
declined to comment on candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the potential directors brings both assets and
liabilities to the table. Bode, a former CNN and NBC staffer, is a
distinguished newsman. He recently made news, however, by losing
his longtime job as host of PBS's ``Washington Week in Review,''
supposedly because the program needed a fiestier feel. He has also
been dean of the Medill School for a mere 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a job at Northwestern University,'' said Bode
Wednesday. ``We've instituted a lot of new programs. I'm sitting
here talking to you looking out my window at Lake Michigan.'' Yet,
he acknowledged being approached about the job and said, ``There
probably is no other job in the county I would consider leaving
this job for except that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has spent much of his career as a professional media
critic. A 1987 Pulitzer winner, he was a media reporter at The New
York Times, the host of National Public Radio's ``On the Media''
program and he is currently executive editor of PBS's ``Media
Matters'' series. Like Bode, his position at Duke gives him an
academic cache, and he and Tifft are authors of ``The Trust: The
Private and Powerful Family Behind the New York Times,'' which is
due out this fall. Jones has some influential backers, but is the
least known of the possible Kalb successors, a potential drawback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I would want the Harvard job,'' he said
Wednesday. ``I don't know very much about what the job would
entail.'' He did say, however, that Patterson had invited him up to
Shorenstein for a meeting, adding ``Sure, I'll be glad to
explore,'' the option.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek's Thomas, the grandson of perennial Socialist
presidential candidate Norman Thomas, is on leave while he
completes a biography of Bobby Kennedy. The author of books on the
C.I.A., superlawyer Edward Bennett Williams, and the US foreign
policy establishment, Thomas is a well-connected political writer.
His frequent appearances as a TV pundit _ at a time when many
critics blame talking heads for debasing public dialogue _ could be
a double-edged sword, however.
</P>
<P>
   Like his potential rivals, Thomas downplayed his Shorenstein
candidacy Wednesday. ``That's news to me,'' he replied when asked
if his hat was firmly in the ring. ``I had a conversation with
(Kennedy School executive dean and search committee co-chair)
Sheila Burke, but I haven't heard back. Obviously that's a great
job and I'm flattered, but I'm happy at Newsweek.''
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial choice might be Gartner. A longtime
newspaper man (Wall Street Journal, Des Moines Register), Gartner's
career as NBC News president literally went up in smoke in 1993
when he resigned after the infamous ``Dateline NBC'' program that
rigged a dramatic truck explosion. Gartner then returned to Iowa to
run the Daily Tribune, became something of a reborn prarie
populist, and won the 1997 Pulitzer for editorial writing. He was
unavailable for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who succeeds him, Kalb may have already secured
his legacy. Noting that ``it took me two or three years before I
was able to establish here at the Kennedy School that there was a
genuine need to study the intersection of press and public
policy,'' he declared that ``first and foremost,'' his successor
must be ``a person who is a journalist and who believes in the
First Amendment.'' Judging from the resumes of the would-be
candidates, that's already a given.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6828 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MUMMY-TEX     05-06 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MUMMY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLICHES CURSE `MUMMY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does Brendan Fraser ever blink? His wide-open saucer eyes are
crystal clear _ he looks like he never misses a night's sleep _ and
are a perfect match for director Stephen Sommers's camera style in
``The Mummy,'' an action-picture remake of the classic. It's not
very scary, but it never stops moving. It's relentless, although it
feels like the kind of movie that irony-free B-movie actor Troy
McClure _ the vacuous dumbbell from ``The Simpsons'' _ would star
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mummy'' gets going with an amazing panoramic view of old
Egypt, where a priest with a haunted look on his face pursues an
affair with Pharaoh's woman. After he's caught, he and his men are
put to death in a gloriously photogenic way. They're all buried
alive, and the priest's sarcophagus is filled with flesh-eating
beetles. (Apparently, Pharaoh's not one of those guys whose bad
side you want to be on.)
</P>
<P>
   The priest, who vows to bring his love back to life, is also
buried with a curse: If his tomb is opened, it will loose a plague
upon on the land. As played by Arnold Vosloo, the priest is the
only person in the movie capable of real suffering _ he howls with
rage and pain as his tomb is sealed.
</P>
<P>
   This prologue is a wildly active piece of storytelling (its
perpetual motion, however, makes it seem exhausting). The movie
fades to 1923, where Rick (Fraser) and his men are searching for
the Lost City where, of course, untold riches have been buried (and
where the searchers will inadvertently activate the curse that
releases the Mummy). They're fighting off Egyptians, who are out to
keep them away. Rick's cowardly guide Benny (Kevin J. O'Connor,
who's so weedy and thin he looks like he's auditioning for a Dead
Kennedys bio-pic) abandons him, and Rick barely escapes with his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Sommers was on a kind of archaeological dig of his own when he
wrote the screenplay. He unearths all of the cliches for ``The
Mummy.'' He's included a good-hearted, two-fisted hero (Fraser
stands in front of the camera as if posing for his own action
figure), a slightly out-of-it but spunky scholarly heroine (Rachel
Weisz), and a sweaty, pudgy, greedy _ and smelly _ Egyptian
sidekick, whose depiction may inflame anti-defamation
organizations. Weisz has a face that's open to the camera. When she
hires Fraser (she saves him from hanging), we notice that her
alertness contrasts Fraser's genial, but opaque, quality. He's as
relentless as the movie _ and the Mummy.
</P>
<P>
   Sommers directed ``Deep Rising,'' in which he also tried to
blend horror and comedy, and the result was just as flat-footed.
I'm not sure whether he understands the difference between comedy
and facetiousness. He kids all of the conventions of the genres he
mixes by very carefully invoking them, right down to the verbal
sparring that smells as musty as the sarcophaguses they find.
That's not quite the same as offering laughs, though.
</P>
<P>
   One thing about ``The Mummy'' is that no one can say it's
dishonest. Everything we're told is going to happen, happens. Its
predictability is inexorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mummy'' is gorgeously photographed by Adrian Biddle, the
cinematographer who shoots many of Ridley Scott's films. And the
craftsmen of Industrial Light and Magic supply the computer magic
that gives life to the skeletal creatures _ other than Kevin J.
O'Connor _ that infest the movie. Instead of being liberated by
this, though, the army of virtual evil comes too easily. It'd be
more fun if some of the horror where suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Sommers tries to provide breathlessness by keeping things
slamming along. With Fraser whipping out his guns to blast away
portions of the creatures, the ``Indiana Jones'' movies come to
mind, but Sommers is also out to follow the lead of the high-flying
action of 1939's ``Gunga Din.'' The movie huffs and puffs along,
wearing itself out instead of keeping the audience so keyed up that
it's breathless. The movie's not half bad, because it doesn't take
itself seriously, although it'd be more fun if it were a half-hour
shorter.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe ``The Mummy'' _ which may be the first movie to inspire a
line of clothing from Banana Republic; the cast is beautifully
turned out in linens and earth tones: khakis of the Living Dead _
is in such a hurry because it comes with an expiration date. As of
May 19, it might as well go right to Blockbuster. That's when the
most frightening curse its creators can imagine appears, when
``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace'' is released upon cineplexes
across the land.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Mummy''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Stephen Sommers
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz
</P>
<P>
   Length: 127 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ PG-13 for violence, maiming, adult language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
