A6829 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-PLAY-BOS &LR;      05-06 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PLAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERIC DAVIS'S MESSAGE OF HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN ROMANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
BORN TO PLAY 
The Eric Davis Story: Life Lessons in Overcoming Adversity On and
Off the Field 
By Eric Davis with Ralph Wiley 
Viking, 278 pp., illustrated, $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are many ways to write a life story. The tone of such a
tale often follows from the author's motives. In the case of major
league baseball player Eric Davis, the tone he has chosen is one of
hope, faith, and resilience. A gifted athlete, his life and career
have been interrupted by numerous injuries, a life-threatening
battle with colon cancer, and the tragic death of his only brother.
One would certainly forgive Davis if he told his story in terms of
sadness or bitterness. But that's not what Davis is all about, and
that's what makes reading his book a must for anyone looking for
encouragement when facing the adversity that life sometimes throws
our way.
</P>
<P>
   The tale is not always told with great detail and depth, but its
effectiveness lies in its simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   I first became acquainted with Davis a year ago, just a few
weeks after I had been diagnosed with advanced colon cancer. Davis,
having just completed 36 weeks of chemotherapy following surgery to
remove a large growth from his colon, was about to begin his 14th
season in the majors as a member of the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The previous October he had staged a remarkably quick comeback
from surgery to return to Baltimore's lineup and help the team
finish strong and advance to the American League playoffs. His
efforts won him many awards honoring his courage, but none could
match the inspiration he brought to thousands of people who were
waging a fight against cancer and were watching his every move with
amazement and hope.
</P>
<P>
   Being one of the newest members of the club, I was stunned to
receive a phone call one afternoon from Davis, who had heard of my
plight from Globe baseball writer Gordon Edes. Davis's words of
wisdom were simple and clear. I would trust in God. I would fight.
And I would win.
</P>
<P>
   To be alive to read his autobiography a year later is testament
to several things, not the least of which is that Davis's spirit is
not misplaced. And it's that spirit, a positive, unflappable one,
that resonates throughout his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man or a woman can come back from cancer and not just exist,
but produce at the same level _ at a higher level,'' writes Davis.
``I took 36 chemotherapy treatments prior to the spring of '98. But
I still come to the post. They'll have to tear this uniform off me
one day. And only God determines when the harvest time has gone. I
just keep plugging on, and let His will be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Davis was born 36 years ago in South Central Los Angeles in
an area many people would call a ghetto _ and he called home. The
youngest of three children, he was raised by parents who taught
their kids to practice their faith, work hard, and be
self-sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Although he excelled at basketball, baseball would become the
game of choice for Davis, who signed with the Cincinnati Reds out
of high school in 1980. A fleet outfielder with a powerful batting
stroke, Davis parlayed those talents into starting roles in the
1987 and 1989 All-Star Games and a World Championship with the 1990
Reds. His career could have been even more impressive if not for
the number of injuries the brittle Davis experienced during his
career, including a serious injury to his kidney and a herniated
disk in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing was more challenging or taxing than what occurred
during the summer of 1997, when Davis began to experience digestive
problems and pain in his abdomen. After months of tests and
misdiagnoses, he was sent to Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore,
where it was determined that he had colon cancer. Just weeks after
he began chemotherapy, he got word that his only brother, Jim, had
died of cardiac arrest at the age of 36, a life wasted on drugs,
gangs, and prison.
</P>
<P>
   Coauthored by former Sports Illustrated writer Ralph Wiley,
Davis's book does not take long to digest. It can easily be read in
a few nights. Davis's writing style is often marked by incomplete
sentences, presented in stream-of-thought style. It is not a great
literary work, but that is not what is important here _ the
important thing is the message.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Davis, who this year is playing for the St. Louis
Cardinals, has had much success in his life, but with it has come
his share share of tragedy. He has chosen to handle all that with a
remarkable attitude of acceptance spiced with a powerful faith in
God. He chooses not to tell a tale of suffering and heartbreak, but
of how _ out of adversity _ one can learn to appreciate life and
set an example for others to follow.
</P>
<P>
   As one of those for whom he has set an example, I will be
forever grateful to Eric Davis and for the story he has to tell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
