<SLUG> BC-TV-REDFORD-CABLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDFORD LAUNCHES ANOTHER SUNDANCE WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It has been Robert Redford's curse his entire
life. You look at that face _ still pretty even though he's not a
boy _ and you expect him to be vapid and boring and perfect for an
``Entertainment Tonight'' sound bite.
</P>
<P>
   Then he talks about vertical integration.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone should know by now that Redford is a bright guy and, in
fact, is something of a visionary _ a feat he rarely gets credit
for. He was in San Francisco Wednesday announcing the launch of his
Sundance Channel on the TCI cable system.
</P>
<P>
   A new cable channel _ on the digital package _ doesn't usually
merit a news conference, particularly if, like Sundance, it only
has 20 million subscribers (that's barely surviving in the cable
world).
</P>
<P>
   So Redford pitched his 24-hour showcase for uncut, independent
films. He talked about how happy he was that his 3-year-old channel
finally made it to San Francisco, a fertile ground for independent
filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   To his right, the guy no one was looking at was TCI West
President John Kopchik. ``This is a special place to live, and
Sundance brings something special to the Bay area.''
</P>
<P>
   By getting on TCI in the San Francisco area, Redford will add
nearly 1 million new subscribers by the start of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But what the news conference really illuminated was Redford's
dogged vision of the Sundance concept _ what is better known these
days as synergy, but what was probably dismissed 20 years ago when
he formed his filmmaker's lab as Redford's Folly.
</P>
<P>
   Turned out he was way ahead of his time, and while the buzz
phrase in Hollywood now is ``vertical integration or die,'' damned
if the tousle-haired pretty boy doesn't have a lock on it.
</P>
<P>
   When the Sundance concept started 20 years ago, Redford knew he
needed a distribution outlet for the films, hence the Sundance Film
Festival five years later. ``That turned out to be more popular
than we'd imagined,'' he said, in one massive understatement.
</P>
<P>
   With the festival becoming a meat market of hype and glory,
Redford started the Sundance Channel in 1996, as a small-screen
vehicle for those films. And now he's launching Sundance Cinema
Centers _ his own theaters, basically.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, he's got a Web site, too (www.sundancechannel.com).
</P>
<P>
   That's a textbook example of vertical integration, perhaps not
the sexiest topic a famous actor could tout, but certainly one that
lends more insight into who he really is than saying, ``I love my
new film.''
</P>
<P>
   Redford the businessman tossed out phrases like ``cross
promotional advantages,'' ``interstitials'' and ``marketplace''
like he was a network honcho.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he is.
</P>
<P>
   Is anyone at the rival Independent Film Channel paying
attention?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
