<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ARCTICCIRCLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFETIME LOVERS GLOW IN A WARM `ARCTIC CIRCLE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coincidence is such a screenwriter's tool that Dallas' recent
USA Film Festival could have developed a seminar on it. Everything
from Arthur Penn's classic ``Little Big Man'' to the latest
no-budget indie depended on it. One of the festival entries, the
Spanish import ``Lovers of the Arctic Circle,'' doesn't just rely
on coincidence _ it turns it into part of the movie's myth.
</P>
<P>
   In Julio Medem's beautifully shot romantic drama, which gives
new meaning to the word ``elliptical,'' there aren't many degrees
of separation. The characters keep running into the most unlikely
people in the most unlikely places, from the Spanish Civil War to
the present-day Arctic Circle in Finland. But there is separation,
thanks to the forces that conspire to keep Otto (Fele Martinez) and
Ana (Najwa Nimri) apart as adults, despite a mutual obsession that
began when they were 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Otto, a dreamer even in his grade-school days, encounters the
young Ana as he's chasing an errant soccer ball (in an
astonishingly photographed sequence that's almost worth the price
of admission by itself). One look at Ana's penetrating, questioning
eyes, and Otto's hooked. Too bad that when he finally gets her
attention with a romantic question written on a paper airplane _ a
message the movie wisely never reveals _ he also inadvertently sets
her widowed mother up with his divorcing father, and Otto and Ana
wind up as infatuated stepsiblings, beginning their lifelong,
on-again, off-again love affair.
</P>
<P>
   Medem, who also wrote the screenplay, is so obsessed with the
cyclical nature of love and life that it even infuses his lead
characters' names (he's a bit heavy-handed in providing continual
reminders that both names are palindromic). Even the shapes of the
names _ the circles of Otto, the acute angles of Ana _ seem to be
intended to reflect the nature of the characters. Fele Martinez _
who's in another Spanish import opening this week, ``Open Your
Eyes'' _ has faraway eyes that are well-suited to Otto's drifting,
wounded soul; Najwa Nimri (also in ``Eyes'') has the sharp,
professional look of a woman who always knows where she's going.
</P>
<P>
   Up to a point, ``Lovers'' is fascinating, largely because of
Medem's visual ideas (keenly realized by an empathetic
cinematographer, Gonzalo F. Berridi), and the movie's delicate
sense of humor. But Medem begins to play too many games with the
audience, ultimately taking his going-in-circles theme a little too
literally. After a while, the multiple coincidences, which the
screenplay admits are unlikely, cease to surprise, and the movie
drifts into predictability. It's unfortunate that such a
worthwhile, sensitively told fable didn't know when it was time to
quit.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Lovers of the Arctic Circle,'' in Spanish with English
subtitles
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Julio Medem
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Fele Martinez, Najwa Nimri
</P>
<P>
   Length: 112 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, nudity and sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
