<HEADER>
A6832 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISC-REVIEWS-LADN     05-06 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISC-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
CHRIS CONNOR/``WARM COOL: THE ATLANTIC YEARS'' (32 Jazz)!off!
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along with June Christy and Julie London, Connor epitomized
``cool'' jazz singing in the '50s. This illuminating two-disc set
compiles tracks from the dozen albums the Anita O'Day-influenced
torch singer cut for Atlantic between 1956-62. The stuff is so
cool, you don't even notice when Connor has entered the picture on
such mellow standouts as ``Angel Eyes,'' ``Misty'' or ``Lilac
Wine.'' Top-notch arrangements by Don Sebesky and Ralph Sharon,
plus colorful backup from the likes of guitarist Freddie Greene,
pianist Jaki Byard and saxophonist Phil Woods maintain high
standards throughout 40 tunes, ranging from ``Strike Up the Band''
to an adventurous arrangement of Ornette Coleman's ``Lonely
Woman.'' 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DAVID SYLVIAN/``DEAD BEES ON A CAKE'' (Virgin)
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1982 breakup of his first group, Japan, Sylvian has
made a series of ambitious musical moves that involved fascinating
collaborations and forays into filmmaking and modern art. Joining
up once again with composer Ryuichi Sakamoto for this superb new
effort, producer Sylvian sustains a consistent, sometimes dreamy
mood throughout. From the languorous beauty of album opener ``I
Surrender'' to the earthy, blues-inflected ``Midnight Sun,'' the
disc mixes rough and smooth in elegant fashion throughout 14
meticulously arranged tracks. Featured musicians include old
friends like Kenny Wheeler and Bill Frisell, along with avant-garde
guitarist Marc Ribot and Brit-Asian tabla player and producer
Talvin Singh. A gem. 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GUSGUS/``THIS IS NORMAL'' (4AD/Warner Bros.)
</P>
<P>
   Iceland's GusGus is an unpredictable nine-member multimedia
collective of singers, musicians, filmmakers, actors and others
specializing in dramatic, electro-tinged soundscapes utilizing
hypnotic rhythms along with pop, soul and techno elements. Thanks
to the group's three very different singers, each carefully crafted
track on its extravagantly pretty second album stands alone while
immediate highlights include the tender ``Bambi,'' the soul-deep
``Very Important People'' and the gorgeous ``Blue Mug,'' among
other brainy pieces. ``This Is Normal'' may be a lot of things, but
normal isn't one of them. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DANNY GATTON/``HOT ROD GUITAR: THE DANNY GATTON ANTHOLOGY'' (Rhino)
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Gatton was the world's greatest unknown guitarist,
nicknamed the Humbler because of his awe-inspiring ability on his
battered '53 Fender Telecaster. Since 1994, though, he's been the
world's greatest unknown dead guitarist, the result of a suicide
just like his mentor, fellow Tele master Roy Buchanan six years
earlier. This 27-track, two-disc set does a good job tracing
Gatton's many moves, from sought-after, rough-and-tumble indie
efforts like ``Redneck Jazz'' and ``Relentless'' (with organist
Joey DeFrancesco) to the wonderful Blue Note jazz session ``New
York Stories'' (with Bobby Watson, Joshua Redman and Roy Hargrove)
and the two polished albums he cut for Elektra in the early '90s. 4
stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VARIOUS/``LIES, SISSIES AND FIASCOES: THE BEST OF THIS AMERICAN
LIFE'' (Rhino)!off!
</P>
<P>
   Ira Glass' ``This American Life'' is one of the best reasons to
listen to National Public Radio. The weekly program, always built
around a central theme and played out in four narrative acts, is an
inspired mixture of humor and pathos. Consisting of 11 monologues
on two CDs, this best-of culls some of the funniest and most
thought-provoking moments from the oddly touching show's three-year
history. Contributions come from Glass, author David Sedaris,
humorist Sandra Tsing Loh and a fellow known as Dishwater Pete
(whose mission is to wash dishes in all 50 states). In addition,
They Might Be Giants contribute a musical nugget. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JIM HALL AND PAT METHENY/``JIM HALL &AMP; PAT METHENY'' (Telarc)!off!
</P>
<P>
   For their first collaboration, these guitarists' guitarists
split composing and arranging duties with each writing a handful of
blues and ballads while also covering such standards as
``Summertime'' and ``All the Things You Are.'' Nearly half the
tracks were recorded in concert, but there's surprisingly little
fire in these serene duets. Hall and Metheny are tasteful to a
fault throughout, soloing on such tracks as ``All Across the City''
and ``Cold Spring'' as if each was afraid of somehow offending the
other. Still, there are enough lovely moments to make this low-key
charmer worth your time. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DOMINIQUE EADE/``THE LONG WAY HOME'' (RCA Victor)
</P>
<P>
   Jazz vocalist Eade continues to develop her warm, intimate way
with a song on this lovely album of songs about the road, the heart
and the home. Eade sings with an accomplished self-assurance on
four originals and eight covers that range from Henry Mancini's
``Two for the Road'' to Ornette Coleman's ``All My Life.'' Eade _
backed by pianist Bruce Barth, bassist Dave Holland, guitarist Mick
Goodrick and percussionist Cyro Baptista _ imbues each lyric with a
specific mood, demonstrating fine chops on a wide variety of songs.
A talent worth continued attention. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Glenn Whipp &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MEL TORME/``LULU'S BACK IN TOWN'' (Avenue Jazz) &QL; 
HERBIE MANN AND SAM MOST/``THE HERBIE MANN-SAM MOST QUINTET''
(Avenue Jazz)
</P>
<P>
   off!
</P>
<P>
   The first two releases from the Bethlehem archives couldn't have
been better choices. ``Lulu's Back in Town'' (3 1/2 stars) has
Torme with Marty Paich's 10-piece band on a 1956 date that has
never been issued on CD. Torme's warm voice has rarely been
displayed to better effect, particularly on the title cut, a
delightful romp that became one of his most popular signature
songs. Also out for the first time on CD, the Mann-Most album (3
1/2 stars) pairs the two jazz flutists on an upbeat, lightly
swinging 1955 album that serves to underscore just how little this
cool instrument is used. It's an adventurous album that belongs in
any jazz library.
</P>
<P>
   _ Glenn Whipp &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
