<HEADLINE>
TUITION TAKEN CARE OF, THEY MADE THE GRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Several years ago, a millionaire went into an inner-city
sixth-grade class and offered to pay the college tuition of all
students in that class if they studied and qualified. How many of
the students went on to college?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.M., Wilkes-Barre, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A: In 1981, Eugene Lang told 61 sixth-graders at P.S. 121 in
Harlem that he would send all of them to college if they finished
high school.
</P>
<P>
   Out of that group, 90 percent graduated from high school or
received a GED, compared with an expected graduation rate of 25
percent. Sixty percent of the students went on to college or
vocational training.
</P>
<P>
   Lang, a retired millionaire who had attended the same school,
started the I Have a Dream Foundation in 1986 to keep other at-risk
children from dropping out. More than 150 projects similar to
Lang's have helped more than 10,000 students with support,
mentoring and tuition assistance.
</P>
<P>
   To contact the group, visit its World Wide Web site at
www.ihad.org or call (212) 293-5480.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was a child, I was the jacks champion of our school
and our town. I recently ordered some from a company and was
shocked when they arrived made of plastic. Where can I find metal
jacks?
</P>
<P>
   _ U.C., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Great Hall Games and Distractions sells metal jacks with a
rubber ball in either a cloth bag ($5) or pine box ($8).
</P>
<P>
   For ordering information, write to Great Hall Games and
Distractions, Box 8239, Austin 78712; or visit the World Wide Web
site lonestar.texas.net/~greathal.
</P>
<P>
   The company specializes in games played during the Renaissance
and sells wooden and brass dice, historic playing cards and cloth
board games such as Pente, Go and Backgammon.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Danny DeVito?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.B., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to the actor and director in care of Creative Artists
Agency, 9830 Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, CA 90212.
</P>
<P>
   DeVito, 54, will be appearing in three films this year:
``Hospitality Suite, Pittsburgh'' and ``Man on the Moon,'' a
biographical film about DeVito's ``Taxi'' co-star Andy Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
