   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, May 7:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 3 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Bonn, Germany) _ Russia and the Western powers
agreed Thursday on a common approach to seeking peace for Kosovo,
including terms for an armed international force to secure the
return of refugees. ``The Russians have accepted the proposition
there needs to be a security presence on the ground in Kosovo,''
Sandy Berger, the U.S. national security adviser, says. Foreign
ministers of the Group of Eight countries meeting outside Bonn
settled on a seven-point plan to be endorsed by the U.N. Security
Council, German officials said. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the Kosovo plan,
looking a how the U.S. is seeking a diplomatic solution that would
save face, what demands will the U.S. and NATO compromise on and
where this NATO-Russian agreement leaves Slobodan Milosevic, the
Yugoslav president. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Ingelheim, Germany) _ President Clinton's day:
He met with Kosovo refugees and promised that Milosevic ``will not
succeed in erasing your presence from the land of your parents and
grandparents.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Developments from NATO headquarters:
the allies are to give a detailed briefing on what has been done to
Serbian forces in Kosovo. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congressional debate continues on
Kosovo spending. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Tirana, Albania) _ Macedonia closes its border
with Kosovo, saying it will take in only as many refugees as leave.
There is talk of busing many refugees from Macedonia into Albania,
which raises the question of how the Albanians can cope with such a
moved. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Tirana, Albania) _ A key separatist leader, Jakub
Krasniqi, says the KLA rebels will never agree to be disarmed,
insists on Kosovo independence and demands an explanation of
controversial statements made by Ibrahim Rugova, a moderate ethnic
Albanian leader. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-RUGOVA (Rome) _ The moderate leader Ibrahim Rugova holds a
press conference with Massimo D'Alema, the Italian prime minister.
By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Fort Dix, N.J.) _ Developments on the
Kosovar refugees brought to the U.S. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, stories on the social and
economic impact of the NATO attacks on Montenegro; the growing
prominence of Robin Cook, the British foreign secretary, and on the
plight of displaced Albanians who remain inside Kosovo, thought to
number 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-IMMIG (Hong Kong) _ With fears of an immigration crisis
already at a fever pitch here, the Hong Kong government warned
Thursday that the former British colony would be economically
devastated by the influx of 1.6 million newly eligible migrants
from mainland China. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-CROWD-CONTROL (Washington) _ The Clinton
administration will provide crowd-control training to the
Indonesian police before national elections in June, despite
concern from Congress and human rights groups over the abysmal
human rights record of the police. Similar training given to the
Indonesian military was shut down by Congress. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-ELECT (Edinburgh) _ Scots and Welsh vote today for
their new parliaments, the first since 1707 for Scots, the first
ever for the Welsh. Results results expected Friday. By Warren
Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ The battle lines on the Hill over
guns become clearer, as Senate Democrats announce a package of
amendments they want to attatch to a Republican juvenile justice
bill next week. It expands a bit on the president's proposals, and
establishes the contours of what is to be the first floor fight in
either chamber on gun control this session. By Frank Bruni. (900
words)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRIVACY (Washington) _ An FTC complaint that a website
misused persoanl information collected from children and teen-agers
has been settled. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OKLA-STORMS (Oklahoma City) _ The pathos of picking through the
rubble to see what's left of your family's belongings. By Rick
Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-STEELE (Alexandria, Va.) _ Julie Hiatt Steele's lawyers
rested their case today without calling any witnesses, saying
prosecutors failed to prove that she had hindered Kenneth Starr's
investigation of President Clinton. Ms. Steele is charged with
lying to investigators to undercut Kathleen Willey's accusation
that Clinton made an unwanted sexual advance. (Summary from wires)
By Don Van Natta. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on politics. By B.
Durmmond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ Abner Louima, a Haitian immigrant,
may testify today at the trial of four police officers charged with
brutalizing him. By Joseph P. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DOCTOR-KILLED (Buffalo, N.Y.) _ The district attorney here
charges James Kopp, an abortion foe, with murder in the shooting of
Dr. Barnett Slepian in October. By Joseph Berger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MICROSOFT (Undated) _ Developments: AT&AMP;T and Microsoft
confirm plans for Microsoft to buy $5 billion of AT&AMP;T preferred
shares in exchange for nonexclusive rights on settop software.
Microsoft will also buy MediaOne's 29.9 percent stake in Telewest,
Britain's second-biggest cable company. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MICROSOFT-TECH (Undated) _ How does the dream of connecting
into every American's home match the reality of the available
technology? By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve
chairman, warns that an increasingly tight U.S. labor market risks
fueling inflation, but he stops short of suggesting that the
central bank will raise interest rates any time soon. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:45, the Dow Jones industrial average
was down 89 points, the S&AMP;P down 30 points, the Nasdaq composite
down 43 points. European stock markets were slightly lower.
Japanese stocks surged 3.59 percent after being closed for three
days, while Hong Kong stocks were flat. At midday, the long bond
was down nearly 1 point, with the yield at 5.75 percent. By Robert
D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BANKING (Washington) _ Developments in the continuing
debate in the Senate on financial services legislation. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-INSURE (London) _ European insurance companies agree
at talks in London to pay out what they call the real value of
pre-war policies bought by Holocaust victims. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
