<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-CONSTRUCTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGINEERS OFFER TWISTER PROTECTIONS THAT CAN BE COSTLY, OR
INEXPENSIVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By TERRY KLIEWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Engineering experts are looking to the Oklahoma catastrophe for
real-world lessons in what might help tornado-threatened Americans
survive the violent storms.
</P>
<P>
   Several engineers said that the fury and devastation of the
twisters that struck metro Oklahoma City could raise new questions,
and possibly provide answers, about how to build homes and other
structures in storm-prone areas.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators will be looking over the wreckage left by Monday
night's tornadoes to see what survived and why. Three engineering
teams from Texas Tech University in Lubbock are at the disaster
scene to begin an on-site survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned about saving lives, of course,'' says Texas
Tech's Doug Smith, a structural engineer on the staff of Tech's
Wind Research Engineering Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``As engineers, we figure you save lives by keeping the
structure intact around the people inside.''
</P>
<P>
   The formula for keeping people safe from storm-blown debris,
falling roofs and walls, and toppling trees is both simple and
complex, say the experts:
</P>
<P>
   ``You put people inside some kind of enclosure that can't be
penetrated or collapsed or knocked around,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   The real challenge is how to build that enclosure without
spending a small fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you're willing to spend, the more you can protect
yourself,'' says Ben Sill, a fluid mechanics engineer at South
Carolina's Clemson University.
</P>
<P>
   That's the chief reason that commercial and institutional
buildings fare far better in storms than residential housing.
</P>
<P>
   The steel girders and reinforced concrete used for office
towers, hospitals and school buildings make them much less likely
to collapse, although flying debris and shattering glass still can
pose lethal hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Apartments and motels, often less strongly built, may not afford
the same level of protection. A lot depends on local building codes
and enforcement, says Bruce Russell, a structural engineer at the
University of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Russell estimates that incorporating truly stormproof protection
into a new home could increase its construction cost by as much as
50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of retrofitting an older home to make it safer would
run at least as much. For most people, that's not practical.
</P>
<P>
   Those building new homes can improve their odds of tornado
survival by designing a bathroom or utility room as an interior
shelter. The designated room should be built with reinforced
concrete-block walls and ceiling, solid-core doors with heavy
hardware, and firm anchoring to a slab foundation, Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   For older homes, the same principle applies, but instead of a
concrete block the plan substitutes multiple layers of heavy
plywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Covering walls and ceilings with three or four layers of
3/4-inch plywood provides almost as much protection,'' Smith says.
Again, heavy-duty doors and hardware, plus firm anchoring, are
essential.
</P>
<P>
   Sill says researchers at Clemson's Wind Load Test Facility have
concluded that adding just one layer of plywood sheathing to the
walls and ceiling of almost any room in a house affords a huge new
margin of safety.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the typical house, where walls are simply siding or brick
veneer on the outside and drywall on the inside, a falling tree or
pole can slice right through,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``By adding material to the wall, the risk is reduced. And the
stronger wall creates much greater protection against all but the
most direct-hitting debris.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemson researchers are investigating the use of other
materials, including Kevlar and chain mesh, as wall reinforcement,
but neither is as cheap or convenient as ordinary plywood, Sill
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The engineers say that residents of the
Texas-Oklahoma-Kansas-Missouri ``Tornado Alley,'' as well as people
living along hurricane-threatened coasts, also should consider
other small steps that can deliver big safety benefits.
</P>
<P>
   One of the foremost simple fixes is the addition of metal straps
for the roof rafters, wall studs and floor joists that comprise the
skeleton of virtually every U.S. home, new or old.
</P>
<P>
   The devices, known along the Gulf Coast as ``hurricane clips,''
tie together the joints between 2-by-4s, 2-by-6s and 2-by-8s that
otherwise are likely held together only by nails.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We put clips on our house when we built it,'' says Russell,
whose Norman, Okla., campus is just minutes from the tornado
disaster area. ``It wasn't expensive. You can buy these things by
the box at Home Depot.''
</P>
<P>
   The same low-tech, do-it-yourself approach can be applied to
mobile homes, which must be securely anchored and fully skirted to
prevent strong winds from sending them tumbling to destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to keep the structure in one place,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The three engineers concede that all bets are off for tornadoes
as powerful as the ones in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Russell says most commercial buildings are engineered to
withstand winds of 100 to 130 mph. Some homes will stand up to such
winds, but many cannot. Most mobile homes are vulnerable at winds
half that speed.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the fiercest of the several funnels that raked
Oklahoma City was rated F-5 on the Fujita scale, which implies wind
speeds in excess of 260 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Engineering for that,'' Sill says, ``is not possible.`` &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
