<SLUG> BC-TV-PVRs-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TV VIEWING TECHNOLOGY IS LOADED WITH KINKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Making the idiot box idiot-proof. That seems to
be the theory behind two new TV set-top boxes that hit the market
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed Personal Video Recorders, or PVRs, the gizmos are being
touted as the next wave in television viewing, allowing users to
create their own instant replays, commercial-free network viewing
experience and effortless recording of shows for later watching.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you have a burning desire to pay top dollar for
less-than-perfect technology that is certain to cost half as much
in the next year or so, you may want to pass up this new wave of
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, two PVRs are on the market: TiVo, which is made by
TiVo Inc. of Sunnyvale, Calif., and ReplayTV, manufactured by
Replay Networks, a new company in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Both have similar core technologies: Massive hard drives
constantly record and play back TV signals streamed in from just
about anything that can capture a TV signal _ satellite, cable or
rabbit ears.
</P>
<P>
   The boxes, both of which resemble faceless VCRs, squeeze the
received TV signal down to a manageable size by way of an MP2 video
processing chip.
</P>
<P>
   A user, via remote control, then manipulates this disk-stored
information by way of built-in software.
</P>
<P>
   Both machines require a phone connection to download updated
listings and other information into the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Because the boxes are constantly recording, you can pause,
rewind and play back any show you're watching. This immediately
translates into a network's worst nightmare: You can start, say,
``Frasier'' at 7 p.m. and then take a 10-minute food break. When
you return to the couch, you can rewind and start watching the show
from its beginning, skipping commercials along the way. By the time
you get to 7:30, you've caught up with the actual real-time TV
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   This also means you can instantly create your own instant
replays.
</P>
<P>
   This technology is not cheap.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo starts at $499 for 14-hour storage capacity, and climbs to
$999 for a 30-hour machine. A 10-hour ReplayTV costs $699, and the
28-hour machine goes for $1,499. These prices don't include
shipping (the devices are available only by mail order from Web
sites).
</P>
<P>
   But TiVo isn't really a price leader. The company also charges
for its interactive, on-screen guide. That can add $200 or more to
the cost of the machine.
</P>
<P>
   While the core technology for both machines is similar, there
are several user features that distinguish the two.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo edged out ReplayTV in set-up simplicity, though both
machines could use another revision or two to make this process
easier. A dizzying array of connecting cords is included with each
machine. Installation involves having to figure out exactly how
you're going to control the PVR and its relationship to any other
video component, like a DVD player or second VCR. Satellite users
have to install included widgets that will link the PVR to the disk
set-top receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Here, ReplayTV fell down in its out-of-the-box experience.
</P>
<P>
   Paltry documentation made for difficult going. And cords were
way too short, requiring two trips to Radio Shack. TiVo included
the right length cords and a video that explained the basic
installation clearly.
</P>
<P>
   There was one glitch in ReplayTV's installation: If you set up
its PVR to also handle a VCR or DVD player, a tiny hiccup in the
picture will occasionally occur (about two to three times per
feature film). Apparently, the signal from these components ``backs
up'' the signal in the MP2 processor. It's a tiny but annoying bug.
</P>
<P>
   But ReplayTV excelled when it came to the interactive TV guide.
ReplayTV's guide lets you see several hours ahead over a range of
channels, much like a standard print TV guide.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo's guides contained lush graphics, but the listings were
confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Recording future shows was also a ReplayTV strength. You
highlight a show on the viewing guide, hit record, answer a couple
of quick questions. A small red ball on the TV guide shows you that
you've chosen the show for later recording. TiVo makes you work
through a few screens and lots of unnecessary choices to record
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ReplayTV also has a better remote control. It doubles as a
universal remote that lets you manipulate DVD or other components.
TiVo's remote will let you control the volume and power for a TV or
audio amplifier. And it doesn't do that very well. The code that
turns on my amplifier shut off my TV.
</P>
<P>
   Another ReplayTV plus: The box contains a ``firewire''
connection that will allow disk drive expansion in the future. TiVo
has no such capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   But TiVo's biggest downfall is the pricing policy of the
company's interactive guide.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo charges $9.99 per month to download the listings necessary
to use its PVR. (A lifetime guide fee of $199 is available, as is a
$99 annual payment plan.) ReplayTV doesn't charge for this service.
</P>
<P>
   The TiVo machine tracks your PVR usage, and uploads those stats
to TiVo's computers. This means you become the target of PVR junk
mail in the form of on-screen ads, some of it based on your
watching habits. And you get to pay for the privilege. It's a
cheapskate strategy that deserves to fail.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, PVRs are impressive. It's technology that does
enhance the TV watching experience. But considering its pricing and
flaws, it's probably best to wait this one out. Cheaper, slicker
machines probably aren't too far away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
