<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6882 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-06 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORMS MAKE PERFECT PETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ever since my neighbors gave me a compost bin as
a housewarming present, I have sarcastically referred to it as ``my
pets.''
</P>
<P>
   The term is meant totally as a slur on me and my un-St. Francis
of Assisi relationship to animals, not on the worms and whatever
else slithers around inside the bin.
</P>
<P>
   When I was an apartment renter, I swore that the minute I had my
own house, I'd get a dog. But I bought my house almost a year ago
and am no closer than I ever was to acquiring a dog, cat, bird or
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Demeece and Sally, the neighbors who gave me the compost bin,
have a dog, a cat and a major composter that makes their backyard
soil ultra-rich. When they brought over my bin _ a green plastic
cooler-like thing with holes in the bottom _ they included simple
guidelines and a list of acceptable and verboten ``food'' for the
worms. (Coffee grounds and filters are OK; lamb chops and cheese
aren't.)
</P>
<P>
   For the first few weeks I was, if not enthusiastic, at least
game. Per Demeece and Sally's instructions I separated the good
garbage from the nasty animal products, cut big chunks into smaller
pieces, stirred them into the fecund-smelling compost and kept a
soggy piece of newspaper over the whole mess.
</P>
<P>
   Stirring isn't easy, by the way. Compost is dense and tends to
clump. Probably I should use one of those three-pronged claw things
that you dig dirt with, but I started with a wooden spoon so I keep
using a wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   When winter came, I thought a lot about going outside, prying
off the compost bin lid and stirring the garbage. But it always
seemed to be pouring rain or freezing. So, I kept chucking all my
garbage into my garbage can and promising myself I'd feed ``my
pets'' in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Months passed. At least three. I felt guilty about neglecting
the worms. But I didn't do anything. Then I went into denial,
refused to look at the bin, even when I was weeding or planting in
the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a few days ago, I cracked. Maybe it was because I'd
spent a long weekend in Las Vegas where it is prohibited by law for
humans to be in harmony with nature.
</P>
<P>
   Expecting a bin full of starved-to-death worm corpses, I pried
off the lid. All was not quiet on the compost front: The soggy
newspaper looked like a piece of gray-black lace; the worms et al
had chewed zillions of little holes in it. And it was pulsating
from underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Using my wooden spoon to pull aside the paper (no way I was
going to touch it with my bare hands), I peered into a roiling sea
of gigantic pink worms, those silvery-and-black oval bugs that
scurry when you pick up a potted plant, teeny white squirmy
lightning bolt things and I don't know what else.
</P>
<P>
   My compost bin looked like a big bowl of living spaghetti.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing for some cannibalism, which I hear compost dwellers
practice, I could only conclude that the worms et al had survived
off the soggy newspaper. Not just survived, THRIVED.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in ages I felt good about what I do for a
living.
</P>
<P>
   I also had to admit that Demeece and Sally not only have
improved my backyard soil, they really did find the perfect pets
for me.
</P>
<P>
   Worms are quiet. They don't shed or cough up fur balls and they
exercise themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other house pets, they chew on one another, not on
furniture or shoes. They don't need a litter box either because
they live in one.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps best of all, when times are lean and food is scarce,
worms can subsist on the one thing I'll always have plenty of _
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's time for names.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
