<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, May 7.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRONX-ARTS (New York) _ Art in the Bronx, like the sprawling
borough itself, is a resilient multi-facetted thing, cosmopolitan
in outlook, but imbued with a spirit of place. It embraces many
media, from video installation to virtuosic aerosal spray painting.
And it turns up in unexpected places: in school hallways, hospital
lobbies, courtrooms, subway stations, apartment living rooms, and _
officially, unofficially, and often heart-liftingly _ on building
facades. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   RECORD-STORES (Undated) _ Take pity on the next generation of
music fiends, for they may not know the pleasure of loitering in
little record stores. People in their twenties, thirties and
forties, less and less guilty about shopping on the internet, are
regularly denying themselves the chance to go into a record shop
and just look. By Ben Ratliff.
</P>
<P>
   STAR-WARS (Hollywood0 _ Distributors get a first peek at ``Star
Wars.'' By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   CIDER-THEATER-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Cider House Rules'' at the
Atlantic Theater Co. Reviewed by Peter Marks.
</P>
