<HEADER>
A6928 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     05-06 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZOOMING IN ON SHOPPERS: RESEARCH FIRM STUDIES PEOPLE'S PURCHASING
HABITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Teresa McUsic 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Paco Underhill says he has shopping down to a science, he
isn't kidding.
</P>
<P>
   The urban geographer and retail anthropologist _ I am not making
up these titles _ is also founder of a research and consulting firm
called Envirosell, which advises Fortune 100 companies.
</P>
<P>
   Underhill's analysis of how we shop may revolutionize the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about daily sales tapes totals. As Underhill
and Bill Gates tell us, most of the information gathered by cash
register codes isn't even used to make in-store changes to increase
sales.
</P>
<P>
   We also aren't talking about market research, which typically
polls people who may or may not remember their last shopping
experience. Underhill says that people often remember seeing
products that aren't even in the store, or they forget the brand of
something they just bought.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly numbers on which you want to make decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Underhill has spent the past 20 years developing
something he calls the science of shopping. He uses video cameras
and discreet observers to record the buying habits of shoppers. His
employees can calculate how many ties you touch before you decide
to buy one, or how many shoppers will come and go without buying
anything.
</P>
<P>
   He has made fascinating observations about shoppers and stores
by watching and recording up to 900 aspects of shopper-store
interaction.
</P>
<P>
   Forget branding, traditional advertising and the other standard
marketing tools.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Most buying decisions are made on the sales floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``An important medium for transmitting messages and closing
sales is now the store and the aisle,'' Underhill says. ``That
building, that place, has become a great big three-dimensional
advertisement for itself. Signage, shelf position, display space
and special fixtures all make it either likelier or less likely
that a shopper will buy a particular item'' (or any item at all.)
</P>
<P>
   If that store is a comfortable environment, shoppers will stay
longer, Underhill tells us. And if they stay longer, they buy more.
</P>
<P>
   Those refreshing ideas can be found in Underhill's new book,
``Why We Buy: The Science of Shopping'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 255
pages).
</P>
<P>
   One of the best things about this book is that it focuses
strictly on one unit of a store _ any store. Therefore, the
information and observations can be applied to a giant chain such
as Nordstrom's or Wal-Mart, or a tiny individual boutique.
</P>
<P>
   And in this day of heavy competition, such advice could give a
retailer the edge needed to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now dangerously overretailed _ too much is for sale,
through too many outlets,'' Underhill writes. ``... Retailers are
not opening stores in the United States to serve new markets
anymore. They are opening stores to try to steal someone else's
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using the traditional marketing tools, Underhill has
his own tools, which he discusses extensively. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _''How to design signs that shoppers will actually read and how
to make sure each message is in the appropriate place.''
</P>
<P>
   _''How to fashion displays that shoppers can examine comfortable
and easily.''
</P>
<P>
   _''How to ensure that shoppers can reach, and want to reach,
every part of a store.''
</P>
<P>
   Those ideas are brought into reality by scientifically
researched equations such as the conversion rate (the number of
shoppers who become buyers); the interception rate (the percentage
of customers who have some contact with an employee); and the
waiting time before checkout.
</P>
<P>
   Underhill uses numerous examples, usually without naming names,
to illustrate his points. He shows how a drugstore moved its
aspirin out of the path of teen-agers heading for soft drinks;
sales of aspirin to its main buyer, senior citizens, rose 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Or how moving a tie rack near Bloomingdale's front door, where
shoppers were being bumped into by entering and exiting customers,
created a substantial and quick rise in sales.
</P>
<P>
   This book provides an excellent way for retailers to examine
their tore space and look for what may drawing customers, as well
as what may be causing them to leave without buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overarching lesson that we've learned from the science of
shopping is this: Amenability and profitability are totally and
inextricably linked,'' Underhill writes. ``... Build and operate a
retail environment that fits the highly particular needs of
shoppers and you've created a successful store.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 112 Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   ``King of Clubs: Growing Rich in More Than Money''
</P>
<P>
   By Robert H. Dedman
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, $21.96
</P>
<P>
   Robert Dedman, chairman of ClubCorp International in Dallas,
offers a simple memoir of his life and times. However, this
fairy-tale version of how Dedman came to be worth $50 million at
age 50 by building an empire of golf courses and country clubs is
less than credible. He offers plenty of boasts about his family but
few sharp-edged business tips. Debbie DeLoach, a Dallas journalist,
is co-author.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart Women Finish Rich: 7 Steps to Achieving Financial
Security and Funding Your Dreams''
</P>
<P>
   By David Bach
</P>
<P>
   Broadway Books, $25
</P>
<P>
   Women live, on average, seven years longer than men. Yet only
about one in five over the age of 65 receives a pension. This is
one of the many reasons why women need financial planning, says
educator David Bach, who also manages a half-billion dollars in
individual investors' money. This book clearly plots a strategy for
taking charge of your finances and investing in your future. IRAs,
life insurance, taxes, asset allocation and other related topics
are covered.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Executive TEMP: The Complete Career and On-the-Job Guide for
the Interim Manager''
</P>
<P>
   By Diane L. Thrailkill
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   The Economist predicts that by the turn of the century, 50
percent of all jobs will be temporary. The Labor Department
suggests that within a decade, 95 percent of all jobs will be
contractual, for a set fee and a set period of time. It's time we
all learned more about temporary employment. This guide covers such
topics as how much to charge, how to market and sell your services,
and how to work with agencies.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
