<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6933 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONTAINER-GARDENS06-C     05-06 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTAINER-GARDENS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prepare for heat, wind if your container garden is to reach new
heights
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The next time you notice one of those lush little
gardens spilling over a high-rise balcony, give its gardener a big
salute.
</P>
<P>
   The owner deserves it. Any successful container gardener knows
there's a science to what goes into making a pretty pot. Choosing
the wrong type of container, soil or plants can send the garden
into terra-cotta terror. But balcony containers face even bigger
obstacles _ exposure to the extremes that come with height.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat in summer and winds year-round can have a devastating
effect on plants,'' said Jeremy Smearman, owner of Planters, a
Buckhead garden center.
</P>
<P>
   Having created containers for balconies as high as 40 floors,
including part-time Atlantan Elton John's condo in Park Place, the
garden designer has seen large, plant-filled terra-cotta pots
topple onto their sides from the force of howling winds.
</P>
<P>
   Heat, especially if the porch faces south or southwest, is
another battle. Even under normal conditions, container gardens
often require daily watering because plant roots not only are
confined but are within a pot that retains heat. Place those
containers on a skyscraper's pedestal for several hours of baking
in Atlanta's summer sun, and the survival stakes run higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a problem for a lot of our clients,'' said Randy
Korando of Boxwoods Gardens &AMP; Gifts in Atlanta, which designs
container gardens.
</P>
<P>
   But by making careful choices in plants and materials, high-rise
dwellers can create a small-scale garden of their dreams. The key,
in addition to planning for exposure, is to aim for a few large
containers instead of a dozen small ones, for both aesthetic and
practical reasons. Clustering a few pots together creates not only
a focal point for the balcony but more mass for withstanding winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to soften the harsh look of a balcony, you want
to use plants with some size and substance to them and also so the
wind won't topple them,'' Smearman said.
</P>
<P>
   Small trees and shrubs make ideal centerpieces for pots,
especially when their trunks are trimmed up so that the container
can be underplanted with smaller plants for color. (And don't worry
about the weight of large soil-packed cement containers, Smearman
said.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other factors to consider:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Containers. Fiberglass, designed to resemble clay pots, once
was shunned as a cheap imitation, but recent advances have made the
plastic material more attractive. It's also popular because it's
lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   But for high-rise gardening, weight is desirable. Smearman
prefers terra cotta, but because it's prone to breakage, especially
during freezes, he uses concrete. His favorite containers are
Haddonstone, which contain limestone and resist cracking.
</P>
<P>
   From a design perspective, he uses pots that complement the
building's exterior _ and often the unit's interior design.
</P>
<P>
   Because concrete and terra cotta are porous, pots made of those
materials dry out more rapidly than fiberglass, said Mildred
Pinnell, a horticulturist at the Atlanta Botanical Garden. The
staff at the botanical garden paints the insides of terra cotta
pots with black roofing sealant to help them retain moisture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wood is another option _ between terra cotta and plastic in
terms of weight _ and styles in it have really improved,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Exposure. The amount of sunlight the container gets _ and in
the highrise gardener's case, its height and building orientation _
determines the choice of plants.
</P>
<P>
   The higher the location, the more extreme the conditions.
``There's even a big difference between the ground and third floor
once you get above the trees,'' Smearman said. ``Anything above 10
floors with southern or western exposure has nothing to abate the
sun because in Atlanta, except for downtown, most of our taller
buildings are isolated and exposed rather than close together,
where they would shade each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that because homeowners increasingly opt for
low-maintenance gardens, the supply of drought-tolerant annuals,
perennials and shrubs is widely available.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Soil. Container plants perform best in loose, soilless potting
mix _ not heavy potting soils _ in which their roots can freely
integrate, Pinnell said.
</P>
<P>
   She and Smearman use a Fafard, which contains finely ground pine
bark and peat moss. For perennials, shrubs and small trees, she
prefers a bulkier material that retains moisture, such as Nature's
Helper Organic Soil Conditioner, mixed with one-fourth compost. And
for highrise containers, Smearman top dresses pots with several
inches of Mr. Natural Complete Landscape Mix (Its expanded slate
helps break down soil) to prevent them from drying out.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Maintenance. Container gardens benefit from a slow-release
fertilizer, such as Osmocote, which Pinnell recommends mixing with
the soil at planting. And because containers demand frequent
waterings _ _ their soil loses valuable nutrients and therefore
requires more feedings. She uses a water-soluable granular
fertilizer, such as Miracle Gro or Peter's.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the wind potential, plants in highrise containers
typically require staking, and don't be afraid to prune them,
Pinnell said, especially trailers such as petunias and verbena. The
ones at the botanical garden are cut back by one-third at three
times during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, they don't look like they've had their summer crew
cut,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C, Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
