A6936 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN06-COX     05-06 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Untangling mystery of the rambling hose
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When I began gardening in Atlanta 10 years ago, one of
my first moves was dismantling a watering system installed by the
previous owners. The system, sprinkler heads sticking out of the
ground, fed by water pipes and controlled by timers, seemed
excessively unnecessary for my small space.
</P>
<P>
   More important, I've always preferred watering manually,
dragging around a hosepipe, as I grew up calling it (I've since
learned it's a watering hose). Watering by hand allows me _
encourages me, actually _ to get a good, close-up look at plants,
so I can see what shape they're in, discover whether they're about
to go bloom or bust. With a sprinkler system, it's possible to go
for weeks, months, even, without peering into the face of an abelia
or a leucothoe, looking down the throat of a daylily.
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, I've looked into a lot of faces, down
countless throats, put a lot water onto the ground. And I've
dragged a lot of hosepipe. In the process I've learned an essential
truth about this indispensable gardening tool: It will always find
a way to frustrate you.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, I didn't always notice the diabolical side of watering
hoses. As a boy playing through the sultry seasons of Alabama,
Mississippi and Illinois, I enjoyed hosepipes immensely. Spraying
friends and getting sprayed by them was great fun. Refreshing, too.
As was that joyful and timeless pose struck by millions of boys of
summer: hose held in one hand, going full blast past mouth
capturing part of cooling stream. Ahhh is all we said.
</P>
<P>
   I've said a lot of unprintables since those idyllic days, as
hoses have found ways to get tangled up when there were no ways.
</P>
<P>
   Whether hoses changed, or whether I did, entanglement seems much
more prevalent these days. Rubber, vinyl, expensive, cheap _ it
doesn't seem to matter to a rambling hose. Never do I get through a
watering without marveling at how adept these tubes are at grabbing
on to something. Anything.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with my pulling the hose out of the crawl space.
Before I've unfurled 10 feet, the thing has somehow stretched a
foot upward and twisted itself around a faucet handle. Once out, it
never misses an opportunity to crimp, cutting the flow of water
down to a trickle.
</P>
<P>
   And if it's not crimping, it's wrapping around itself like a
demented snake, forcing me to pick through its 75 feet to find head
and tail.
</P>
<P>
   At one spot in my garden, where the walkway makes a 90-degree
turn, no hose can ever make the corner without grabbing raised
bricks and holding on until pried loose. Similarly, one rosemary
unfortunate enough to live in my watering path gets grabbed and
choked as if by a boa constrictor. This routine mugging got so bad
that the poor rosemary had gotten shaky, threatening to fall out of
the ground. So, the other day, I put a rock in front of it, hoping
to protect it from the rubber marauder.
</P>
<P>
   Problem with the rock is that any object in the garden amounts
to a hose magnet. While the rock will protect the rosemary, it also
will give the hose another snagging point, joining all the
containers, benches, bricks and various follies scattered through
the garden.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how carefully I try to guide a hose through
soft-stemmed plants such as coneflower and zinnia, it manages to
stretch out and roll onto them, pinning them to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Solutions don't come easy.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, thinking my hose was too inflexible, I bought
one that seemed soft and manageable. But as soon as it got home and
engorged, it grew as untamed as the rest, jumping here and there,
unpredictably. At another time, I went from a 100-foot hose to one
half that length, believing the shorter pipe would be more wieldy.
It wasn't. I tried one of those ``hose pots,'' hoping it would
allow me to use only as much pipe as I needed, leaving the rest
neatly coiled. Of course, it refused to coil in a continuous
circle, preferring to go clockwise, then counterclockwise, then
clockwise again. I ended up with half a hose in the pot and the
other half twisted outside it. Eventually, some foolish thief stole
the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Given hoses' hellish behavior and my increasing reliance on them
amid so many hot, dry seasons, I must confess there have been times
I regretted undoing that automatic sprinkler system.
</P>
<P>
   When such second thoughts strike, I open the faucet wide,
maneuver the hosepipe into position, blast a few aphids off the
rose bush, and then, as the water grows cooler and cooler, I let it
streak across my lips. Ahhh.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes a weekly column on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay(at)bellsouth
</P>
<P>
   .net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
