<HEADER>
A6937 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-MATERNITY06-COX     05-06 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-MATERNITY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maternity clothes with versatility can keep any mom-to-be
looking stylish while waiting for the big event
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A stylish maternity wardrobe is not an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're expecting a millennium baby or an heir in a few
months, you can find cool-looking comfortable clothes that'll take
you from work to play.
</P>
<P>
   The key to building your versatile wardrobe is to base it around
key pieces in a basic color scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've invested in core pieces, then add layers, suggests
Cherie Serota, who co-authored ``Pregnancy Chic'' (Random House,
$16.95) with her partner, Jody Kozlow Gardner. For warm weather,
they suggest a cotton twin set, a shirt jacket in stretch twill and
a V-neck T-shirt. For cooler weather, consider a turtleneck
sweater, a bootleg pant and a cardigan jacket.
</P>
<P>
   But versatile doesn't have to mean boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pregnant women simply want to wear trendy fashions, in both
color and style,'' says Lisa Price, owner of the Great Beginnings
maternity shop on Cheshire Bridge Road. She should know, since
Price and her husband, David, are expecting their first baby in
July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to offer clothes that will make women feel good about
themselves,'' she said. This season that includes trendy Capris,
men's-style shirts, and pretty, simple dresses.
</P>
<P>
   To help a woman look fashionable throughout her pregnancy, we
chose nine essential items for those nine special months. Our color
scheme? Black and white with touches of color.
</P>
<P>
   C A S U A L
</P>
<P>
   1. Chic Capris are the must-have pants of the season. These
black stretch twill pants, from Belly Basics ($55), hit midcalf;
inserts of elastic on both sides of the pant allow the belly to
expand.
</P>
<P>
   2. The ultimate men's shirt comes in white cotton or colorful
French blue stripes ($69) from Belly Basics. Wear it over all types
of pants as well as short skirts.
</P>
<P>
   3. Low-heeled shoes are essentials, and black slides from BCBG
($94.95) are simple and easy to, well, slide into. However, some
offices might consider them too sporty; if that's the case, stick
to low-heeled pumps and keep your slides for the weekends. Just
make sure your toes are well-pedicured. Clothes and slides from
Nordstrom in Perimeter Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Day-to-evening
</P>
<P>
   4. The trendy twin set has morphed into the newest blazer. It's
hot fashion news but cool to wear, if the sweaters are knitted from
cotton, silk or a rayon blend. This floral rayon/nylon set (tank is
$180; cardigan is $220) can be worn together in the office. For a
dressy look on the town, remove the cardigan. From A Pea in the Pod
in Phipps Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   5. Well-cut trousers are versatile and a wardrobe must. Try
these black rayon pants ($98), which can be dressed up or down. At
Great Beginnings on Cheshire Bridge Road.
</P>
<P>
   Professional
</P>
<P>
   6. Give me a T-shirt in a short-sleeved, white cotton V-neck.
The essential layering piece can be worn alone, under jackets or
cardigan sweaters. This version ($36) is from Belly Basics. At
Nordstrom.
</P>
<P>
   7. The little black skirt with its elastic waist can be dressed
up or down and worn with a variety of tops. This polyester skirt
($88) is from A Pea in the Pod.
</P>
<P>
   8. The jacket of all trades is a comfy one in pale blue linen.
This version ($148) has the chic styling of a shirt and is perfect
to wear with skirts or trousers. The chic designer diaper bag ($80)
is by Kenneth Cole. Both items from A Pea in the Pod.
</P>
<P>
   After-five9. A pretty empire-styled dress is perfect for formal
occasions. Pink is big this year and looks fetching on most
moms-to-be. This dress in silk charmeuse ($168) was designed by
Nancy Hellmuth. At Great Beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   Coordinating with a neutral color a good place to start
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for a maternity wardrobe? Here are additional tips for
moms-in-the-making:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Base your wardrobe on a neutral color. Dressing from head to
toe in black, beige or navy looks elegant and clean-lined. Add
color through accessories or layering pieces.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For those of you who want help finding mix-and-match maternity
separates, consider kits, such as Belly Basics' Pregnancy Survival
Kit. Created five years ago by New York marketing executives Cherie
Serota and Jody Kozlow Gardner, the little white box contains four
core black pieces: a short skirt, leggings, a tunic and a
knee-length, long-sleeve dress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buy your maternity clothes in stages. ``Your waistline expands
first, then your belly,'' says shop owner Price. ``I didn't need
the stretch panels at first in skirts and pants, but at five
months, I started to appreciate them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep to your size. Maternity fashions are made with the same
proportions as nonmaternity clothes, but with additional room in
the belly. If you are a size 8 before you are pregnant, buy that
same size in maternity wear.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Look for dresses and tops that have tiebacks. These can be
loosened as your pregnancy progresses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Play up your positive features. If you have good legs, show
them off with a short dress or skirt. If your eyes are blue, play
them up with the color shirt you choose.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Steer clear of splashy prints that aren't slimming to start
with. Why wear them now? Stick to small prints or stripes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accessories such as scarves, pearl necklaces and button
earrings can change the look of a basic dress or pantsuit to
increase your wardrobe's versatility.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure you wear a supportive bra and maternity hosiery.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
