<HEADER>
A6938 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-MOTHERSDAY09-CO     05-06 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-MOTHERSDAY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finally, mom gets the royal treatment
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 9.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton / Fashion Editor
 &HT;    Photos By Jean Shifrin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note: Last month, we invited readers to write in and
nominate mothers whom they felt were deserving of a ``supermodel''
makeover. Out of nearly 100 entries _ all of them worthy _ we
selected two winners based on the special sacrifices they've made
for their families' sakes. What follows is a detailed description
of a day like no other for each of them, a day they spent being
pampered instead of pampering those they love.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANA _ Stoicism is a virtue that Carole Arnoldi and Sunghee
Lee have in common. But there's a time and a place for keeping a
stiff upper lip, and the occasion of having a Mother's Day makeover
isn't it.
</P>
<P>
   If Arnoldi and Lee had been more accustomed to being fussed
over, Stan Milton Salon cosmetician Karin Robinson would have had
an easier time applying their makeup. ``It's funny how tense they
are,'' Robinson commented during a break in the five-hour
``supermodel'' makeover session that the two were awarded. ``I have
to keep telling them, `Relax, girls; this is supposed to be fun.'
''
</P>
<P>
   But as this was the first-ever makeover for each of the moms,
both of whom were nominated by their daughters, the nervousness was
understandable. ``I'm not used to the attention,'' explained
Arnoldi.
</P>
<P>
   They got a quick lesson in being attended to. As soon as they
arrived, a team of salon staffers converged to see what they had to
work with in terms of skin, hair and makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Milton and his chief colorist, Kirby Allen, did an analysis of
Lee's hair and determined that she needed color enhancement,
reddish-brown highlights and a cut that was more flattering to her
bone structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so sure about this,'' Lee said in Korean, through her
daughter, Jennifer, who came along to interpret.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Lee saw the tomato-red dye that Allen was applying,
she yelled across the salon to her daughter, ``What's he doing?''
</P>
<P>
   The makeup application process proved easier for the pair to
endure. In fact, when lunchtime arrived, both Lee and Arnoldi opted
to go hungry rather than risk smudging their lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   But before the cosmetic phase, the two were introduced to
something neither had ever tried: eyebrow waxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have it done for the first time, the skin in the
treated area does tend to get red and irritated,'' said esthetician
Brenda Smith. ``But if they continue to wax, their faces will get
used to it and the hairs that grow back will be softer and easier
to remove.''
</P>
<P>
   The final phase was outfitting the pair in designer fashions and
getting them to pose in glamour mode. That's when their
camera-shyness really surfaced. Luckily, both had their children
present to help coax smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said she felt ``younger'' after the makeover experience. ``I
learned how to do my makeup. . . . That's new to me.''
</P>
<P>
   As Arnoldi prepared to leave the salon, she still seemed
embarrassed by all the attention. But she did remark on the
makeover's potential residual effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be habit-forming,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Headline) Kids' future prompts move from South Korea
</P>
<P>
   Sunghee Lee's children are no dummies.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter who nominated Lee for a makeover, Jennifer Kim, is
a sophomore at Emory University, double-majoring in economics and
neuroscience behavioral biology. And her son, Michael, the quiet
one, is a Georgia Tech senior studying computer science.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 49, a homemaker who lives in Marietta (Ga.), left a
husband, and a life, behind in South Korea five years ago to help
ensure that her children's futures would be as bright as they now
appear. She hasn't made many friends and speaks hardly any English,
so social contact is restricted mostly to Sunday services at her
Korean-speaking Protestant church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything she does is sacrificial,'' daughter Jennifer said.
``I try to buy her gifts now and then, to please her. But what she
really needs is to do something for herself.''
</P>
<P>
   (Headline) Partner in fight against cancer
</P>
<P>
   When a woman spends nine years nursing her husband through a
losing battle with cancer, it's understandable that she could lose
some of her sense of self.
</P>
<P>
   Recently widowed Carole Arnoldi, 51, of Peachtree City (Ga.) was
nominated by her daughter, Tina, because ``she needs somebody to
pay attention to her needs for a change. She needs to be
pampered.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother of three appeared nervous when she arrived for her
makeover at Stan Milton Salon, and she grew even more reluctant
when the time came to pose for a post-makeover glamour shot. She
endured the whole process because her daughter wanted her to. And
that's what being selfless is all about.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
