<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6939 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CAROLINA09-COX     05-06 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAROLINA09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Relax and breathe in the mystery of life in S.C. Lowcountry
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 9.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE GRAND STRAND, S.C. _ Not long after I cross the Little Pee
Dee River, cruising toward the coast along U.S. 501 through
wide-spot-in-the-road towns of Galivant's Ferry and Aynor, the
head-turning roadside billboards begin to proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   Angelo's Steakhouse hawks a sizzling slab of beef called the Big
Daddy. The Landmark resort crows over its 10 pools. Ripley's
Aquarium promises ``more fish, more fun.'' Everything in Myrtle
Beach, it seems, sells some sort of abundance: 100 golf courses,
all-you-can-eat seafood buffets. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I'm on a trip to bountiful, but it's bounty of a different sort.
I've come in search of the laid-back side of the Grand Strand, the
lofty-sounding name given to the upper reaches of South Carolina's
Lowcountry. I'm interested in catching glimpses of alligators and
ospreys, hearing Gullah ghost tales and finding traces of tideland
rice plantations that flourished in the 18th and 19th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   At last I spy a billboard that suits my style. It reads simply:
Glitz. Circa 1700s. Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   It just so happens that Georgetown is on my itinerary. But
first, I'm bound for Conway, 15 miles northwest of Myrtle Beach.
Then, I'll be heading south to the coastal towns of Murrells Inlet
and Pawleys Island before reaching the historic seaport of
Georgetown, about 40 miles from Conway.
</P>
<P>
   For the next four days, armed with the pocket-size South
Carolina Nature-Based Tourism Directory, I'll explore the natural
amenities and history of the Waccamaw Neck, the land between the
river and the coast, in Horry and Georgetown counties.
</P>
<P>
   I'll marvel at the wondrous marriage of art and nature at
Brookgreen Gardens, a sprawling paradise near Pawleys Island.
Across U.S. 17 at Huntington Beach State Park, I'll wander through
wisteria-draped archways at a 15th-century-style brick Spanish
castle named Atalaya, where Anna Hyatt Huntington created many of
the massive sculptures that grace Brookgreen.
</P>
<P>
   While I prefer to stay at bed-and-breakfast inns (the more
historic and out of the way the better), there are plenty of
hotels, motels, condos, beach houses and campgrounds on and near
U.S. 17 that may work better for families.
</P>
<P>
   Even kids hooked on miniature golf and water parks will no doubt
find adventures of the eco kind to be lots of fun. For instance,
there's Capt. Dick's Saltwater Marsh Explorer, Carolina Safari Jeep
Tours and sailings across Winyah Bay aboard the schooner Jolly
Rover with a pirate guide. And for hands-on action, families can
rent bicycles for a spin under moss-draped live oaks or embark on a
canoe or kayak expedition in tea-colored rivers and cypress swamps.
</P>
<P>
   There's mystery, it seems, around every bend.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent blue-sky Sunday, Virgil Graham steers his bright red
Carolina Safari jeep off busy U.S. 17 and through the gates of
Huntington Beach State Park. He turns our attention to the dense
subtropical forest we are entering, a green tangle of wild
muscadine vines, palm, bladderwort and Venus' flytrap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prehistoric,'' Graham pronounces, almost reverently.
``Prehistoric is how it looks to me. Primeval.''
</P>
<P>
   Passenger Lois Brunetti of New York, who just the night before
partied with friends at the Myrtle Beach House of Blues, gets the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jurassic Park,'' she says, nodding.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
