<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6940 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CAROLINATOUR1S     05-06 1769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAROLINATOUR1STTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    4-Day trip turns back the clock and spotlights the world around
us
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 9.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rivers are dark, the marshes mysterious and the gnarled live
oaks with their filigree of silvery moss hold ancient secrets. The
upper coast of South Carolina, with its natural charms, beckons to
the adventure seeker.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we call nature-based tourism is just outdoor recreation
with a new spin on it,'' says Tim Todd of the 5-year-old South
Carolina Nature-Based Tourism Association.
</P>
<P>
   By any name, it's a compelling reason to wander off the usual
track, as I did on a recent four-day trip.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   Conway, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to pass right by Conway as you speed along U.S.
501 toward Myrtle Beach _ and 50,000 cars do just that each day in
the summer. But if you turn left on Third Avenue just before
crossing the Waccamaw River, you'll discover a tidy little town of
12,000, where massive live oaks have the right of way and a
downtown renaissance has brought trendy restaurants, chic shops,
antiques and art galleries to Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Myrtle Beach, interestingly, was developed as a resort by F.G.
Burroughs of Conway more than a century ago and named by his wife
for the myrtle trees abundant in the area.
</P>
<P>
   I have just enough time to check in at the 2-year-old Cypress
Inn and meet innkeepers Carol and Jim Ruddick before walking to the
Conway Marina to make the 2 p.m. river cruise on the Kingston Lady.
We'll be rolling down the winding Waccamaw, which cuts through a
vast cypress swamp. Capt. Dick Davis is hoping the alligator the
school kids saw on his morning cruise will still be sunning on the
banks of the Waccamaw. ``Musta been 300 pounds,'' Davis says.
</P>
<P>
   As Davis steers his vessel through the deep, dark caramel water
tinted by tannin, he regales his passengers with stories of the
steamship era, the sawmilling industry, Native Americans and
Spanish invaders, and nomadic tribes of 10,000 years ago. He points
out green river turtles (also called cooters) on logs, otter and
beaver, heron and kingfisher, and, yes, that lazy ol' gator.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly an hour down the winding river, we see the restored
plantation home built by Henry Buck of Bucksport, Maine, who
purchased 12,000 acres along the Waccamaw in the 1820s and
established a sawmill and later a shipbuilding business.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the marina, Davis tells us that Conway was founded
in 1735 as Kingston to be a defensive outpost for Charleston a
hundred miles south.
</P>
<P>
   I want to know more, so I strike out with the city's visitor
coordinator Betty Molnar, who has developed several self-guided
tours, including ``A Guide to Some of Our Oldest Citizens,'' the
revered live oaks, whose spreading branches embrace the town and
provide a playhouse for squirrels. (Don't be surprised when the
pavement detours around one of the massive trees.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the most intriguing is the Alligator Oak in the First
United Methodist Church cemetery at Fifth Avenue and Main Street.
Look at the round knot on the trunk as an eye and use your
imagination. Across the street are two more treasured trees in
front of the Horry County Museum (it's pronounced oh-REE). Don't
miss the handmade porcelain dolls representing five women whose
life stories encapsulate the town's history.
</P>
<P>
   Walking tours start at the Conway Area Chamber of Commerce at
Second and Main, where you can pick up a map and guides. The
downtown is compact, so you can easily wander down to the
Riverwalk, stroll Main Street with its boutiques, antique stores
and restaurants, and stop by the Presbyterian Church cemetery
that's on the National Register of Historic Places because of its
Victorian grave statuary featuring sculpted figures of children
sleeping beneath a tabletop.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-room Cypress Inn on Elm Street is the only B&AMP;B in the
historic district, and its location overlooking the Waccamaw is
ideal: The Riverfront Tennis Center is across the street and next
door is the Conway Marina, where you can rent canoes and
paddleboats. Although modern, the three-story inn evokes the 19th
century. The rooms, decorated with antique furnishings and designer
fabrics and wallcoverings, feature Jacuzzi tubs. The front porch,
lined with rockers, overlooks a small private marina. Never-empty
pitchers of lemonade and iced tea await guests.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the locals clamor for tables at the trendy Rivertown
Bistro. Friday night dinner was everything it was cracked up to be:
crawfish au gratin on fried zucchini with roasted sweet red pepper
cream, raspberry salad (mixed greens topped with roasted pecans,
feta cheese and raspberry vinaigrette) and lightly blackened
dolphin on a jalapeno grits cake topped with a blue crab shallot
cream.
</P>
<P>
   I'll work all this off tomorrow, I tell myself.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY MORNING
</P>
<P>
   Murrells Inlet
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at Capt. Dick's Ma-
</P>
<P>
   rina for the Saltwater Marsh Explorer excursion, I promptly
purchase a sweat shirt in the store. I'm ill prepared for the cold
front that's moving through. Not so the Junior Girl Scouts of Troop
20 from Summerville, S.C., who scramble onto the boat in a giggling
mass. A curious brown pelican watches from a post.
</P>
<P>
   Marine biologist Robert Van Buskirk shows off a cannonball
jellyfish he scooped in a net as it floated beside the boat. It
looks like a huge, slick shiitake mushroom. A crab has hitched a
ride under its umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   ``He slimed me,'' says Van Buskirk, as the girls squeal eeeyew
and back away. ``Don't become a marine biologist if you don't like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet hands fly up when Van Buskirk asks for volunteers to stuff
fish parts into the crab trap. Soon, they're all digging in a layer
of muck from the marsh floor, holding up a sort of yucky algae
called dead man's fingers and pursuing skittish hermit crabs.
</P>
<P>
   Van Buskirk tells us the salt marsh is like a big fish nursery,
where puffers, sea robins, skate and pinfish begin their lives. We
have about a half-hour for shelling on a barrier island.
</P>
<P>
   On the way back in, the Girl Scouts chatter about their
adventure. What did 9-year-old Chanelle Davis like? ``The pelican,
the animals, and the ride was smooth. And the gift shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Back onshore, I give in to a powerful craving for _ what else? _
seafood. Capt. Dave's Dockside Restaurant is just yards away. I
polish off a basket of quarter-sized hush puppies and honey butter
before tucking into a divine Lowcountry concoction of shrimp with
sausage and tasso gravy over creamy grits. Neptune never ate so
well.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY AFTERNOON
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown
</P>
<P>
   The sun reappears, but my anticipated afternoon sail on the
Jolly Rover tall ship from Georgetown's pleasant Harbor Walk has
been scrubbed thanks to the unsettled morning weather. So instead,
I hop aboard a green trolley in front of the visitor center on
Front Street for some dry-land cruising around the seaport that was
discovered by the Spanish in 1526 and laid out in 1729 by Elisha
Screven along the Sampit River.
</P>
<P>
   Several early 18th century houses still stand, and many more
date to the 19th century. At least a half-dozen homes in the
National Register Historic District are now bed-and-breakfast inns.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest church is the Prince George Episcopalian, whose first
services were held in 1747 when the church building was under
construction. A 250-year-old live oak presides over the cemetery,
where members of many prominent families are buried.
</P>
<P>
   The 1841 town clock tower on Front Street now houses the Rice
Museum, whose exhibits trace the rise and fall of rice cultivation
on coastal plantations. At the other end of downtown is the
Kaminski House, built in 1769 by a local merchant. It is now a
house museum filled with English and American furniture and
artifacts dating from the late 1700s and significant pieces by
Charleston cabinetmakers of the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1812, Theodosia Burr Allston left Georgetown harbor on the
Patriot to visit her father, Aaron Burr, in New York. The ship was
lost at sea in a violent storm or, some say, sunk by pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her ghost is often seen walking along, retracing her last
steps on earth,'' says trolley guide/driver Glen Morris.
</P>
<P>
   She's but one of the many souls believed to be roaming around
Georgetown County. There's Alice, a young woman who wanders about
looking for her lost engagement ring from the boy her family would
not permit her to marry. And the Gray Man of Pawleys Island, who
perished in a hurricane and now warns tourists to take cover when
storms approach.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield Plantation
</P>
<P>
   A fingernail of a moon hangs low in the eerie black sky as I
drive down a two-mile unpaved road through dense forest, back to
the antebellum rice plantation where I'm spending two nights. I've
been in Georgetown for a dinner of lime-spiked Bahamian grouper and
wild rice at the Rice Paddy overlooking the Sampit River.
</P>
<P>
   Rice. It's a leitmotif throughout the Tidelands. Long-grain rice
turned wealthy planters into Southern aristocrats.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is no longer cultivated in the region's marshes _ it hasn't
been since the late 1920s _ but remnants of 19th-century abundance
remain at Mansfield. An avenue of 160-year-old oaks leads past rows
of slave houses and a slave chapel to the modest plantation house
and its outbuildings, including stables and a winnowing house.
Overnight visitors stay in one of three guest houses and gather in
the formal dining room in the main house for a breakfast served on
good china.
</P>
<P>
   The property, stretching from U.S. 701 to the Black River, is
inhabited by deer, alligators, ducks, woodpeckers, owls and many
other birds.
</P>
<P>
   Sally and Jim Cahalan have owned the plantation since 1994, when
she inherited it from her father, Wilbur Smith. Guests come to
explore the cypress swamps in canoes and kayaks, go duck hunting
with Jim or just settle into a rope hammock or lawn chair to take
in the views of the marshlands.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield's natural setting appeals to four researchers on a
geology field trip from the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution in
Massachusetts. Fossils from limestone samples they dig from Pee Dee
River formations will be used in experiments to help predict
climate changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area was under the ocean at one time,'' says Marti
Jeglinski. ``This is where a lot of those fossils were
distributed.''
</P>
<P>
   And after a day of digging _ or sightseeing, for that matter _
those hammocks look mighty inviting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1521EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6941 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CAROLINATOUR2N     05-06 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAROLINATOUR2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA: look mighty inviting.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Safari
</P>
<P>
   Jumping into the back of Carolina Safari's big red tour Jeep for
a jaunt into the wilds of coastal South Carolina from Myrtle Beach
to Pawleys Island, I feel like a kid at Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   It's fun bouncing down U.S. 17 with naturalist-photographer
Virgil Graham at the wheel. As he drives, the Myrtle Beach native
shares his knowledge of the area's history in a rambling narrative
that touches on Spanish settlement in the 1500s, pirate escapades,
indigo cultivation, salt mines, turpentine production and the
origins of Calabash shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   In Murrells Inlet, we hear the tale of a sailor named Drunken
Jack and the treasure he buried and see in the distance the island
that bears his name. Even though it's not open for lunch, Graham
drives us by the area's oldest seafood restaurant, Oliver's Lodge,
built in 1859 and a dining spot since 1910.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing south, we pull in at the entrance of Brookgreen
Gardens for a bit of background on the world's largest sculpture
garden, established in 1930 by Archer Huntington and his wife,
sculptor Anna Hyatt Huntington. Graham whets my appetite for a
visit the next day.
</P>
<P>
   We cross the highway to Huntington Beach State Park, where the
Huntington's Moorish-style beach retreat Atalaya stands roofless
but still fortress-like, with sturdy brick walls and iron window
bars. Inside the park, we stop to look at alligators sunning on a
small island and observe osprey and cormorants. There, standing in
the spartina grass, is a great white egret in a National
Geographic-worthy pose _ as if he is well aware of the
point-and-shoot cameras aimed his way.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we're on our way to a rice plantation that's now a golf
course and a historic cemetery on Pawleys Island. Graham gives us
his interpretation of the Gullah dialect and spins yarns about
plat-eyes, boo-daddies and haints _ the boogeymen of Gullah
culture.
</P>
<P>
   The cemetery is at All Saints Waccamaw Parish Church,
established 1767. It's the burial site of poet James Dickey
(1923-1997), whose granite tombstone is engraved with the words ``I
move at the heart of the world.'' But most intriguing is the
gravestone of a young woman named Alice, buried in ignominy near
the brothers who disowned her for defying them when they forbade
her to see the man she loved. Someone ha-- left dimes and pennies
on a flat stone with the simple inscription: ALICE.
</P>
<P>
   At the Island Country Store restaurant, where we lunch at picnic
tables under the live oaks, we devour fried grouper sandwiches
while watching boat-tailed grackles help themselves to leftovers at
uncleared tables.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   Brookgreen Gardens
</P>
<P>
   As soon as I enter the gates, I know I've come to a special
place. Even so, I was unprepared for the dramatic impact of this
300-acre botanical garden in the heart of a 9,100-acre preserve
stretching from the Atlantic Ocean to the historic rice fields of
the Waccamaw River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gray Oaks of Mystery,'' a poetic 10-minute video shown in the
Welcome Center, sets the tone for my visit. By the time I reach the
pool with Huntington's graceful sculpture ``Diana of the Chase'' in
the middle, I have become keenly aware that this is a place where
art and nature are in harmonic convergence.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1930, the land that once comprised four rice plantations
has been a natural haven for more than 500 outdoor sculptures, many
created by Anna Hyatt Huntington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knew this was back here?'' exclaims Norma Benton of Kansas
City, echoing the sentiment of many awed visitors. ``We've been
coming to Myrtle Beach for years and had seen the sculpture at the
entrance, but we had no idea it would be this wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Brookgreen isn't exactly a secret. The first public sculpture
garden built in the United States, it is listed on the National
Register of Historic Places and is a National Historic Landmark.
</P>
<P>
   From the Diana fountain, an allee of 250-year-old live oaks
leads to a series of connecting gardens, designed by the
Huntingtons in the shape of a butterfly, as a backdrop for Anna's
sculptures. Soon, other sculptors _ Daniel Chester French, Gutzon
Borglum, Frederic Remington _ were invited to exhibit pieces from
small to monumental among the plant collection of 2,000 species.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the outdoor displays, there are two indoor
exhibits in the Rainey Sculpture Pavilion: ``Birds of a Feather:
Sculpture From the Brookgreen Collection'' and ``The Sculpture of
Grainger McKoy,'' a temporary exhibit that will be up through the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The gardens are also designated as a wildlife sanctuary; 194
species of birds have been identified. The Lowcountry Wildlife
Trail north of the formal gardens offers visitors the chance to see
native wildlife in natural habitats along a paved three-quarter
mile path. There is a cypress aviary, otter pond, alligator swamp,
fox glade, raptor aviary and white-tailed deer savanna.
</P>
<P>
   I buy a ticket for a one-hour creek excursion on the 48-foot
pontoon boat Springfield (on weekends, two-hour cruises past Sandy
Island and 18th- and 19th-century plantation houses on the Waccamaw
are offered). Guide Lucius Fishburne explains that we are floating
on canals dug by slaves, taking advantage of the twice daily tidal
fluctuations to flood and drain the rice fields.
</P>
<P>
   On this brief cruise, we see an alligator swimming near the
dock, a turtle that ducks when he sees the gator coming, a great
blue heron and an osprey tending its nest. Wooden boxes on posts
have been erected along the creekside as wood duck habitats.
</P>
<P>
   Plan to spend a full day or more (the admission ticket is good
for seven days). There is a shady picnic area near serene Jessamine
Pond as well as the Terrace Cafe, featuring a light menu of
sandwiches, salads and she-crab soup, and the Old Kitchen,
specializing in pastries and hot or cold Carolina peach tea.
</P>
<P>
   Too soon it is closing time. I should have arrived earlier. Four
hours is not nearly long enough to linger in this beauty.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Litchfield Plantation
</P>
<P>
   Good thing I am staying at this very elegant, very Southern
country inn on my last night on the coast. If it had been early in
the trip, it would have been tough to tear myself away for anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Pat and Bea Boland of New Canaan, Conn., were feeling
a couple of days into a weeklong vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been thinking about driving down to Charleston,'' says
Pat, after lingering at least an hour over breakfast at the
Carriage House Club, ``but . . . I don't know. I came here to relax
and I just don't want to go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's so much to do inside the gates of the former
rice plantation on Pawleys Island. Tennis courts and a swimming
pool are about it. But the lush natural setting invites indolence:
long strolls on the sweeping green lawns. Drinks on the patio as
sunset drops a pink scrim behind the gray-bearded live oaks beside
the lazy creek. Naps in a big canopied bed.
</P>
<P>
   The original 1750 plantation house, a stately three-story
mansion painted white with black shutters, stands at the end of a
quarter-mile allee of live oaks. A guest house and cottages are
tucked away on these 600 acres sprawling from King's River Road to
the Waccamaw River. A private oceanfront beach house for the use of
guests is about three miles away.
</P>
<P>
   This four-star restaurant is known for creative cuisine in a
clubby atmosphere. A mixed grill of salmon, grouper and beef
tenderloin served with _ you guessed it _ rice was perfect. The
tastiest lemon chess pie I've had in years topped the repast.
</P>
<P>
   Walking back to the mansion, which I had all to myself that
night, I recall the story of a former owner, Dr. Henry M. Tucker,
who made sickbed calls at night. Returning, he would ring the
gatehouse bell with his riding crop. After his death, subsequent
owners of the plantation reported hearing the ringing. Finally, the
bell was removed so they could get some rest.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of long days adventuring in nature, today's guests do
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
