A6942 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SOUTH-PREDISNE     05-06 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SOUTH-PREDISNEY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Before Disney, Southern vacations were a magical mystery tour of
tacky, tawdry delights
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 9.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucky for Tim Hollis that his father was such a pack rat. The
old man never tossed anything from their family vacations: road
maps, postcards, tourist brochures, bumper stickers, motel
matchbooks. He even kept their parking stub from the grand opening
of Six Flags Over Georgia in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Hollis has made loving use of the memorabilia in a new book,
``Dixie Before Disney: 100 Years of Roadside Fun'' (University
Press of Mississippi, $25). Part history, part nostalgia trip, the
oversize paperback documents the era of tourism that faded when
Walt Disney World reared its mighty mouse ears in 1971 and made
everything before seem puny.
</P>
<P>
   As Hollis tells it, the South pioneered tourism American-style.
Natural Bridge, Va., was drawing visitors in the 1700s. (Thomas
Jefferson, who once owned the property, built a cabin for visitors,
making him arguably one of the first tourist court operators.) Hot
Springs, Ark., was designated a federal preserve decades before
Yellowstone. Silver Springs, Fla., was so popular in the 1800s that
two former Union generals, Grant and Sherman, braved hostile
territory to see it _ even without glass-bottom boats.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollis' heart belongs to the 1960s and the roadscape of his
youth. The 36-year-old Birmingham native never got over his first
Howard Johnson's sign; the neon figures of Simple Simon and the Pie
Man seemed to beckon him. He remembers family drives to the beach
and the mountains as a child's delight of flashing marquees, pecan
logs, wax museums and alligator farms. Slow two-lane highways and
shoddy motel rooms are mercifully forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, everyone drove on their vacations, so you had all
these places that were designed to make the trip fun,'' Hollis
says. ``Now more people fly. The trip doesn't matter as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollis, an editor at a small publishing company in Birmingham,
has taken after his late father. He still enjoys driving vacations,
most recently to Gatlinburg, Tenn. And, like his dad, he hangs on
to everything; when Six Flags closed its ``Tales of the
Okefenokee'' ride, he went so far as to dub the soundtrack so he'd
have a recording of the goofy song.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite vacation spots? Rock City and any miniature golf
course with concrete dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   His choice for tackiest tourist trap? It's a tie between two
defunct enterprises: Gatlinburg's ``Tour Through Hell,'' a biblical
house of horrors, and Sarasota's Floridaland, which boasted so many
attractions in one place that visitors were told they could skip
the rest of the Sunshine State. (The concept lives on in Orlando.)
</P>
<P>
   For all his roaming, Hollis has missed a few places that he
memorializes in the book. His biggest regret is that he never made
it to Dogpatch USA, an Arkansas theme park based on the ``Li'l
Abner'' comic strip and a passel of half-witted hillbilly
stereotypes. By the time he got to the Ozarks, hit done closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go back to the site,'' Hollis says. ``Maybe
there's a petrified Li'l Abner sitting out there waiting for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
