<SLUG> BC-WORKSHOP-FANS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ceiling fans now easier to install than ever
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even if a home has a good air conditioning system, a ceiling fan
can be invaluable when it's muggy outside but not hot enough for
cold air.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers have simplified the task of installing ceiling
fans by designing units that require little assembly. Just make
sure the fan includes all the necessary parts.
</P>
<P>
   Jabari Cook, a lighting expert at Home Depot on Cumberland
Parkway, says a standard 8-foot ceiling fan can be installed in
about an hour. Beginners, however, should allot at least 2 1/2
hours to be on the safe side.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the supplies you'll need in addition to the ceiling
fan:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Phillips screwdriver
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A flathead screwdriver
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A package of orange or yellow wire nuts
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A flashlight (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Before you begin:
</P>
<P>
   Turn off the light switch in the room where the fan is to be
installed and the main power switch, to avoid electric shock.
Remove the existing light fixture to expose the junction box and
ceiling wires.
</P>
<P>
   Installing the fan:
</P>
<P>
   (Not pictured.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove all parts from the fan box and insert rubber bushings
into each fan blade. Make sure the bushings are tight, to prevent
the fan from wobbling.
</P>
<P>
   1.
</P>
<P>
   Using a Phillips screwdriver, remove screws on the fan motor;
then insert screws into the fan blades.
</P>
<P>
   2.
</P>
<P>
   Line up the blades with the screw holes and reinsert the screws
that were removed in Step 2. Make sure each blade is screwed
tightly to the motor.
</P>
<P>
   3.
</P>
<P>
   After all fan blades are secured, screw the fan rod to the base
of the fan, making sure the wires are free of tangles. Set aside
until the hanger bracket is installed.
</P>
<P>
   4.
</P>
<P>
   Screw the hanger bracket into the junction box. Make sure it is
screwed in tightly.
</P>
<P>
   4a. (Not pictured.)
</P>
<P>
   Pick up the fan motor with attached blades and let it hang on
the side of the hanger bracket. (A little hook is attached to it to
make installation a one-person job.) Twist each wire from the
junction box clockwise around each fan wire, matching colors. For
example, the black wire from the junction box should be spliced to
the black wire of the fan, etc.)
</P>
<P>
   5.
</P>
<P>
   After the wires are connected, screw the fan rod, which extends
from the center of the fan base, into the hanger bracket. Screw the
canopy to the hanger bracket. At this point, the fan should be
securely mounted to the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   6.
</P>
<P>
   To connect the light fixture to the fan, twist the wires from
the light fixture to the fan wires. Again, going clockwise, twist
like colors together. Fold wires at the splice and attach a wire
nut.
</P>
<P>
   Final step:
</P>
<P>
   Screw the light fixture to the fan by lining up holes. Fit the
glass globes over the light sockets and tighten. Turn the power
back on.
</P>
<P>
   7.
</P>
<P>
   Hit the switch, turn on the fan and take a breather.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth installment in our Spring Workshop series, a
step-by-step guide to doing inexpensive weekend projects for the
home or garden. If there's a project you'd like to suggest or you
want more information about this series, call 404-222-8689 or send
an e-mail to dflanders(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
