<SLUG> BC-FARE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FARE GAMES': A FEW TIPS ON A COUPLE OF NEW YORK CABBIES WHO ARE
NOT HAILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No pun intended, but the tale of two cabbies called ``Fare
Games'' is pedestrian.
</P>
<P>
   No particular wit or style or particularly insightful
storytelling gifts emerge from this straightforward account of two
friends who drive cabs in the streets of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the misadventures that befall them, like cheap
tippers, nasty fares, deviant passengers and a stickup, clearly
typify life behind the wheel of a yellow cab, ``Fare Games,''
written and directed by Brian O'Hara, never really captures the
pace or essence of the city in relating a familiar story.
</P>
<P>
   Its principal roles are acceptably acted, for the most part, but
some of the lesser portrayals are far from elegant examples of the
actor's art.
</P>
<P>
   One of the cabbies, the tall, good-looking Jimmy (Eddie
Estefan), a long-married suburbanite and father of two children who
are away at summer camp, is eager for more sex than he is getting
at home. The other cabbie, Martin (Russel Stewart), balding,
divorced, with an adolescent daughter who lives far away with her
mother, has no woman in his life.
</P>
<P>
   As the screenplay has it, Jimmy's wildest fantasies come true
when one of his fares turns out to be a young and easily available
new arrival to the city _ a college student who just happens to be
occupying a home (with pool) in Riverdale while her aunt and uncle
are away.
</P>
<P>
   And late one night, Martin's fare turns out to be Susie
(Elizabeth Curtain), a topless dancer in her 20s who first asks him
to pick her up on a regular basis and then accepts his offer of
shelter when her refusal to dance nude costs her her job.
</P>
<P>
   So while Jimmy is frolicking the nights away with Jennifer
(Marina Morgan) and telling preposterous stories about his
whereabouts to his wife, Barbara (Andre Leigh), Martin is
proceeding tentatively into a serious relationship with Susie.
</P>
<P>
   In their regular meetings over lunch in a diner, Martin warns
the smitten Jimmy that his fling is really a flirtation with
marital disaster. Meanwhile the suspicious Barbara, briefed by one
of her frequently divorced girlfriends, is preparing to trap Jimmy
into a confession.
</P>
<P>
   And, the insecure Martin is beginning to believe that his
happiness with Susie is doomed to be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fare Games'' may be drawn from life, but it is not drawn with
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `FARE GAMES'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Brian O'Hara, based on a story by Isaac
Agami; director of photography, Larry Revene; edited by Kevin
O'Hara; music by TAJ; produced by Agami; released by Edison Agami
Films. Running time: 90 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Eddie Estefan (Jimmy), Russel Stewart (Martin), Elizabeth
Curtain (Susie), Marina Morgan (Jennifer) and Andre Leigh
(Barbara). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
