<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUSHER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PUSHER': A DRUG PUSHER'S LIFE IS ROTTEN IN DENMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Trainspotting'' was a darkly thrilling film about the lives of
Scottish heroin addicts. ``Pulp Fiction'' was a brilliantly
original look into petty criminals' lives, including heroin sale
and use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pusher,'' a new Danish film, is proof of just how boring a
week in the life of a real heroin dealer probably is.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, the film's young director and co-screenwriter,
Nicolas Winding Refn, talks a lot about how proud he is of not
having gone to film school, and how his father _ the film editor
Anders Refn, who worked on, among other things, ``Breaking the
Waves'' _ thought he was insane to try to make a movie without any
training. But he did it, and isn't he clever?
</P>
<P>
   Refn has indeed made a movie. It opens with a drug dealer named
Frank (Kim Bodnia) and his buddy Tonny (Mads Mikkelsen) driving
through parts of Copenhagen with no scenic beauty at all and
discussing how much they enjoy fellatio and other, less
conventional sexual practices.
</P>
<P>
   That's Monday. On Tuesday, Frankie gets a big drug order from a
Swedish customer but has trouble getting the product from his
supplier because he owes him money. On Wednesday, Frankie and Tonny
talk some more about fellatio, as well as whether they should go to
a movie or rent a video.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, Frankie makes the sale, but before he can
collect the money, the police arrive. On Thursday Frankie wakes up
in a jail cell. It's downhill from there. At one point, he is
driven to the lowest of lows: asking his mother for money.
</P>
<P>
   For almost two hours, ``Pusher'' seems to be saying: look how
honest and dirty and real we're being, look how we're showing you
the dark underbelly of the world that addiction has made. This
might be effective if the last drug movie in theaters had been
``The Man With the Golden Arm'' (in which Kim Novak helps Frank
Sinatra kick heroin by locking him in a room and hiding the sharp
cutlery). More than 40 years later, it seems almost naive.
</P>
<P>
   But Refn may yet have justification for boasting about his
natural talent. There is one magnificent scene in ``Pusher'' in
which Frankie and his girlfriend, Vic (Laura Drasbaek), come back
to her apartment in a late-night early-morning haze, do drugs
separately and exude a horrible raw loneliness that is painful, but
illuminating, to see. Maybe Refn's next film will take us into that
emotional territory.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `PUSHER'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Nicolas Winding Refn; written (in Danish, with
English subtitles) by Refn and Jens Dahl; director of photography,
Morten Soborg; edited by Anne Osterud; music by Peter Peter and
Povl Kristian Mortensen; production designer, Kim Lovetand
Julebaek; produced by Henrik Danstrup; released by First Run
Features. Running time: 105 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Kim Bodnia (Frank), Zlatko Buric (Milo), Laura Drasbaek
(Vic), Slavko Labovic (Radovan), Mads Mikkelsen (Tonny) and Peter
Anderson (Hasse).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1539EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
