<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONEWARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE WARS: COMPETITORS AT&AMP;T, BELL HAVE LOTS AT STAKE IN
DEREGULATION BILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAX B. BAKER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Southwestern Bell says AT&AMP;T will take its profits back
East if it wins the Texas telephone war. AT&AMP;T says Bell charges
consumers too much to make calls from Midland to Marfa.
</P>
<P>
   But when a telephone deregulation bill is approved by a House
committee in a few days, don't expect AT&AMP;T, Bell or any other Texas
phone company to claim victory.
</P>
<P>
   Bitter disputes over a bill co-sponsored by state Rep. Toby
Goodman, R-Arlington, are expected to continue as lawmakers try to
make a connection on legislation that they hope will cut telephone
bills, improve service and boost competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has more spin doctors than a presidential
campaign,'' said Goodman, who spent hours co-writing the bill.
``But they are spending tens of millions of dollars on television
because this is a big business deal.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest telecommunication bill to be considered by
Texas lawmakers. The House State Affairs Committee is expected to
vote on it early next week.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is a rewrite of legislation approved by the Senate last
month, and Goodman is a co-author with state Rep. Leticia Van de
Putte, D-San Antonio. The 43-page bill is so complex that Goodman
admits he's been ``going nuts'' over it.
</P>
<P>
   Although time is running out on the legislative session _ it
ends this month _ Rep. Sylvester Turner, the Houston Democrat who
is vice chairman of the State Affairs Committee, predicted that the
House telephone bill will be based on Goodman's version.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, Van de Putte and Rep. Kim Brimer, the Arlington
Republican who is a member of the State Affairs Committee, were to
explain the bill to representatives of the telephone industry and
consumer groups on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman and Van de Putte said their bill is the next step in
telephone deregulation efforts initiated by the House in 1995. That
legislation, which froze local and intrastate access rates, expires
in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should decrease your bill if you make (intrastate)
long-distance calls,'' Goodman said. ``This is not a bill that
should increase the cost of telephone service.''
</P>
<P>
   After members of the State Affairs Committee raised concerns
that their bill gave too much to Southwestern Bell, Goodman and Van
de Putte included additional amendments making it tougher on the
telephone giant.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of the rates charged by Southwestern Bell are
capped, and the bill forces the company to absorb up to $38 million
a year in providing telephone services to public institutions such
as hospitals and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   During lengthy committee hearings, Van de Putte defended the
bill, saying Bell didn't ask her to write legislation that allowed
the state to take ``$300 million out of (Bell's) pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not enjoyed at all just the slightest inference that
I'm carrying water for Bell. ... I have not enjoyed that,'' said
Van de Putte, who has been accused of protecting Bell, which has
its corportate headquarters in San Antonio and provides telephone
service to about 77 percent of Texas consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Bell is not pleased with everything in the bill, said David
Cole, president of Southwestern Bell-Texas. But being able to
package its services, as they could not before, makes the measure
palatable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm giving up $300 million; that's a significant financial hit
for us,'' Cole said. ``But if we are able to compete in the same
manner as our competitors are, that's what we are interested in
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending millions of dollars over more than two years
asking for a reduction in access fees, AT&AMP;T officials also are not
happy with the measure.
</P>
<P>
   A grassroots coalition formed by AT&AMP;T, Partnership for a
Competitive Texas, paid for the ads featuring ``Carolyn.'' She
complains that a call from Midland to Marfa costs more than a phone
call to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T wanted the Legislature to do nothing, which would have
allowed the PUC to take control of the rates being charged, said
Vaughn Aldredge, vice president for government affairs at AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   When it appeared that lawmakers were convinced they needed to do
something, AT&AMP;T agreed to the Senate bill allowing Southwestern
Bell less flexibility in setting prices and in packaging its
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with the changes, this bill is extremely favorable to
Southwestern Bell and GTE. There is not a balance here yet,''
Aldredge said. ``We thought the Senate bill struck a delicate
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller, independent telephone companies also want to disconnect
Goodman's bill, saying they are getting caught in a squeeze to
please Bell and AT&AMP;T. Allowing Southwestern Bell pricing
flexibility will destroy competition, they say.
</P>
<P>
   They say Goodman's bill will ``emasculate'' the PUC and allow
deregulation of an industry that still needs some regulating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tantamount to giving Bell nuclear weapons'' when you
allow Bell and the other telecommunication giants to operate
unregulated, said Royce Holland, chief executive officer of
Allegiance Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups also wonder what, if any, benefit Texans will
see.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not about saving anybody any money. It's about
which of those companies get their money,'' said Janee
Briesemeister, senior policy analyst at Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Major components of the proposed telephone deregulation bill:
</P>
<P>
   _Limits local and residential basic telephone rates along with
those for call waiting and digital services at current rates until
September 2005, when the state Public Utility Commission will
determine the rates.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, those rates are $9.75 monthly for basic residential
services and about $28 for essential services used by most
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   _Limits what Bell can charge for Caller ID, call return, voice
mail, call forwarding and other services until it enters the
long-distance market or until July 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   _Grants Bell and GTE the authority to introduce new services and
to ``bundle,'' or offer promotional packages. Previously, state law
has prohibited the companies from ``bundling'' because they are
monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   _Establishes how much Bell or GTE can charge to protect
consumers from predatory pricing.
</P>
<P>
   _Reduces access fees on intrastate long-distance phone calls
from 11.36 cents to 8.36 cents per minute in Bell's service
territory. Bell would lose an estimated $300 million in annual
revenue under this provision.
</P>
<P>
   _Mandates a simpler phone bill that lists three basic charges:
basic, optional, and taxes and surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
