<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTLE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CASTLE': A RHINESTONE THAT'S WORTH FIGHTING FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A man's home is his you-know-what, even if that home is only a
dilapidated eyesore built on toxic landfill and separated by a
chain-link fence from an airport runway.
</P>
<P>
   But as they say, it's all in the eye of the beholder. And to
Darryl Kerrigan (Michael Caton), a happy-go-lucky tow-truck driver
and hero of ``The Castle,'' this property is nothing less than an
irreplaceable little patch of heaven on earth, a storehouse of
golden memories.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl and his unflappably cheery brood (he has a wife,
daughter, three sons and several pet greyhounds) are this
Australian movie's sentimentalized version of a John Waters family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Castle,'' a feel-good comic fairy tale that flashes its
family values like an oversize rhinestone bracelet, finds Darryl
enlisting his neighbors in a campaign to save their homes from
demolition when the airport decides to expand. Shortly after an
official appears to assess the area's property values, the
Kerrigans are informed that their house has become a ``compulsory
acquisition'' with a buyout price of $70,000. Darryl decides to
fight back, resisting first bribery, then intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, those wacky, tacky Kerrigans! The movie (and its soundtrack
of smile-button '70s hits like ``We've Only Just Begun'' and ``Make
It With You'') continually dares us to sneer at their garish tastes
and naive assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   As the assessor inspects his home, Darryl proudly points out the
fake chimney, plastic trim and giant television antenna as major
enhancements. Inside is a pool room stuffed with tchotchkes
(including a recently acquired Franklin Mint beer mug) that Darryl
views as priceless heirlooms.
</P>
<P>
   In Darryl's rose-colored view, the Kerrigans have the best of
all possible lives. Each night he rapturously oohs and ahs over the
meatloaf and chicken casseroles served by his pretty, perky wife,
Sal (Anne Tenney).
</P>
<P>
   One evening, when he asks her what she did to make the ice cream
so delicious, she replies, ``I scooped it out of the tub.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kerrigans also maintain a dingy summer cottage beside a grim
little lake overlooked by high-voltage power lines. Taking a deep
breath of summer air after a day spent in a motorboat fishing for
carp, Darryl exhales contentedly and rhapsodizes over the fragrant
fumes of diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
   If ``The Castle'' is essentially a one-joke movie, the sheer
giddy stamina with which it insists on the Kerrigans' joie de vivre
keeps it afloat. For his initial courtroom skirmish, Darryl engages
Dennis Denuto (Tiriel Mora) a local lawyer of spectacular
incompetence and naivete.
</P>
<P>
   In the wittiest scene, this bumbling idiot argues to a
hard-boiled judge that ``the vibes'' of Australia's Constitution
support Darryl's cause.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl ultimately finds a fairy godfather in Lawrence Hammill,
an eloquent retired constitutional lawyer played by Charles (Bud)
Tidwell whom he encounters by chance outside the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, ``The Castle'' begins to curdle in its own
lurking sentimentality. What is the value of a house versus the
value of a home? Ah, yes, be it ever so humble, and all that. But
``The Castle'' moves along nimbly enough to keep from settling into
a pudding that even Darryl, in all his gastronomic innocence,
couldn't stomach.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Castle'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It has some mildly strong language.
</P>
<P>
   `THE CASTLE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rob Sitch; written by Santo Cilauro, Tom Gleisner,
Jane Kennedy and Sitch; director of photography, Miriana Marusic;
edited by Wayne Hyett; music by Craig Harnath; production designer,
Carrie Kennedy; produced by Debra Choate; released by Miramax.
Running time: 85 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Michael Caton (Darryl Kerrigan), Anne Tenney (Sal
Kerrigan), Stephen Curry (Dale Kerrigan), Anthony Simcoe (Steve
Kerrigan), Sophie Lee (Tracey Kerrigan), Tiriel Mora (Dennis
Denuto) and Charles (Bud) Tingwell (Lawrence Hammill).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
