<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7000 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIRROR-FILM-REVIEW-NY     05-06 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRROR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE EMPTY MIRROR': HITLER MEETS FREUD ON A BLOOD-RED COUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adolf Hitler may have been many things, but it seems unlikely
that he was the colossal bore portrayed in the hyperthyroid
hodgepodge of pseudo-psychotherapy called ``The Empty Mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   This film appears to proceed on the assumption that if the
screen is splattered with enough images of a ranting actor,
documentary film footage of the Nazi era and World War II, torrents
of viscous blood, Aryan Rhinemaidens out of a fever dream,
suggestions of sexual dysfunction and youthful trauma, a brunette
brandishing a dagger and a jailer ominously tapping a club,
Hitler's psyche will be laid as bare as a nut from its shell.
</P>
<P>
   To help matters along, toss in lots of flames, the sage of
Vienna, Sigmund Freud, and an assortment of Richard Wagner's
greatest hits.
</P>
<P>
   In a perverse kind of historical justice, the petard that hoists
this misguided project is the Fuhrer himself. Seen in clips from
Leni Riefenstahl's notorious documentary ``Triumph of the Will,''
the charismatic Hitler who bent a nation to his purpose
effortlessly pales poor Norman Rodway, the English actor whose
misfortune is to be saddled with trying to reveal history with
histrionics.
</P>
<P>
   Trapped in this film, directed by Barry J. Hershey from a
screenplay by Hershey and R. Buckingham, are Joel Grey, playing
Josef Goebbels as a cross between a simpering sycophant and a
talking history text for those who came late to the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Shadix perpetuates the image of Hermann Goring as the
Fatso in a perception of Nazism as some sort of comic opera. Doug
McKeon plays the pitiable military typist who has to listen to
Hitler's logorrhea as he dictates his memoirs, and the Swedish
actress Camilla Soeberg portrays Eva Braun.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Empty Mirror'' much style delivers little substance.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE EMPTY MIRROR' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Barry J. Hershey; written by Hershey and R.
Buckingham; director of photography, Frederick Elmes; edited by
Marc Grossman; music by John Frizzell; production designer, Tim
Colohan; produced by David D. Johnson, M. Jay Roach and William
Dance; released by Lions Gate Films. Running time: 119 minutes.
This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Norman Rodway (Adolf Hitler), Camilla Soeberg (Eva Braun),
Peter Michael Goetz (Sigmund Freud), Doug McKeon (Typist), Glenn
Shadix (Hermann Goring) and Joel Grey (Josef Goebbels).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FATHER-FILM-REVIEW-NY     05-06 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THIS IS MY FATHER': A FAMILY STORY _ IN MORE WAYS THAN ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This Is My Father'' follows a Chicago schoolteacher and his
teen-age nephew back to their Irish homeland, where the latter
strikes the fancy of a couple of schoolgirls. ``Is it true every
American has a gun?'' they ask him jokingly. And: ``Do you know any
murderers?'' The boy mentions an acquaintance who shot and killed a
teacher in math class. This scene may mean to be facetious, but it
stands out painfully in the midst of an otherwise gentle,
picturesque romance.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed with obvious sincerity by Paul Quinn,
``This Is My Father'' casts a glum James Caan as an Irish-American
in search of his roots, with Jacob Tierney as his engaging nephew.
Then it flashes back to 1939, when the family was much more
interesting. The story centers on the romance between pretty,
impetuous 17-year-old Fiona Flynn (Moya Farrelly) and a shy
orphaned farmer who is several years her senior. In the village
where the film takes place, the farmer is discussed so dismissively
that ``the likes of Kieran O'Day'' seems to be his full name.
</P>
<P>
   Kieran O'Day is played with conviction by Aidan Quinn, the
director's brother, in a film that is as much a family story as the
one told onscreen. The cinematographer is a third Quinn brother,
Declan, whose triumphs include ``Leaving Las Vegas'' and ``Vanya on
42nd Street.'' This time, he gives the Irish landscape a deep-hued
radiance, in contrast to the drab Chicago scenes that open the
story.
</P>
<P>
   All three brothers are co-executive producers of Paul's first
feature. They give a knowing wink to the stock Irish figures who
abound here, and also give this tale the doomy inevitability of an
Irish ballad.
</P>
<P>
   Armed only with a snapshot of his mother and her unknown beau,
the teacher arrives at a bed-and-breakfast and persuades an aged
fortuneteller (Moira Deady) to give him clues to his father's
identity. The old woman introduces the film's main story in a long,
enveloping flashback. She explains how Kieran O'Day was a tenant
farmer on land owned by Fiona's malevolent mother (Gina Moxley),
and how the mother fought to keep Fiona away from him. The
fortuneteller also manages to summon many details about village
life, from the memory of a dance at the temperance hall to the way
Fiona was called ``Hussy!'' by disapproving neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   By way of bringing the community to life, the film casts some
stellar Irish actors in what are essentially cameo roles. Colm
Meaney does his usual scene-stealing as the fortuneteller's happily
conniving son, while Brendan Gleeson has only the tiny role of a
local policeman. Stephen Rea, as a visiting priest who means to
reprimand Fiona and Kieran for their flirtation, solemnly satirizes
a clergyman too interested in his parishioners' carnal secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The film sometimes uses its cameos too desperately, as when John
Cusack turns up in a seaplane. He plays a Life magazine
photographer who arrives to take a picture of the lovers at just
the right moment.
</P>
<P>
   The film's taste for such coincidences winds up diminishing the
power of its final revelations. And events that ought to prompt
strong emotion begin feeling like plot contrivances too.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the actors, especially Aidan Quinn, move through this story
in quietly impassioned style and do what they can to override its
hackneyed elements. In its heartfelt, slightly awkward way, ``This
Is My Father'' means to be as evocative as the romantic old
photograph that sets it in motion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THIS IS MY FATHER'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Paul Quinn; director of photography,
Declan Quinn; edited by Glenn Berman; music by Donal Lunny;
production designer, Frank Conway; produced by Nicolas Clermont and
Philip King; released by Sony Pictures Classics.
</P>
<P>
   With: James Caan (Kieran Johnson), Jacob Tierney (Jack), Colm
Meaney (Seamus), Moira Deady (Mrs. Kearney), Aidan Quinn (Kieran
O'Day), Moya Farrelly (Fiona Flynn), Gina Moxley (the Widow Flynn),
Stephen Rea (Father Quinn), John Cusack (Eddie Sharp) and Brendan
Gleeson (Officer Jim).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 120 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is My Father'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes mild cursing and very brief
sexual situations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
