<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIRL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      05-06 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SENT DOWN GIRL': RELEGATED TO THE HINTERLANDS, A CHINESE
GIRL'S SPIRIT IS BATTERED BY THE REVOLUTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Xiu Xiu: The Sent Down Girl,'' a tragic story spun out of
China's Cultural Revolution, has irritated the Chinese authorities
not just because it was made surreptitiously and without official
approval, but because of its damning assessment of Mao Zedong's
grandiose experiment in mass indoctrination.
</P>
<P>
   That radical exercise in social engineering, conducted from 1966
to 1976, involved the relocation of nearly eight million Chinese
young people from cities to the country's remote provinces for
specialized (often agricultural) training.
</P>
<P>
   A major goal was to eradicate lingering class distinctions by
forcing everyone to join the proletarian labor force. The film
portrays that experiment as a colossal failure, ineptly carried out
and steeped in corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by the Chinese actress Joan Chen, who adapted the
screenplay with Yan Geling from Ms. Yan's novella ``Tian Yu''
(``Celestial Bath''), ``Xiu Xiu'' is not explicitly
autobiographical, even though Ms. Chen, a respected Chinese
actress, grew up in China during those years.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Wen Xiu (nicknamed Xiu Xiu), a tailor's teen-age
daughter transported from her home city of Chengdu to the Tibetan
plains to learn horse herding, is narrated by a young male admirer
whom Xiu Xiu meets shortly before her departure. In his account of
her life, pieced together from anecdotes, Xiu Xiu's fate assumes an
almost operatic fatefulness.
</P>
<P>
   Xiu Xiu's equestrian training is supposed to prepare her for
membership in the Iron Girls' Cavalry. But during the time she
spends on the plains living in a tent with her teacher and guide,
Lao Jin (Lopsang), she spends a lot more time gazing into a
kaleidoscope the young man gave her than on learning to tame
horses.
</P>
<P>
   A silent loner and true nomad, emasculated during the war with
Tibet, Lao Jin has only two possessions: a cheap, battered portable
radio that he rarely plays and a gold tooth made from his mother's
melted-down earrings.
</P>
<P>
   On the day her six-month training period is to end, Xiu Xiu
(pronounced ``show show'') dresses up and waits for a local
administrator to appear and accompany her home. But no one comes.
More days pass.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, a handsome peddler arrives and gives her the
discouraging news that the girls' cavalry has been disbanded and
that only young people who are politically well-connected have been
allowed to return home.
</P>
<P>
   After promising to use his connections at the local headquarters
to help Xiu Xiu, he seduces her and departs the next day. Xiu Xiu
eagerly awaits his return. But instead of coming back, he directs a
succession of soldiers and bureaucrats to her tent where they take
advantage of her desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the months together, Xiu Xiu and Lao Jin have developed a
silent, deepening bond that is sealed in one final, courageous act
of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is a secondhand tale told by someone imagining what
happened, the harsher aspects of the story are softened by the
movie's allegorical perspective. As much as the film sympathizes
with Xiu Xiu's plight, it never delves into her soul.
</P>
<P>
   The rigors of the climate and of Xiu Xiu's austere outdoor life
are de-emphasized by the film, which prefers to drink in the
desolate beauty of the landscape and to concentrate on symbolic
visual portents. The demure poetic distance the film maintains from
its brutal physical facts mutes the impact of the story. Instead of
devastating, ``Xiu Xiu'' is merely sad. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Xiu Xiu: The Sent Down Girl'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent of adult guardian). It includes sexual
situations and nudity. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XIU XIU: THE SENT DOWN GIRL
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Joan Chen; written (in Mandarin, with English
subtitles) by Yan Geling and Ms. Chen, based on the novella ``Tian
Yu'' by Ms. Yan; director of photography, Lu Yue; edited by Ruby
Yang; music by Johnny Chen; production designer, Pan Lai; produced
by Alice Chan and Ms. Chen; released by Stratosphere Entertainment.
Running time: 99 minutes. This film is rated R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Lu Lu (Xiu Xiu), Lopsang (Lao Jin), Gao Jie (Mother), Li
Qianqian (Sister), Lu Yue (Father) and Qiao Qian (Chen Li). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1620EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7036 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-1000(     05-06 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: PLEASE DON'T PET THE CHINESE DRAGON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans see animals as pets. The Chinese see them as
everything else: emblems of the four directions of the compass and
symbols of longevity, good luck, protection and love of virtue.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have been molding, carving or painting real and
mythical animals since the Neolithic period, circa 6500 to 1700
B.C. In a recent show, ``China: 5,000 Years,'' the Guggenheim
Museum displayed jade birds and pig-dragon ornaments from the
Hongshan culture (3600 to 2000 B.C.) and elephants and rams
adorning bronze pots from the Shang period (1600 to 1100 B.C.).
</P>
<P>
   On Friday Christie's Los Angeles is holding an auction, ``Myth
and Reality: Animals in Chinese Art,'' which includes a
three-legged Shang bronze vessel decorated with dragons and
cicadas. The piece is one of 112 lots that Christie's Chinese-art
specialist, Michael Hughes, has assembled, with, he said, ``animals
in a variety of media from various periods.'' The jade, bronze,
porcelain and painted animals all share one attribute: charm.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary E. Scott, a former professor of Chinese art at London
University who is now a consultant to Christie's in London, said in
an interview: ``Animals were important to the Chinese from the very
early times. Animals were not only to hunt with or provide food;
they were also seen as symbolic. They were tied to ritual and
sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the Bronze Age, animals are seen as intermediaries between
humans and the spirit world. Animals were guardians of the soul.''
</P>
<P>
   In the catalog for the sale, Ms. Scott writes: ``Animals and
birds are frequently symbols in Chinese culture, and no distinction
is made between real animals and those of mythological origin. The
creatures of the Chinese zodiac, for instance, include 11 real
animals: rat, ox, tiger, hare, snake, horse, goat, monkey, cock,
dog and pig, with one mythological animal: the dragon.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that dragons and cicadas decorate the bronze
vessel in the sale. ``Dragons are always good,'' Ms. Scott said in
the interview. ``They become a symbol of the emperor and power
later on. They scare away bad things.'' The cicada symbolizes
immortality and resurrection because it metamorphosizes from a
larva to a winged insect. ``Naturalistic images of animals were
felt to have supernatural powers,'' Ms. Scott added.
</P>
<P>
   The vessel is expected to bring in $35,000 to $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the sale is a beautiful round bronze weight from the
Warring States Period (475 to 221 B.C.), which depicts a tiger
mauling a fallen deer. The tiger has wrestled the deer to earth,
its left paw holding down one antler while it twists around to bite
the deer's neck. The tiger is inlaid with gold markings; the deer
has inlaid silver ``fur.'' The eyes of both are inset with amber
glass.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lally, the president of J.J. Lally &AMP; Co. Oriental Art in New
York, said such weights were used to anchor the shrouds of the dead
during this period. ``They usually came in sets of four,'' he said.
``The tiger attacking a deer was a fashionable subject,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Han times, Ms. Scott said, ``the tiger was regarded as
the king of wild creatures and symbolized the ruler and unlimited
power, as well as courage, dignity and military powess.''
</P>
<P>
   By the beginning of the Song Dynasty (A.D. 960 to 1279), such
weights were named scroll weights, because they held down hand
scrolls as they were unwound.
</P>
<P>
   ``They became a rich man's luxury object,'' Lally said. ``The
$20,000 to $40,000 estimate seems sensible for an object that's
2,500 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   The Han Dynasty (206 B.C. to A.D. 220) is represented in the
sale by a 30-inch-long pottery tortoise that looks as if it could
outrun the hare. It has personality. Its massive carapace is carved
in a diamond pattern. There is a knobby ridge along its back, and
its head is extended, eyes bulging, mouth partly open.
</P>
<P>
   In ancient times in China, a dark warrior, a combination of
tortoise and snake, symbolized the North, Ms. Scott said. The green
dragon represented the East, the white tiger the West, and the red
bird the South.
</P>
<P>
   Tortoises and turtles are also associated with longevity. The
pottery tortoise is expected to sell for $50,000 to $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   Faberge-like in size and style are two small rock crystal bears
from the Han Dynasty. Each is crouching with its right knee raised
and its left tucked beneath the body. The fur ruffs are incised.
The mouths are animated, as if growling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hardly ever see any rock crystal bears before the 18th
century,'' Lally said. It is extremely unusual to have rock crystal
bears from the Han, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Lally, who recently sold a similar bear, said all three might
have come from one tomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually none of them were known until one burial came to
light,'' he said. ``Then many appeared on the market in one go. No
one knows the significance of the bear's posture, but it became
conventional as bears became caryatids to support vessels.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking porcelains in the sale is a blue and
white pear-shaped vase from the Yuan Dynasty (1279 to 1368 A.D.).
It has two vividly painted, prancing mythical qilins racing across
it. Anyone who drinks Kirin beer from Japan will recognize this
mythical animal from the beer label; kirin means qilin in Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   A qilin has the head of a goat, the hooves of an ox, the horns
and body of a deer, the scaly skin of the dragon and a leonine
tail. Its body emits stylized flames.
</P>
<P>
   The qilin was meant to be a gentle creature that treads so
lightly it leaves no footprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It damages no living thing,'' the Christie's catalog says.
``Symbolizing, among other virtues, prosperity and wise
administration, the qilin only appears during the reign of a noble
and honorable ruler.''
</P>
<P>
   Lally called the qilin ``an auspicious beast,'' adding: ``He has
flames flying off his flanks. It is a good animal to have on your
side.''
</P>
<P>
   The estimate is $50,000 to $70,000. ``If it were in perfect
condition, it would be $200,000,'' Lally said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other pieces in the sale carry more modest estimates. A
12-inch-long painted pottery boar from the Han Dynasty, which looks
like a piece of American folk art, is estimated at $1,000 to
$2,000. The wild boar, which symbolizes the richness of the forests
where it lived, is a favorite subject in Chinese art.
</P>
<P>
   So is the domesticated pig. One striking example, also from the
Han, is a very pregnant sow. Ears out and snout raised, the
20-inch-long pig has a swollen body, with nipples almost touching
the ground. Estimate: $10,000 to $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the Chinese collector, the symbolism of animals in a work
of art is always a secondary concern,'' Lally said. ``For us, it's
fascinating to know how it was viewed at the time it was made and
what power or symbol it was meant to embody. Part of the pleasure
of owning an ancient piece is to place it in context. You don't
have to be superstitious to love having an auspicious animal
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1622EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7041 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-DISNEY-UNIVERS     05-06 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DISNEY-UNIVERSAL-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAT IN HAT MEETS HULK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 9)  
(jt) 
 By JON NORDHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; And it happened that both of them came to a place where they
bumped. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; There they stood. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Foot to foot. Face to face. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ As I scanned the glowering three-foot-high
concrete figures locked in each other's baleful gaze, they became a
metaphor for a larger battle that is taking shape in Orlando, Fla.
After a decade of living in the shadow of Walt Disney World,
Universal is beginning to position itself as a competitor, if not
an equal, to the colossus down the road.
</P>
<P>
   With the opening this spring of the 110-acre Islands of
Adventure, five years in the making, and a 30-acre dining and
entertainment complex called City Walk (plus three luxury hotels
that will place 2,400 rooms on the property by 2001), Universal is
the first Disney wannabe to directly challenge Disney as a
principal Orlando destination.
</P>
<P>
   When added to the existing nine-year-old theme park _ Universal
Studios Florida _ the attractions will more than double its size.
The new entity, now collectively called Universal Studios Escape,
is estimated to have cost $2.6 billion. But the expansion has to be
measured by more than just acres and dollars. The changes will
allow Universal, a unit of Seagram, to market Escape
internationally as a three- or four-day vacation where visitors can
eat, sleep and enjoy the theme parks without leaving the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the new attractions have strengthened Universal's
position as a mecca for high-voltage adventure rides as well as
attracting the kiddie-family crowd that has been a Disney franchise
since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that we're going after the Magic Kingdom
crowd,'' said Thomas L. Williams, president of Universal Studios
Escape. ``There's going to be a lot more fun stuff for the kids as
well as the most technologically advanced, story-driven thrill
rides in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thrill'' in this case might be an understatement. On a visit
during a sneak preview in April, I rode in the front seat of the
Incredible Hulk, a steel roller coaster on Marvel Super Hero
Island, one of the five man-made theme ``islands'' that make up
Islands of Adventure. The others are Seuss Landing, the Lost
Continent, Jurassic Park and Toon Lagoon. Hulk is a psychically
bruising upside-down, twist-and-drop experience that made the
wooden-track roller coasters of my youth _ like the venerable
Cyclone on Coney Island _ seem like a rowboat ride in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   This $15 million Swiss-made devil launches passengers strapped
in a 32-seat vehicle up rails on an enclosed 30-degree ramp,
accelerating from a rolling start to 40 miles an hour in 2 seconds.
Park officials say the propulsion's G-force is the same as
experienced by an F-16 pilot on takeoff. At the top of the ramp the
vehicle whips out into the open air and turns nearly upside down,
giving riders a momentary weightless sensation before plummeting
110 feet. The next two minutes on the 3,000-foot track is an
unrelenting series of towering loops, drop-dead plunges and
sideways careerings.
</P>
<P>
   After the dizzying experience, I walked away in a straight line,
but the following day I felt a twinge of vertigo whenever I bent
over to tie my shoes or lie down.
</P>
<P>
   After that, a chance to ride Dueling Dragons _ a similar
computer-controlled coaster that launches two sets of cars on dual
overhead tracks, so riders' legs dangle beneath them as they fly
upside-down and sideways before the vehicles barely miss at 60
miles an hour _ was easy to pass up, even though it lasts only 50
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Universal also has perfected in-your-face assaults on the senses
in its new ``dark rides,'' attractions housed entirely within
buildings that give visitors the visceral impression they are
battling comic book villains, futuristic aliens or prehistoric
monsters. In some of these rides, special glasses and 3-D films
heighten the effects.
</P>
<P>
   The Amazing Adventures of Spider-Man, which moves on a track
inside a 1.5-acre set, is billed as the most technologically
advanced dark ride in existence. Riders are loaded into cars that
sweep them into a fast-moving urban scene where the webby hero in
red and blue tights appears to leap onto the front of the vehicle,
followed by a succession of evil malefactors, including the
tentacled Dr. Octopus. A whirling spin above city towers culminates
with a wild 400-foot crash dive into a street, which made me blink
hard and hold tight though I knew it all was a 3-D illusion. The
car moves all right, dipping and rising and pitching forward, even
as it moves along on the track. Twenty-five large format movie
projectors and even more smaller ones cast a panoramic action
environment laden with quick movement, flashing scenes and
clamorous sounds that block reality and _ in conjunction with the
short but quick movements of the car _ seduce the brain into buying
the story line. After two days of all this I was
adrenaline-depleted.
</P>
<P>
   By next year, Universal will open Men in Black, a
80,000-square-foot dark ride based on the hit film of the same name
about alien hunters, that Universal says will outdo Spider-Man.
``We define the Universal brand of entertainment as being on the
cutting edge of technology and creativity,'' said Mark Woodbury,
the company's vice president for design and creative development.
``We do our storytelling with icons of popular culture like Dr.
Seuss, E.T. and Marvel Comics super heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Far more separates Universal and Disney than the 15 miles
between the two Florida resorts. In a way, both are heirs to
escapist formulas identified with each studio in their early years.
Disney offered light, airy and sentimental family entertainment
that charmed and delighted. Universal produced hair-raising
monsters and shrieks. Disney gave the public Mickey Mouse and
Donald Duck; Universal set loose Frankenstein's monster and
Dracula.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney World made its debut at the height of the Cold War,
Vietnam and urban unrest, when escape to light fantasy was a
welcome respite, just as its most famous characters enchanted
audiences during the Depression and World War II. Universal opened
its Florida gates as the Cold War ended, domestic calm reigned, and
computer technology was revolutionizing popular entertainment. Even
the brief Persian Gulf war whetted some American appetites for
laser-guided fantasies and games of futuristic conflict. And
Universal has benefited greatly from its association with Steven
Spielberg, a creative consultant, whose hits like ``Jaws,''
``E.T.'' and ``Jurassic Park'' translate easily into popular theme
park rides.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The expanded park thus squarely sets up the competition between
Universal's established muscular appeal and Disney's. The next
step, going after the family segment and establishing a high-end
resort business, is the real challenge to Universal in its
high-stakes expansion. Neither company releases attendance figures,
but Amusement Business, a trade publication, estimated 1998
attendance at Universal Studios at 8.9 million, about one-third of
what Disney World draws.
</P>
<P>
   Disney World has added a number of thrill rides recently but
maintains the moves were the result of public demand, not a
response to Universal. ``We wish Universal success, but our focus
is on the explosive growth at this property,'' said Rick Sylvain, a
Disney spokesman. Disney's thrill rides include the Tower of Terror
at Disney-MGM Studios, a milelong test track ride at the Epcot
General Motors attraction, and a steel-track roller coaster with
multiple inversions due this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Islands of Adventure opens to the public this month, and the
first big hotel development, the 750-room Portofino Bay, is now
taking reservations for stays that begin Sept. 1 (rates start at
$245 a night). But annual pass holders and large numbers of tour
groups, mainly from Britain and for the most part under age 50,
have been admitted in recent weeks. Those I talked with seemed
generally impressed, even amazed, by the total experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, wow, wow!'' exclaimed a man walking out of Spider-Man
with a face flushed by the Florida sun and the ride. ``I've never
seen anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The park's compactness _ the three sections are an easy walk
from one another, compared with the bus, monorail or car rides that
link the Disney attractions _ is an advantage for those with
limited time. Visitors now enter the attractive City Walk
development on people-movers streaming from two garages that can
hold 19,000 cars. To the right lies Universal Studios and to the
left is Islands of Adventure.
</P>
<P>
   City Walk, inspired by the attraction of the same name at
Universal Studios in Los Angeles, has dozens of retail shops, clubs
and restaurants, and is free. There is a variety of food, jazz and
other live music at places like Jimmy Buffett's Margaritaville, the
Hard Rock Cafe and Motown Cafe, and fine dining at Emeril's,
operated by the celebrity chef Emeril Lagasse, and the Latin
Quarter, a restaurant with special appeal to visitors from Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   A 130-foot-tall lighthouse inspired by the ancient wonder at
Alexandria marks the entrance to Islands of Adventure (admission
$42) at Port of Entry, where curio shops, colorful street
characters and sinuous music are designed to convey the mystery of
a romantic place like Zanzibar. The five islands lie immediately
ahead, around a large lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   I took the circular path going to the right into Seuss Landing,
a whimsical collection of structures with no sharp angles, painted
in bright colors. A large carousel with 54 mounts based on Dr.
Seuss animals carries young riders who can activate functions that
wiggle noses and wag tails. Even live palm trees seem bent by
Seussian forces. Actually, they are survivors of Hurricane Andrew
in 1992 in South Florida, many obtained from nurseries that could
not sell their misshapen trunks. A Cat in the Hat patrols the
streets under his bent stovepipe, and small children and their
parents can take a four-minute ride named after the character,
accompanied by bouncy music and recorded text from the story. Exits
_ after a few spins at the ride's end _ are made through a gift
shop that, among other articles, sells a Cat in the Hat costume for
$28. A quick bite is available at the Green Eggs and Ham Cafe, with
the namesake dish prepared with spinach and parsley, park officials
assured me.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop on the counterclockwise route is The Lost
Continent, starring the Dueling Dragons double coaster, the
Poseidon's Fury adventure ride and another called The Eighth Voyage
of Sinbad. Jurassic Park follows with a learning center describing
DNA sequencing in elementary terms, play areas and lifelike
animatronic dinosaurs. The first-rate river adventure ends with a
sharply angled 85-foot water slide that saves riders from a
Tyrannosaurus Rex (at the price of soaking their clothes and
cameras).
</P>
<P>
   For nature-minded visitors, the star of the island is the lush
vegetation creating a 25-acre ``prehistoric'' rain forest with
4,000 palm trees. At Toon Lagoon, there's Popeye's oversized tug
boat to clamber aboard, Dudley Do-Right's Ripsaw Falls flume ride
and a virtual history of the comics with live shows and other
tributes to characters ranging from Krazy Kat to Hagar the
Horrible. The last stop is Marvel Super Hero Island. And if
Spider-Man and The Hulk haven't done you in, you can try Doctor
Doom's Fearfall, in which seated passengers are blasted up the
sides of 200-foot-high structures, rapidly dropped to the base and
blasted up again _ something like a rigid bungee jump. I passed.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
