<HEADER>
A7061 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      05-06 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOL ROCKS AND VOTE, THEN STANDS IT ON ITS HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELECTION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Broderick, Reese Witherspoon, Chris Klein, Jessica
Campbell, Phil Reeves, Mark Harelik &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Alexander Payne &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 105 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People like you have to pay a price for greatness,'' says a
geometry teacher to Tracy Flick (Ms. Witherspoon), an alarmingly
driven teen-ager he is about to seduce. The price he pays for that
interaction is loss of his job and marriage and banishment to
Milwaukee, where he is last seen slapping price stickers on
products at a supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   It can be hazardous around Tracy, who later sets out to become
president of the student government at George Washington Carver
High School. Terms like ``mission'' and ``on message'' don't quite
suffice for a candidate who stamps out her own campaign buttons,
goes berserk when one of her banners gets torn and bakes a cupcake
for every potential voter on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy is all facial expression (wonderfully managed by Ms.
Witherspoon) and voice, which is often lifted in shrill blasts of
resolve. When not grinning maniacally during photo opportunities,
her expression is one of fierce, furrow-browed determination, with
eyes narrowed to slits at displeasure and lips ever pursed to spout
the next bromide about morals and ethics and the call to
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that Carver High has a budding monster on its hands, a
preciously high-minded teacher named Jim McAllister (Broderick)
decides it is imperative to find someone to run against Tracy and
derail the Flick express. That would be Paul Metzler (Klein), a
quarterback hero type with the manner of a sheepish schoolboy,
which he is.
</P>
<P>
   But then the race gets a wild card: Paul's feisty little sister,
Tammy (Ms. Campbell), who is wrestling with personal issues and
wants to head government simply so she can dismantle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president I won't do anything,'' she tells an assembly.
That gets a standing ovation. Tracy, by contrast, sounds more and
more like she has a future inside the Beltway. Time for desperate
measures. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX The fact that boys and girls, as well as their teachers and
parents, are involved in a variety of sexual activities is always
apparent if not depicted. (There is also a bit of frontal nudity,
albeit in a museum exhibit.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Quite a lot in the high school vein, and sometimes in
sudden, strong bursts, which is done for effect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 Parents might well object to the language and sexual
situations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Older children will want to see the movie, which
casts a sharp satirical eye at student and adult alike. It is high
school, after all. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOST AND FOUND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Spade, Sophie Marceau, Patrick Bruel, Artie Lange, Jon
Lovitz, Martin Sheen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jeff Pollack &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 98 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A scrawny restaurateur named Dylan (Spade) needs to obtain a
bank loan and get a life. An annoyingly self-deprecating
professional twerp, he has honed his woes into a shtick, right down
to a cutesy poor-me patois full of lame jokes that poke snide,
phony fun at himself and others.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with women are chronic, but one day he is run into and
flattened by a beautiful cellist named Lila Dubois (Ms. Marceau).
Lila has a little dust mop of a dog named Jack, who is always
running off. Dylan decides to keep retrieving Jack as a device to
see Lila.
</P>
<P>
   Why she would have any interest in such a person is a tough plot
element to sell even in a Hollywood fantasy as ridiculous as this
one. Lila, though, has her own troubles having to do with a stalled
career and a boorish former boyfriend (Bruel), a big-time pianist
who comes from France to win her back. Perhaps she is just
distracted enough to put up with Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   They share a gambol or two and trade reflections on life. Then
the dog swallows a diamond ring, meaning that Dylan has to kidnap
him long enough for the gem to pass through his digestive track.
Naturally, mounds of excrement are carefully probed.
</P>
<P>
   On the financial front, the bank president (Sheen) holds out on
the loan. But Dylan counters with an amazingly bad Neil Diamond
impersonation, which amuses the banker's wife. Loan approved. That
still leaves problems with Lila. Don't ask. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX There are a few partly clothed situations and many off-color
allusions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY A moderate amount. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 11 There is a dog, but this is a limp, sour film with
nothing to recommend itself to young children.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP It's hard to imagine teen-agers having any
interest in a movie that from its humor to its situations is as
flat as this one. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Polley, Desmond Askew, Taye Diggs, William Fichtner, Jay
Mohr, Scott Wolf, Timothy Olyphant &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Doug Liman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 100 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What happens? It's hard to describe in linear terms but Ronna
(Ms. Polley), who is a check-out person at a supermarket, fills in
for Simon (Askew), who has gone to Las Vegas with some friends.
When Adam (Wolf) and Zack (Mohr) come in looking for drugs, Ronna
procures some from Todd (Olyphant). But there is an altercation
over payment and Todd seeks out Ronna, who's now selling baby
aspirin to a van full of teen-agers who are expecting something a
little stronger.
</P>
<P>
   In Las Vegas Simon suddenly develops incredible sexual prowess
and sets a hotel room on fire. Later he shoots a lap-dance parlor
proprietor and gets into problems with people who chase him and his
friends all the way back to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   While that is going on, Zack and Adam, a gay couple, are part of
a police sting supervised by an officer who is also trying to
recruit them as salesmen for Confederated Products, an Amway-type
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Be assured that all of this fits together, and wryly so, after
circling back to the place where it started with Ronna at her post
at the check-out counter. Organized in sections like Quentin
Tarantino's ``Pulp Fiction,'' Liman's film continually poses
questions that are cleared up in due course and in consistently
amusing fashion. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE There is a shooting and a woman is struck by a car, but
with many opportunities for horrific violence, the film abstains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Simon goes to bed with two women in Las Vegas and there are
other sexual situations and many references. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE Drug use and talk about same is prominent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP Mention any movie in the same breath with ``Pulp
Fiction'' and adolescents will come running. While the sex and
profanity will obviously concern many parents, the natural audience
starts between 15 and 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIDER-THEATER-REVIEW-     05-06 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIDER-THEATER-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CIDER HOUSE RULES': A JOHN IRVING TALE FILLS A STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So after three hours and 15 minutes in the wilds of
New England with orphans and abortionists, prostitutes and health
nuts, cranky old trainmen, stout-hearted nurses and mischievous
tomboys, are you up for another three?
</P>
<P>
   This seems a perfectly reasonable question to ponder at the
conclusion of the Atlantic Theater Company's presentation of Part
One of ``The Cider House Rules,'' since this often frisky
adaptation of John Irving's rangy 1985 novel ends smack dab in the
middle of Irving's tale.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic has opted for the time being to offer only the
first half of the sprawling production, directed by Tom Hulce and
Jane Jones, that was first presented at nonprofit theaters on the
West Coast. The two-part stagings ranged in duration from seven
hours at the Seattle Rep to a pared-down six-plus-change at the
Mark Taper Forum in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A novelistic drama that so baldly tests an audience's endurance
must strive to be at least as engrossing as the book on which it is
based; theatergoers need some justification for bypassing the
express and hopping on the local. And in the long run ``The Cider
House Rules,'' it's distressing to report, does not provide it.
Although the ride progresses on a smooth trackbed of noble
intentions, one arrives at the end of Part One (subtitled ``Here in
St. Cloud's'') relieved to disembark. In the workmanlike treatment
by Hulce and Ms. Jones of Peter Parnell's blueprint of a script,
not only does three hours and 15 minutes of gallivanting in Maine
prove to be enough, it's more than enough.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt ``The Cider House Rules,'' with its luxurious
digressions, confident pacing and doubling and tripling of roles
for 19 actors _ a teeming horde by Off Broadway standards _ will
have its partisans. As consumers, Americans have a weakness for
things that come in big packages; whether it's buying in bulk or
sitting through bulky movies, we are susceptible to the notion that
more is more.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, more can indeed be more: ``The Life and Adventures
of Nicholas Nickleby,'' the eight-and-a-half-hour dramatization of
the Dickens novel by the Royal Shakespeare Company, was one of the
great theatrical coups of the last quarter century.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the evident care that has gone into the production,
``Cider House,'' which opened last night, is no ``Nickleby.'' Not
that it was required of the adapters of Irving's novel to imitate
the 1981 Broadway hit in all of its particulars. (Even if the
Irving novel, and the play, allude frequently to Dickens.)
</P>
<P>
   But ``Cider House'' comes up short because it fails at a
critical task, and one that ``Nickleby'' accomplished brilliantly:
the creation of a vital corps of indelible characters who allowed
audiences to live in the play with them. Dickens' people grew and
shriveled before our eyes; their quirks and vanities and
compulsions were revealed to us, not dictated to us, as those of
Irving's characters seem to be. It is as if the one production
emerged from the truth of the heart, and the other from mere
hearsay.
</P>
<P>
   The shortcomings of this ``Cider House,'' in fact, seem to
mirror those of two of its minor characters, the Winkles, a lusty
couple of fresh-air enthusiasts, played by Martin Moran and Cynthia
Darlow, who are prospective adoptive parents for Homer Wells (Josh
Hamilton), the play's orphan-hero.
</P>
<P>
   The Winkles are robust and good-natured, but all their better
impulses come to naught; intrepid swimmers, they drown after they
fail to discern the rumble of a log drive unleashed by a lumber
mill upriver. The production, too, is infused with a certain brio,
yet there is a tone deafness when it comes to the emotional
universe in which its characters are supposed to dwell.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Nickleby,'' too, the story of ``Cider House'' is laid
out on a broad canvas with minimal scenery _ David Zinn's
understated costumes and John Arnone's double-decker clapboard set
convey the pleasing serenity of a Quaker meetinghouse _ and the
speaking part of omniscient narrator is passed on from actor to
actor.
</P>
<P>
   Though the time is the 1920s and '30s, the sensibility is
unmistakably late 20th century: the production, like the novel, is
an attempt to frame on both epic and human scale a contemporary
pair of issues, abortion and adoption.
</P>
<P>
   This ambition is embodied by the play's two central characters,
Homer and Dr. Wilbur Larch (Colm Meaney). Wilbur is an
obstetrician-turned-abortionist who runs the St. Cloud's orphanage,
the setting for much of Part One of ``The Cider House Rules'' _ the
title refers to a locale in the second half of the novel. Homer is
a gentle and questioning orphan who after several failed adoptive
tryouts becomes a ward of St. Cloud's and the presumptive son to
the steady and principled Wilbur.
</P>
<P>
   The adapters of ``Cider House'' gamble heavily on our emotional
investment in Homer and Wilbur; an extended flashback to Wilbur's
young adulthood provides the backstory for his abortion advocacy,
which will become a matter of contention between the doctor and the
orphan, who grows up to work in Wilbur's infirmary. Still, as
imagined by Parnell, Ms. Jones and Hulce, Homer and Wilbur never
translate into complex or vibrant beings.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is a sweetly boyish Homer, but there is an essential
blankness in the rendering of him _ he absorbs rather than acts _
that hardly makes him compelling over the long haul. Meaney's
reserved Wilbur is more troublesome. His is a performance of such
extreme Yankee stoicism _ remember this actor's bemused Irish
father in ``The Commitments''? _ that it comes across as diffident.
The flavors of a relationship allowed to marinate over so many
stage hours must appeal to the entire palate; this one doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Around this central pair orbit a multitude of secondary
characters, some of whom spring agreeably to life, like the St.
Cloud's nurses (Marceline Hugot and Peggy Roeder) and a whore from
Wilbur's past (Leslie Hendrix). The orphans of St. Cloud's, like
the outcasts of Dotheboys Hall in ``Nickleby,'' are played by
grown-ups, and few are permitted to develop any real personality.
The exception is Jillian Armenante, who contributes a showy
physical performance as Melony, the toughest, orneriest and
man-hungriest orphan in the institution.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Her zesty, mountain-woman arrival hits you like a snowball in
the kisser; suddenly, there is a larger-than-life figure in your
midst, a character recognizable from the pen of the whimsical
Irving. Ms. Armenante, with the gait and set jaw of a tailback,
tumbles and climbs and claps Homer on the back so hard that he
coughs. Her admirable energy aside, though, the performance is in
another production from everyone else's, and it comes across as a
little desperate. This may be the result of some encouragement by
directors eager to get the evening's juices flowing, but while Ms.
Armenante is wacky, she is also out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   The play's narrative style, chosen, in Ms. Jones' words, so that
the author's work can be presented ``exactly as he wrote it,''
points up some other questionable choices by the directors. While
the sharing of narration is a tried and true device, having the
actors comment omnisciently on their  &UR; own &LR;  thoughts and behavior
often seems redundant. And there are weird and glaring
inconsistencies in the physical staging. The miming of a knock on a
door, for instance, is accompanied by the sound of knocking, but
the opening and closing of the invisible door remains silent. A
doctor dons surgical dress and has an assortment of obstetrical
instruments in front of him, but mimes the removal of surgical
gloves.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of theatrical incongruities that get tallied
in the mind as credulity begins to flag. An audience comes to an
enterprise of the scope and vigor of ``The Cider House Rules'' with
all the puppy-dog optimism of those outdoorsy, adventurous Winkles.
It's a real letdown, though, when the expedition proves less
enthralling than what was described in the brochures.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE CIDER HOUSE RULES'
</P>
<P>
   `Part One: Here in St. Cloud's'
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Peter Parnell, from the novel by John Irving;
conceived and directed by Tom Hulce and Jane Jones; sets by John
Arnone; costumes by David Zinn; lighting by Adam Silverman;
composer, Dan Wheetman; production stage manager, Amy Fritz;
production manager, Richard Burgess. Presented by the Atlantic
Theater Company, Neil Pepe, artistic director, Hilary Hinckle,
managing director. At 336 W. 20th St., Chelsea, Manhattan.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jillian Armenante (Melony), Colm Meaney (Dr. Wilbur
Larch), Josh Hamilton (Homer Wells), Cynthia Darlow (Billie Winkle
and Adoptive Mom), Martin Moran (Grant Winkle and Wilbur Walsh),
Aunjanue Ellis (Mrs. Eames' daughter and eclampsia patient),
Marceline Hugot (Nurse Edna and prostitute), Peggy Roeder (Nurse
Angela and Mrs. Claus), Leslie Hendrix (Mrs. Eames and Sally
O'Malley) and Todd Weeks (Fuzzy Stone and Mary Agnes Cork).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
