<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUPRE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JACQUELINE DU PRE': A MEASURED LIFE STUDY OF A MERCURIAL GENIUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hardly had the need arisen when Elizabeth Wilson's ``Jacqueline
du Pre: Her Life, Her Music, Her Legend'' arrived to supply a
corrective. The world does not always appear so well regulated.
</P>
<P>
   It did not seem so when du Pre, after a woefully brief,
brilliant career as a cellist, was forced to stop performing in
1973, at 28, by multiple sclerosis. Nor did it seem so when, a
decade after her death, her sister, Hilary, and her brother, Piers,
published ``A Genius in the Family: An Intimate Memoir of
Jacqueline du Pre'' in England, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That book, since issued in the United States and turned into the
film ``Hilary and Jackie,'' seemed bent on reducing the superstar
cellist to the all too human size of her siblings and left no one
in the family looking good. Now Ms. Wilson, herself a cellist and
the author of the valuable ``Shostakovich: A Life Remembered,''
sets things right with the most thorough and measured treatment of
du Pre's life and artistry to date.
</P>
<P>
   Like the finest earlier du Pre biographer, Carol Easton, Ms.
Wilson knew du Pre personally. Though they were English
contemporaries, they met only in Moscow, where Ms. Wilson was
studying at the conservatory when du Pre went there in 1966 to
study with Mstislav Rostropovich. The author also benefits from the
cooperation of many of du Pre's friends and intimates. Some,
including her husband, the conductor and pianist Daniel Barenboim,
withheld that cooperation to the sister and brother: not
unreasonably, it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this book is not a panegyric either to du Pre or to those
around her. Ms. Wilson does not flinch from the awkward facts
revealed in the recent book and film: that du Pre, in the throes of
a physical and psychological breakdown that in retrospect can
hardly be viewed apart from her devastating illness, for a time
became intimate with Hilary's husband, Christopher Finzi; and that
Barenboim, living in Paris while du Pre languished in the later
stages of her disease in London, had taken up with Elena
Bashkirova, whom he has since married.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Ms. Wilson sensationalize, and placed in the
context of so rich a life so bountifully related, those facts
recede to manageable perspective. Clearly, the main characters are
to be pitied rather than judged.
</P>
<P>
   Du Pre's mother, too, receives a more sympathetic portrayal here
than she did from the children who survived her. Iris Greep, an
accomplished pianist, ``had the sensitivity to recognize the unique
nature of Jackie's talent _ namely the deeply felt inner passion
which illuminated her attitude to music from the earliest age,''
Ms. Wilson writes. Evidently, neither that unique talent nor the
mother's attentions to it afforded much pleasure to du Pre's
siblings, especially to Hilary, a flutist of some talent who seems
to imagine that if choices and breaks had fallen differently, she
might also have had a major career.
</P>
<P>
   As a musician herself, Ms. Wilson is well equipped to seek out
the source of du Pre's genius. Technique was never a prime concern,
and in fact du Pre's methods were often unconventional, mercurial
and inimitable. She seemed to grasp music whole and emit it intact,
without a thought to individual notes, finger shifts or bowings.
</P>
<P>
   But it is too facile to think of such an intuitive artist as
some sort of idiot savant. Du Pre made an early escape from the
English school system and was not well educated outside music, a
failing she profoundly regretted and partially remedied during her
years of paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Even in music, her horizons were limited; as Ms. Wilson takes
pains to establish, du Pre ran deep and impetuous rather than broad
and meandering. There was never an indication that she would not
have understood thoroughly what she was doing if she had cared to
try. Just such an understanding emerged in some of her teaching in
later years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression, from hearing and seeing her play, was that the
music just poured out of her, as a natural and unthought process,''
Robert Cohen, a cellist who studied with du Pre, tells Ms. Wilson.
``Soon I realized that she had always known precisely what she was
doing _ you understand this when you listen to the records.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is not without flaws. Annoying Britishisms survive from
the original publication last year. Ms. Wilson drops homey
abbreviations liberally (CBSO, for example, for the City of
Birmingham Symphony Orchestra). She is also quaintly cavalier about
American institutions and individuals, misidentifying orchestras
and misspelling names with some regularity. (She probably fails to
realize how rudely she has deflated the grandly named Daniel
Webster, a critic of The Philadelphia Inquirer, in calling him
David.)
</P>
<P>
   More damaging is a prose style that tends to plod. Nonspecialist
readers may tire of some painstakingly detailed musical discussion,
returning as it so often does to the same few works that anchored
Ms. du Pre's repertory, which was limited not only by her short
career but also by a basic lack of interest in music of any great
modernity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is the very depth and detail of that discussion that
makes Ms. Wilson's work so valuable, pinning down the elusive
qualities that made for du Pre's genius and, in the end, separated
her by a wide margin from most of her professional peers as well as
her siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Du Pre also comes in for brief treatment in another new book,
``Musical Prodigies: Perilous Journeys, Remarkable Lives,'' by
Claude Kenneson, another cellist and a professor emeritus at the
University of Alberta. Kenneson discusses 44 musical prodigies,
ranging from Mozart to the Scottish percussionist Evelyn Glennie,
in greater or lesser detail.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneson provides fine insights, particularly in the cases of
cello prodigies he has taught: Eric Wilson and Shauna Rolston.
Bejun Mehta offers as epilogue his own fascinating account of his
journey from broken-down boy soprano to worldbeating countertenor.
</P>
<P>
   But the du Pre account, one of the weaker sections, consists
largely of her mother's tribute ``Born for the Cello'' and is not
particularly enlightening. Kenneson makes no reference to ``A
Genius in the Family'' (or even to sibling rivalry), drawing
instead on Ms. Easton's biography and William Wordsworth's
``Jacqueline du Pre: Impressions.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter is the source of a telling comment of du Pre's with
regard to Elgar, which her own life seems to have borne out in
abundance: ``A genius is one who, with an innate capacity, affects
for good or evil the life of others.'' From both sides, the
testimony is ample.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `JACQUELINE DU PRE
</P>
<P>
   Her Life, Her Music, Her Legend'
</P>
<P>
   By Elizabeth Wilson
</P>
<P>
   466 pages. Arcade Publishing. $27.95.
</P>
<P>
   `MUSICAL PRODIGIES
</P>
<P>
   Perilous Journeys, Remarkable Lives'
</P>
<P>
   By Claude Kenneson
</P>
<P>
   386 pages. Amadeus Press. $29.95.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
