<HEADLINE>
`TWAIN' IS BACK, PEPPERY AS EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The old man in the white suit puffs on a cigar and considers
Satan, a figure blamed by everybody for the sins of everybody else.
``Let's hear his side,'' Mark Twain says. ``Anybody who's charged
with being spiritual head of four-fifths of the human race, and
political head of all of it, must have executive ability.''
</P>
<P>
   The year is 1905, and Twain, as depicted by Hal Holbrook in
``Mark Twain Tonight!,'' is 70 and on a bristling good tear about
politics, racism, lying, the tendency of the righteous to make a
graveyard of the globe in their quest for admission to the kingdom
of heaven, and humans' exalted notion of themselves in the ranking
of God's creatures. ``Man's idea is that the deity sits up nights
admiring him,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   When it was broadcast by CBS on March 6, 1967, the 90-minute
show attracted 30 million viewers. Last week it was released for
the first time on video by Kultur
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook, now 74, began what has become 45 years of Twain
performances with a monologue at Lock Haven State Teachers College
in Pennsylvania in 1954. He currently performs the show 20 to 25
times a year and the idea remains the same: an evolving
accumulation of observations drawn from Twain's writings and put
together with considerable dramatic license by Holbrook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twain never wrote the show, but everything in it he wrote,''
he said last week. With someone as prolific as Twain, material is
still plentiful. ``Any one selection of 5 or 10 minutes could come
from 15 different sources,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Lock Haven State, the audience began to laugh. ``I realized
you could go out on stage and get away with this,'' Holbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   Years earlier he and his first wife, Ruby Holbrook, both freshly
graduated from Denison University, toured rural Texas performing
excerpts from Shakespeare and, ``if you can believe this,''
Holbrook said, ``Robert and Elizabeth Barrett Browning.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences, he added, were accustomed to Roy Rogers. ``Our
get-away-with-your-life number was Mark Twain,'' he said. In New
York, he expanded the Twain part of the routine and performed it at
the Purple Onion Club and later off Broadway at the 41st Street
Theater. Ed Sullivan came with some fight-crowd friends, liked what
he saw and bought six minutes for his own show.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966 ``Mark Twain Tonight!'' played on Broadway and won a
Tony. In the first section of the CBS production, Twain salutes the
first pioneer to arrive on any scene (whisky), chides the National
Asylum for the Helpless (Congress) and male 20-somethings (``young
men studying for the gallows''), and suggests that the cow-catcher
on a slow-moving, much-delayed train he'd been riding be moved from
the front to the back to prevent the cows from getting on board.
</P>
<P>
   The second section includes a passage from ``Huckleberry Finn.''
Jim, the runaway slave, is determined to find freedom and work hard
so he can buy his wife. Then they'll both work hard so they can buy
their children.
</P>
<P>
   Later Twain positions most of mankind somewhere between the
angels and the French. ``It's a shame the Noah party didn't miss
the boat,'' he says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tape is $24.95. Information: (800) 458-5887. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another Day in Paradise &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Always colorful and sometimes exuberant, Larry Clark's film
about four druggy losers has none of the cautionary power of his
bruising first film, ``Kids.'' Mel (James Woods, with Vincent
Kartheiser) and Sidney (Melanie Griffith) and Bobbie (Kartheiser)
and Rosie (Natasha Gregson Wagner) are sort of elder and younger
Bonnie and Clydes on a slide to nowhere. Whether any of them last
to achieve full adulthood is questionable, but Clark is more
interested in day-by-day details in his second, more benign film,
which, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``delivers what
his first promised: bad times with a wicked way of looking good.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Trimark. $99.99. 101 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: May 11. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Star Trek: Insurrection &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the series' latest installment, the starship Enterprise sets
down on a bucolic planet where a tribe of 600 called the Baku lives
in utopian harmony and never gets older. That interests the Sona,
an ancient and leathery breed who definitely need a change of scene
before they fall apart completely.
</P>
<P>
   A plot is hatched to remove the Baku, which calls for the
strong, wise intercession of Jean-Luc Picard (Patrick Stewart), the
Enterprise captain, who then finds himself charged with treason by
corrupt superiors. ``What makes this hokum work as entertainment is
the series' unquestioned belief in basic human benignity'' (Stephen
Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Paramount. $104.16. 103 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
Release date: May 11. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Talk of Angels &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent and weakest addition to the ``irresistible
governess'' genre, the beautiful, clever Mary Lavelle (Polly
Walker) becomes romantically entangled with a member of her
employer's family. In this case Nick Hamm's film goes whole hog,
imagining itself as the Spanish Civil War equivalent of ``Dr.
Zhivago.''
</P>
<P>
   As Mary's lover there is the handsome, married Francisco
(Vincent Perez), but like Ms. Walker he isn't much of an actor.
Sets are lavish, scenery and costumes are sumptuous. Now if
anything else worked, the movie ``might at least have worked as a
sudsy, aromatic bubble bath'' (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Miramax. $104.16. 96 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: May 11. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Velvet Goldmine &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Todd Haynes' film brilliantly reimagines the heyday of British
glam-rock and the David Bowie of the early 1970s as a brave new
world of electrifying theatricality and sexual possibility. Tracing
its tendrils back to Oscar Wilde, the story carries the Wildean
flamboyance forward to the pansexual pop utopia over which Bowie
presided.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying the Bowie-esque Brian Slade, Jonathan Rhys Meyers
stands out in a film that doesn't address Bowie directly but
``appropriates his shimmering, protean aura in virtuoso ways''
(Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Miramax. $104.16. 123 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: May 11. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELIZABETH R. Glenda Jackson stars as the monarch who surprised
them all and ruled effectively for more than 40 years. Made for
British television, the 8{-hour epic was also a huge hit in this
country. 1971. BBC/Fox Video. Six cassettes, $99.98. 510 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   CHARLES: DEAD OR ALIVE. He claims to be a watchmaker and
businessman, the third generation to head a prosperous family
business, but Charles is really a fugitive of sorts: a 50-year-old
who has left his family and struck out to discover new truths for
himself. That leads to a world of thought and reverie in Alain
Tanner's first film, which in its best moments, Roger Greenspun
wrote in The New York Times, reflects ``a sense of intelligent,
poised relaxation.'' 1969. New Yorker. $89.95. 93 minutes. French
with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE OF JESUS. Working with grim exactitude to convey the
unhappiness of a becalmed village in northern France, Bruno
Dumont's first feature film tells the story of Freddy, a sad lad
with an inexpressive face and a brutish skinhead look. When one of
their number lies dying of AIDS, Freddy (David Douche) and his
friends set up a vigil, experiencing a brush with death that leads
to desperate behavior later. Flat and unswerving, the film, Janet
Maslin wrote in The Times, nevertheless ``does bring haunting power
to the bitter, tongue-tied helplessness that sets its tragedy in
motion.'' 1998. Fox Lorber. $89.98. 96 minutes. French with English
subtitles. No rating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
