</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7085 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0507-C     05-06 1661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WEST, RUSSIA AGREE ON PLAN FOR SECURITY FORCE IN KOSOVO
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trims.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT_ In a potential breakthrough in the search for peace
in Kosovo, Russia formally agreed Thursday to support a plan for
placing the embattled Yugoslav province under the protection of an
international security force that would guarantee broad autonomy
for ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton hailed the agreement as ``a move forward,''
but vowed that NATO warplanes would continue pounding Yugoslavia
from the air in the hope of speeding the advance of diplomacy on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real peace process underway, but it has no chance
of reaching a satisfactory conclusion unless we maintain allied
unity and firmness,'' Clinton told a group of European
correspondents here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention of changing policies until the basic
conditions are met,'' he added. ``I will stay for as long as it
takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's agreement was reached during a meeting in nearby Bonn
among top diplomats from the United States, Russia and six other
democratic powers, the so-called Group of Eight, or G-8. Their
agreement to a set of principles appeared to put new pressure on
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to accept foreign troops on
Serbian soil in exchange for an end to the NATO air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has not accepted the terms, and Clinton made clear
that tough diplomacy lies ahead on what could still be a long road
toward peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the process is long, but I don't think we can
afford to be discouraged or be impatient,'' Clinton said, following
a meeting focused on Kosovo with German Chancellor Gerhardt
Schroeder(CQ).
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that there is no reason whatsoever to now think about
a change in the NATO strategy, now that the strategy does seem to
work,'' Schroeder added. ``And I'm talking about the military as
well as political initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   After six inconclusive weeks of bombing, though, Clinton just as
clearly welcomed the possibilities presented by Russia's acceptance
of the need for some sort of armed security force to oversee the
return of refugees and the establishment of broad self government
for Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to read this as a move forward in increasing the
likelihood that there will ultimately be a resolution of this that
will actually work,'' Clinton said. ``I was personally very pleased
by it.''
</P>
<P>
   With Russia on board -- in principle at least -- with most of
NATO's terms, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the United
States would seek a United Nations Security Council resolution ``as
quickly as we can,'' authorizing peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan hailed the
agreement as an ``important step,'' and welcomed the decision to
seek a U.N. Security Council resolution for any international force
needed in Kosovo to protect the return of hundreds of thousands of
refugees Yugoslavia has expelled.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has so far rejected such a force, on the grounds that
it would violate Yugoslav sovereignty. Instead he has said he would
accept lightly-armed civilian monitors operating under U.N.
auspices.
</P>
<P>
   However, Russia's participation in drafting Thursday's accord is
the latest indication that Milosevic was prepared to settle, even
as allied warplanes continued pounding the country Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   His decision last week to release three captured U.S. soldiers
seems to have been a signal that he was ready to compromise. And a
trip to Rome on Wednesday by moderate Kosovo Albanian leader
Ibrahim Rugova took many by surprise _ Western leaders considered
Rugova a prisoner of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Serb permission for Rugova to go to Rome indicated that he was
likely carrying a message from Milosevic outlining his desire to
compromise on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thursday's accord appeared to present Milosevic with a
stark choice: accept a NATO-led security force or part ways with
Moscow, his closest and most influential partner and the only
reliable friend of Yugoslavia's able to block a Security Council
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come to a wider agreement with the Russians,''
Albright told reporters following the G-8 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The group was not able to agree on a critical feature of any
peacekeeping operation: the composition of the force.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its NATO partners are demanding that the
contingent be a fully combat-ready ground force, with tens of
thousands of infantry troops, backed with tanks and air power,
commanded and controlled by NATO. Otherwise, Clinton maintains,
ethnic Albanian refugees won't feel safe to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has rejected such a formulation, saying the peacekeepers
should operate under U.N. auspices, an idea the United States
regards as a dead letter.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said Thursday's G-8 agreement marks an advance because,
for the first time, Russia has bought into the idea that the force
must be a military operation, not simply civilian monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The document doesn't specify a military force, only a
``security'' presence the agreement describes as ``effective,'' and
``capable.''
</P>
<P>
   That, said Albright, means NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agree it has to be a military force,'' Albright said.
``It has to be robust and be able to play its role,'' of providing
the protection needed to insure ethnic Albanian refugees that it
would be safe to return to their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have NATO at its core and it will have other countries
associated with it,'' she said, referring to the long-standing U.S.
position that Russian troops should be part of any peacekeeping
force in Kosovo, as they are in the NATO operation policing the
fragile peace in neighboring Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement signed by Albright, Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov and their counterparts from Britain, Canada,
France, Germany, Italy and Japan, the countries endorsed several
``general principles,'' that should guide a resolution of the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The principles included an end to the fighting in Kosovo and the
safe return of the estimated 1.5 million ethnic Albanians who have
fled their homes in the ravaged province.
</P>
<P>
   In the key areas of the formulation of the peacekeeping force
and the withdrawal of Yugoslav troops and police from Kosovo,
however, the G-8 document was sufficiently vague to allow each
nation to give its own public interpretation of the agreement's
specifics.
</P>
<P>
   That tact is meant to allow Russia to finesse the tricky
domestic politics of sidling up with NATO, which most Russians
regard as a needless and threatening post-Cold War anachronism. The
ambiguity, however, also carries the risk that not all parties
believe they have agreed to the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for ``effective international civil and
security presences,'' for example, without specifying the make-up
of either.
</P>
<P>
   The civil presence, which would help to set up democratic
institutions and the roots of self-government for Kosovo's ethnic
Albanian majority, is less of an issue than the security force.
Clinton and his NATO counterparts have long spoken of the need for
a civil operation, and have often suggested the use of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) for such
a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's G-8 statement also calls for the ``withdrawal from
Kosovo of military, police and paramilitary forces.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't specify, however, how many must be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon estimates there are some 40,000 such forces inside
Kosovo. Milosevic has insisted on keeping about 11,000 inside
Kosovo after any peace accord is reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the U.S. view that all forces need to be withdrawn,''
Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its NATO allies hold Yugoslav military and
police responsible for widespread atrocities that allegedly have
left more than 4,000 ethnic Albanians dead since March 24, when
NATO launched air strikes against Yugoslavia after a year of
mounting tension between the Serb-dominated Yugoslav government and
Kosovar Albanian rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has challenged the scale of alleged atrocities against
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, but admits that a crackdown he ordered
on the armed Albanian separatists has raged far beyond acceptable
bounds.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also endorses NATO's earlier call to place Kosovo
under international administration over some unspecified period of
time.
</P>
<P>
   The G-8 document calls for the United Nations to oversee the
interim administration of Kosovo. It also calls for ``substantial
self-government,'' for the province's majority ethnic Albanians,
but rules out independence, citing the need to retain Kosovo as
part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional trim begins.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left Germany Thursday and was scheduled to spend the
night in Washington before leaving town again Friday for a two-day
trip to Houston, Austin and finally, Oklahoma City to visit the
areas ravaged by killer tornadoes earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Winding up a two-day swing through Belgium and Germany, Clinton
visited earlier Thursday with Albanian refugees at the Rhein Main
Air Base here, home to a fleet of giant U.S. cargo planes and
refueling tankers supporting NATO's ongoing humanitarian efforts
and air strikes in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important that every freedom-loving person in the
entire world know the story of Kosovo,'' Clinton told the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has been done to you and your children and your homeland
cannot be undone. But you must know that you have not been
forgotten or abandoned,'' Clinton said, vowing, ``You will go home
again -- in safety and in freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
