<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7090 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-PROBE-HNS &LR;      05-06 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION'S HANDLING OF SPY INVESTIGATION TO BE PROBED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Justice Department officials and FBI agents will
serve on a special task force to probe the administration's
handling of allegations that a Los Alamos computer scientist passed
nuclear weapons secrets to China, Attorney General Janet Reno said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to review everything we've done to see if there is
anything that could have been done differently,'' Reno said at her
weekly news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The task force will include assistant U.S. attorneys and FBI
agents not connected with the government's past investigation of
scientist Wen Ho Lee and will examine how the Clinton
administration and previous Republican administrations handled
suspicions that Lee was a spy, Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   She would not comment on the size of the task force, what
specific areas or which personnel it would cover or when its
findings would be released.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came a day after Senate Republicans accused the
administration of bungling its investigation into the spying
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think heads should roll,'' Don Nickles, R-Okla., the Senate
majority whip, said Wednesday at a hearing held by the Energy and
Natural Resources Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles criticized the Justice Department for failing in 1997 to
get a warrant to search an unclassified computer belonging to Lee
at his lab work space. That computer became the focus of
investigation after it was learned that Lee had downloaded highly
secret information into it from a classified computer network.
</P>
<P>
   ``An individual is suspected of being a spy with access to all
of our warhead information ... and we did not get into his
computer,'' Nickles said. ``This is total incompetence.''
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, the director of the Los Alamos National
Laboratory in New Mexico, John Browne, said that although Lee was
suspected for nearly three years of having given secrets to China,
lab officials kept him at his job because FBI agents said removing
him could jeopardize their investigation of the physicist.
</P>
<P>
   Browne, a 20-year employee at Los Alamos who became the research
lab's director 18 months ago, said Lee, an American citizen born in
Taiwan, would have been transferred out of the secure areas if the
FBI had approved such a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``This points out the dilemma of balancing the requirements of
national security against the constraints guiding law enforcement
efforts,'' Browne said.
</P>
<P>
   Browne also revealed that FBI agents dissuaded lab officials
from checking the scientist's office computer by telling them that
a search might taint evidence and ruin a potential criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Lee, like all other employees at the lab, had
signed a waiver permitting his e-mail and personal computer to be
reviewed without his knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the waiver, Browne said, the FBI and Justice Department
decided a court warrant would be needed before that step could be
taken. Without a warrant, Justice and FBI officials told him,
information taken from Lee's computer under the waiver could not be
used in any criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was fired on March 8 from his job as a computer scientist
with access to secrets about the W-88 warhead, the most advanced in
the U.S. arsenal. Lee remains under investigation for possible
espionage, dating back to the 1980s, but has not been charged with
any crime.
</P>
<P>
   He also faces possible charges of transferring more than 1,000
classified nuclear computer files to his unclassified computer
between 1983 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the FBI is investigating whether some other party
gained access to the material with or without Lee's six-digit
password.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has repeatedly denied that he committed any crime. China
also has denied that it stole U.S. nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   According to government officials, after two years of
investigation gave no indication that Lee had any relationship with
Chinese intelligence, the FBI tried last summer to entice him into
spying using two Chinese-American agents. The agents told Lee they
were looking for information to help their country, but he turned
them down.
</P>
<P>
   The main indication so far that Beijing gained U.S. nuclear
secrets is the discovery of a 1988 Chinese military document that
contains data on the exact dimensions and shape of the W-88
miniature warhead and the weight and explosive yields of a six
other U.S. systems, according to administration sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
