<HEADLINE>
DECREASED EXPECTATIONS WHILE GETTING THE DICKENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If competing with Charles Dickens were not daunting enough,
moviemakers who take on his work also find themselves up against
the memories of adaptations past, and none more memorably than
``Great Expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans may argue over whether the book is among Dickens' best, but
the 1947 British adaptation, directed by David Lean and brought
back with welcome frequency on television, is by any measure a fine
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry if comparisons prove invidious, but the respectable BBC
version that begins on Sunday on ``Masterpiece Theater'' provides
scant competition for John Mills, Alec Guinness, Finlay Currie,
Francis L. Sullivan, Valerie Hobson and others who carried the tale
of Pip's enlightenment about life, love and loyalty so vibrantly
onto the larger screen.
</P>
<P>
   In the new version, Ioan Gruffudd makes an earnest and generally
engaging Pip, ``a young fellow of great expectations'' who depends
on the kindness of a stranger. It gives away no secrets to reveal
that Pip endures some hard knocks from assorted odd teachers in the
course of his moral education.
</P>
<P>
   There is Magwitch (Bernard Hill), the escaped convict who starts
out as a boy's nightmare and ends up a pussycat; Estella (Justine
Waddell), who starts out as a haughty beauty trained to wreak
vengeance on all mankind and ends up a victim of her own misshapen
character, and of course Miss Havisham, whom Charlotte Rampling
plays not as a batty old lady but as a vulnerable middle-aged one.
</P>
<P>
   Hill brings spirit to the proceedings at every appearance, but
Ms. Waddell could do with more variety in her interpretation, and
it does not take long for Ms. Rampling's persistently enigmatic
expression to lose force.
</P>
<P>
   Other characters, the calculating and sardonic Jaggers, his
clerk, Wemmick, of the businesslike exterior and warm interior, and
the amiable Herbert Pocket add flavor. But the only full-bodied
figure is Joe Gargery (Clive Russell), Pip's brother-in-law and, as
the feckless young man belatedly learns, the sturdy moral center of
this complicated parable. Pip himself comes across as less fun and
more of a whiner than I remembered.
</P>
<P>
   The work's abounding coincidences and mild mysteries are
efficiently if somewhat somberly treated in Tony Marchant's
three-hour adaptation. The director, Julian Jarrold, resorts too
often to an overactive camera and scenic embellishments (all those
candles!) as though he didn't trust Dickens to provide sufficient
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   As always, true Dickensians will lament the absence of some
characters and the diminishment of others, but the producers did
well to shun the happy ending that Dickens tacked on.
</P>
<P>
   So don't let your expectations get too great. This production,
though always intelligent, is smaller than life and much smaller
than Dickens.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MASTERPIECE THEATER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Great Expectations &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Sunday and Monday nights &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 9)
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Tony Marchant from the Charles Dickens novel. Julian
Jarrold, director; David Snodin, producer. Howard Kingston,
production executive. Produced by BBC America and WGBH, Boston.
Michael Wearing (BBC) and Rebecca Eaton (WGBH) executive producers.
Ms. Eaton, series executive producer; Russell Baker, host.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Ioan Gruffudd (Pip), Justine Waddell (Estella), Charlotte
Rampling (Miss Havisham), Bernard Hill (Abel Magwitch), Gabriel
Thomson (Young Pip), Gemma Gregory (Young Estella), Laila Morse
(Molly), Nicholas Woodeson (Wemmick), Leslie Sharp (Mrs. Joe),
Clive Russell (Joe Gargery), Emma Cunniffe (Biddy) and Daniel Evans
(Herbert Pocket). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
