<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7105 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOLPLACES-2ndTake-TE     05-06 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOLPLACES-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: to milkshakes. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's easy to fall in love with northwestern Montana in the
summer. The days are long and beautiful, and the nights sparkle
with the Northern Lights. There was only one reason I left: I heard
they get around 69 inches of snow in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Whitefish, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   Average July low: 48
</P>
<P>
   Cool information: Flathead Valley Convention and Visitors
Bureau, (406) 756-9091; Glacier Park Lodging, (602) 207-6000;
Grouse Mountain Lodge, (406) 862-1888; Glacier Raft Co., (800)
235-6781; Huckleberry Patch, (406) 387-5670.
</P>
<P>
   Cool Web site: www.fcvb.org
</P>
<P>
   Cool thing to do: Drink a huckleberry milkshake at The
Huckleberry Patch in Hungry Horse.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THE WATER FALLS: Brevard, N.C., is famous for at least two
things: white squirrels and waterfalls.
</P>
<P>
   In my years of travel to this picturesque western North Carolina
town, I never spotted any of the ghostlike nut-gatherers, but I did
take in scores of the 150 or so assorted waterfalls that bathe the
lush forests.
</P>
<P>
   Why are there so many falls in one spot? The best hypothesis I
heard was that the area was perfectly situated near the base of the
Blue Ridge Mountains, which happen to be the first barrier the
clouds hit as they move up from the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   As the clouds rise up the mountains, they dump rain _ about 100
inches a year _ which cascades down the rocky hillsides, forming
such wonders as Whitewater Falls, Looking Glass Falls and Bridal
Veil Falls.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite by far is Sliding Rock. For the modest fee of $3 a
carload, you can slide down a 60-foot-long natural rock chute that
dumps you into a 6- to 7-foot-deep pool where the water temperature
is 55 degrees _ in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that even Lassie took the plunge while filming the
TV show. Of course, it could have been a doggie double.
</P>
<P>
   Bathhouses are available, and lifeguards are on duty from 10
a.m. to 6 p.m. in the summer. Wear your cutoffs _ the rock can take
its toll on thong bikinis.
</P>
<P>
   Brevard is next to the Pisgah National Forest, which lays claim
to being the birthplace of modern forestry methods, thanks to the
largess of George Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   When he built nearby Biltmore House, he also acquired 125,000
acres and hired forestry experts to manage it. You can live the
life of those early forestry students at the Cradle of Forestry and
their methods with a sawmill and locomotive circa 1914. Entry fees
are $4 for adults and $2 for kids 6-17.
</P>
<P>
   The city also appeals to music lovers, who flock to Brevard
College each summer for its annual music festival, which will run
June 23-Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Brevard remains quieter and quainter than much of the mountains.
The casino crowd is in nearby Cherokee, and the masses thronging
the Great Smoky Mountains National Park are hours away in line at
some overpriced restaurant in Gatlinburg, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The town offers traditional bed-and-breakfast inns, including
the Inn at Brevard.
</P>
<P>
   Summer days can get warm here, typically into the low 80s, but
cooling off is easy enough. Just head up the mountain or down the
river.
</P>
<P>
   Brevard, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Average July low: 60
</P>
<P>
   Cool information: Contact the Brevard Chamber of Commerce, (828)
883-3700; Cradle of Forestry, (828) 877-3130; Brevard Music Center,
(828) 884-2019; Inn at Brevard, (828) 884-2105.
</P>
<P>
   Cool Web site: www.mountains-nc.com/brevard
</P>
<P>
   Cool thing to do: Try nature's own water slide at Sliding Rock.
Hey, Lassie did it.
</P>
<P>
   VIRTUOUS VICTORIA: Imagine Britain if it were just a bit more
British and you'll get a feel for Victoria, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   There's high tea, kilt shops, fine china and plenty of pubs with
amusing names. There are also manners _ lots of them _ everywhere.
One sign in front of a manicured home read: ``We request that no
rubbish be placed here.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's a culture shock for many Americans who try to
get in for high tea at The Empress Hotel wearing shorts and
sneakers. But such niceties make a trip to this Anglophile heaven
the perfect antidote to hot tempers as well as hot temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria's harbor skyline is dominated by British Columbia's
Capitol building and The Empress Hotel. Tourists of both sexes
diligently ante up the $25 Canadian for high tea in the hotel
lobby, but it's really a female thing. My husband uncomfortably
nibbled finger sandwiches as the women at a neighboring table
talked hysterectomies.
</P>
<P>
   Many traditionalists insist on staying at The Empress, but the
city has quaint bed-and-breakfast inns on almost every corner.
</P>
<P>
   Budget-minded travelers can check into the University of
Victoria, which opens up its dorm rooms to visitors during the
summer. A four-room suite rents for about $104 in American dollars
and includes a kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Butchart Gardens is a must-see. About 13 miles north of the city
in an abandoned quarry, the gardens are an amazing collection of
flora and fountains. Things get jazzed up at night with colored
spotlights shining on the elaborate floral displays. It's
inexplicably appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria has almost perfect summers _ rarely cloudy or rainy,
with high temperatures in the '70s. The ocean water looks nice, but
don't try to get in. The only swimmer I saw during my weeklong stay
was a Labrador retriever.
</P>
<P>
   The city can easily be handled on foot, and public buses are
plentiful, but perhaps the best way to experience it is on a motor
scooter. I rented one from a Budget booth on Douglas Street for $26
a day and cruised the island at 15 miles per hour. It was just fast
enough to make a breeze, and slow enough to smell the tall pine
forests along the coast and shrimp on the grill of a million-dollar
home in the Saanich Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Once, I looked back to see a dozen cars dutifully creeping
behind me. The amazing thing was the silence _ no one was honking.
I pulled over to let them all pass and took a moment to soak up the
overwhelming pleasantness of this place. I knew it would be over
all too soon and I'd be back on Airport Freeway with my air
conditioner on the fritz.
</P>
<P>
   At least I'd have my memories to keep me cool.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria, British Columbia
</P>
<P>
   Average July low: 52
</P>
<P>
   Cool information: Tourist Bureau, (250) 953-2033 or (800)
663-3883; Empress Hotel, (250) 384-8111; University of Victoria,
(250) 721-8396; Budget (250) 953-5300.
</P>
<P>
   Cool Web site: www.tourismvictoria.com
</P>
<P>
   Cool thing to do: Rent a bike or motor scooter and ride the back
roads.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
