<SLUG> BC-COOLPLACES-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP YOUR COOL: FOUR FABULOUS PLACES TO BEAT THE HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KATHRYN HOPPER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know it's coming.
</P>
<P>
   The relentless heat of the Texas summer sun will soon be here,
which means it's time to makes plans to be somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   If the thought of being near ice, snow, or anywhere evenings get
chilly enough for a long-sleeve cotton sweater sounds good come
July, then consider four vacation spots guaranteed to help you
chill out.
</P>
<P>
   LAND OF ENCHANTMENT: Somewhere between chic Santa Fe and plain
old El Paso is Ruidoso, a city equally removed from the first two
both geographically and spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's a French restaurant, but only one. Yes, there are
lots of Southwestern knickknacks, but they're reasonably priced.
Yes, there's a disco, but it's part of the liquor store.
</P>
<P>
   Ruidoso has served as a summer getaway for Texans for years, and
now it's booming right along with the Lone Star State. The main
drag through town, U.S. 70, is being widened to four lanes, and
construction is popping up like yarrow under the pinon trees.
</P>
<P>
   Like Fort Worth, Ruidoso has an odd mixture of cowboys and
culture. Horse lovers have long gathered at Ruidoso Downs, where
races are run every summer weekend. The action culminates on Labor
Day with the running of the $2 million Quarter Horse Futurity.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the track is The Museum of the Horse, which offers
a Las Colinaslike bronze sculpture of giddy equines dubbed Free
Spirits at Noisy Water.
</P>
<P>
   The area proudly plays on its ties to outlaw Billy the Kid, who
once eluded capture in a fight on Main Street by hiding in a flour
barrel. On May 28, the Billy the Kid Casino opens at Ruidoso Downs.
</P>
<P>
   The Spencer Theater for the Arts opened two years ago. The
514-seat auditorium is a stark modern building that looks a bit odd
in the rugged mountain landscape but draws a variety of artists,
from the Southern Comfort House of Blues tour to the National
Russian Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road off U.S. 70, the Hurd Ranch Guest House is a
combination upscale inn and art gallery. The inn has three adobe
casitas that boast every extra amenity from satellite dishes to
Saltillo tile floors.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch is also home to an impressive collection of works by
N.C. Wyeth and his son, Andrew Wyeth. Why so many Wyeths? Henrietta
Wyeth, N.C. Wyeth's daughter and Andrew's sister, married Hurd
Ranch founder Peter Hurd.
</P>
<P>
   If you're more into casinos than casitas, head for the Inn of
the Mountain Gods, which is part of the Mescalero Apache Indian
Reservation and, as such, can offer two floors of poker, slots and
keno.
</P>
<P>
   Dining options continue to multiply in Ruidoso. La Lorraine is
an intimate French bistro where lunch can be had for less than $15.
The Lincoln County Grill features sandwiches and burgers, plus such
caloric splurges as The Avalanche, a sundae sculpted to resemble a
mountain catastrophe with spiraling chocolate and swirling nuts.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Alto, hang with the locals at Farley's. The restaurant
offers decent pizza and cold beer, which can be enjoyed over Van
Halen tunes blaring from the jukebox. Billiards and bowling are
part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned that Ruidoso and the surrounding area have endured a
prolonged drought. On a recent visit, high winds kicked up enough
dust to cloud the mountain vistas, and the normally vigorous Rio
Ruidoso was weakening to creek status.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still trickle enough to dip your toe in the river
water and savor what's left of last winter's snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   Ruidoso, N.M.: Average July low: 47
</P>
<P>
   Cool information: Ruidoso Chamber of Commerce, (800) 253-2255;
Ruidoso Downs, (505) 378-4142; Spencer Center for the Performing
Arts, (888) 818-7872; Hurd Ranch Guest Homes, (505) 653-4331; Inn
of the Mountain Gods, (800) 545-9011.
</P>
<P>
   Cool Web site: www.ruidoso.net//reservations
</P>
<P>
   Cool thing to do: Order The Avalanche at The Lincoln County
Grill. The only thing it will kill is your appetite _ for the day.
</P>
<P>
   A GLACIER RAN THROUGH IT: Glacier: Even the name is enough to
give you a chill, or at least the hope of one.
</P>
<P>
   Although Glacier National Park in Montana does have glaciers, 38
at last count, they are getting smaller each year because of global
warming. Most park visitors view the glaciers from the famous Going
to the Sun Road, a 52-mile, two-lane blacktop that snakes along the
mountainsides, eventually crossing the Continental Divide at Logan
Pass.
</P>
<P>
   The road is typically open from June to around October, but
summer snows can sometimes block the way at higher elevations.
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to drive it yourself, but that means worrying
about tumbling over the guardrails on the many hairpin curves or
rear-ending the Winnebago in front of you. Instead, ride one of the
park's red buses, known as jammers.
</P>
<P>
   For an up-close glacier experience, brave the four-mile hiking
trail (all uphill) to Grinnell Glacier. It's just one of many
trails that wind around lakes and alpine meadows, all inviting
enough to send you into a Julie Andrews impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   But don't forget there are bears.
</P>
<P>
   I actually saw one of the estimated 200 grizzlies while
ensconced in my rented Ford Explorer. A young male grizzly
sauntered across Going to the Sun Road in search of huckleberries
or perhaps something even tastier _ Californians.
</P>
<P>
   Glacier devotees typically try to find accommodations inside the
park at one of several lodges operated by the park service. Those
rooms are quick to fill during the high summer season, so be
prepared to check out accommodations in nearby towns including
Whitefish and Kalispell in the Flathead Valley. The Grouse Mountain
Lodge in Whitefish is a pleasant convention-oriented hotel with a
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   The valley, named for the Flathead Indians, is in many ways just
as beautiful as Glacier, and certainly provides a softer summer
experience. It's worth making time to sail on Flathead Lake or raft
down the Middle Fork of the Flathead River.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Montana, load up on huckleberries. The wild
berries, a Rocky Mountain cousin to blueberries, are in season in
late summer. The park service offers maps for huckleberry picking.
</P>
<P>
   The Huckleberry Patch in Hungry Horse sells them in everything
from pancakes to milkshakes.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
