<HEADER>
A7131 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      05-06 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO REFUGEES: `YOU WILL GO HOME AGAIN IN SAFETY AND IN
FREEDOM' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGELHEIM, Germany _ President Clinton came face to face
Thursday with the reasons he has risked American soldiers' lives
and expended so much political capital in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time,the president sat down with a group of ethnic
Albanians who had been expelled from their homes in Kosovo by the
Serbs and had ended up at a refugee center in this small town about
an hour's drive southwest of Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton promised the refugees: ``You will go home again in
safety and in freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Joined by German Chancellor Gerhardt Schroeder, Clinton listened
as about two dozen men, women and teen-agers related often
emotionally wrenching tales of brutal treatment by the Serb police
and their fears of returning to live side by side with the same
people who threw them out of their country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are used to getting killed and getting murdered,'' one
woman told the leaders. ``But the rape is the most difficult thing
for Albanians. I just cannot describe it. I don't know how to
describe our suffering.``
</P>
<P>
   Others told of years of being harassed by Serbs, of eventually
being forced out of their homes by armed police, of being ordered
to hand over their gold and their cash in exchange for their lives
as they fled for the border.
</P>
<P>
   One man told of how the police demanded more cash than he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said I just have to go and look around to find it. And
then they said, don't come back without 1,000 deutsche marks. And
then I went and borrowed 1,000 marks and returned them to the
police. And they said, `Go and never come back in this land of
Kosovo,''' he told Clinton and Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier the president met in a dormitory style room with a
family of seven adults and two children, including a boy who was
born the night the NATO bombings began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The father, Sabit Salihu, 60, related how the family had been
chased from their homes in the village of Dervar on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``My home was burned. We were beaten. Everything was stolen from
us,'' Salihu said as he broke down in tears. ``It is impossible to
describe what they have done to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who Republicans in Congress are criticizing for
involving the United States in NATO's air campaign against Serbia,
urged the refugees to continue telling their tales to help bolster
worldwide support for their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that people not forget that what is called
ethnic cleansing is not some abstract idea; it is real people with
real families and real dreams being uprooted from their homes,
their schools, their work, their children, their parents, their
husbands and wives,'' the president said as many of the center's
300 refugees listened.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vowed to continue the bombing campaign against Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to ensure the refugees will eventually
be able to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Milosevic has not succeeded in erasing your identity from
the pages of history, and he will not succeed in erasing your
presence from the land of your parents and grandparents,'' the
president said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that computer terminals would be installed in
refugee centers that will provide ethnic Albanians news in their
own language about the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the refugees here the return home may be difficult
even if an agreement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Ekrem Lapashtica, a 24-year-old video store owner, said the
police gave his family five minutes to leave their Pristina
neighborhood. Lapashtica told of being forced to wait in long lines
to board trains to the Macedonia border while Serb police harassed
them and demanded money.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took some people and I don't know what happened to
them,'' Lapashtica said.
</P>
<P>
   Lapashtica said he rises every day and reads an Albanian
newspaper to find out what is going on in the conflict. With no
employment here, he spends the day playing pingpong at the sports
center in the compound, a group of spare buildings that resembles a
summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   Life in Germany is better for Lapashtica and others than for
many other refugees who are living in poor conditions in border
camps in Macedonia and Albania. But he said, ``I can hardly wait to
go back to Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he was asked if he could live with the Serbs,
Lapashtica responded, ``Never again.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
