<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7140 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALLORY-DAUGHTER-ART-     05-06 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALLORY-DAUGHTER-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMOUS CLIMBER'S DAUGHTER ``MISSED HIM TERRIBLY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TIM TESCONI   
 The (Santa Rosa, Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Clare Millikan was 8 years old on that June
day in 1924 when word came that her father, British mountain
climber George Mallory, had been ``lost'' on Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   Millikan, now 83 and living in Santa Rosa, soon realized she
would never see her beloved father again, a man who taught her to
climb trees and speak French. Mallory, a schoolmaster in Cambridge,
England, was a brilliant scholar and seasoned athlete known for his
adventurous spirit and crazy antics.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother gathered us on her bed to tell us that my father had
been lost on Mount Everest. I've always thought the word `lost' was
so confusing to a child, because if you're lost you can jolly well
be found again,'' Millikan said Wednesday from her Santa Rosa
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   She was the oldest of three children. Her sister, Beridge, was 6
and her brother, John, was 2 when their father vanished on June 8,
1924.
</P>
<P>
   This week, 75 years later, Millikan got word that her father's
body had been found on a windswept ledge on Mount Everest, the
world's tallest mountain. Preserved by the bitter cold temperatures
at that altitude, the body was found at 27,000 feet by five young
climbers retracing the route Mallory and his climbing partner,
Andrew Irvine, had taken in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mallory who quipped that he wanted to climb Everest
``because it is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Practical and spiritual, Millikan said that after nearly eight
decades the news that her father's body had been found didn't cause
too much grief. For years, she said, she has dreamed of her father
and his demise on Everest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed him terribly,'' she said. She had always hoped his
death was peaceful and painless. She said closure for her had come
years ago _ in her nightly dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't very excited when I heard. My father left his body so
long ago. His body has no use for him now,'' Millikan said.
</P>
<P>
   She said it's the family's desire that Mallory's body be left on
Everest, where it has reposed for generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one for bringing bodies back in body bags. I think a
body should stay where the person died,'' Millikan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need for something funereal now,'' said Millikan,
who for the past four years has lived at Friends House, a
Quaker-run residential center for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery of Mallory's and Irvine's disappearance has
intrigued the world, remaining one of the great unsolved adventure
stories of the century. Since they vanished, the persistent
question has been whether the men died while ascending or
descending Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   If they made it to the top of Everest, they would have been the
first, accomplishing the feat 29 years before Edmund Hillary and
Tenzing Norgay stood atop the mountain's 29,028-foot summit in June
1953. The hope is that the Kodak camera Mallory and Irvine carried
and the film inside will be found undamaged to solve the mystery.
If there is photographic proof, they would go into the record books
as the first to conquer Everest.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Britain they have always been national heroes. They name
Boy Scout troops after them,'' said Millikan, who has lived in the
United States for 60 years. A peace activist and environmentalist,
she lived in Berkeley until moving here.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Simonson, one of the Everest climbers searching for
evidence of Mallory and Irvine, said his group wants to determine
once and for all the fate of the English climbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The achievement of climbers such as George Mallory and Andrew
Irvine is not fully appreciated,'' Simonson said an interview with
Mountain Zone, a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get within a few hundred feet of the summit in 1924,
wearing tweed clothing and using extremely heavy and primitive
oxygen gear, was incredible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Irvine's body has not been found yet.
</P>
<P>
   Millikan said her great love for her father never made her feel
obligated to believe that he had ascended Mount Everest. She said
it really didn't matter to her whether he made it to the top or
not. She is haunted by fears that her father was more concerned
with conquering the mountain than returning to his family in
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to know that he took every possible precaution _
and didn't do anything harebrained _ so that he could come back to
his family. That would be important for me to know,'' said
Millikan, a rock climber herself when she was younger. Her husband,
Glenn Millikan, a renowned scientist, also died rock climbing. His
death in 1947 in a gorge in Tennessee left her to raise her three
sons, who also do rock climbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My one ambition was to go up and finish climbing Mount Everest
for my father,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Millikan remembers that when her father left for the expedition
to Mount Everest _ his third trip to the mountain _ he said he
would be careful and vowed to return unharmed. But, she said, it
was not to be.
</P>
<P>
   Millikan said that after her father's death there were dramatic
changes in her life. Her mother was forced to sell the family home
in Cambridge and move her family to her father's country home in
another part of England. Millikan said her grandfather was
financially well fixed, so her family had a comfortable life and
the children went to good schools and eventually universities.
</P>
<P>
   Millikan's sister, Beridge, who became a pediatrician in the
United States, died of breast cancer. Her brother, John Mallory,
lives in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   She said that as a child, she and her siblings would make grave
markers for birds that died after becoming entangled in nets to
protect the fruit on trees. She said they also made little graves
piled with flowers for their father because they had no headstone
in a cemetery to mourn their loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way to heal and pay homage to our lost father,''
Millikan said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
