<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN-SAVVY CLINTON TO ATTEND TEXAS FUND-RAISERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
and ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton drops by La Colombe d'Or in
Houston &UR;  &LR; on Friday, he won't be just sampling the French cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   As he has so many times in the past, the president will be
prospecting for cash in the Lone Star State, this time on behalf of
the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The trip, however, comes at a time of intense competition for
campaign dollars in a state that has increasingly tilted away from
the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The state's popular Republican Gov. George W. Bush has been
vacuuming up funds across the state for his expected presidential
bid. Of the $7.6 million that Bush has reported raising for his
exploratory committee this year, $4 million came from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, some Texas Democratic donors would rather give to
congressional campaigns where they can be assured the money will
remain in the state. Money contributed to the national party often
is spent elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee
raised $1 million on a swing through Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly competition for campaign money in Texas
these days,'' Houston political consultant Nancy Sims said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sims said corporate executives, lawyers and others in
Texas who want to nourish simultaneous bonds with Republican and
Democratic leaders will continue to find a way to signal their
support for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   And despite their sagging electoral fortunes in the state, Texas
is still viewed as a gold mine by national Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent election cycle, which ended last December,
the national Democratic Party and its candidates scooped up more
than $16 million from Texas, about 40 percent of all money raised
in the state over the two-year period, according to the Center for
Responsive Politics. Only in New York, California and Illinois did
the party do better.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee alone raised $1.4 million in
unrestricted ``soft money'' contributions during the 1997-98
election cycle from Texas, according to the Center for Responsive
Politics analysis. The donor list includes some of the state's top
companies and their executives, many of whom have a stake in
decision-making in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC received $55,000 in corporate and employee giving from
the natural gas giant Enron, which is lobbying for electric utility
deregulation and is headed by prominent Houston Republican Ken Lay.
</P>
<P>
   The party also received about half that much from Maxxam Inc., a
Houston-based timber, aluminum and real estate conglomerate that
recently reached a deal with federal regulators to sell a stand of
centuries-old redwood trees in northern California.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines, Houston-based Browning Ferris Industries and
EDS, the computer company formerly owned by independent
presidential candidate Ross Perot, also contributed to the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats even received $10,000 from the financier wife of
Richard Rainwater, the Fort Worth billionaire who has been a
business partner of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Trial lawyers, however, stand out as the Democrats' best friends
in Texas when it comes to dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list of Texas contributors to the DNC was
Houston-based Williams &AMP; Bailey, a high-octane personal injury law
firm. Partner Kenneth Bailey is hosting Friday's fund-raising
luncheon at the posh La Colombe d'Or in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Between 30 to 40 people are expected to shell out $20,000 a
couple to hear the president, with the party officials estimating
the event will bring in $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bailey's partners, John Eddie Williams, will share a $3.3
billion fee for his role with four other lawyers in a recent state
tobacco settlement. The firm gave a total of $250,000 to the
Democratic Party over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The president will end his day in Texas at a fund-raiser in
Austin at the home of an old friend, Roy Spence. The advertising
executive has known Clinton since the two worked on George
McGovern's presidential campaign in 1972. With a minimum
contribution of $1,000 required and a crowd of 125 expected, the
event should generate $250,000, according to DNC officials.
</P>
<P>
   The two events had originally been scheduled for last month but
were canceled because they were scheduled a day after the Colorado
high school massacre.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said Clinton was pressured to quickly reschedule
his Texas trip to prevent some of the donors from reneging on their
financial commitments. Much of the money has already been collected
for the two events.
</P>
<P>
   ``They paid for it. They want the man standing in their living
room.'' said state Democratic Party spokeswoman Liz Chadderdon.
</P>
<P>
   A fund-raiser Clinton headlined for Democratic gubernatorial
candidate Garry Mauro last September netted about $250,000 for
Mauro's campaign, despite a disastrous finish at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   DNC spokesman Peter Kauffmann said the president, despite last
year's scandal, still remains a big draw.
</P>
<P>
   However, the president's approval rating has declined in Texas
since his impeachment ordeal, according to the latest Texas Poll.
The survey of 1,003 Texans found that 48 percent believe he is
doing a good job as president while 49 percent disapprove of his
job performance. In a previous survey, conducted during the Senate
impeachment trial, Clinton's job approval stood at 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And many Democrats are unhappy that DNC fund-raisers tend not
only to siphon money out of the state for projects that do not help
elect local candidates but also end up hampering other fund-raising
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they don't do well,'' said one top Democratic House
aide of the national party's fund-raising events in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The aide said the congressional Democrats need all the cash they
can raise to help retake the House in 2000. If Democrats hope to
regain the House they cannot afford to lose the 17 seats they now
hold in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also are focusing on keeping control of the Texas
House and retaking the state Senate to ensure the party can play a
role in congressional redistricting after the 2000 Census.
</P>
<P>
   The DCCC hosted a fund-raiser in Houston on April 8 at the home
of lawyer Lee Godfrey, which featured House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Houston lawyer Richard Mithoff said he was willing to shell out
money for the DCCC because it helps candidates in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to do is put the money where I think it will
make the biggest difference,'' Mithoff said. ``And I think that is
the view of a lot of my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Kauffmann at the DNC said that the party does return a
small portion of the money raised to the state parties. In the last
election cycle it was 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
