<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOLLOY-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOLLOY': BEFORE THE WAITING STARTED, BECKETT LOVED HIS MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WILBORN HAMPTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before Gogo and Didi began their long wait for Godot,
before Clov and Hamm wound up the alarm clock, before Krapp began
making tapes, Molloy resolved to go and see his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Beckett conceived ``Molloy,'' the first novel in his
caustic trilogy that includes ``Malone Dies'' and ``The
Unnamable,'' after a revelatory visit to his mother in Dublin
during which he realized she had not long to live. It was at that
moment, he said later, that he ``became aware of my stupidity; then
I began to write the things I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Molloy'' was the first inspiration of Beckett's new creative
life, and it previews the compelling and darkly humorous works for
the stage for which he became most famous and is now more widely
remembered. Although written as an interior monologue, the novel is
as gripping as any of the plays and would seem ideal for the
theater. Conor Lovett, an Irish actor, has excerpted passages from
the first part of ``Molloy,'' and is presenting them at the Irish
Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   Lovett's program credits list appearances in several Beckett
plays, and he clearly understands the text. He captures all the
rhythms and nuances of Molloy's strange account of his search for
his mother, and he delivers these fragmented snatches of memory in
a deadpan monotone that is effective. But what is oddly missing is
any sense of dramatic continuity to the story. The selection of the
material seems more like an abridged sampler of ``Molloy'' than any
serious attempt to get at the heart of the novel itself.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Lovett ignores the famous opening _ ``I am in my
mother's room. It's I who live there now. I don't know how I got
there.'' _ and takes all his material from about one-fourth of the
first section of the novel, and all of it from the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The excerpts chosen by Lovett and also by Judy Hegarty, who
directs the performance, appear aimed at underscoring the comedy in
Beckett's novel, especially the scatological (almost as if Howard
Stern helped in the editing), and Lovett's delivery at times more
resembles a stand-up comic's routine than a one-man dramatization.
There is mystery and suspense as well as humor in the novel, with
Beckett doling out little hints to the plot and character of Molloy
along the way, but Lovett seems to be playing straight for punch
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hegarty's direction does little to enhance the theatricality
of the performance. When Lovett occasionally drops into the voice
of the different characters Molloy meets _ a policeman or Lousse,
the woman whose dog he runs over with his bicycle _ they all tend
to sound alike. The decision not to put Lovett's Molloy on crutches
(or his bike), but to stand in one of three solo spots on a bare
stage, only enhances the impression of this ``Molloy'' being an
audition for an evening of Beckett at Caroline's.
</P>
<P>
   But the words are still those of one of our century's greatest
storytellers, and if Lovett's hour of recitation brings no special
insights to Beckett's extraordinary tale, the humor he conveys may
send his theater audience to the novel itself, and that would be no
small accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MOLLOY'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Judy Hegarty; production manager, Rebecca Wilson;
lighting by Jeff Tapper; producers, Georganne Aldrich Heller and
Beverly Karp. The text is compiled from the first part of Samuel
Beckett's novel ``Molloy.'' The Gare St. Lazare production is
presented by the Irish Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   With: Conor Lovett (Molloy).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
