<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, May 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   High pressure centered over the Grand Banks will circulate
ocean-chilled air into the coastal regions of New England and the
Middle Atlantic region Friday, causing low clouds to linger from
Delaware to southeast Maine. As onshore winds ascend the east
slopes of the Appalachians, fog and drizzle will develop. Just over
the crest of the Appalachians, a warm and humid air mass will be
found from central New York to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Sultry weather will persist in the Southeast, but an approaching
cool front will be the focus of more intense thunderstorms from the
Florida panhandle to the western Carolinas. Most of Florida and the
Southeast Coast will be dry with ample sun.
</P>
<P>
   A jet stream disturbance will move through the Ohio Valley as
the northern section of a cold front pushes slowly eastward. The
air mass over eastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania and New York will
be ripe for gusty thunderstorms. A couple of storms may become
severe.
</P>
<P>
   The storm center which has brought clouds and showers all week
to the northern Plains and Midwest will make slow progress toward
Lake Superior causing dull, cool and damp conditions to linger over
the Dakotas, Minnesota and parts of Nebraska and Iowa. A corridor
of dry and pleasant weather will stretch from the southern Plains
to Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Colder, moist air from the North Pacific will surge into the
Northern Rockies, accompanied by clouds and showers, especially in
the mountains. The Southwest will be quite warm over the interior,
but fog should return to the southwest California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Limited in Scope
</P>
<P>
   Most outbreaks of severe weather are limited in scope. Suppose
the Storm Prediction Center in Norman, Okla., issues a tornado
watch that covers 30,000 square miles of the Deep South. Further
assume that, within the watch area, two massive 60-mile long,
half-mile wide twisters develop. This affected area amounts to 0.2
percent of the watch area. Now suppose that several smaller
tornadoes also occur in addition to narrow streaks of large hail
and damaging straight-line winds. In most cases, the total area
affected by severe weather would still only amount to a fraction of
1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
