<SLUG> BC-STAR-WARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME AROUND, THE FORCE MAY NOT BE WITH IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Perish the thought! Will the new ``Star Wars'' prove
to be a bit of a disappointment?
</P>
<P>
   The new George Lucas extravaganza, ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace,'' which opens on May 19, was shown to film industry
exhibitors under tight security on Tuesday night in eight cities,
including Los Angeles and New York. Although some executives who
saw the movie said they thought it would have enormous appeal for
children, some fans and distributors said the 130-minute $115
million epic was not as good as earlier installments of the ``Star
Wars'' series like ``Star Wars'' or ``The Empire Strikes Back.''
Variety reported Thursday that there was a ``less than
enthusiastic'' response to the film at the screenings and that
reactions were decidedly mixed, with only polite applause in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   On the Ain't It Cool News Web site (www.aint-it-cool-news.com)
some fans who apparently slipped into the screenings complained
that the story was weak and the film too ``young-themed'' and
``kid-friendly'' to appeal to adults. They said the film had ``no
chance of overtaking `Titanic's' ticket sales or critical
adulation.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus on the Web site was that the special effects were
dazzling but that the film, released by 20th Century Fox, would
appeal mostly to children. ``Good, but not great,'' one 16-year-old
fan wrote. ``As a science fiction film it was excellent. But as a
`Star Wars' film? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Another said, ``I was really hoping to like it more.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, studio executives said, expectations for the film
are so extraordinary that it is bound to disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sherak, chairman of 20th Century Fox's Domestic Film Group,
said the film had been shown to recruited audiences in 16 cities
over the last two days. Eight screenings were scheduled Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response has been fantastic,'' Sherak said. As for the
criticism, Sherak said, ``You can take the Gettysburg Address and
find holes in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sherak added that the two screenings in New York and Los
Angeles ``did not go over the moon'' for two reasons. At the Astor
Plaza Theater in Manhattan, he said, the air-conditioning broke
down and left the audience in a disgruntled mood. ``Rosie O'Donnell
said on television that it was 120 degrees,'' he said. In Los
Angeles, Sherak said, there were not many children in the audience
and the ones who were there were admonished by their parents to be
quiet because it was an important screening. ``Kids were on their
best behavior,'' he said. ``But when we've screened it elsewhere,
the kids applaud. They cheer. It plays through the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Two rival studio executives who have every reason to criticize
the movie because they have films opening in June that could be
hurt by the competition said they were dazzled by it. But one said
he doubted that the movie would earn the kind of repeat business
among teen-agers and adults that made James Cameron's ``Titanic''
such a huge hit. That film has grossed about $1.8 billion around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrific,'' one executive said of ``Star Wars: Episode I
_ The Phantom Menace.'' ``It absolutely delivers. It's a great show
for the family. But there may be some question of adult
replayability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It does go a little younger,'' he said of the film, which is
rated PG. ``Especially in these days of hard-edged PG-13 movies.
This is definitely PG.''
</P>
<P>
   Another top studio executive who saw the film said: ``The
effects are brilliant. It's everything you would expect out of the
film. The story is fun. The characters are not as emotional as the
first installment. There's not that rebelliousness and casualness
that you had in Harrison Ford.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, virtually everyone in Hollywood expects the long-awaited
sequel to emerge as the biggest film of the summer and probably the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The film is the first of three planned ``prequels'' that will
trace young Anakin Skywalker's rise to Jedi knight and his ultimate
surrender to the Dark Side. Its stars include Ewan McGregor as
Obi-Wan Kenobi; Liam Neeson as Qui-Gon Jinn, the Jedi master;
Natalie Portman as Queen Amidale, and Jake Lloyd as young Anakin.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who is usually reserved and press-shy, has thrown himself
into a publicity blitz for the movie, which many film industry
executives say could take in as much as $100 million in its first
five days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
