<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For `Parade,' Life After Death
</P>
<P>
   Call it a miracle or a menace, but ``Parade,'' the long-closed
musical produced by a deeply bankrupt company, refuses to fade
away.
</P>
<P>
   The musical's life after death was highlighted on Monday morning
when it landed nine nominations for the Tony Awards, more than any
other show.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday ``Parade'' was voted best musical by the New York
Drama Critics Circle, although after a squabble over whether any
award at all should be given in such an anemic season.
</P>
<P>
   More accolades for the show might come on Sunday, when the Drama
Desk announces its awards: ``Parade'' is nominated for 13 awards,
again more than any other production.
</P>
<P>
   Some producers say the attention paid to ``Parade'' reiterates
the paucity of decent musicals this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In another season, they would have been happy not to nominate
it,'' said one producer, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
``But it's the only real musical there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates for best book for Tony, for example, included
the limited narration of ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' and
Pam Gems' well-worn backstage ancedotes in ``Marlene.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ``Parade'' nomination was for choreography, another
element in short supply in this season _ and, in fact, in
``Parade.''
</P>
<P>
   But the show's producers said the attention was deserved. ``The
operative words are `validation' and `bittersweet,''' said Bernard
Gersten, the executive producer of Lincoln Center Theater, a
producer of the show with Livent, which has been in bankruptcy
court since November.
</P>
<P>
   Gersten said that 75 percent of Tony voters had seen the show
before it closed on Feb. 28 and that the cast album, released last
month, was sent to all voters.
</P>
<P>
   The musical is likely to have a production number _ the duet
``All the Wasted Time'' _ at the Tony broadcast on June 6, he
added. But Keith Sherman, a spokesman for the show, would not
confirm this.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond CDs and award plaques, the show may have another life.
Officials for the Prince Music Theater in Philadelphia, named for
the ``Parade'' director Hal Prince, said on Wednesday that a new
production of the musical is likely for spring 2000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's Humming &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If this year's crop of musicals wilted on the vine, the harvest
season may bring some hope.
</P>
<P>
   After an ultra-private reading of the score and script last
Friday, confirmation came this week for one highly anticipated
production: ``Wise Guys,'' by Stephen Sondheim and John Weidman.
</P>
<P>
   Producers Scott Rudin and Roger Berlind plan to present the
musical, about two rakish brothers, in November at the New York
Theater Workshop in the East Village. In an odd twist, the
production will only be open to workshop members; no public tickets
are available. Victor Garber and Nathan Lane will star.
</P>
<P>
   The creative overhaul of ``Aida'' continues elsewhere. Disney
officials confirmed this week that the playwright David Henry Hwang
is working on the book of the Broadway-bound musical, which stalled
in Atlanta last fall after mediocre reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Hwang, whose official title will be ``creative consultant,''
joins a new team whose aim seems to be to add artistic gravitas to
a show whose earlier incarnation was considered too cartoonlike.
The newcomers include the director Robert Falls (a Tony nominee for
``Death of a Salesman'') and the designer Bob Crowley (a double
Tony nominee for ``Iceman Cometh'' and ``Twelfth Night''). The
first performances of the new ``Aida,'' are planned for November in
Chicago. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Success in `Sideman' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Off Off Broadway actors decided the Tony Awards, Frank Wood
would have been a shoo-in years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of his 12-year career, Wood has been a common
sight at such downtown theaters as LaMama, SoHo Rep and the
Workhouse Theater, now called the Flea. ``I was always seeing the
same people in the audience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for much of last year Wood has been on Broadway, playing the
emotionally removed father in ``Side Man,'' a performance that was
rewarded on Monday with a Tony nomination for featured actor.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination came as something of a surprise to the
38-year-old actor. ``People had been saying it might be possible,
and I said, `No, it won't,''' he said. `But all of the sudden,
about 48 hours before, I got queasy.''
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of the New York University graduate acting program,
Wood has been with the play since its early readings in 1996.
Between nonpaying acting jobs and low-paying day jobs, Wood said he
had some ``extended fantasies'' about leaving the business.
</P>
<P>
   But now he says he hopes to be around for a while. ``I would
tell my dad, `I think I'm on the cusp,' meaning `Lend me some
money,''' Wood said. ``But when I told him about the nomination, he
said, `You turned out to be right.''' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James Houghton, who built the Signature Theater Company into one
of New York's more prominent Off Broadway theater companies, has
been named as the successor to Lloyd Richards as the artistic
director of the Eugene O'Neill National Playwrights Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Richards has led the annual conference in Waterford, Conn.,
since 1969. Among the plays developed under Richards' direction
include ``House of Blue Leaves'' and ``Fences.'' Houghton is to
continue as artistic director of the Signature.
</P>
<P>
   Bebe Neuwirth has signed to play the title role in this summer's
production of ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' at the Williamstown
Theater Festival in Williamstown, Mass. Also confirmed this week:
David Schwimmer (of the NBC sitcom ``Friends'') in ``The Glimmer
Brothers,'' and Barry Edelstein as director of ``As You Like It,''
starring Gwyneth Paltrow.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a last-minute injection of cash from new investors or
ticket buyers, ``The Gershwins' Fascinating Rhythm'' will close on
Sunday, producers said Thursday. The revue opened April 25 to
generally poor reviews.
</P>
</TEXT>
