<HEADLINE>
SABATES ADMITS HE MADE MISTAKES WITH RACING TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Tenn.) (rk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has not gone the way Felix Sabates planned.
</P>
<P>
   His two drivers, Joe Nemechek of Lakeland, Fla., and Sterling
Marlin of Columbia, Tenn., have managed just one top-10 finish
between them, a ninth at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth by
Marlin.
</P>
<P>
   Both are mired far down in the point standings, Marlin at 16th
and Nemechek at 38th.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sabates, that wasn't supposed to happen this year.
</P>
<P>
   After years of turmoil and changes on Team SABCO, Sabates
thought he had things under control. Cuban-born Sabates' revolving
door had spit out drivers, crew chiefs, mechanics, sponsors and
cars at a frantic pace until this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a big mistake when I hired Robby Gordon. It set us back
three years,'' Sabates remarked. ``At the time, it seemed like the
right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very disruptive. I'm lucky nobody quit. He really
caused some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In a follow-the-leader mode, the leader being Rick Hendrick,
Sabates expanded from a one-car to a three-car team in 1997,
bringing in the talented but temperamental Gordon from the
open-wheel ranks as his lead driver.
</P>
<P>
   It never worked. Gordon acted like a prima donna from the start.
He trashed Sabates' operation and failed to last the season.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, Sabates, who lives in Charlotte, N.C., struggled
to make his three-car team work, then dropped to two this season
when he lost one of his sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he admits going to three cars before he even had one
working well was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jumped in too quick,'' Sabates said. ``I thought I could
make it go. I was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had too many distractions, and we were spread too thin in
the engine department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got much more stability this year,'' Sabates said. ``We
didn't lose a single person except for the group I had to let go
when we dropped the 46 (his third car, driven primarily by Jeff
Green in 1998).''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite a more smoothly functioning operation, Sabates'
cars are still not competitive.
</P>
<P>
   That may reflect on the personnel. While Sabates has a
hard-working group led by team manager Tony Glover, who made a name
for himself when he was crew chief for Ernie Irvan and Marlin when
both won the Daytona 500, few teams match up to the likes of Jeff
Gordon, Mark Martin, Dale Jarrett and a couple others.
</P>
<P>
   And those are the teams you have to beat if you expect to win
races and championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about a championship right now. I'd be happy
if we can finish in the top 15,'' Sabates remarked.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I feel we can do that. It takes time to build things back
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when they hadn't been built very high to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
