<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV13-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TAKE OUR DAUGHTERS TO WORK DAY' SUCCESS STORIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, May 13)  
(mk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because my daughter is 2, she didn't come to my office for Take
Our Daughters to Work Day, although I look forward to the time when
she's old enough to help me write an inviting lead or choose what
photographs to play with a centerpiece package.
</P>
<P>
   My 8-year-old son has been to my office several times, and by no
means do I intend to leave him out of what Mom does for a living.
In fact, the other day when I got my hair cropped short for summer,
he told me: ``You look good. You look like an editor. Like a boss
of someone.''
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that's a vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But I see daughters benefiting from this special day, especially
the ones whose dads let them tag along. Our company's graphic
artist brought his 10-year-old daughter with him. They drew
together with markers and went out for pizza. And we all caught up
on fifth-grade fashion: clunky shoes and fluffy purses.
</P>
<P>
   Last year on Take Our Daughters day, which is always on the
fourth Thursday of April, I had a very special guest. A dear
friend, who had breast cancer, asked me to bring her daughter to
the paper because the child was interested in writing. We typed a
bit into the computers that morning, had a fun lunch, and even
bought a new Beanie Baby at a downtown boutique. (No woman's ever
too young to learn to fit in some errands over lunch break.) A poem
she wrote was published in the newspaper's poetry corner the
following week.
</P>
<P>
   The Ms. Foundation for Women, creators of the Take Our Daughters
to Work Day, have come out with a new book, ``Girls Seen and Heard:
52 Life Lessons for Our Daughters'' (Putnam, 1998, $12). The book
grew out of one belief: that girls were confident at 11, but
confused at 16. What happened in those five years?
</P>
<P>
   Well, puberty for one. An interest in boys. Body image. Emerging
sexuality. And a growing awareness of what the world expects of
them.
</P>
<P>
   These life lessons are intended to be ammunition against this
difficult time. Some of the ideas are tangible (a scrapbook to keep
track of activities, filled with crayons, markers, scissors, glue
and disposable camera to create a record of why ``I'm a girl worth
watching''). Others are starting points for discussions (moms and
daughters writing poetry together about memories past; making a
list of ``what's right about yourself;'' having ``dream update''
sessions.)
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of Take Our Daughters to Work success stories: A
group of girls who got their fathers' company to quit investing in
a tobacco company. Firefighters who had taken their sons to sit in
the firetrucks but never their daughters until one of the firemen
started participating in the event. Girls who developed a new
appreciation for how hard their parents worked and how important
their jobs are as nurses and teachers and truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also anecdotes of girlhoods gone awry, which
suggest some steps that might have prevented tragedies like alcohol
poisoning, an arrest for drug dealing or unprotected sex. One idea
emphasized repeatedly is to get preteen girls involved in
after-school activities that keep them active and interested, and
give them a place to belong, such as band, karate or soccer. Many
of the lessons are for the parents too _ a reminder that our
children learn from watching us. Dare to live a creative,
fulfilling life, and your daughters will believe that it can be
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know why adults are always asking kids what they want to
be when they grow up?'' asks comedian Paula Poundstone. ``'Cause
they're looking for ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland, Fla., Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
