<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7188 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-JAPAN07-COX     05-06 1771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-JAPAN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Discovering Japan's Three Beautiful Scenic Views
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a place, on a mountaintop, overlooking a band of sand
stretching across an ocean bay, where the Japanese go to see the
mythical Bridge to Heaven. It's a remote spot, called
Amanohashidate, revered as the place where creation gods spilled
jeweled drops of brine to form the islands of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese have hiked up the mountain, wearing kimonos, for
centuries. Today, they can ride a cable car to a special viewing
platform.
</P>
<P>
   There, on the mountaintop, those who truly want to ``see'' the
bridge in the sea below must perform a time-honored ritual. They
turn their backs to the water. They bend over at the waist. And
they gaze from between their legs _ looking at the world upside
down and backwards _ at the panorama spread out before them.
</P>
<P>
   This is the one place where Japan's world-famous rules of formal
etiquette don't apply. Dozens of giggling Japanese bend over and
point their rear ends toward the sky to achieve the proper view of
the Miyazu Bay and the sacred, 2-mile long sand bar that arches
across it. When seen upside down and backward, this crescent of
sand seems to float in a blue sky, a sacred bridge with no
beginning or end.
</P>
<P>
   The Bridge to Heaven may be an optical illusion, but it is so
important to the Japanese that it is designated one of the Three
Beautiful Scenic Views of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Travel books don't give much ink to this triumvirate of beauty,
known in the Japanese language as the ``Nihon Sankei.'' The three
natural sites are not the familiar cultural icons the world
associates with Japan. Majestic Mt. Fuji didn't make the list.
Neither did the carefully raked gravel meditation gardens of the
Zen monks or the spectacular cherry blossoms that inspire haiku
contests.
</P>
<P>
   The list seems as unlikely as an American ``tally of grandeur''
that rejects the Grand Canyon, Yellowstone and the towering
Sequoias.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Japan's list is perfectly Japanese. It embraces what is not
conspicuous. It captures a beauty laced with an essence of
subtlety. Like the unhurried washing of a ceramic cup that turns a
tea ceremony into a work of art. Or the Japanese archery
tournaments that award more points for the slow, precise pulling of
the bow than for hitting the bull's eye.
</P>
<P>
   A personal quest
</P>
<P>
   I knew nothing about the three views until I went to Japan for a
fellowship program sponsored by the Japan Society in New York City.
A small mention of the scenic views in a guidebook caught my
attention because each location was within hailing distance from a
major city I was scheduled to visit.
</P>
<P>
   That did it. Visiting these three beautiful spots became my
personal quest. In my mind, I chanted their names so often that the
exotic-sounding titles became a mantra.
</P>
<P>
   These are the most honorable places:
</P>
<P>
   Miyajima, an island near Hiroshima where a giant, red shrine
gate stands in the bay and appears to float at high tide.
</P>
<P>
   Matsushima, a collection of pine-covered islands off the coast
of Northern Japan so beguiling that Matsuo Basho, the father of
haiku, could say nothing more than ``Matsushima, Ah! Matsushima!
Matsushima!'' when he visited in the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   The legendary Bridge to Heaven, the sand bar that's covered with
gnarled pines in a bay off the Sea of Japan, three hours by train
from the ancient temple city of Kyoto.
</P>
<P>
   During a four-month stay, I never met anyone in Japan who had
visited all three sights. Their far-flung locations _ one on the
Pacific Coast, one in the Inland Sea and another off the Sea of
Japan _ makes it difficult to hit all three. Most Japanese use
their scant vacation time to revisit their favorite shrine or
family in their hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew about the three beautiful places, but no one could
tell me who had selected the sights. Or why. Or when. Like so many
other things in Japan, the list of the three most scenic views was
just accepted as official because it had been designated so.
</P>
<P>
   But as I pinpointed the three places on a map of Japan, a common
theme appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Water.
</P>
<P>
   Each scenic view focuses on an object floating in water, the
life force most cherished by the Japanese. Every aspect of Japanese
culture is tied to water _ food, tea ceremony, flower arranging,
papermaking, rice paddies, cloth dying, gardening and the long
luxury of the bathhouse. The imagery of water is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Even Japan's most famous haiku, by Basho, embraces water:
</P>
<P>
   ``The old pond _
</P>
<P>
   a frog jumps in,
</P>
<P>
   sound of water.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan is an island nation, and the sea that kept the Japanese
samurai world isolated from the West until Commodore Matthew Perry
arrived in 1853 is still shaping the national character. Japan has
become one of the world's most advanced countries, unleashing
robots and Walkmen, but its people are still in tune with the
rhythms of the tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mizu'' is the Japanese word for water. Mizu is sacred and holy
and honorable. Mizu is the beautiful in the Three Beautiful Scenic
Views.
</P>
<P>
   Arrangement of form is at the heart of the Japanese aesthetic.
The Japanese appreciate not only beautiful objects, but also the
spacing between them. ``One looks not only at trees and leaves
themselves, but at the shapes and areas of sky they enclose, not
only at the distribution of stones on a beach, but the water and
sand between,'' American artist Frances Blakemore wrote in 1975
when she had an art gallery in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Each of Japan's three official beautiful views allows visitors
to contemplate the relationship between the land and the sea, how
one cannot be without the other.
</P>
<P>
   But I found more than visual beauty at the three sites. Each one
revealed a key aspect of Japanese heritage and offered cultural
enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermilion gate
</P>
<P>
   At Miyajima, I came face-to-face with Shinto, the indigenous
religion of Japan that predates Buddhism. Miyajima is home to a
large Shinto shrine, Itsukushima Jinja, originally built in 593 and
dedicated to the deities of fishing.
</P>
<P>
   In Shintoism, all natural things are believed to possess a
spiritual side. Shinto honors gods of nature, but offers no
doctrine. It is an ancient religion of ceremony, and gods are
honored with performance of rituals. Worshipers must purify
themselves before entering a shrine by washing their hands and
mouth at a special pavilion. At the main shrine hall, visitors toss
donations into a box, pull a rope that rings a bell, clap three
times and bow to the gods.
</P>
<P>
   Miyajima's prime object of enduring beauty is the 53-foot
vermilion gateway that stands sentry in the bay in front of the
shrine. The gate's beauty is affected by the tides. At high tide,
the formidable gate, called a ``torii,'' appears to be floating on
the water. At night, the archway shimmers under floodlights.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, all boats arriving at Miyajima had to pass
through the gate.
</P>
<P>
   The area had the feel of a tourist trap, with souvenir shops and
food vendors around every corner. But the giant red torii in the
water, more elaborately carved than most shrine gates, kept
catching my eye. It seemed to pulsate as a beacon to keep me
focused on the shrine and the sacredness of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Islands in the bay
</P>
<P>
   The second beautiful scenic spot, Matsushima, highlighted the
geography of isolation that has shaped so much of Japan's culture,
a way of life based for centuries on separateness from the rest of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Matsushima is a bay filled with more than 250 small islands that
dot the sea like flotillas of runaway Christmas tree lots. Each
islet is a different size and shape, and some have natural arches
that a sightseeing boat can pass through. They stretch into the far
horizon and seem to keep going on forever.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing the islands is like looking at pint-sized replicas of
the larger Japanese islands. People in Japan are proud of their
island heritage, but the four main islands are so big it is
difficult to get the sense of an archipelago when you are on them.
The Matsushima islands are a humbling reminder of the passage of
time and the evolution of land masses.
</P>
<P>
   In Matsushima, I headed up one of the tallest hills in town to
catch the same view seen by Basho, who made a pilgrimage to
Matsushima in the late 1600s. Today, part of the view is marred by
the smokestacks of a nearby power plant, but islands floating on
the horizon still hold an aura of exotic Japanese mystique.
</P>
<P>
   The Bridge to Heaven
</P>
<P>
   The third beautiful view, Amanohashidate, the Bridge to Heaven,
was my stepping stone to Japanese mythology, which modern Japanese
continue to hold dear. The creation of Japan is attributed to a
male and female god who stood on the Amanohashidate sand bar in the
dawn of time and stirred sea water with a jeweled spear. The
droplets formed an island where they married and begat more gods of
nature, including deities of the oceans, moon and sun.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese myth merged into history in the year 500 when the first
emperor of Japan claimed to be the son of a god. Until the end of
World War II, the emperor of Japan and his imperial family were
considered to be descendants of the gods. Even today, the emperor
conducts secret rituals at harvest time in which he is supposed to
mate with the earth goddess.
</P>
<P>
   Amanohashidate is perched on a fishing bay off the Sea of Japan.
The town is divided by the famous sand bar that forms the legendary
Bridge to Heaven. The sand spit is just 2 miles long and only 66
feet wide in some places. As I walked the tree-shaded trail, the
breeze that caresses the tall pines filled the air with a soft
symphony of whispers.
</P>
<P>
   I rode a cable car up the mountain to the Bridge to Heaven
viewing platforms with a Japanese tour group. We walked together to
the edge of the mountainside, but no one wanted to be the first to
bend over in front of the crowd. A few awkward minutes passed
before modesty gave way to mirth and the bending over began.
</P>
<P>
   When I took my turn, I couldn't see the Bridge to Heaven right
away. All I saw was a big sand bar looming behind me. But then I
remembered the instructions to look only at the view that appeared
between my legs. Suddenly, the sand bar was framed and centered. I
squinted to blur the view a bit, and then the image of an ancient
bridge began to shimmer before me.
</P>
<P>
   Folded into the ultimate Japanese bow, I learned that beauty
appears to those willing to look for it. Even when it's upside down
and backward.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
