<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7200 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      05-06 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS TEEN BOY A THREAT OR A VICTIM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Days before the massacre at Columbine High School in
Colorado, 14-year-old Tim Murphy turned in a fictional story, a
fairy tale, for a class at Pioneer Elementary School in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   Tim is an eighth-grader, an athlete, but he's not the best
student. He had trouble coming up with an idea for his story.
</P>
<P>
   His mother says a friend of Tim's in the same class decided to
base his fairy tale on the teen TV show ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer.'' The friend's's story was called ``The Teacher Slayer.''
It was meant also to be a take-off on a movie called ``The
Faculty,'' in which teachers at a high school turn out to be space
aliens who are destroyed by students. (``The Republic's'' Bob
Fenster called it ``a gore fest.'')
</P>
<P>
   Tim's mother, Kristin, says her son took the idea for his own
fairy tale from that of his pal. Tim's story was titled, ``The
Wicked Teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   In it, a teacher who appears nice at first turns out to be a
witch who attacks the protagonist. Tim's tale reads in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``She sliced his finger off and tackled him. She tore his flesh
with her teeth and just then a couple of his friends came in and
just happened to have a shotgun. The teacher was just about to kill
Joey when, boom! The teacher's head was in about sixty million
pieces on the wall.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
MASS HYSTERIA
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not long after turning in the assignment, Tim received a 10-day
suspension for ``written statements that threaten the safety of
school staff.'' Today, he faces a long-term suspension hearing that
could keep him from ever returning to Pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so emotionally distraught over this,'' Kristin said. ``I
know my son. I know he's not a threat to anyone. The fact they're
trying to link my son to that type of behavior is really horrifying
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Tim's mom, at least one teacher with whom Tim has
had trouble in the past has gone outside the school disciplinary
process to file a complaint with the police over Tim's fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that there is a mass hysteria linking this to
what happened at Columbine High School,'' she said. ``I want to
protect our children as much as anyone, but I'm afraid we're going
to wildly overreact.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course we are.
</P>
<P>
   That's what we do in America. We ignore problems until it's too
late, then respond in a way that's completely out of proportion.
It'll happen soon in schools across the land.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin read Tim's story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was bad judgment on my part not making him change
it,'' she said. But, she added, Tim's class has read stories by
Stephen King in school. And he watches movies and TV, like every
American boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just took down my copy of `Grimm's Fairy Tales,' '' she
said. ``They're as gory as it gets. But that doesn't mean the Grimm
brothers killed people.''
</P>
<P>
   Denton Santarelli, a Peoria School District official, told me
Wednesday that he couldn't discuss specifics of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``However,'' he said, ``because of (Colorado) there is an
emotional reaction to perceived threats. Our responsibility is to
try to separate that out, keeping in mind that the ultimate goal is
to benefit all the children, including the child who may have used
poor judgment. &QL; 
THE FEAR EQUATION
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said the suspension hearing ``is to make sure we have all the
facts. That we're not overreacting, we're not underreacting, we're
considering all the factors most relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   The most relevant factor is fear.
</P>
<P>
   Tim's friend had his hearing and received a long-term
suspension. Tim's mother worries that her boy also will be
banished. Not because he's a danger, but because it makes school
officials feel as if they're doing something _ (begin ital)
``anything'' (end ital) _ about the problem of teen violence.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are afraid. Teachers are afraid. Administrators are
afraid of appearing weak or ineffectual.
</P>
<P>
   After watching coverage of the massacre at Colorado's Columbine
High School on the day it happened, Kristin said Tim told his
parents he was afraid to return to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I convinced him it would be OK,'' Kristin said.
``We told him his school was completely safe.'' &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
