A7203 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     05-06 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEARING THE SCARF IN THE WRONG PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today the scarf; tomorrow the fez.
</P>
<P>
   Merve Kavakci had to have expected that her appearance in the
Turkish Parliament wearing a navy blue head cloth would provoke a
strong negative reaction.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly she was not prepared for the explosion of shouted
insults, rhythmic clapping and cries of ``Out! Out!'' that assailed
her there.
</P>
<P>
   She could not have imagined that Premier Bulent Ecevit would be
so incensed that he would demand of the speaker of the Parliament,
``Please put this lady in her place.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit then delivered an impassioned speech affirming the right
of individuals to exercise their private rights in private without
interference from the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is not a private space. This is the supreme
foundation of the state. It is not a place in which to challenge
the state,'' said Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
   Kemal Ataturuk, the founder of the Turkish republic, would have
been proud of him.
</P>
<P>
   Kavakci didn't get sworn in. The speaker called a recess, and
Kavakci didn't return when the session resumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that over a head scarf?'' you ask. Well, it was not the
garment per se that was found to be so offensive. It was what it
represented in the eyes of those assembled _ a throwback to the
past, a threat to the tradition of secularism in government that
Turkey's political and military leaders view as crucial to
preserving freedom and propelling the continuing modernization of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Kavakci belongs to the religion-centered Virtue Party, which is
cut from the same cloth as the outlawed Welfare Party. Welfare was
banned last year for being anti-secular. To the powers that be in
Turkey, that is the same thing as being subversive.
</P>
<P>
   With her headgear, Kavakci was making a statement about her
Islamic faith. She was one of two scarf-wearing women elected to
Parliament last month. The other woman chose not to wear her scarf
to Parliament and drew thunderous applause from the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Kavakci insists that she will return and be sworn in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to pledge my allegiance to the secular republic. What
difference does my head scarf make?'' she asked in a TV interview.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she knows what difference it makes. And surely she
knows that she never will receive her oath of office if she insists
on wearing one.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is the distinct possibility that Kavakci could
go to jail for her sartorial defiance.
</P>
<P>
   The wearing of head scarves by women, which is required in some
Muslim countries, is not prohibited outright in Turkey. But civil
servants can't wear them, and they can't be worn in courtrooms and
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no law or rule specifically prohibiting
wearing them in Parliament, the very idea _ until Kavakci's
audacious display _ was considered unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Kavakci now faces the possibility of doing some serious jail
time because prosecutors have launched an investigation of the
American-educated computer scientist, with a view to charging her
with inciting religious hatred.
</P>
<P>
   The Turks, 95 percent of whom are Muslims, have taken the issue
of separation of state and mosque very seriously ever since
Ataturk, 75 years ago, established the secular republic, abolished
the religious caliphate and called for banning the scarf, the veil
and the fez.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about maintaining that separation has been intensified
in recent years by the rise of religious fundamentalism in the
Islamic world. The Turkish ruling elite has only to look next door
at Iran to conjure up frightening visions of a day when women in
their country would be required to wear the scarf.
</P>
<P>
   There is a message in this for Americans. Some in this country
would tear away the partition between church and state that the
founders of this secular republic so painstakingly erected.
</P>
<P>
   They don't form political parties. But they do organize, pool
their resources and exert their combined leverage to bend parties
and candidates to their religiously motivated will.
</P>
<P>
   In this secular republic (under God), they have every right to
exercise their political influence to push such policies as
government subsidies for religious schools, prayer and the teaching
of creationism in public schools, and prohibiting all abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God that in this country the religious organizations that
push those and other policies that would breach the church-state
wall cannot be banned and that individuals cannot be jailed for
such advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, their continuing assaults upon the wall do threaten the
right of all Americans to believe, profess and worship as they
choose. America's versions of Turkey's woman who wore her scarf in
the wrong place must be continually challenged and put in their
place.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil)at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECORD-STORES-3TAKES-     05-06 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-STORES-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STALKING THAT RARE RECORDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Take pity on the next generation of music fiends, for
they may not know the pleasure of loitering in little record
stores.
</P>
<P>
   People in their 20s, 30s and 40s, less and less guilty about
shopping on the Internet, are regularly denying themselves the
chance to go into a record shop and just look. In their defense,
they complain that the clerks don't know the stock or know too much
and beam out rays of fringe-scholar intimidation. Or buyers talk
about what a waste of time it has become to go to a real store,
although some of the bigger virtual record shops on line say
they've got stock when they don't and end up sending out records
six months later or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   As a suburban teen-ager within bus distance of New York, I did a
lot of growing up on my trips in the early 1980s to specialist
record stores, looking for funk, jazz, rock and punk. I discovered
new neighborhoods, learned how to hold my own with older people,
discovered places to eat and figured out whom I didn't want to talk
to. I realize now with a sense of alarm what I might have lost if I
had had access to the Internet with its current level of
sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   I also contracted a mild form of the itch that still strikes
when I see some long-coveted record or CD: the sensory love of the
object. There's something about record stores, as kiosks of
information, as places where you can learn about style, slang, art
and sound, that I will never want to reject, no matter how much I
struggle against the idea that records, as opposed to performance,
can properly teach you about music.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still a place for independent, specialist record
stores in New York, despite the increasing availability of almost
anything on line and the increasing dominance of chain stores like
Tower, HMV and Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the ethnic and social profile of a neighborhood
supports a store; sometimes a store presents a certain style so
well and completely that one wouldn't want to go anywhere else to
find it. Sometimes it's just a heady pit stop, the equivalent of a
barbershop or cafe. Sometimes the stores become the origin of the
music, not just the middlemen, as more record shops move into
distributing hard-to-find records or just setting up their own
record label. Each one of those CDs sent around the world is
publicity for the store, and they're cheaper when you buy them at
the source.
</P>
<P>
   I recently spent several pleasant days around the city
revisiting some independent record stores, retailers of mostly new
records. These stores have survived the dark days through
specialization and fearsome knowledge of their own product. Almost
all the stores below serve customers by mail order; some are
getting a leg up on their competition by establishing Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   African Music
</P>
<P>
   To walk into Roger Francis' AFRICAN RECORD CENTER is to
experience that rare feeling of knowing that you did, in fact, get
there before some other people. You can't believe you're seeing
these racks full of pasteboard-cover LPs. Francis, a Brooklynite,
has owned the African Record Center in East Flatbush since 1968,
and from the beginning made trips to Africa to import the music. He
started the Makossa label, which he runs out of the back room; his
was the first place where records by Manu Dibango, Fela Kuti,
Franco and others could be found in New York. He has also organized
American tours for some African artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We introduced African music to the United States,'' said
Francis, not quite suppressing a grin. ``I will make that statement
humbly but boastfully at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   He still keeps racks full of Nigerian, Ghanaian, Ethiopian,
Cameroonian, Zairian, Haitian and Cuban LPs as well as CDs. Zouk
music, from Martinique, is his bread and butter these days.
</P>
<P>
   Francis' brother Rudy runs the Yoruba Book Center, two blocks
away, which specializes in books of the black diaspora. Its wares
include the entire catalog of the local Athelia Henrietta Press,
which publishes books on Yoruban religion and culture. The bookshop
also sells hard-to-find LPs of African and Haitian music, and its
biggest sellers are cassettes of Yoruban religious music.
</P>
<P>
   The best seller at African Record Center is ``Soukous
Vibrations, Vol. 5'' (Afro-Rhythms). I bought Lafayette Afro Rock
Band's ``Voodounon'' (Editions Makossa), an LP, for $10.
</P>
<P>
   Latin Music
</P>
<P>
   A chain store has moved in one block away from BATE, one of the
city's oldest Latin-music stores, on Delancey Street on the Lower
East Side. It makes Anna and Dominick Torres, owners of 31-year-old
Bate, a little worried, as does the changing profile of the
neighborhood; it's no longer the Latin stronghold it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   But Bate has something that many chains don't: back-catalog
items. In the rear of the store _ it's really two stores in one,
with a separate counter for the rhythm-and-blues and hip-hop
section _ the racks are deep with Fania, Harlequin and Tumbao, the
collector labels of salsa. It's one of the few places in the city
with a decent supply of Cuban music.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, six years before the Torreses started Bate, Cristina
Barreiro's father, Alfonso Rubio, opened CASA LATINA, a Latin-music
record store on East 116th Street in East Harlem. Rubio, who died
in 1978, was an Argentine tailor who fled Buenos Aires with his
family when President Juan Peron decided to widen Avenida de Mayo
and gave merchants 24 hours to vacate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '62, when my mother died,'' Ms. Barreiro said, ``he wanted
me to have a place that I could go to after school. So I used to
leave school and come to the store.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barreiro has been working at the store since 1966; she now
runs the place with her husband, Vicente. The long, deep store,
full of CDs, books, videos and percussion instruments, is becoming
a city landmark. With the recent closing of the Record Mart in
Times Square, Bate and Casa Latina are the best-stocked Latin music
stores in the city; they're also both places where you can sing a
fragment of a song you've heard on the radio, and the owners will
decipher and name it for you.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Vicente's a walking computer,'' Ms. Barreiro said. ``Other
stores used to call Casa Latina when a customer didn't know what he
was looking for, and Vicente would help out. But he had to stop
doing that. Now he just tells them that we have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Casa Latina also sells congas, bongos, guiros and shekeres, as
well as concert videos and books on salsa and Afro-Cuban music.
</P>
<P>
   At Casa Latina the best seller is Tito Rojas' ``Alegria y
Penas'' (MP/Sony). I bought El Gran Combo's ``Pasaporte Musical''
(Combo) for $13.99.
</P>
<P>
   Rock and the Fringe
</P>
<P>
   ROCKIT SCIENTIST in the West Village feels familiar, like the
one-stop shops that flourished in the 1980s: small and narrow, a
one-man operation, with tightly pruned sections that try to
represent every strand of Western world hipsterism since 1955 or
so. John Kioussis, a former manager of Venus Records, presides
here, wedged between a cash register and turntable up front,
offering advice and filling the room with loud music.
</P>
<P>
   Every good record store is for snobs, but the genre pool in
Rockit Scientist tends toward the open-minded. Kioussis is
especially good on 1960s rock and soul, with respectable sections
of reggae and jazz.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER MUSIC in the East Village, many times bigger, gets deeply
into the outsider niche; anything nontraditional has rack space
here. It's startling to find the shop so full of people late on a
Sunday, milling around the brightly lighted store looking for
fringe culture.
</P>
<P>
   This shop was founded a little more than three years ago by
former clerks from the music section at Kim's Video on Bleecker
Street, and since then the staff has grown to 20 from 3. The store
now sells tickets to concerts around town, and the sections, like
the store's habitues, keep dividing further and further into
specifics.
</P>
<P>
   What was once ``electronic music'' now has separate sections for
German minimalists and Vienna composers; what was once called
``decadanse'' now has separate sections for Japanese, French and
Italian pop. (This is where you find retro flavors like the old
records by Lucio Battisti, Nico and Francoise Hardy.)
</P>
<P>
   The store is the only place to find a three-CD set by the Dutch
electronic composer Dick Raiijmakers; most of the records of the
late-'60s Brazilian Tropicalia movement, or the beautifully
packaged ``Tarot'' album by the German musician Walter Wegmuller.
One of the success stories of alternative culture in New York, the
shop presents the corners exceedingly well and doesn't bother at
all with the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   The best seller at Other Music is Tom Waits' new album, ``Mule
Variations'' (Epitath). I bought Oval's ``Szenario'' (Tokuma), an
import CD, for $22.99. Reggae
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, everyone wanted to be in a band,'' said
Ira Heaps, the proprietor of the reggae record shop JAMMYLAND in
the East Village. ``Now everyone wants to be a DJ.''
</P>
<P>
   So he changed his shop, which had been open since 1993,
accordingly. Then, around 1996 he noticed that dub music _ extended
remixes of reggae songs with deep echo and tape-edit
experimentation _ had taken on a different meaning, bridging with
the new electronic music. So he began to specialize in dub and
stock as much vinyl as CDs; he may soon be the manufacturer and
distributor of the vinyl albums from Blood and Fire, the English
dub label.
</P>
<P>
   Jammyland, narrow, plentiful and homey _ there's an exposed
kitchen in the back _ carries a small amount of African music and
electronic dance music. But what makes it special is its supply of
records on labels like Justice League, Reggae Retro and Clocktower,
which aren't available at chains.
</P>
<P>
   The best seller is Augustus Pablo's ``This is Augustus Pablo''
(Above Rock Music/Jammyland). I bought that CD for $11.99.
</P>
<P>
   Hip-Hop
</P>
<P>
   There are two DJ booths at BEAT STREET in downtown Brooklyn, and
three full-time DJs, all continually pumping out loud hip-hop and
reggae beats through enormous speakers. Amazingly, they don't quite
clash; the downstairs space is that wide and deep. And students of
rhythm are always standing around the booths. Beat Street is
hip-hop central; this is where DJs shop and where they can walk out
with stacks of old breakbeat records as well as what's just hit the
street.
</P>
<P>
   This is also where you find a full complement of kung fu videos,
the new Missy Elliott single or a copy of Herman Kelly's ``Dance to
the Drummer's Beat,'' which is to an old-school hip-hop DJ set what
tomatoes are to chili.
</P>
<P>
   The best seller is Nas' ``I Am . . .'' (Columbia). I bought
ESG's, ``Come Away With ESG'' (99), an LP, for $10.99.
</P>
<P>
   Arabic
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Rashid inherited his record-and-video store, RASHID'S in
Cobble Hill, Brooklyn, from his father, Albert, a Lebanese
businessman who made soundtrack records from popular Arabic films
and worked as an agent in the United States for the Egyptian singer
Mohammed Abdel Wahab. The family opened up shop in the mid-1960's
and established, as Rashid likes to say, the largest collection of
Arabic records in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Rashid's is a distributor as well, responsible for most of the
Arabic CDs that end up in the chain stores; it's the place to seek
out first for CDs by popular singers like Amr Diab or a collection
of CDs by the singer Ahmed Adawiia, which were banned in Egypt
because of risque lyrics. In a black velvet case, the store sells a
72-CD boxed set ($795) of the later work of Oum Kalsoum, ``the
daughter of the Nile,'' who may be Egypt's most popular musician of
the century.
</P>
<P>
   The best seller is Ragheb Aleme's ``Alby Eshekha'' (Ahmed Moussa
&AMP; Co.). I bought Ahmad Fathi's ``Ya Bou Zaid'' (Al Jazira), a CD,
for $14.98.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
