<HEADLINE>
INFLUX OF CHINESE MIGRANTS COULD RUIN HONG KONG ECONOMY, OFFICIALS
WARN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ With fears of an immigration crisis already at a
fever pitch here, the Hong Kong government warned Thursday that the
former British colony would be economically devastated by an influx
of well over 1 million newly eligible migrants from mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   In a 17-page report, the government laid out a Malthusian vision
of Hong Kong in which a flood of people would swamp the schools and
welfare rolls, create double-digit unemployment and dwell in
squatters camps or on rooftops until the city built more than
530,000 new apartments.
</P>
<P>
   With its current population of 6.8 million, Hong Kong is already
one of the most densely packed cities in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that Hong Kong cannot bear the burden of these
1.67 million people,'' the territory's chief executive, Tung
Chee-hwa, said in a rare appearance at the legislature here. ``The
consequences are unimaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Hong Kong had little choice but to ask the Chinese
government to intervene _ either by amending the territory's
constitution or by modifying a recent Hong Kong court ruling that
granted residency to children born on the mainland who have at
least one parent living in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-democracy leaders said both proposals would erode Hong
Kong's autonomy. The court ruling in January was seen as a litmus
test of ``one country, two systems,'' the agreement under which
Hong Kong was supposed to be a semiautonomous region within China
with its own legal system.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also said the government was manipulating public opinion
by putting out forecasts that were exaggerated and intended to
scare.
</P>
<P>
   The government's estimate that 1.6 million mainland Chinese
would be eligible for residency was five times its own previous
estimate. And Thursday's report depicted the migrants almost as an
invading army _ saying they would overcrowd classrooms and
hospitals, blight the environment and saddle the local government
with $91 billion in additional capital spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it sound like they are barbarians who would ruin Hong
Kong,'' said Lee Wing-tat, an outspoken pro-democracy politician.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Lee, the leader of Hong Kong's Democratic Party, said:
``They don't want to implement the court ruling, so they are
drumming up hatred and fear-mongering. This brings out the worst in
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials defended their forecast, saying the
estimate of migrants grew because the court extended residency to
illegitimate children with at least one Hong Kong parent. But they
acknowledged that the economic report did not account for the fact
that 20 percent of those surveyed said they had no plans to move to
Hong Kong, even if they had the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty percent of 1.6 million is still a lot of people,'' said
Regina Ip, the secretary of security. ``We certainly did not cook
up or inflate the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   With or without the dire forecasts, the government may have
little trouble rallying support for measures to stem the tide.
Although most Hong Kong people are descendants of refugees from the
mainland _ many of whom came when Britain welcomed anyone who made
it across the border _ the prospect of a fresh wave of mainlanders
stirs deeply ambivalent feelings here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wrong not to let them come at all,'' Shirley Leung, a
messenger, said as she hurried through a rain-spattered square
Thursday afternoon. ``But if they all come at once, I am worried
that the crime rate will go up. Or else there will be problems in
education, social welfare, and housing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even opposition leaders like Mr. Lee concede that Hong Kong
would have trouble accommodating 1.6 million migrants, or about
one-quarter of its existing population. Faced with a choice, Mr.
Lee said he would prefer to have Beijing amend the constitution
than modify the court ruling.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But amending the constitution would take at least a year, and
other legal experts said Hong Kong could not live with the
uncertainty for that long. On Thursday, consensus seemed to be
coalescing around a proposal by Albert Chen, dean of the law
faculty at the University of Hong Kong, in which the government
would seek a reinterpretation of the ruling followed by an
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Chinese government has steered clear of the debate.
On Wednesday, Prime Minister Zhu Rongji told Hong Kong's No. 2
official, Anson Chan, that he would prefer the territory to resolve
the issue on its own. Legal experts said China was loath to be seen
as meddling in Hong Kong's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute seemed to put Tung in an awkward spot as well.
Traditionally a champion of ties with the motherland, the chief
executive came under fire Thursday for Hong Kong's unremittingly
negative view of the mainland Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are our compatriots,'' he said, somewhat haltingly. ``But
I am concerned that if they come to Hong Kong, they will meet up
with even worse treatment than they got in the mainland.''
</P>
</TEXT>
