u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIGAP07-COX     05-06 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIGAP07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INSURERS WARN DRUG BENEFITS WOULD RAISE 'MEDIGAP' COSTS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Including prescription drug coverage in Medicare,
or allowing states to require such coverage in supplemental
insurance policies, would dramatically raise the price of
``Medigap'' policies, the health insurance industry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 12 million of the 34 million seniors who receive
Medicare also purchase private policies that cover such expenses as
Medicare's deductibles and copayments.
</P>
<P>
   Providing prescription drug coverage through Medicare, which has
been proposed by key Democrats in both houses of Congress, would
raise these Medigap costs by $1,000 a year, according to a study by
the Health Insurance Association of America (HIAA).
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic bill envisions Medicare paying 80 percent of drug
costs, with patients paying 20 percent in copayments after a $200
deductible. The cost of these copayments would cause premiums to
rise, the insurers said.
</P>
<P>
   Another bill, offered by Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., the ranking
Democratic member of the Ways and Means health subcommittee, would
allow states to require that Medigap plans offer prescription drug
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, only three of the 10 major Medigap companies offer
prescription drug coverage. Requiring drug coverage in all Medigap
plans would increase costs by $1,700 a year, according to the HIAA
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mandating Medigap coverage for prescription drugs is a bad
idea whose time has not come and never will,'' said Chip Kahn, HIAA
president. ``It will sharply raise premiums and increase financial
pressure on seniors who depend upon Medigap to help pay their
health costs. ``
</P>
<P>
   Mary Nell Lehnhard, senior vice president of the Blue Cross and
Blue Shield Association, warned that the proposals to require drug
coverage could price supplemental insurance out of the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will be saying to (seniors) you have no choice except an
unaffordable product,'' Lehnhard said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Stark, who has spearheaded the legislation,
said his office had not seen the insurance industry's report and
would not comment immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
