<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7220 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUMMY-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      05-06 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUMMY-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S `MUMMY'S' DAY! LET ACTION SEASON BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The good news: It's not ``Allan Quartermain and the
Lost City of Gold.'' Of course, it's not ``Raiders of the Lost
Ark,'' either. But then what is?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy'' is a definite charge, if you're looking for
spectacle, rowdy adventure and supernatural horror all crammed into
a raucous two hours of high-testosterone special-effects
filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   A remake of Boris Karlov's 1932 movie series in name only, ``The
Mummy'' reinterprets the curse and the adventurers who unwittingly
unleash it.
</P>
<P>
   In this version, the mummy is an ancient Egyptian priest, lying
undead beneath the sand for 3,000 years and waiting for some fool
to set him free so he can wreak havoc on the world.
</P>
<P>
   Glad to lend a hand is an American treasure hunter (Brendan
Fraser), a beautiful Egyptologist (Rachel Weisz) and a pack of
two-fisted, three-gunned adventurers looking for gold beneath the
sands of the lost City of the Dead.
</P>
<P>
   What they find is a flesh-eating, soul-sucking skeleton who is
invincible or relatively so. When the trepid rogues aren't chasing
the skeleton or running from it, they're fighting mysterious
guardians of the crypt, assorted plagues of Egypt, brain-chewing
bugs, a deadly army of the dead and various other creepy-crawly
horrors.
</P>
<P>
   Director Stephen Sommers (``The Jungle Book'') has taken the
advanced ``Indiana Jones'' course and learned his lessons well. He
keeps the movie pumping with battles, both natural and
supernatural.
</P>
<P>
   But Sommers is no Steven Spielberg, or, rather, he wants to be
too much so that he copies nearly every Spielbergian move, which
gives ``TheMummy'' an easy predictability that undercuts the
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of the fights are stirring in that
it's-summer-let's-have-some-action sense. Fraser (``George of the
Jungle'') makes a stalwart Harrison Ford substitute, able to
deliver a punch or a punch line with equal flair.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a much-needed comic element is the very funny Kevin
O'Connor (``Deep Rising'') as a cowardly but resilient weasel.
</P>
<P>
   The special effects are often knockouts. But there are times
when the computer-generated effects look like computer-animated
effects.
</P>
<P>
   As a warm-up act for other summer spectaculars, ``The Mummy''
gets the season off to a racing start. At least it does for adults.
``The Mummy'' is far too violent and gruesome for young kids.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is rated PG-13, ``The Mummy'' contains more than
enough grisly death scenes to have earned an R. The lower, more
kid-friendly rating is another example of how the desire of studio
marketing departments to sell violent movies to kids overpowers the
duty of the rating board to offer parents honest guidance about
movie content. 3 stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
