<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     05-06 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: `LOVE LETTER'; `EYES WIDE SHUT'; ROLES FOR LATINOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Kate Capshaw still recalls her conversation with
Steven Spielberg, her husband, when he noticed a dozen copies of a
novel, ``The Love Letter,'' on a table in their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must like this book,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of bought it,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean `sort of?''' Spielberg asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of bought it to turn into a movie,'' said Ms. Capshaw,
who acquired the film rights to the book, by Cathleen Schine, for
$30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg was nonplussed. ``Do we get to read it?'' he asked,
referring to Dreamworks, the company Spielberg owns with Jeffrey
Katzenberg and David Geffen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a Dreamworks movie,'' she said. ``This is really a
small movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg said, ``At least let us pass on it.''
</P>
<P>
   In recalling the conversation the other day, Ms. Capshaw said:
`` If someone like Michelle Pfeiffer or Jessica Lange or Julia
Roberts had bought a book, that would be one thing. But that's not
what my career has offered me. I was a little nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   After the conversation with her husband, Ms. Capshaw and her
producing partners, Midge Sanford and Sarah Pillsbury, gave the
novel to Dreamworks. The company quickly agreed to make the
romantic drama about a woman, played by Ms. Capshaw, and other
people in a small New England town who find an anonymous love
letter that alters their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens May 21, the only studio movie to open against
George Lucas' ``Star Wars: Episode I _The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Capshaw said it took awhile for the film to get started.
``First I had like 20 babies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple adopted a child and she gave birth to one before the
movie was made, raising the number of children they have to seven.
</P>
<P>
   Then, while Spielberg directed ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Ms.
Capshaw worked on the screenplay with Maria Maggenti and hired a
Hong Kong director, Peter Chan, whose previous films included
``Comrades, Almost a Love Story'' and ``He's a Woman, She's a
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Spielberg's involvement was intimidating to the
director and other actors, Ms. Capshaw said her husband
deliberately avoided any interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he talked, it was only in a supportive way,'' she said.
``He only opened his mouth if he was asked a question. He's a very
good boy in that way. He knows who he is. But his passion for
filmmaking is so contagious. He loves being on movie sets. It's
exciting for him to be on the set of an $8 million movie, like
ours, or a $100 million movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Capshaw is worried about the competition with the new ``Star
Wars,'' which opens May 19, but she remains optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if we're going up against them; we're so
different,'' she said. ``If `Star Wars' is like the big wedding,
we're like the flower girl, something delectable coming down the
aisle, but not the main event.''
</P>
<P>
   Chan, who is 36 and lives in Los Angeles, said he was surprised
that he was offered the movie, mostly because of its small-town
America setting; he grew up in Bangkok and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a pretty interesting choice to choose a
Chinese director for something so American,'' he said. ``But the
subtlety of the story was something that I related to and something
that was, as Kate said, very Chinese, too. It deals with people who
keep their feelings internal, people who can't talk to each other
and express what they really feel. The love letter helps everybody
come out of their shell and go for what they want in life. All
these feelings are universal.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Capshaw, Chan sought to put the best light on the
box-office competition with ``Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are such a smaller movie, such a different movie,'' he
said. ``Maybe it's a blessing. Maybe people will actually want an
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   A Kubrick Odyssey
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three years ago, Todd Field, a mainstay in independent
films as an actor, writer and director, suddenly received a call
from Jan Harlan, a longtime associate of Stanley Kubrick's and
associate producer of the new Kubrick film, ``Eyes Wide Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `We've been looking for you,''' recalled Field. ``He
said, ` Kubrick is interested in having you play a role in his new
film,' and I said, `Uh. . . uh . . . uh . . .' I couldn't speak. He
asked me if I was available on a certain date. I had actually
committed to work on a television series with Ed Zwick and Marshall
Herskovitz. The first read-through was actually the next day. It
was a horrible nightmare. I said to Jan that I wasn't sure about
those dates. I said I'd call him back.''
</P>
<P>
   He hung up the telephone, he recalled, and then his wife, Serena
Rathbun, a writer, told him to call back immediately and say he
would do it.
</P>
<P>
   Field said: ``This was like the Dalai Lama arriving at your
doorstep. How can you say `No?' I called Ed and Marshall and told
them what happened. They couldn't have been nicer. They said, `Of
course you have to do it.' Then I called Jan back and said, `I
didn't know what I was thinking.'''
</P>
<P>
   Field is contractually forbidden to talk about his role in or
the details of the much-anticipated Kubrick film, a psychosexual
drama starring Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman, which is scheduled to
open July 16. It is the last film by Kubrick, who died March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Field is best known for his roles in Nicole Holofcener's
``Walking and Talking'' and Victor Nunez's ``Ruby in Paradise.'' He
has also been a co-producer and had a starring role in ``Broken
Vessels,'' directed by Scott Ziehl, about ambulance drivers in Los
Angeles. That film will be released on July 9.
</P>
<P>
   Field's role in ``Ruby in Paradise'' attracted Kubrick's
attention. Field said the prospect of working with the director of
such classic films as ``Dr. Strangelove'' and ``2001: A Space
Odyssey'' left him intimidated. But, Field said, Kubrick was far
from intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put you at instant ease,'' Field said. ``You could have
been talking to your best friend's grandfather. He was really a
warm, funny, smart New Yorker. He was from the Bronx, and he still
had that New York accent. He liked talking about baseball. He was
up on all the latest. In a way it made me all the more nervous. In
the beginning I thought: `This is too good to be true. It can't
last.' But it did.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``After we did a bit of work together, Stanley
would do a wonderful thing. When he felt you got the scene, Stanley
would look you in the eye and smile and shake your hand and say,
`Congratulations.'''
</P>
<P>
   Field called the director ``the easiest person I ever worked
with.'' He added:
</P>
<P>
   ``For all of his technical prowess, for all the gear and
gadgets, he understood actors in extraordinary ways. We would sit
down and dissect the work. He wasn't afraid of actors. He almost
demanded that actors bring something to the table. Everyone's
thoughts and opinions were not only encouraged but listened to and
explored. Sometimes it worked, sometimes it didn't. By the end of
rehearsals, it was like being in a play. The work had a certain
grace and sophistication. I'll never forget working with him.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Unequal Opportunity
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every studio executive and talent agent in Hollywood
knows that Latino actors have a hard time finding work in studio
films and television series. But not this hard.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are some well-known Latino actors like Jimmy
Smits, Salma Hayek, Jennifer Lopez and Edward James Olmos, a report
on Latino employment in Hollywood, sponsored by the Screen Actors
Guild, found that the number of Latino performers in films and
television is declining.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that the percentage of roles going to
African-Americans and American Indians had declined since 1997, the
last time a report was made. The only positive shift, according to
the study, was a slight increase in representation of Asians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos, who constitute approximately 10.7 percent of the U.S.
population, continue to be the most underrepresented ethnic group
on prime-time television and in films,'' the report said. ``Their
appearance in films and TV is less than one-third of their real
proportion of the U.S. population.''
</P>
<P>
   Screen Actors Guild president Richard Masur said the findings
were extremely disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout the 1990s,'' he said, ``the America portrayed in
films and on television was moving slowly but steadily toward the
reality of our American scene. This is the first time the Guild has
seen those numbers decline'' in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos were not the only group underrepresented, according to
the study. There were also the issues of sexism and ageism.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that two out of three performing jobs went to
those under 40. And men received 63 percent of all jobs in 1998,
while women received 37 percent. Masur said that underemployment of
women, minorities, older people and performers with disabilities
was endemic in the entertainment business.
</P>
<P>
   ``These performers are simply not receiving the numbers of roles
they can and should be playing to accurately reflect American
life,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
