<HEADLINE>
A SPECIAL MOTHER'S DAY GIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patience Auer of Sebastopol is getting a horse for Mother's Day.
It is not just any horse. Its name is Bruce and it used to belong
to her 28-year-old daughter who had a habit of adopting old race
horses.
</P>
<P>
   Patience's daughter, Nessie (short for Vanessa) Gack was killed
last January in San Diego in a freak accident involving a horse.
She had been having trouble with a bad knee from a skiing accident.
She was a tall, thin, loose-limbed woman, said her mother, and
every so often her knee would pop out. Sometimes she wore a brace,
but at Christmas she told her mother even with the brace her knee
was becoming unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   She'd put off having surgery for a variety of reasons, mainly
because she was finishing up work on her doctorate. Always ``a take
charge child,'' she was at age 28 ``happy, alive, energetic and
vital, at the peak of her being.''
</P>
<P>
   In January she was completing a double major in communications
and cognitive science at the University of California in San Diego,
focusing on how children learn in the world of computers. She had
sent off a chapter to be included in a book on the educational
potential of CD Roms.
</P>
<P>
   In her other world, she had three horses, all one-time race
horses, no longer moneymakers, that she was training to jump. She
also had a part-time job at a stable, teaching riding and training
other people's horses.
</P>
<P>
   That January day she was leading someone else's horse out of the
barn to tie up and put tack on when her knee suddenly buckled. She
wasn't wearing a helmet.
</P>
<P>
   From what her mother can put together, Nessie started to fall
and held onto the reins. The horse began swinging its head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horse freaked and his head hit Nessie's head.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that quick and lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Nessie suffered a massive brain injury, went into a coma and
died 10 days later.
</P>
<P>
   There was a memorial at the time in San Diego but Patience
needed a few months before having one at home for Nessie's old high
school friends. Now she's planned a memorial for June 5, a picnic
in Sebastopol's Ragle Park where horses are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Adopting her daughter's horse was not planned. It started as a
fantasy and eventually turned into the most natural thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   The night before the accident Nessie told her mother about
Bruce, named after a blind date that wasn't successful. She had
intended to turn him into a jumper but discovered he had a pin in
his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me that I should take him, that we would be perfect
for each other, because he's shy. She said he needed a mom.''
</P>
<P>
   After the accident, as family and friends hoped for a miracle,
Patience had dreams. First she had a dream about a kitten that she
was trying to keep safe and hidden in a shoe box. A few days later
she dreamed she was in an old house and a lizard ran across the
floor. She bent down and put it in her pocket. When she went
outside, the lizard leaped out and turned back to look at her,
``letting me know it didn't want to be caught.'' Soon after, her
daughter died.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner of the mother's living room there's an altar with
a painting of a lake and sky with a large teardrop in the middle,
like a giant crystal. She explains, ``I asked how would I know
Vanessa is with me and I got this image of a tear drop in my mind's
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to it is a happy gathering of family photos _ Nessie with
her younger brother, clowning with high school and college friends,
smiling from the top of a horse at age 2. There's a pair of
stirrups.
</P>
<P>
   Now, will come a reminder named Bruce, boarded nearby so
Patience can begin to visit him regularly. The mother said she and
Bruce need to get to know each other.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of The New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
