</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-LUXURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINING FORD'S LUXURY QUARTET TO SING IN 4-PART HARMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM DIEM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Until recently, Ford Motor Co.'s only prestige brand
was Lincoln, which for decades was No. 2 to Cadillac in the
American luxury market but was virtually unknown in much of the
world. But in March, with Ford having acquired a fourth luxury
marque, the company formed Premier Automotive Group as an umbrella
for Lincoln, Jaguar, Aston Martin and Volvo. That group is selling
twice as many luxury cars as General Motors, and within five years
its divisions expect to add at least 250,000 sales, putting Ford on
par with the BMW Group and DaimlerChrysler, which produces
Mercedes-Benz automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   If its luxury sales increase as much as Ford anticipates, the
company's profits will rise by more than $500 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   As Ford's group vice president, Wolfgang Reitzle is in charge of
Premier Automotive Group. He is also chairman of Jaguar Cars of
Britain and Volvo Cars of Sweden, and he is responsible for
insuring that Lincoln, Jaguar, Volvo and Aston Martin do not steal
customers from one another.
</P>
<P>
   Reitzle, the former No. 2 executive at BMW, was hired on March
19 when Premier Automotive Group was formed. One of the first
consequences was a decision to postpone by 12 to 18 months a plan
to import Lincolns to Europe this fall. Up to now, Europeans have
shown little appetite for American luxury cars; compared with
homegrown models, they have tended to handle more ponderously and
take up more space on cramped Old World streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to give Wolfgang the opportunity to take a look at
it and decide, Is this the right way to go?'' said Nick Scheele,
the former Jaguar chairman who is now senior vice president for
marketing sales and service at Ford of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of premium cars have been strong, and Ford executives say
they think the growth will continue. According to Mavel SA, a
French consulting company, global production for Ford's luxury
brands in 1998 totaled 662,137, compared with 933,580 for
Mercedes-Benz, 911,897 for BMW and Rover, and 299,122 for GM's
premium brands, Cadillac and Saab.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the luxury market is where the money is. ``Profitability
has averaged 3.5 percent over the last four years in volume
segments,'' said Andrew Blair-Smith, an auto-industry stock analyst
with Commerzbank in Frankfurt. ``But in the premium segment, for
Audi, Mercedes-Benz and BMW, it has been 7 to 8 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Reitzle, 50, has two jobs: co-ordinating the marketing of each
brand and the product development for all four. On the marketing
side, ``one has to be very careful to keep the identity of each
brand,'' Walter Hasselkus, former chairman of the Rover Group _
which is owned by BMW _ said in a telephone interview from his home
in Munich, Germany. He endorsed the idea of the premier group.
``When you are in the mass manufacturing business, it is an
advantage to separate the premium brands from the mass brands,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Scheele insisted that each of the brands had a strong identity,
and that each had plans to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln's cars, and its Navigator sport utility, have an
all-American aura. While the focus of the other marques is
European, the operations of Lincoln Mercury have been moved from
Michigan to California in an attempt to read the pulse of
car-conscious trend-setters on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   With Volvo and Jaguar well established internationally, Reitzle
may decide to keep Lincoln as an all-American luxury brand. GM's
strategy is to make Cadillac a global brand competing directly with
BMW and Mercedes. It is investing heavily in European racing, and
it is developing a rear-drive luxury car platform.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo's reputation of concern for safety and the environment
sets it apart from Lincoln, Jaguar and Aston Martin. Volvo expects
to increase worldwide sales to 500,000 by 2002, from 400,000 now,
in part by snaring more Americans. Sales begin this summer in the
United States of compact S40 sedans and wagons built in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguar's image is of sensuous, powerful elegance in the upper
luxury brackets. Last year, it sold 27,000 in North America out of
a production total of 50,000, and it intends to quadruple its sales
by 2002. To that end, it is bringing out smaller cars; the S-Type
goes on sale in the United States this spring, and an even smaller
car, with the code name X400, is due in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Aston Martin, the producer of luxury sports cars once known as
the choice of James Bond, stands by itself. It sold only 625 cars
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Reitzle ``will insure that the product plans themselves are
coherent and avoid duplication,'' said Joe Greenwell, a spokesman
for Jaguar here.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say they think Reitzle will seek common platforms
for cars from Volvo, Lincoln and Jaguar. The Jaguar S-Type and the
Lincoln LS already share their underpinnings, and the Jaguar X400
will use elements of the Ford Mondeo platform, which is also the
right size for the next Volvo 40-Series. But Scheele said potential
savings from common platforms must be balanced against the
potential risk of losing brand identity.
</P>
<P>
   It is more important to worry about factors that differentiate
the premium vehicles, like tuning their engines for distinctive
performance. For example, the S-Type and the LS share a 4-liter,
32-valve V8 engine. Each combustion chamber in the Jaguar is 1
millimeter deeper than in the Lincoln, so it produces 276
horsepower, compared with the Lincoln's 245. It also has more
torque, or acceleration power.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Reitzle was hired he introduced himself at Jaguar
headquarters in Coventry, England. Afterward he had a short holiday
in Florida, then began visits to Volvo in Sweden; Jaguar; Ford in
Dearborn, Mich., and Lincoln in Irvine, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in an information-gathering mode and getting on with that
very fast,'' said Greenwell, the Jaguar spokesman. In Britain,
Reitzle studied business plans and visited the plants and
engineering centers of Jaguar and Aston Martin. This summer,
Reitzle will establish an office in central London with a staff of
fewer than 20 brand specialists and secretaries. He will juggle
time and travel schedules, since he will be in contact with offices
in four time zones.
</P>
<P>
   Reitzle is known in the industry as a car enthusiast, and he
owns a classic E-Type Jaguar. ``Reitzle is a coup _ he's a product
maniac,'' said Steve Haggerty, an analyst at Schroder &AMP; Co. in
London.
</P>
<P>
   A former colleague at BMW agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This premium car division suits Dr. Reitzle,'' Hasselkus said.
Reitzle and Hasselkus lost their jobs last winter, along with Bernd
Pischetsrieder, BMW's chairman, over the poor performance of the
Rover Group. While Land Rover's sport utilities have done well, the
group lost $1 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As head of product development and heir apparent, Reitzle was
closely identified with BMW. At that German company's annual
financial press conference in March, shortly after Reitzle's
departure, Joachim Milberg, the new BMW chairman, said: ``We are
confident he will not harm BMW. I wish him the greatest possible
personal happiness and satisfaction in his working career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
