<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7230 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-WEBSITE2-BOS &LR;      05-06 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WEBSITE2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REFUGEE WEB WIZARD DAZZLES IN A NEW LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania -- Three weeks ago, Vigan Budima was just
another young refugee, one of the thousands of anonymous faces seen
fleeing desperately from Kosovo. But in the days since, he has
become something else: the top Web page designer at Albania Online,
the biggest Internet company in the capital, his temporary
hometown. Budima, 18, arrived here with his parents after a
four-day journey through Montenegro with only packets of food and
the clothes on his back. He had no idea what had become of his
brother, Valon.
</P>
<P>
   So, as thousands of refugees waited in long lines for a
telephone, Budima knocked on the door of an Internet provider he
saw listed in the newspaper and asked if he could send his brother
an e-mail. Within hours, he had persuaded the owners of Albania
Online to hire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for me. I don't have anything else to do,'' Budima
said, fiddling with a computer mouse and demonstrating his latest
designs from what has become his private office. ``Also, this is a
poor country. This Internet is new for them. There's not much
home-page development here.'' His good fortune is one extraordinary
story in a country where hundreds of thousands of Kosovars spend
their days in cramped refugee camps, and hundreds have no shelter
at all. But his ambition is strikingly common among his peers, many
of whom have sought jobs or volunteer work since arriving in
Albania in an effort to hold on to a fragment of normal life.
</P>
<P>
   In hotels and restaurants in Tirana, as well as in humanitarian
organizations in northern Albania, Kosovars are seeping into the
fabric of the country, with engineers working as English
translators and teachers working as office assistants. Some have
even managed to get jobs in their own field, like the doctors now
working with humanitarian health teams.
</P>
<P>
   Their motive clearly is not economic; few Albanian companies can
afford to pay refugees for work, and any wages are far below what
professionals earned in Kosovo. Instead, many refugees seemed to be
emerging from a state of shock into one of boredom, leaving them
anxious to re-create pieces of their former lives.
</P>
<P>
   They are frustrated by the length of time that has passed since
they left Kosovo. Although they hope to return home in a matter of
weeks, many say they are looking for things to do in the meantime
-- particularly if it means helping other refugees. ``You've got to
remember: These aren't peasants. Kosovo is not in the Stone Age,''
said Rick Grant, an official of CARE International. ``These are
educated, cultivated people, and it's natural for people who are
successful in their homelands to want to show some initiative, even
in this kind of situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Grant said, ``Nothing is worse than to sit in a refugee
camp, day after day after day. It's like being in a penitentiary.
There's absolutely nothing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdet Nila can attest to that. After traveling into Albania
from his hometown of Pec, Nila, 35, said he spent a week in a
Tirana refugee camp, wandering all day between rows of tents. When
the owner of a nearby hotel offered to shelter Nila and his family
for a few days, he accepted, but only after insisting on
volunteering as a translator at the hotel's front desk. He soon
realized he was the only employee who could speak English.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the owner, no pay is fine,'' said Nila, who ran a
family paint business in Kosovo and who now stays with his wife,
parents, and three children in room 42 of the Hotel Balkani. ``In
the camp, all the time I was saying, `I need work to spend my time.
I don't want to just walk around and smoke cigarettes.' `` Urban
Kosovars appear to be the most restless -- and the most useful to
Albanian and foreign companies -- because many worked at office
jobs in cities such as Pristina and Prizren and learned to speak
more than one European language. In that sense, they are more
employable than many Albanian natives, whose formal education
sometimes stops at the eighth grade. The sudden emergence of
refugees in the work force is a welcome sign to humanitarian
officials, who say it creates a kind of welfare-to-work atmosphere
in a system otherwise built on communist-era dependence.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovar Albanians ``obviously know the language, know the
culture, know the needs,'' said Rick Brennan, director of health
for the International Rescue Committee, a New York-based medical
team that has hired refugees in Macedonia and Albania. ``It allows
them to maintain their skills and their dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   At Albania Online, the symbols of Budima's gratitude are
emblazoned on his computer screen. He has created five home pages
in the past two weeks -- including ones for the Albanian Democratic
Party and for the country's largest radio station. He learned his
skills after school on an outdated computer in his parents' home.
But he was a pro even in high school: When his brother Valon, 27,
opened an Internet-provider firm in Pristina, Budima became a
long-distance employee, designing sites and communicating by modem
from Pec.
</P>
<P>
   His brother's company, Pro.net, shut down last month after the
NATO airstrikes began. Valon left a few days later. Budima and his
parents, both teachers, left their apartment March 28.
</P>
<P>
   After driving first to Montenegro, they decided to go on to
Albania, in the hopes that distant relatives might take them in.
When Budima got here, he thought that he might be able to reach
Valon by e-mail. ``I came here and asked if I can use the computer
for just half an hour,'' he said from the office of Albania Online.
``Then I showed them some home pages I'd done. They were
impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked out a deal: $30 per home page and access to the
Internet. But several days later, he got an even greater reward.
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail came back from Valon. He said he had fled south from
Pristina toward Macedonia, spending six horrific days trapped near
the border before being allowed to enter a refugee camp. After
making it to safety, Valon had the same inspiration as his younger
brother.
</P>
<P>
   He sought out an Internet cafe. And there, from hundreds of
miles away, he let his family know he had survived.
</P>
</TEXT>
