</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN SAYS HE'LL BE ON BEST BEHAVIOR ON RETURN TO BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ He promises no death stares toward the owner's box, no
glaring at the general manager's suite. Mo Vaughn says there'll be
no gestures and no angry remarks directed at Red Sox management
when he comes home to Fenway Friday night wearing the uniform of
the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not walking into Fenway Park to make a statement,'' Vaughn
said, sitting at his locker preparing to play at Tiger Stadium
earlier this week. ``I made my statement when I played there. I'm
not here to get up there and hit a home run and look up at Dan
Duquette's box or John Harrington. I'm not gonna do that. I've come
up big so many times I don't have to do that. I really want to get
this first one over and let it go and then just go play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Return of Mo. Citizens of Red Sox Nation circled this date
when the American League schedule came out last winter. But who
would have dared guess that Mo's comeback concert would feature
Pedro Martinez on the mound for the Red Sox?
</P>
<P>
   New England sports fans have endured several of these painful
reunions in recent years. In July 1997, Roger Clemens came home and
struck out 16 Sox in a dramatic display of skill and acrimony.
Clemens eyeballed the executive suites when he came off the mound
in the eighth inning after fanning Mo with his last pitch of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   And who can forget the Returns of the Tuna? In 1997, Bill
Parcells's still-bumbling Jets took the heavily-favored Patriots
into overtime. In Tuna Bowl II last autumn, the Jets kicked butt in
Foxborough, effectively torpedoing the Patriots' season.
</P>
<P>
   Going back seven decades, there was the homecoming of beloved
Babe Ruth when the big galoot first returned to Fenway in a Yankee
uniform in 1920 (Those goofy New Yorkers had this silly notion that
Boston's former ace pitcher would better serve them as a full-time
outfielder). The Babe stayed at what is now Miles Standish Hall
(Boston University) when he made his return engagement and a
scorecard ad urged fans to smoke Babe Ruth cigars. The Globe's Mel
Webb wrote, ``The Sudbury farmer is a great favorite in Boston and
holiday crowds are likely to show him how much they regret his sale
to New York.'' The Sox held Ruth to two singles and a double in a
doubleheader sweep of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Mo. The Black Bambino.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn says he's been watching the Sox struggles. He's pulling
for his friends on the team. But it's hard to miss the big hole in
the lineup. Boston's run production is way down and Sox fans are no
longer wearing ``Mo Who?'' sweatshirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to live with decisions that they made,'' said Mo.
``Whether they win or lose, they're still (expletive), so it
doesn't matter. Management's got to take heat. That means if they
have a long year, which makes it tougher on them _ and I don't want
that for them _ everybody knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows the Sox did not want Vaughn back. Despite an MVP
trophy and a six-season stretch in which he averaged 36 homers and
110 RBIs, Duquette and Harrington did everything possible to make
it appear they were courting Vaughn while sending larger messages
that he was not welcome back. When it all washed out in a downpour
of badwill, Mo had an $80 million contract and Duquette had
rejection letters from Bernie Williams, Albert Belle, Will Clark,
and Garth Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mo returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about coming to Boston and this and that. I really
haven't thought about it that much,'' he says. ``I've been lucky
enough to move on. I've been lucky enough to understand my
situation a long time ago before the whole thing came down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no controversy anymore. It's not like I'm out here to
prove to the Boston Red Sox fans or media that I can play this
game. I'll be battling one of the best pitchers in baseball, no
doubt about it. Pedro, he'll come in. He'll establish the inside. I
probably won't move.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have gone through all the things I have gone through in the
past two or three years _ it's not as painful as people think
because it was expected. I don't know what it's going to be like in
terms of how the fans are gonna be, but I'll always miss the
intensity of Fenway Park, the intensity of the fans. I think that's
what gave me my focus. Now it's just a situation that is over with.
It's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things have not gone particularly well for Mo and the Anaheim
Angels. While Boston has struggled through its spring of
Bestseller-List-Meets-Disabled-List (Jimy Williams is the boy who
loved Tom Gordon), the Angels have encountered more of the bad luck
that marked their four decades of existence. They have the usual
raft of disabled players and struggling pitchers, but are fortunate
that no team in the AL West has bolted from the blocks.
</P>
<P>
   It's been painful for Mo. In the first inning of his first game,
he almost broke his left ankle when he plunged into the Cleveland
dugout in pursuit of an Omar Vizquel popup. In his subsequent
first-inning plate appearance, he fell in the batter's box when he
flied out to left field. By midgame, he was en route to the
hospital. Vaughn was on crutches when he conducted his first
postgame interview with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   After a stint on the disabled list due to a ``high ankle
sprain,'' Mo returned with a vengeance, hitting a monstrous SkyDome
home run in his first at-bat. He hit his fourth homer Wednesday
night in Detroit, and comes to Fenway batting .300 with 13 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to get back on the field. Mo is an active person. When
he was a kid, Shirley Vaughn would make little Mo run around the
block a few times before sending him to school. He had to do
something with all that energy. Now he loathes the gentleman-farmer
lifestyle of the major league designated hitter. The Angels finally
put him back at first base Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so much of a better player when I play defense,'' said
Vaughn. ``Jimy Williams wouldn't let me DH when I was hurt. He said
I was (expletive).
</P>
<P>
   ``The ankle has been kind of tough, and I haven't been able to
do much, but that's the way it's got to be to get it right. This is
an injury where I never broke anything or had surgery or anything
like that, but it's probably the worst injury I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are from Boston, the Anaheim Angels really can't tell you
anything you don't already know about Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim manager Terry Collins said, ``He's been everything you
expect. He's a true professional in the way he goes about things.
He prepares as good as anybody I've been around. This guy knows
what the game is about. He's willing to pay the price to win and
he's not afraid to tell others how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, with a guy like him your whole lineup changes. And
he can hit anybody. Mo's got a big back.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels shorstop Gary DiSarcina, who's on the disabled list
because he was struck by coach George Hendrick's fungo bat while
standing around the cage, said, ``I knew a lot about who Mo was and
what he did in the community. But as a teammate, he's very
professional. He treats everybody the same _ the clubhouse kids,
players, coaches, the media. It's kind of surprising and
refreshing. Nowadays, you sometimes walk around on eggshells when
you are around superstars. Not with Mo.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina lives on Cape Cod and watched the Vaughn saga unravel.
He thinks he knows what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if you have insecure management and a superstar who
speaks his mind and says, `This ain't right,' of course you'll have
problems. Management's not going to want that guy around. Maybe
he's too vocal. He threatens their leadership. That's what it look
like to me. I think Red Sox fans could see how the relationship had
run its course.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins concluded, ``Mo's everything we heard about. I'll give
(Angels GM) Billy (Bavasi) credit. He did his homework. This guy's
the real deal. And we've got a lot of people looking forward to
Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mo remembers the return of Roger. It was a Fenway event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for me because this guy had raised me in this
game in a lot of ways, and I never understood why he wasn't playing
for us. He hit me the first time up. I said, `Why'd you hit me?' He
said, `I just wasn't ready to pitch to you yet.' He struck me out
three times. I was the last one in the eighth inning. Ninety-seven
miles an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Mo's family will be at the game. He's commuting from his home in
Easton throughout the weekend. A friend will deliver him via limo,
and no, there won't be much time for the Foxy Lady.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's aware that there was some ``Mo Who?'' sentiment around
Fenway early in the season when the Sox were 5-1. There won't be
much of that in Boston Nomar Garciaparra has just one homer and the
Sox can't score enough runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be checking out their hacks from the side,'' said Vaughn.
``And I'm always gonna offer knowledge to guys. Those will always
be my guys. It'll be good to see Jimy Williams and the coaching
staff. They helped me out a lot. But really I just want to get on
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   What if he crosses paths with Duquette?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not gonna say anything. I really don't have anything to
say to him. And I'm sure he doesn't have anything to say to me. If
I walked right in front of him, I wouldn't know what to say. I'd
probably say, `How you doing'?''
</P>
<P>
   And the honest answer would be, ``Not too well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are reeling. Perhaps they would be scuffling even
with Vaughn, but that won't soothe the fandom.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn isn't gloating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to have anything thrown up in their face to make
myself feel good,'' he said. ``It's not me against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like playing on the West Coast you get to see them on
TV a lot. They got some guys I don't know. I find myself talking to
the TV a lot. I'll always worry about them. I don't know what to
expect from them when negative times come along. I'll always just
hope that they're all right because it can get tough up there. It
can get very, very tough. They've just got to stay together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was able to take a lot of things off a lot of
people. I just don't want any of them to feel . . . what I learned
about this game more than anything over the last couple of years
that I played is that you can't be a one-man gang. Everybody's got
to help. Nomar's not going to win or lose games. He's just got to
do his part.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter how you feel when things are going good.
It's how you react when things are going poorly. That's what I was
there for.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are going poorly. But Mo doesn't play ball for the Sox
anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
