<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7238 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-06 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ARE IN IT FOR REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The dust has settled. The fog has lifted. The Boston
Bruins, with all due apologies to Walter Zenga's improved
Revolution, are the only viable game in town.
</P>
<P>
   The town is ready to embrace them, and this is a town that knows
how to embrace a hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone needs any reminder, it is here for us in the form of
Clark Booth's splendid book, ``Boston Bruins, Celebrating 75
Years,'' a labor of love for one of our true hockey mavens. Read a
few chapters and you'll be ready to put the pads on yourself.
</P>
<P>
   What would really be good is for the young players to devour
this book. Then they would know what their franchise heritage
really is, assuming Clark wouldn't lose them with a first page
reference in which he compares the Bruins to ``the Lancastrian
kings, whose recklessness was at the core of their charm and whose
excesses were invariably redeemed by valor.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I can certainly think of more than a few Bruins whose
recklessness was the very essence of their charm (Terry O'Reilly,
for openers). We've had many players who displayed valor, and the
hope now is that the supply is being replenished in the form of
both the young stars in the making and the quality veterans who
have been leading by all kinds of example during the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   You would certainly think that Tim Taylor has shown a few of the
younger lads what playoff grit is all about, and Dave Ellett makes
two. And any time the youngsters want to gaze at the definitive
personification of grit and valor they need only focus on No. 77,
who, in case you haven't been paying attention, has once again been
nominated for the Norris Trophy. Of course around here, that's a
bit like saying that if it's spring it must be time for the Pops.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of likable, downright effervescent
personalities among the younger players, but the one who seems to
have the best overall feel for being a Boston Bruin, in the Clark
Booth sense, is Anson Carter. I'm not saying the others aren't
having a good time, but he realizes the full possibilities of being
a hockey player in what remains a hockey town.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the matter of the Game 6 crowd (You can throw
in Game 4, too). ``You'd better believe a crowd like that helps
us,'' he says. ``They were in full voice even before the game
started. The ceiling was shaking. Ray Bourque said it best: `It was
like being in the Old Garden.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Carter has been a Bruin since March 1, 1997, and he was starting
to wonder if he had been dropped off in the wrong rink by mistake.
Quite frankly, this wasn't the Bruins' experience he had been
hearing about. ``I was looking forward to playing in the city of
Boston and for a franchise with a history like the Bruins,'' he
explains. ``I grew up in Toronto, so I know what the Original Six
is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't hearing a 23-year-old rhapsodize about the ``Original
Six'' make those little hairs on the back of your next snap to
attention?
</P>
<P>
   Anson Carter knew about the ``Big, Bad Bruins,'' I am sure. He
had heard Boston was a great place to be a hockey player. But he
never got to play in the Garden, and in the first two-plus years he
skated in the Fleet there was no special aura. He was beginning to
wonder if he would ever experience even a small portion of the
excitement that has greeted storied Bruins teams of the past.
</P>
<P>
   As much as people, myself included, romanticized the Garden, the
Bruins' buzz was not just about the Garden. It was about the team,
and about performance, and about playing the kind of hockey that
sells in this town. People here need to feel that, if only they
were good enough, they could skate a shift and be welcomed as one
of the gang. They want teams that hit, teams that don't back down.
They want a decent goaltender. After all, this is the franchise
that has had as its last line of resistance the likes of Tiny
Thompson, Frankie Brimsek, Terry Sawchuk, and Gerry Cheevers. Even
Jacques Plante passed through the Garden portals, turning in a
memorable shutout in his Boston debut. They've got the goaltender,
unless a Vezina Trophy candidate isn't good enough for someone.
</P>
<P>
   They've also got the kind of credibility an impressive Stanley
Cup series victory can bring. And the Carolina triumph was
impressive. The Bruins won a smooth Game 4 behind a raucous home
crowd, extricated themselves from a 2-0 two-period deficit before
winning on Mr. Carter's goal in the second OT in Game 5, and closed
out the series with a shutout conquest in Game 6, backed by a crowd
that, as Carter notes, bore the valued Ray Bourque imprimatur.
</P>
<P>
   The next step may or may not be too big for this group, but the
intriguing thing is that no one truly knows. The Bruins are in the
Eastern Conference championship mix, the town is alive, and the
players are thriving in the invigorating atmosphere. We can say
with assurance that they will not be easily deterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could it be more exciting?'' reasons Jason Allison. ``It's
Stanley Cup time. The adrenalin is pumping. Especially in this
conference, anyone left has a chance. Any team can win it. There's
not one of the four left you can look at and say, `That team can't
win it.' That includes us.''
</P>
<P>
   These Bruins can in no manner whatsoever be compared to their
elders. This isn't the Shore team or the Kraut Line team or the Orr
team. But, without doubt, something is stirring here. In reference
to the 1970 champs, Clark Booth maintains that ``the frozen ponds
of the National Hockey League composed their Agincourt.'' Give this
bunch a few more years and Mr. Booth might have to rack his
historical brain anew for a suitable salutation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
