<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, May 7. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Bonn, Germany) _ The West and Russia agreed for
the first time Thursday on the need for an international military
presence in Kosovo to keep any eventual peace, but the composition
of such a force and conditions for its deployment remained in
dispute. An agreement reached by foreign ministers from the Group
of Seven and Russia marked a decisive step away from the specter of
a wider conflict over the Balkans between Washington and Moscow. It
also intensified pressure on Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav
president, by demonstrating that Russia is not ready to turn its
back on the West to support him. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the Kosovo plan,
looking a how the U.S. is seeking a diplomatic solution that would
save face, what demands will the U.S. and NATO compromise on and
where this NATO-Russian agreement leaves Slobodan Milosevic, the
Yugoslav president. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRIZREN (Prizren, Yugoslavia) _ A look at a town cleared
of virtually all of its inhabitants. By Steven Erlanger
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-BUSH (Washington) House Republican leaders are so united
in their support for Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for their party's
presidential nomination that they have already begun meeting
informally to discuss a common agenda for Bush and House candidates
in the 2000 election. These meetings are the latest demonstration
of how much of the party appartus _ including the entire House
leadership _ has concluded that Bush's nomination is inevitable. By
Richard L. Berke
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-SPENDING (Undated) _ American consumers are on a
rampage, increasing their spending even faster than they did last
year. Retail analysts and economists point to numerous factors,
including the continued rise of both the stock market and home
values, to explain much of the gains. But another change is also
helping: While the wealthiest consumers powered the expansion in
its early stages, spending by those in the bottom 40 percent of
income, defined as households making up to $28,500 a year, has been
picking up. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MICROSOFT (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T and Microsoft have confirmed
plans for Microsoft to buy $5 billion of AT&AMP;T preferred shares in
exchange for nonexclusive rights on settop software. Microsoft will
also buy MediaOne's 29.9 percent stake in Telewest, Britain's
second-biggest cable company. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DOCTOR-KILLED (Buffalo, N.Y.) _ The district attorney here
charges James Kopp, an abortion foe, with murder in the shooting of
Dr. Barnett Slepian in October. By Joseph Berger.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN (Washington) _ Despite a remarkable run of prosperity
that he credited in large part to new technology, Alan Greenspan,
the Federal Reserve chairman, warned Thursday that the economy
could still be derailed by its old nemesis, inflation. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
</TEXT>
