u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     05-06 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEN MINDS, NEW IDEAS NEEDED IN THE WAKE OF HIGH SCHOOL MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 9)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In Littleton, Colo., the dead have been buried, the
memorial services have been held, the tears have been shed, and the
students who survived the massacre at Columbine High have begun
classes in another school.
</P>
<P>
   Pain and heartache continue to grip the pleasant community at
the foot of the Rocky Mountains as residents try to reconstruct
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the post-mortems continue to demonstrate that
a terrible tragedy like the one that exploded at Columbine High
School often reinforces human biases instead of opening minds and
changing opinions.
</P>
<P>
   In the rush to judgment, advocates of gun control demanded
stricter controls. Critics of current American values and political
leadership urged a renewal of old values and a change in leaders.
Those who cite the violence in movies, television, computer games
and rap lyrics wanted stricter control of such entertainment.
People who attribute the disaster in part to the absence of prayer
in public schools called for its return. Those who fault today's
family life demanded a revival of the ways of earlier eras, which
may or may not have been better.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on. Some of the demands are valid; others are not.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of broadening people's views, disasters like
Littleton and the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing often reinforce the
views they already hold.
</P>
<P>
   There is a huge market in America for smut, violence and
pornography. Not only do people pay money to witness this trash on
the big screen and the small screen, but critics often praise it
because they say violence and a graphic depiction of the sordid
side of life give provide ``realism.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be all right for adults. But it can be dangerous for
impressionable young people, especially those who have mental
problems.
</P>
<P>
   We now know that Eric Harris, one of the young men responsible
for the carnage at Columbine High, was highly disturbed _ filled
with hate, a love of war and a compulsion to kill. He could see in
movies and on TV and the Internet and could find in gun shops the
weapons to reinforce his hallucinations and his plans to spread
mayhem throughout his school, his community and even his country.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of tighter gun control point out that Harris and his
colleague, Dylan Klebold, made their own bombs, as did Timothy
McVeigh who killed 168 people in Oklahoma City. That is true. But
Harris and Klebold also obtained guns that they used to murder 12
fellow students and one teacher before killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Convening a National Rifle Association meeting in Denver shortly
after the tragedy in nearby Littleton, NRA President Charlton
Heston suggested callously that the organization had been made a
scapegoat for the Columbine massacre simply because one was needed.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Brady law that requires law enforcement officers
to check the backgrounds of would-be gun buyers appears to have
reduced the number of new gun purchases.
</P>
<P>
   But obviously more needs to be done. Guns appear to have been
obtained surrepticiously for Harris and Klebold by friends who were
old enough to buy them legally.
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting seriously a ban on guns used by hunters or
target shooters. But Congress, which often has acted like an
adjunct of the NRA, can and should do more to make it difficult for
potential murderers and thieves to obtain guns.
</P>
<P>
   Family values cannot be dictated by government. They must be
taught in the home. That means parents should become more involved
in the lives of their youngsters and should more carefully assess
their actions.
</P>
<P>
   It also could be helpful if teachers were required to instruct
their students in how to treat others. Many youngsters grow to
adulthood without ever learning good manners or proper etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment probably prevents government-decreed
censorship of motion pictures, television, computer games and rap
lyrics. But government leaders, from the president on down, and
private organizations dedicated to ethical and religious principles
can use their power of persuasion to achieve change.
</P>
<P>
   As for prayer, many of us believe it should be taught in the
home and the house of worship rather than in publicly funded
schools. It also is questionable whether prayer in public schools
could pass Constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   But the teachings of the various religions certainly could be
part of the curriculum a youngster learns in his or her formative
years.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, many actions can be taken at the national and the local
level to try to avert disasters similar to the one at Columbine
High. It is possible that it might not have happened if Harris and
Klebold had not been treated as outcasts by other students.
</P>
<P>
   We cannot revert to the Victorian age or to the 1950s. But we
can open our minds to the problems we face and seek ways to help
our young people and steer them away from such tragedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
