</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-ROMANIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE IN FIRST VISIT TO ORTHODOX ROMANIA IN 1000 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a bold and risky move to bridge a schism that has lasted
nearly 1,000 years, Pope John Paul II travels to Romania Friday for
the first papal visit to a majority Orthodox Christian nation since
the Roman Catholic Church and the Orthodox split in 1054.
</P>
<P>
   The historic trip is the most significant effort in recent
memory to try to reconcile the divisions between the two churches
that occurred nearly a millennium ago over bitter arguments about
papal authority.
</P>
<P>
   For John Paul, who has made improving relations between the
Roman Catholic Church and other faiths a hallmark of his
pontificate, his 86th pilgrimmage outside Italy is a major gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on John Paul's words and how they are interpreted by
the world's 223 million Orthodox, the visit could either help bring
the two churches closer or could simply harden existing feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely critical trip from both churches'
perspective,'' said the Rev. Thomas Reese, a papal analyst and
editor of America, a Jesuit magazine. ``The pope has had a policy
in which he would not go to an Orthodox country unless he was
invited by the Orthodox Church. He certainly doesn't want to do
anything to cause an ecumenical incident.''
</P>
<P>
   The division of Chrisitianity into eastern and western churches
revolved around theological issues, especially the Orthodox refusal
to recognize the pope as the head of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   While most Orthodox recognize the Ecumenical Patriarch who sits
in Constantinople as the spiritual leader of their faith, Orthodox
churches are divided into more than a dozen autonomous and largely
ethnic branches.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond long-running theological disputes, in recent years the
two churches have quarreled over church property and proselytizing.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War thousands of Catholic churches in the Soviet
Union and Soviet bloc countries were confiscated and taken over by
Orthodox Christians. And since the collapse of the Soviet Union,
the Orthodox have accused Catholics of trying to convert Orthodox
in former Communist countries.
</P>
<P>
   The squabbles between Orthodox and Catholics have sometimes
turned violent. Last year in Romania, for instance, Greek Catholics
got into a shoving match with an Orthodox congregation that had
been evicted from a Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a fight that has lasted 1,000 years and
that's not something that is going to be easy to overcome,'' noted
Juliane Cooper, a history professor at the University of New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   A highlight of John Paul's three-day visit to Romania and a
major ecumenical event is expected to occur on Sunday when the pope
and Romanian Orthodox Patriarch Teoctist are scheduled to attend
each other's liturgies.
</P>
<P>
   Arranging a papal visit to an Orthodox land was an arduous task.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul was eager to travel to Russia, the country with the
world's largest Orthodox population, but the Orthodox Church there
has refused to invite him.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican then turned to Romania, where 80 percent of the 22
million people are Orthodox and whose Orthodox Church is second to
Russia's in numbers and importance.
</P>
<P>
   But it took months of delicate negotiations before the Romanian
Orthodox Church would accede to a papal visit. One key Vatican
concession is the pope's agreement not to visit Transylvania or
Moldovia, two regions with large concentrations of Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   The Romanian Orthodox Church feared that the pope's presence in
those two areas would stir up tensions between the Orthodox and the
Catholics. The Russian Orthodox Church has warned that the pope's
visit could easily exacerbate tensions between the Orthodox and
Roman Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul also will have to be cautious in how he addresses the
war in Yugoslavia, which the Vatican has tried to bring to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   While Romania, which borders Yugoslavia, has allowed NATO to use
its air space, the Romanian Orthodox Church supports their fellow
Orthodox Serbs in their claims to sovereignty over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican, meanwhile, has been vocal in its condemnation of
ethnic cleansing of Muslim Kosovars by armed Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   But John Paul, more than any other pope in recent memory, has
repeatedly expressed deep respect and fondness for the Orthodox.
``He feels that the well of spirituality runs very deeply in the
east, more so than in the west,'' said the Reverend Richard
McBrien, a professor of theology at Notre Dame University.
</P>
<P>
   And, Reese added, John Paul has ``always believed that the best
ecumenical opportunity for the Catholic Church is with the Orthodox
because our theology is so similar.''
</P>
<P>
   Undoing divisions that have lasted for centuries will require
``small incremental steps,'' said Thomas Groome, a theology
professor at Boston College. ``This trip is a small step and might
very well be remembered in the future as a big moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
