<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROMISES REFUGEES THEY WILL GO BACK HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGELHEIM, Germany _ Meeting for the first time with the human
beings whose plight is behind the biggest military gamble of his
presidency, President Clinton Thursday told more than 300 ethnic
Albanian refugees that they would return to their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Under overcast skies in a clean but cheerless refugee camp in
the rural Rhineland, Clinton spoke to a group of traumatized people
who were, like him, serious and somber.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will go home again, in safety and in freedom,'' Clinton
said. He gave them no time frame, and they responded with polite
applause.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared moved during more informal meetings, first with
one family, and then with two dozen refugees who were flown to the
German camp April 9 after fleeing into Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees told variations of the same theme: how they were
rousted from their homes by Serb paramilitary police who threatened
them with death unless they boarded trains in Pristina, the Kosovo
capital, for Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   A teenage boy broke down, telling Clinton, ``I cannot talk about
Kosovo.'' Clinton, moved by the boy's distress, later comforted
him. White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said the refugees
reassured Clinton that the war against Yugoslavia was justified and
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton toured the refugee camp with German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder before flying to Bonn for a meeting with the German
leader. Schroeder told the refugees that their plight had
strengthened the resolve of NATO to see through its bombing
campaign until Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic gives in to
NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the camp, a former youth offender facility where the
refugees live in clean, spartan dormitory rooms with bunk beds,
Clinton sat and listened to the story of Sabit Salihu and his
family. Salihu, 60, said that his grandson, Blendan, was born March
24, the day NATO began bombing, but that four days later masked
Serb forces ordered them to leave or be killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My home was burned. We were beaten. Everything was stolen from
us,'' Salihu told Clinton, speaking through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Salihu said that during their trek out of Kosovo, his three
daughters smeared their faces with mud to make themselves
unattractive after learning that Serb troops had been raping
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Salihu's 25-year-old nephew, Rexhap, said Serb troops taunted
them as they fled, saying, ``If you want NATO and Clinton, go
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's eyes were moist as he listened.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the glare of the president, other refugees were
cautious when asked if NATO needed to do more. None of them blamed
NATO's bombing for hastening their expulsions, saying Milosevic was
determined to drive them out of Kosovo anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But Beckim Ademi, 25, a truck driver, urged NATO to send in
ground troops to finish off the paramilitary forces hiding in
civilian homes in Kosovo. ``They need to go in now, to help the
people stuck inside Kosovo,'' said Ademi.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees here are the few lucky ones. They all survived days
in an open field in Blace, a border crossing in northern Macedonia,
and were picked at random to be flown out to Germany. Many families
said they had been separated in the confusion as Macedonian
authorities bundled them onto buses.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left the camp, Clinton urged the assembled group of
refugees not to become bitter. He told them he was of Irish
heritage and quoted the Irish poet William Butler Yeats, who in his
poem ``Easter 1916,'' about violent nationalism, observed, ``Too
long a sacrifice can make a stone of the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask you . . . not to let your hearts turn to stone,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the refugees politely applauded and Clinton shook hands
as the public address system bizarrely and inexplicably played a
cheery accordion version of ``Red River Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   But away from the president, refugees were saying they cannot be
anything but bitter. Ekrem Lapashtica, 24, said he ran a video
store before the Serbs forced him out. Now he wants to join the
rebel Kosovo Liberation Army and fight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the only way we get our rights back,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1831EDT &QL; 
