<HEADER>
A7256 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      05-06 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEVIL IS IN THE _ MANY _ DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 44 days of NATO bombing and 44 days of Yugoslav defiance,
a plan to end the Kosovo conflict is finally taking shape.
</P>
<P>
   A joint statement issued Thursday by the United States, Russia,
and other members of the Group of Eight nations meeting in Bonn,
Germany, is a big step forward, say diplomatic analysts. But the
devil _ a brigade of devils _ will be in the details.
</P>
<P>
   What the Group of Eight (which also includes Britain, France,
Italy, Germany, Canada, and Japan) achieved was to bring Russia
over to the NATO position that Serb forces must leave Kosovo and
that an international security force must be allowed to enter to
protect refugees as they return.
</P>
<P>
   The language of the statement was hazy, however, when it comes
to the type of international force that would go in and other
crucial issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is positive. Bringing Russia in as a real participant is
an important accomplishment. But the parties will now have to come
to the table to talk about specifics, and that will be a very long
process,'' said Jeswald Salacuse, a professor of international
negotiation and conflict resolution at Tufts University's Fletcher
School of Law and Diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest problem: Before the bombing stops, Yugoslav leader
Slobodan Milosevic will have to accept the G-8 plan, at least in
principle. As of Thursday ight, he had not. So NATO air raids
continued.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect a bombing halt until Milosevic makes a credible
withdrawal from Kosovo, said Peter Galbraith, former US ambassador
to Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing he'd like better than a bombing halt and a
permanent period of negotiations,'' said Galbraith. ``At that point
there would be no punishment for him, and he would be much more
firmly in control of Kosovo than before the war began. That is a
trap that NATO has to avoid.''
</P>
<P>
   But before Milosevic accepts the G-8 plan or any other, Yugoslav
officials have made clear, key points of contention _ especially
the matter of what kind of international force will be deployed to
Kosovo _ will have to be clarified.
</P>
<P>
   The wording of the G-8 plan was vague on this point, mentioning
``deployment in Kosovo of effective international civil and
security presences'' but not specifying what countries would make
up the force or how it would be armed.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said the force must
have ``NATO at its core'' and include American and British troops.
Milosevic has long objected to this. He wants a lightly armed force
without NATO involvement. Russia says Milosevic's acceptance of the
type and strength of the force is essential.
</P>
<P>
   Anything less, for Milosevic, would be a loss _ and could
threaten his survival as Serb leader. But without overwhelming NATO
military strength inside Kosovo, the alliance will not be able to
intimidate local combatants or deter revenge attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence of uniforms alone does not a military operation
make,'' said William Nash, a former major general who commanded US
Army troops in the 1995 Bosnia deployment. ``In Bosnia, having a
robust force with great capacity was crucial. We were in charge. We
eliminated the opportunity for ongoing violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash acknowledges that in Bosnia all of the sides had stopped
fighting and that the cease-fire had held for two months before the
NATO force went in.
</P>
<P>
   Composition of the force is only one of the military questions,
said Roger Fisher, director of the Harvard Negotiation Project and
long active in international conflict resolution. Among other tough
issues, he said, will be how to verify Serb forces have pulled out
of Kosovo, how to schedule the transition of control, and how to
settle disputes that will arise on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Then there will be big questions involving the return of ethnic
Albanians to Kosovo, many of whom have been stripped of their
identity papers, and how to get humanitarian aid into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Finally will come the biggest question of all: the future of
Kosovo. The Serbs rejected the Rambouillet plan for Kosovo that was
drafted before the conflict began. Almost certainly, they would not
accept it now, even after being pounded by NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all these substantive items, how do you take this plan
forward so that it gives Milosevic and his people a sense that they
are participating in this?'' asked Fisher, who said what is needed
now is a neutral party, such as United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan, to mediate between Belgrade and the 19-member NATO
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   That won't be easy either, he admits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a situation where you have a committee on one side
and a liar on the other,'' said Fisher. ``How in the hell does
Milosevic give credible assurances that he is complying?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
