<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7266 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-VACATION-KIDS-     05-06 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VACATION-KIDS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR VACATIONS RATED G 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 9) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By CARL SOMMERS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the structure of the school year and the rhythms of the
business world, summer travel is often family travel. Visits to
museums, historic sites and restaurants must be leavened with
diversions for children, and a family at the beach needs backup
when it rains.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, destinations are complying. Museums are adding
areas for toddlers or emphasizing yucky stuff kids like, bugs and
rats among them. Sea life entertainment centers are adding rides
and theme restaurants staffed with actors and entertainers.
Historic centers are catering to smaller visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Even amusement parks realize that not all children want to
experience several G-forces on a roller coaster, so they are
enlisting employees to wear cartoon-character costumes and wander
around areas that contain gentler rides.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of child-oriented attractions that visitors
would not have seen last summer:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAKING A SPLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: The Sea World parks, long known for dancing dolphins
and leaping whales, have been adding attractions of a more
mechanized sort. The park in San Diego opens its first adventure
ride May 29, though it is one that doesn't leave the water. It is
called Shipwreck Rapids, and the premise is that riders are island
castaways in an inner tube (actually a nine-passenger raft) trying
to navigate a rough river that will return them to civilization.
</P>
<P>
   On the trip, the passengers bounce through rapids, and in case
they are not wet enough, pass under dripping cargo nets and leaky
buckets left by wrecked ships and narrowly miss a partly submerged
ship's propeller. They will see live turtles and crabs and actors
in the role of castaways along the banks.
</P>
<P>
   The raft enters a dark tunnel and the hissing engine room of a
ship before ending the trip at the foot of a restaurant called the
Shipwreck Reef Cafe. There, diners can view live flamingos, ibises,
sea turtles and occasionally penguins, sea lions or otters.
</P>
<P>
   Sea World California, 500 Sea World Drive, San Diego, (619)
226-3901, is generally open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., but 9 a.m. to 10
p.m. starting on June 12; open later on weekends. Admission is $38;
$29 for children 3 to 11, $35 for 55 years and older. Parking costs
$6; www.seaworld.com.
</P>
<P>
   BRANSON: There are steel coasters and wood ones. May 16, in
Branson, Mo., Silver Dollar City, a turn-of-the-century-theme park
in the Ozarks, is adding Buzz Saw Falls, a ``liquid'' coaster.
</P>
<P>
   This ride takes visitors in a free-floating boat that plunges
down a flume at up to 51 miles an hour and then becomes a regular
mechanical coaster that is pulled up a track before making a final
six-and-a-half-story drop.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Dollar City, on West Highway 76, Branson, Mo., (800)
952-6626, is open daily in summer 9:30 a.m. to 7 p.m. Admission:
$31.20, $20.50 for ages 4 to 11 and $29.10 for 55 and older;
www.silverdollarcity.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILD THINGS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: In a world of animatronic T. Rexes and 12-story
upside-down triple-spiral roller coasters, a four-inch-long animal
that looks like a hot dog with buck teeth and a tail may seem like
an unlikely attraction for children. But naked mole rats, native to
Africa, have been drawing crowds at a number of zoos around the
country, and now the children's section of the St. Louis Zoo is
home to 15 of them.
</P>
<P>
   They live in six large transparent cylinders connected by clear
tunnels, something like an ant farm. In fact, the animals have a
social system much like that of ants, with a breeding queen and a
few breeding males. The others, male and female, are workers and
soldiers. The naked mole rats have eyes that don't see, but their
noses and ears work well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very popular because they're repulsive,'' said Alice
Seyfried, supervisor of the children's zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The children's zoo also has new shows featuring otters and birds
and the main zoo expects to open a ``river's edge'' exhibit,
featuring Asian elephants.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Zoo, Forest Park, St. Louis, (314) 781-0900, is
open daily 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. (till dusk on Tuesday between Memorial
Day and Labor Day). Admission is free. The children's zoo is free
from 9 to 10 a.m. and $3 thereafter; children 2 and younger are
always free. Web site: www.stlzoo.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BRONX: Visits to New York often include a performance of
``The Lion King,'' with its stylized African setting, at least for
those who get tickets months ahead. Families can step into another
re-creation of Africa beginning June 24 at the Bronx Zoo, in the
Congo Gorilla Forest.
</P>
<P>
   A trail about a half-mile-long will take visitors through a
6.5-acre tract of central African rain forest, past colobus
monkeys, okapi, mandrills, guenons and red river hogs. The shady
forest will include more than 20,000 plants of 400 species, with
rocky outcrops, streams, wading pools and thickets of bamboo.
</P>
<P>
   The trail leads to a 37,000-square-foot building with smaller
African rain forest animals, like fish, snakes and mice. After a
seven-minute film about gorillas, the screen will rise to reveal a
large window through which a troop of gorillas will be visible.
Visitors then move on to other sites _ indoors and out _ to see
these and other gorillas _ there are about 20 in all.
</P>
<P>
   Also inside will be 21 interactive learning bays, in which, for
example, a human can call up a thermal image that illustrates how a
heat-sensing snake ``sees'' him. An area devoted to rain forest
conservation, built around an artificial rain forest tree with a
wedge cut out by a chain saw, will teach about deforestation,
overpopulation and other threats, and allow visitors to donate
their admission fees to the preservation of gorillas, elephants,
mandrills or okapi.
</P>
<P>
   On eight consecutive weekends beginning June 26 (including
Monday, July 5), Celebration Congo, free with zoo admission, will
feature African music and dance, stilt walkers and face painters.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx Zoo, Fordham Road and Bronx River Parkway, Bronx,
N.Y., (718) 367-1010, is open weekdays 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., weekends
10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. Admission is $7.75, $4 for ages 2 to 12 and 65
and older. Wednesday admission is free, with a donation suggested.
Admission to Congo Gorilla Forest will be $3; www.bronxzoo.com.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: When the weather doesn't cooperate, a museum can make
for diverting and even educational shelter, if it knows how to
engage children. In this city known for rainy days, the Pacific
Science Center offers 4,000 square feet at a steady 80 degrees
(though a bit humid at 80 percent) and an average of 6,000
foot-candles of light; on a typical cloudy Seattle day, about 1,800
foot-candles reach the ground at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Those bright, warm conditions are in the new Tropical Butterfly
House, and are perfect for butterflies, around 1,000 of which
flutter freely there. Pupae are brought in, from, say, Costa Rica,
and blue morphos butterflies emerge, or gold-banded foresters from
Kenya hatch as visitors watch through a window to the Emerging
Room. Since each butterfly lives little more than two weeks,
species are rotated.
</P>
<P>
   Next door, bugs are a big attraction at the museum's new Insect
Village. There is an insect zoo, where visitors can see 10 types of
insects, like hissing cockroaches, giant centipedes and hairy
tarantulas, and six types of arthropods (not the same thing, one
learns) and can touch some of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Insecta Sideshow is a ``tent'' that tells, through
interactive displays, of fleas that can jump 200 times their
length, of ants that can lift more than 50 times their weight and
of beetles that hunt underwater. A Wall of Fame illustrates the
smallest (a wasp one two-hundredth of an inch long), the heaviest
(a quarter-pound beetle), the longest (a 22-inch walking stick) and
the loudest (an African cicada as loud as a jackhammer) insects.
The museum also has an IMAX Theater, which can show 3-D movies.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Science Center, 200 Second Avenue North, Seattle, (206)
443-2001, is open weekdays 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., and 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.
weekends and all summer. Admission is $7.50, $5.50 for ages 3 to 13
and 65 and older. IMAX and laser shows are $4.50 and up;
www.pacsci.org.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
