<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, May 7. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Y2K HOTELS (Phoenix) - Father time wears a Rolex this New Year's
Eve and free-spending partiers might wake up in the new millennium
with a Dom Perignon-like hangover. Four nights at the MGM Grand and
Barbra singing `The Way We Were` (Before We Were Broke) at a Jan.
31 show is $8,500. The Phoenician's seven-night package is $6,600
per couple. The Arizona Biltmore is bringing in the Righteous Bros.
and the Temptations on back to back nights in a package that ranges
from $7,000 to $15,000. By PETER CORBETT. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SCHOOL-THREAT (Prescott Valley, Ariz.) - Two 8th-graders in a
Prescott Valley charter school have been arrested for allegedly
telling authorities they'd been planning to shoot teachers and
students in their school. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ALBERTO RIOS-BOOK (Phoenix) - Bilingualism has served writer
Alberto Rios well, teaching him that everything has more than one
name. Critics have said he writes in Spanish that looks like
English: English words, Spanish syntax. The emotion is uniquely
Rios. Though primarily known as a poet, Rios has just published a
new collection of short stories, ``The Curtain of Trees,'' which
draws from his heritage in a Mexican-American family of
storytellers. By BARBARA YOST. Story moved in the ``E'' category &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Before the massacre at Columbine High
School in Colorado, 14-year-old Tim Murphy turned in a fictional
story, a fairy tale, for a class at Pioneer Elementary School in
Glendale. Tim's story was titled, ``The Wicked Teacher.'' Not long
after turning in the assignment, Tim received a 10-day suspension
for `'written statements that threaten the safety of school
staff.'' That's what we do in America. We ignore problems until
it's too late, then respond in a way that's completely out of
proportion. It'll happen soon in schools across the land. By E.J.
MONTINI. Story moved in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MUMMY-MOVIE (Phoenix) - The good news: It's not ``Allan Quartermain
and the Lost City of Gold.'' Of course, it's not ``Raiders of the
Lost Ark,'' either. But then what is? ``The Mummy'' is a definite
charge, if you're looking for spectacle, rowdy adventure and
supernatural horror all crammed into a raucous two hours of
high-testosterone special-effects filmmaking. By BOB FENSTER. Story
moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Phoenix) - Cheap wheels, basic transportation.
Whatever you call it, the Chevrolet Metro is as minimalistic as
they come. Also known as Suzuki Swift, the Metro is best regarded
as an urban vehicle, a commuter or grocery-getter that is cheap to
buy, cheap to own and cheap to operate. It's there to get the job
done, but it also provides some sporty small-car enjoyment. And the
gas mileage is excellent. By BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in the ``L''
category. Embargoed for Saturday, May 8. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
