<HEADER>
A7268 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-VACATION-KIDS-     05-06 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VACATION-KIDS-ART-2NDTAKE-$adv09-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: www.pacsci.org.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SCREAM A LITTLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRANSON: A whole new amusement park, Branson USA Entertainment
Park, opens Friday. Set on 50 acres, the park will have about 20
rides, including a six-story steel coaster from Belgium, the
Firestorm, and a 10-story Ferris wheel from Italy that offers
riders in 26 gondolas views of Branson and the Ozarks.
</P>
<P>
   Future stock car racers will be able to ride on two elevated
go-cart tracks ($5) and there will be food and 20 shops selling
mainly souvenirs and toys. There will be six rides for the very
young.
</P>
<P>
   Branson USA Entertainment Park, Highways 376 and 76, Branson,
Mo., (417) 335-2396, is to open daily 11 a.m. to midnight.
Admission is free; an all-day pass for rides costs $15.95, $7.95
for ages 4 to 9.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER: Familiar cartoon characters, particularly ones with
prominent ears, have some history as a device for attracting
children to parks. The dozen Six Flags parks have enlisted Bugs
Bunny, along with other Looney Tunes characters.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, Six Flags Elitch Gardens has redone its children's
play area, called it Looney Tunes Movie Town and put in 10 rides
for children under 54 inches tall. Among them are Pounce and
Bounce, in which children seated in a cylinder are pulled about 20
feet to the top of a tower and dropped, a carousel called Around
the World in 80 Seconds and Marvin the Martian's Reel Spin.
</P>
<P>
   A play area called the Looney Tunes Acme Prop Warehouse, for
children 54 inches or shorter, will mainly feature foam balls that
can be thrown or shot with an air cannon, plus slides. A musical
show, ``What's Up, Rock?'' will feature Bugs Bunny, Daffy Duck,
Sylvester, the Tasmanian Devil and other characters performing
'50s-style songs.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the Batman Forever Thrill Spectacular is a stunt show
in which the Caped Crusader, Robin and the Riddler fall from
heights, fly and flip on motorcycles amid explosions and fireballs.
And those too tall for the Acme Prop Warehouse, that is over 54
inches, can get full-size thrills on the area's fourth roller
coaster, the Boomerang, which sends riders down a 125-foot drop and
through three loops before they reverse the trip, facing backward.
</P>
<P>
   Six Flags Elitch Gardens, 299 Walnut Street, Denver, (303)
595-4386, is open 5 to 10 p.m. Friday, 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. Saturday
and 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. Sunday till Memorial Day, then 10 to 10 daily
June 4 to Aug. 30. Admission is $28, $14 for children shorter than
48 inches and $16 for those 55 to 69; www.sixflags.com.
</P>
<P>
   PIGEON FORGE: Dollywood, Dolly Parton's entertainment and
amusement park in Tennessee, has put in a new roller coaster. The
park celebrates the culture and music of the Great Smoky Mountains,
and the Tennessee Tornado provides riders views of the Smokies from
above, on a 137-foot climb, and from within, through a dark tunnel.
The coaster emerges and takes riders on a series of 360-degree
loops at 63 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The park has also opened the Southern Gospel Music Hall of Fame
and Museum, tracing gospel music from the 19th century to today.
</P>
<P>
   Dollywood, (800) 365-5996, is in Pigeon Forge, 35 miles
southeast of Knoxville, and is open April through December. The
hours vary, but on most summer days they are 9 a.m. to 9 p.m.
One-day admission is $29.99, $20.99 ages 4 to 11 and $24.99 for 60
years and older, plus tax; www.dollywood.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SINK OR SWIM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO: The Titanic and its fate may have seemed fusty until
the movie of a couple of years ago captured the imagination of the
public and the hearts of Leonardo-smitten teen-agers. A new
attraction in the Mercado shopping and entertainment complex in
Orlando, Fla., Titanic _ Ship of Dreams, houses pieces of both the
real and cinematic versions.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors start at a ``dock'' with a 40-foot section of a ship's
side as the sounds of horse hooves, a foghorn and shouts of people
seeing off passengers are broadcast. Inside, they walk through
re-creations of rooms in the Titanic, including the grand staircase
and more than 200 artifacts from the ship, including a deck chair
(predictable joke here), letters on ship stationery, a life jacket
and first-class china.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the movie memorabilia: a costume worn by Leonardo
DiCaprio among them. Staff members in period costume play the role
of passengers and tell stories about the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Titanic _ Ship of Dreams, 8445 International Drive, Orlando,
Fla., (407) 248-1166, is open daily 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. Admission is
$14.95, $9.95 for ages 6 to 11; www.titanicshipofdreams.com.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Aquariums are associated with sights of the sea, but the
New England Aquarium in Boston is directing attention to its
sounds. A new exhibit, ``Sounds of the Sea,'' hums, clicks, rumbles
and roars with the crack and creak of an iceberg, the odd clang of
a walrus and the snap of shrimp, among other noises that fish hear
(they do have ears).
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit includes three chambers that broadcast the calls of
migrating humpback whales and the natural and man-made _ from
sources like boats and oil _ sounds they hear in the Atlantic.
Sound ``dictionaries'' translate the noises.
</P>
<P>
   At interactive stations, visitors can impersonate a dolphin
bouncing sounds off the ocean floor or hear how an operatic tenor
singing underwater would sound a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds of the Sea'' is in the Exploration Center next to the
main exhibition building of the New England Aquarium, Central
Wharf, Boston, (617) 973-5200. From July 1 to Labor Day, the
aquarium opens daily at 9 a.m. and closes Monday, Tuesday and
Friday at 6 p.m., Wednesday and Thursday at 8 p.m. and weekends at
7 p.m. The rest of the year, it is open weekdays 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
and weekends 9 a.m. to 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $12, $6 for ages 3 to 11 and $10 ages 60 and older;
www.neaq.org.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
