</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-VACATION-KIDS-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: www.neaq.org.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S SHOW TIME &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMSBURG: Long an attraction for adults and older children
keen on learning about Colonial America, Colonial Williamsburg has
been making efforts to engage younger visitors. The latest is
children's theater.
</P>
<P>
   The show, to be held Wednesday nights this summer, is ``Bill and
Betsey's Pirate Adventure,'' aimed at ages 5 to 12. In it, three
20th-century children arrive in Colonial Williamsburg to meet their
grandmother. They fall asleep and dream about joining forces with
life-size versions of Bill, Betsey, Farrah and Hotch Potch, the
official dolls of Colonial Williamsburg, to find Granny Epps. It
seems she is being held by pirates who have fled custody and stolen
cookies from a bakery as they fled.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Granny gives the pirates her recipe for gingerbread
cookies, they become honest bakers in old Virginia and she is
released. Songs are sung, children get to parade across the stage,
and they have absorbed some details about 18th-century life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill and Betsey's Pirate Adventure'' will be performed
Wednesday at 6:30 p.m. in Hennage Auditorium in the DeWitt Wallace
Gallery from July 7 to Sept. 1. Admission is $10.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial Williamsburg, Post Office Box 1776, Williamsburg, (800)
447-8679, is open daily 9 A.M to 5 p.m. One-day admission is $27,
which does not provide parking ($6) or entry to the museums or
Governor's Palace, and $16 ages 6 to 12. A Patriot's Pass, $35, $20
for children, provides admission for a year, including parking and
admission to other sites, plus $2 off tickets to the play;
www.history.org.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR ALL AGES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SANDUSKY: Too often, parents have a choice between
stomach-dropping thrill rides that would scare their children and
kiddie rides that leave the parents on the sideline waving weakly
each time the little car comes around. But parks are beginning to
install what they call family rides, big enough for grown-ups and
children to ride together but tame enough to leave their stomachs
where they are.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Point, a 364-acre park on a peninsula in Lake Erie in
Sandusky, Ohio, has 67 rides, including 13 coasters _ steel, wood,
stand-up, all-dark, suspended _ and a 300-foot free-fall ride. This
season, Cedar Point is opening a family section called Camp Snoopy.
It will feature Peanuts characters (Charlie Brown, Lucy, Sally,
Schroeder and, of course, Snoopy) wandering around and appearing in
musical shows.
</P>
<P>
   The area has six family rides (and one just for kids), including
cars on a track, a ``camp bus'' on a big arm that goes around, up
and down, and a 38-foot-high roller coaster called the Woodstock
Express.
</P>
<P>
   Also new this year: an expansion to the Hotel Breakers on the
grounds, a '50s-theme diner and a ``stock-kart'' raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Point, 1 Cedar Point Drive, Sandusky, Ohio, (419)
627-2350, is open daily today to Sept. 6, plus Sept. 12, 18, 19,
24, 25 and 26 and Oct. 1, 2, 3, 8, 9 and 10. Hours: 10 a.m. to 7
p.m. weekdays most of May and to 10 p.m. weekends, and 10 a.m. to
10 or 11 p.m. or midnight most of June, July and August.
</P>
<P>
   One-day admission is $32.95 (lower after Labor Day), $27.95 for
those 48 to 54 inches tall, $8.95 for ages 4 and older under 48
inches tall; www.cedarpoint.com.
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO: With the swirl of activity at Walt Disney World, a
circus there would seem redundant. Yet Disney World does indeed
have an outpost of the Cirque du Soleil, in the Downtown Disney
entertainment and shopping district.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute production is ``La Nouba'' (from the French
``faire la Nouba'' meaning ``to party'' or ``live it up'') and it
features more than 60 gymnasts, acrobats, dancers and clowns. The
central idea is a clash between the monochromatic Urbains and the
colorful Cirques, performed in the French Canadian company's
distinctive dreamlike and highly theatrical style.
</P>
<P>
   In the Animal Kingdom, the animal park that opened last year, a
whole new continent _ Asia _ has opened, with real animals in
manufactured scenes. One attraction is a ride on the Kali River
Rapids through rain forest (including a burning logged-out area)
and by temple ruins and waterfalls. Another is the Maharajah Jungle
Trek, a walk that includes sights of gibbons on a Nepalese-style
tower and ruins of a Thai temple, tigers at a maharajah's palace,
giant fruit bats by cliffs, a komodo dragon and a variety of birds.
And the Flights of Wonder show, at the Caravan Stage outdoor
amphitheater, has been revamped with a new story line and new
birds, including macaws and ibis.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic Kingdom section has added Buzz Lightyear's Space
Ranger Spin to Tomorrowland. This ride is essentially a shooting
gallery: Visitors join Buzz (the ``to infinity and beyond''
character in ``Toy Story'') in a quest to keep the sinister Emperor
Zurg from stealing all his fellow toys' batteries to fuel his own
weapon of destruction. On their space cruisers, equipped with twin
laser guns and a joy stick that spins the craft, children blast
orange Emperor Zurg insignias and battle giant robots.
</P>
<P>
   At Epcot, the one-mile Test Track enables visitors to drive
indoors through cold and hot conditions and outdoors up to 65 miles
an hour. Drivers can go up hills and take their cars through skids
and a 50-degree banked curve.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Doug Live'' stage show has been inaugurated at the
Disney-MGM Studios park. Doug is the animated character of a
children's TV show muddling through his middle school years. And
near the entrance to the Blizzard Beach water park, is a new
36-hole miniature golf course, half the holes in summer sand and
half in winter ``snow.''
</P>
<P>
   General information on Walt Disney World is available at (407)
824-4321. Hours vary for the various parks but in summer, the
Animal Kingdom is usually open 8 a.m. to 7 p.m., the Magic Kingdom
9 a.m. to 10 p.m., and Disney-MGM, 9 a.m. till 7 to 10 p.m.
Admission to any one park is $42, plus tax, $34 for ages 3 to 9;
there is a variety of multipark and multiday passes.
</P>
<P>
   La Nouba tickets, which are $56.50 and $45.20 for ages 3 to 9,
plus tax, can be reserved at (407) 939-7600. Performances take
place Wednesday to Saturday at 5:30 and 8:30 p.m. and Sunday at
2:30 and 5:30 p.m.; www.disneyworld.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
