<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOP ON PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Perhaps the Kentucky Derby's crowded 19-horse field
will be an inspiration. The thunder of 76 hooves made for the most
exciting race in many years, and a dark horse took the roses,
paying off very well on long odds.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months from the first primary, the Republican presidential
field is similarly jammed with panting runners. Twelve announced,
semi-announced or thinking-about-announcing GOP candidates are
poised at the political gate to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first presidential election since 1944 in which the
Republican pack has not been dominated by an incumbent president, a
towering World War II hero or a seemingly invincible single
frontrunner. The temptation to run has been irresistible for a host
of candidates without much going for them.
</P>
<P>
   Out of this mob scene a handful of stars will gradually emerge.
A few months on the road will eliminate those who cannot get
nationwide attention, raise dizzyingly large sums of money or stay
out of political trouble. In New Hampshire last Sunday, the state
Republican Party tried to jump-start the 2000 show by gathering
eight candidates to present abbreviated versions of their case for
themselves and raise a little money in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the biggest GOP names did not show _ Texas Gov. George
W. Bush, Arizona Sen. John McCain and conservative television
commentator Patrick Buchanan. The biggest name who did appear,
Elizabeth Dole, stole the evening with sensible, tolerant positions
on gun control and abortion that defied heavy-handed party
orthodoxy and represented a clever effort to reach beyond the GOP
right wing. For her independence, she was booed.
</P>
<P>
   Question: When is it good for a presidential candidate to be
booed in the first primary state? Answer: When the state is
irrationally pro-gun and the candidate is a well known but
electorally untested woman who needs to demonstrate that she can be
tough.
</P>
<P>
   Bush naturally dominated the field just by not being there, but
then he's never anywhere but Texas, at least until next month. His
so-called yellow rose garden strategy cannot go on forever, despite
his healthy lead in the Republican polls. Voters are rallying
behind the family name. They don't know the individual.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hiding behind his local duties, he'd better let them
know how he thinks and what he's like soon. He who sits on hot
political lead can get bottom burned.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is creating a vacuum that allows others to get noticed. He
leads Dole, his nearest challenger, by 2 to 1 in most polls. But
she is moving now and should not be underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   And McCain, who got family-friendly points by staying away from
New Hampshire to celebrate his son's 13th birthday, is steadily
rising in the polls in response to his hawkish stand toward the
Serbian assault on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He was supported for president by 14 percent of local GOP voters
surveyed in a New Hampshire TV station poll last week, double his
previous numbers. That's not stratospheric, but he is breaking out
of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates most identified with one or more key
issues often do better than those who have a reputation for a mushy
general philosophy. McCain will now forever be the foreign policy
hawk in the race. Dole will be the gun control diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Publishing baron Steve Forbes, known for his radical flat-tax
proposal when he ran four years ago, is trying to broaden his
appeal by talking about other issues and modifying the flat-tax
nonsense. He has merely lost his focus. What makes Forbes stand out
now? Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is a publicity sideshow, always good for an outrageous
quote but no longer fresh, as he was in 1996. Furthermore, this
time his isolationism is not just nuts but positively dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to imagine anyone but their mothers seeing the
others as serious presidential material. This is a lot of
``formers'' in search of current employment. These guys need to get
a life.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle is still a joke. His prompt
reaffirmation of the wisdom of the National Rifle Association's
resistance to modest gun control measures confirms that he hasn't
learned a thing since he left office seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's former Secretary of Education Lamar Alexander,
whose major national qualification for the White House is a Cabinet
post that he thinks is of so little importance that he told
Congress to abolish it.
</P>
<P>
   And there's former anti-abortion lobbyist Gary Bauer, who vowed
to ``devote every waking hour of my presidency'' to outlawing that
legal procedure. This means he would be asleep when problems of
Social Security, Medicare, Kosovo, the economy, education, crime
and national security hit his White House desk. Hmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Rep. John Kasich, young and stingy, thinks that cutting
federal budgets for public services that voters need and want will
win him votes. Dream on, tightwad.
</P>
<P>
   Why talk show host Alan Keyes and New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith
are in this beats me. It will beat the voters too.
</P>
<P>
   And last but maybe not least, there's New York Gov. George
Pataki, who is making the standard preliminary moves of a potential
presidential candidate, short of actually committing himself. The
locals say he's really after the vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   We've all been complaining that the primary season is
front-loaded and short and will be essentially over by mid-March of
next year. Maybe that's not such a bad idea after all. The sooner
the field is thinned out, the better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
