A7275 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CGARCIA-COLUMN07-COX     05-06 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CGARCIA-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I hope prequel reignites magic of 22 years ago
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like a lot of young boys in the late 1970s, I was a
big ``Star Wars'' fan. Actually, I was a fan even before the movie
was released on May 25, 1977, before any of us had an inkling of
the movie's seismic power, before I was bonking my brother on the
head with my plastic Eveready light saber.
</P>
<P>
   A few months earlier, my journalist father had received a
Twentieth Century Fox press kit, which included a lobby card and a
sheaf of glossy 8-by-10s showing various ``Star Wars'' characters.
He gave it to me. Unsure what the movie was all about (space? the
desert?) and humming with questions (``Mom, what's a Wookiee?''), I
was nevertheless enthralled. I stuck the pictures on my wall.
Chewbacca was my favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the movie, of course, amplified my ardor for ``Star
Wars,'' exponentially. I acquired ``Star Wars'' toys, trading
cards, sheets, the soundtrack, even the disco mix of John Williams'
theme song by Meco. The Force wasn't with me; it owned me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' monopolized my imagination for a healthy spell.
Its appeal was clear: the simplistic, archetypal narrative, so
rigidly Manichaean (a word I wouldn't learn to love until I was at
least 11); the whiz-bang effects; the crisp lines and bone-white
surfaces of the space ships; the androids, Tusken Raiders, Jawas on
down. And, yes, Wookiees.
</P>
<P>
   For little boys, the film was a triumph of visceral fulfillment,
with only the most elemental emotional cargo to weigh on our tiny
chests. It was light, digestible and furnished a semblance of
resonance, of something lasting and vital. A semblance because by
the time ``The Empire Strikes Back'' came around, in 1980, my
enthusiasm for ``Star Wars'' was receding. By ``Return of the
Jedi,'' in 1983, it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   You know why I bring all this up. On May 19, almost 22 years to
the day since George Lucas unveiled ``Star Wars,'' the film's first
of three planned prequels, ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace,'' will open. We're all aware of the clangorous pre-hype. We
know the drill.
</P>
<P>
   As you read this, I'm in New York for Fox's official ``Phantom
Menace'' press preview. I see the movie Saturday. I'm not telling
``Star Wars'' zealots _ the bedraggled souls outside the cineplex
in lawn chairs surrounded by Taco Bell wrappers _ this information
to taunt them or incite envy. That would require partiality on my
part, the presumption that I felt one way or another about seeing
``Phantom Menace'' and that I could empathize with those who are
already in line or who waited six hours at the mall to purchase a
plastic Jar Jar Binks.
</P>
<P>
   I don't and I can't. Save for a twinge of anticipation, I have
no investment in the movie. If Lucas decided to pull it and scotch
all prequel plans, my reporter side might quicken, but my
movie-loving side would not stir. My oath as a critic: I will
approach the movie as I do any movie, for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Of course I want to like, nay, love ``Phantom Menace.'' I wish
every movie I saw was my favorite movie. I hope it's wildly
entertaining. I hope it dazzles, thrills and makes me laugh. I hope
I feel what I did 22 years ago. I hope by next week I'll be
energetically playing with my new Jar Jar figurine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
