<HEADER>
A7276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-TRENDS07-COX     05-06 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-TRENDS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Independents move online as fall books debut
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Independent booksellers are heading into uncharted
territory at a time when book publishers seem bound to
tried-and-true formulas.
</P>
<P>
   At Book Expo last weekend, the same annual conference where
publishers traditionally introduce their fall lists, independent
booksellers were banding together to form Book Sense, a presence on
the Internet to keep their business from slipping away to companies
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second Harry Potter book (``Harry Potter and the Chamber
of Secrets'') is not in the stores yet,'' said Barbara Thomas,
past-president of the American Booksellers Association and current
president of its board, ``but so many people are buying it off the
Internet that by the time it gets to our stores, many of the people
who want it will already have it.'' Thomas, owner of Toad Hall
Children's Bookstore in Austin, sees Book Sense as a good
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Though no single hot new book emerged at Book Expo, certain
trends surfaced for this fall. Once again, publishers mostly sought
a sure thing _ adventure books, appraisals of the century,
celebrity heroes, political figures, TV tie-ins and authors with
recognizable names like Frank McCourt, Michael Crichton, Mary
Gordon, Walter Moseley, Sue Grafton, Patrick O'Brian and Thomas
Cahill.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure sells
</P>
<P>
   Following the runaway success of Jon Krakauer's ``Into Thin
Air,'' about climbing Mount Everest, and Gary Kinder's best-selling
``Ship of Gold in the Deep Blue Sea,'' about diving for treasure,
several publishers provided new nonfiction escapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Life and Adventures of John Nicol, Mariner,'' edited by
Tim Flannery (Atlantic Monthly Press, October) tells the true story
of a Scottish-born sailor in the 18th century who sailed around the
world twice, battled pirates, traded with Native Americans, fought
in two revolutions and fell in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Whitaker: A Life on the Edge, Memoirs of Everest and
Beyond'' (Mountaineers Press, September) and ``Himalaya: Life on
the Edge of the World'' by David Zurick and P.P. Karan (Johns
Hopkins Press, November) take you beyond Krakauer's ill-fated
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin provides a more leisurely, philosophical escape
in ``River Horse: A Voyage Across America'' (October) by William
Least-Heat Moon, author of the best-selling ``Blue Highways.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiction writer Pam Houston (``Cowboys are my Weakness'')
describes her real-life adventures in ``A Little More About Me,''
which ranges from Bhutan to Bolivia to a valley in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Century books
</P>
<P>
   Every publisher seems to mark the turn of the century. ``The
American Century: Art and Culture, 1950-2 000'' by Lisa Phillips
(Norton, October) is the second volume from the Whitney Museum of
Art. Or there's ``The Century of Sex: Playboy's History of the
Sexual Revolution, 1900-1999'' by James R. Petersen (Grove,
October) and edited by Hugh Hefner. Yale has ``American Chronicle''
by Lois Gordon and Alan Gordon (November); the University of
California Press has UCLA film Professor Peter Wollen's
``Addressing the Century: 100 Years of Art and Fashion''
(September).
</P>
<P>
   In ``The New New Thing: A Silicon Valley Story,'' journalist
Michael Lewis searches out the man he feels most embodies the
spirit of the coming technological age (Norton, October).
</P>
<P>
   Stars and more stars
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity heroes from sports include biographies of Joe Dimaggio
by Richard Ben Cramer (Simon &AMP; Schuster, September) and Jack
Dempsey by Roger Kahn (Harcourt, Brace, October), author of ``The
Boys of Summer.'' Pulitzer Prize-winning writer David Maraniss has
``When Pride Still Mattered: The Life and Myth of Vince Lombardi''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, October).
</P>
<P>
   Books on political figures range from Gail Sheehy's ``Hillary's
Choice'' (Random House, September) to George Bush's letters
(Scribner, October).
</P>
<P>
   Television tie-ins look promising. ``Julia and Jacques Cooking
at Home'' (Knopf, September) offers recipes and commentary by Julia
Child and Jacques Pepin, to go with their October PBS television
series. Also in October from Knopf is ``Not For Ourselves Alone''
about early feminists Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B. Anthony,
by Geoffrey C. Ward and Ken Burns, to accompany a PBS show. In
October from Morrow, ``Fooling With Words: A Celebration of Poets
and Their Craft'' by Bill Moyers, to go with a PBS special.
</P>
<P>
   A fascinating offering all to itself is ``Dr. Seuss Goes to War:
The World War II Editorial Cartoons of Theodor Seuss Geisel'' by
scholar Richard H. Minear, published by The New Press.
</P>
<P>
   Anniversaries galore
</P>
<P>
   What don't we celebrate?
</P>
<P>
   Graywolf Press celebrates its 25th anniversary with an
impressive literary anthology. Coming in November, the Iowa Writers
Workshop marks 30 years with an anthology and essays by Tom Grimes,
director of the graduate writing program at Southwest Texas State
University.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the Kansas Centennial edition of ``The Wizard of
Oz'' by L. Frank Baum, with an introduction by Ray Bradbury.
</P>
<P>
   Memoirs, memoirs
</P>
<P>
   Summer memoirs by thirtysomethings following in the wake of
``Bridget Jones's Diary'' are giving way to stronger stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the sequel to Frank McCourt's ``Angela's Ashes''
(Scribner, September), a memoir of his Irish-American childhood.
Called `` 'Tis,'' it chronicles his journey from impoverished
immigrant to best-selling author.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lanterns,'' (Beacon Press, October) by Marian Wright Edelman,
president of the Children's Defense Fund, recalls the mentors who
inspired her.
</P>
<P>
   Larry McMurtry, Pulitzer Prize-winning author of ``Lonesome
Dove,'' presents a self-portrait that says a lot about small-town
Texas in ``Walter Benjamin at the Dairy Queen, Reflections at Sixty
and Beyond'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, November).
</P>
<P>
   Brothers Frederick and Steven Barthelme describe a period after
their parents and brother Donald died when they lost almost
$250,000 gambling (Houghton Mifflin, November). And Willie Morris
has an intriguing title, ``My Cat Spit McGee'' (Random House,
November).
</P>
<P>
   Bantam is publishing John Glenn's memoir (written with Nick
Taylor) in November, and several publishers have books about space.
Knopf has a fascinating photo book called ``Full Moon'' selected
from 32,000 pictures taken by Apollo Astronauts. Yale University
has ``The Planets'' by David McNab and James Younger.
</P>
<P>
   Serious issues
</P>
<P>
   Following the violence at Columbine High School, some books look
particularly timely. Child psychologist and mystery author Jonathan
Kellerman has the nonfiction ``Savage Spawn: Reflections on Violent
Children'' (Library of Contemporary Thought, September). Richard
Rhodes has a new book on why people commit violence called, ``Why
They Kill'' (Knopf, September).
</P>
<P>
   Some books stand alone. ``Africana: The Encyclopedia of the
African and African American Experience,'' edited by Kwame Anthony
Appiah and Henry Louis Gates Jr., is a comprehensive reference due
out in November from HarperCollins.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Cahill's ``Desire of the Everlasting Hills'' is also
unique. The author of ``The Gifts of the Jews'' interprets the
cultural impact of Jesus and early Christianity (Nan Talese,
November).
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Cantrell's book for Yale University Press on Stephen F.
Austin should command interest here, as will David Dillon's
University of Texas Press book, ``The Architecture of O'Neil Ford:
Celebrating Place'' (November).
</P>
<P>
   Fiction to watch includes: ``At the Full and Change of the
Moon'' by Dionne Brand; ``Personal Injuries'' by Scott Turow;
``Headlong,'' by Michael Frayn; ``Timeline,'' by Michael Crichton;
``The Great Shame'' by Thomas Keneally; ``Walkin' the Dog'' by
Walter Mosley; ``In America'' by Susan Sontag; ``Peel Me Like an
Onion'' by Ana Castillo; and, for Christmas, ``When Angels Sing''
by Turk Pipkin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
