<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exercise clothes help moms-to-be work out
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed until Sunday, May 9
 &HT;    By Michele Chan Santos
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Bess Hilpert exercised through each of her three
pregnancies _ as a result, she says, she felt better about herself
and recovered from labor and delivery quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a problem: She had trouble finding workout clothes
that were suitable. She'd buy one outfit, then have to move up to
the next size, then another, then another. None of the exercise
clothes she found provided good support for her belly or back, she
says.
</P>
<P>
   That frustration turned itself into a business. Mothers in
Motion, the company Hilpert founded and launched this spring with
Virginia Harrison, makes leggings, running and bike shorts, briefs,
unitards, sports bras and other exercise wear for expectant
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers in Motion isn't the only company in the United States
making fitness wear for pregnant women _ Fit Maternity and Beyond
in Mount Shasta, Calif., has created some items, as have Fit for
Two Maternity in Littleton, N.H., among others _ but Hilpert says
her products offer the best support.
</P>
<P>
   She patented a paneled inner-support system used in each
garment. Belly halters in the clothing bear the weight of the
uterine wall; there is also a back panel at the base of the spine
and two inner-thigh panels for the leggings, unitards and shorts,
as well as a special design for bras. The lining of the clothes is
a high-tech fabric made by DuPont, which keep them cool to wear.
</P>
<P>
   James Clapp, author of the book ``Exercising Through Your
Pregnancy'' and a physician at Case Western Reserve University
Medical Center in Cleveland, is testing the Mothers in Motion
clothing in a clinical study. In time-motion studies, he is
comparing the clothing to other exercise gear used by pregnant
women. Although the research isn't complete, Clapp says that ``in
general, women in mid and late pregnancy find that Bess's garments
are more comfortable and offer more in the way of breast, back and
abdominal support than their usual exercise garb.''
</P>
<P>
   Mothers in Motion is an outgrowth of Hilpert's experience as an
exercise physiologist. In the 1980s, she ran her own company, Bess
Gatewood Stretch and Alignment. (Gatewood is her maiden name.) She
designed rehabilitation or exercise programs for clients, including
celebrities like Jodie Foster, Bette Midler and Olivia Newton-John.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling business is run out of Hilpert's home in Round
Rock. A factory in California makes the items; they are stored in a
warehouse in Austin, and phone operators in Austin take sales
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison worked as a runway model, showroom model and a ``fit''
model for many years, and that experience is invaluable, Hilpert
says. As a ``fit'' model, Harrison would try on clothes for
designers and tell them how well the garment moved, if it clung to
one side for too long, if a shoulder was too tight. They would
remake or alter clothing designs based on her input. Now, they draw
on Harrison's experience in the fashion industry and Hilpert's
experience in the fitness industry.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are young, Hilpert's sons _ Eddie, 6, Nathaniel,
5, and Calvin, 4 _ know their mother's business is important to
her, she says. ``They believe in what Mommy's doing. My boys also
understand it is for them, and they were my inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
