<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UHLER-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doff your top hat to celebrate Astaire's 100th birthday
 &HT;    By Steve Uhler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Can't act. Can't sing. Balding. Can dance a
little.''
</P>
<P>
   Some nameless movie studio executive wrote that curt assessment
after seeing Fred Astaire's first screen test. The man who wrote it
has long been forgotten, but everybody knows Fred Astaire, right?
</P>
<P>
   Right?
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it _ there's not much of a market for Fred Astaire
these days. And the anonymous executive's critique wasn't totally
off the mark. As a screen presence, Astaire simply couldn't compete
with Cary Grant or Clark Gable _ or even Harpo Marx. The image of
Astaire that exists today is an evocative icon from another period
and place altogether. And his raison d'etre _ the movie musical _
is as extinct as the dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   But the man could dance. And when he did, the real world _ and
all critical carping _ faded into insignificance. Astaire
transported audiences to an elegant fantasy world of exotic
locales, huge art deco sets, impossibly glossy floors, impeccably
tailored top hats and tails, lavish gowns ... and, above all,
passionate, romantic dances. He looked so natural on his feet that
it appeared he could dance before he could think. Astaire in motion
was the personification of carefree sophistication, natural grace
and style.
</P>
<P>
   Monday marks Fred Astaire's 100th birthday. Celebrate his
centennial in style by renting any of these great videos (and if
you want to slip off your shoes and try dancing along, who's
looking?).
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Top Hat'' (1935) is quintessential Astaire, with all the
elements that made movie musical magic: a classic score by Irving
Berlin (``Cheek to Cheek,'' ``Isn't It a Lovely Day?''), superb
dance routines (choreographed by Hermes Pan), great comedic support
(by Edward Everett Horton), stunning white art deco designs and,
above all, Ginger Rogers. Astaire and Rogers went together like ...
well, like Astaire and Rogers. Katharine Hepburn once said that
Astaire gave Rogers class, and she gave him sex. ``Top Hat'' is the
most sexually charged of their films together. Keep an eye out for
a young Lucille Ball in the flower shop.
</P>
<P>
   Most Astaire-Rogers musicals had throwaway plots, often
involving mistaken identities that only served as jumping-off
points for their awesome dance numbers.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Shall We Dance?'' (1937) is no exception, with Rogers and
Astaire as a dance team pretending to be married through such
Gershwin classics as ``Let's Call the Whole Thing Off'' and ``They
Can't Take That Away From Me.'' It was around this time that RKO
had Astaire's legs insured for a half-million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Carefree'' (1938) is almost more of a screwball comedy than
a musical. Rogers plays a radio star who falls for psychiatrist
Astaire even though she's engaged to his best friend (perennial
lady-loser Ralph Bellamy.) Music by Irving Berlin includes
``Dancing in the Dark.'' The highlight is a beautifully
choreographed tour of a country club. This was one of their last
films together.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Easter Parade'' (1948) is a Technicolor Pygmalion-esque
comedy with Astaire as a Henry Higgins-like dance instructor to
Judy Garland's wholesome novice, the only time these two stars were
paired together. If Astaire's opening number, ``Drum Crazy,''
doesn't pick up your pulse, you're rhythmically dead. Garland
shines in a superb comic performance _ and she never looked better
(except maybe in ``Meet Me in St. Louis''). The highlight is their
rendition of ``A Couple of Swells,'' dressed as tramps.
</P>
<P>
   In his later years, Astaire's gift for creating inventive ways
to showcase his solos reached its zenith.
</P>
<P>
   _ In ``Royal Wedding'' (1951), Astaire co-stars with Jane Powell
as a brother and sister musical act who travel to England to
perform. Their journey coincides with the marriage of Princess
Elizabeth (soon to be Queen Elizabeth II); naturally, they both
find romance. In one sequence, Astaire dances with a hat stand _
and makes it look as graceful and animated as any of his two-legged
partners. This is also the film in which he ecstatically dances on
the walls and ceilings to ``You're All the World to Me,'' a
seamless blending of dance and movie magic. Don't try this at home.
</P>
<P>
   Also recommended: ``The Gay Divorcee'' (1934), ``Follow the
Fleet'' (1936), and ``Band Wagon'' (1953) and ``Silk Stockings''
(1957), both with the wondrous Cyd Charisse.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
