</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CUTS-0507-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MACK OFFERS MAJOR TAX-CUT PLAN
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Republican senators wrangled Thursday over how
extensive a tax cut to push for, Sen. Connie Mack introduced a
wish-list bill Thursday that contains $755 billion in cuts over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, R-Fla., offered his proposal prior to a closed-door
meeting of Republican senators to discuss ways of offering a
phased-in tax cut that could be touted during next year's elections
but which would not have much impact until years later.
</P>
<P>
   Mack is the third-highest ranking GOP senator, chairman of the
Joint Economic Committee, and a member of the tax-writing Senate
Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal which would offer a $140 billion cut over five
years before ballooning in later years has not been introduced as a
bill. A committee spokeswoman said Mack has just begun seeking
cosponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Unprepared for the cost of the war in Yugoslavia and boxed in by
their promises not to use Social Security surpluses to pay for tax
cuts, Republicans are seeking a plan that will allow them to claim
tax relief before the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, it's not a matter of if we cut, but how much, and
how we can maximize the pro-growth impact of whatever tax cuts we
decide to enact,'' Mack said during a Senate floor speech.
</P>
<P>
   While pondering how to give workers a tax cut, Republicans are
giving serious consideration to President Clinton's proposals to
close several corporate tax shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking to see where there are opportunities to raise
revenues so we can give the working people a tax cut,'' said Sen.
William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance Committee.
``We want to give as large a tax cut as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack's bill would increase the standard income tax deduction
from $4,300 to $7,200 for individuals and double it from $7,200 to
$14,400 for couples, thus eliminating the so-called ``marriage
penalty'' for joint returns.
</P>
<P>
   It would cut capital gains rates by 25 percent, slash dividend
tax rates, repeal estate and gift taxes, and give permanent tax
credits for research and development expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would reduce the amount of Social Security benefits
subject to income taxes from 85 percent to the 50 percent level
that existed before the 1993 tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
