<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7284 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OKLA-STORMS-ART-2TAKE     05-06 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLA-STORMS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEW OF AN EPIC DISASTER FROM THE 900 BLOCK OF WINDERMERE DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RICK LYMAN and STEVE BARNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORE, Okla. _ What is left of the 900 block of Windermere Drive
still curves gently on this Oklahoma City suburb's western edge,
but it is a jumble now of splinters, shards and half-loaded pickup
trucks, its few remaining walls rarely rising higher than four
feet.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the many blocks that felt the full force of the
monster tornado that clawed through central Oklahoma on Monday
night. Now, three days after the disaster, most families have
either finished picking through the rubble or were making a few
last forays in search of family photos and heirlooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emergency people came out here and told us that after we
were finished taking what we could find, they were going to cart
off what they could and then just burn the rest,'' said Roger
Hanes, standing outside the shoulder-high rubble of his home at 929
Windermere Dr. ``They said there's no place in the world to bury
all this stuff, so they're going to have to burn it. Then I guess
we'll all have to decide whether to rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a tendency in epic disasters like this to take the
eagle's eye view and see it from high above, the long trail of
debris stretching into the distance, or to focus instead on tiny
details, like children's toys caught in the rubble. But it is at
the intermediate level, of individual homes and blocks, that
disasters like this are really felt. That is how it is on the 900
block of Windermere Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma officials said Thursday that the fatality toll from
Monday's storm had risen with the deaths overnight of three of the
injured in area hospitals and now stood at 41 in Oklahoma and five
in neighboring Kansas. In addition, 1 Texas woman was killed on
Tuesday in a tornado and four people died in another string of
twisters in Tennessee on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma officials spent much of Thursday trying to whittle away
at the list of those still unaccounted for following Monday's
storms, a list that reached 100 names on Wednesday, and were able
to report by late afternoon that, after comparing lists of those at
shelters and motels and receiving a flurry of calls from people who
wanted to report that they were still alive, only 14 names remained
on the list of the missing.
</P>
<P>
   There was guarded optimism that most of these would turn up,
too.
</P>
<P>
   On the 900 block of Windermere Drive, residents said they were
confident that all of their neighbors had been accounted for. They
counted themselves fortunate, too, that apparently no one on their
block had died in the storm, though a few had been wounded and
three had been killed on neighboring blocks in their square-mile
1970s subdivision of two-story, brick-and-frame houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was this neighborhood like?'' asked Darrell Brooks,
paging through a recently unearthed photo album in the driveway of
his home at 1000 Windermere Dr. ``Oh, it was pretty much like this,
kind of trashy.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks laughed and shook his head. ``No, I'm just kidding,'' he
said. ``It was a normal, everyday middle-class community, a slice
of the Midwest heartland. Everybody took care of their lawns,
everybody got along.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred and Butch Phillips were trying to toss aside the last
remaining shards of dry wall and two-by-four to see what was buried
beneath what had been their garage at 924 Windermere. The couple
were wellknown on the street as hosts of the annual block party, a
combination potluck and barbecue usually held in their front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have another block party, too, we are,''
Phillips said before breaking down, briefly, in a wave of sobs.
``Sorry, I can talk again now. As soon as we get this cleaned up,
we're going to have a block party right on this driveway. We're
taking down the numbers of where everybody is and we're bringing
them back. We're going to build this neighborhood back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Grief, for the most part, was buried beneath veneers of
camaraderie and dark humor. Phillips had put a sign on the front of
the ruins of his house offering it for sale as ``a fixer upper.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the block, Beverly Rushie could not stop laughing about the
Valentine's Day card from her granddaughter. The computer chip
embedded in it had been broken in the storm and now played the
theme song from ``Love Story'' over and over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-one years and not a shingle disturbed before now,''
said Alice Brooks, Darrell's wife. ``We had just retired and bought
an RV and were getting ready to travel. Man, we thought we were
settled in. It just goes to show you never to be complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pollard worked up on the tottering second-story of his
home at 917 Windermere Dr., which had been the only house in the
vicinity to retain its upper floor. ``Must have been built right,''
Pollard said. ``Either that, or we're just lucky. It's a mess
though, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Several groups moved up and down the block with camcorders. An
almost constant traffic jam clogged the street with rental trucks,
insurance representatives, police, television station vans and even
giddy residents who had managed to get their tornado-battered
vehicles started and were driving them, improbably, for one last
time.
</P>
<P>
   The mounds of debris were also aswarm with search parties from
neighboring blocks looking for household items that had been
carried off by the winds.
</P>
<P>
   Christina Piper, whose head had barely missed being crushed by a
neighbor's truck that landed on her grandfather's house a couple of
blocks away while she huddled in a bathtub under a mattress on
Monday night, was looking for the family's 16-foot ski boat. It had
mysteriously disappeared, apparently carried through the air, from
the rubble of their attached garage.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if her neighborhood had a name, Ms. Piper scratched
her head. ``Doesn't really have one,'' she said. ``Gone with the
Wind, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Carter could not look for what had become of his four
vintage cars because he was in intensive care in a nearby hospital,
his scalp sheared back, his leg broken and a nail impaled in his
chest. So several relatives were combing the debris. Carter's 1940
Chevy had flown a few feet across his front yard, his 1925 Ford
pickup was upside down about 50 yards away, in someone's back yard,
and his 1960 Chevy Impala was half buried in Hanes' front yard. But
they were still looking for the red 1971 Super Sport that had taken
wing and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hanes had found something else in his front yard, a purse that
he at first thought belonged to his wife. But when he opened it, he
discovered that it belonged to Karen Doshier, who had improbably
survived with just a few bruises in the knee-high rubble that had
been her house just across the street from Hanes at 926 Windermere
Dr.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Jerry Doshier, is an assistant chief in Moore's
fire department, and he had been working on the roof of City Hall
several blocks away when the tornado plowed through his
neighborhood. ``I saw it lift the roof off of my house and I just
lost it,'' Doshier said. ``Then I got over here and I saw her come
climbing out and it was like, I don't know, it was like I could
think again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Doshier had huddled in a ball on the floor of her bedroom
closet, a battery-powered lantern in one hand and her purse in the
other. ``She said that she felt this rush of air and then she was
shaking back and forth, real fast, and all of a sudden there was
the sky over her head,'' Doshier said. ``She came up out of a hole
that was maybe two feet deep and a foot-and-a-half around with only
three or four bruises. She thought she was the only one left alive.
I mean, look at that rubble. That's all that's left of the house.
How she came out of that alive, I'll never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The lantern was found about 30 yards away in the front yard,
broken in half. The purse, its contents intact, was another 20
yards away in Hanes' front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to understand,'' Doshier said. ``Something like
this shows you, all of this stuff, all of this rubble, it's just
things, it's just stuff. It doesn't mean anything. It's only people
that mean anything. It's true. I mean it. See, that's my truck over
there, that Dodge. Do you want it? Here's the keys. It doesn't mean
anything. People have to know that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
