<HEADER>
A7288 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      05-06 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART WORLD NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Calif.)  (bl) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Lost Treasure To Be Auctioned
</P>
<P>
   A haunting landscape by the Hudson River School master Frederic
Edwin Church is being offered for sale at Sotheby's in New York on
May 27. The painting, which features a cross in the foreground,
comes with an unusual past.
</P>
<P>
   For years it was lost and known to Church scholars only from
passing references. But in 1980 it was rediscovered hanging in the
Des Moines Women's Club, where it had been since the group received
it in 1952. Club members knew the painting not as ``To the Memory
of Cole,'' as the artist had named it, but as ``Sunrise in the
Catskills.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Church scholars, David C. Huntington, who died in 1990, and
J. Gray Sweeney, an art history professor at Arizona State
University, had spent years looking for ``To the Memory of Cole,''
which Church painted in memory of his teacher, Thomas Cole, in
April 1848, two months after Cole's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had found two references to the painting from newspaper
clippings in the early 1970s,'' said Sweeney. ``Then one day in
1979 I got a call from David Huntington, who said he had been
contacted by the Des Moines Women's Club, which wanted him to look
at a Church they owned. He asked me if I'd go instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney remembers the moment he first saw the painting. ``It was
like an electric charge, a powerful moment of recognition,'' he
said. ``It can only be described as a national treasure. It's an
audacious, daring statement by a 22-year-old genius who is saying:
`I am a Cole student. I shall wear his mantle.'''
</P>
<P>
   The painting was originally owned by George Austen, a New York
auctioneer. The work predates Asher B. Durand's monumental
``Kindred Spirits,' now in the collection of the New York Public
Library, which had long been considered the only painting to
commemorate Cole's death.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, Cole was working on a series of
allegorical paintings called ``The Cross and the World,'' and they
directly influenced ``To the Memory of Cole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Church saw the cross as a symbol, or perhaps an ideal or
proposed tombstone, but one never realized it was for Cole's
tomb,'' said Sweeney. ``The rays of morning light that illuminate
the cross symbolize rebirth.''
</P>
<P>
   In an economic climate where top American paintings are hard to
come by and prices keep rising, Sotheby's estimates that the
painting could sell for $5 million to $8 million. The proceeds will
go to create an endowment for the upkeep of the Des Moines Women's
Club's 1907 building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to see it go, it's like my baby,'' said Anabelle
Wonders, a former executive director of the club. The painting is
in a collection of about 60 works, European and American, that the
club owns and exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wonders said the club first began talking to Sotheby's in
the 1980s. At the time, she said, the members did not really want
to part with it. And American paintings were not as highly valued
then as they are today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an iconic painting,'' said Dara Mitchell, director of
American paintings at Sotheby's. ``Obviously, great paintings by
Church rarely come on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mitchell noted that Sotheby's seems to get the chance to
sell a work like this about every 10 years. In 1979 the auction
house sold Church's ``Iceberg,'' which became the first American
painting to sell for more than $1 million. (It made $2.5 million.)
In 1989 Sotheby's sold the artist's famous image ``Home by the
Lake'' for $8.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Church's first great statement,'' said Sweeney.
``Today there are only about a half-dozen Churches left in private
hands, and this is the best of them. It's my greatest hope that a
museum will buy it so it can stay in the public eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Gift of a Rarity
</P>
<P>
   ``The Perfect Accord,'' one of the last Watteau paintings in
private hands, has been given to the Los Angeles County Museum of
Art by the Ahmanson Foundation, a Los Angeles-based foundation that
is a longtime supporter of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, from around 1716, depicts five elegantly dressed
people in a wooded park. A man in the center is playing the flute
and a young woman beside him is singing. It was painted for the
artist's friend Nicholas Henin, who oversaw architectural projects
for the French court.
</P>
<P>
   After changing hands several times, the painting was bought in
1892 by the Iveagh family of Britain and remained in the family
until recently. One of Lord Iveagh's daughters, Lady Bridget Ness,
the wife of Prince Frederic of Prussia, was the family's last
owner. ``She loved it so much she had a special case made and took
it with her wherever she went,'' said Graham W.J. Beal, director of
the Los Angeles County Museum. When she died a year ago, Simon
Dickinson, who has galleries in New York and London, sold the
painting to the foundation on behalf of the family trustees.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first Watteau to enter the museum's collection and is
on view in the Carter Gallery. This is the first time ``The Perfect
Accord'' has been seen publicly in more than 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not having a Watteau has been a notable gap,'' Beal said.
``The preparatory drawing for the work is also in Los Angeles, at
the Getty.''
</P>
<P>
   Help for Uncle Sam
</P>
<P>
   When the U.S. Pavilion at the 1999 Venice Biennale opens June 12
with the installation and performance artist Ann Hamilton, the
exhibition will have corporate sponsorship for the first time, and
the sponsor is Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci and its creative director, Tom Ford, have over the years
financed decorative arts, photography and performing arts projects
in London, Japan and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Venice installation is also receiving support from the
United States Artists at International Festivals and Exhibitions,
which is a partnership of the U.S. Information Agency, the National
Endowment for the Arts, the Rockefeller Foundation and the Pew
Charitable Trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
