<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO, RUSSIA AGREE TO FRAMEWORK FOR POLITICAL END TO KOSOVO CRISIS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Russia and the NATO alliance have agreed on
a framework for seeking peace for Kosovo, including the need for an
armed international force to secure the return of hundreds of
thousands of refugees to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached early Thursday at a meeting of the
world's eight leading economic powers, does not address the makeup
of any security force or Russia's demand for an immediate end to
NATO's bombing campaign, now in its seventh week.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the agreement by Russia _ a longtime ally of
Yugoslavia _ for an armed security force in Kosovo is expected to
further isolate Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and increase
pressure on him to end the conflict on terms dictated by the United
States and its NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant step forward,'' President Clinton said
during a meeting in Bonn with German Chancellor Gerhardt Schroeder.
``I think you have to read this as a move forward and (as)
increasing the likelihood that there'll ultimately be a resolution
of this that will actually work.''
</P>
<P>
   While working out details of the agreement and a decision by
Milosevic to pull out of Kosovo, Clinton said the bombing campaign
against Yugoslavia will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real peace process under way, but it has no chance
of reaching a satisfactory conclusion unless we maintain allied
unity and firmness,'' Clinton told reporters as he wrapped up a
two-day European trip to visit U.S. troops and Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention of changing policies until the basic
conditions are met,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's framework for a political end to the Kosovo crisis
was adopted by foreign ministers from seven Western powers and
Russia _ known as the G-8 or Group of Eight _ meeting in Bonn. Once
details of the plan are worked out, it will be submitted for
approval to the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   As outlined by the G-8, the plan calls for immediate end to
violence and repression in Kosovo; withdrawal of Serbian military,
police and paramilitary forces from Kosovo; deployment of a U.N.
peacekeeping force; a U.N.-supervised administration of Kosovo to
aid the transition to self-government; return of all refugees and
displaced people; unimpeded access to Kosovo by international aid
groups; and comprehensive economic redevelopment of the region.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers also agreed to keep China informed of
negotiations, hoping that with Russia now aboard, China _ a member
of the Security Council _ would not veto any resolution calling for
involvement of U.N. forces in post-war Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan called the agreement ``an
important'' step toward reaching a political solution to the Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   State-run media in Yugoslavia quoted Milosevic as saying that a
political or diplomatic settlement was possible after NATO halts
its bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Under relentless bombing since March 24 by NATO, Milosevic has
softened his long-held opposition to any peacekeeping force in
Kosovo. Before the bombing, Milosevic's negotiators refused to
discuss the concept at talks in Rambouillet, France. Over the past
two weeks, the Yugoslav president has said he would consider a
peacekeeeping contingent that was unarmed or carried only light
weapons. At the same time, he has insisted on keeping 11,000 Serb
troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals by Milosevic have been turned down by NATO, a
rejection underscored Thursday when Clinton and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright reaffirmed their desire for ``a strong military
force with NATO at its core'' to ensure the security of ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Albright characterization of allied involvement in
post-war peacekeeping has shifted in recent weeks from a demand
that NATO forces be deployed in Kosovo to the use of NATO-led
forces to, as described Thursday, having NATO troops at the
``core'' of any foreign military presence in the troubled province.
</P>
<P>
   Although Russia has objected to a peacekeeping force directed
and dominated by NATO, Sandy Berger, the president's national
security adviser, said the agreement Thursday shows an evolution in
Moscow's position. ``I think Russia is moving toward the NATO
position,'' he told reporters aboard Air Force One between Bonn and
Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Narrowing of the gap between Washington and Moscow could
influence Milosevic's calculations. ``The Serbs have to see they
are increasingly isolated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials argued that the agreement worked out with the
United States, Germany, Britain, France, Canada, Italy and Japan
signals more movement by the Clinton administration than Russia.
The agreement reflects Moscow's call for an international presence
in Kosovo under the direction of the Security Council, said Sergey
Lavrow, Russia's ambassador to the U.N.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am glad that this is now accepted by our Western partners,''
Lavrow told reporters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry that it took them one and a half months of bombing
to come to the same solution which we were offering,'' Lavrow said,
failing to mention Russia's long-held opposition, until Thursday,
to arming any international forces deployed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not to say that we are already there,'' the ambassador
said. ``We would still have to see how the details of those
arrangements could be negotiated, and this would require good will
on both sides as was repeatedly stressed by Russian leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
