<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THREE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THREE SEASONS' IS A GRIPPING, IMMENSELY SATISFYING FILM 
</HEADLINE>
 SEASONS-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year-and-a-half ago, I happened to be walking down a side
street in Saigon when I happened upon a shoe-string film crew
shooting what they claimed was the ``first-ever American feature
film'' to be shot in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to the crew members and the 26-year-old
Vietnamese-American director, Tony Bui, I distinctly remember
thinking that the script sounded cliched, and _ even though Harvey
Keitel had been talked into being in a few scenes _ the movie
didn't have the future of a snowball in hell.
</P>
<P>
   Well, never underestimate a determined young man with a dream.
That film, ``Three Seasons,'' turned out to be the hit of the last
Sundance Film Festival, and one of the most accomplished, lyrical,
beautifully textured first films I've seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   It's basically an omnibus movie that weaves together the stories
of four Saigon characters: a young woman (Nguyen Ngoc Hiep) who has
just come to work on a suburban lotus farm, a street urchin named
Woody (Nguyen Huu Duoc), a cyclo driver (Don Duong), and an ex-U.S.
Marine (Harvey Keitel).
</P>
<P>
   The young woman, unable to sell her flowers in a Saigon more
interested in plastic flower replicas, gradually withdraws into a
dreamy longing for a lost past and develops a ``beauty and the
beast'' relationship with a reclusive poet with leprosy.
</P>
<P>
   The boy Woody (named after the Woody Woodpecker T-shirt he
wears), sells wristwatches and other trinkets from a suitcase
provided by a child-exploiting Fagin, and his story involves his
frantic quest to recover that suitcase when it disappears during a
blackout at Saigon's ``Apocalypse Now'' bar.
</P>
<P>
   The cyclo driver has fallen in love with a prostitute (Zoe Bui)
who hangs out at the city's posh Majestic Hotel, and his story
involves his efforts to acquire enough money to buy her services
and taste the luxury of one night in a four-star hotel.
</P>
<P>
   And the Vietnam-veteran Marine has returned to Saigon to search
for the daughter he fathered 30 years ago, but mostly just boozes
it up in the bars of the Rue Catinet by night, and pathetically
wanders the streets by day, like some ghost of the old American
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Director Bui follows these four quests rather lightly,
occasionally mixing them up (as when Woody believes the Marine has
stolen his suitcase), and his intention is less narrative drive
than a sequence of scenes that collectively create a kind of visual
``symphony'' of a Saigon in lightning transition.
</P>
<P>
   It's a gorgeous movie in which every shot seems imaginative and
revealingly composed, and yet _ like ``The Bicycle Thief'' and
other great Italian neo-realist classics of the post-war '40s _ it
still has a documentary-like feel, so it's both poetic and
realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, ``Three Seasons'' has that ring of truth and subtle
moral power that is always impossible for a filmmaker to fake. Bui,
who left Vietnam at age 2 but returned when he was 19, sees his
country with a sharp, loving, sad eye that makes his film gripping,
melancholy, immensely satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Three Seasons. Directed and written by Tony Bui. Cast: Harvey
Keitel, Don Duong, Nguyen Ngoc Hiep, Tran Manh Cuong, Nguyen Huu
Duoc, Zoe Bui. October Films. 113 minutes. In Vietnamese with
English subtitles. Rated PG-13 for sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
