<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7303 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MUMMY-SPI &LR;      05-06 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MUMMY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MUMMY' REMAKE TRIES TO BE EVERYTHING, FAILS AT BEING ANYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Universal Pictures announced it was planning a big-budget
remake of its 1932 horror classic, ``The Mummy,'' the word was it
would be a similarly stylish, evocative and subtle film that would
rely more on atmosphere and suggestion and less on special effects.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't happened. Somewhere along the pipeline, the
project morphed into an overblown, special-effects-o-rama comedy
that's closer in spirit to ``Abbott and Costello Meet the Mummy''
than to the critically acclaimed horror movie from the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   Small boys and teenagers will like ghoulish violence and goofy
imitation-Indiana Jones action sequences, but others are likely to
be bored by its numbingly predictable and repetitive non-stop
action. Devotees of the original will want to throw rocks at it.
</P>
<P>
   The story starts off in 1719 B.C. with a computer-generated
prologue that vaguely recreates the original premise _ Imhotep, a
high priest in the court of Themes, has fallen in love with the
Pharaoh's mistress, and is turned into a living mummy for his
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to 1923 (the Egypt of the King Tut discovery), and the rest
of the story follows an American adventurer (Brendan Fraser) and a
clutzy Anglo-Egyptian archeologist (Rachel Weisz) who find the lost
city where the Mummy lies in a state of suspended animation, and
release him.
</P>
<P>
   But this Mummy is not so much a lovesick sap out to gain the
reincarnation of his lost love as he's a supernatural Hitler out to
enslave the world by unleashing the same series of plagues _
locusts, boils, comets, etc. _ that Moses did, as if inspired by a
recent viewing of ``The Prince of Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a exaggerated, campy mess, and one that has no respect
for the geography and culture of ancient Egypt either _ so if
you're a fan of those endless Egyptology specials on the Discovery
Channel, you'll be overwhelmed by the inaccuracies and
anachronisms.
</P>
<P>
   It's very much one of those big-studio concoctions that try to
be everything and end up being nothing: not creepy enough to be an
effective horror movie, not funny enough to be a rollicking comedy,
not historically credible or adventurous enough to be a rousing
action spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Fraser has a few enjoyable moments as the thick-headed
hero (half-Indiana Jones/half-George of the Jungle) but the
dumbed-up script doesn't allow him to do anything with the part,
and he has zero romantic chemistry with co-star Rachel Weisz.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of today's wannabe summer blockbusters, much of the
film is digital, but the effects _ a zip through a Middle Kingdom
Egyptian city, a sea of flesh-eating scarabs, a desert storm shaped
like a mummy's face _ always look exactly like what they are:
cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   The Mummy. Directed and directed by Stephen Sommers. Cast:
Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz, John Hannah, Arnold Vosloo, Kevin J.
O'Connor. Universal. 114 minutes. Rated PG-13 for horror violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
