</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRIZREN-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBING OF A KOSOVAR TOWN TRIGGERS FLIGHT AND WIDER PANIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ The ethnic Albanian woman, when a stranger
said hello Thursday, pulled her child's arm so hard to get away one
could almost hear the tendons pop.
</P>
<P>
   Two elderly Albanians, chatting quietly on a street corner,
scurried off when a stranger approached them to talk, heading in
opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   A middle-aged Albanian, walking his bicycle up one of Prizren's
ancient cobbled streets, past the shut-down stores and broken
windows, stopped politely. But when asked how his life is now, his
eyes darted convulsively as he pushed his bike away.
</P>
<P>
   This charming medieval city in deep southwestern Kosovo, where a
15th-century church hugs a steep hill just above a 14th-century
mosque, is rank with tension and fear.
</P>
<P>
   Although a few Serbs stopped briefly to talk, the anxiety of the
people on the street is matched only by the edginess of the many
soliders and militarized policemen who fill the town, and who
stopped a reporter to check his papers nearly every time they
noticed a notebook or camera.
</P>
<P>
   There are many more soldiers and policemen visible here than in
Pristina or Pec, and a few plainclothesmen with automatic rifles
also walk the streets.
</P>
<P>
   There is much to make everyone nervous.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, many of Prizren's Albanians, perhaps as many
as 30,000, were pushed and panicked into flight in the few days
following a bomb blast in a poor residential area that killed at
least five civilians and wounded 23 others.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus of ethnic Albanians brought new charges of organized
ethnic purging from NATO officials and the U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees. A spokesman for the U.N. agency, Ray Wilkinson, said
last Friday from Albania: ``To me it seems this is the final
cleansing of Prizren.''
</P>
<P>
   The city itself is hardly empty, and many Albanians, however
fearful, remain here, rarely going outside. As they walk, they
watch warily for anyone who approaches, and when they pass a
soldier, they drop their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It is not entirely clear what happened last week in Prizren, a
city of some 180,000 people before this war began, including some
11,000 Serbs, 130,000 ethnic Albanians, 10,000 Turks, 20,000 Muslim
Slavs and Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing early last Friday of the residential area, known as
Ciganska mala, or ``Gypsy neighborhood,'' did frighten many, who
had been holed up in the houses and apartments for days, some
residents said.
</P>
<P>
   But the bombing also served as a trigger, it seems, for an
effort by Serb authorities _ which they deny _ to arrest certain
Albanians and order others to leave, setting off a wider panic.
</P>
<P>
   People rushed for the bus stations, even if no Serb came to
their door. In two days _ Friday and Saturday, while much attention
was focused on the Rev. Jesse Jackson's mission to free three
captured American soliders, residential areas of Belgrade were
bombed and a passenger bus was hit by a missile just north of
Pristina, killing 41 people _ some 30,000 ethnic Albanians from
Prizren crossed the border into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Others took buses to Pristina or to Podgorica, in Montenegro.
Refugees arriving in Albania said many people were warned to leave
by the Serbs, who charged them a dollar for the 10-mile bus ride to
the Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   Rexep Hoti, a 60-year-old who agreed to speak Thursday, said
that people were terrified by both the bombing and the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told some people to move, but not in my neighborhood,''
which is known as Brezovica, like the name of the resort town
nearby. ``Nobody came to tell us to leave, but some were
threatened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some left because they were told, some because they were
scared and some of them saw their neighbors leaving, so they left
too,'' he added. ``Some from the villages were sure they would be
killed, and they made a fear among the ones in the town.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped and said with wonderment: ``They just walked out of
their big houses and left them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of the war, there was little bomb damage in
Prizren. ``But when the bombs landed on the houses, a lot of people
also became afraid,'' Hoti said. ``I'm afraid, too. I stay at home
and came out to buy some bread,'' lifting up a plastic bag with a
loaf inside. ``I'm not walking around much.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoti is a widower, with a son in Germany. Living alone, he said,
he had less reason to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Hoti's comments about panic reflected those made by the U.N.
spokesman, Wilkinson, last Friday. ``We have started to hear that
panic is setting in,'' he said then. ``A lot of these people are
saying, `My God, everyone is leaving. I've got to leave.' `'
</P>
<P>
   The war came comparatively late to Prizren, where the streets
signs are written in three languages. But since NATO expanded its
air campaign in Kosovo, Prizren and its surroundings have been
bombed almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   The Car Dusan Silni barracks and warehouses have been hit
regularly, as well as nearby transmitter towers and other targets,
and 10 more civilians have been killed, Yugoslav authorities say.
Those people who would talk Thursday said there was an increasing
fear among everyone here about the bombs.
</P>
<P>
   There was a continuous rumble of NATO warplanes overhead,
invisible through the heavy cloud cover, and the intermittent sound
of detonations seemingly far away, echoing off Prizren's embracing
hills.
</P>
<P>
   Lubitsa Stankovic, 48, walking quickly with a friend, said:
``Everyone is afraid of the bombs and the sirens. When they were
just shooting the barracks, we were not that scared, but now when
they hit the other things and kill innocent people, it's
terrifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Albanians, Stankovic said: ``We're afraid,
they're afraid. A lot of people left because of fear, including
Serbs.'' Many Albanians left in the last week, she said, ``but many
are still here, and my Albanian neighbors ask me when this madness
will stop _ when they are bombing we are all together.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Aleksandar Milosavljevic, 24, said that ``the planes come every
day, and people are afraid, especially after the bombs hit Ciganska
mala. In my street, everyone stays in their houses.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, he said, he and his sister, Marijana, 22,
decided to reopen their small clothing store, with its stocks of
Levi jeans, polo shirts and Byblos sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   There is very little else that is open in Prizren, he said,
since most of the commerce was done by Albanians, and their stores
are closed. ``At least there's electricity today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he missed most, he said: ``The nightlife.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the road from Pristina to Prizren, some 50 miles, was
almost entirely empty, except for a few busses, a handful of cars
and a few solitary military trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The former Kosovo Liberation Army strongholds of Dule and Suva
Reka are practically depopulated, with most shops and houses
burned. The drivers of the few vehicles visible race through the
villages, still afraid of snipers. The roadsides are dotted with
dead animals, overgrown fields and hidden anti-aircraft and
artillery pieces. Overhead, like a drill in the brain, there is the
steady rumble of NATO aircraft, circling for targets.
</P>
</TEXT>
