<SLUG> BC-VIRUS-IDENTIFIED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBOLA-LIKE VIRUS IDENTIFIED, AUTHORITIES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Authorities Thursday identified a deadly cousin
of the Ebola virus as the disease that has struck inhabitants in a
remote corner of the eastern Congo, killing as many as 52 people.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the World Health Organization said they are
planning to send a team to the region this weekend to investigate
outbreak of the Marburg virus, one of the world's most lethal and
deadly diseases. Soviet biological warfare experts allegedly
converted it into a weapon in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The team will fly to Kampala, Uganda, Saturday before seeking
permission to cross into Wasa, a rebel-controlled region 30 miles
from the Ugandan border, said Gregory Hartl, a spokesman for the
international health organization.
</P>
<P>
   There is no known cure or vaccine for the outbreak, which was
first reported in Congo by scientists from the French organization
Doctors Without Borders. International specialists say they have
learned little about the virus since it was identified in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have absolutely no idea of the source of the virus,'' said
Hartl. ``It has caused one past outbreak and several sporadic
cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Marburg, a close viral cousin of the Ebola, causes a hideous
death for those who contract it. ``Both Marburg and the closely
related Ebola virus are often characterized by the sudden onset of
fever, malaise, muscle pain, headache and conjunctivitis,''
according to a WHO statement. ``This is followed by sore throat,
vomiting, diarrhea, rash and both internal and external bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Alibek, a former Soviet biological weapons expert who
defected nearly a decade ago, described in his book ``Biohazard''
the slow, gruelling death of a Soviet colleague, Nikolai Ustinov,
who accidentally pricked his finger with a concentrated dose of
Marburg.
</P>
<P>
   The disease _ known as a viral haemorrhagic fever _ induced
fever, headaches, and nausea and shock before causing internal
bleeding and ultimately death. ``The virus prevents normal
coagulation,'' Alibek wrote. ``As the virus spreads, the body's
internal organs begin to melt away.''
</P>
<P>
   Alibek said Thursday that the Soviet Union successfully
weaponized a dry form of Marburg by 1990. He said Russia continues
to possess the capacity to attack an American city with a
Marburg-filled warhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This virus fortunately appears in isolated areas and it is not
very stable in natural conditions. That's why it doesn't cause
larger outbreaks,'' he said. But he added that an attack on a
heavily populated area by a Russian laboratory super strain could
cause ``thousands or hundreds of thousands of deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia denies that it possesses biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The first recorded outbreak of the disease occurred in 1967 at
the Behring pharmaceutical works in Marburg, Germany, which was
experimenting with green monkeys from Uganda. Thirty-one people
died during the outbreak. Two more perished from the virus during
the same year in Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, scientists investigating the disease's origins
traveled to Uganda to determine the cause, according to Hartl.
While they suspected the monkeys were the culprit, they were never
able to conclusively prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the World Health Organization believes the virus is
transmitted to humans following contact with infected animals or
animal tissues. Humans can also contract it from close contact with
an infected person or infected body fluids.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the US Center for Disease Control in Atlanta said
that a handful of smaller outbreaks have been recorded in South
Africa, Zimbabwe and Kenya during the past 25 years. But the recent
case in eastern Congo is the largest yet. And it is far more
virulent that the European strain, which killed some 30 to 35
pecent of those infected by it. Of an estimated 76 cases in the
Congo, 52 have died.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Skinner, a spokesman for the US Centers for Disease Control,
said the disease -- catalogued along with Ebola, Lasa fever and
Crimean Congo haemorrhagic fever as a Level 4 virus -- is among the
most lethal and least understood in the world. He said a sample of
the virus would probably be made available to CDC scientists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
