<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-FUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRISTOL-MYERS PLEDGES $100 MILLION TO AIDS FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unprecedented effort by a private corporation to stem the
AIDS epidemic and provide care for its poorest victims, a leading
US-based pharmaceutical company Thursday pledged $100 million over
the next five years to fight AIDS in five hard-hit African nations.
</P>
<P>
   The contribution, by Bristol-Myers Squibb Co., will fund
programs to prevent new AIDS-virus infections and to provide care,
including drug treatment, to a region where 3.5 million people _
more than 7 percent of the population _ are already infected. Few
can afford the costly drugs used to treat the disease in developed
nations.
</P>
<P>
   The additional $20 million a year amounts to a 14 percent jump
in total AIDS funding in sub-Saharan Africa, where currently only
about $140 million is available to fight the disease. South Africa,
Botswana, Namibia, Lesotho, and Swaziland will share the funds.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Piot, director of UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS
agency, said he hoped the drug company's move ``will be imitated by
more multinational companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The new money will be targeted in part to programs to improve
care for women and children in nations where 16 to 36 percent of
pregnant women carry the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), which
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Recent research has shown drugs given during pregnancy can cut
in half the rate of HIV transmission from mother to infant at a
cost of about $80 per case. But providing such treatment requires a
chain of support services seldom found in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot parachute the drugs into these countries. We need
the infrastructure to deliver care,'' said Dr. Joseph Saba of
UNAIDS, who has campaigned vigorously for drug company
contributions. ``We need well-trained doctors and nurses;
laboratory facilities for people to get tested; pharmacies where
the drugs can be made available and managed properly. We need
patients to be aware of the treatments they need and how to take
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Combined with a $25 million pledge this week by Microsoft's
William Gates to support AIDS vaccine research, the Bristol-Myers
Squibb contribution heartened activists who have recently worried
about a decline in AIDS-fighting support in this country and
abroad. ``It indicates a dramatic rise in interest in the global
pandemic,'' said Daniel Zingale, executive director of AIDS Action,
a Washington-based advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice to hear these things years ago,'' said
Jacob A. Gayle Jr., the UNAIDS liaison to the World Bank, who spoke
Thursday night at a Boston forum on African AIDS sponsored by the
21st Century Group, an organization of black professionals.
``However, hopefully 20 years hence we'll look back and say this
contribution began a whole new era of response to this epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bristol-Myers Squibb chairman and chief executive, Charles
A. Hiembold Jr., said the $18.3 billion-a-year firm felt ``a moral
obligation to take action against this grave situation.'' But
company executives and consultants noted that the step will serve
the drug firm's commercial interests as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty. I think the company will benefit from this,''
said Barry Scott, vice president of Bristol-Myers Squibb's
international division. ``I don't know how.. . .But I'd be avoiding
the obvious to say there would be no effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Marlink of the Harvard AIDS Institute, who will
serve on a scientific advisory board for the new project, said the
contribution ``will buy goodwill. It may open doors. If I were in
the upper reaches of a pharmaceutical company very involved in AIDS
drugs, I would note that this epidemic is growing, and it's
disproportionately affecting southern Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb makes three leading AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Like other AIDS-drug manufacturers, it has recently been alarmed
by threats from some African nations to manufacture cheap,
unauthorized versions of costly AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to South Africa's health minister, Dr. Nkosazana Zuma,
Scott added: ``Certainly we are challenging the health minister on
intellectual properties issues and we will continue to challenge
her on it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scott said those threats ``did not enter into'' the
company's decision to contribute $100 million to South Africa and
four neighboring countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7312 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MOTHERS07-COX     05-06 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MOTHERS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parental influence on child limited, author says
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``If I were the father of one of those boys, how
would I go on living?''
</P>
<P>
   That was the first question Harriet Lerner's husband asked when
the news of the Colorado tragedy broke and the couple learned that
students had been responsible for the killing.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, a staff psychologist and psychotherapist at the
Menninger Clinic in Kansas, shared his sentiments _ only more so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers are blamed for everything and blame themselves in this
society,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In town recently to promote her new book, ``The Mother Dance,''
(Harper-Collins, $25), Lerner also has authored ``The Dance of
Anger'' and ``The Dance of Intimacy.'' ``My husband calls me the
Fred Astaire of the self-help world,'' she laughs.
</P>
<P>
   But she isn't laughing when she begins talking about parental
culpability for a child's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are responsible for their own behavior but they are
not responsible for their children's behavior ... which they can
influence but not control,'' she says emphatically. ``A particular
mother can behave badly, even abominably, but she cannot make her
child become a serial killer or even get straight A's.''
</P>
<P>
   Lerner says there are many factors beyond a parent's control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids come into the world with their own unique strands of
DNA,'' she says. ``Some kids are genuinely easy kids and some kids
are a piece of work!''
</P>
<P>
   While, in the best of all possible worlds, parents would pay
perfect attention and be perfectly attuned to their children's
thoughts and actions, Lerner says many parents are often exhausted
and hardly able to pay attention to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making excuses regarding neglect, abuse or even
insensitivity,'' she adds. ``I'm merely saying there are times when
parents barely get through the day. All of us make mistakes in what
we do and what we fail to do.''
</P>
<P>
   An example from her own life? When her two boys were young, the
family started off on a car trip after stopping for gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drove off leaving our younger son behind in a seedy gas
station,'' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   When she tells the story, the reaction is always laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has done things like this,'' Lerner says. ``And we
were lucky. If we had been unlucky, we might have been put in jail
in today's world. We all have vulnerabilities, limitations and `bad
mother days.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lerner says our society encourages mothers to cultivate guilt
like ``a little flower garden.'' Her gift to mothers on Mother's
Day, she says, would to encourage them to let go of nonproductive
self-doubt and guilt.
</P>
<P>
   When her first son was born _ in the '70s _ there was something
to make every mother feel guilty, each in her own way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers who worked outside the home were told their children
would not thrive, while homemakers were depicted by the media as
idiots who drooled over their newly waxed floors,'' she says.
``Career women were pitted against stay-at-home moms.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Lerner, it was a false and decisive polarity for
which feminism was then blamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women today still feel on the defensive, as if differences are
a condemnation or judgment,'' she says. ``It's easy for one woman
to be critical of another woman's parenting or feel defensive about
her own choices.''
</P>
<P>
   When Lerner decided to write a book on parenting, she first went
to a giant bookstore to see what was already on the shelves. What
she discovered were ``several million'' books on the subject. What
was missing, she noted, were books from a mother's perspective:
books that told what mothering was really like from the inside and
how a woman's life was changed and transformed after her first baby
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motherhood is surrounded by such false sentimentality that
mothers are hungry to hear the voices of other women telling the
truth,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The new book is written for mothers and grandmothers of all ages
and covers experiences from conception to empty nest. Lerner shares
much from her own life. Fathers, she says, will relate to it as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What motherhood taught me is humility,'' she says. ``Before I
had kids, I was amazed at the improper behavior of other mothers
and I knew I would never do any of those things. ... I would never
scream at my kids or fight with my husband within their earshot or
feed them at McDonald's. And I definitely wasn't going to be a
worrier like my own mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' she says, smiling, `` I did all those things and
more. We don't have a clue what our children will evoke in us until
we have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lerner says novelist Fay Weldon put it best: ``The greatest
advantage of not having children must be that you can go on
thinking you are a nice person. Once you have children, you
understand how wars start.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your kids will make you love them in a way you never dreamed
possible,'' Lerner concludes. ``They will also teach you that you
are not the calm, clear, mature, highly evolved, saintlike person
that you fancied yourself before you became a mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Lerner believes that while today's dads are deeply committed to
being more connected to their children than in previous
generations, far too much is still expected of mothers and far too
little expected of fathers in terms of the daily hands-on job of
rearing children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work in therapy and many modern parents who are totally
committed to shared parenting and earning do remarkably well until
the first baby comes along. Then they discover how incredibly
powerful the old roles of `man the breadwinner' and `woman the
primary nurturer' really are. It puts a tremendous strain on the
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Lerner disagrees with some parenting advice, such as the notion
of ``letting go'' of kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that any parent can be invasive, intrusive or over
controlling at any stage of the life cycle,'' she says. ``It's true
that parents need to have a profound respect for differences.
However, we should never let go. Our children always need us to
stand for connection ... even if they seek distance and even if
they refuse to speak to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead we should be reaching for deeper and more complex ways
of staying connected. Get help when you need it. Never give up on
your kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
