<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7315 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-LEE-BOS &LR;      05-06 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-LEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE SEEN AS SYMBOL OF ASIAN COMMUNITY'S POLITICAL ACCEPTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON AND ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's Asian-American community flooded Senator Edward
Kennedy's Washington office two years ago with letters and phone
calls, urging him to support Bill Lann Lee's nomination to head the
US Justice Department's civil-rights division.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, many of those same supporters will sit down to
hear a man they had hope will be the country's first civil rights
chief, despite Lee's repeated failed nominations. Lee, 50, the son
of a poor Chinese immigrant, symbolizes for many the entrance of
the Asian community into the country's powerful public policy
arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``African Americans have really established a strong hold in the
political arena which we are striving for,'' said George Cha,
former president of the New England Organization of
Asian-Americans. ``So, it's Bill Lann Lee . . . who we consider one
of the forerunners of success in our community.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an Asian American he means our maturation into the
political process,'' he said. ``But globally he represents true
access for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The permanent appointment of Lee, currently acting attorney
general for civil rights, to the post has been delayed by vigorous
Republican opposition _ which many see as a national metaphor for
the changing face and continuing attack of affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he is neither black nor white and the first Asian
American to be tapped for this post _ he is symbolic,'' said Frank
Wu, associate professor at Howard University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's nomination has been blocked by the Senate Judiciary
Committee each time it has come up since he was first chosen by
President Bill Clinton in December 1997, becoming the flash point
in the perennial debate over civil rights and affirmative action
that often occurs in an election season.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton resubmitted his nomination in March _ for the third time
_ after Congress passed a watered-down resolution condemning
discrimination in the wake of an embarrassing disclosure that two
Republicans, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi and
US Representative Bob Barr of Georgia, maintained ties to the
Council of Conservative Citizens, which promotes the preservation
of the white race.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Clinton administration seized on the Republicans'
fumble to play to the minority vote, particularly Asian Americans,
who may be crucial to Vice President Al Gore's presidential
prospects in western states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing a Republican candidate for president wants to
confront going into an election would be his party's unfair
rejection of a leading Asian American civil rights expert,'' said
one administration official. ``It's really not justifiable and it
would be very difficult to explain why our party did this.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials downplay Lee's involvement in
affirmative action cases, saying they constitute only a minute
portion of his workload at the Justice Department. Instead, they
emphasize his efforts to combat hate crimes, enforce the Americans
with Disabilities Act, and his pioneering role in promoting
mediation and alternative dispute resolution, which brings parties
together while avoiding expensive litigation.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee's critics focus on his support of affirmative action:
``Mr. Lee thinks that the Constitution is not color-blind, but
color-coded, that the rights that an American have under the
Constitution and under civil rights laws depends on his melanin
content, where his ancestors came from and his or her sex,'' said
Roger Clegg, a former Justice Department official now general
counsel for the conservative Center for Equal Opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say Mr. Lee spends only 10 percent of his time working
on affirmative action issues,'' continued Clegg. ``Saying that he
shouldn't be criticized because of those 10 perent of the cases is
like saying the airlines shouldn't be criticized because only 10
percent of the planes crash.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House brushed aside such arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Lann Lee did not create the (affirmative action) laws,
Congress did, and if critics have a problem with the law then their
problem should be with the Congress,'' said White House spokesman
James Kennedy. ``He's caught in the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This nominee shares the views of the president and the
president deserves to have someone whose views reflect his.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's open support of affirmative action dismantles the myth
that Asian Americans oppose affirmative action and that the
argument of race and discrimination is a black and white matter,
said Wu, the Howard University Law School professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very often when people assume Asians are foreigners, guests
and tourists _ they (Asian Americans) feel frustrated because the
dialogue on race is going on without them as if they didn't have a
stake in this country'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Orrin Hatch, the Judiciary Committee chairman, who has
vehemently opposed Lee's nomination, recently gave White House
officials a glimmer of hope by asking his staff to review Lee's
record over the 1 1/2 years he's been acting attorney general.
Kennedy said administration officials view the request as a
``positive sign'' that could pave the way toward consideration of
Lee by the entire Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But not so fast, said Judiciary Committee spokeswoman, Jeanne
Lopatto. ``Senator Hatch has not changed his position on Bill Lann
Lee,'' she said Thursday, adding that the Utah Republican continues
to oppose his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Attorney General Janet Reno pleaded Lee's case
before the committee, which has oversight of the Justice
Department. She called him ``splendid'' to work with and said he
would ``serve you and this nation very well.'' Hatch, however, said
he was still conducting the review of Lee's tenure and was
non-commital about scheduling a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who spent two decades as a lawyer for the NAACP Legal
Defense Fund, was born and raised in Harlem. His parents, Chinese
immigrants, owned a small laundry. His father, who experienced
mean-spirited discrimination, inspired young Lee to pursue a career
in civil rights, according to his biography.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Bronx High School of Science, he won a
minority scholarship which helped him attend Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is a man who grew up in Harlem, worked for the NAACP.
It's a rare thing to find someone who was a beneficiary of an
affirmative program and is successful and confident enough to tell
people that he would not have had doors open had it not been for
affirmative action,'' said Andrew Leong, assistant professor at the
Law Center at the University of Massachusetts. ``So he is a very
proud symbol not just for the Asian community but for people of
color.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee studied at Yale University, graduating Phi Beta Kappa in
1971. Three years later he would began a career as a civil rights
attorney which stretched for nearly a quarter of a century. His
career with the NAACP Legal Defense began in 1974 as an associate
attorney. In 1983, he left the organization to become the
supervising attorney for civil rights at The Center for Law and
Public Interest in California. He would return to the NAACP in
1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
