<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-PILGRIM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD PILGRIM CHIEF QUITS FOLLOWING RECORD LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The chief executive of Harvard Pilgrim Health Care
resigned Thursday amid financial turmoil at New England's largest
health maintenance organization.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Greenberg's abrupt departure occurred less than a week
after Harvard Pilgrim reported its largest annual loss ever and
said it would significantly raise premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Like other HMOs nationwide, Harvard Pilgrim, which insures 1.3
million people, has been buffeted by soaring prescription drug
costs, rising medical inflation and intense competitive pressure to
keep a lid on premium increases.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim did not specify the reason for Greenberg's
resignation. Its chairman Alan R. Morse said the departure was ``a
private matter between Allan and the board of directors.'' In a
memo to employees, Morse said the HMO has created a transition team
to run the company until a replacement can be found. ``Dr. Gil
Shapiro and I, along with several other members of the Board will
work with the senior management team of Harvard Pilgrim to make
sure that the important work of the organization continues without
interruption,'' Morse wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, 46, whose resignation was effective immediately, was
not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came swiftly after Harvard Pilgrim, which is
consistently rated one of the country's best HMOs for quality of
care, announced it lost $94 million from operations in 1998 on
revenue of $2.6 billion. A $40 million gain from interest income
helped lower the net loss to $54 million. Still, the losses were
unprecedented in magnitude for Harvard Pilgrim, which was formed in
1995 with the merger between Harvard Community Health Plan and
Pilgrim Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, who was chief executive of Pilgrim, became CEO of the
combined organization in 1996. Since then, the company's senior
management positions were gradually taken over by executives from
Pilgrim, culminating in a layoff in November, which swept out many
Harvard managers, including Dr. Patrick Mattingly, senior vice
president for strategy, and Dr. John Ludden, a medical director.
The merger also created computer integration problems, which cost
Harvard Pilgrim significant sums to correct. Those costs were among
the reasons cited by the HMO for its 1998 losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allan has to own a lot of the responsibility,'' for the
losses, said Stephen Caulfield, chairman of the Chickering Group,
an insurance company in Cambridge. ``He chose to imprint the
organization with his people and his ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Other health care executives give Greenberg credit for leading
one of the mostly highly regarded HMOs in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't forget that Harvard Pilgrim is nationally
recognized as an outstanding HMO and that it is a formidable force
in this marketplace,'' said Ann Thornburg, a health care consultant
with PriceWaterhouseCoopers in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Newsweek magazine ranked Harvard Pilgrim as the best
HMO in the country, while US News &AMP; World Report gave it four
stars, its highest rating, for the third year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Though rumors have circulated in recent weeks regarding
Greenberg's term in office, news of his departure shook the Boston
health care world .
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great surprise to me,'' said Dr. Manuel Lowenhaupt,
who was a board member of Harvard Community Health in the 1980s and
is a partner at Deloitte &AMP; Touche Consulting Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really sad,'' said Dr. Harris Berman, chief executive of
Tufts Health Plan, the region's second-largest HMO and Harvard
Pilgrim's archrival. ``I feel very badly about it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Berman said Harvard Pilgrim's losses, though
large, are symptomatic of the entire managed care industry. After
suppressing health insurance premiums for years to gain new
customers _ a practice that is part of what the industry calls an
``insurance cycle'' _ HMOs nationwide are starting to pay the
price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurance cycles make everybody look dumb,'' said Kenneth
Abramowitz, a health care analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co.
in New York. ``The board could have blamed it on the cycle, or the
people. Since it's difficult to pin the blame on some amorphous
cycle, it's easier to blame it on the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Abramowitz said Harvard Pilgrim may be trading one set of
problems for another by trying to find a new CEO, given that the
field of candidates is thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry is generally lacking in talent and experience,''
he said. ``I would hope that when the board makes a decision like
this, they have a lot of talent underneath to move up the ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim has been searching unsuccessfully since February
for a chief operating officer, a new position for the organization.
Now the search is under way for a CEO as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Morse, a former banker with US Trust who in
1995 became the state's superintendent of financial services, said
Harvard Pilgrim has created an office of the CEO to be occupied by
six executives, including himself; Shapiro, a board member; William
Frado, general counsel; Esther Emard, senior vice president for
regional operations; Larry Gibson, senior vice president for human
resources and information technology; and Dr. Joseph Dorsey,
medical director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
