<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-STREET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE STREET SELLING BANKING OPERATION TO CITIZENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Every three months for the past five years, Lawrence
Fish, chief executive of Citizens Financial Group Inc., telephoned
Marshall Carter, head of State Street Corp., asking to buy what
remained of State Street's bank.
</P>
<P>
   The persistence paid off, with State Street agreeing Thursday to
sell all of its branches and deposits and a big chunk of its
commercial loans to Citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, the latest transaction to alter New England's rapidly
changing financial landscape, signals the rise of Providence-based
Citizens as a regional bank with a full menu of lending operations.
It also marks the final exit of State Street _ a giant, high-tech
securities processor and money manager that evolved from a
financial institution whose charter was approved by John Hancock in
1792 _ from traditional banking.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Citizens will buy all of Boston-based State
Street's retail bank, or four branches with $1.6 billion in
deposits, and around one-third, or $2.2 billion, of State Street's
commercial loans.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition may help position Citizens more favorably before
industry regulators, who are working to decide what size bank
should be allowed to bid for assets to be divested by Fleet
Financial Group Inc. and BankBoston Corp. as a condition of their
blockbuster merger. That sale will put $13.6 billion in deposits
and 270 branches in New England, including 200 in Massachusetts, on
the market, the largest divestiture ever.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller Citizens, whose mainstay has been traditional,
slow-growth deposits rather than corporate lending, wants to buy
some of those assets. But regulators favor banks with strong
commercial lending practices _ usually larger banks _ as bidders.
By bulking up through the State Street deal, Citizens may stand a
better chance of becoming a contender.
</P>
<P>
   For Citizens, a private company owned by the Royal Bank of
Scotland, the transaction is ``a defining moment in our history and
transforms Citizens into the premier middle-market and
small-banking practice here in New England,'' Fish said Thursday.
The deal increases Citizens' commercial portfolio by nearly 50
percent to $7 billion, or one-third of its $21 billion in assets.
Around $2 billion of the total is real estate loans.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens is paying the portfolio's book value of $1.1 billion
plus a $350 million premium, all in cash. The book value does not
include $500 million in repurchase agreement deposits.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, part of a trend of consolidation in the banking
industry, represents State Street's final farewell from mainstream
banking. The company began two centuries ago as a traditional bank
but over the past two decades has transformed itself into the
world's third-largest securities processor _ a global back-office
operation that keeps track of what institutional investors buy and
sell. In addition to collecting fees for overseeing $5 trillion in
assets in custody, it also manages $525 billion in assets through
its State Street Global Advisers, the nation's third-largest money
management firm.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens gains two State Street branches in Boston and two in
Quincy, as well as a loan book focused on small and mid-sized
businesses in the Northeast. The company, which now has 239
branches throughout five New England states and is the region's
second-largest bank behind Fleet-BankBoston, gains 300 State Street
employees. It pledged no cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The sale leaves State Street with $4 billion in lease financing,
and real estate and securities-backed loans to institutional
investors. While State Street will retain its banking charter, it
will close its remaining downtown branch and provide bank services
only to institutional and private clients. Traditional banking, or
retail deposits and commercial loans, accounted for only 8 percent
of State Street's bottom line last year. State Street's entire
commercial lending business had pre-tax profits last year of $88
million, according to the Royal.
</P>
<P>
   But despite a sign atop its tower that says ``State Street
Bank'' _ a fixture it cannot change under Boston architecture
regulations _ State Street is no longer a bank. ``The company sees
itself as a technology firm, as doing processing for other
customers,'' said Stephen Biggar, an analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's
equity research group.
</P>
<P>
   While a Royal statement said the acquisition ``positions
Citizens to take strong advantage of the continuing consolidation
in the New England market,'' Citizens hastened to say the sale was
in the works months before Fleet and BankBoston's deal in March to
combine into the nation's eighth-largest bank. But Carter said at a
press conference Thursday that for Citizens, the merger was one
factor behind the timing of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Fish first approached Carter about a sale in mid-1995, when
State Street had finished shaping up a loan portfolio battered in
previous years by New England's recession. Undaunted by Carter's
response of ``maybe, but not now,'' Fish called his colleague every
quarter to see if sentiment had changed, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at a Kennedy School of Government dinner last December for
the British chancellor of the exchequer, Fish found himself
strategically positioned next to Carter at the head table,
according to an executive familiar with the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both looked at each other and said, `maybe it's time we
talked','' the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Several conversations followed in January and February,
culminating in a verbal agreement Sunday while Fish was golfing at
the Sawgrass Country Club in Jacksonville, Fla. A final deal was
signed early Thursday after the two sides worked through the night
to hammer out a servicing arrangement for the loans.
</P>
<P>
   Although several large national banks and some smaller local
outfits had made inquiries, Carter said he had not shopped the
assets to other buyers because he viewed Citizens as the best
option for State Street's banking customers.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens has grown rapidly this decade through acquisitions,
quintupling its deposits and commercial loans since 1992. But ``we
don't want to be a $50 or $100 billion company,'' or twice to five
times current size, Fish said Thursday. Fleet-BankBoston will have
over $160 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   London financial circles buzzed with talk Thursday that the
Royal might be more likely to sell Citizens, an attractive
franchise that contributes 25 percent of its parent's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In an industry increasingly divided between giant banks with
hundreds of billions of dollars in assets and tiny community
players, there are not many banks of Citizens' size left.
</P>
<P>
   State Street has various ways to use the sale proceeds. ``We
have historically looked at small and sometimes not-so-small
acquisitions _ that will be one option,'' said company spokesman
Gregory Ahern. Other possibilities include reinvesting in
technology or conducting a stock buyback.
</P>
<P>
   State Street shares, on an upswing for nearly two decades, rose
3-1/16 Thursday to close at 86-9/16. They are up 23 percent so far
this year.
</P>
<P>
   For the Citizens deal, which is expected to close in the third
quarter, State Street was advised by Goldman Sachs. Citizens used J
P Morgan &AMP; Co, the Boston law firm of Goodwin Proctor &AMP; Hoar, and
PriceWaterhouse Coopers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
