<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-PETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMAL WELFARE GROUPS SEARCH FOR MISSING PETS IN TORNADO RUBBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY BLANEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY, Okla. _ Animal welfare officials from North Texas
and across the country converged Thursday to help find pets buried
in the rubble left by Monday's killer tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers were asking for chain saws to cut through debris in
search of dogs, cats and birds believed to be under mountains of
brick, glass and wallboard, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of pounds of dog and cat food have been donated to feed
unclaimed pets.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency Animal Rescue, a nonprofit group based in Sacramento,
Calif., was in suburban Moore, where 55 dogs had been rescued by
Thursday, said the group's director, Terri Crist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no count on the dead ones,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Locating cats is an entirely different beast, Crisp said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so frightened,'' Crisp said. ``They are staying
hidden.''
</P>
<P>
   Last night, humane traps were being put out for the felines.
</P>
<P>
   A team of 35 will work through Tuesday to help Moore animal
control officials. The California group works only disasters,
handling eight last year.
</P>
<P>
   Suzi Green, a nurse at the Equi-Center Veterinary Hospital in
Oklahoma City, estimated Thursday that hundreds of horses had been
killed, based on reports that she was getting from owners.
</P>
<P>
   The vet hospital had about 30 injured horses, she said,
including 19 from Tinker Air Force Base, where a barn was leveled
and two other horses were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarian Mike Wiley had blisters on his hands after working
20 hours straight _ from Monday night until Tuesday afternoon _ to
stitch up lacerations from flying debris, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't hardly bend his fingers,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   In rural areas near Newcastle, a community south of Oklahoma
City, veterinarian Kim Murdoch treated a herd of 60 injured cattle,
some with lacerations as large as footballs, she said. She had to
destroy 12 animals that had broken bones.
</P>
<P>
   She had no estimate of how many cattle were killed in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The suburbs of Del City and Midwest City are getting assistance
from Oklahoma City's Animal Welfare division.
</P>
<P>
   Animal control officers from the North Texas communities of
Grapevine, North Richland Hills, Fort Worth and DeSoto arrived or
were en route to Oklahoma City on Thursday. Workers also came from
the McKinney and Dallas offices of the Society for the Prevention
of Cruelty to Animals and the Humane Society of the United States'
Southwest Regional Office.
</P>
<P>
   Others have come from Colorado, California and Arkansas,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis White, director of the Humane Society's southwest office
in Dallas, drove past one of the worst hit areas Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a Hiroshima bomb,'' he said. ``I think they're
going to find a lot of dead animals who were crushed by houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the surviving dogs and cats have been reunited with
their owners, said Dr. George Cooper, superintendent of the animal
welfare division. By Wednesday, 14 of 42 animals had been picked
up.
</P>
<P>
   In the storm's immediate aftermath, pet dogs growled at rescue
dogs searching the debris for dead and injured people, said Carla
Gathright, a Norman animal control officer.
</P>
<P>
   She rescued one cocker spaniel that she couldn't believe was
still alive. The dog was upside down in a hole next to where a
wooden light pole had broken in two. The dog's head was in muddy
water from the rainfall, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to smash the dirt away from her to get enough room to
pull her out,'' Gathright said. ``You could hear the gurgling of
mud as she fought for air.''
</P>
<P>
   In one garage, an animal control officer found a small dog
inside the wheel well of a car that was about 5 inches off the
floor, all its tires flattened, Gathright said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very traumatized,'' Gathright said.
</P>
<P>
   In Newcastle, a 1-year-old Australian shepherd got a new name
after the twister. Buddy is now called Lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The dog's owner, Lee Kuhlman, 31, said his cousin had been
keeping the dog at his home in Newcastle. Monday morning, Buddy had
been chained as usual to a steel fence post moored in concrete.
After the tornado swept through Monday evening, all the homes
around the cousin's house were destroyed and the dog was gone.
</P>
<P>
   But when Kuhlman returned to the house Tuesday to help clean up,
a neighbor down the street had good news. He had found Buddy alive,
still on the chain. Kuhlman promptly renamed him Lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear to you this dog had to have been blowing in the
wind,'' Kuhlman marveled. ``It just blows my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
