<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TECH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM DESTROYS HOME _ EXCEPT FOR BUILT-IN SHELTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL CITY, Okla. _ When light began peeking underneath her
bedroom closet door Monday evening, Beth Bartlett knew her house
was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Huddled among her clothes in a space specially constructed to
serve as a closet and in-home storm shelter, Bartlett could
ascertain what the tornado was doing to her Del City neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a loud roar, but you could hear things crashing into
one another and debris just kept pummeling the house,'' Bartlett
said on Thursday. ``You could tell the house was taking a pounding.
Then I saw the light under the door and I knew. ... I knew the
house was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the bombed-out conditions that greeted her when she
emerged from her shelter, Bartlett, 40, was elated to have
survived.
</P>
<P>
   Without the 12-inch-thick concrete walls and added supports to
make the closet shelter even stronger, Bartlett and her mother,
Norma Bartlett, likely would have been injured or killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have that closet to hide in, I don't think we
would have made it,'' said Norma Bartlett, 64. ``Our old hiding
place was the hallway closet and everything from one of the
bedrooms got sucked right in there. We would have been beaten to
death with debris.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bartlett had constructed the in-house shelter because
of a lifelong fear of tornadoes, her decision made her an unlikely
guinea pig for severe weather researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the shell of her home on Thursday, Texas Tech University
researchers were trumpeting her shelter as proof that tornadoes
need not be deadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that even the most powerful of tornadoes are
survivable,'' said Larry Tanner, an architect and structural
engineer with Texas Tech's wind engineering program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone, even those on a moderate income, can have a shelter
in their home where they can ride out a tornado. It's simple and
not that expensive to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett purchased the family home of 35 years from her mother
after they decided to become roommates. It sits in a Del City
neighborhood decimated by the storm, just two blocks from the
western edge of Tinker Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   Because Bartlett's shelter was rolled into her remodeling
project, she isn't sure of its exact cost, but Tanner estimates it
would cost between $3,000 and $5,000 to build a similar one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a do-it-yourselfer, you can do one like this for
$2,500,'' Tanner said. ``If you hire someone to do it for you, your
costs are probably going to double. But for someone building a new
home, the costs would be considerably less if it was done at the
time of construction.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech, which has pamphlets on constructing
tornado-resistant shelters inside homes, has been bombarded with
thousands of calls after Monday's tornado. Somewhat surprisingly,
Tanner said they are finding few Oklahoma City residences with any
kind of storm shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Three Texas Tech teams are in the Oklahoma City area to assess
the damage and learn more about the manner in which buildings are
destroyed by tornadoes. Besides homes, they are studying how
commercial structures withstood the storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see on the Bartlett's home how a piece of a lumber
became a missile and tore into the roof,'' Tanner said. ``What
happens is a tornado destroys your neighbor's house and then it
becomes a weapon against your home. And once that debris breaks
through or tears off the roof, the structural integrity is gone and
you will probably lose your home.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Bartlett's shelter survived, the house was in
shambles. She said she will rebuild, with an improved shelter being
the most important part of the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already been told I need three dead-bolts on the door
instead of one, so that's one improvement I'll make,'' Bartlett
said. ``And that will make Mom feel better. She's was convinced the
door wasn't going to make it through the storm, but it did and we
did. And we'll rebuild right here, where we belong.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
