<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7325 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-BUSH-725&AMP;ADD-N     05-06 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-BUSH-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ALREADY EXPLORING A UNITED AGENDA WITH HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders are so united behind Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas for their party's presidential nomination
that they have already begun meeting informally to discuss a common
agenda for Bush and House candidates in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   These meetings are the latest demonstration of the extraordinary
degree to which the party apparatus has concluded that Bush's
nomination is inevitable even though there are nearly a dozen
contenders, the governor has not formally announced his candidacy
and the first primary votes will not be cast for nine months. The
outpouring is all the more striking because members of Congress
traditionally prefer backing one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the nation's governors have already rallied to
Bush's side, and he enjoys many other institutional advantages,
including the early backing of more than a third of the Senate
Republicans as well as the behind-the-scenes encouragement from
fund-raising officials of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's support is so vast that his endorsements rival those of
Vice President Al Gore on the Democratic side. That is remarkable
given that Gore has only one opponent and has been the presumed
Democratic nominee to succeed President Clinton since their
election in 1992 _ two years before Bush was even elected governor.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best example of the groundswell for Bush is in the
House, where the top leaders are already backing the governor.
Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois had agreed to be the Bush
campaign's chief House liaison, but he stepped aside when he rose
to the speakership. He is officially neutral only because of his
position.
</P>
<P>
   The second- and third-ranking House Republicans, each from
Texas, Dick Armey and Tom Delay, also back Bush. The chairman of
the House Republican conference, Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, is a
member of Bush's exploratory committee, as is Rep. Roy Blunt of
Missouri, the chief deputy whip. In all, 94 House Republicans have
signed with Bush, including more than half the committee chairs.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders view Bush's nomination as so inevitable that they
recently began the informal meetings with him as well as his
advisers, including Karl Rove, his top strategist, to discuss a
unified agenda on issues ranging from Social Security to taxes to
education. They have also begun to discuss joint electoral and
fund-raising strategies for the 2000 campaign. The meetings were
first reported Thursday in Roll Call, a newspaper that circulates
on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians involved in the sessions cautioned that they were
preliminary and were geared to announcing a common agenda at the
end of the primary season _ not for imminent policy initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes, as I believe, there's a great opportunity for us
to come together around a common set of principles,'' Armey said in
an interview. ``We'll work out the details through the basic
legislative process. You will probably see a final distillation of
all these ideas in a set of programatic objectives that would not
be announced formally until after he's the nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey said the participants were far from reaching specifics. On
Social Security, for instance, he said, there was only ``the sense
that this is something we'll want to address together.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell of Georgia, a member of Bush's exploratory
committee, said he has rounded up 20 senators to back the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell explained that there was ``a natural coalescing of
thinking'' between lawmakers and Bush. ``Where we think an issue is
developing, obviously, I'd be on the phone talking to him about
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of this budding alliance may say more about a
transformation among House Republicans than about Bush: It
underscores a reality that lawmakers of all stripes are so eager to
find a leader _ and to retake the White House _ that they are
willing to back a politician who is untested on a national stage.
</P>
<P>
   That many of the most conservative members of Congress are
backing Bush may also reflect a triumph of pragmatism there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taming them and domesticating them from going on further
kamikaze missions like impeachment,'' said a supporter of Bush who
also works closely with House Republicans. ``I've got several
clients in the House who have gone down and met with Bush and said,
`I'm tired of being viewed as an extension of Trent Lott and Newt
Gingrich.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The overwhelming congressional backing could help Bush navigate
the minefield of national issues. And the support of many of the
most conservative members could also provide Bush cover so he can
espouse nuanced views on matters like abortion.
</P>
<P>
   So many House members are jumping on the Bush bandwagon because
he is so far ahead in the polls that they see him as inevitable.
Many lawmakers said they were also drawn to him because he comes
from a big state, has impressive political skills and has
successfully pulled in votes from Democrats and independents as
well as from Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians like nothing better than jumping in front of a
parade,'' said Ed Brookover, a strategist who is close to many
House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In backing Bush, members of Congress are passing over their own
colleagues in the race: Sens. John McCain of Arizona and Bob Smith
of New Hampshire, and Rep. John Kasich of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, particularly Bush's rivals, warn that that the
Bush juggernaut amounts to short-sighed foolishness.
</P>
<P>
   One top strategist to a Bush opponent, who agreed to speak only
on the condition of anonymity, put it this way: ``They're
panic-stricken on Capitol Hill, and they're afraid they're going to
lose their five-seat majority. And they're looking for a savior.
But in trying to preclude a contest from taking place before it's
even started, they're putting an awful lot of eggs in the basket
for a candidate they know absolutely nothing about.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman, said the discussions
demonstrate the governor's commitment to developing ``a positive,
issue-oriented agenda.'' ``These discussions are about the agenda
that would emerge from the 2000 presidential campaign should
Governor Bush be elected president,'' Ms. Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Haley Barbour, the former chairman of the Republican Party who
is a member of Bush's exploratory committee, said the early support
``should not be misread into thinking he's going to get the
nomination on a silver platter: he's not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
