<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7328 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-CROWDED-BOS &LR;      05-06 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-CROWDED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG FEARS POPULATION SURGE UNDER RESIDENCY RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In 10 years, this city will be a miserably
overcrowded and polluted place, burdened with double-digit
unemployment and astronomical public spending, if 1.67 million
mainland Chinese are allowed to emigrate, government officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers would be forced to spend $92 billion on new
construction, land and transportation infrastructure for five new
cities, 266 extra schools and a half-million added public housing
apartments, if the government abides by a local high court ruling
granting residency to all mainland-born children of Hong Kong
residents, the government says.
</P>
<P>
   Social service advocates and politicians have accused officials
of exaggerating the numbers and of creating an absurd scenario to
scare the public into demanding that Beijing intervene to stem the
predicted tide of arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   Legal scholars have warned that asking Beijing to override Hong
Kong's high court, or to amend the local constitution to limit
residency rights here, could be a dangerous step toward eroding
Hong Kong's judicial independence and autonomy from China, which
regained control of the British colony in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong cannot bear the burden of an additional 1.67 million
people,'' said the chief executive, Tung Chee-hwa says. ``The
consequences are unimaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said that by 2009, more than $4 billion would have to
be spent annually on housing, education, training, health care,
welfare and transport for migrants. Perhaps an even greater
constraint is the 14,826 acres of land needed for new facilities
and infrastructure, the report said. In the 1990s, an average of
just 494 acres a year were made available for development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The remaining solution,'' Tung told legislators, ``is that we
ask the National People's Congress to amend the Basic Law, or for
the NPC standing committee to give an interpretation'' of a local
high court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In January Hong Kong's Court of Final Appeal ruled that the
Basic Law, Hong Kong's post-colonial constitution, grants residency
rights to all children of Hong Kong residents, even illegitimate
ones and ones born before their parents became residents. Last
week, the government said 1.67 million people would eligible for
residency within 13 years under the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, many have questioned the figures. The numbers imply
that one of four Hong Kong men has out-of-wedlock children in
China, and that mainland mothers are widely flouting China's
one-child policy. High numbers of mainland children born to Hong
Kong parents also contradict Hong Kong's low birth rate.
</P>
<P>
   Critics lambasted the government for not reporting last week
that 20 percent of people surveyed had said they did not want their
mainland-born children to move here, or did not expect them to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, China still restricts exit permits for its citizens,
so there is no reason to believe that all eligible people would be
able to come to Hong Kong soon _ even if Hong Kong wanted to accept
them. At present, 150 mainlanders settle here every day under a
quota agreed to by Hong Kong and mainland authorities. And there is
no sign that Beijing will start issuing 1,000 exit permits a day _
the number needed to fulfill Hong Kong's dire predictions about an
influx.
</P>
<P>
   Government critics worry the immigration issue is a Trojan Horse
that will persuade the public to invite China's interference _ and
thereby undermine Hong Kong's autonomy on everything from civil
rights to economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't we ask the central authorities to trust Hong Kong to
solve it ourselves?'' Democratic Party legislator Albert Ho asked
Tung. ``Hong Kong people have been scared...so they will agree to
whatever you propose.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not our tactic,'' Tung replied. ``But if you have a
better solution, I am more than happy to hear about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the government meant to scare people, it has done
so.
</P>
<P>
   Chiu Wai-ming, 39, a construction worker who admitted his own
parents came here from China, said: ``I'm not well-educated, but I
know it'll be a burden and may affect social order. The best
solution is to overrule the court's decision. If we can't do that,
then let them come in gradually, in 10- to 20-year increments. It's
like rain _ if every day there's a small amount, it's OK. But if
one day it rains too much, you have a flood.''
</P>
<P>
   Some estimates about the impact of new arrivals appeared
contradictory or were such worst-case scenarios that they strained
credulity.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the government said new migrants would add 876,500
people to the labor force, lowering wages and per capita income and
increasing unemployment by 10 percentage points in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Migrants' advocates said that in fact, countless jobs would be
created by the government's predicted building boom.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary for Security Regina Ip denied a report that that the
government had ``cooked up or inflated'' figures, saying it had a
duty to tell residents what would happen if every eligible migrant
were to come. Already, Ip said, 45,000 children of Hong Kong
residents have arrived since Hong Kong returned to China in July
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gillian Yau, 23, a graduate student in social sciences, said she
thinks the ``government is playing tricks with numbers. Quite a
large number don't want to come, because they already have families
there or because life wouldn't be as good for them here if they're
unemployed. Yet the government's trick is very effective, because I
know a lot about this issue, and even I am scared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
