<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES A PICTURE IS JUST A PICTURE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Why Are Our Pictures Puzzles?'' (Routledge; $80)  &UR; James &LR; 
 &UR; Elkins &LR;  writes about art historians' tendency to over- &LR; analyze
great works. Some examples of this tendency, cited in an essay
about the book in Lingua Franca magazine:
</P>
<P>
   Renoir's 1875 painting ``Woman at the Piano,'' according to
Norwegian art historian  &UR; Birger Carlstrom &LR; , is an allegory
revealing the painter's worries about the Panama Canal, which was
just getting under way. In one murky corner of the work _ which
depicts a romantic-looking woman seating on a bench and tickling
the ivories _ a ``brownish squiggle'' is said to evoke the Latin
American isthmus. The painting, says the Norwegian, was meant to be
a prophesy of financial problems about to beset many French
investors.
</P>
<P>
   German scholar  &UR; Bernhard Koerner &LR; , analyzing  &UR; Rembrandt &LR; 's
``Rape of Ganymede,'' thinks that an infant's squiggly stream of
urine is meant to be a heraldic fertility symbol.  &UR; Sidney Geist &LR; 
says that a Cezanne landscape, ``Small Houses at Anvers,'' is
really a Freudian depiction in which the hills duplicate the
contours of the genitalia of a hermaphrodite.
</P>
<P>
   Elkins also discusses  &UR; Frank Meshberger &LR; 's 1990 analysis of
 &UR; Michelangelo &LR; 's Sistine Chapel ceiling, in which the drapery behind
the figure of God in the panel depicting Adam's creation are
representative of an outline of the human brain. Meshberger says
that the leg of one of the angels behind God ``represents the
pituitary stalk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pictures are effectively and forever without meaning,'' writes
Elkins. ``Art history is the bruise that has grown up around that
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MATERIAL GOODS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Can anyone get a bargain at Chanel? The New York Observer says
the couturier has twice-yearly sales, by invitation only, followed
by one-week 40 percent sales open to the public, then
employees-only sales, even more reduced. Finally, whatever is left
is destroyed so it won't wind up in a discount store. ``We do shred
the merchandise,'' said Chanel Vice President  &UR; Barbara &LR; 
 &UR; Cirkva &LR; , ``so that it does not fall into strange channels of
distribution. That is a tradition here.'' The buttons are the only
things saved.
</P>
<P>
   _ Update: That auction of left-behind stuff at  &UR; Burt &LR; 
 &UR; Reynolds &LR; ' former dinner theater in Florida netted some fancy
prices. A picture of Burt and &UR; Loni  &LR; fetched $10; Burt and  &UR; Groucho &LR; 
 &UR; Marx &LR; , $20; Burt and the pope, $50.
</P>
<P>
   _ World Championship Wrestling has licensed Perfumania to sell
WCW Nitro, a men's perfume. ``It will be upscale,'' Perfumania's
 &UR; Ilia Lekach  &LR; told the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gazoontite (that's gesundheit in the correct German), a Union
Street store for allergy sufferers and asthmatics, had a
grand-opening party last  &LR; Sunday night. Inside the store: ``all
kinds of things to help people to breathe happier and healthier.''
Outside on the sidewalk:  &UR; Greg Chew &LR;  and at least one other
customer, smoking.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the latest issue of the airline magazine Ambassador,
 &UR; Marty Olmstead  &LR; asked a number of hotel concierges about odd
requests they had received. One with a particular local flavor: The
Hotel Nikko in San Francisco was asked to ``deliver a traditional
Chinese dress, embroidered with a golden dragon, large enough to
fit a 6-foot-2 man.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sophie Rhys-Jones  &LR; and &UR; Edward Windsor &LR;  have registered at the
London china shop Thomas Goode, reports the Weekend Financial Times
of London, where there's an aura of danger.
</P>
<P>
   In 1906, says that newspaper,  &UR; Czar Nicholas II  &LR; placed an order
with Goode to replace dishes broken in a set first ordered in 1776.
A few years later, he was assassinated. In recent years, after
 &UR; Gianni Versace &LR;  ordered a plate in the same style, he was
assassinated, too. The Financial Times says it ``hopes that
Rhys-Jones and her fiance will exercise extreme caution when
selecting the pattern of their dinner service.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The British Design Council, preparing for a millennium
demonstration of the ``latest examples of British brilliance in
innovation and creativity,'' has selected more than 600 products
and services to be exhibited, says the Wall Street Journal. Among
them: Viagra, largely developed in British laboratories; the
Teletubbies; and water beds for dairy cows, ``which provide
unsurpassed comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The great Fred Morton joins Vanity Fair as a contributing
editor. Fred is a splendid writer (12 books) with a subtle
appreciation for the Austro-Hungarian Empire. And he's an habitue
of Elaine's.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Columnist James Brady in Advertising Age.
</P>
</TEXT>
