<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7334 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-06 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE ROGUES' GALLERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine what it would sound like if the world's biggest rogues _
North Korea's Kim Jong Il, Iraq's Saddam Hussein, Yugoslavia's
Slobodan Milosevic and Syria's Hafez al-Assad _ had a conference
call about Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Kim: Is everybody on the line?
</P>
<P>
   Saddam: Kim, how are you _ you old Scud-maker you!
</P>
<P>
   Kim: Actually, that's what I was calling about. I just saw this
report that the Americans had run out of air-launched cruise
missiles. Turns out they stopped the production line back in '95.
Can you believe that? I have more Scuds than they have cruise
missiles. Heck, Saddam, you still have more Scuds buried in the
desert than they have cruise missiles. Anyway, I was thinking about
launching another missile test over Japan right now, or maybe a
probe across the 38th parallel. My people are starving, and every
time I rattle my cage the Americans send me more potatoes. Maybe
Iraq could take a bite out of Kuwait at the same time and we could
``triangulate'' Bill Clinton. Boy, would that bring the potatoes!
</P>
<P>
   Saddam: I love it! The last Pentagon strategic review said the
U.S. could fight two wars at once _ one on the Korean Peninsula and
one in the gulf _ but it looks to me like they can barely handle
one, let alone three.
</P>
<P>
   Kim: Can I put you all on hold? I've got a call coming in from
Li Peng in China. (Long pause) I'm back. You're gonna love this. Li
is thinking this might be China's moment to seize Taiwan, but he
says Zhu Rongji and Jiang Zemin are opposed. Those two are such
lackeys. They just want to kiss up to the Americans to get into the
World Trade Organization. I've been having trouble with those two
myself. They keep me on a short leash. Does Clinton realize how
much he needs China to keep Asia quiet right now? The Americans
probably hope we haven't noticed that they moved their only
aircraft carrier in North Asia _ the Roosevelt _ over to the coast
of Yugoslavia. But we notice everything.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam: The Americans think that nothing is connected and that
the world stands still for them. I have a question for brother
Slobodan, though: What's it like fighting 19 countries at once? I
thought I had the record.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan: Rope-a-dope, that's my strategy, rope-a-dope. Whatever
you do, don't turn on your anti-aircraft radars. That was your
mistake, brother Saddam. Every time you turned on your radar they
sent a radiation-seeking missile right back down the radar beam and
blew you away. You're still doing it, you idiot. NATO pilots never
know when I might turn my radar on, so they won't fly below 15,000
feet. They fight like they're Northwest Airlines. And always
remember the Jesse Jackson rule: If you can capture just one U.S.
pilot, Jackson will pay you a visit within 30 days and shift the
whole U.S. focus from its strategic war aims to POWs. As soon as
Jackson starts mediating, people forget what the war is about and
put you on the same moral plane with the U.S. president. Then
you're home free. Right, brother Hafez?
</P>
<P>
   Hafez: You're all idiots.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan, Kim, Saddam: What?
</P>
<P>
   Hafez: How many times have I told you all _ being an extremist
is not just knowing when to go over the line, but when to duck back
behind it. Sure, I leveled a whole town, Hama, when the Muslims
there threatened me. But then I rebuilt it. Sure, I'm bleeding the
Israelis in Lebanon, but I stop just before they get frustrated
enough to bomb me. Saddam, you mistook the world's tolerance for
your war against Iran for a green light to invade Kuwait. Slobo,
you mistook the world's tolerance for your war in Bosnia for a
green light to ethnically cleanse Kosovo. You're both fighting as
though the Soviet Union were going to resupply us all again. It's
not. The Russians want cash now. All Primakov ever says to me is
``Show me the money.'' Look where the Russians agreed to be part of
the international peace force in Kosovo. It was at this week's G-8
economic meeting! It's all part of a package deal for them.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you guys are going to win, all right. But win what? Without
a deal with the West you'll never be able to rebuild your
countries, and you personally will be on the run forever. Your
people may hate the Americans now, but as time goes by they will
hate you more, and you'll be lucky if you don't live to see it. All
you're winning is the right to sleep in a different bed every night
for the rest of your lives. Thanks, but I like to sleep at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
