<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: 100 BRAVE ARABS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By A.M. ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Palestinian state will be created. It will be a dictatorship
_ ranging from stifling to murderous, and most of the time both.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The world's governments, including the United States, will not
worry about that. They never really thought Arabs were entitled to
human liberty in their own nations. Neither did Arabs; only a few
spoke or risked themselves for it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The questions remaining about the official creation of Palestine
are time and what security conditions the Israelis will squeeze out
to slow down its military growth.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Labor government unofficially created Palestine at
Oslo. The United Nations, vastly distasteful of Israel, will make
sure it becomes official. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is re-elected, Palestine
will come about somewhat later, as he insists on strong security
conditions. If Ehud Barak wins, he will be spurred on by Washington
and Western Europe, which back him, not to be security-finicky, but
he will not be their patsy.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The dictatorial nature of Palestine's government is predictable
because of history, past and present. Arabs never produced a
democratic society nor world Islam a liberalizing movement of
moment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last month about 100 Arabs from 15 countries did meet, at great
danger to themselves, to send a cry of Arab rights _ to the world,
which eagerly avoided it, and to their own people, those who
somehow get word past censorship and police. Morocco was the only
Mideast country that would allow them to meet and in which they
felt relatively safe from Arab spies shadowing them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The final statement of the conference included the usual Arab
demonization of Israel _ racist, Zionist, imperialist Israel. Only
a few Arab intellectuals ever are courageous enough to skip that.
But if a man risks one hand for democracy, I suppose you cannot
blame him for not sticking the other in the fire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, the statement deals bravely with the ``grim'' truth
that even whatever scraps of liberties Arabs did hold are
declining. Saudi Arabia and some gulf states, it says, lack even
the symbols of democracy _ no constitution, parliament or modern
legal system. Why bother? Countries that had made progress are
pedaling back _ Tunisia, Egypt, Yemen, Jordan. In Iraq, Syria,
Sudan, Bahrain: ``massive and dangerous human rights violations.''
Only Morocco got some praise for a ``relative improvement'' this
past decade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The statement attacked armed Muslim groups for physical and
intellectual terrorism. Searing the hand deeper, the signers
denounced regimes that used ``Islam's specificity'' as an excuse to
reject reform _ an attack on fundamentalism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is it because of religion that Islam has so miserably failed to
create democracy and tolerate human rights? Maybe, but Catholicism,
Orthodox Christianity, Judaism and particularly Protestantism often
overcame the bigotries and calls for eyeball-plucking in their own
religious histories. They produced democracies by the score.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the reason is in social history as well as religious _
Islamic disdain for rule by majority decisions. Perhaps it is the
absence of the ``legal person'' the West inherited from Roman law _
local governments, colleges, societies, corporations that run their
affairs and can be held responsible, subject to suit.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's borrowed knowledge. But I know all by myself that one
Mideast democracy exists, and would seem to be something to be
cherished by the others. I remain astonished and disgusted that
whenever something happens in Israel not to their liking, European
democracies threaten to cut it back to borders that guarantee its
death. American journalists who proclaim love for Israel screech
that its ethic, morality and legal system are collapsing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I try to explain why I am so troubled about that incessant
denigration of Israel's democracy _ or America's. Prof. Ruth Wisse
of Harvard, at a dinner for that intellectually indispensable
magazine Commentary, found the words in what Jean-Francois Revel
wrote 16 years ago.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Exaggerated self-criticism would be a harmless luxury of
civilization if there were no enemy at the gate. ... But if it is
repeated often enough, it is finally believed. Where will the
citizens of democratic societies find reasons to resist the enemy
outside if they are persuaded from childhood that their
civilization is merely an accumulation of failures, and a monstrous
imposture?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
