<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO REPORTS ON DAMAGE DONE TO YUGOSLAV FORCES IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO said Thursday that its bombing had
destroyed half the Yugoslav army's ammunition stores in Kosovo and
200 tanks and other armored vehicles, artillery pieces, and trucks
_ about 20 percent of all Yugoslav heavy equipment in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz, a spokesman for the allied military
command, predicted that as bombing intensified and the weather
improved, 50 percent of the armored personnel carriers, long-range
guns and other heavy weaponry the 40,000 Yugoslav soldiers, police
and paramilitaries in Kosovo need to continue operations against
ethnic Albanian civilians there would soon be knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mission,'' Jertz said, ``is to pin them down, cut them
off, and take them out. We have pinned them down, we have pretty
much largely cut them off, and we are about to take them out.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials admitted the bombing campaign had failed to stop
the Yugoslav forces in Kosovo from driving most of the 1.8 million
ethnic Albanians in the province out of their homes. But Thursday,
presenting the most comprehensive picture yet of the effects of 43
days of allied air strikes, NATO officials promised that their
attacks would intensify until those forces were destroyed and
international peacekeepers could take hundreds of thousands of
refugees back in.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to dispel the impression that six full weeks of allied
bombing had had no effect at all on the Yugoslav forces that have
driven more than a million people from their homes in Kosovo since
the NATO bombing began March 24, allied officials said that the
bombing would continue until the Yugoslavs were forced to let them
all return in safety, under the protection of an international
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have adapted our tactics to take advantage of a wide
variety of intelligence gathering facilities,'' Jertz said. With
more than 1,000 planes available for air strikes, he said, ``We
have planes circling waiting to respond to targets of opportunity
designated by forward air controllers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
