<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUGOVA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO MUST BE PART OF PEACEKEEPING FORCE, KOSOVAR LEADER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova said Thursday
that NATO must be included in any international force sent to
secure the return of ethnic Albanian refugees to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking softly in French at a news conference in Rome, Rugova,
in his first public remarks since he left Kosovo on Wednesday, said
that ``an international force, NATO and other countries, is a key
condition for the return of the refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   Rugova gave almost no details about his circumstances over the
last six weeks in Yugoslavia, where he had been shown on television
meeting with President Slobodan Milosevic and making conciliatory
statements, prompting NATO leaders to suggest that he was being
coerced. He said he had arrived in Italy to ``rebuild the political
life of our country.'' Rugova added that the withdrawal of Yugoslav
forces and an international presence were ``essential'' to any
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A moderate political leader who describes himself as a pacifist
and who accepted the agreement at Rambouillet, France, Rugova said
his views had not changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent the last 10 years seeking peace and trying to avoid
that Kosovo end up the way it is right now,'' he said. He added
that he would continue to push for a non-violent solution so that
ethnic Albanians and the Serb civilian minority in Kosovo could
``build a future.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps mindful that the Yugoslav authorities would be closely
watching his statements in the West, Rugova did not address the
conditions of his stay in Kosovo, which some have described as
house arrest, or his current views of the bombing campaign. Instead
he suggested that he had remained there to work on a negotiated
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my stay in Kosovo I had contacts with the Serbian
authorities,'' he said. ``We discussed a process for continuing a
political process and creating a climate of trust between us. I
sought steps for a peaceful political future.''
</P>
<P>
   Rugova said he had left Kosovo because he needed to confer with
colleagues who are in exile in Albania and Western Europe. ``I do
not like being in exile, and neither do my people, I am here for
them and to see that an international force in Kosovo can create a
real society in Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, British Defense Secretary George Robertson said
that Foreign Secretary Robin Cook had phoned Rugova to invite him
to London and ``welcome him back to the free world.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the guerrilla force
fighting for independence, have been increasingly critical of
Rugova, whom they say they have replaced as the legitimate voice of
ethnic Albanians. But Rugova insisted that ``I am the elected
representative of the people of Kosovo, and I still represent the
people of Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
