<HEADLINE>
THUMBNAILS ON TORNADO VICTIMS
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: We hope to update) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brief looks at some of those killed in the Oklahoma tornadoes:
</P>
<P>
   Jake Self, 86, Del City
</P>
<P>
   Self was a retired minister who came to the profession late in
life, his son, Phil, said. Known in his later years simply as
``Brother Jake,'' Self grew up in Oklahoma, farming, ranching and
working as an oilman until he had a born-again experience at age
40.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the second half of his life as a Baptist minister, his
son said.
</P>
<P>
   Self died in his house on Darla Drive after a tornado lifted a
van onto the bathroom where he had sought shelter.
Jeffery Yonnes Jr., 4 months, Midwest City
</P>
<P>
   ``J.R.'' was a ``little blond, blue-eyed chubby guy,'' said his
grandfather, John Richmond. He was a good baby who would just lay
there and smile at whomever passed by.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just starting to laugh out loud at you if you tickled
him,'' Richmond said.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. was thrown out of the bathtub after his home on Will Rogers
Road split apart. He was found dead in a neighbor's yard.
Bonnie Price, 46, Bethany
</P>
<P>
   Price was a nurse who loved working with the elderly, whether it
was caring for residents of three nursing home centers in nearby
Kingfisher, Okla., or for her widowed father until his death in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a special talent and a special love to work with
elderly people, and she definitely had that,'' said her older
sister, Alice Redwine.
</P>
<P>
   Price was at her late father's home in Dover, where she had
spent much of her childhood, when Monday's tornado struck. She is
survived by a son, Jeffrey Don Price of McCloud; a granddaughter,
Natasha; three sisters; and a brother.
Molly Kughn, 76, Guthrie
</P>
<P>
   Kughn wasn't slowed by her age.
</P>
<P>
   In her later years, the widow kept busy, attending church
regularly, joining every club she could and working at the youth
center in the Abell community that she had called home for 23
years. On Monday Kughn's son, Gary, called his mother and told her
to go to the storm cellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said `no, the cellar had water in it.' She decided to ride
the storm out,'' said her sister, Fayola Ambrose, 78.
</P>
<P>
   After the storm passed a neighbor tried to check on Kughn. He
sawed through a large tree that had fallen on the home but could
not find her in the rubble. She was later found in the nearby
pasture.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Ann Arthur, 51, Midwest City
</P>
<P>
   Arthur, who had a heart transplant in July 1997, sang soprano in
the Hillcrest Christian Church choir, delivered meals to the
elderly and was a member of the Christian Women's Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very active for somebody who had health problems
herself,'' said friend and fellow church member Linda Hill. Arthur
was friendly and outgoing and loved ceramics, cake decorating and
working with the youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first things I noticed about her is, she had very
beautiful fingernails, and she always painted each fingernail a
different color. She was that kind of person,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   When the tornado hit, Arthur was seeking shelter in a closet of
her home with her husband and mother, both of whom survived. Hill
said Arthur's husband, Melvin, returned Wednesday to find the house
destroyed but a few items untouched.
</P>
<P>
   His glasses sat on the bathroom cabinet. ``The china cabinet was
still sitting there with the china inside, and nothing was
broken,'' Hill said.
Kara Wiese, mid-20s, Bridge Creek
</P>
<P>
   Kara Wiese's world evolved around her 6-year-old son, Jordan,
family members said.
</P>
<P>
   The single mother was clutching her son tightly in the bathroom
when the tornado's strong winds ripped the family's mobile home
apart. Jordan was thrown into a nearby ravine and quickly sought
out a neighbor to help search for his missing mother.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese was identified yesterday through fingerprints that her
mother had saved from her daughter's school days.
Others, including locations where their bodies were found:
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Battaglia, 37, Norman
</P>
<P>
   Esther Louella Coburn, 35, Moore
</P>
<P>
   Asheton M. Darnell, 3 weeks, Bridge Creek
</P>
<P>
   Bill Doty, 54, Oklahoma City PNoah Fish, age unknown, Del City
</P>
<P>
   Naomi R. Greaser, 59, Tuttle PJohn Green, unknown PDavid Henry,
36, Oklahoma City PLinda B. Hogan, 50, Oklahoma City
</P>
<P>
   Charles R. Keithline IV, 24, Oklahoma City PMolly Kughn, 76,
Guthrie PLeona M. Lucas, 41, Blanchard PWilliam Lucas III, 39,
Blanchard
</P>
<P>
   Allen D. McClure, 45, Stillwater PGustia Miller, 75, Del City
PHelen Moore, 46, Dover
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Payne, 49, Midwest City
</P>
<P>
   Ralph C. Payne, 80, Midwest City PBonnie Price, 46, unknown
</P>
<P>
   James A. Rawlings, 73, Bridge Creek
</P>
<P>
   Naomi J. Rawlings, 73, Bridge Creek PJames Russell Reeves, 33,
Norman
</P>
<P>
   Danette H. Rodgers, 30, Moore PHerbert G.J. Self, 86, Del City
