<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-ESCAPE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBORS FIND SAFETY IN SHELTER JUST BEFORE TORNADO ROARS THROUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORE, Okla. _ In a scene that could have been written for the
movie ``Twister,'' Sheila Meadows and her family risked their
safety to save the lives of eight neighbors who outran Monday's
tornado and made it to the Meadows' storm shelter with less than a
minute to spare.
</P>
<P>
   Meadows lived in a four-bedroom home at 620 N.W. 21st St. The
house, like most on the street, isn't there anymore. When Meadows
heard the tornado warning early Monday evening, she and her
teen-age daughters, Christina and Nikki, and 6-year-old son,
Victor, climbed into their shelter several feet underground.
</P>
<P>
   Meadows' husband is in the Army and stationed in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The Meadows were joined by four others, and all were nervously
waiting for the tornado to pass when they heard someone fiercely
pounding on the door. Two of the men in the shelter opened the door
and were greeted by one of Meadows' neighbors, who motioned to
seven others running from a tornado now visible and gaining on
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to climb over a chain-link fence, and the fence kept
rising up,'' Meadows said. ``One of my neighbor's daughters was
almost being blown away as they were helping her get over the
fence.''
</P>
<P>
   The wind was getting stronger and threatening to knock the door
off its chain latches as the eight neighbors struggled to reach
shelter. One by one, they climbed down the concrete stairs and
huddled close _ 16 people in a shelter built for eight.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the door was closed and secured. ``Then it got real
loud,'' Meadows said. ``The tornado hit and everything was shaking.
But we made it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
