A7347 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-06 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRIAL POWERS PROPOSE KOSOVO PEACE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In what many described as an important
diplomatic breakthrough, the world's biggest industrialized nations
and Russia Thursday agreed on a plan they say could end the
conflict in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the foreign ministers from the so-called Group of
Eight industrial powers were hailing their framework for an armed
international force in Kosovo, all sides stressed that wide gaps
remain between NATO and the Russians, who are sympathetic to their
fellow Orthodox Christian Slavs in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   For example, NATO wants a total withdrawal of Serb forces from
Kosovo while the Russians are talking about a partial withdrawal.
And NATO insists that its troops must be at the core of any
peacekeeping mission inserted into Kosovo, while the Russians say
it must be United Nations-led.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers of NATO countries, including Secretary of
State Madeleine K. Albright, called the plan a breakthrough. Igor
Ivanov, the Russian foreign minister, was more circumspect, saying,
``it would be premature to speak of a breakthrough, but progress
has been made.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, just a month after Russian politicians were warning that
the conflict between NATO and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
could start World War III, the joint statement of the G-8 countries
meeting outside Bonn was widely welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, Belgrade permitted the return of UN
relief agencies to Kosovo, and UN Secretary General Kofi Annan said
he would send a mission to assess the situation. UN agencies left
Kosovo before the start of the NATO air campaign on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy said diplomats from the
``G-8'' countries will confer over the next few days to draft a UN
resolution to back the plan. The G-8 countries are the United
States, Germany, France, Britain, Russia, Canada, Italy and Japan.
Only Russia and Japan are not part of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   There was no official response from the Yugoslav government, but
in what some were taking as a hopeful sign official Serb media
Thursday night quoted Milosevic saying that he could pull his
troops out of Kosovo in a week if the bombing stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Ending his two-day visit to Belgium and Germany, President
Clinton called the G-8 plan ``a significant step forward.'' Clinton
said the plan increased ``the likelihood that there will ultimately
be a resolution of this that will actually work.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton and other NATO country leaders insisted the bombing
would go on until Milosevic agreed to NATO's demands, which differ
from the G-8 plan only on the insistence that the peacekeeping
force have NATO ``at its core.'' Frustrated Russian diplomats
believe there would be a quick settlement if NATO stopped bombing
and let Milosevic save some face.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth straight day, the Yugoslav capital Belgrade was
not bombed, what some saw as a meager gesture to keep the
diplomatic momentum moving forward. Another gesture, some said, was
Milosevic's decision to let the moderate ethnic Albanian leader
Ibrahim Rugova to leave for Italy on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meanwhile, said Thursday that he believed that a
resolution of the conflict could come about even if Milosevic
remained in power _ a stunning admission given the heated rhetoric
from Clinton and other NATO leaders about Milosevic being a war
criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Keen to isolate Milosevic and bring the Russians closer to their
position, the western allies approved a statement that did not
mention NATO as being part of the peacekeeping force that everyone
agrees is needed to convince ethnic Albanian refugees to return
there after being forcefully expelled by the Serbs. In another
concession to Russian opinion, the G-8 will formally inform China
of their plan. China frequently votes with Russia against the west
in the UN.
</P>
<P>
   The plan talks of deploying ``effective international civil and
security presences, endorsed and adopted by the United Nations,
capable of guaranteeing the achievement of the common objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   But foreign ministers from NATO countries insisted they had not
compromised on having a heavily-armed international force to keep
the peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This must mean a strong military force with NATO at its
core,'' said Albright.
</P>
<P>
   The German foreign minister Joschka Fischer, who hosted the
two-hour talks Thursday, said that ``without robust military
presence, nothing will be achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Minister Robin Cook said refugees would not
return unless the protection afforded them was credible, not the
light arms of typical UN peacekeeping missions.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian diplomats were trying to persuade the NATO nations
to compromise on their insistence to lead the peacekeeping force,
saying it will give NATO their victory, and Milosevic his way out.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the peacekeeping force, the plan calls for an immediate
and verifiable end to violence and repression in Kosovo; withdrawal
of Serb forces from Kosovo; establishment by the UN of an interim
administration in Kosovo; the return of refugees, and a political
process to disarm the separatist Kosovo Liberation Army in return
for giving Kosovo ``substantial self-government.''
</P>
<P>
   But that last point insists that Kosovo remain part of
Yugoslavia, which ethnic Albanians are unlikely to accept given
what they say Serb forces have done in ethnically cleansing them
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent progress in diplomatic talks added fuel to another
dispute over Kosovo _ that between NATO and the KLA, which long
pleaded for a NATO intervention. Jakup Krasniqi, spokesman for the
KLA and its self-proclaimed government of Kosova, said any
international force in Kosovo should be led by NATO _ not the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is NATO that should command and control any force that is
sent to Kosovo _ not any other force outside NATO is acceptable,''
Krasniqi said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the KLA will not disarm, despite the fact that
demilitarization of the KLA was one of the key elements of the
Rambouillet agreement, which collapsed when Milosevic refused to
allow foreign troops in Kosovo to enforce the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all that has happened in Kosovo in the past months, we
cannot disarm the KLA,'' Krasniqi said. ``The circumstances under
which the KLA would agree to disarm do not exist, and I do not
think they will ever exist in the Balkans. Such a demand is
completely unjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Krasniqi also said the KLA was committed to independence, which
the West has opposed, but said they were open to having Kosovo as a
protectorate.
</P>
<P>
   While Milosevic has been largely blamed by the West for the
failure of peace talks earlier this year, the KLA also held up the
agreement. The rogue army was the last holdout on the Albanian
delegation side, and has said it will not give up its weapons, even
if there is a peacekeeping force in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The division among ethnic Albanians _ one which dragged out the
talks and threatened their implementation on the ground _ still
exists, even while they are at war with the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA has declared one government, headed by KLA leader Hasem
Thaqi, while the more moderate wing of the Albanian rebellion has
declared Bujar Bukoshi as its leader-in-exile.
</P>
<P>
   Bukoshi is closer to the thinking of Rugova. Many Albanians are
still loyal to Rugova, who for a decade led a non-violent effort to
free Kosovar Albanians from Serb oppression. But an strong group of
Albanains now despises Rugova, saying the KLA's violent rebellion
is the only solution. Speaking Thursday in Rome, where he met with
Italian prime minister D'Alema, Rugova said he wanted an
international force that included NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The schism bodes poorly for political stability in Kosovo after
the fighting is over. But Krasniqi said the KLA would not fight the
Western soldiers to get their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KLA would not fight against the peacekeepers,'' he said.
``The KLA has an enemy to fight already.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Staff writer Milligan reported from Albania.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
