<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wachovia appoints new chief for Georgia
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wachovia Bank has named Isaiah Tidwell president of
its Georgia operations. The bank becomes the second major financial
institution in recent months to name a minority executive to
oversee its business in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Tidwell, 54, formerly the regional executive in charge of the
Charlotte, N.C., area, is the bank's highest ranking
African-American executive. In March, Bank of America, which still
operates under the NationsBank name in Georgia, named a minority
executive, Michael H. Dulan, to be president of its Georgia
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Tidwell's appointment follows a series of management changes at
Wachovia that began when G. Joseph Prendergast, formerly the top
Atlanta-based executive with the bank, this year was named
president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Tidwell succeeds D. Gary Thompson, 52, who now is CEO for the
bank in Georgia and Florida. Tidwell will report to Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``His coming will help us continue what has been very good
growth in this market,'' said Thompson, who added that Atlanta,
Charlotte, Tampa, Fla., and Richmond, Va., are viewed as strong
growth markets for Wachovia.
</P>
<P>
   Tidwell, a native of Charlotte, has spent virtually all his
26-year banking career with Wachovia in North Carolina. He became a
regional vice president in 1990, assuming responsibility for
Charlotte and Mecklenburg County, home of the corporate
headquarters of both NationsBank and First Union, both aggressive
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it quite stimulating,'' Tidwell said. ``You wake up in
the morning, and there's no question who the competition is. You
just look at the office towers.''
</P>
<P>
   When he moves to Atlanta by early June, Tidwell said he
understands that his job will be ``growing the bank rapidly and
very profitably.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is an important market for Wachovia, representing about
30 percent of its revenue. Wachovia operates in 27 Georgia counties
and has 135 branches, 90 of them in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In his new role, Tidwell said he intends to get involved in the
community. In Charlotte he was a past chairman of the Afro-American
Cultural Center board and past treasurer of the Charlotte Chamber
of Commerce. He also is a past chair of the Charlotte/Mecklenburg
Education Foundation, a former general campaign chairman of the
United Way of Forsyth County and its president in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
