<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-ENTERTAIN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV screens hit minivans for movie watching, games
 &HT;    By Karl Ritzler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a cross-country automobile trip in the '50s _
before freeways and air conditioning _ my sister and I amused and
annoyed each other by playing license-plate bingo, staring at
endless stretches of scenery and making funny noises.
</P>
<P>
   A generation later, my own three kids amused and annoyed each
other on road trips _ thankfully on freeways and with air
conditioning _ by hogging the seats, playing the alphabet game and
making funny noises.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just in time for road trips with grandchildren, automakers
have found a way to amuse the back-seat passengers the whole way _
with movies and video games. And I don't mean movie soundtrack
tapes or hand-held Gameboys. These are real movies on videotape and
full-action games with a TV screen on which to play them.
</P>
<P>
   Oldsmobile was first out of the blocks with its Silhouette
Premiere minivan equipped with a factory-installed pop-down TV
screen and a bank of controls for the videotape, game, radio and CD
players.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. isn't far behind. A rear-seat entertainment
system that will play movies or video games is an option on Ford
Windstar and Mercury Villager minivans. The console-mounted system
built by Ford unit Visteon will be available for all automakers'
minivans, sport-utility vehicles and conventional vans by the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   A DaimlerChrysler spokesman said the automaker has no plans to
add a similar option in its segment-leading minivans, explaining
that the company is looking at the technology but is concerned
about the cost.
</P>
<P>
   In an affinity marketing campaign, Oldsmobile is teaming with
the American Film Institute, Sony and Blockbuster for an
interlocking tour and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   AFI recently brought its touring collection of movie memorabilia
and props to Northlake Mall. Blockbuster is stocking some of the
AFI's best 100 movies of the past century. Oldsmobile dealerships
might have a movie theme for the Silhouette in the showroom.
Prospects who test drive the minivan get $25 gift cards, funded by
Oldsmobile, for Blockbuster movies. Sony shows off its DVD
technology at the AFI display and is marketing its video games to
minivan buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Rainbolt, assistant brand manager for Silhouette, said the
minivan's entertainment system is the first one on the market to be
fully integrated into the vehicle. Aftermarket systems have been
available for years.
</P>
<P>
   She said it is designed to keep everybody happy.
</P>
<P>
   The controls for the video, CD and radio are in both the front
and back. When the radio is off, sound for the video systems comes
through the speakers. But turn the radio on, and headphones are
needed for video or CD listening. That way, front passengers can
enjoy their music while one rear-seat passenger rocks to a CD and
the other blasts space aliens on the video screen.
</P>
<P>
   The liquid crystal display monitor, mounted on the roof just
behind the front seats, flips up and out of the way when not in
use. Even when it's down, it doesn't block the rearview mirror. The
rear controls are mounted alongside the screen and include a
universal adapter for video games.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment system is part of the Silhouette's Premiere
package, which includes a whole menu of extras. It has a sticker
price of $31,680, about $3,500 more than the base price of the
next-lower-priced minivan.
</P>
<P>
   GM is beginning to install the entertainment center _ covered by
the factory warranty _ in the Pontiac Montana and eventually will
add it to the Chevrolet Venture.
</P>
<P>
   GM officials say sales of the Silhouette have exceeded
expectations. The company hopes to sell more than 40,000
Silhouettes this year, about one-third of them with the Premiere
package.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's Visteon system is mounted in a console between the front
seats. The $1,299 system can be ordered with a new vehicle, where
it is installed as the vehicle comes out of the assembly plant, or
added to an older vehicle at a Ford or Mercury dealership, said
Mark Horvath, a marketing specialist with Visteon. Installations in
other vehicles may be through auto dealers or audio stores, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The setup is integrated for automobile use, but it also can be
removed when the owner changes vehicles. A Nintendo 64 system is
part of the package, but other game systems also can be used. The
videotape player is part of the console, and the whole thing can
operate with or independently of the vehicle's audio system.
</P>
<P>
   Sales data were not available yet, but Horvath anticipates
Visteon will sell all the systems it can supply.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, though, license-plate bingo will never be the same if
the driver has to play it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
