<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDA-BAMA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Honda picks Alabama for $400 million plant
 &HT;    By Karl Ritzler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ After months of secret negotiations, Honda
made it official, announcing it will build an auto and engine plant
on 1,350 acres off Interstate 20 near Lincoln, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Construction on the 1.7 million square foot, $400 million plant
will begin in mid-2000. The plant will build either minivans or
sport-utility vehicles and employ about 1,500 people.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia economic development officials, who earlier acknowledged
that Honda had considered Georgia, expressed optimism that the
plant's economic benefits will ripple into this state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Honda officials would have given a stronger look at
Georgia,'' said Tim Chason, the Georgia Chamber of Commerce's chief
operating officer. ``I still look at it as an opportunity for our
state to compete for the suppliers to Honda.''
</P>
<P>
   Chason suggested that although there are no glaring
deficiencies, the state needs to review how competitive its
economic incentives are for car makers. Gov. Roy Barnes has
promised to review the state's overall industrial incentives this
year. Georgia's incentives have been viewed as conservative
compared to other states.
</P>
<P>
   Honda made no mention of other states it considered for the
plant.
</P>
<P>
   The company chose the Alabama site because of the ``outstanding
community of people, excellent transportation systems and the
necessary infrastructure to support industry,'' said Koichi
Amemiya, president and chief executive officer of American Honda
Motor Co., Honda's North American subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   More than $158 million in tax abatements and incentives from
Alabama and local governments helped, too.
</P>
<P>
   The major incentives include the $16 million site, the state is
providing $55.6 million in tax breaks, a $30 million training
program and about $45 million in improvements _ mostly roads _
around the site.
</P>
<P>
   That compares with an estimated $325 million the state used to
bring the Mercedes-Benz sport-utility plant to Vance., Ala., in the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Don Siegelman welcomed the company, saying in Japanese,
``Our friendship will last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman said the incentives offered to Honda were the same
that would be offered to any major company coming to Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the plant builds a new sport-utility or the company's
Odyssey minivan will depend on market conditions over the next few
years, said Richard E. Colliver, executive vice president with
American Honda. The plant will be capable of building both.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Alliston, Ontario, minivan plant is unable to keep
up with demand he said. While the minivan and sport-utility market
has grown rapidly, Honda hasn't been able to keep up, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jeff Schuster with J.D. Power in Michigan said a new
Honda SUV would replace the company's current Honda Passport and
Acura SLX. Both are built for Honda in Indiana by Isuzu. Schuster
said Honda wants to improve the quality of vehicles carrying its
names.
</P>
<P>
   Honda said it will hire most of the workers locally. The company
will begin accepting applications in late 2000, and hiring will
begin in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Wages will be competitive, officials said. In Ohio, the pay at
Honda assembly plants is about $20 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The plant is unusual because it will build both vehicles and
engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a manufacturing viewpoint, the new plant in Alabama is a
different approach. In Ohio, vehicle and engine production are
housed in different plants.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, we will combine them into one efficient plant,''
said Koki Hirashima, CEO of Honda of American Manufacturing. The
V-6 engines will be built from recycled aluminum ingots, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said it was too early to determine what suppliers
will be used. Generally, suppliers locate near an assembly plant to
facilitate just-in-time delivery of parts.
</P>
<P>
   Hirashima pointed out, ``We don't decide which suppliers will
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
