<HEADER>
A7353 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIMEWARNER07-COX     05-06 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMEWARNER07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T's deal likely to benefit Time Warner
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Time Warner is not part of AT&AMP;T's tentative purchase
of MediaOne, but the 800-pound gorilla of the media business could
score big in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   That's because a change in MediaOne's ownership would eliminate
a quarrelsome partner for Time Warner. It also would create a
potential opportunity for Time Warner to regain full control of its
highly valuable entertainment assets.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne owns 25.5 percent of Time Warner Entertainment, a
venture that owns Warner Bros. TV and movie studios, premium cable
TV channel HBO and Time Warner Cable. Time Warner owns the
remaining 74.5 percent of the venture.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner Entertainment has been a venture marked by
often-bitter quarreling among the partners. But now, with the
potential entry of AT&AMP;T, the chemistry of the venture is poised to
change.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Time Warner declined to comment on its entertainment
venture or AT&AMP;T's tentative deal to buy MediaOne, the third-largest
cable TV operator, for $62 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company's only comment has been a statement by Chairman
Gerald Levin, which applauded how Comcast President Brian Roberts
handled himself in his losing bid for MediaOne. Roberts and Levin
have long been close allies and friends.
</P>
<P>
   While quiet publicly, Time Warner is closely studying AT&AMP;T's
deal. The company sees plenty of opportunity on a variety of
fronts, depending on how the final deal is structured.
</P>
<P>
   The deal must also win federal regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and Time Warner are not strangers. Months ago, the
companies struck a tentative deal for AT&AMP;T to provide local
telephone service through Time Warner's digital cable networks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the companies each control a cable modem service
that provides high-speed access to the Internet through digital
cable TV networks. Time Warner's service is called Road Runner and
AT&AMP;T's At Home. The two services are not direct competitors because
they serve separate markets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet both AT&AMP;T and Time Warner could cut costs and strengthen
marketing of cable modems by combining or forming a strategic
partnership between Road Runner and At Home.
</P>
<P>
   But where AT&AMP;T as MediaOne's new owner could help Time Warner
the most is in the entertainment venture. The venture was created
in the early 1990s as a way for Time Warner to help finance the
high cost of reconfiguring its cable systems as digital networks.
</P>
<P>
   That involved selling off stakes in Time Warner's entertainment
assets to a variety of companies, including what was then U S West.
U S West eventually spun off its cable assets into MediaOne, which
also held the company's stake in Time Warner Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been a collegial partnership. The two quarreled from
the start, the battles intensifying in recent years. Time Warner,
for example, never notified MediaOne that it would make a bid for
Atlanta-based Turner Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting is now a unit of Time Warner, and MediaOne
has resisted several of the unit's big initiatives. MediaOne, for
instance, has refused to pay a price increase for carrying Turner
Broadcasting's TNT cable TV channel. It also won't pay new fees to
carry sister channel TBS, although almost every other cable TV
operator does.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Time Warner wouldn't mind finding a new
partner for its entertainment venture. But some industry observers
also wonder whether the venture has outlived its purpose. Time
Warner, after all, has completed much of the expensive rebuilding
of its networks.
</P>
<P>
   While Time Warner won't comment, some industry observers believe
the company may seek to buy back the 25.5 percent of its
entertainment assets outside its control. Indeed, the company has
been moving in that direction for years, having bought out every
other partner except MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   But will AT&AMP;T be ready to sell off MediaOne's stake in Time
Warner Entertainment? Only time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
