<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-FUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRISTOL-MYERS PLEDGES $100 MILLION TO AIDS FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unprecedented effort by a private corporation to stem the
AIDS epidemic and provide care for its poorest victims, a leading
US-based pharmaceutical company Thursday pledged $100 million over
the next five years to fight AIDS in five hard-hit African nations.
</P>
<P>
   The contribution, by Bristol-Myers Squibb Co., will fund
programs to prevent new AIDS-virus infections and to provide care,
including drug treatment, to a region where 3.5 million people _
more than 7 percent of the population _ are already infected. Few
can afford the costly drugs used to treat the disease in developed
nations.
</P>
<P>
   The additional $20 million a year amounts to a 14 percent jump
in total AIDS funding in sub-Saharan Africa, where currently only
about $140 million is available to fight the disease. South Africa,
Botswana, Namibia, Lesotho, and Swaziland will share the funds.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Piot, director of UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS
agency, said he hoped the drug company's move ``will be imitated by
more multinational companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The new money will be targeted in part to programs to improve
care for women and children in nations where 16 to 36 percent of
pregnant women carry the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), which
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Recent research has shown drugs given during pregnancy can cut
in half the rate of HIV transmission from mother to infant at a
cost of about $80 per case. But providing such treatment requires a
chain of support services seldom found in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot parachute the drugs into these countries. We need
the infrastructure to deliver care,'' said Dr. Joseph Saba of
UNAIDS, who has campaigned vigorously for drug company
contributions. ``We need well-trained doctors and nurses;
laboratory facilities for people to get tested; pharmacies where
the drugs can be made available and managed properly. We need
patients to be aware of the treatments they need and how to take
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Combined with a $25 million pledge this week by Microsoft's
William Gates to support AIDS vaccine research, the Bristol-Myers
Squibb contribution heartened activists who have recently worried
about a decline in AIDS-fighting support in this country and
abroad. ``It indicates a dramatic rise in interest in the global
pandemic,'' said Daniel Zingale, executive director of AIDS Action,
a Washington-based advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice to hear these things years ago,'' said
Jacob A. Gayle Jr., the UNAIDS liaison to the World Bank, who spoke
Thursday night at a Boston forum on African AIDS sponsored by the
21st Century Group, an organization of black professionals.
``However, hopefully 20 years hence we'll look back and say this
contribution began a whole new era of response to this epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bristol-Myers Squibb chairman and chief executive, Charles
A. Hiembold Jr., said the $18.3 billion-a-year firm felt ``a moral
obligation to take action against this grave situation.'' But
company executives and consultants noted that the step will serve
the drug firm's commercial interests as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty. I think the company will benefit from this,''
said Barry Scott, vice president of Bristol-Myers Squibb's
international division. ``I don't know how.. . .But I'd be avoiding
the obvious to say there would be no effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Marlink of the Harvard AIDS Institute, who will
serve on a scientific advisory board for the new project, said the
contribution ``will buy goodwill. It may open doors. If I were in
the upper reaches of a pharmaceutical company very involved in AIDS
drugs, I would note that this epidemic is growing, and it's
disproportionately affecting southern Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb makes three leading AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Like other AIDS-drug manufacturers, it has recently been alarmed
by threats from some African nations to manufacture cheap,
unauthorized versions of costly AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to South Africa's health minister, Dr. Nkosazana Zuma,
Scott added: ``Certainly we are challenging the health minister on
intellectual properties issues and we will continue to challenge
her on it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scott said those threats ``did not enter into'' the
company's decision to contribute $100 million to South Africa and
four neighboring countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
