<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBOLA-LIKE DISEASE IDENTIFIED AS CAUSE OF 59 DEATHS IN CONGO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Congo, Zimbabwe, South Africa, Kenya)   By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The disease that has killed 59 people in
northeastern Congo is caused not by Ebola but by a similar virus
that is nearly as deadly but not as contagious, doctors reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marc Biot, of the medical group Doctors Without Borders,
said a blood sample from one victim who died showed the disease to
be caused by the Marburg virus, named after the city in Germany
where it first appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ebola, the virus causes high fevers and heavy bleeding but
is not transmitted as easily to other people, Biot said. There is
no cure.
</P>
<P>
   A team of doctors from Doctors Without Borders traveled this
week to the town of Durba in Congo, near the border both with Sudan
and Uganda, to investigate the deaths. Nearly all of the victims
have been miners who work illegally in a closed gold mine, living
together in filthy conditions and drinking water that drips from
the mine.
</P>
<P>
   Biot said that 76 people might have been infected, and that most
of them worked in the mine. But he said the number of cases did not
appear to be spreading outside that group, though doctors are still
interviewing people in the area. An exception was a doctor who died
after treating the miners; his blood tested positive for the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might cautiously say that this is not a very large
epidemic,'' Biot said.
</P>
<P>
   The symptoms are similar to those caused by Ebola, the most
deadly of the so-called hemorrhagic fevers. In 1995, 244 people
were killed in an outbreak of Ebola in the city of Kikwit, in
western Congo.
</P>
<P>
   But laboratory tests conducted in South Africa showed it to be
Marburg disease, which Biot said had never infected a large number
of people outside a laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one people were infected by the disease in a laboratory
in Marburg in 1967, in an outbreak believed to be caused by a group
of African monkeys there. Biot said that nearly a quarter of the
people had died, and that much smaller, recent outbreaks in
Zimbabwe and Kenya had claimed more victims.
</P>
<P>
   Victims of the disease suffer from early symptoms that resemble
malaria _ headache, as well as fever and pains in joints and
muscles. On the second day, diarrhea and vomiting begin, and soon
blood appears in both. Death usually occurs on the sixth day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
