<HEADER>
A7365 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCHS07-COX     05-06 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Churchs seeking female franchisees
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Women like Bridget Chisholm who are interested in
franchising are getting a helping hand from Atlanta-based Churchs
Chicken.
</P>
<P>
   The company, a division of AFC Enterprises, announced Thursday a
new program aimed at increasing the ranks of female franchisees and
diversity in its restaurant system. The Churchs Professional
Mentoring Program, which will initially last about a year, will be
launched this month during a restaurant industry trade show in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Chisholm, a Memphis, Tenn., businesswoman, is among three women
who have the rights to develop four Churchs restaurants in the
city. ``This program will help women know that opportunities are
out there,'' Chisholm said.
</P>
<P>
   By 2000, about 80 percent of all new businesses will be owned by
women, but females will head only 10 percent of franchises, said
Hala Moddelmog, president of 1,400-unit Churchs and one of the
highest-ranking women in the quick-service restaurant industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real gap there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 20 percent of Churchs franchisees in the United
States are women, a number Moddelmog would like to see grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've definitely done a better job than others, but we realize
that there's opportunity to dig into why women are not going into
franchising,'' she said. Reasons include access to capital and a
perception that franchising does not lend itself to creativity.
</P>
<P>
   The program is designed to address both issues. Moddelmog said
she hopes to match women with investment capital with women who are
interested in running franchises. Additionally, she wants to
establish a mentoring program.
</P>
<P>
   Although Churchs is starting the program, the hope is that other
AFC divisions will use similar approaches and eventually it will
spread throughout the industry. Other divisions include Popeyes
Chicken &AMP; Biscuits and Cinnabon International.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Rosenthal, a spokesman for the Maryland-based National
Foundation for Women Business, said the program will help more
women enter the ranks of entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any program that recognizes the expertise and significant
economic clout of women is a good program,'' Rosenthal said.
``While women business owners have made significant progress within
the last decade, there are still some challenges in respect to
access to capital and in general with women-owned firms being taken
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago kickoff, which will be held May 24, is accessible
via the Internet. Participants can access the forum at
www.churchs.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
