r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-NOTES07-COX     05-06 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Publishers jump on NASCAR bandwagon
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Publishers used to believe auto racing fans didn't
read books. A few wondered aloud if they could read at all. For
years, stock car racing was considered by some to be a blue-collar
event where hard-drinking good ol' boys made fools of themselves in
the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Books on auto racing suddenly are a hot commodity among New York
publishers. ``There's a huge market out there for books on
NASCAR,'' says Ed Hinton, a Sports Illustrated staffer who recently
signed a $231,000 deal with Warner to write a book on racing at
Daytona, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the interest, Hinton says, is that the
demographics have changed significantly in the past 10 years. ``The
income and educational level of the fans is way up. My wife and I
went to Talladega and sat in the grandstand recently, and we were
astounded at how quiet the crowd was. NASCAR is being overrun by
nice people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinton, 50, a former Atlanta Journal-Constitution writer who
lives in Cumming, says his book will be a combination of stories
about the drivers and a history of the sport. ``What I did in the
proposal was to write a sampling of the kinds of stories I sit
around and tell people. It's going to be about a rollicking bunch
of guys and the mischief they got into.''
</P>
<P>
   The book won't be finished until next winter, but Hinton has
already been besieged by Hollywood producers anxious to make a
deal. ``Last weekend I met with a guy who's interested in a six- to
10-part HBO miniseries, and another guy who's interested in making
a big, epic film and wants to get started right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Why all the interest in racing? Tom Cruise's 1990 movie ``Days
of Thunder,'' the emergence of driver Jeff Gordon as a sexy
superstar, and the number of cable channels that carry racing may
all be factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Bobby Cox and a lot of the Braves watch racing on
TV after the games,'' Hinton says. ``And attendance at races has
doubled since 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   AT WIT'S END: When Margaret Edson's play ``Wit'' won the
Pulitzer Prize, publishers Faber and Faber suddenly found
themselves in an embarrassing situation. Since play scripts
published as books rarely sell well, the company had printed only a
few thousand copies of the $12 paperback. Amazon.com quickly sold
out and Faber and Faber had to rush back to press for more copies
of the 37-year-old Atlanta kindergarten teacher's play about a
woman's confrontation with terminal illness.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Edson's fellow Pulitzer winner Michael Cunningham is
reaping the benefits of the prize as well. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux
has gone back to press twice with ``The Hours,'' for a total of
115,000 copies. This has been a good year for Cunningham, who also
won the PEN/Faulkner Award for fiction and the American Library
Association's Gay, Lesbian and Bisexual Award.
</P>
<P>
   IRISH ROOTS: Frank Gannon is hoping some of the luck of the
Irish that Frank McCourt enjoyed with ``Angela's Ashes'' will rub
off on him. The Demorest humorist and essayist has signed a
six-figure deal with Warner Books to write a nonfiction book with a
first-generation Irish theme. ``The book is about me, as a
middle-aged guy, realizing that even though both of his parents
were born in Ireland, he knows nothing about his Irishness,'' says
Gannon, the author of ``Yo, Poe!'' and a contributor to GQ and The
New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of Gannon's parents talked about the old country, so
he's having to do a lot of detective work in Ireland and on Ellis
Island. ``I'm finding out that my dad, in a strange way, hated
Ireland. Anything that reminded him of the farm life he had back
there, he blocked out. Almost every day since I started the book,
I've found something that either made me laugh very hard, made me
angry or made me feel like crying.'' Gannon expects to finish the
book in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   MORE PRIZES: The New Yorker magazine is launching yet another
literary competition. The prestigious magazine will award $10,000
in each of five categories: lifetime achievement, fiction,
nonfiction, poetry and best first work. Nominees will be listed in
the last issue of the year and winners _ selected by readers _ will
be announced on Feb. 14, 2000, on the magazine's 75th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Edson
</P>
<P>
   One line of headline goes in this space hereg
</P>
<P>
   DThursday, May 6, 1999 HH The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
