<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7367 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-ELECTION07-COX     05-06 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-ELECTION07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biting, funny film about politics transcends its high school
class
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You might be laughing too hard to notice, at first, the
melancholy edges of ``Election,'' a high school satire from the
director of ``Citizen Ruth.'' Unlike the dozen other teen flicks at
the mall, the film has a grip on the kind of mundane reality that
usually gets exiled from mainstream movies. It's a broad comedy
grounded with precise anthropological observation _ a combination
that can make you both giggle and wince.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Broderick plays Jim McAllister, a Nebraska schoolteacher
who really, really loves his job. His chipper, cheery notion of a
peaceful status quo is exactly what the movie sets out to upset.
``It wasn't just a job for me,'' he says in voice-over. ``I got
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, he becomes too involved, thanks to student Tracy
Flick (Reese Witherspoon), whose perky persona masks a ruthless
lust for power. Her latest target: presidency of the student
government. Tracy goes out for everything, whether it's acting in
the school production of ``Fiddler on the Roof'' or reporting news
blurbs for the student TV station. ``I volunteered for every
committee, as long as I could lead it,'' she says in her own
voice-over.
</P>
<P>
   Letting us into the heads of both these characters, the movie
clues us in to director Alexander Payne's bigger issue.
``Election'' takes a skeptical look at the idea of ``truth'' by
showing us the same situation, ``Rashomon''-style, from different
perspectives. Additional points of view come from two other
students, the popular jock Paul (Chris Klein) and his lesbian kid
sister Tammy (Jessica Campbell). They constitute a round-robin
chorus of self-deluded rationalizations.
</P>
<P>
   They're all involved in the presidential race, thanks to Jim. He
urges Paul to run against the unopposed Tracy. Tammy also enters
the race in anger when she finds out that her ex-girlfriend is now
dating her brother. (Fair warning: The story is driven by the
characters' libidos, resulting in some frank sexual scenes and
dialogue.)
</P>
<P>
   The film's unspoken idea is that nobody really enters politics
for the good of their constituents; a personal agenda is the glue
that holds up campaign posters. In ``Election'' we watch the
characters (well, except for Paul, who's too dim to scheme) break
rules and lie to get what they want. It's one of the movie's balder
jokes that Jim teaches his students the difference between ethics
and morals, even as his vendetta against Tracy blurs his own
integrity, at school and at home.
</P>
<P>
   While the plot makes ``Election'' sound like a bouncy comedy,
it's really a bittersweet ode to the everyday lies people tell
themselves to justify their actions. Payne, shooting in his native
Nebraska, uncovers a plaintive beauty in the bland, blue-gray
landscape that underscores his cruelly funny tone.
</P>
<P>
   In the supporting cast, Klein delivers an endearing goofiness,
speaking in the awed tones of a guy educated on self-help manuals;
he makes Keanu Reeves look like a Fulbright scholar. Campbell is
terrific as Tammy, whose clear-eyed self-interest marks her as the
character most likely to succeed in life, if not in school. Her
bluntly practical platform for the presidency is one of the movie's
highlights, as she tells the other students, ``Vote for me because
I don't even want to go to college, and I don't care!''
</P>
<P>
   As a decent guy who gets in over his head, Broderick is ideal,
lending both his boyish charisma and memories of his 1986 screen
role as class cutter Ferris Bueller. Witherspoon is a perfect foil,
a lethal kewpie doll with a glass-cutting chipmunk voice. (Fans of
the actress should check out her hilarious, white-trash-sexpot
performance in the barely released ``Freeway,'' a ``Red Riding
Hood'' update set in a trailer-park landscape.)
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Flick is the sort of megalomaniac whom Max Fischer, the
hero of ``Rushmore,'' would either adore or battle to the death.
The films have more than that in common. Both are sharp originals
that find fresh bite in that most strip-mined of movie settings,
the high school. Here's hoping that ``Election'' doesn't tank at
the box office the way ``Rushmore'' did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Election'' ends with one last glimpse of Tracy, a visual punch
line that's terribly resonant in a world where Monica Lewinsky can
derail the nation's political process. By its final reel, the movie
has reduced lofty ethical arguments to the absurd, impotent splat
of a soft-drink cup hurled against the side of a limousine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Election''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew Broderick and Reese Witherspoon. Directed by
Alexander Payne. Rated R for strong sexuality, sex-related dialogue
and language, and a scene of drug use. At metro theaters. 1 hour,
44 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A cruelly funny satire of the political process,
set in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
