<HEADER>
A7369 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-LOVERS07-COX     05-06 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-LOVERS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slow meltdown hits `Arctic Circle'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fickle finger of fate, as they used to call it on the old
``Laugh-In'' series, is both the theme and the operative plot
device in ``Lovers of the Arctic Circle,'' a fairly foolish and
fully overwrought Spanish film.
</P>
<P>
   Director Julio Medem harks back to the days when art movies
focused on beautiful scenery and even more beautiful young lovers.
He offers us Love! Valor! Passion! And enough fateful coincidences
to choke a horse.
</P>
<P>
   The lovers in question, Otto and Ana, have been running into
each other since they were kids. Recognizing that their names are
palindromes (spelled the same backward and forward), the pair
instantly decide that they're soul mates.
</P>
<P>
   During the rest of the picture, circumstances conspire to throw
them together and then tear them apart. And as the circle widens to
include others, the pileup of coincidences begins to look like a
bad day on I-285.
</P>
<P>
   As Otto and Ana, Fele Martinez and Najwa Nimri make a striking
couple. Martinez looks like every smolderingly sensitive European
protagonist you've ever seen, while Nimri has the big-eyed, fragile
beauty of someone who must've played Anne Frank before graduating
from drama school.
</P>
<P>
   The movie isn't tedious, just mildly irksome as it strives for
an outsized romanticism it never quite achieves. In an early scene,
Ana notes, ``There are no more good coincidences. It's my fault. I
used them too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said about the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lovers of the Arctic Circle''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Fele Martinez and Najwa Nimri. Directed by Julio Medem.
Subtitles. Rated R for sex and language. At Garden Hills.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 52 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Goes in circles, and not always on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
