<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7370 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS09-COX     05-06 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Clock' argues for taking longer view of time
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May9.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are forever running out of time. We inventory it by multiples
of 10 _ the decades we peel away as if they were sections of a
tangerine _ but it is the seamless minutes and hours that slip by
unnoticed. The present evaporates with every second, receding
irretrievably into the past, and the future is reconfigured daily.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the year 2000. ``When I was a child,'' the computer
designer Daniel Hillis wrote a few years ago, ``people used to talk
about what would happen by the year 2000. Now, 30 years later, they
still talk about what will happen by the year 2000. The future has
been shrinking by one year per year for my entire life.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who remembers high school Latin knows that tempus fugit.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Brand would like to slow it down _ or, rather, expand
our consciousness of it so that we are concerned less about the end
of a millennium and more about what might be called the eternal
present. ``The Clock of the Long Now'' is an anti-millennial book
in the sense that it argues for a reconsideration of how we
understand past, present and future.
</P>
<P>
   Brand is an environmentalist best known, perhaps, as the author
of ``The Whole Earth Catalog.'' But he is also a futurist and a bit
of a gadfly, trained as a biologist but interested in just about
everything. If anyone can say of the Internet that he was present
at the creation, or very soon after, Brand would qualify. He helped
found, in 1984, a computer teleconferencing system he called the
Whole Earth 'Lectronic Link. Based in the San Francisco Bay Area,
the WELL was a computer bulletin board that anticipated what we
know today as the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   If that was the future in 1984, it is both future and present
that concern him today:
</P>
<P>
   ``Civilization is revving itself into a pathologically short
attention span. The trend might be coming from the acceleration of
technology, the short-horizon perspective of market-driven
economics, the next-election perspective of democracies, or the
distractions of personal multitasking. All are on the increase.
Some sort of balancing corrective to the short-sightedness is
needed _ some mechanism or myth that encourages the long view and
the taking of long-term responsibility, where `the long term' is
measured at least in centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants to build a new clock, somewhere in the American desert,
and he wants it to keep time for 10,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a clock,'' he writes, ``if sufficiently impressive and
well engineered, would embody deep time for people. It would be
charismatic to visit, interesting to think about and famous enough
to become iconic in public discourse.'' It would be to the world
what Big Ben is to England. And, ideally, ``it would do for
thinking about time what the photographs of Earth from space have
done for thinking about the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   As both those passages might suggest, Brand thinks big better
than he thinks small (can an inanimate object be ``charismatic''?).
But it is the business of futurists not to worry overmuch about
undotted i's and uncrossed t's. They work with the capital letters,
and Brand, it has to be said, at least draws enough sense from them
that a determined Luddite like myself will grant him a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clock of the Long Now'' is by turns New Agey and quixotic,
contrary and provocative. But at its heart is a recognition that
technological revolutions (if that's what in fact they are) and
continuity are not incompatible: ``You need the space of continuity
to have the confidence not to be afraid of revolutions. You can
always improve things as long as you're prepared to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, waiting is not something we do well. We're better at
hurrying. We want things sooner rather than later. And we use time
more as a commodity than as a resource. Borrowing from James Carse,
a religion professor at New York University, Brand distinguishes
between finite and infinite games. A finite game, in Carse's words,
``is played for the purpose of winning, an infinite game for the
purpose of continuing the game.'' Thus, as Brand writes,
``football, elections, and much of business are finite games:
win/lose. Family, gardening and spiritual practice are infinite
games: Losing is meaningless.'' What matters in finite games is not
how they end _ the score _ but how they continue.
</P>
<P>
   To most Americans, such an argument is not just uncongenial but
seditious. Life is about winning, not losing. Yet the real
objection has nothing to do with winning or losing. It's that time
is precious precisely because it is finite.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Brand sees better than most of us one relationship
between time and consequence: ``Earthquakes, war, murder, the
burning of libraries . . . bad things happen fast. Reforestation,
the growth of a child, the maturing of an adult, building a library
. . . good things happen slow.''
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds overdramatic, it is no more so than our frantic
obsession with the immediate and the Right Now. We no sooner have
it securely in hand than we wonder where it went, and what we
really had.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Clock of the Long Now: Time and Responsibility. By Stewart
Brand. Basic Books. $22. 176 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
