<HEADER>
A7372 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-KING-640&AMP;ADD-N     05-06 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-KING-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN'S KING ASKING WEST TO CANCEL HALF NATION'S DEBT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Since his father's death propelled him to the
throne, King Abdullah of Jordan has been a man in motion. He has
installed a new government, moved to shore up his country's
troubled economy and scurried around the region to patch up
relations with Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 37-year-old ruler is embarking on another trip, this one
to try to persuade Western governments to cancel $3.5 billion in
Jordan's obligations, fully half the country's debt. He said
Thursday that this was necessary to help Jordan, which has proved
pivotal to peace in the Middle East, become ``more stable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You need Jordan to be strong so that we can shoulder our
responsibilities and be able to support the countries of the
region,'' Abdullah said over a long lunch with foreign journalists,
his first such interview since taking power.
</P>
<P>
   The king's focus on the economy represents a shift from that of
his father, King Hussein, who died on Feb. 7 and whose main
priority had been Middle East peace. But Abdullah spoke with both
candor and concern Thursday in suggesting that his country needed
more outside help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in a crisis period,'' he said, but added, ``Time is
short.''
</P>
<P>
   With just 4 million people and few natural resources, Jordan
owes a staggering $7 billion to Western creditors, and its debt
payments now consume a quarter of its budget. Unemployment has
soared well into the double-digits, average incomes have plunged,
and diplomats say they worry that mounting social discontent could
make it difficult for Jordan to play its stabilizing role in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The king said he was not worried about domestic unrest. But as
he prepared to leave on Saturday for a journey that will take him
to Britain, Germany, Canada and the United States, he argued that
the combination of Jordan's problems and its strategic significance
meant that Western leaders would be prudent to halve its debt
burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm saying is we are keeping up our side of the
bargain,'' he said, referring to steps that Jordan has already
taken at the advice of the International Monetary Fund. ``We are
moving forward, we are moving according to the way you've advised
to do it. Please meet us halfway and help us to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah said he was grateful for steps already taken by the
Clinton administration, which canceled hundreds of millions of
Jordanian debt in 1994 after Hussein made peace with Israel and has
tripled its aid to Jordan in the last two years, to $700 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Forgiving $3.5 billion in debt would be a much bigger step,
however. Most of it would have to be borne by the Europeans, who
are Jordan's biggest creditors, and some have sent mixed signals. A
British emissary, Derek Fatchett, said here this week that European
countries were ready to help ease Jordan's debt problems, but
Fatchett mentioned debt rescheduling, not debt forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah was asked what would happen if the request was not met.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what cards are dealt,'' he answered, ``we will
persevere. But at what expense?''
</P>
<P>
   Since he inherited the throne, Abdullah has grown a beard, and
he has also grown in confidence, apparently as a result of his
rapid immersion into the world of statesmanship. He was named crown
prince in January, replacing the longtime official heir, Prince
Hassan, just days before his father's death from cancer. And having
made his career the military, Abdullah had never expected to become
king.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that he had recognized that there was ``no time to
feel sorry for oneself'' or for the ``great loss of King Hussein,''
who died after 47 years on the throne.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to focus and get things together so that people could
feel secure, and move forward,'' he said, adding, ``I was always
told by my father, you get knocked down, you get right back up.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another item in his conversations with Western leaders, Abdullah
said, will be policy toward Iraq, whose citizens' suffering under
the economic sanctions imposed by the United Nations after Iraq's
1990 invasion of Kuwait strikes angry nerves in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was outspoken in calling for a change in the Iraqi
government in the mid-1990s, but it retreated from that stance
under Hussein and, if anything, Abdullah seemed Thursday to back
further away. He said he believed that dialogue with Iraq might be
more productive than continued sanctions, and he vowed that Jordan
would play no role in any American-led efforts to topple the Iraqi
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Abdullah seemed determined to dispel any
impression that he has begun to turn his back on Israel. Jordan's
peace with Israel remains deeply unpopular here, but the king said
that, like his father, he was ``absolutely committed'' to it
</P>
<P>
   Still, it has been widely noticed in the Middle East that his
first foreign visits were to Arab countries, including Syria,
Libya, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates, which have been
hostile toward Israel and have often criticized Jordan's separate
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want relationships with everybody, and I think we can do
that,'' the king insisted. But he also said that, in reaching out
to Arabs with whom relations have been cold, one of his motivations
had been to ``reassure our nationals, many of whom had worried that
Jordan might have severed too many Arab bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   The king said he held out hope that Israel and the Palestinians
could quickly resume negotiations after the Israeli elections on
May 17. If there is momentum in those talks, he predicted, it might
well produce a ``cascade effect that could smooth over other
differences, including those between Israel and Syria.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah has maintained a studied neutrality on the Israeli
elections. All three men seeking to become Israel's next prime
minister have visited Amman in recent weeks, and the king has held
a private meeting with each of them.
</P>
<P>
   But it is no secret in Amman that Hussein had come to see Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, the Likud Party leader, as an obstacle
to a broader peace, and a slip of the tongue by Abdullah Thursday
seemed to suggest that he might prefer one of Netanyahu's two
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The king said he would be optimistic about peace ``if we have a
new face in Israel,'' and then he caught himself. What he had meant
to say, he insisted, was ``if we have a new phase.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
