<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7374 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-790     05-06 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-ART-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEMOCRATS UNVEIL GUN CONTROL PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seizing what they hope is new momentum for gun
control after Littleton, Colo., Senate Democrats on Thursday
unveiled a broad package of proposals that Republicans, though
skeptical, did not dismiss out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans will probably not allow discussion of all the
measures, from child safety locks on handguns to new regulations
for gun shows. However, the majority leader, Trent Lott of
Mississippi, has promised Democrats that they can offer a few gun
control amendments to a Republican juvenile justice bill. That bill
is scheduled for consideration early next week.
</P>
<P>
   It will mark the first floor debate on gun control in either
chamber of Congress this year. Moreover, it should provide a
glimpse of how far apart the two parties stand, and whether the
battles lines have changed, following the shooting spree that left
15 people dead at Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next week will be, really, a great opportunity and a day of
reckoning,'' Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said on Thursday at a
news conference at which he and five other Senate Democrats
announced eight amendments that Democrats wanted to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said that the package of amendments, which closely
mirrored the gun control proposals that President Clinton announced
last week, was intended to ``maximize its impact on criminals and
children while minimizing its impact on law-abiding gun owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have not indicated support for any of the
proposals, but neither have they clearly signaled an unyielding
opposition, a sign that the bloodshed at Columbine, and at other
schools before it, may have softened their stance or at least put
them on the political defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Republican aides said on Thursday that the atmosphere on
Capitol Hill had been altered and that Republican leaders were
reluctant to be portrayed as reflexively opposed to new gun control
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that leaders were discussing whether there were a few
modest proposals they could support, but that they were also
questioning whether new laws would be any more effective in
reducing violence among children than more vigorous enforcement of
existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   Lott expressed such skepticism earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if the solution or the prevention of this sort of
problem like we had in Colorado is necessarily more federal
legislation,'' he said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would support any of the proposals Democrats
had begun talking about, like tighter restrictions on the sales of
firearms at guns shows, Lott said, ``I sure do like gun shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott and other Republicans have received more support and money
from the National Rifle Association than their Democratic
counterparts have. The rifle association generally opposes gun
control legislation, though a spokesman for the organization, Bill
Powers, said on Thursday that it would release its own set of
legislative proposals next week for reducing violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   That development, like Lott's promise to allow a debate on gun
control, reflected a sharp sensitivity right now to public opinion
about the issue. According to an Associated Press poll released on
Thursday, support for gun control has increased since Columbine,
though only 51 percent of Americans think new laws would be more
effective than better enforcement of existing ones.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats are generally more enamored of gun control than
Republicans, the divide is not a clean one, and many Democrats in
Congress, including party leaders, have been tentative about
promoting the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic advocates of gun control intensified their public
relations campaign on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As Senate Democrats delineated their plans at a news conference
rife with charts, props and expressions of outrage, 31 female
Democratic members of the House sent the speaker, Dennis Hastert of
Illinois, a letter that looked forward to Mother's Day this weekend
and urged him to support gun control legislation as ``the greatest
gift we could give America's moms.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee had signaled
such eagerness to force a debate on gun control in a hearing
scheduled for Thursday on a juvenile justice bill that Republicans
on the committee postponed the event, according to several
Democratic and Republican aides.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals by Senate Democrats include the institution of a
three-day waiting period before handgun purchases; the closing of
loopholes that exempt gun shows and the Internet from regulations
governing the sale of firearms in stores; a ban on juvenile
possession of any assault weapons, and the imposition of criminal
penalties on adult gun owners whose children gain access to those
weapons and injure themselves or others.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., said that measures like these
should not be overlooked as many Republicans and Democrats promote
a broader cultural debate about the causes of violence among
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with my colleagues who call for more guidance, more
prayer and more virtue,'' Durbin said. ``But I don't agree that
easy access to guns has nothing to do with this carnage.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbin and other Senate Democrats said they had pared their wish
list of legislation, most of which represented minor tinkering as
opposed to massive overhaul, to proposals that had at least some
chance of passing.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, when measures requiring child safety locks and
holding parents responsible for the misuse of their guns by
children came to the Senate floor, they were soundly defeated. In
addition, the juvenile justice bill to which such legislation might
be amended next week is by no means guaranteed to pass the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
