A7375 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MUMMY07-COX     05-06 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MUMMY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Mummy' should have been kept under wraps
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just because a movie has desert scenery, a hunky action hero,
hissable bad guys and supernatural hoodoo doesn't make it an
Indiana Jones movie. You'll miss Steven Spielberg's masterful touch
watching ``The Mummy,'' a petrified mix of retro adventure, clumsy
slapstick and minimal chills.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the 1932 Boris Karloff film, the movie sends adventurer
Brendan Fraser and Egyptologist Rachel Weisz in search of the
legendary, treasure-laden city of Hamunaptra. They're accompanied
by her brother John Hannah, and by a rival team of treasure-seekers
(four guys so expendable they might as well be tattooed ``Mummy's
Boys'').
</P>
<P>
   They're the ones who waken the corpse of high priest Imhotep, an
icky shell of computer-generated cartilage who replenishes his
flesh by sucking dry the dudes who woke him up. The movie gives us
acid booby traps, plagues of locusts and scarabs, and swell tidal
waves of sand. Some of the CGI effects are cool, but to see them
means wading through a script that reads like a first draft.
Thriller? Campy sendup? Promo reel for Industrial Light &AMP; Magic?
Stick around, ``The Mummy'' is always switching tones.
</P>
<P>
   Hannah survives. But in their rogue-and-schoolmarm roles, Fraser
doesn't have the rugged heft he needs, while Weisz turns in an
annoyingly ``cute'' performance befitting a community theater
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Sommers wrote and directed ``The Mummy,'' so he deserves
double the blame for the lameness. He's also responsible for last
year's awful ``Deep Rising.'' Apparently the money guys at
Universal forgot to watch that movie before signing Sommers. Now
that's a real curse.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mummy''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz. Rated PG-13 for pervasive
adventure violence and some partial nudity. 2 hours, 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Mummy, make it stop!
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
