<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7376 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INS-RIGHTS-VIOLATORS-     05-06 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-RIGHTS-VIOLATORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TIGHTENS IMMIGRATION SCREENING IN WAKE OF GLOBE REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Immigration and Naturalization Service has
adopted tighter screening procedures to try to ensure that people
who participated in atrocities are not among the 20,000 Kosovo
refugees expected to arrive in the United States over the next
three months, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said the changes were prompted by reports in a
Boston Globe series this week that suspected participants in ethnic
cleansing were recently allowed to settle in places such as
Everett, Mass. and Burlington, Vt., by portraying themselves as
victims of atrocities in the former Yugoslavia. Immigration
specialists involved in the immense US refugee program said that
the screening process had become easy for non-deserving immigrants
to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   INS officers interviewing Kosovo refugees in Macedonia have
received training to help them recognize members of the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army, Serb collaborators or criminals who may be
among the refugee population, US immigration officials said. The
government also has added a ``secondary'' layer of interviewers to
assist asylum officers who determine that a refugee applicant
should be questioned further.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials said they hope the changes will form the
basis for a new global policy for screening refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Globe series caused a closer look at what should be the
appropriate level of screening,'' said Dan Cadman, head of the
Immigration and Naturalization Service's National Security Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, legislators have called on the Clinton administration
to clarify how a broad range of suspected human rights offenders
have gained entry to the United States, as the Globe reported.
Representative Cynthia A. McKinney, a Georgia Democrat, called for
hearings in an interview Thursday. Representative James McGovern, a
Massachusetts Democrat, sent a letter to Attorney General Janet
Reno wanting ``to know what transpired in these cases that allowed
these men to seek refuge in the US.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, a Connecticut Democrat, who has pushed
for the creation of a permanent international war crimes tribunal,
called the series ``troubling, to say the least.'' In a statement,
Dodd said the articles ``highlight a problem that needs to be
addressed. Our nation shouldn't send mixed signals with respect to
human rights. What we do is as important as what we say.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we have a double standard when individuals with
questionable human rights records fall between the cracks and are
allowed to enter and remain in the US,'' said Dodd, whose father,
Thomas J. Dodd, worked as a prosecutor at the Nuremberg war trials.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Mark Foley, a Republican from Port St. Lucie,
Fla., said he was shocked to learn that Carl Dorelien, a former
colonel in the murderous Haitian regime ousted by a 1994 US
invasion, has been living in his district.
</P>
<P>
   ``What amazes me is that nobody thought to notify us about the
potential of this guy being in our comunity,'' Foley said. ``We
seem to be fixated on Meghan's Law, and having sex offenders living
among us. I think it would be nice to know that this guy who
commanded 7,000 troops that led to the death of 5,000 people is
living next door to me. I mean, he's not the kind of guy that you'd
come over and bring a fruit basket to and say `Welcome to town.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern, who has worked for several years on Salvadoran human
rights issues, said he has been stymied in his efforts to find out
why Carlos Eugenio Vides Casanova, a former Salvadoran general, was
allowed to settle in Palm Coast, Fla., despite the conclusion of a
UN Truth Commission that he participated in the coverup of the
massacre of four American churchwomen in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe series showed that the Salvadoran case is ``the tip of
the iceberg,'' McGovern said. `'I'm not so much interested in
assigning blame on how they got here. I just want them out. They
don't belong here. And this kind of subdued response from the
administration I think is just wrong. These people committed
horrendous atrocities and they belong in jail. They don't belong
anywhere near the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe documented the cases of three Bosnian refugees, two
living in New England, who allegedly participated in ethnic
cleansing operations in the former Yugoslavia. In each case, the
refugees apparently concealed their military backgrounds from
relief organizations involved in the ``pre-screening'' of refugees
and INS asylum officers who conducted interviews and made the
decision to grant refugee status.
</P>
<P>
   According to US immigration officials, the INS has been pushing
for changes in the refugee screening process. But the Globe's
findings helped propel the agency to implement changes immediately
at Fort Dix, N.J. and Macedonia, where about 20 asylum officers
have been sent to screen thousands of refugees, most of whom were
stripped of all identification before being driven from Kosovo by
the Serb army.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States, to its credit, we're very warmhearted and
welcoming people,'' said Cadman. ``And somtimes it just takes a
sober look to recognize that you can be both welcoming and
protective of your own people's interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials cautioned that the changes were not foolproof and
still might not ensure that undeserving immigrants slip through the
cracks. ``There is no absolute failsafe, particularly in this
situation, where the Serbs deliberately stripped everyone of their
identities,'' said a US official, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes, asylum officers have received training in how
to better detect whether an applicant is concealing information or
lying about his past, US officials said. The officers also have
been instructed to ask a series of questions that would help elicit
whether an applicant may have participated in human rights abuses
or witnessed them and could provide useful information to war
crimes investigators.
</P>
<P>
   If an INS asylum officer questions a refugee's persecution
claim, the officer now can refer the case to another officer who
will investigate the claim's veracity, US officials said. Officials
said the secondary screening officers will interview the applicant
again and attempt to verify details about the claim.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said the officers are particularly concerned with
former members of the KLA, an organization that has been linked to
terrorism; Serb combatants and collaborators; and criminals who
have engaged in drug trafficking or alien and document smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the officers were focusing primarily on young
adult men. ``Generally we'll be looking at adult males who would be
considered of fighting age,'' said a US official. ``We are going to
want to know why they are there.''
</P>
<P>
   John Fredriksson, associate executive director of Immigration
and Refugee Services of America, which is helping to implement the
Kosovo refugee program, said he was concerned that reports of
suspected participants in ethnic cleansing in the US might provoke
``an overreaction that could hurt a lot of refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials said the changes were necessary to balance the
long-standing practice of the United States to accept tens of
thousands of refugees each year with the reality that the system
had become vulnerable to fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refuge that we grant is a treasured thing,'' said one
immigration official. ``And it's the worst of all ironies if it
goes to someone who has inflicted pain and suffering on others and
caused them to seek refuge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
