<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN STANDARD TURNS AWAY FROM TRADITIONAL MANAGEMENT
HIERARCHIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.J., Texas)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carrie-Ann Houser was a year out of college when American
Standard Cos. hired her for an entry-level human resources job. A
couple of years later, her ``coach'' _ whose main job is
shepherding careers _ tapped her to revamp the way benefits are
administered. Scarcely a year later, she joined a
benefits-administration team.
</P>
<P>
   Her title never changed _ in fact, her business card has no
title _ but her responsibilities and salary rose steadily. ``In a
traditional setting I'd be waiting for someone to leave, and
clawing my way to their place,'' Ms. Houser said.
</P>
<P>
   American Standard, though, is far from traditional these days.
Yes, it makes plumbing supplies, air conditioners, truck brakes _
not things to get Internet-generation hearts pumping.
</P>
<P>
   But listen to Michael Hammer, the consultant in Cambridge,
Mass., who coined the term ``re-engineering'' and is the architect
of the ``process organization,'' which turns corporate hierarchies
on their ear. He sees American Standard as more avant-garde than
Silicon Valley companies that are long on promises of wealth but
short on job flexibility and career counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to working with people, they are as different
from the traditional corporation as day is from night,'' Hammer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Look at American Standard business cards and that difference is
palpable. They list nebulous titles like process owner or group
leader _ or no titles at all. Even Emmanuel A. Kampouris has caught
the vague-title bug _ in the annual report, Mano Kampouris, 64, is
chairman, president and chief executive, but his card lists him
simply as corporate leader.
</P>
<P>
   And any number of once-high-ranking executives are now
``coaches,'' charged with guiding employees along career paths that
are not always easy to spot.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been a simple transition, particularly for executives
who saw the perks and prestige they felt had rewarded their hard
work be ripped away. ``It has meant learning to manage our egos,
and accepting that we could learn as much from blue-collar workers
as from each other,'' Kampouris said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees own 25 percent of company stock, often in lieu of a
pension. Electronic flash boards, tallying orders and shipments,
are ubiquitous in the factories as well as in offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say that everyone is on the team, then you have to
communicate the same way to each one,'' said G. Eric Nutter, who
heads the domestic plumbing business.
</P>
<P>
   True, the news is not always good. American Standard's sales and
earnings are cyclical. The company carries heavy debt, and its
stock is a so-so performer, so it cannot just buy other companies
as a hedge. The few acquisitions it has made are not helping much.
</P>
<P>
   But it is seemingly mundane stories like Carrie-Ann Houser's
that mark the real change at American Standard, based in
Piscataway, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, when it went public for the second time, it had already
put in place ``demand flow'' technology, a way of rearranging
equipment and retraining factory workers that speeds orders along,
resulting in fewer products eating up working capital in inventory.
The logical next step was to streamline the operations before,
after and around the time a product is made.
</P>
<P>
   Process organization regroups everyone, from bosses to hourly
workers, into teams headed by ``process owners.'' Then, instead of
letting different departments handle budgeting, staffing, accounts
receivable, and other aspects of an order or assignment, it lets
each team take the project from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   This can be an angst-filled cultural change. For managers, it
means the death of fancy titles, big offices, power over
subordinates, all the ego trappings of corporate success. And for
up-and-comers, it means a promotional path that is fuzzy at best.
</P>
<P>
   So three years ago American Standard turned to coaching. Today,
it has 278 people, many of whom once had fancy titles, who act as
mentors to about 100 employees each, and it expects to have 300
coaches by summer. The coaches catalog their proteges' skills and
interests, find them training to shore up weak spots and move them
along fast enough to avoid boredom but slowly enough to prevent
overload.
</P>
<P>
   In salary and prestige, these coaches, who as a group cost more
than $33 million a year, are on a par with process owners; but they
are judged not by how well they churn out products or rake in
dollars, but by how well the Carrie-Ann Housers move along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process owners worry about customers, while the coaches
worry about our people,'' explained Helmut Sander, who coaches the
coaches at Wabco, American Standard's Brussels-based auto-products
group. Andrew Stevenson, a business leader at Trane, the company's
air-conditioning business, based in Trenton, N.J., put it more
simply: ``Coaches are guidance counselors who help us move around,
not just up.''
</P>
<P>
   Examples of coaching's handiwork abound:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ray Helmich, an engineering coach, guided a shop foreman who
enjoyed working with computers to a better job in information
technology. ``He only had a high school degree, so no one would
have recruited him,'' Helmich said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Diane Notta was an obscure finance department employee when
her coach pushed her to brush up her customer-service skills and
apply for the post she now holds shepherding customer orders at
Trane. ``This job would have seemed beyond my comfort zone if my
coach hadn't led me through each step,'' Ms. Notta said.
</P>
<P>
   _ James M. Freeman, an accounting team leader in plumbing, had
an idea for saving on lighting costs. ``Everyone's reaction was,
`What does an accountant know about lighting?' '' he recalled. His
coach tutored him on how to present his case better, and he got the
go-ahead to spend $135,000 on energy-saving bulbs. ``The incident
will help my career,'' Freeman said. ``It showed my tenacity.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fast-tracking people has not kept American Standard from
missteps. A few years ago it bought a money-losing medical
diagnostics company that Roger W. Parsons, managing director of the
British merchant bank Rea Brothers Group and an American Standard
director, acknowledges ``was not one of our best moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Many shareholders were disappointed when in January 1997 the
company rejected a $50-a-share acquisition bid from Tyco
International, when American Standard was trading in the low $40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been good, considering the premium and how
aggressive a cost cutter Tyco can be,'' said Sholom Dinsky, a
managing director at Prudential Investments, who still has a hefty
chunk of American Standard stock in his portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to wring costs out of its plumbing business, which has
been hard hit overseas, resulted in such hefty write-offs that the
company lost $117 million in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And its February purchase of the bathroom products division of
Blue Circle Industries, which Kampouris insists gives American
Standard invaluable distribution in Europe, prompted many analysts
to downgrade their recommendations on the stock to neutral at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is surprising that they are allocating such a large amount
of capital to their lowest-return business,'' David J. Pizzimenti
of Schroder &AMP; Co. wrote in a February report.
</P>
<P>
   Still, American Standard ended last year with sales up 11
percent, to $6.7 billion, and net income up 4 percent, to $637
million. And it had working capital down to 2.9 percent of sales,
from 4.7 percent in 1997. First-quarter results were rosy, too,
with net income at $47 million, up 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they see something wrong, they quickly take steps,'' said
Michael Jaffe, an analyst with S.&AMP; P, Equity Group.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kampouris, whose twinkling eyes and informal manner
belie a steely resolve, keeps raising the bar. That habit exacts
both admiration and annoyance from the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons remembers Kampouris handing out badges with the letters
TNE on them. ``They stood for `twice net earnings,' one of Mano's
goals,'' Parsons recalled. ``His people took them to mean
`terrific, not enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kampouris can perhaps be forgiven for pushing hard. Ten years
ago a botched management buyout left American Standard essentially
comatose, trying to service $3 billion in debt on $3.6 billion in
sales. Kampouris, who has been with the company 34 years and was a
leader of the buyout, took over as chief executive, and began
hacking costs and bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He recognized that if you can get the senior people to change
their mind-set, the junior people will come along,'' said Ram
Charan, a Dallas management consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching system, of course, has been part and parcel of that
one-for-all approach. ``Coaching was a good way to find jobs for
people who might have been downsized and a great way to utilize
people who care less about their outside status than about their
internal sphere of influence,'' Kampouris said.
</P>
<P>
   Many managers could not do that and left or were reassigned.
Others identified so thoroughly with their charges that they would
insist on third, fourth, ninth chances for people who eventually
had to be dismissed anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But a highly visible few embraced the chance to coach. David R.
Pannier was vice president for marketing at Unitary Products, which
makes small air-conditioners, when the new structure went into
place. He immediately volunteered as coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a manager has seven things to do, developing people
always winds up the seventh,'' he said. ``Well, I had 20 years of
sales and marketing experience, and I was ready to use it to
develop people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kampouris uses both the carrot and the stick to make the system
work. Coaches whose people make good progress get nice bonuses and
eventual promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Pannier, for one, spent less than two years as a coach before he
was made group leader of Unitary Products. It was a similarly short
hop for Gary Uhl, an industrial engineer-cum-plumbing products
sales coach, to his current job as a process owner in the plumbing
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned about customers and sales, and that increased my own
skills level,'' Uhl said.
</P>
<P>
   But woe to any manager who fails to embrace the spirit of
coaching and the process organization.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer, who periodically visits American Standard outposts to
audit their progress, reported back that senior managers at one
overseas branch were not relinquishing authority to the process
teams. Kampouris dismissed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emmanuel Kampouris is mild mannered, he's courtly and
delightful and kind,'' Hammer said. ``But if you're being
halfhearted or insincere, you don't want to be on the receiving end
of his evaluation.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
