<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN PERSECUTION UNITES TWO STRANGERS IN US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT DIX, New Jersey _ Mirsade Bejiqi and Arlinda Gashi were not
friends at home in Pristina, the capital of Kosovo. Nor did they
meet on the trains on which they fled from Serbs, who were
persecuting them for their Albanian Muslim ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday they stood together like young women who'd known
each other forever, trying simultaneously to face a new life in
America and to keep alive the memory of their homeland in the
Balkans. They were the first of the group of 453 refugees who
arrived here Wednesday to talk about their dreams, and their
nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very tired (on arrival), but for us it was like we
were born again,'' said Bejiqi, 20. ``Our minds were so confused
with what we'd left, what we'd seen there.... We went through
everything, and now it seems there is another view of life.''
</P>
<P>
   As she and Gashi, 19, talked with the first journalists allowed
to meet with refugees, the fenced-in compound in which they are
being held for interviewing and processing by immigration and
public-health officials pulsed with energy and echoed with the
joyous shrieks of children at play _ an Albanian version of
dodge-ball, soccer, or paratrooper-assisted baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The young women were upbeat, riding a wave of relief at being
out danger. They were clean, well-fed, and rested to boot. But
their attitudes were not the same. Bejiqi looked more to the
future; Gashi _ perhaps because her experience at the hands of the
Serbs was more severe _ kept looking back.
</P>
<P>
   Already she had seen relatives severely beaten and a schoolmate
killed when, nine nights after NATO began bombing Yugoslavia in the
so-far-unsuccessful effort to stop expulsion and displacement of
ethnic Albanians, ``the police came in our house and said go out,''
Gashi said.
</P>
<P>
   They demanded 5,000 German marks, she said, and ``we said, `Kill
us. We don't got.' They said give us 500 and go.'' With a loan from
some cousins, that is what she, her parents, and her brother did.
</P>
<P>
   That same night, Bejiqi, her parents, and two brothers, who had
been hiding in cellars in downtown Pristina, also entrained after,
she said, ``there came a mass of people _ not soldiers, Serbian
people _ and told us to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knew where they were going. Everyone wound up in an open
field in Blace, the no-man's-land at the Macedonian border where,
incredibly, life got worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day it rained,'' Bejiqi said. ``People were dying day
and night, and many children were born.''
</P>
<P>
   Both families were in the first masses of refugees moved to
NATO-run camps in Macedonia, both were among the first to volunteer
for evacuation, even if that meant transfer to the American
military base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a signal that these were people who were prepared to
make the break,'' said Roger Winter, director of the
non-governmental Immigration and Refugee Services of America, the
lead refugee resettlement organization. ``They valued their own
lives and the lives of their children, and they were prepared to
make the leap.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, both girls are intent on returning to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to come here, in America. It was my dream,
what I answered when they asked in school where did I want to go,''
Bejiqi said. ``But it is important to go back. Albanian people do
not want to live outside Kosovo. It's ours. We built it.... We will
rebuild it. No problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Servicemen and women attending to the refugees' needs said that,
jet lag notwithstanding, many rose early Thursday to look around _
and eat. While only cold turkey sandwiches and snacks were
available Wednesday night, Thursday three hot meals were provided
by the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola and bananas led the initial list of favorite foods,
followed by ``any kind of bread that isn't white,'' said Capt. Ron
Frame, a supply officer. Lima beans and mashed potatoes were
least-liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not asking for anything,'' said Staff Sgt. Terry Wade,
whose unit flew in from Fort Bragg, North Carolina, to assist the
refugees. ``They are putting their hands out, asking, `Can we sweep
the floors? Can we do anything to help?' ''
</P>
<P>
   As America's newest residents ate, played, and napped, still
under tight Immigration and Naturalization Service control,
government and private-agency officials offered sometimes-differing
views on whether they had been screened for political and military
involvements before leaving Macedonia, and whether all would be
able to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Lavinia Limon, director of refugee resettlement for the US
Department of Health and Human Services, the lead government agency
in the Fort Dix program, said that the refugees were all evaluated
and found eligible for asylum before leaving Macedonia, a view
echoed by a State Department refugee program official.
</P>
<P>
   But Amy Otten, a spokeswoman for the US Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said in response to questions from The
Globe: ``The processing done over there is really very skeletal.
The interviewers (here) are pretty skilled at ferreting out
(indications of unacceptable military or political activity) but we
do have to rely heavily on what they tell us.''
</P>
<P>
   The US screening procedures did not concern the young people who
made up about half the first group of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to say thanks to everyone,'' said Bejiqi. ``I
especially want to thank American people. They help us a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
