A7384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-INSURE-585&AMP;     05-06 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-INSURE-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURERS AGREE TO PAY CLAIMS ON PRE-HOLOCAUST POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Several large European insurance companies agreed for
the first time Thursday to pay claims on policies bought by
European Jews before the Holocaust, under a formula that reflects
present-day values. The settlement could potentially result in
billions of dollars in payments.
</P>
<P>
   The exact terms of the agreement, reached after two days of
rancorous negotiations in London, were not released, and the
insurers declined to comment on them. But the broad outlines of the
agreement were announced by the World Jewish Congress, which
participated in the negotiations, and Lawrence Eagleburger, the
former secretary of state who is chairman of the committee that has
been conducting the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was seen as a significant breakthrough on an issue
haunting Europe more than 50 years after World War II. It is the
latest unfolding of an effort that began more than three years ago
to secure financial reparations from Swiss banks for survivors of
the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the effort, led by American Jewish groups, senior
U.S. officials and American lawyers, has mushroomed to encompass
claims against European insurance companies and German corporations
accused of employing slave labor. Just Wednesday, for example,
Volkswagen was sued in the United States on behalf of former Polish
and Russian slave laborers who claim their children died in a
decrepit nursery run by the German automaker during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with the insurers is significantly different from
other settlements of Holocaust claims because it takes into account
a half-century of inflation, interest payments and currency
depreciation, which could drastically magnify the size of payouts.
</P>
<P>
   The formula for devising the exact amount of payments has not
been worked out yet, but estimates of total payouts have ranged
from $1 billion to $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Eagleburger will lead a separate committee to resolve the value
of the policies before negotiations resume in Jerusalem next month.
</P>
<P>
   A statement on the agreement by Eagleburger did not say how
claims would be verified. But it said he had instructed his staff
to ``establish the claims process and begin work on the outreach
process necessary to inform potential insurance claimants that they
can file claims.''
</P>
<P>
   Elan Steinberg, executive director of the World Jewish Congress,
said the insurance companies agreed to make the payments only after
Eagleburger threatened to go public and ``tell the truth'' that
negotiations were a failure due to the insurers' intransigence. The
insurance companies at the negotiations are some of the biggest in
the industry: Allianz AG of Germany, AXA of France, Assicurazioni
Generali of Italy, Winterthur of Switzerland and Anglo-Swiss Zurich
Financial Services. Many other European insurance companies are not
party to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   At issue were thousands _ possibly many more _ of life and other
insurance policies taken out in prewar Europe by Jews who later
died or suffered under the Holocaust. For decades after the war,
insurance companies avoided paying out on the policies, arguing in
some cases that, since their Eastern European subsidiaries had been
nationalized by communist governments in the postwar era, they were
not responsible.
</P>
<P>
   But, more recently, regulators in the United States, notably in
California, put pressure on the European insurers. California
threatened to suspend the business licenses of more than 100
European insurers unless they moved to settle with claimants.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, after the first day of negotiations,
Steinberg said that the talks were stalled on many issues,
including the policy values and the insurance company
nationalizations.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, after a second day of discussions, Steinberg said,
``the rabbit was pulled from the hat'' after Eagleburger told
insurance company negotiators that he would disclose their attitude
to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Until all of the details are worked out, Steinberg said, the
insurance companies agreed to make what he called ``fast-track''
payments to some of the thousands of aging people with direct
claims on the policies. In addition, he said, the companies agreed
to assume responsibility for policies predating the postwar
nationalization of insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nationalization issue was resolved only five minutes after
the talks ended. It was that dramatic,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts said Thursday's agreement was unlikely to eat
significantly into the European insurance companies' huge holdings.
But, some analysts said, the companies may have feared setting a
precedent that would be used by American lawyers who won a
billion-dollar settlement from Swiss banks and are also pursuing
class-action suits against German companies that employed slave
labor. In that case the issue of the value of wartime money
translated into 1999 terms would assume significance because the
German government has already paid some claims that Jewish groups
now consider to be too low.
</P>
<P>
   Eagleburger is to meet Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, along with
Israel Singer of the World Jewish Congress, next week to discuss
that issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
