<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS STILL LOOKING FOR MISSING, BUT NUMBER IS LOWER THAN EXPECTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Using listening devices and specially trained
dogs, rescue workers returned to obliterated neighborhoods on
Thursday with hopes of finding people who have been missing since
tornadoes struck Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Search teams were dispatched to five areas where there is the
``possibility'' that people remain trapped, said the Oklahoma State
Medical Examiner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Crews were using dogs and sophisticated listening and lighting
devices to search crevices of wrecked buildings, shattered cars and
piles of trash for anyone, alive or dead.
</P>
<P>
   Officials, however, refused to speculate on their chances of
finding anyone alive in the swath of death and destruction that
stretched through Oklahoma City and 11 counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that there are bodies out there; we just don't know
how many,'' said Oklahoma Police Sgt. Jerry Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The death count from Monday night's tornadoes rose to 41
Thursday, when three more people died in area hospitals, according
to the medical examiner's office. All 41 have been positively
identified.
</P>
<P>
   The medical examiner's office, which is helping coordinate
search efforts, said 14 people remained missing last night, down
significantly from the 54 on a list issued earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The number of missing dropped, officials said, as names were
matched with victims who had gone to hospitals or emergency
shelters, or had sought refuge with friends or family members.
</P>
<P>
   Those who remained unaccounted for ``all could have been in
harm's way'' when a vicious storm system spawned an estimated 76
tornadoes in a five-state area, state Medical Examiner Fred Jordan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be searching in all of the areas where we
believe there are legitimately missing people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was ``no evidence ... of living people,'' Jordan
stressed that the missing persons' list ``does not mean in any way
that these people are assumed dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he feared more bodies would be found, Jordan said:
``We might find a few more, but hopefully it will be far fewer''
than the number of missing.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue crews were concentrating on specific areas after finding
evidence of more people under debris, said Ray Blakeney, director
of operations for the medical examiner's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some areas where there is a possibility that we may
have some remaining individuals,'' Blakeney said. ``We have
isolated these areas and we have five teams out at the present time
in these areas trying to locate anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the search teams were concentrating in the southern
portion of Oklahoma City and in the outlying areas of Bridge Creek,
Moore, Del City and Midwest City.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, emergency crews worked to clear debris and fallen
power lines, and families continued to pick through whatever is
left of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 2,250 people have sought help at emergency Red
Cross shelters in the area, said Ben Frizzell, spokesman for the
Oklahoma Department of Civil Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to clean up and replace the damage will be astounding,
with estimates ``already up to about three-quarters of a billion
dollars,'' said one state insurance official who asked not to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't get really close to $1 billion,'' he said,
referring to the total property loss, ``I'll be surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   State Farm said it expects its policyholders to make about
30,000 claims for a total of $183 million. No estimates were
available from other insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Gov. Frank Keating met with other state lawmakers
and area mayors to discuss the needs of communities hardest hit,
and what can be done quickly for people who lost everything,
including identification papers.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Buchanan, a spokesman for Keating, said some victims are
having trouble applying for assistance from the Red Cross and the
Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) because they do not have
even a driver's license or birth certificate to prove their
identity.
</P>
<P>
   In Moore, where an elementary school and high school were
destroyed, the 2,200 students will return to classes Monday,
finishing the final two weeks at a nearby college, another
elementary school and an old administration building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel strongly that in a time of crisis, one thing the
school can offer is routine, stability and structure in the school
day,'' said district spokeswoman Susan Pierce.. ``It's important
for those students who have suffered a great loss.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
