<HEADER>
A7397 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      05-06 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO'S ACCORD WITH RUSSIA LEAVES UNANSWERED QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, anxious to find a
political solution to the Kosovo war as soon as possible, managed
to get the Russians on their side on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, Washington and the allies, calculating that
isolating Slobodan Milosevic was critical to setting the stage for
negotiations, finessed several of their key demands and made it
clear that there was room for maneuver on the composition of an
international security force.
</P>
<P>
   With the Russians on board, administration officials acknowledge
there will be some hard choices to face as they try to fashion
negotiating principles that do not stray too far from demands that
NATO previously insisted were nonnegotiable.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's statement in Germany was intended by the Western
allies to set the stage for what is known as a U.N. Chapter 7
resolution, which authorizes military operations in a country
without its consent.
</P>
<P>
   In drafting the resolution, a process now being hotly debated at
the White House, the administration will probably supply many of
the answers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key questions is the composition of the security
force that is planned to return the refugees to the province _ how
much will be a NATO operation, and how much a U.N. operation.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's meeting in Germany, the word NATO was purposely
dropped as the price for winning Russian agreement. Milosevic, too,
has opposed involvement by the alliance in any type of force in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A piece of paper from the summit in Bonn, though, did not mean
that either the allies or the Russians had changed their minds on
this issue, a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be fooling ourselves if we thought the Russians
wanted NATO at the core of the force,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   So now the question became whether the Russians gave in first on
the pre-eminence of NATO in the force or whether the allies did,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The missing element in Thursday's meeting was Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   It was not expected that he would be heard from as the allies
cobbled together their diplomatic phalanx. But the Russian envoy,
Viktor Chernomyrdin, is expected to go to Belgrade in the coming
days. The U.S. deputy secretary of state, Strobe Talbott, plans to
meet with Chernomyrdin in Moscow on Sunday, presumably before the
Russian envoy departs for Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   After Chernomyrdin's Belgrade trip, it will become clearer
whether Milosevic is under enough pressure from the airstrikes to
give a little. Or whether as some in the administration fear,
Milosevic will sit back, watch and wait for concessions.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Milosevic has barely squinted at the allies' demands. At
the start of the airstrikes, he said he would consider an unarmed
U.N. mission in Kosovo. Last week, in an interview with a Western
journalist, he asserted he would allow a peacekeeping force with
weapons of self defense. But he specifically ruled out foreign
soldiers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, as anxious to play a world role in the Kosovo
solution as the White House is anxious to get out of Kosovo, have
assumed a heavy mantle.
</P>
<P>
   In moments of candor, the Russians acknowledge they do not have
great leverage over the Yugoslav leader who has become more of a
burden to them as a traditional ally than an asset. And it appears
that the Russians have not been consulting with Milosevic this
week.
</P>
<P>
   But there is only so much, some argue, that the Russians can do.
``The Russians can't deliver Milosevic unless Milosevic wants to be
delivered,'' said a State Department official, expressing some of
the doubts in the higher levels of the department that the Russian
strategy is going to work as well as the White House would like.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been trying to find a way out of Kosovo
fairly urgently, driven partly by the unpopularity of the NATO
strikes in Congress and the dip in President Clinton's public
opinion polls among the reasons. To accomplish a swift resolution,
the White House has to find some fairly creative solutions on the
composition of the peacekeeping force, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Already there is discussion within the administration about
whether the force should be formed around the guidelines of the
U.N. force in Bosnia during the war there. Known as UNPROFOR, these
troops were authorized to fire only in self defense and did not
include Americans. This option has been ruled out, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Another option, becoming known as ``glorified UNPROFOR,'' would
put a U.N. label on a force with much stronger rules of engagement
than in Bosnia and would include American and other NATO forces.
Such a force, under a U.N. command, is being likened to the
multinational force that was deployed in Somalia in the early 1990s
and left after the deaths of 17 American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   This option is unlikely to win favor because the administration
has insisted that NATO have command and control of any American
peacekeeping troops dispatched to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The third option, which has been the preferred administration
notion so far, would have troops from the main NATO countries in
the force, including the United States, as well as non-NATO
countries such as Russia and Ukraine. In such a configuration, the
NATO forces would be under NATO command and control and the
non-NATO forces would have a separate command.
</P>
<P>
   One scenario of this third version, according to a Russian
Foreign Ministry official, would place some of the Russian troops
in a northern part of Kosovo where there is a concentration of Serb
religious monuments and significant numbers of Serbian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the allied troops would be in the remainder of
Kosovo as a way of enticing the ethnic Albanian refugees back to
their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees have made clear that after the terror and mass
expulsions by the Serbs they will not return to Kosovo with
Russians, perceived as Serb allies, as their protectors.
</P>
<P>
   In their statement on Thursday, the foreign ministers of the
Group of Seven richest nations and Russia left open another
contentious question: how many of the Serb forces now in Kosovo
would have to leave.
</P>
<P>
   On this issue, the Russians side with the Serbs, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the allies have always agreed that Kosovo should remain
part of Yugoslavia _ under an expanded autonomy arrangement _ the
Russians argue that the Serbs should be allowed to keep some forces
in Kosovo as part of a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In their past declarations, the allies had not stated that the
Serbs had to withdraw `all' forces, although the United States and
Britain have maintained that is what they meant.
</P>
<P>
   If Serb forces, no matter how minimal, were permitted to stay in
Kosovo, the chances of a refugee return _ the very raison d'etre of
the bombing _ would be extremely limited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTLAND-ELECT-NYT &LR;      05-06 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS IN SCOTLAND, WALES GO TO POLLS TO DECIDE LEGISLATURES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURGH, Scotland _ Britons voted Thursday in elections that
will give Scotland its first legislature in nearly 300 years and
Wales its first ever.
</P>
<P>
   The vote for more than 12,000 members of local councils
throughout Britain, the 129 members of the Scottish Parliament and
the 60 members of the National Assembly of Wales also constituted
the first national report card on the performance of Prime Minister
Tony Blair since his election two years ago, and the voting offered
an opportunity for the opposition Conservatives to start rebuilding
after their overwhelming 1997 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the polls closed at 10 p.m. Thursday, the BBC
forecast Labor winning the most seats in the Scottish Parliament
but not enough to exercise total control. If the votes bear out
that prediction, Labor would be expected to make a cooperative
arrangement with the centrist Liberal Democrats, thereby
introducing coalition politics into Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The Scots and the Welsh were exposed for the first time to
Continental-style proportional representation voting. They cast two
parliamentary ballots, one from a list of district candidates and a
second from a list of parties. To choose local councilors, they
filled out a third ballot. Final results will be known on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The two regional legislatures, along with the new one
established in Belfast for Northern Ireland, form the centerpiece
of Blair's program of ``devolution,'' the decentralizing of power
and parceling out to the regions of Britain authority long held in
London.
</P>
<P>
   Control of foreign, defense, economic and fiscal policy remains
with the British Parliament, but the new bodies will have sway over
matters like transportation, health, education and housing in their
regions.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's election amounted to a fundamental remapping of the
British political landscape. The vote here has attracted interest
from other European countries with autonomous regions, and in the
international press corps assembled in Edinburgh to cover the
elections there were a striking number of correspondents from
restive places like the Basque and Catalan provinces of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The new Scottish legislature has greater power than its Welsh
counterpart, and the race here between Labor and the upstart
Scottish Nationalists has drawn the most attention of any of the
contests across Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, celebrating his 46th birthday Thursday, called on Scots
to give a thumbs-down to the Nationalists' hopes for full
independence for Scotland, and voters at one Edinburgh polling
station seemed to be heeding his call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're independent enough as we are,'' said Robert
Docherty, a student. ``I have no worries about my Scottishness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
