<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS SLIDE AFTER GREENSPAN SPARKS RATE-HIKE JITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks fell Thursday, after Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan cast an early pall over trading with comments that
revived fears of tighter credit.
</P>
<P>
   The stock and bond markets remained under pressure through most
of the day. It was the fifth consecutive session that stock prices
switched direction from the day before. At the close, the
technology-heavy Nasdaq market had skidded 2.45 percent, or 62.17
points, to 2,472.28, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks
was down by 1.13 percent, or 15.26 points, to 1,332.05.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip Dow Jones industrials staged a late-session
comeback that briefly lifted the average into positive territory
but, unlike Wednesday, it retreated again to close with a small
loss, 8.59 points, to 10,946.82.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to citing exceptionally strong growth of the economy
and ``imbalances'' that could lead to revived inflation, Greenspan
referred directly to the stock market. The long expansion, he said,
``has induced a spectacular rise in equity prices that to many has
reached well beyond the justifiable.''
</P>
<P>
   With interest rates rising as much as 1/10 of a percentage point
along a broad front, stock-market traders once again bailed out of
Internet and other computer-related stocks and redeployed some of
this money into less expensive issues, including some of the
cyclicals such as papers.
</P>
<P>
   But other groups, including retailing and oil, slumped as well,
and analysts struggled for explanations of the recent churning and
rapid-fire rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of conviction'' in the market, said Alan
Bond, president of Albriond Capital Management. ``People have
clearly used advances to take some profits.''
</P>
<P>
   To Robert Froehlich, vice chairman of Scudder Kemper
Investments, the cashing in of profits lately has been mostly an
effort to rebalance portfolios swollen with gains in
high-technology and does not reflect a decision that cyclicals
should be bought because of improved prospects for economic
recovery abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you lighten up is where you made all your money,''
Froehlich said, contending that moving some of it into economically
sensitive stocks was simply a search for better value. ``I think
people are misreading the rally in cyclicals,'' he said, and
loading up on them is probably a mistake since the higher commodity
prices needed to sustain further big gains are unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T made the biggest impact on the Dow, surging another 5
points, to 61 15/16 following Wednesday's 5]-point advance.
Microsoft is to invest $5 billion in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Next were Alcoa, a hard-core cyclical, rising 3 9/16, to 63},
and Johnson &AMP; Johnson, a drug and medical supplies company that is
almost impervious to economic conditions, up 3|, to 97|.
</P>
<P>
   But just as many Dow stocks fell as rose. The biggest losers
were J.P. Morgan, down 3 11/16, to 135 5/16, Hewlett-Packard off 2
15/16, to 77 5/16, and Citigroup off 2 15/16, to 69 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers slumped despite stronger-than-expected April sales,
with Wal-Mart down 2 3/16, to 42~, TJX down 2 1/16, to 30{, and
Costco down 2 11/16, to 79 3/16. Mobil, falling 3 11/16, to 102},
led the oil stocks lower, with Exxon and Chevron each losing more
than 2 points. Royal Dutch, however, gained 1 11/16, to 60 15/16,
after reporting a profit decline that was less than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The battering of technology stocks took America Online down 10,
to 119}, Microsoft 1 3/16, to 77 15/16, Amazon.com 9[, to 137],
Priceline.com 11}, to 139 7/16, Ebay 11 5/16, to 175{, and Intel 4
5/16, to 59 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab, the Internet-oriented brokerage house, lost 4[,
to 103], after trading as high as 155 in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, volume eased a bit further to
879.11 million shares as advancing issues barely edged declining
ones, 1,503 to 1,490. Nasdaq volume was 909.6 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
