<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-WORK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSES PITCH IN TO HELP EMPLOYEES AFFECTED BY TORNADOES
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) By ANDREW BACKOVER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ Keith Prather showed up on Thursday at York
International's massive air-conditioning-unit plant on Interstate
35.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than taking his place on the assembly line, he picked
up empty boxes, snacks and water from a donation pantry recently
set up in the company's lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado that ripped through his southeast Oklahoma City
neighborhood left Prather, 28, his wife and two children homeless,
but York helped book the family into a nearby hotel, gave them $200
for necessities and is paying him despite his having not worked all
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is doing wonderful things,'' said Prather, who took his
family to a shelter in a mall to ride out the storm. ``They got in
touch with my mother-in-law and said they had hotels and money.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the Oklahoma City metropolitan area, companies large and
small are supporting workers who lost much, if not everything, to
the storm. Even as businesses themselves lose untold amounts due to
absenteeism, loss of power, transportation and merchandise, they
are donating food, clothing, supplies, cars, shelter and phone
service.
</P>
<P>
   Economists and state commerce officials have yet to put a price
tag on losses in productivity, spending and personal assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we are simply not there,'' said Ann Dee Lee, a
spokeswoman with the Oklahoma Department of Commerce, which tracks
manufacturers and service businesses, but not the retail industry.
``We don't know who's been hit and who hasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days after Monday's tornadoes, up to 400 of York's 1,200
employees missed work because they lost their homes, transportation
or access to day care, or they couldn't get through closed roads or
were helping others, said Becky Payton, York's human resources
manager. No employees were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The company had to shut down shifts and had trouble getting
parts in and out the door, but it still gave affected employees a
minimum of $200, rental cars, temporary shelter and access to
donations collected from employees, customers and suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wal-Mart on Southwest 19th Street in Moore, where 675
people work full- and part-time, about 100 people have missed work
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Forty employees at that store and a Wal-Mart in south Oklahoma
City have lost their homes and possessions, said district manager
Mike Moore.
</P>
<P>
   The store lost power overnight Monday and began giving away
supplies to emergency relief agencies while ``tens of thousands''
of dollars worth of refrigerated and frozen food was lost, Moore
said. With a disaster backup plan in place, the store had shipments
of replacement food the next day.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Wal-Mart has given $15,000 in cash and $25,000 in
merchandise to affected employees and nearly $40,000 to area Red
Cross agencies, Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't replace everything that was lost, but we are doing
what we can,'' Moore said. ``If it means the store is going to pay
for them to stay in a motel for a week or two, that's what we're
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Many others employers feel the same way. VIP Communications, a
wireless phone and pager merchant in Moore, set up a free wireless
phone for victims to use.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herriott, owner of Tightwads Variety Stores on North Janeway
Street in Moore, has fed 2,200 people barbecue ribs, brisket and
hot dogs the past two days in front of his business, which has been
closed without power since Monday. A nearby neighborhood filled
with his usual customers was flattened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merchandise-wise, we lost a few thousand dollars at least, and
we're lucky,'' he said, pointing to the nearby destruction. ``We
cater to the neighborhood, and there ain't nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
