<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-DEAD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6-YEAR-OLD BOY HAS NOT YET GRASPED THE LOSS OF HIS MOTHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. _ Days after rescuers found him searching
for his mother amid the rubble left by a killer tornado, Jordan
Wiese, 6, passes the time playing Nintendo at his grandmother's
house in the rural community of Bridge Creek.
</P>
<P>
   His family learned Thursday that Jordan's mother, Kara Wiese,
won't be coming home. They tried to break the news to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His only response at that time was `How come?''' said Darlene
Quiroz, Wiese's aunt and Jordan's godmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to give him time to digest it,'' she said. ``He's been
so busy, he hasn't had time to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's family has waited since Monday, when the tornado's
winds ripped Wiese from her son's tight embrace, for word of her
fate.
</P>
<P>
   Unbeknownst to them, Wiese had already been found.
</P>
<P>
   Since about 4:30 a.m. Tuesday, fewer than 12 hours after the
tornado struck, the body of a woman lay in a school turned
temporary morgue. The body was transferred to the Oklahoma medical
examiner's officer.
</P>
<P>
   There, authorities recognized it as similar in description to
Wiese.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, family members were asked to bring in Wiese's
fingerprints, taken while she was still in school, for comparison.
When the phone rang about 9 a.m. Thursday, any hopes the family had
were erased.
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning they called and said it's definite,'' Quiroz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alone Monday night in the devastated Southern Hills area of
Bridge Creek, the bruised and battered kindergartner had wandered
around searching for his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so worried about his mom,'' Quiroz said. ``He wanted to
get to someone he knew so they could help find his mom.''
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor found the boy, who was taken to Southwest Medical
Center, then released the next day to his grandmother, Mary Wiese.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the families of the 40 other people whose bodies
have been recovered, the shock of what happened is still sinking in
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Redwine can still vividly remember the ``girl chat'' she
had with her 46-year-old sister, Bonnie Price, days before Price's
only son, Jeffrey Don Price, got married last month. They discussed
what they were wearing, made jokes and laughed heartily.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the family was burying Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll cherish the memory of that conversation always,'' Redwine
said.
</P>
<P>
   Redwine did not learn until hours after the tornado that her
sister, a nurse who worked various shifts at three retirement
centers in Kingfisher, had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Price was at her late father's home in Dover when her
niece called and urged her to take shelter in the storm cellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said `Bonnie, the storm's heading right for you,'''
Redwine said.
</P>
<P>
   Price declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said `No, I'm not scared of the storm. If it comes, Ill
just get in the bathtub,'' Redwine said.
</P>
<P>
   Price was found in the rubble of the home about midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did not make it to the bathtub,'' Redwine said.
</P>
<P>
   Redwine said she believes that Price had no idea what hit her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like she just went to sleep,'' Redwine said.
``Seeing the peace on her face helped.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
