<HEADLINE>
COMPANY AGREES TO ALTER USE OF DATA GLEANED FROM CHILDREN ON WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In its second Internet-privacy enforcement action,
the Federal Trade Commission said Thursday that a
multibillion-dollar investment company had agreed to change the way
its World Wide Web site treats information it gathers from children
and teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   The agency announced a settlement with Liberty Financial Cos. of
Boston, whose Young Investor Web site has advertised itself as ``a
place to learn about money and maybe even earn some too.'' The FTC
said Liberty Financial had not kept its promise that all data
collected from users would be kept ``totally anonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, whose survey asked Web site users about their
weekly allowances, whether their parents were saving for their
college education and other financial matters, actually used the
information to identify specific individuals, the government
alleged.
</P>
<P>
   The company also failed to keep promises to send e-mail
newsletters and to award prizes in contests designed to appeal to
children, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pitofsky, the FTC chairman, said Liberty Financial had
agreed to post a more detailed privacy notice on its Web site and
to obtain verifiable parental consent before collecting personal
identifying information from children.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Thayer, a spokesman for the company, which manages assets
worth $61 billion, said Thursday that Liberty Financial had kept
the information it gleaned from children ``confidential,'' if not
strictly anonymous, and had never misused it. ``Liberty Financial
supports completely the FTC policy to protect the privacy of
children,'' Thayer said.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, in the government's first Internet-privacy
enforcement, the FTC reached a settlement with Geocities, a
California-based organization that offers members their own Web
pages, e-mail addresses and information of topics of interest to
them.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC said Geocities had lied when it told more than 2 million
subscribers, both adults and children, that it would not disclose
personal information it collected. In fact, the FTC said, the
information was used by advertisers. Geocities did not admit
wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
