<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-STOCKOPTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK OPTIONS ROIL BLACK EMPOWERMENT COMPANY IN SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Two board members of South Africa's
most prominent black empowerment company have announced their
resignations in the face of increasing outrage over a plan to award
themselves and two other board members stock options worth more
than $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company, New Africa Investments Ltd., said that its founding
directors, Dr. Nthato Motlana and Jonty Sandler, would resign as of
Tuesday, May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Motlana, 74, who was President Nelson Mandela's personal
physician and a founder of Soweto health clinics, had been the
leading beneficiary of efforts by white South African businesses to
empower blacks by breaking off large chunks of their operations and
selling them to black executives at below-market prices.
</P>
<P>
   For the last five years, black empowerment has been possibly the
most important trend in South African business. At one point, by
some calculations, blacks had gained ownership or significant
control of companies representing 10 percent of the market
capitalization on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But such deals have been criticized as creating a handful of
black millionaires without improving the lives of ordinary black
people or changing the white domination of South African business.
The shake-up at New Africa Investments, the country's best-known
empowerment vehicle, is likely to again raise questions about the
broader achievement of empowerment deals.
</P>
<P>
   New Africa Investments, the corporate face of a group of holding
companies controlled by family trusts representing Motlana, Sandler
and two other board members, was founded in 1993 and performed well
in the mid-'90s, building a huge media and financial services
conglomerate. But over the last year, the price of its shares owned
by the public have sunk to a 40 percent discount to their net asset
value.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the four board members had planned to award
themselves $20 million worth of stock options, an arrangement
largely attributed to Sandler, the only white member of the board.
</P>
<P>
   The board withdrew the proposal the day before the company's
annual meeting last month, when shareholders discovered the plan
and vehemently objected.
</P>
<P>
   The company went ahead with the meeting, but Motlana apparently
refused to answer questions on a variety of subjects including the
option proposal and other aspects of the board members'
compensation. When a shareholder noted that an annual report had
said New Africa Investments was committed to openness and
integrity, Motlana closed the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, several big stockholders threatened to sell their
shares and objected to the way the meeting had been handled.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations, which were announced late Wednesday, were
welcomed Thursday by the stock market, with New Africa Investments
shares rising by nearly 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to announcing the resignations of Motlana and
Sandler, the company said that the two remaining board members,
Dikgang Moseneke and Zwelakhe Sisulu, had volunteered to open their
pay packages for renegotiation, an extraordinary development in the
South African corporate world.
</P>
<P>
   Motlana's departure from New Africa Investments was the second
big blow to black empowerment. It followed the forced resignation
last year of Mzilikazi Khumalo as chairman of JCI Mining Co.,
barely a year after taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Under Khumalo's leadership, the company was virtually destroyed.
Khumalo's fortunes were hurt by a sinking gold price, but he drove
off other executives and secretly committed the company to buy $50
million worth of shares in a mining-exploration company he partly
owned. That deal was canceled when the board discovered it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
