<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7415 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-ART-1     05-06 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-ART-1STTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUIMA TAKES STAND IN NYC POLICE-TORTURE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: More to be filed. See also NY-LOUIMA-SCENE, NY-LOUIMA-GAYS.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly two years after leveling a police brutality
charge that shocked New York City, Abner Louima took the witness
stand Thursday and told a rapt courtroom audience a horrific story
of being tortured by two officers in the restroom of a Brooklyn
police station.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during Louima's three-and-a-half hours of
testimony, some of it brutally graphic, the 32-year-old Haitian
immigrant stood up, scanned the room and pointed at one of his
accused attackers, Officer Justin Volpe. Volpe stared back,
expressionless.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in calm, steady tones, his voice breaking only once,
Louima testified in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn that after
being arrested in a Flatbush street brawl in August 1997, he was
beaten in a police car by four officers, and that two of them later
took him into a restroom at the 70th Precinct station house.
</P>
<P>
   He said that there, while he was handcuffed and crying in pain
from a kick to the groin, one of the officers held him down while
the other thrust an object into his rectum and then his mouth,
telling him that he was tasting his own feces and warning him that
if he ever told anyone what had just happened, he would be killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officer Volpe put an object in my rectum and pull it out and
he put it in my mouth,'' Louima said, speaking in heavily accented
English.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that the object was part of a broken broomstick.
They say that it tore his rectum and bladder, injuries that
hospitalized him for two months and required two operations.
</P>
<P>
   Louima did not identify the officer who held him down, but
prosecutors have charged that it was Officer Charles Schwarz. He
and the other two officers on trial, who are accused only of
beating Louima in the police car, are white, and their alleged
brutalization of Louima, who is black, has given the case racially
charged dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe and Schwarz, along with Officers Thomas Wiese and Thomas
Bruder, are on trial on federal charges of violating Louima's civil
rights.
</P>
<P>
   In the blistering start of cross examinations that will continue
next week, Volpe's lawyer portrayed Louima not as the victim of
nightmarish police abuse, but as a money-motivated plaintiff who
was reciting a concocted, well-rehearsed story designed to win him
millions of dollars in a civil suit he has filed against the city
and police.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, contended that Louima was already
ahead of the game because he has been getting $2,000 a month from
the FBI for rent and other living expenses for himself and his
family, and additional money from supporters like the fight
promoter Don King. Those contributions, Kornberg said, has garnered
more income for Louima than his work as a private security guard
did before his encounter with police.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are making more money, getting more money per month from
the government, than you were making when you were working,''
Kornberg declared before Louima said he has been unable to work
since the alleged incident. In a series of questions about details
that Louima has given to investigators and to the news media about
his encounter with the police officers, Kornberg showed
inconsistencies intended to demonstrate that Louima's tale of abuse
is not credible.
</P>
<P>
   He noted, for example, that Louima originally had said that he
had been attacked with a plunger, but that now the prosecution says
the object was part of a broomstick. And when Kornberg resumes his
cross examination of Louima at the next trial session on Monday, he
is expected to stress two lies that Louima admitted to earlier
under questioning by a prosecutor, Alan Vinegrad.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lies, Louima admitted under Vinegrad's friendly
questioning, was that he had originally told investigators and
reporters that one of the officers who attacked him had said ``This
is Giuliani time! It's not Dinkins time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Was that true?'' Vinegrad, an assistant U.S. attorney in
Brooklyn, asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' responded Louima, his slender, 5-foot-8-inch figure clad
in a long black jacket and folded into the witness chair next to
Judge Eugene Nickerson's bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever hear any police officer make that statement?''
Vinegrad asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, explaining that he had begun falsely reporting
it at the urging of a supporter _ a brother-in-law of a nurse at
the hospital _ who told him he was an auxiliary police officer and
frequently heard polilce officers make such statements.
</P>
<P>
   Louima said the man told him, ``I must say it to get the mayor's
attention and the attention of people responsible for justice.''
Four months later, Louima testified, he confessed the falsehood to
federal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   As for the plunger detail, he said he had honestly thought the
object was a plunger because while he had not seen the object, he
had seen Volpe pick it up inside the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg on Thursday did not reach what is expected to be the
most sensational topic of his questioning, involving his suggestion
in the trial's opening arguments on Tuesday that Louima had
suffered his rectum and bladder injuries not at the hands of
police, but in an act of consensual sex with another man before he
encountered the officers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
