<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves rotation's ready to roll
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Figure this one out. Four-time Cy Young Award winner
Greg Maddux owns a 4.34 ERA, two-time Cy Young winner Tom Glavine
has a 4.61 ERA, and new Braves No. 4 starter Kevin Millwood is at
4.70.
</P>
<P>
   And still the Atlanta starting rotation, which begins a
nine-game road trip tonight in San Diego, is at its usual perch
atop major league baseball's ERA list at 3.75.
</P>
<P>
   Mathematically, the Braves owe John Smoltz and his 1.69 ERA. But
the numbers also say something else _ the other starters are
beginning to put things together.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first 15 games, Atlanta's starting pitching staff
ranked eighth in the majors with a 4.27 ERA and a 5-5 record. In
the dozen games since, Atlanta starters have gone 8-2 with a 3.20
ERA. The last full time through the rotation, each of the five
starters recorded victories, the first time that had happened since
September 1997. In the process, rookie Odalis Perez got his first
major-league win and lowered his ERA to 3.70.
</P>
<P>
   With another strong performance from Smoltz on Wednesday,
Atlanta's pitchers moved past Houston (3.78).
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be pretty happy about what's gone on,'' Glavine
said, ``because, let's face it, I haven't thrown the ball very
well; Kevin's been off and on. You've got a young guy in Odalis
who's done pretty well. So, really, John and Greg were the only
guys in the rotation who were really throwing the ball well. We've
got a bullpen full of young guys trying to get experience, and yet
we've got a pretty darn good record (19-8).
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's the encouraging thing _ that as a staff we're
not where we want to be yet, but we're still winning a lot of ball
games. So how good are we going to be when we're all pitching
well?''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood has made the biggest turnaround on the staff, bouncing
back from three subpar starts to make two good ones. He will pitch
the series opener tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood thinks peer pressure is helping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you want to be good,'' he said. ``It makes everybody
work a little harder, study film a little more, study hitters a
little more. There are three pitchers in this clubhouse who are
three of the best in baseball. I'm not going out trying to be
better than them. I'm trying to be as good as I can be, and if
that's not as good as them, then that's that. But you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   After the series in San Diego, the Braves play three at San
Francisco, Monday-Wednesday, before facing the Cubs in Chicago
starting next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
