<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TOBACCO-MONEY-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER WON'T FIGHT TO COLLECT DISPUTED $260 MILLION FROM TOBACCO
SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Miss., Texas) (rk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lawyer who was awarded $260 million from Texas' settlement
with the tobacco industry backed down Thursday from efforts to
collect the money from the state.
</P>
<P>
   His retreat followed Wednesday's accusation by the Texas
attorney general that the fee had been ``procured by fraud'' with
the help of former Attorney General Dan Morales.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of the case date from January 1998, when Texas became
the third state to settle litigation seeking to recover
smoking-related Medicaid costs from the tobacco industry. As a
result of the Texas settlement, for $17.3 billion, the lawyer, Marc
D. Murr of Houston, was awarded the $260 million by a state
arbitration panel last September.
</P>
<P>
   But other lawyers later maintained that Murr had done little or
no work on the case. And on Wednesday, Attorney General John
Cornyn, who took office this January, said in a court filing that
his predecessor, Morales, had fraudulently arranged to have it
appear that Murr had played a central role in representing the
state and for him to get 3 percent of the settlement. Cornyn's
filing alleged phony contracts between the state and Murr
characterized by backdating and false signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Morales and Murr worked together at a Houston law firm in the
early 1980s, and they have remained friends. The FBI has been
looking into the matter of Murr's fee, say people who have been
reached by investigators. Justice Department officials declined to
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said as early as last summer that Murr had played an
important role in the preparation of the state's lawsuit. And a
lawyer for Morales has called Cornyn's accusations false and
bizarre, and accused Cornyn, a Republican, of trying to damage the
political career of Morales, a Democrat who did not run for
re-election last fall but is seen as a prospective candidate for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   In his filing, Cornyn said a contract, providing a 3 percent
fee, which Murr presented to the state arbitration panel last year,
was a fake. This was the panel that ultimately awarded Murr $260
million, half the 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But in December, other lawyers in the case told a national
arbitration panel that they were not aware that Murr had even been
involved in the lawsuit. The national panel awarded Murr just $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   In their settlements with Texas, Mississippi and Florida _ the
first three states to reach accord with the tobacco industry _ the
cigarette makers agreed to pay those states' lawyers whatever
amounts were awarded by the national panel. Since that panel
awarded Murr only $1 million, the state of Texas faced having to
pay the remaining $259 million awarded by the state panel.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, at a hearing in the U.S. District Court in
Texarkana, Texas, Murr, required to show why the state panel's
award should not be thrown out, agreed not to pursue any money from
the state. That move left his compensation at $1 million from
tobacco companies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The issue that would have been argued before the court Thursday
was whether the state arbitration panel _ whose members were chosen
by Morales, representing Texas, and Murr _ had been improperly
constituted. Once Murr abandoned his fight, Judge David Folsom gave
him 60 days to change his mind, although Murr would have to go
before a new arbitration panel to argue his case.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said that he strongly doubted any such turnabout and that
his office's investigation of Murr would likely end unless Murr
again sought money from the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming Murr doesn't press any more claims against the state,
then I think those matters will necessarily be the focus of only
the federal investigation,'' Cornyn said in an interview. ``I think
our job relative to Murr will have concluded.'' But he added, ``If
I had to guess, I would say it will come up in some courtroom
someplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn declined to elaborate on that remark or to specify what
evidence of wrongdoing he had.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in Texarkana Thursday, Murr's lawyer, Roy
Q. Minton of Austin, acknowledged that one contract between the
state and Murr had been assembled after the date inscribed on it,
The Associated Press reported. ``We frequently have contracts that
are dated from the day they are effective,'' Minton said.
</P>
<P>
   Minton did not return a telephone call seeking comment on the
reason for Murr's retreat.
</P>
</TEXT>
