<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAPLAY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Heat is on!
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The team that might win the NBA title resides under the
perpetual sun of South Florida and in the shadow of vibrant Miami
Beach. But don't let that intoxicating atmosphere fool you about
the Heat. They wear hard hats, not Speedos.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Riley's club takes a physical, unrelenting, forceful
posture. It's almost as if the Heat's approach is to hound the ball
every inch of the floor for 48 minutes _ and occasionally score a
basket or two.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds ugly, yes. But it has been effective enough to place
Miami atop the Eastern Conference as the wide-open playoffs start
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits everywhere agree: There is no clear-cut favorite to win
this year's Michael Jordan-less championship. The only certainty is
that the Bulls, who won the last three, will pass the torch. They
failed to even qualify.
</P>
<P>
   So, why not the Heat?
</P>
<P>
   _ They have the best record in the Eastern Conference at 33-17,
giving them the home-court advantage for three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ They have the best coach in the league in Riley, who won four
championships with the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   _ They have MVP candidate Alonzo Mourning, who has been more
controlled and mature this season.
</P>
<P>
   _ They have an outstanding defense, second statistically to
Atlanta, allowing 84.0 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   _ They have one of the league's best postseason performers in
Tim Hardaway, who is fearless and virtually unguardable without a
double-team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right there,'' Hardaway said. ``The playoffs are a
different story from the regular season; everybody knows that. But
we've put ourselves in a position now to handle our business to get
to the finals. It's about showing now that we're coming with it
every game. No excuses. We have a team that should win.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley is especially excited because he has a healthy team. Miami
started the season without two inured starters, guard Voshon
Leonard and small forward Jamal Mashburn. Mashburn came back a
month ago and has played mostly solid ball. Leonard has been back
from leg troubles for a few weeks. Mourning overcame a bad eye to
return recently, so Riley has the full complement of players
heading into the battle royale against the eighth-seeded New York
Knicks on Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mentality of this team is that we can beat anyone,''
Mourning said. ``I don't know if anyone's afraid of us, but we're
not afraid of anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's modus operandi is to attack _ on defense. Riley is
notorious for three-hour practices if he is unhappy with his team,
and much of that time is spent working on fierce defense. They do
drills on ``blitzing,'' or double-teaming the pick-and-roll play;
on low-post defense, with a forearm in the offensive player's back;
on one-on-one defense, preventing penetration into the lane; on
aggressively trapping the ball; on double-teaming the low post, on
anything to stop the other team from scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got drills on everything and we practice them at every
practice,'' Hardaway said. ``I know I've become a more complete
player because of the emphasis we put on playing defense. It's like
this: If you're going to win, you have to play tough defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley is the purveyor of that mentality. His Knicks teams of the
early 1990s played rugged defense and forced the league to crack
down on hand-checking. It was an unsightly approach, but they
advanced to the '94 NBA Finals, losing to the Houston Rockets in
seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple,'' Riley said. ``You must develop a winning
culture to be a champion in this league, and the foundation of that
has to be defense. It's about effort, and it's about heart, and
it's about determination. At times, we put it together, and you
could think of unlimited results. Other times, there's slippage.''
</P>
<P>
   The most memorable and painful evidence of that came two
Sunday's ago, when Miami blew a 20-point lead at home to the hated
Knicks. It's a defeat that delayed the Heat coronation as Eastern
Conference champions _ and a win that catapulted New York into the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the two meet again in the first round. Their previous
series are unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   In '97 at Miami Arena, P.J. Brown picked up and tossed Charlie
Ward on his head under the basket, touching off a fracas that
involved every Knick. Leaving the bench during a melee is grounds
for suspension, so Patrick Ewing, Allan Houston and Larry Johnson
all had to sit out a game. Miami won the series.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, at Madison Square Garden, Mourning and Johnson threw
punches at each other in a wild altercation that featured New York
coach Jeff Van Gundy holding onto Mourning's leg. The Heat was the
No. 2 seed, but with Mourning suspended, the Knicks advanced as the
seventh seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those incidents happened, but they are so removed from this
team now that it's not worth talking about,'' Riley said. ``But it
was a learning experience for everyone, especially 'Zo.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning's playoff flops are undeniable, but there's also no
denying that he has played this season with an edge, not over the
edge. He still lets out primal screams during the heat of the game,
but he has shown a restraint not seen in the past, when his
emotions hampered his effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't here when that stuff happened,'' veteran guard Terry
Porter said, ``so all I can go by is this year. And this year,
'Zo's been awesome, totally professional. When he's in the lineup,
we know we have a chance to win against anybody. His presence gives
us a confidence that you get from a superstar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying we go as far as he takes us, because we all
have to play hard and well,'' Porter said. ``But if he's playing
like he's played this season, and we follow his lead, the sky's the
limit.''
</P>
<P>
   WHY MIAMI MIGHT WIN THE TITLE
</P>
<P>
   1. Their slow-it-down style. It matches the playoffs' pace. The
Heat thrive at a crawl, which is how they played all season.
</P>
<P>
   2. Their downright dogged defense. Miami always is in the game,
even when it can't score consistently, because the defense does not
allow big runs. At the same time, it can generate a decisive spurt.
</P>
<P>
   3. The dominance of Alonzo Mourning. He's the best big man in
the league. His 20-point scoring average is major, but more
important is the way he controls the lane and intimidates on
defense. On top of that, he's their emotional leader. His
enthusiasm permeates the team.
</P>
<P>
   4. Their point guard can create off the dribble in the clutch.
The Heat can clear out a side and allow Tim Hardaway to develop and
make shots for himself and his teammates. If he's double-teamed, he
is a cunning passer to the open man. If guarded in single coverage,
Hardaway is virtually undefendable.
</P>
<P>
   5. Home-court advantage through the conference playoffs. Miami
Arena is not exactly New York's Madison Square Garden or Utah's
Delta Center _ buildings where fans are rabid _ but even the
beachcombers of Miami would be ear-splittingly loud in a decisive
game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
