<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON ATTORNEY WITHDRAWS $260 MILLION CLAIM IN TOBACCO LEGAL
FEES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEXARKANA, Texas _ A friend of former Attorney General Dan
Morales abruptly withdrew his claim for $260 million in legal fees
from Texas' tobacco case Thursday, one day after Attorney General
John Cornyn accused the two of trying to secure the payment by
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn predicted that Houston attorney Marc Murr's decision to
vacate the controversial award will end Murr's chances to cash in
on part of the $17.3 billion tobacco settlement negotiated by
Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, a Republican who succeeded Democrat Morales on Jan. 1,
has accused his predecessor and Murr of falsifying signatures and
backdating two contracts in which Murr was hired to represent Texas
in its lawsuit against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   While Morales has angrily denied Cornyn's claim that the
contracts were ``fake,'' Murr's attorney conceded to reporters
Thursday that the contracts may not have been signed on the dates
indicated. But the attorney, Roy Minton of Austin, said he didn't
think that was unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, meanwhile, declared victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mr. Murr's claim is over. This is a complete and total
victory for the state of Texas and Texas taxpayers,'' Cornyn said
after Minton asked U.S. District Judge David Folsom to vacate the
arbitration award.
</P>
<P>
   The judge gave Murr two months to reopen his request. But if he
sticks with Thursday's decision, he would still earn $1 million
from the tobacco settlement _ a fee set by a national arbitration
panel to be paid by the tobacco companies. Even so, other attorneys
in the case claim he did little or no work.
</P>
<P>
   Minton made his request to withdraw Murr's claim for $260
million in a brief courtroom hearing Thursday that followed
closed-door meetings between U.S. District Judge David Folsom and
the lawyers. &UR;  &LR; Murr didn't publicly comment.
</P>
<P>
   Any effort by Murr to reopen arbitration on his fee would be
fought again by Cornyn, who campaigned against big attorney fees
paid by the state. If Folsom were to allow more arbitration, Cornyn
presumably would help pick the new arbitrators, who could be less
receptive to Murr's application than the previous panel. The three
arbitrators who awarded Murr $260 million were retired judges
chosen by Murr and Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom, in an order setting the hearing, said that one of the
arbitrators was to be named by him.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has denied Cornyn's accusations about the preparation of
contracts that Morales and Murr purportedly signed on Oct. 17,
1996, and Jan. 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the contracts ``fake,'' Cornyn said they didn't exist on
the dates they were supposedly signed.
</P>
<P>
   The October 1996 contract, Cornyn said, which provided a 3
percent contingency fee for Murr, actually wasn't created until
1998. He said the January 1997 agreement, which replaced the
earlier contract and promised Murr a ``reasonable'' fee, also was
created at a later date by shifting some signatures from another
document.
</P>
<P>
   Will Pryor, a former top assistant to Morales, said that he and
Murr both signed a contract Jan. 31, 1997, to assist Morales in the
tobacco suit. That was 10 months after the suit was filed and a
year before it was settled. Pryor, who by then was a mediator in
private practice in Dallas, said the contract called for him and
Murr to split a 6 percent contingency; it did not call for a
``reasonable'' fee, as Murr's contract on that date later stated.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor said he quit the case several weeks after signing it
because he felt uncomfortable with the arrangement. He said he was
worried questions might be raised because of his former close
association with Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Murr also has had an association with Morales, having known him
since the early 1980s. Murr also did some legal work for Morales
during one of his early political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn contends that Morales used Murr's signature on the
earlier contract, which included Pryor, to later create a separate
contract exclusively for Murr with the Jan. 31, 1997, date.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Travis County District Attorney's Office,
which is responsible for prosecuting state officials for criminal
wrongdoing, said he hadn't seen any evidence in Cornyn's
allegations that warranted a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But the accusations added to questions already raised by other
lawyers, who contended Murr did little work on the suit. Although
Morales has insisted that Murr played a crucial role in the
landmark case, often as a behind-the-scenes adviser, Murr's name
didn't publicly surface until about the time the suit was settled
early last year.
</P>
<P>
   Minton said he has ``never known for sure'' when the October
1996 contract actually was signed. And of the January 1997
contract, he added, ``We have always known that was a document put
together sometime after Jan. 31.''
</P>
<P>
   Minton said it wasn't unusual for lawyers to formalize
agreements in writing on different dates from which the agreements
actually were made.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Schenkkan, an Austin attorney representing several state
legislators who have challenged the legal fees in the tobacco case,
said it was ``certainly true that not all backdated contracts are
illegal.'' But he said the Texas Constitution prohibits lawyers and
other contractors from being paid for work performed for the state
before a contract was signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, backdating the contracts has great legal
significance,'' Schenkkan said. ``I think they (Murr and Minton)
should fold and go home. There is no way in a fair forum that Mr.
Murr will get any money at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn had subpoenaed Morales for possible testimony in
Thursday's hearing, but Morales successfully convinced Folsom to
quash the subpoena. Cornyn's allegations about fraud were raised in
his formal response to Morales' motion to quash.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said he was convinced his accusations
amounted to civil fraud on Morales' part, but he said he hadn't
determined yet if the allegations amounted to criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand by each and every word that we wrote in our
response,'' Cornyn told reporters. ``We would have been ready to
present the witnesses to back up each and every word.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said he hadn't decided what to do with his evidence now
but he didn't plan on making it public while his investigation
continued. He said the FBI also has been investigating Murr's role
in the tobacco suit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
