<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers' draft lottery is May 16
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before Thrashers general manager Don Waddell has a
chance to test his skills as a talent evaluator, he has to hope for
a little luck.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL confirmed Thursday that the lottery-style drawing to
determine the first pick in the June 26 entry draft of amateur
players will be held May 16 in the league's New York office.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers and the 11 nonplayoff teams are in the lottery. No
team can move up more than four spots from its current position or
drop more than one. Therefore, only five teams _ Tampa Bay,
Atlanta, Vancouver, the New York Islanders and Nashville _ actually
have a shot at the first pick, and the Thrashers are guaranteed to
select first, second or third.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers will be weighted second with Vancouver, behind
top-seeded Tampa Bay. Each team will be given an allotment of
numbers. The winning number will be determined by the four
ping-pong balls that pop out of a machine.
</P>
<P>
   Czech native Patrick Stefan, who played this season for Long
Beach in the International Hockey League, is considered the best
player in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion draft to stock the Thrashers with players already
in the NHL will be June 25 in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
