</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC SAYS HE THINKS `FAIR AGREEMENT' CAN BE REACHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ President Slobodan Milosevic was quoted
Thursday as saying that he believed a ``fair agreement'' on Kosovo
could be reached in negotiations with the West, ending the bombing
and allowing the return of at least some refugees.
</P>
<P>
   As is customary here, Milosevic's comment was delivered via the
state news agency Tanjug after the Yugoslav president met in
Belgrade with Karolos Papoulias, the former Greek foreign minister
and current head of the Greek Parliament's foreign affairs
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fair agreement on all the unresolved issues can be achieved
in a political process with direct negotiations, and must involve
the end of attacks, the restoration of peace and the return of
Yugoslav citizens to their homes,'' Tanjug said in summing up
Milosevic's views.
</P>
<P>
   Tanjug added that an agreement was possible as long as it
respected all ethnic communities in the region, and preserved
Serbia's and Yugoslavia's territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The reference to Yugoslav citizens may prove problematic for
Kosovar Albanians who, when they fled or were forced out of the
province over the past six weeks, often had their identity papers
and other official documents burned by Serb security forces. They
could find it difficult to prove that they are Yugoslav citizens.
Serb media have long asserted that a substantial number of the
Kosovar Albanians _ thought to number 1.8 million, or 90 percent of
the province's population before the war _ had immigrated illegally
from neighboring Albania, and were never Yugoslav citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came as the Group of Seven most industrialized
nations plus Russia announced agreement on principles for ending
the crisis over Kosovo. There was no immediate official response in
Belgrade to the plan, but during the day, government officials
spoke favorably about the chances for negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade enjoyed another quiet night Wednesday, the third in a
row that has been free of bombing, adding to hopes in the city that
the leadership is inching toward an end to the war. Fuel depots in
the towns of Nis, Kraljevo and Prahovo to the south and east of
Belgrade were hit overnight, and a fierce fire was reported to have
taken hold in Nis, southern Serbia's largest city.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in Belgrade, minds were concentrated on diplomacy. Some
members of the government kept up their strident anti-NATO rhetoric
and continued to reject the possibility of foreign troops in
Kosovo. Most seemed, however, to support the process of negotiation
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The latest gesture from the government has been to allow Ibrahim
Rugova, a Kosovo Albanian political leader, to travel to Italy with
his family. Rugova had been living in Kosovo under what the Serbs
called police protection and NATO called house arrest for the last
six weeks. He recently signed a peace agreement for Kosovo with
Serb President Milan Milutinovic, a close ally of Milosevic, and _
after almost 10 years of being virtually ignored by Belgrade _ is
now being singled out as an Albanian leader from Kosovo who is
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of Ibrahim Rugova's mission in Italy is to search for
a political settlement and continue with the political process,''
said Ivica Dacic, the spokesman for Milosevic's ruling Socialist
Party. He added that Rugova's trip to Italy was proof that he had
not been detained in Kosovo against his will.
</P>
<P>
   Dacic also held out a promise for negotiations on an
international force in Kosovo. The force had to be a U.N. mission,
he said, and the mandate, formation and time frame for the force
could be agreed upon, but ``only in direct talks'' between the
United Nations and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav United Left, the party headed by Mirjana Markovic,
the influential wife of Milosevic, issued a statement on Wednesday
saying that a diplomatic political solution was required for
Kosovo. The party had ``always been committed to negotiation,''
quoted the Beta news agency. It did not, however, go further than
the usual proposed ``U.N. presence'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The extreme nationalist Vojislav Seselj, a deputy prime minister
and leader of the Serbian Radical Party, rejected any possibility
of foreign troops entering Yugoslavia, saying that only civilian
observers would be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has changed and nothing will be changed in our
policy,'' he said at a news conference in his party headquarters.
``We have nothing to discuss with the Americans, the French, the
English or the Germans about our internal problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Seselj fills the role of the West's most extreme opponent in the
government and does not necessarily reflect the immediate
intentions of the president. He admitted himself that he had
opposed the release of the three U.S. soldiers last week without
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked for them to be tried on charges of terrorism because
they were involved in war against the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia,'' he said. But Milosevic ``decided to release them,
according to his constitutional right, and there is nothing
dramatic in that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same breath, Seselj voiced effusive praise for ``the
great activist'' Rev. Jesse Jackson who, he said, came to Belgrade
to ask for the soldiers' release. Jackson's visit received huge and
enthusiastic coverage in Serbia's official media.
</P>
<P>
   Local analysts, citing sources close to the leadership, claim
that Milosevic is now ready to accept a lightly armed United
Nations mission in Kosovo, as long as it does not contain troops
from those NATO countries heavily involved in the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The message being conveyed to the public in Belgrade is that
NATO needs a deal as much as Belgrade does. The government line
continually given out by officials and in the media is that NATO is
stuck in a bombing campaign that it cannot win and is desperate to
find a way out. Another opinion often aired by the censored media
is that the West will buckle before Yugoslavia will, either because
of strains and differences within NATO or because Western
democracies will not find the resolve to prosecute a lengthy war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
