</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL FORCE WILL NOT DISARM, KLA OFFICIAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ A senior Kosovo Liberation Army official said
on Thursday that the guerrilla force would not allow itself to be
disarmed, a central tenet of the proposed peace deal unveiled by
Western and Russian diplomats in Germany earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Jakup Krasniqi, said, ``After all that has
happened in Kosovo we cannot discuss anymore the disarming of the
KLA,'' Krasniqi said. But when pressed, Krasniqi said KLA soldiers
``would never'' fight peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Krasniqi, a high-ranking KLA political official who was a member
of the Kosovar delegation to the peace talks in Rambouillet,
France, also said that the guerrilla group would only support a
peace deal involving a NATO-led military force entering Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And in a signal of a widening rift in the Kosovar leadership, he
openly attacked Ibrahim Rugova, the longtime Kosovar political
leader who was abruptly allowed to fly to Italy on Wednesday after
being held in Yugoslavia for six weeks under conditions NATO
officials described as ``house arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   Krasniqi denounced Rugova a ``traitor'' after Yugoslav officials
announced days after NATO bombing began that the moderate Albanian
leader, who had sought a nonviolent solution to Kosovo's problems,
had reached a political settlement with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We demand a clear statement of support of our war aims and the
full withdrawal of all Serb forces in Kosovo,'' Krasniqi said. ``We
also demand from Rugova a public explanation for all events and his
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that NATO will continue to be firm in its own stance
that they will accept nothing less than a NATO-led force to enter
Kosovo. After all, this is the reason why the bombing started,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of the possibility of partitioning Kosovo, he
said, ``Partition is not acceptable. If any plan about partition of
Kosovo is put on the table, you can be sure that not only the KLA
but all the people of Kosovo will oppose it to the last man.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials, particularly Christopher Hill, the U.S.
ambassador to Macedonia and author of the Rambouillet Accord, have
backed Rugova as the true leader of the Kosovo's 1.8 million ethnic
Albanians. But KLA officials insist they are now the true voice of
Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   Some Western diplomats and Clinton administration officials have
downplayed the importance of the KLA, dismissing them as a highly
disorganized, overly secretive and largely ineffective fighting
force with little political support among Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of the expulsions of over 600,000 ethnic
Albanians from the province in the last six weeks, the group's
standing appears to have soared among refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA has proven to be a wild-card in the past, with the KLA
leaders' initial refusal to sign the Rambouillet peace accord
catching administration officials off-guard and complicating
American efforts to pressure Milosevic into signing the accord.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians will be able to live again in Kosovo with Serbs
``who did not commit crimes,'' Krasniqi predicted. And he added
that Serbs in Kosovo, who made up roughly 10 percent of the
population before the expulsions began, should receive the same
treatment as ``every other minority in democratic Europe.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Krasniqi said that the guerrilla force was voluntary but
functioned at a ``professional'' military level.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists from The Times of London and the Reuters News Agency
who spent several days on the KLA's front lines in Albania this
week reported the group's success had been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   In fighting over the last month that produced hundreds of
casualties, KLA forces have driven three miles into Kosovo, they
said. But the guerrillas have been unable to completely break
Serbian lines and create a corridor for ferrying supplies to
encircled units inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KLA forces do appear better armed and organized than they did a
year ago, they said. The guerrillas now trade mortar fire with
Serbian units inside Kosovo and displayed large numbers of mortars,
recoilless rifles, rocket-propelled grenades, and other small arms
and ammunition, much of it made in China. But the soldiers
themselves appeared inexperienced and the KLA is clearly
benefiting, they said, from NATO bombing attacks that keep Serb
forces pinned down along the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
