<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONGRESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE CONGRESSIONAL LEADERS COORDINATING STRATEGY WITH BUSH CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional leaders are working with Texas Gov.
George Bush on a coordinated campaign strategy for next year's
elections, in another sign of Bush's status as the top Republican
in Campaign 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Putting aside the traditional reluctance to get involved in
party nomination battles, House GOP leaders are treating Bush
almost as if he were the Republican nominee. Both camps hope that
the cooperation will pay off in an election that gives Republicans
bigger majorities in Congress as well as control of the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to run as a candidate who can work with the
Republican Congress,'' Bush spokesman Dave Beckwith said. ``We're
trying to make sure we're on the same page because we want to
cooperate with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said Bush is looking to members of Congress to help him
develop positions on national issues and for political intelligence
from their home states. More than 90 of the 222 House Republicans
have expressed support for Bush's candidacy, although some have not
formally endorsed him.
</P>
<P>
   His most ardent supporters include two top House leaders from
Texas, Majority Leader Dick Armey of Irving and GOP Whip Tom DeLay
of Sugar Land. Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois is publicly
neutral, but he is also considered part of the Bush team.
</P>
<P>
   Others who are actively advancing Bush's cause on Capitol Hill
are Rep. Pete Sessions of Texas, Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, Rep.
Jennifer Dunn of Washington and Rep. Roy Blunt of Missouri, who was
selected as Bush's official liason to the House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's ties with the Senate are not as strong, largely because
two senators _ Bob Smith of New Hampshire and John McCain of
Arizona _ are also seeking the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the two Texans, Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison,
the governor's chief ally in the Senate is Sen. Paul Coverdell of
Georgia. Bush is hosting a fund-raiser for Senate Majority Trent
Lott of Mississippi this weekend, but Lott is officially neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the endorsement of just about everyone up here. There
are a lot of open lines of communication,'' one House leadership
aide said. ``It's definitely unique. I've never seen anything like
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cooperation has its limits. Bush has mildly criticized
the Republican-controlled House for refusing to endorse the air war
in Yugoslavia now that it is under way. DeLay helped scuttle a
resolution of support by lobbying against it.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bush has reassured congressional leaders that
he will not make Congress-bashing part of his presidential campaign
strategy. In 1996, Republican nominee Bob Dole tried to distance
himself from Congress in an election year that resulted in GOP
losses on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're cooperating. We're not going to run against Congress,''
Beckwith said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
