</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SWEDISH PRIME MINISTER NAMED TO INQUIRY INTO MASS KILLINGS
IN RWANDA   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Sweden, Rwanda, France, Belgium)   By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan has chosen Ingvar
Carlsson, a former Swedish prime minister, as co-chairman of an
inquiry into the U.N. role in the mass killings in Rwanda in 1994,
diplomats said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Carlsson, 64, was prime minister between 1986 and 1991 following
the assassination of Olof Palme, and again between 1994 and 1996
and is known as a discreet, reserved man. He also served as a
co-chairman of the Commission on Global Governance, a private panel
that explored what could be done to ease world conflict and make
government more responsive.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's report, issued in early 1995, explored at some
length the Hutu-inspired massacre of more than 500,000 Tutsi and
moderate Hutu in 1994. The panel recommended that the U.N. charter
be amended to permit the use of force to address human rights
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats from the Swedish embassy declined to comment Thursday
on the appointment, and Carlsson could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about their views of Carlsson, whose appointment Annan is
expected to announce as early as Friday, human rights monitors
expressed relief and enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If confirmed, the selection of such a strong, independent
figure would mean that the panel is likely to insist on a tough
investigation, and that means that the inquiry will be credible,''
said Kenneth Roth, the executive director of the New York-based
Human Rights Watch. The private human rights group had harshly
criticized the United Nations, as well as France, Belgium, and the
United States for failing to prevent the genocide and for doing too
little to stop it once it began.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing his intention two months ago to launch the
inquiry, Annan said he was doing so because of the scale of the
killings and the questions that ``continue to surround the actions
of the United Nations immediately before and during the period of
the crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision followed widespread criticism not only of Security
Council actions before and during the massacres, but also of Annan,
who was at the time heading the organization's peacekeeping
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The identify of the other panelists could not be learned
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
