</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAISER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Labor Peace Plan
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Tom Abate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Phil Grauss brings a fresh new attitude to the job these days when
he dispenses pills and advice to patients at the Kaiser pharmacy in
Petaluma.
</P>
<P>
   Grauss is a leader of the Engineers and Scientists Union of
California, which recently signed its first contract with Kaiser
after an organizing drive made relatively amicable as a result of a
novel partnership between the HMO and a coalition of labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Kaiser Permanente and most of its unions agreed
to solve problems in a cooperative fashion. It included Kaiser's
promise to make it easier for unions to organize workers, and added
union members to labor-management quality councils.
</P>
<P>
   But the marriage has been controversial. Not all the unions have
signed on. Noticeably absent is the California Nurses Association,
which believes unions should keep management at arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the partnership is being closed watched. ``This is
the largest, most complex labor-management partnership in the
country, perhaps the world,'' said Pete diCicco, an official with
the AFL-CIO, who is coordinating the union end of the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Grauss' union has been one of the beneficiaries of the alliance.
It took four years of organizing before Kaiser made the 1,000
pharmacists an initial contract offer in December. After they
rejected it, Kaiser made a second offer in January for raises of 7
to 14 percent, which the union accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Despite how long it took to make the deal, Grauss is grateful
that, through the 2-year-old partnership between Kaiser and 20
California local unions, the HMO decided not to use legal tactics
that could have delayed a contract indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sort of partnership is going to work rather well,'' said
Grauss, who, as a result of the partnership, now sits on
labor-management committees to improve pharmacy service.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Oakland headquarters of the California Nurses
Association, union leader Jim Ryder speaks bitterly about ``the
sham of a partnership'' which Grauss and other union leaders
christened in spring 1997 _ while CNA nurses were striking because
the HMO had offered them a contract calling for cuts in wage and
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``CNA feels the partnership was used by Kaiser in an attempt to
defeat us,'' says Ryder, who's proud of CNA's absence from the
partnership and the militant tactics it continues to employ against
Kaiser.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between CNA's in-your-face attitude and Grauss'
patient persistence underscores the controversial nature of the
partnership, which Kaiser forged with 20 of the 25 locals that
represent the vast majority of its 70,000 California employees.
</P>
<P>
   On its surface the partnership is simple, says Dick Pettingill,
president of Kaiser's California division. ``We're creating an
environment where labor and management can sit around a table and
solve their problems with less friction, which should improve the
way we deliver patient care,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marlayne Morgan, assistant business manager of Grauss' union,
points out that Kaiser also has some very practical reasons for
making an alliance with its unions.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, many of Kaiser's paying members have always come
from union-paid insurance plans. As a result of the partnership,
the AFL-CIO promised to encourage other unions to join Kaiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't just do this out of the goodness of their
hearts,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Dany Valenzuela, Kaiser's director of labor relations in
California, says despite having had its share of strikes over its
50-year history, Kaiser had also seen itself as basically
pro-union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked across the table from each other and said, `We are
not each other's enemy,''' Valenzuela says, explaining the
labor-management pact.
</P>
<P>
   Sal Rosselli, president of Service Employees International Union
Local 250, agrees, at least, that Kaiser isn't labor's  &LR; worst
 &LR; enemy.
</P>
<P>
   If Grauss' union is the poster child for the partnership,
Rosselli's union is its chief advocate and largest member. SEIU
local 250 represents 16,000 Northern California Kaiser workers who
do every job except those of doctors and nurses.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the largest health care unions, not just here but
nationwide, SEIU views the partnership as a way to nurse its
strength. By collaborating with the generally labor-friendly
Kaiser, SEIU reserves its picket-power for the employers it
considers more hostile, like Sutter and Catholic Health Care West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kaiser isn't perfect, but it's the least offensive,'' Rosselli
says. ``They've done one big thing no other health care employer
has done _ include the rank-and-file people who provide health care
at the same table, in equal numbers, with physicians and managers
to make decisions about how care should be done.''
</P>
<P>
   One big omission in the partnership is the CNA, which has kept
its 8,000 Northern California Kaiser nurses out of this portrait of
Kaiser's labor-management conclave.
</P>
<P>
   Rosselli says CNA stands virtually alone among the larger unions
in shunning the partnership. Nurses in Southern California, and in
other states where Kaiser has offices, have joined SEIU and the
other unions in what is a national pact.
</P>
<P>
   But CNA has prominent allies who say it, and not the SEIU-led
union majority, is the best guardian of both union and consumer
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``CNA is the lighthouse for labor in the entire country,'' says
consumer activist Ralph Nader. ``They have all the old-fashioned
sense of proper militancy versus management.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader says CNA willingness to confront Kaiser, not just on pay
hikes, bit on issues like Kaiser's bid to close its hospital in
Oakland, make it a better consumer advocate than the
``deal-cutters'' at SEIU.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Anderson, who represents SEIU and the other unions in
the partnership, dismisses his critique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph Nader wouldn't know a hospital from an airline hanger,''
says Anderson. ``He ran out of issues a decade ago and he's been
trying to get involved with health care, when he doesn't live here
and he doesn't know anything about the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this, the sniping among labor factions, and the desire of
management to make public relations hay out of the partnership, has
a familiar ring to Gil Preuss, a professor at Case Western Reserve
University who has studied labor-management partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't new, but they are new to health care,'' says
Preuss, who says the steel, auto and communications industries
forged partnerships in the 1970s and 1980s, when their fields were
undergoing dramatic change caused by competition or deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's the most pressure on organizations, both sides
have the most incentive to choose one of two paths,'' Preuss says,
``either traditional adversarial relations or closer integration
and cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure certainly describes the health care industry in
September 1995, when former SEIU national leader John Sweeney, now
head of the AFL-CIO, placed a private call to Kaiser Chairman David
Lawrence. Cost cutting by insurance firms and government agencies
had the put the screws on HMOs, who turned around and sought
layoffs and wage rollbacks from workers, setting labor and
management at each other's throats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember we had our first meeting in secret at the
Dallas-Fort Worth Airport because we weren't sure where all this
was going,'' Lawrence says.
</P>
<P>
   That was in early 1996. It was more than a year before Kaiser
and the SEIU-led union coalition hammered out a written agreement
calling, in essence, for the two sides to bargain in a less
confrontational manner. SEIU and other union members voted
overwhelmingly to ratify the partnership in May 1997 _ while CNA
nurses were still staging walkouts.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser eventually withdrew its wage giveback demands and offered
all its Northern California unions, both its partners and the CNA,
small wage hikes. Leaders on both sides of the union divide still
debate whether it was CNA militancy or partner patience that won
those raises.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the contending factions argue about whether the
partnership is really giving rank-and-file workers a say in how
Kaiser does business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't Orwell's Animal Farm, you don't just get in there
and start playing manager,'' says Pete diCicco, the AFL-CIO
official who heads the partnership coalition. He cites successes,
like the new attitude at Kaiser's South San Francisco facility, a
former labor-management sore spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're down to two grievances there from hundreds
before the partnership,'' says diCicco, who attributes the change
to ``the fact that we talk differently to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Also open to debate is which approach better serves patients,
CNA picketing _ nurses rallied this week in Oakland to protest the
proposed closure of Kaiser's hospital _ or the worker-management
committees that are sprouting up throughout Kaiser's far-flung
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Preuss, the Case Western professor, says his research holds
lessons for both sides. Preuss has studied a labor-management
partnership that began in 1984, involving 14 hospitals and several
unions in the Minneapolis-St. Paul area. Though much smaller than
the Kaiser experiment, the Twin Cities partnership suggested that,
over time, cooperation yielded better staff-to-patient ratios and
other measures that improved care.
</P>
<P>
   But in what seems like a warning to labor, the 14 hospitals that
startedthe partnership have settled into three camps: one that
still hews to the cooperative line, one that has turned against the
unions and one somewhere in between.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
