</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Interviewers Who Don't Call Back
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I had a job interview on March 31, and the company told
me they'd be making a decision by April 9. April 9 passed and,
several days later, I called to find out what they had decided.
They told me that the interviewer was on vacation until April 26,
that a decision would be made upon his return and that I still was
a candidate. Now it's May, and I still haven't heard from them. Is
there a tactful way to inquire again, or should I wait for them to
contact me?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  By all means, call them. It's completely reasonable to
want to know what's happening with this job. In fact, the company
may even view polite persistence as a sign that you're really
interested in this position _ or as evidence you know how to follow
up and get things done.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure you're polite and friendly when you call, of course. You
could say something like, ``Hi, I just wanted to let you know I'm
still extremely interested in that job. Do you know when you might
have a decision? Would it be OK if I checked back with you next
week?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, don't take these delays personally. It's tempting to
get paranoid and assume that you're out of the running, but the
company may simply be moving slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation is really typical,'' said Abby Snay, executive
director of Jewish Vocational Services in San Francisco. ``It seems
like over the past few years, the hiring processes have really
gotten extended. Sometimes a company's staff is so thin that people
have multiple tasks and just have to squeeze hiring in between
everything else. Or they try to make hiring more collaborative, and
it takes time to get input from numerous people.''
</P>
<P>
   Think  &LR; you've &LR;  got problems? Career counselor Lois Reed, program
director at Alumnae Resources in San Francisco, had a client who
was forced to call one potential employer 32 separate times.
</P>
<P>
   In the end? She got the job. ``Persistence pays off,'' Reed
said.
</P>
<P>
   401(k) Fees
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently left my job and was told that I had to pay a $75
processing fee in order to take my 401(k) investments with me. Is
this legal?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no rule against charging a processing fee like the
one you describe. But such fees must meet three criteria, according
to Bette Briggs, regional director of the U.S. Pension &AMP; Welfare
Benefits Administration:
</P>
<P>
   _The fees must be authorized in the ``plan document,'' the
document that lays out the rules for your 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   _The fees must be reasonable and related to actual costs
connected with your 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   _The fees must be levied consistently on all accounts: The
company can't charge a fee to one employee while exempting another.
</P>
<P>
   Ask your plan administrator (who probably is your old employer)
for a copy of the plan document, if you don't have one in your
files. Read through it to see if it authorizes such a fee.
</P>
<P>
   You may have two bases for complaint here _ if the fee isn't
mentioned in the plan document, or if it's much higher than the
actual costs it supposed covers. (A $75 fee sounds awfully high.)
</P>
<P>
   Present your concerns to the human resources folks at your old
company. If that doesn't help, call your local office of the
Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration. In the Bay Area, you
can reach the PWBA at (415) 975-4600.
</P>
<P>
   401(k) Statements
</P>
<P>
   Q: My company recently moved our 401(k) funds from one financial
management firm to another. The last statement we received from the
former firm covered the period from April through June 1998. The
initial statement for the new firm started at September 1998. I
have asked for a statement covering July and August but have gotten
nowhere. The new firm said it must come from the old firm, but the
old firm says it's impossible to provide. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Most 401(k) plans only are required to issue annual
financial statements. There's no law saying they must issue
quarterly statements _ let alone monthly statements like you're
seeking for July and August.
</P>
<P>
   The central question here is whether all your funds were
transferred correctly to the new management firm. You should be
able to roughly answer that by comparing those two statements
covering June and September _ taking into account how much money
you deposit in your 401(k) each pay period, while allowing for some
growth or shrinkage due to fund performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to compare the two statements,'' said Briggs of the
Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration. ``See if the numbers
add up. If there's a problem, alert the plan administrator or call
our office.''
</P>
<P>
   More 401(k) questions? Along with its help line at (415)
975-4600, the PWBA offers a range of free brochures relating to
pension and retirement plans. For copies, call (800) 998-7542 or
see  &LR; www.dol.gov/dol/pwba. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
