u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      05-06 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD BE BOURQUE'S YEAR FOR THE NORRIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It had to be a shock to the greater metropolitan New York area
that Brian Leetch's name didn't _ didn't _ make the honor roll
Wednesday when the National Hockey League announced the finalists
for the Norris Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, what horror.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch has been named the league's top defenseman twice, in 1992
and '97. Now, I hate to cast a quizzical eye at the Professional
Hockey Writers Association, because I am a longtime dues-paying
member, but when I think of all the attributes that should be in
the Norris mix _ first and foremost dotting all the I's and
crossing all the T's in the defensive zone _ Leetch's image doesn't
exactly sprinkle into my mind like so much pixie dust.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of things in New York, Leetch's talents are vastly
overblown. I say this realizing that in the next few weeks he
likely will sign a new deal with the Rangers worth an average of $8
million or $9 million a year over the next four or five seasons. He
has ample hardware on his shelf _ including that '94 Stanley Cup _
and the lack of endorsement from here in the Hub of Hockey, even if
he is a former BC Eagle, won't make his morning cup of coffee turn
cold.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins captain Ray Bourque, back on the ice for the start of the
Boston-Buffalo second-round playoff series, again made the list of
finalists, alongside Detroit heavy hitter Nicklas Lidstrom and St.
Louis sharpshooter Al MacInnis.
</P>
<P>
   In case you've lost count, let's review: This is the 14th time
in 20 seasons that Bourque has made the final cut. He has won the
Norris five times ('87, '88, '90, '91, and '94) and has finished
runner-up five times ('82, '85, '92, '93, and '96). The award was
first presented in 1954 (Red Kelly, Detroit), and no one else has
as many first- and second-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Will Bourque win it this year? He'd get my vote (full
disclosure: I wasn't asked to vote). By my count, Bourque should be
pocketing his 11th or 12th Norris this year. That said, I sincerely
doubt he'll upset MacInnis, the sentimental favorite.
</P>
<P>
   No question, MacInnis is a worthy candidate. The same goes for
Lidstrom, who also can pound the puck from the point and has the
added cachet of being instrumental in two straight Cup wins. By the
time the Norris is presented in Toronto June 24, Lidstrom very well
could have a third Cup victory _ and no doubt Bourque would empty
out his own trophy case for just one Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Word around the league since midseason has been that the
35-year-old MacInnis will be a Norris shoo-in. He's a good guy, an
ever-willing interview (believe me, it counts in the balloting),
and has finished runner-up twice, both times to Bourque ('90 and
'91).
</P>
<P>
   If MacInnis wins, he'll be the beneficiary of democratic
thinking, PHWA voters distributing the vote for the sake of
breaking away from the list of suspects. It has happened before in
Norris voting. Witness 1981, when Pittsburgh's Randy Carlyle won
his one and only Norris. Carlyle had talent, and he helped make a
moribund Penguin franchise fun, but he didn't have Norris talent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some of the names who won in the year leading up to
Carlyle's triumph: How about Bobby Orr (eight straight), Denis
Potvin (three out of four years), and Larry Robinson (two out of
four years, including the year before Carlyle was selected)? But
Carlyle put in his time and he finished with decent numbers _ 647
points and a surprising 1,400 penalty minutes. He clearly was not
the game's best blue-liner that year (Potvin and Bourque were
better choices), but you just never know what happens when the
polls are open.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque is still the game's best defenseman, when we talk about
all the elements of the job, defense first, and then all other
factors given even weight from there _ leading the breakout, puck
control, innate sense of when to join the rush, when to pinch,
quarterback the power play, hold the blue line, and oh, yeah, point
production. Points should be considered last of all, but that
thinking hasn't been invoked since the early '80s, when Rod Langway
deservedly won the Norris twice for his air-tight defense in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL awards are based solely on play in the regular season.
The reason for that is obvious: Only 16 of the NHL's Original 27
teams qualify for Cup contention. But did we need a better case for
Bourque being the league's best defenseman than the double OT game
in Greensboro, N.C., last week? The 38-year-old amassed no fewer
than 53-plus minutes in a 95-minute game. He had some 40 percent
more minutes than any other blue-liner, on either side, and he
still was at his metronomic best when Anson Carter popped in the
winner. Don't forget, Bourque had the second assist.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, No. 77 was back on the beat, helping to shape
Boston's postseason fortunes. Much has been made during these
playoffs about the players who haven't suited up, either because
their teams were eliminated or they were injured. We can be
thankful, though, that Bourque, MacInnis, and Lidstrom all made it
to Round 2. Your homework over the next 7-10 days: Examine the play
of all three, and report back if you sincerely think MacInnis or
Lidstrom is better than Bourque. What, your dog ate your homework?
Understood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
