<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DOCTOR-KILLED-NYT &LR;      05-06 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DOCTOR-KILLED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE ABORTION FOE CHARGED WITH MURDERING CLINIC DOCTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Canada)  (bl) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Hoping to intensify what is already an
international manhunt, law enforcement officials Thursday charged
James Kopp, a roving abortion protester, with murdering a Buffalo
abortion clinic doctor in a sniper attack last October.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities admitted they had no idea where Kopp was or
whether he was even on this continent. But, they said, they hoped
that by upgrading the warrant against him to one for murder they
could heighten the interest of the public and police agencies in
the United States and abroad. Until Thursday, Kopp had been
classified only as a material witness in the killing of the doctor,
Barnett Slepian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here today to tell you that this man is our suspect and he
should be charged with the death of Dr. Slepian,'' said Bernard
Tolbert, the agent in charge of the FBI's Buffalo office, at a news
conference featuring a battery of top federal, state and local law
enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will find this man,'' he vowed. ``We may find him in
western New York. We may find him in the United States. We may find
him internationally. But we will find him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kopp faces charges on state and federal levels, and both carry
maximum penalties of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney for western New York, Denise O'Donnell, filed
a complaint Wednesday charging Kopp with ``using deadly force to
prevent Dr. Barnett Slepian from providing reproductive health
services,'' a violation of the 1994 Freedom of Access to Clinic
Entrances Act.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, Erie County District Attorney Frank Clark, filed a
complaint in criminal court in Amherst, the Buffalo suburb where
the 52-year-old obstetrician was slain, charging Kopp with
intentional murder in the second degree, which carries a maximum
penalty of 25 years to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said that at this point the case did not seem to meet any
of the categories of crime covered by New York's death penalty law,
like multiple murder or murder in the commission of another felony.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the charges Thursday, law enforcement officials,
who said they had no evidence so far that Kopp had been helped by
anyone, offered a few new details about the Slepian investigation.
In an interview, Clark said the authorities had identified a rifle
unearthed in April in the woods behind Slepian's home as the murder
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Tolbert said the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms had
traced the history of the rifle, but he refused to give any
information about its make or caliber.
</P>
<P>
   Slepian was slain at about 10 p.m. Oct. 23 by a single gunshot
that was fired through a rear window and struck him as he stood in
his kitchen. The sniper fired from woods about 100 feet away,
buried the rifle and fled through a neighborhood of suburban homes,
the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the 44-year-old Kopp, who is almost 6 feet tall
and has weighed between 155 and 170 pounds, was last sighted Nov.
3, 11 days after the murder, in New Jersey. Although they found one
of Kopp's cars in December in a parking lot at Newark International
Airport, the authorities said they had not been able to locate his
other car, a green 1977 Dodge Aspen bearing Vermont license plate
BFN595.
</P>
<P>
   They listed a patchwork of skills that Kopp possesses _
including carpentry, telephone and lock installation, masonry,
welding and typing _ that he could presumably use to support
himself in his underground life. They also listed three of his
aliases: Clyde Swenson, Jim Cobb and Jack Crotty.
</P>
<P>
   The officials asked anyone with germane information to call
(800) 281-1184 or (716) 856-7800, and noted that a $500,000 award
has been offered in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The heightened urgency of the investigation was dramatized by
the presence at the news conference of Bill Lann Lee, acting
assistant attorney general of the Justice Department's civil rights
division.
</P>
<P>
   By charging Kopp with murder and a federal crime of violence,
the authorities said, they hope they can persuade officials in
Washington to include Kopp on the FBI's most-wanted list and assure
the display of his photographs at thousands of post offices and
federal buildings. His name will now carry greater prominence in
national law enforcement data banks.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough that moved the identification of Kopp from a
witness to the sole suspect was the discovery of the rifle. But
officials also said they had been able to tie Kopp to the ambush
site through a fiber that matched ones found in Kopp's 1987
Chevrolet Cavalier and through a hair that they said very closely
matched Kopp's. The Cavalier was also spotted near Slepian's home
10 days before the shooting by a jogger who wrote down the license
plate number, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Should Kopp be captured, the authorities will have to decide in
what order he will be prosecuted. Clark said it made sense for him
to try Kopp first. If Kopp should win an acquittal at the local
level, the federal government, which does not have as strong a
restraint against double jeopardy, could try him again on the
charge of a deadly assault against an abortion provider, he said.
Slepian was the prime gynecologist at Buffalo's only abortion
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Donnell said her agency had not yet discussed the order of
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp is also being sought for questioning in gunfire assaults in
Canada and western New York against four other doctors, none of
whom were killed. Winnipeg Police Service Inspector Keith McCaskill
flew in for Thursday's news conference and said that the attacks
were probably linked but that Canadian police did not have enough
evidence to charge Kopp.
</P>
<P>
   According to family members, Kopp grew up in Marin County,
Calif., the child of a corporate lawyer and a nurse. He attended
the University of California at Santa Cruz near his home and
received a master's degree in biology from California State
University at Fullerton. After his parents' bitter divorce and his
sister's death from leukemia, he spent years in a search for
spiritual meaning, allying himself first with a fundamentalist
Protestant group and later adopting a spartan Roman Catholicism,
said relatives. During one period in his life, he washed his few
items of clothing in a bucket, avoided sexual contact and distanced
himself from his family.
</P>
<P>
   During that period he made contact with the anti-abortion
movement, and starting in the late 1980s, be roamed the country
going from clinic demonstration to another. Eventually he joined
one of the most zealous offshoots of the movement, the Lambs of
Christ.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
