<HEADLINE>
BU SOCIAL SCIENTIST WOLFE JOINS NEW POLICY CENTER AT BC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Alan Wolfe, the prominent social scientist and public
commentator on everything from forgiveness for a philandering
president to suburban malaise, is leaving Boston University to head
the new Center on Religion and American Public Life at Boston
College.
</P>
<P>
   The center is being billed as the first of its kind in the
nation, bringing together visiting professors, graduate students,
and public intellectuals to consider issues at the intersection of
religion and public policy: vouchers for religious schools, capital
punishment, and even the role of churches in stemming gang
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its time has come,'' Wolfe said Thursday. ``The basic idea is
that there been kind of a vacuum in American life; academics have
ignored the study of religion in the social sciences. At one level,
that contributes to the fact that organizations like the Moral
Majority have filled that vacuum. This is not a center to advocate
faith, but to have the academy think about where religion and
public life come together. I don't have a position myself, I just
want to lead the discussion because it is a discussion that has
been avoided by the academy for the past 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   While several universities have institutes or professors
studying the impact of religion on politics, Wolfe said he
envisions BC's center as a place for broader discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Historians might come there to study religious traditions
unfamiliar to them, law professors might debate cloning or
euthanasia, and social scientists could look at data evaluating
whether vouchers improve the academic performance of minority
students.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe is leaving a position as a university professor at BU,
which produced some cross-town gloating Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan Wolfe's hiring is a coup for Boston College,'' said David
Burgess, the college's dean of faculties.
</P>
<P>
   J. Robert Barth, dean of arts and sciences, said that he was
``absolutely thrilled'' to have Wolfe at BC. ``He has a keen
interest in making sure that serious discussion of religious issues
takes place in academe,'' Barth said. ``He has chosen to come to BC
because he knows that discussion will not be neglected here.''
</P>
<P>
   At BC, Wolfe will be a professor of political science as well as
the head of the center. A 1963 graduate of Temple University with a
doctorate in political science from the University of Pennsylvania,
he began teaching at Rutgers University. His 33-year academic
career has included stints as a professor or visiting scholar at
Harvard, Columbia University, City University of New York, and as a
Fulbright professor at the University of Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe is working on his 13th book, ``Moral Freedom,'' to be
published in 2001. Discussions at the center would be based on the
broad blueprint of his most recent book, ``One Nation After All:
What Middle-Class Americans Really Think about God, Country,
Family, Racism, Welfare, Immigration, Homosexuality, Work, the
Right, the Left and Each Other.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing it as a ``middle-class morality project,'' Wolfe
based that book on 200 interviews conducted across the country. His
finding was that Americans share a basic set of values.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think complexly and yearn for a sense of right and
wrong,'' he wrote. ``But they think that what is right and wrong
for themselves is not necessarily a guide to what is right and
wrong for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe starts at BC on July 1. He said the center would be in the
planning stage during his first year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
