<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-FORCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORCE STILL WINNING THROUGH INTIMIDATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the Force _ John Force.
</P>
<P>
   At least in the National Hot Rod Association Funny Car class,
where the eight-time champion has used a mental advantage to
dominate the competition since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the history of John's eight championships, there have
always been cars that are capable (of beating him),'' said teammate
Tony Pedregon, who joined Force's Castrol team in 1996. ``I think
intimidation has had a lot to do with it. I think what people have
a tendency to do when they race John, and now me, is to say, `Wow,
we have to race John now. Load it up.' That's a mistake because for
the most part these cars are on the edge anyway, and unfortunately
they go up and smoke the tires.''
</P>
<P>
   That trend has continued so far this season. Force, who beat his
teammate to win last weekend's Penzoil Nationals near Richmond,
Va., has won four of the first six national events. Pedregon, who
runs the same Ford Mustang as his boss, has won the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Force even joked about the dominance following Monday's
final-round victory over Pedregon that saw him register a
4.940-second pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked what's it going to take to beat me? I tell
them, `That's easy,''' Force said. ```Just hire my crew chiefs
(Austin Coil, Bernie Fedderly and John Medlin).' I don't know much
about these hot rods. Those guys and the team deserve all the
credit. They've worked their (tails) off.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their early-season dominance, neither Pedregon or Force
is submitting a championship acceptance speech just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have just been following our way'' the first part of
the season, Pedregon said. ``We've outperformed (the competition)
at a few races, but there have been other events where the guys
have been right there, and maybe they've just made a mistake or
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that lasting two much longer. There are cars out
there that can out-qualify John. Anytime you can do that, you can
race with him. I think they just need to settle down and focus.
Their time is near, they just need to take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a bit early. The first few races, we've run on
exceptionally good race tracks. I think that favored us. As we get
into the heat of the summer, it's going to equal and level out the
whole field. The good teams haven't surfaced yet, but it's a matter
of time before they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cory McClenathan, who had struggled for consistency during the
first five events, won his first race of the season when he
defeated Larry Dixon in Monday's Top Fuel final.
</P>
<P>
   It moved the driver of the Joe Gibbs-owned dragster to fourth in
points and he became the fourth different winner in Top Fuel this
season. Only points-leader Mike Dunn has won twice.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Capps' struggles continued last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego resident, who appeared to get out of his slump
when he qualified second in Dallas in late April, lost in the first
round last weekend to Whit Bazemore. It was the fifth time in six
national events that Capps had lost in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Capps, who finished a close second to Force in Funny Car last
season, also failed to qualify at one event.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
