<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELMS, CITING INQUIRY, BARS HEARINGS ON HOLBROOKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Neb.)  (rk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said Thursday that it would be ``insane'' to
hold confirmation hearings for Richard C. Holbrooke until the
Justice Department had turned over internal documents about its
ethics investigation of the longtime diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's toughly worded statement was made in response to a
request by two Republicans on the committee that the panel move
quickly to approve Holbrooke's nomination to lead the American
delegation to the United Nations. The nomination has been stalled
for nearly a year by ethics inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, whose panel formally received the nomination in February,
said through his spokesman that ``it would be insane for this
committee to hold a hearing on the Holbrooke nomination while the
Justice Department is withholding documents necessary for us to
review their investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional officials said Helms made essentially the same
argument to President Clinton in a telephone conversation on
Wednesday and warned him that the nomination would not advance
without the Justice Department documents.
</P>
<P>
   There are parliamentary means by which a nomination can be
forced to a vote despite the all-out opposition of a committee
chairman, but this would be very unlikely in the case of Helms.
</P>
<P>
   The two Republican senators, Rod Grams of Minnesota and Chuck
Hagel of Nebraska, offered their support for Holbrooke's nomination
and called on Helms to hold hearings as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Their request to Helms comes a week after the State Department
inspector- general cleared Holbrooke in the second of two ethics
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The first investigation, conducted by the Justice and State
Departments, ended in February with Holbrooke's agreement to pay
$5,000 to settle civil charges that he violated federal lobbying
laws in his contacts with the American Embassy in South Korea after
he resigned from the State Department in 1996. Holbrooke denied
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The second investigation, by the State Department's inspector
general, focused on speaking fees that Holbrooke received while
working as an unpaid White House envoy to the Balkans. That inquiry
ended with no finding of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Helms and the committee had requested a variety of internal
documents from the Justice and State Departments over the initial
investigation. Congressional officials said that while the State
Department had turned over some documents, the Justice Department
had so far refused to turn over any.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokesman had no immediate comment on the
request by Helms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
