<SLUG> BC-MA-UMASS-CAMPUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS TO CREATE SIXTH CAMPUS IN WESTBOROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The University of Massachusetts will announce Friday
that it plans to open a new, sixth campus this fall, the first
expansion of the state's public university since the birth of
UMass-Boston 35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   With a campus on a state-owned 36-acre parcel in Westborough,
the newest UMass branch will offer MBA and other graduate degrees
designed to appeal particularly to employees of the burgeoning
companies in the Route 495 beltway.
</P>
<P>
   That area is the fastest growing part of the state, measured in
both job creation and residential growth. The towns in the
Interstate 495 corridor saw a doubling in the number of
schoolchildren between 1989 and 1996. And while the number of
companies statewide decreased by 2.3 percent, the number in that
region increased by 13.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators have complained that UMass left a hole in that part
of the state, with graduate programs in Boston, Amherst and Lowell
all a long commute away for residents who wanted or needed to
update job skills. Corporations, too, have banded together looking
for ways to make sure the area can provide people with the skills
to fill new jobs, mostly in high technology and health care fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing here is in the very best sense a public
purpose, a public mission'' said UMass President William M. Bulger,
who will announce the plan in a lunchtime speech to business
groups. ``The nature of the university is in its land grant origin.
That defined its purpose, which was to educate the citizenry, the
idea that knowledge is infinitely expandable, and should be
available to the largest number of people possible; the recognition
that it's not just abstract ideas, there's a very practical purpose
to it. In the last century, that was agricultural training. Now,
our new purpose is defined by new needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Bulger said, the campus can make the difference for
a company considering where to locate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every economist will tell you that the most important asset
for the community when people look to locate a business is the
workforce,'' he said. ``There should be a favorable tax structure,
infrastructure, all that is critical, but nothing matches the whole
matter of workforce.''
</P>
<P>
   The UMass Center for Professional Education will open in
September with 200-300 students, eventually adding more programs
and growing to 3,000 students, putting it above or on par with
graduate schools on the five other campuses. Courses will be
staffed by professors from the other UMass campuses.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, the campus will offer a prerequisite program for the
professional MBA program. The degree programs will be added in the
next year. These programs will be 12 course, 36 credit graduate
level programs. Courses will cost $1,500, for a total of $18,000
for a degree. Many companies, Bulger said, will likely pick up the
cost for their employees.
</P>
<P>
   UMass officials worked closely with 495 companies to develop
plans for the new campus. Nine of the 20 Massachusetts companies on
Inc Magazine's list of fastest growing companies are in that
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the 495 corridor continues to grow and thrive, the Center
for Professional Education should be a great resource for Mass
Electric and other local companies who have an ongoing need for
qualified, well-trained employees,'' said Lawrence J. Reilly, the
president of the Massachusetts Electric Company.
</P>
<P>
   State Representative Barbara Gardner, the Holliston Democrat,
said she heard demands for nearby professional degree programs from
not only corporate constituents, but from residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there are a lot of people in high tech companies that
have not had the opportinity to shift gears because they could not
get the technical training or the advanced degrees they would
reqiure,'' she said. ``I can see a huge, huge population that will
want to take advantage of these programs. They're all fast-growing
communities, a lot of people are young professionals, and they've
obviously had good educations, but they're also on a fast track.
Now they'll be able to complete their education without going to
Amherst or Boston. It's higher salaries, it's more income for the
state, there's just nothing negative about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Communities in that area, Gardner said, are also struggling with
problems produced by growth, such as traffic congestion and school
construction. The new UMass campus, she said, will serve as a sort
of think tank where local officials can share ideas on how to deal
with common problems.
</P>
<P>
   The new campus is about three miles from the Route 495-Route 9
interchange, on the grounds of the former Lyman School, which was
once the state's first reform school.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1984, the historic buildings on the land have been
operated by the Massachusetts Technology Collaborative, a
consortium of public and private colleges and companies led by a
23-member board that is appointed by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The university will lease buildings on the land for $40,000 a
year. Without the demands of an undergraduate campus _ dorms, in
particular, the program will ultimately end up making money for the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the idea of education as something beyond training,''
Bulger said. ``But the land grant people recognized this other
need. I think it's the very thing we're here for, to provide this
practical kind of help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
