u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALA-HONDA-NYT &LR;      05-06 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-HONDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDA ANNOUNCES PLANS TO BUILD $400 MILLION FACTORY IN ALABAMA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Ohio, Ky., Tenn., Mich. and Ind.)   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ In the latest sign that foreign auto manufacturers are
shifting toward bigger vehicles and moving south in the United
States, Honda announced Thursday that it would build a factory in
rural Alabama to assemble large sport utility vehicles and Odessey
mini-vans.
</P>
<P>
   Honda Motor Company Ltd. said that it would spend $400 million
to erect the factory in Lincoln, 40 miles east of Birmingham. The
Mercedes division of DaimlerChrysler AG makes its M-class sport
utility vehicles in Tuscaloosa, Ala., which is 50 miles southwest
of Birmingham, while Bayerische Motoren Werke AG is preparing to
produce BMW X5 sport utility vehicles in Spartanburg, S.C., for
sale beginning in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly going to be sport utility alley down there,''
said Michael E. Robinet, the director of forecast services at CSM
Worldwide Inc., which is based in Northville, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Honda executives and Alabama officials said that the state had
agreed to provide incentives valued at $158.4 million, including
$102.7 million worth of roads, utilities and land for the site; the
rest of the money would be in tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   Southern states have been very successful in luring automakers,
partly because their anti-union laws and traditions make it hard
for the United Automobile Workers union to organize workers and
partly because the states offer particularly generous incentives.
Honda executives were defensive about the incentives, saying that
they were taking Alabama's standard offer for new businesses
entering the state, and had not demanded a special arrangement.
Still, state officials went out of their way Thursday to present
Alabama as being open to outsiders, with Gov. Don Siegelman using
several Japanese phrases to welcome Honda during a press conference
in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Koichi Amemiya, chief operating officer for the Americas at
Tokyo-based Honda, said that the factory would start production in
early 2002 and reach full production a year later, when it is
expected to employ 1,500 people. The factory will be capable then
of producing 120,000 vehicles and 120,000 engines a year; the
engines and vehicles will be produced in a single, large building
instead of two separate factories, marking a change from
traditional auto assembly techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas G. Elliott, Honda's executive vice president for U.S.
operations, said that the new factory was needed because of strong
demand for so-called light trucks, a lightly regulated class of
vehicles that includes pickup trucks as well as sport utility
vehicles and mini-vans. While Honda refused to identify the sport
utility vehicle, it is expected to replace the Honda Passport,
which will be somewhat larger.
</P>
<P>
   The same brisk demand has prompted General Motors Corp. to
announce plans to expand its factory in Arlington, Texas, and
consider converting a car factory in Oklahoma City to light-truck
production. Toyota Motor Corp. has just built a pickup truck
factory in Princeton, Ind., where it also plans to start making
full-sized sport utility vehicles soon. DaimlerChrysler AG plans to
replace an aging Jeep factory in Toledo, Ohio, with a larger modern
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Japanese automakers have put most of their operations
in southern Ohio, Kentucky and Tennessee, staying close to
Interstate 75, which runs to Detroit and provides ready access for
auto parts companies. But suppliers have also been moving to the
south to reduce labor and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Lincoln is named for Gen. Benjamin Lincoln, a
Revolutionary War hero, not for President Abraham Lincoln, who
served during the Civil War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
