<HEADLINE>
RADICAL SURGERY WILL TEST COURAGE OF 5-YEAR-OLD CANCER PATIENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Five-year-old Nicole Andrewson has been brave
through months of chemotherapy and radiation to fight a deadly
cancer gnawing at her left thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she begins a still-greater test of her courage.
</P>
<P>
   About noon, surgeons at the University of Kansas Medical Center
will begin a rare operation on this Wichita-area girl to salvage
what they can of her leg.
</P>
<P>
   They will amputate her leg at the hip, remove the diseased
portion of her thighbone, rotate the leg 180 degrees so that her
foot faces back, and then use three or four screws to reattach the
thighbone to her hip.
</P>
<P>
   When the surgery is complete, her knee will serve as a new hip
joint. Her ankle will serve as her knee. And a prosthetic lower leg
will be fashioned that will attach to her foot.
</P>
<P>
   The operation could last until midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole is a spindly little girl. Her blond hair has just started
growing back after cancer therapy took it away. Hints of mischief
and anxiety pass quickly over her face. What remains is a look of
determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got a stubborn streak in her,'' her mother, Kimberly,
said Thursday as Nicole waited for final blood tests at KU Medical
Center. ``She's bound and determined she's going to get over
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole knows exactly what she faces.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have been frank, telling Nicole about her condition,
said her grandmother, Nancy Bye. Nicole has taken it in stoically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed. She can handle emotions adults can't handle
sometimes,'' Bye said.
</P>
<P>
   When Nicole's mother asked her on Thursday where on her body
doctors would operate, Nicole rubbed her left thigh with her hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to go underneath?'' her mother asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fake leg,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole was diagnosed a year ago with Ewing's sarcoma. It's an
aggressive bone cancer that usually strikes young people.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole had been complaining for some time about knee and leg
pains, but doctors thought initially it was just the result of
growth spurts.
</P>
<P>
   That was until the day last May, when her leg swelled and she
wouldn't stop crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got into a chair and she just lay there in pain,'' her
mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole's doctor referred her to specialists who discovered the
cancer. Then came radiation and rounds of chemotherapy that lasted
almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were days she was scared, getting blood pulled from her
and medication put down her,'' her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout it all, she has clung to her big pink stuffed
elephant called a Puffalump. The tattered animal is going into
surgery with her today.
</P>
<P>
   For a child in Nicole's situation, there are no easy
alternatives, said Kim Templeton, her surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   More radiation might not eradicate the cancer, and may itself
induce cancer later on. A full amputation of Nicole's leg would
eliminate the cancer, but would make rehabilitation difficult.
</P>
<P>
   So Templeton is performing a procedure called a rotationplasty.
It's so rare she has done it only one other time, while in surgical
training. The surgeon she was assisting on that operation had never
done the procedure before.
</P>
<P>
   It will take six to eight weeks for Nicole's leg to heal where
it will be reattached to her hip. At that point, she'll receive a
prosthesis.
</P>
<P>
   Templeton said Nicole should eventually be able to play football
and wrestle, her two ambitions after surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a fairly indestructible reconstruction. The leg
itself should be able to tackle pretty much anything,'' Templeton
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nicole will need physical therapy to learn how to use her
ankle as a knee joint. To straighten out her leg, she will have to
point her foot down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing in a young kid like this how quickly they catch
on,'' Templeton said.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologically, however, the healing may take longer. So far,
the one subject certain to upset Nicole is how her foot appears
after surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you still worried?'' her mother asked her. ``Are you still
worried about your foot?''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole nodded.
</P>
<P>
   Templeton thinks Nicole will grow to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's different, but that's OK,'' the surgeon said.
``You've got to understand, the long-term goal is to keep her
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   And that will take all Nicole's courage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
