<HEADLINE>
GONZALES FAMILY RECALL JOY OF SEEING SON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDSTUHL, Germany _ The anxious nights were over, their son was
free and standing before them after a month in Serb hands, but
emotion had robbed Rosie and Gilbert Gonzales of the right words.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out they were not needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just hugging him,'' Rosie Gonzales said Thursday at
Landstuhl Regional Medical Center, recalling her Monday reunion
with her son, U.S. Army Spec. Steven Gonzales of Huntsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just walked in the room. I saw him. I couldn't believe it.''
she said. ``I just wanted to grab a hold of him and not let go. And
tell him I love him. I didn't want to let him let go.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, 22, Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek,
Mich., and Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles were
brought to the hospital and joyous reunions with their families
after Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic released them at the
urging of U.S. political activist Jesse Jackson. They had been
captured March 31 along the Macedonia-Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   The Gonzaleses, along with Gilbert's sister, Rosie Barrow, left
Texas on Sunday for the reunion. Gilbert brought his son a souvenir
from home _ a Texas A&AMP;M University T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to see that he had gone through the whole thing and that
they brought him home in one piece,'' Barrow said. ``We are just so
grateful and thankful.''
</P>
<P>
   After three days of visits scheduled between their son's medical
checkups, psychological evaluations and military investigations,
the family traveled to Wurzburg, where the three soldiers were
decorated.
</P>
<P>
   They then went to nearby Schweinfurt where Gonzales was one of
the lowest-ranking members of the First Squadron, 4th U.S. Cavalry
ever to be inducted into the ``Order of the Spur.''
</P>
<P>
   The honor of wearing spurs is usually reserved for sergeants and
higher-ranking officers who earn the right after mastering cavalry
skills. Stone and Ramirez, who already wear the spurs, put one on
each of Gonzales' boots during a welcome home ceremony at the base
in Schweinfurt, where the three are stationed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a state of shock, receiving my spurs,'' Gonzales told
the hundreds of soldiers and their families who waved U.S. flags
and yellow ribbons. ``It's a great gift.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said Thursday the three soldiers had been beaten
with rifle butts, kicked and punched as they were captured and that
initial interrogation sessions had been harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Kenneth Bacon said in Washington the Army has
concluded ``beyond a shadow of a doubt'' that the three soldiers
were on the Macedonian side of the border when they were captured,
not on the Yugoslav side as Yugoslav authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were taken by a substantially larger force,'' Bacon said.
``I don't know how much larger, but they felt that they didn't have
any alternative but to stop. And, in fact, as they tried to get
out, they ran into an obstacle, which I believe was a ditch, which
also made it difficult for them to get away.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors found a stitched-up wound on the top of Ramirez's head
and two fractured ribs. Stone was found to have a broken nose.
Doctors said Gonzales ``turned out fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Each soldier spoke briefly at the welcome party Thursday,
thanking Jesse Jackson and the group of clergy who negotiated their
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to thank the Lord, our God,'' Gonzales said. ``For he
was truly my fortress and my refuge during our captivity.''
</P>
<P>
   In prison, Gonzales said, he held on to the belief that his unit
heard their radio distress call when the three were captured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the faith that they were doing all they could and that
we would soon be home,'' he said. ``It's great to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony the soldiers were scheduled to return to
Landstuhl where they will be given leave Friday. Gonzales was to go
home to Texas with his parents for a 30-day leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take him home with us,'' Rosie Gonzales said.
``Family is very important to him. He wants to go spend some time
with us.''
</P>
<P>
   After his leave, she said, he will return to his unit in
Schweinfurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing really, really well,'' she said. ``He's upbeat.
He's full of life, and he's ready to go out there and tackle it.
He's looking forward to going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through many emotions over the last month,'' she
said. ``It was difficult. You always worry about your children but
you never can imagine that something that horrible could happen. It
was a real rough time, but we made it through.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turned 22 during captivity. He can never forget that. But
he had so much love and support from a wonderful family, from his
friends, that I think he is going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
