<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS WON'T START COLD THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Skirmish. It's an excellent word, as used by Jeff Van
Gundy Thursday in a sentence that began, ``If a skirmish comes
about, and inevitably it will. ...''
</P>
<P>
   The coach of the Fightin' Knicks would naturally know all about
skirmishes going into yet another playoff series with the Fightin'
Heat of Pat Riley.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks and the Heat put up their dukes starting at 12:30
p.m. Saturday in Miami. Don't hold hot coffee or cold soda in your
lap if you're seated in the first few rows.
</P>
<P>
   According to my Funk &AMP; Wagnalls _ hey, you think Walt Frazier's
got the only dictionary? _ the word ``skirmish'' has roots in old
French and old High German, and refers to the act of fencing or
preliminary fighting between small parties: ``Any encounter or
action that evades the main contention or business.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds about right with these two teams. They have
skirmishes from time to time when Coach Riley's lads wield their
elbows and the Knicks do the same. The trick is to avoid letting
the skirmishes take you out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy thinks the Knicks got themselves in trouble in last
year's playoff series with Miami by being too gentlemanly, too
polite, too kind. He suggests that he and the Knicks had dweled too
much on the 1997 playoff series, when P.J. Brown and Charlie Ward
started scuffling, and most of the Knicks' bench went galloping off
to investigate, despite the pleas of wise old heads Buck Williams
and Herb Williams. The Charge of the Light-Headed Brigade cost the
Knicks the services of most of their starters in either the sixth
or seventh games, both of which they lost. The memory of looking
like blockheads, coupled with reminders from the league, the team,
the news media and the fans caused the Knicks to come out as if
anesthetized last year, when they lost to Miami, 93-83.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we did a poor job,'' Van Gundy said Thursday,
including himself first in his criticism, as he always does. ``They
played with great intensity, and we played with great poise.''
</P>
<P>
   Both traits are preferable, but Van Gundy would prefer intensity
to poise, and so would his former employer.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing thing about last year's series was that the Knicks
responded by winning the second game and then the fourth game, in
which Alonzo Mourning and Larry Johnson had themselves a downright
ugly fistfight between two lugs who do not like each other.
</P>
<P>
   That skirmish is now famous for the sight of Van Gundy's hanging
on to Mourning's leg like a terrier trying to subdue a Clydesdale.
</P>
<P>
   Both players were suspended for the fifth game, which only
proved that Mourning was far more valuable than Johnson, then and
now. The Knicks won, 98-81, but Van Gundy does not want to take any
chances with a placid opener on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last season we were almost complacent,'' Van Gundy told the
press Thursday, knowing the message had time to be passed along to
his players. ``They handed our heads to us,'' Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Van Gundy hastened to add: ``I don't think they will be
thinking about fighting. That's a fascination coming from the
outside.'' Still, he can understand why people are a bit
preoccupied by the potential for skirmishes _ ``since it happened
two years in a row,'' Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   He knows there is a history here. He was seen-but-not-heard
assistant to Riley in New York, a loyalist, a friend. He doesn't
even want to hear questions about the last time he spoke with
Riley, etc., etc. It's an old story. Nor does Van Gundy want to be
identified with Riley's code for success, often explained between
hard covers or lucrative motivational speaking gigs. One trademark
of Riley players is never, ever helping opponents off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a rule, but I don't know why you'd want to,'' Van
Gundy said Thursday, referring to offering a helping hand. ``You
fouled him. You didn't commit a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not surprised that Riley is trying to work up indignation
that the Knicks allegedly feel they have an advantage in a short
series with the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   `That's their mantra,'' he said. ``We want them? Nobody would be
foolish enough to want a No. 1 seed. It's almost as if they're
underdogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he said, ``I want us to defend with the desperation of
underdogs and play with the poise of favorites.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy is much too professional to ever think the Knicks
could or should save his job with a passionate last stand. He knows
there will be a skirmish here and there, but he doesn't want one to
take them out of the series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
