<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PEACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ELEMENTS OF A PEACE DEAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, May 7:
</P>
<P>
   Much diplomatic work remains, but the framework for a reasonable
political settlement in Kosovo may be falling into place, thanks in
part to Russia's constructive role as a peacemaker. A critical move
came Thursday, when Moscow parted company with Serbia and formally
endorsed the use of an international security force in Kosovo after
the war ends. In joining the United States and its allies in
support of this and other core principles for a peace deal, Russia
has left Slobodan Milosevic increasingly isolated in his fight with
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's action can tip the Balkan war toward resolution, but
only if Milosevic is ready to accept some of the terms that he
rejected two months ago, before the NATO air war began. President
Clinton, for his part, will have to insure that the details of any
accord hold fast to the principles he and other NATO leaders have
enunciated. Milosevic will doubtless be looking for every advantage
he can find if negotiations begin in earnest, and sound guidelines
will mean little if the actual terms of a settlement are vague or
unenforceable.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Russia now agree that an effective
international security force must be positioned in Kosovo once the
war ends to prevent further ethnic conflict and to assure the safe
return of more than a million displaced ethnic Albanians. That is a
pivotal agreement, and marks a significant shift in Moscow's
position. But the composition, command and precise role of such a
force was not addressed in the joint statement issued Thursday in
Bonn by the United States, Russia, Britain, Germany, France, Italy,
Canada and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   To be effective, the force must include NATO and Russian
soldiers and be adequately armed. It will need robust rules of
engagement and commanders willing to use them to prevent future
Serbian attacks and to discourage ethnic Albanian guerrilla
fighters from assaulting Serbian targets in Kosovo. The mandate for
the force should come from the United Nations Security Council, as
the Bonn statement suggested. That would help overcome Serbian and
Russian concerns about placing foreign troops on Yugoslav soil.
</P>
<P>
   The other principles that Russia endorsed Thursday echo ideas
that Moscow had previously approved, but they remain important to
any settlement. They include the withdrawal of Serbian forces from
Kosovo, the need for temporary international administration of the
province once the war ends and the eventual restoration of
substantial self-government in Kosovo. It will not be easy to
develop a detailed agreement with Serbia on any of these issues,
especially if Russia fails to press Milosevic to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
   There is not yet sufficient reason to suspend the bombing, and
there will not be until Milosevic calls off his murderous assault
on Kosovo, starts withdrawing his troops and commits himself to the
Bonn principles. Only then can serious negotiations commence. But
for now, at least, it is a hopeful sign that Russia has
reconsidered its reflexive support for Milosevic and seems
determined not to let the war in Kosovo shatter its ties with the
West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
