A7452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-WHITMAN-NYT &LR;      05-06 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WHITMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE TEST FOR GOVERNOR WHITMAN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, May 7:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey is facing a leadership test
that will provide a measure of her fitness for higher office. For
years she ignored or minimized complaints that state troopers were
engaging in racial profiling, the practice of stopping motorists
based on their skin color. Now, even as racial profiling is
belatedly being curbed, she is pushing hard to get her attorney
general, Peter Verniero, a seat on the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero not only had oversight responsibility for the police
agency that engaged in the profiling, he has been judged
unqualified for the court by the state bar association. By trying
to muscle this nomination through the state Senate, Whitman has
shown herself more concerned with rewarding a flawed political ally
than with making a high-quality judicial appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Black and Latino legislators in New Jersey strongly oppose
Verniero's nomination because he failed to investigate
discrimination complaints in a timely manner. Only recently has he
issued a report acknowledging that racial profiling by troopers
exists, and the state is now entering into settlement talks with
the U.S. Department of Justice to end the practice. Verniero's
promotion would be a slap to minority communities that believe he
should have attacked the problem years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman seems, however, to care little about anger in those
communities or about the opinions of the legal community. The state
bar association's judicial and prosecutorial appointments committee
has found that Verniero is not qualified for the Supreme Court
because he lacks legal experience. Verniero has tried no cases
before juries, has no judicial experience and lacks a substantial
record of legal accomplishment. His claim to fame is his utter
loyalty to Whitman and his service as a chief political aide in the
Whitman administration for the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the Republican-controlled state Senate, support for
Verniero is soft. If he wins Senate confirmation next Monday, it
will probably be by only one or two votes. The Republicans may end
up placing him on the court to avoid either undermining Whitman
before her Senate race or incurring her wrath for the next two
years. Unfortunately, New Jersey residents may have to live with
Verniero on the court for the next 30 years, long after Whitman and
her allies have passed from the scene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
