u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUSTICE-SPY-CASE-NYT &LR;      05-06 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUSTICE-SPY-CASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.M.) 
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT TO INVESTIGATE HANDLING OF SPY CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday that the
Justice Department would examine whether federal authorities had
mishandled the investigation of a nuclear scientist suspected of
spying for China.
</P>
<P>
   Reno announced the internal inquiry one day after Republican
senators accused the Justice Department and the FBI of repeated
lapses in a national security investigation of the scientist, Wen
Ho Lee, over nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to review everything we've done to see if there is
anything that could have been done differently,'' Reno said
Thursday at her weekly briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's willingness to re-examine the case was an indication that
the China espionage inquiry is emerging as a potentially
embarrassing issue for the department as criticism from Congress
intensifies. The review was first reported Thursday by The
Washington Times.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing on Wednesday, lawmakers expressed outrage over the
many aspects of the case, but their complaints seemed to focus on
the Justice Department's refusal in 1997 to allow FBI agents to
examine Lee's office computer.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico
have said that the Justice Department's stance on the case kept
them from spot-checking Lee's computer, fearing it might taint a
possible case against him.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's refusal to allow a search of the
computer kept authorities from knowing, for nearly two years, that
Lee had routinely transferred into an unclassified network millions
of lines of secret computer codes used in the development of
advanced nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   FBI counterintelligence officials sought permission from the
Justice Department to use more aggressive investigative techniques
against Lee in June 1997 through a warrant obtained under the
Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act. Usually, such applications
seek permission to search or wiretap a suspect's home or office.
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department turned down the application because,
as one official put it Thursday, it lacked ``currency,'' meaning
that the evidence against Lee was too dated and insubstantial.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials appealed the decision to Reno, but the
subordinates who reconsidered the issue rejected the application a
second time later in 1997. Other officials said Thursday that the
FBI did not specifically ask for permission to search Lee's office
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Reno said that the sequence of decision-making that
held back the agents remained unclear. In part, she said, the
review will seek to unravel what happened between officials at two
agencies that frequently tangle over legal standards and strategies
in criminal and espionage cases.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, a routine bureaucratic fight may have far-reaching
consequences. When agents finally opened Lee's computer earlier
this year, they discovered that he had transferred files from 1983
through 1995, and officials have said there is evidence that
someone else examined the files once they were in the unclassified
system. Still, there remains no evidence that Lee passed the code
information to the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the review would reach back nearly two decades to
examine whether authorities had responded seriously to signs, some
of them blurry, suggesting that employees at the U.S. weapons labs
were engaged in espionage. In part, the effort parallels White
House efforts to spread responsibility for any lapses to previous
Republican administrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes back to 1982,'' Reno said. ``We've got to look at what
was done since that time, what we can learn to make sure we did
everything right, that our predecessors did right. And by right, I
mean that they did or we did it in the best way possible,
consistent with the law, to protect national security.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who was fired in March, has not been charged with any
crime, and his lawyer has denied that he did anything wrong.
Law-enforcement officials said that reconstructing Lee's past
activities to determine whether he engaged in espionage had proven
difficult. Chinese officials have said they did not pilfer American
nuclear secrets, but have not discussed the specifics of the case.
</P>
<P>
   The administrative review will be led by Justice Department
lawyers and FBI agents who were not involved in the original
inquiry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
