<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.D.)  
 EDITORIAL: MISPLACED PATRIOTISM   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, May 7:
</P>
<P>
   The nation owes two principled Democratic senators from North
Dakota its thanks. Kent Conrad and Byron Dorgan have both announced
that they will oppose the so-called Flag Desecration Amendment
approved by an 11-7 margin in the Senate Judiciary Committee last
week. The amendment, which would allow federal laws banning flag
desecration, is a sad example of patriotism gone awry. It would
undermine the right of free expression in the name of protecting
the flag that symbolizes that freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Following the committee's action, Conrad and Dorgan, whose votes
were considered key, announced that they intended to vote ``no'' on
the amendment, much as they both did on the last Senate go-round in
1995. That leaves the amendment at least two votes shy of the
two-thirds majority required for passage by the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been debating the amendment on and off since 1989,
when the Supreme Court, in a controversial ruling upholding the
First Amendment, held that flag-burning was constitutionally
protected free speech. It is time to move on. Having no epidemic of
flag desecration to point to since the court spoke, Judiciary
Committee chairman Orrin Hatch, the amendment's leading Senate
sponsor, ought to drop this destructive effort to weaken the Bill
of Rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
