A7459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPY-RETIRE-NYT &LR;      05-06 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPY-RETIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIA'S TOP SPY TO STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jack Downing, a legendary cold-warrior who came out
of retirement two years ago to help revive the CIA's badly depleted
clandestine espionage service, is stepping down as the agency's top
spy, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Downing, 58, the only man in the CIA's history to serve as
station chief in both Moscow and Beijing, said in an interview that
he would retire from his post as director of the agency's
directorate of operations at the end of July. He will be succeeded
by his deputy, James Pavitt, 53, who in addition to a career in
espionage has also been exposed to Washington politics and policy
through a stint at the National Security Council at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Downing, who was coaxed out of retirement in 1997 by the
director of central intelligence, George Tenet, is one of the last
of a generation of CIA officers who spent their careers fighting
and winning the Cold War. Unlike many of his contemporaries, who
retired soon after the Soviet Union's collapse, the Aldrich Ames
spy scandal and drastic budget cuts, Downing returned to help pull
the agency out of its post-Cold War identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   His return has parallels to the fictional return of George
Smiley, the spy master who, in the novels of John le Carre,
returned to save British intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   During his two-year tenure, Downing focused his efforts on
hiring a new generation of case officers to fill the holes left by
the turnover that occurred at the end of the Cold War. Downing also
laid out a five-year plan establishing a strategy for the agency to
handle post-Cold War intelligence challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Downing tried to turn around the depressed morale and
aversion to risk that had taken hold inside the agency by the time
of his return. Bureaucratic imperatives and intense political
oversight had, by the mid-1990s, begun to strangle the willingness
of CIA case officers to risk conducting secret operations.
</P>
<P>
   Downing said that he had ``grave doubts about coming back,'' but
that he has loved his return to the spy world.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet said Thursday that Downing's return had been critical to
helping the service recover from the malaise. ``He's a legend who
will never be fully appreciated by the American public because he
did so much in anonymity,'' Tenet said. ``But you can't brand him
just as a cold warrior. He bridged two eras, and brought new
thinking to the problems the agency has today.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his latest tour was not the first time Downing was
asked to pull the CIA out of a crisis. In 1986, he was sent to
Moscow as station chief after the KGB had arrested most of the
CIA's Russian agents. At the time, the CIA did not know that Ames,
a mole inside the agency, was the cause of the losses. Downing
stayed in Moscow until 1989, rebuilding the agency's Soviet
network.
</P>
<P>
   He retired the first time in 1995 after a tour as Beijing
station chief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
