<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE LEERED. DID HE LEARN?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used in
the final graf instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable to
some newspaper systems.) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. During a recent office trip to a regional meeting, I had a
run-in with one of the top executives. On the return bus ride, the
executive, having had one too many that evening, took the seat next
to me and proceeded to make advances _ verbal and physical _ for
two hours. Not wanting to cause a scene, I sat quietly, trying to
steer the conversation in a safe direction. (Many of my co-workers
were asleep and probably didn't witness the incident.) The next
day, the executive acted as though nothing had happened. After
several days, I confronted him. He apologized and expressed great
embarrassment. Three weeks later, I'm still enraged, hurt and
uncomfortable at work. What should I do next?
</P>
<P>
   A. For what it's worth, you are far from alone. Such stories are
so depressingly common _ even in the 1990s _ that someone should
write a column aimed at unenlightened corporate executives and call
it ``10 Ways to Convince Women at the Office That You're a Complete
Jerk.'' Its first recommendation would be ``Get tanked and drool
sweet nothings into her ear.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, you were correct to confront the executive, said
Elizabeth Lansberg, a lawyer at Equal Rights Advocates, a women's
group in San Francisco. ``That's always the first step,'' she said.
``We counsel women that, if they feel comfortable enough, they
should talk to the harasser and say clearly that they don't like
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the executive did have the good sense to apologize.
His chagrin, though no excuse for his boorishness, suggests he's
not a total heel _ at least not when he's sober.
</P>
<P>
   So where to go from here? Legal action isn't really an option at
this point, said Martha Davis, legal director at the NOW Legal
Defense and Education Fund in New York. It is rare for courts to
rule that a single incident constitutes sexual harassment. (Most
such cases have involved sexual assault.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for that rule of thumb _ if it's a single incident,
it has to be severe _ is based on the idea that in the workplace
you have to have something of a thick skin,'' Ms. Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to pursue the issue, check your company's internal
grievance procedure. Such procedures have become more common as
companies try to protect themselves against liability in harassment
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Filing a grievance could have therapeutic value, Ms. Davis said,
and could result in a reprimand of the offending executive. But be
aware that your action could make it even more awkward for you to
work with him (although overt retaliation on his part, of course,
would be illegal).
</P>
<P>
   If you sense that he is truly sorry, you may want to let the
issue rest _ for now. Find a sympathetic friend or two to help you
work through the anger. Be cautious, however, about discussing the
matter at work. Once a story enters the rumor mill, it takes on a
life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts also recommend that you write down everything _
from first boozy leer to final apology _ and keep the document
safely at home. Should anything else happen, you'll be in a much
stronger position to teach Lothario a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York, NY
10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
