while trying to find belongings in what is left of her house on
Thursday. What is left of the 900 block of Windermere Drive is now
a jumble of splinters, shards and half-loaded pickup trucks
following this weeks tornadoes. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
Eds: Those in the photo refused to be identified by name.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WEST POINT, N.Y. -- May 6, 1999 --
WEST-POINT-FUNDRAISING, 5-06 -- Cadets walk to a class on the
academy's campus on Thursday. Forced to compete with increasingly
wealthier universities and on a tight post-Cold-War defense budget,
the United States Military Academy at West Point on Friday will
announce the first major private fund-raising campaign in the
history of the service academies. (James Estrin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) TRENTON, N.J. -- May 6, 1999 -- AMERICAN-STANDARD, 5-06
-- Coaches at American Standard, makers of plumbing supplies, air
conditioners, and truck brakes, to name a few, sheperd the careers
of the company's employees. Earl Berg, right, a coach, talks with
Perry Gilbert, the team leader of an assembly line at Trane, about
Gilbert's advancement possibilities within the company. Trane is
owned by American Standard. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- May 6, 1999 -- KOSOVO-PRIZREN,
5-06 -- Rexep Hoti, 60, one of the ethnic Albanians who chose to
remain in Prizren. In the last week, many of Prizren's Albanians,
perhaps as many as 30,000, were pushed and panicked into mass
flight in the few days following a bomb blast in a poor residential
area that killed at least 5 civilians and wounded 23 others.
(Steven Erlanger/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 6, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES, 5-06 -- Conor
Lovett in Samuel Beckett's ``Molloy,'' at the Irish Arts Center.
Beckett conceived ``Mol loy,'' the first novel in his caustic
trilogy that includes ``Malone Dies'' and ``The Unnamable,'' after
a revelatory visit to his mother in Dublin during which he realized
she had not long to live. It was at that moment, he said later,
that he ``became aware of my stupidity; then I began to write the
things I feel.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 6, 1999 -- CIDER-THEATER-REVIEW, 5-06 --
Josh Hamilton, left, and Colm Meaney in ``The Cider House Rules''
at the Atlantic Theater Company. The Atlantic has opted for the
time being to offer only the first half of the sprawling
production, directed by Tom Hulce and Jane Jones.(Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SANTA ROSA, Calif. -- May 6, 1999 -- MALLORY-DAUGHTER,
5-06 --Clare Millikan was eight years old when her father, British
mountain climber George Mallory, had been ``lost'' on Mount Everest
in 1924. This week, Millikan got word her father's body had been
found on a windswept ledge on Mount Everest. The preserved body was
found at 27,000 feet by five young climbers retracing his route. It
was Mallory who quipped that he wanted to climb Everest ``because
it is there.'' (John Burgess/Santa Rosa Press Democrat) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) OKLAHOMA CITY -- May 6, 1999 -- OKLA-STORMS-1, 5-06 --
Steve Pollard, left, and his step father David Johnstun, clear
debris from their two story house on Windermere Drive in Moore, a
suburb of Oklahoma City, on Thursday. What's left of the 900 block
of Windermere Drive is a jumble of splinters, shards and
half-loaded pickup trucks. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- May 6, 1999 -- CONGRESS-GUNS, 5-06 -- Sen.
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., foreground, talks with an aide during a
press conference to propose measures to protect children from guns.
In the background from left are Sens. Frank Lautenberg, Richard
Durbin and Charles Schumer. Invoking the massacre at Columbine High
School, the Democratic senators said Thursday they are looking
forward to offering a series of gun-control measures that have long
been stalled in the Republican-controlled Senate. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) FORT DIX, N.J. -- May 6, 1999 -- NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES, 5-06
-- A U.S. soldier helps a young ethnic Albanian refugee with flying
a kite on Thursday near the barracks where many of the refugees are
being housed. More than 450 Kosovar refugees arrived from refugee
camps in Macedonia on Wednesday. (Keith Meyers/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WICKENBURG, Ariz. -- May 6, 1999 -- TUNDRA-HAT-TEST-AZR,
05-06 --Leaning on the Toyota's full-size pickup truck, the Tundra,
from left, C.W. Williams, Jeff Deming and Willum Mallernee, cowboys
at Rancho de los Caballeros, want to know whether its tough enough
for the range. They decided to give it ``the hat test.'' ``You
know, there's nothing worse than getting into a truck and finding
out your hat don't fit,'' explains Williams, 53. (Bob
Golfen/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- May 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 9
--BEBE-MILLER-DANCE, 05-06 -- At left, Bebe Miller, choreographer
and creative director of Bebe Miller Dance rehearses with her
company. This 60-minute piece, ``Going to the Wall,'' had its
premiere at Dartmouth College last year. It will be seen for the
first time in New York on Tuesday at the Joyce Theater, when the
company begins a weeklong engagement, its first in three years.
(Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 9 --
MONTE-CARLO-BALLET, 05-06 -- Jean-Christophe Maillot the artistic
director and choreographer of Les Ballets de Monte Carlo, cavorts
during a recent visit. His company opens a weeklong season at City
Center in New York City on Wednesday. The program spotlights
Maillot's sleek new rendering of ``Romeo and Juliet,'' set to
Prokofiev's familiar rhapsodic score. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- May 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 9 --
ELIZABETH-FRANZ-THEATER-2, 05-06 -- Elizabeth Franz and Brian
Dennehy as Willy and Linda Loman in the 50th-anniversary production
of ``Death of a Salesman'' now on Broadway. When asked about her
role, Elizabeth Franz says ``I have a lot of Willy Lomans in my
life.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- May 6, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 9 --
