<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7471 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGIOUS-LEADERS07-C     05-06 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGIOUS-LEADERS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Day of Prayer, a lesson in allegiance to God and man
 &HT;    By Kim Sue Lia Perkes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Thousands of Central Texans joined more than 2
million Americans on Thursday who observed National Day of Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the nation, large crowds gathered at noon outside
city buildings and inside churches to pray for the nation's
political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, the day kicked off with a 6:45 a.m. breakfast where
more than 1,000 people showed up to pray and hear the Rev. E.V.
Hill, pastor of Mount Zion Baptist Church in Los Angeles. Hill, a
nationally recognized religious leader, grew up in Seguin.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, filling in for Gov. George W. Bush, drew
laughter when he asked the crowd ``to pray for us the next 26 days
that peace breaks out in the Texas House and Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill began his message by saying being back in Austin was
bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin is the place where people are kind,'' he said. It's
also where he first fell in love, only to be dumped. ``I come to
Austin with mixed emotions,'' he said with a broad smile. ``I come
partly to want to pray and partly to want to cuss.''
</P>
<P>
   After the laughter died down, Hill launched into a serious
message about how prayer must be done properly and is a powerful
force that works. Unfortunately, he told the crowd ``prayer in
America . . . has been reduced to a program item.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's politically correct environment sometimes drives God and
Jesus Christ out of prayers in the public arena, which creates a
secular program item rather than a spiritual engagement, Hill said.
His goal, he said, is to make prayer spiritual ``to the only one
that can answer prayer, and that is God through Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   In an age in which diversity is celebrated, such controversial
statements are classic Hill, who makes no bones about where he
stands on an issue. Recently, Hill has been under fire for his
allegiance to the Rev. Henry Lyons, who resigned in March as
president of the National Baptist Convention USA after being
convicted of stealing more than $4 million from the nation's
largest and most influential black denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who is running for Lyons' post, said he is not one to
abandon a friend in hard times. ``That doesn't mean you necessarily
condone everything the friend does,'' he said in an interview.
``Whatever smut that might have gotten on me _ that's small
compared to what Jesus took on from us.''
</P>
<P>
   At the prayer breakfast, Hill said he never would be where he is
now without the power of prayer. His mother prayed for him to
graduate from high school at a time when blacks were expected to
drop out after 10th grade to work. He made it through high school.
</P>
<P>
   His mother bought him a bus ticket to Prairie View A&AMP;M
University, about 45 miles northwest of Houston. ``My momma said
just before the bus took off, `Be a good boy and I'm praying for
you,''' he said. As he stood in the school's registration line with
$1.83 in his pocket, he feared getting to the front of the line,
where a sign announced that students must pay $83 in cash or
cashier's check to enroll. A school official told him to get out of
line. Hill had been awarded a four-year scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that prayer works,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
