<SLUG> BC-BILLINGS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETERS SHUFFLE AGENCY ASSIGNMENTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ill. Idaho, Calif., Ohio, Minn., Mass.)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many years, a certain newspaper would run a headline over
its weekly patents column proclaiming ``Wide Variety of Ideas
Covered by Patents Issued During Week.'' Now it is the advertising
column that is all about a wide variety, in this instance
advertisers in fields as diverse as computers, banks, baking mixes
and appliances, which are all making account changes.
</P>
<P>
   The combined billings that were shifted Thursday were estimated
at $130 million to $155 million. The bulk of that, $70 million to
$90 million, involved Dell Computer Corp., which named Ammirati
Puris Lintas in New York, a unit of the Interpublic Group of Cos.,
to handle assignments for its home and small-business group
products in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The decision puts Ammirati Puris back in the competitive
computer category in a big way. Last year, it lost the account of
Compaq Computer Corp., with billings estimated at $200 million, to
DDB Worldwide Communications Group in New York, a unit of Omnicom
Group; the Compaq loss was one in a series of difficulties suffered
by Ammirati Puris that included turbulence among the senior
managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of that external stuff factored into our decision at
all,'' Frank Muehleman, vice president and general manager for the
Dell small-business division in Round Rock, Texas, said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team we dealt with'' at Ammirati Puris, he added, ``which
is the team we will be working with, has been stable throughout the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammirati Puris was selected after a monthlong review that had
been narrowed to that agency and two others: Bronnercom in Boston,
formerly Bronner Slosberg Humphrey, and Temerlin McClain in Irving,
Texas, part of True North Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The assignments awarded to Ammirati Puris had been handled by
Goldberg Moser O'Neill in San Francisco, which had worked for Dell
since August 1988. Goldberg Moser, which is majority owned by the
Lowe Group unit of Interpublic, resigned the assignments April 5,
along with Dell accounts involving computer sales to government
agencies, schools and in Latin and South America, soon after Dell
decided to undertake a review on the home and small-business group
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Ammirati Puris ``will likely get'' the additional Dell accounts
that Goldberg Moser had also handled, Muehleman said, adding that
the assignments awarded yesterday composed the bulk of the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Ammirati Puris has replaced Compaq with Dell, Goldberg
Moser re-entered the computer category, too, replacing the lost
Dell assignments last week with the account of Micron Electronics
in Nampa, Idaho, majority owned by Micron Technology, with billings
estimated at up to $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles office of DDB Worldwide was involved in another
decision Thursday as the Wells Fargo Corp. in San Francisco
consolidated most of its advertising and marketing assignments
there. Billings were estimated at $45 million to $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   DDB Los Angeles becomes the primary agency of record for Wells
Fargo after a four-month ``shootout'' between that agency and
Carmichael Lynch in Minneapolis, part of Interpublic. The
competition grew from the merger in November between the Norwest
Corp. in Minneapolis, whose agency was Carmichael Lynch, and the
old Wells Fargo, whose agency was DDB Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael Lynch will continue as the agency of record for the
Norwest Banks unit of Wells Fargo in Minneapolis. Among the tasks
to be handled by DDB Los Angeles in addition to brand advertising
will be to promote a renaming for all Norwest banks in 16 states as
Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   On the baking-mix front, Aurora Foods Inc. in Columbus, Ohio,
further consolidated its portfolio of familiar brands with Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather Chicago, part of the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of WPP
Group PLC, by awarding the agency the assignment for the Duncan
Hines product line. Billings on the account, which includes cake,
muffin, brownie and cookie mixes and frostings, were estimated at
$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy Chicago was awarded Aurora's Log Cabin syrup account in
1997, followed by the Mrs. Butterworth's syrup assignment last
year. The Duncan Hines account comes from N.W. Ayer &AMP; Partners in
New York, part of MacManus Group, which had handled the brand since
1987, when it was still owned by the Procter &AMP; Gamble Co.; P&AMP;G sold
Duncan Hines to Aurora in 1998 and Aurora at that time kept Ayer on
the account.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora has only recently started running a new campaign for
Duncan Hines from Ayer, carrying the theme ``You're why I bake,''
which seeks to stimulate consumers to bake more by striking
emotional chords. Now, though, Aurora said, it wanted to
consolidate more brands with one ``strategic marketing partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Beth Casey, president and chief executive at Ayer, said:
``Unfortunately this business isn't always about doing great work.
And consolidations are sometimes an example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, Sunbeam Corp. in Boca Raton, Fla., awarded the creative
part of the account of the Mr. Coffee line of appliances, with
billings estimated at $4 million to $5 million, to Moss/Dragoti
Advertising in New York, part of DDB Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after two months of meetings by executives at
Moss/Dragoti and Sunbeam that included Jo Anne Lala, senior vice
president for marketing. Spending is expected to increase next year
with the introduction of additional products under the Mr. Coffee
brand name.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Coffee and other Sunbeam brands, including Oster and
Coleman, had been handled by Ogilvy Chicago until that agency's
contract with the company expired on Dec. 31. Sunbeam's advertising
plans have been in flux since June, when Albert J. Dunlap, its
contentious chairman, was ousted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
