r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TUINEI-TE     05-06 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TUINEI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECALLING TUINEI: `ALWAYS SMILING'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Former Cowboys offensive tackle Mark Tuinei,
pronounced dead after being found unconscious in his car yesterday
morning, was remembered at a solemn Cowboys headquarters yesterday
for his jovial nature and friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei, 39, who played 15 seasons with the Cowboys and was the
anchor of an offensive line that keyed three Super Bowl titles, was
discovered early yesterday morning by a friend. The cause of death
has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Many Cowboys players and coaches were left feeling a deep sense
of loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me personally, it's been like losing an older brother,''
said a teary-eyed Daryl Johnston, who played nine seasons with
Tuinei. ``It's going to take a hard time to get over this.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said there is only one way to remember Tuinei, who was
known as the team's chief practical joker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will remember him in the way he was always was ... always
with a smile, always laughing, always enjoying life,'' Johnston
said. ``That's the way we want to remember Mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys assistant coach Bill Bates was a teammate of Tuinei's
for 15 years. The two share the team's all-time service record with
former defensive end Ed Jones. Bates, also a roommate of Tuinei's
during their career, knew his fun side as well as anyone.
Yesterday, he wished this was one of those funny moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys that know him are going to think that this was one of
`Tui's' big jokes,'' Bates said. ``Unfortunately, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had so much fun with him. He was one guy who lived life to
the fullest. I can't find one person who spoke negatively of Mark.
We are all going to miss him very much.''
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a regular practice day turned into what an
emotional Cowboys owner Jerry Jones called ``a great day of
sadness'' when news of Tuinei's death spread around the Cowboys'
training facility.
</P>
<P>
   Practice was called off and the players went home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally shocking for all of us,'' Cowboys defensive
line coach Jim Bates said of the emotional locker room. ``It was
tough on us. The coaches didn't feel like coaching and the players
didn't feel like playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman, who relied on Tuinei to protect his
blind side when in the pocket, said ``right now there is a sense of
disbelief. I don't know anybody who can truly describe the emotion
that everybody is feeling. We are affected deeply.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the nicest guys to ever wear a Cowboys uniform
.... He was such a great friend and teammate. When I look back on
the times with Mark, I will do so with a smile because of the type
of guy he was and the impact he had on so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei's career ended following the 1997 season because of
lingering problems with both knees. The Cowboys released him in
April 1998 for salary cap reasons.
</P>
<P>
   That the 6-foot-5, 320-pound Tuinei lasted 15 years was a
testament to his talent and his determination. Undrafted after his
senior season at the University of Hawaii, he made the Cowboys'
roster as a free-agent defensive lineman in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei caught the attention of then-coach Tom Landry and
defensive line coach Ernie Stauntner because of his nasty on-field
attitude. In 1985, Tuinei was moved to offense, where he was tried
at center and tackle. He became a starter at left tackle midway
through the 1986 season and stayed there for 12 years, including
the Super Bowl title seasons of 1992, 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   One of the highlights of Tuinei's career was playing in the Pro
Bowl after the 1994 and 1995 seasons in Hawaii. Often overlooked on
a dominant offensive line that included the quotable Nate Newton
and the intimidating Erik Williams, Tuinei savored the appreciation
of his peers, but he especially enjoyed getting to play in front of
friends and family in his native Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei's tough side came from being raised in Nanakuli, a town
of about 10,000 on the island of Oahu. He often got into fights as
a youth and continued to get into trouble as a collegian. Tuinei
was kicked out of UCLA as a sophomore. He continued his bad-boy
ways when he transferred to the University of Hawaii. But a
three-month jail stint following his junior season prompted him to
change his ways, he once said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys took a chance on him as a free agent in 1983,
Tuinei was still nasty on the field, but off the field was evolving
into the person former Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach once
called a ``gentle giant.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the person the Cowboys remembered yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a football player, he was someone who never asked for
anything other than an opportunity,'' Jones said. ``He made the
absolute best of all his opportunities. He was a consummate team
player. He came to work every day for 15 years. Our hearts are with
his loved ones, his wife, family and all who were touched by Mark
and called him a friend. This is a very sad time for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei's wife, Pono, was in Hawaii at the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said he was planning to move home next week and become
an assistant high school football coach at his alma mater, Punahou
School. The couple did not have any children. Memorial services
have not been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
