<SLUG> BC-TAX-CUTS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HOUSE MOVES TOWARD $418 MILLION TAX CUT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The House unexpectedly granted $418 million in
sales and franchise tax breaks Thursday, doubling the pricetag on a
package of proposals to help small businesses and families that buy
school supplies, nonprescription drugs and diapers.
</P>
<P>
   The same Republicans who prevailed in broadening the proposals
also snuffed out Democrats' attempts to limit their duration to two
years.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the four separate bills were tentatively
approved by unanimous votes. After another round of votes today,
the bills go to the Senate for further consideration. That body has
approved a single tax-relief bill that included more than $600
million in various business and sales tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing the House majority's feverish desire to maximize tax
breaks this year while the state is operating with a rare budget
surplus, proponents of the tax-break package withdrew a fifth bill
that would have exempted back-to-school clothing from sales taxes.
That measure, House Bill 2280, by Rep. Harold Dutton, D-Houston,
could have been amended to exempt almost anything from any sales
taxes, which legislative sponsors said the state cannot afford. It
will be retooled and resubmitted. It could reduce sales-tax
collections by about $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the package said the state can barely absorb the
revenue losses as they were approved, though they comply with an
informal agreement to limit tax breaks to about $550 million. The
bills' proponents also warned that the amended versions, with their
higher pricetags, would eliminate the possibility of research and
development tax credits and a proposed sales-tax exemption on
Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the House's actions would make it harder to increase
education spending and achieve Gov. George W. Bush's objective of
lowering property taxes by $2 billion, Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I was trying to do ... was present a balanced tax package
so we'd be able to do the other business tax cuts the governor
wanted and that the Republicans wanted,'' said House Ways and Means
Committee Chairman Rene Oliveira, D-Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that the bottom line could be broad tax relief for
typical Texans _ something Democrats also favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened today is good for Texas consumers. What it is
not good for is the rest of the governor's tax (relief) package,''
Oliveira said.
</P>
<P>
   The House tentatively approved these tax-relief bills:
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 2371, by Rep. Roberto Gutierrez, D-McAllen, exempts
from the state's 6.25 percent sales tax diapers for children and
adults, other than those provided by diaper services. Cities were
given the option of continuing to collect sales taxes on diapers,
if they use the proceeds to back bonds. The exemption would reduce
state income by $63 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 209 by Rep. Henry Cuellar, D-Laredo, exempts from
the sales tax the purchase of about 40 school supply items if
bought in August. Proposed at $25, the exemption was limited to
items costing less than $75. Items such as paper, pens, glue and
art supplies were listed. Home schoolers would be eligible for the
exemption, which also would apply to their textbook purchases. Its
impact on state revenues was estimated at a minimum of $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 2372, also by Gutierrez, initially was proposed to
cover only over-the-counter children's medicines. On the floor, it
was amended first to include senior citizens and then to include
all nonprescription drugs for all buyers, raising its cost to $225
million.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 551 by Rep. Tony Goolsby, R-Dallas, would exempt
from the franchise tax those corporations whose gross receipts fall
below $250,000 a year. It was amended upward from the proposed
$100,000, which increased its cost from $57 million to $120
million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
