 NEW YORK: the officers.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fifth defendant in the case is a sergeant, Michael Bellomo,
who is accused of trying to cover up the alleged beating of Louima
in the police car. All the defendants say the charges against them
are untrue.
</P>
<P>
   The case was originally prosecuted in state court by the
Brooklyn district attorney, Charles Hynes, who turned it over to
the U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, Zachary Carter, for federal
prosecution, in part because convictions in federal court could
bring stiffer punishments. Volpe and Schwarz could be sentenced to
up to life in prison if they are convicted of attacking Louima with
the stick.
</P>
<P>
   Describing what happened in the station house, Louima said the
officer identified by prosecutors as Schwarz brought him into the
restroom after loosening Louima's belt and pulling his pants and
underwear down to his knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I get inside the bathroom, Officer Volpe close the
door and I saw him pick up something by the garbage can,'' said
Louima, who added that his hands were cuffed behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened then?'' Vinegrad asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pushes me to the ground,'' the witness said, adding that
his face was ``close to the toilet bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened then?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he kick me on my groin,'' Louima replied, going from
there to a description of punches he said he suffered and the stick
attack that he said was inflicted on him.
</P>
