<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      05-06 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS, BACKING BILL FOR KOSOVO, ADD BILLIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted Thursday night to spend billions of
dollars for the NATO bombing campaign in Yugoslavia that it
declined to endorse days ago. Its Republican leaders vowed to pour
billions more into a military they said President Clinton had
gutted.
</P>
<P>
   Rewriting the deeply mixed message it sent on the battle in the
Balkans last week, the House approved Clinton's $6 billion request
to finance the air war and to aid refugees. It added almost $7
billion in Pentagon programs, many of which bear no direct relation
to the fighting in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on the $13 billion military spending bill was 311-105.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, the House rejected, by a tie vote, a nonbinding
resolution expressing support for the airstrikes. Republicans voted
overwhelmingly against that measure in a symbolic condemnation of
President Clinton's policies. Thursday night, they voted for the
Pentagon, not for the president as commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my colleagues who disagree with the president's policy, let
me say simply, you had your vote last week,'' said Speaker Dennis
Hastert, who had been silent during that earlier vote. ``Today, let
there be no mistake. The United States Congress stands with its
soldiers, sailors and airmen as they defend America.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority whip, Rep. Tom Delay of Texas, said, ``While we may
not support the president's ill-advised war, we do support our
troops.''
</P>
<P>
   The emergency spending bill _ to which $106 million in aid for
American farmers was added by amendment, bringing the total to
$13.1 billion _ will go to a House-Senate conference next week. The
Senate majority leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, said that the
Senate might well cut it; some senators want to spend no more than
the original $6 billion request.
</P>
<P>
   Honing political themes for next year's election campaigns, the
Republicans said that Clinton's foreign policies and military
practices had plunged the United States into a national security
crisis. They warned that U.S. soldiers would die in combat without
more money for a military starved for bombs and missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without any coherent international blueprint, the White House
has bombed its way around the globe while dropping troops far and
wide for ill-defined peacemaking duties,'' Delay said. ``This
policy has gutted the American military, which now must be
rebuilt.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., the Armed Services subcommittee
chairman, argued earlier that ``we are looking at body bags
stretched out in front of us,'' filled with ``dead Americans who
ran out of ammunition.''
</P>
<P>
   The emergency spending would come from surplus Social Security
funds, which both parties have promised not to touch. But ``without
national security, there is no Social Security,'' Hunter said
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, the ranking Democrat on the House
Appropriations Committee, sought to cut $1.2 billion from the bill,
which he said would leave enough ``to support every possible
requirement'' the military faced.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that Republicans, having held control of Congress and
the federal budget since 1995, were to blame for any real or
imagined shortfalls at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The money requested by the White House to finance the bombing
campaign would pay for 24-hour-a-day air strikes through the end of
September, he said, adding, ``We will run out of targets before we
run out of missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Democrats, 137 voted for the spending bill, though
many said they supported only the $6 billion request. The House
bill adds $5.8 billion in military programs to that request, which
covered military operations in the Balkans and Iraq as well as $566
million in aid for war refugees and assistance to the nations
taking them in.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money added by the House would go for military
weapons, operations, training, recruitment and pay increases. The
emergency bill also includes nearly $1.1 billion to build military
installations in NATO nations and in the Persian Gulf, and $50
million for a new U.S. Embassy in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Obey's amendment to cut the spending bill was defeated 164 to
260, with 45 Democrats joining 215 Republicans. An amendment backed
by three conservative Republicans to finance the bill by cutting
domestic programs by about 5 percent lost on a 101-to-322 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Another amendment, sponsored by Rep. Ernest Istook, R-Okla.,
would have barred U.S. ground troops from the Balkans. It lost,
117-301.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
