<HEADER>
A7493 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NY     05-06 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEE GIVES BIRTH IN NEW JERSEY TO AN ALL-AMERICAN BOY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT HOLLY, N.J. _ His fists balled tight and his eyes opened
on a new world, the first American was born here Thursday from the
Kosovar exodus, less than 24 hours after his mother arrived from a
refugee camp in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to name the baby America, but I have to talk to my
wife and parents first,'' Naim Karaliju, 28, the overwhelmed
father, said at Burlington County Memorial Hospital a half-hour
after his wife, Lebibe, gave birth to their first child. Doctors
said that Karaliju hugged the 7 pound 7.7 ounce boy close to his
heart when they presented him with the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, it's a boy,'' he blurted out.
</P>
<P>
   On their first full day at Fort Dix, where the refugees are
expected to remain for several weeks, families played on the grass
behind a four-foot-tall wooden fence. Three women were sent to
Burlington County Memorial Hospital, one for blood clots in her
leg, and another for uterine bleeding. A 77-year-old woman,
suffering from chronic lung disease, was held in isolation, while
doctors determined whether she was suffering from infectious
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Karaliju, 21, who was among the first 453 of 20,000
Albanian refugees from Kosovo who came to the United States
Wednesday, told immigration officials in Macedonia that she was
only seven months pregnant, apparently in order to be able to
travel. But during the 13-hour flight from Skopje, Macedonia, she
began to feel weak, and doctors at the hospital here found that the
expectant mother was dehydrated and about to give birth. She later
told doctors that Thursday was her due date.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Snyder, the doctor who delivered her baby, said that
Mrs. Karaliju's blood was Rh negative, a condition that could
threaten any future pregnancies she might have, and which she would
probably never have discovered in the refugee camp where she was
just days before.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, himself, appeared taken by the horizon that suddenly
appeared before the newborn, so different from that the baby would
have faced had his mother stayed in the Stankovic refugee camp,
packed to triple capacity when they left. ``Who knows what's going
to happen?'' the doctor asked. ``This child could be the president
of the United States one day.''
</P>
<P>
   During pauses in Mrs. Karaliju's labor, Snyder said, he asked
her about the events that made her family refugees. She told him
that Serbian paramilitary forces bearing weapons came into the
family's home in the Kosovar village of Ferizaj, and gave them 30
minutes to leave their home forever. The expulsion, she told him,
came six weeks ago, before NATO began bombing the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``After talking to her, I thought this really proves that we
need to be fighting there,'' the doctor said. Snyder, who is
Jewish, said that because of the extermination of Jews in Europe
during the Holocaust, he felt he understood the trauma and
injustice of ethnic cleansing today. Albania was one of two
countries, along with Denmark, that made a policy of refusing to
hand over their Jews to be killed by Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Karaliju, the new father, told a press conference that he was
glad when NATO began bombing Serbia. ``That meant there was help
out there,'' he said, speaking through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   As the child gazed out of his bassinet in the hospital nursery,
wrapped in a red and white blanket, his father headed back to Fort
Dix, where the Immigration and Naturalization Service was giving
the newcomers a day of rest before beginning the long work of
screening them for official acceptance by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Lavinia Limon, director of the Health and Human Services
agency's Office of Refugee Resettlement, said that the refugees'
reception Wednesday night did not go as smoothly as everyone hoped.
Machines broke down, computers froze, and extended families,
fearful of being separated, insisted on remaining together, slowing
down interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The immigration screening, which involves medical, security and
background checks, will take several weeks, with nonprofit
resettlement agencies placing the refugees in apartments and jobs
across the United States once they are approved. A second charter
flight of 400 more or so refugees is expected here Friday; 100 more
refugees with relatives in the United States are to arrive Saturday
at John F. Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
