<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERY U.S. INCOME GROUP SEEMS TO BE SPENDING MORE
</P>
<P>
   American consumers are spending faster than they did last year.
In the first four months of this year, sales in stores open at
least a year rose 6.7 percent, one of the biggest jumps in years.
That came on top of a dizzying 5.1 percent increase last year.
</P>
<P>
   Retail analysts and economists point to numerous factors,
including the continued rise of both the stock market and home
values, to explain much of the gains. But another change is also
helping: While the wealthiest consumers powered the expansion in
its early stages, spending by those in the bottom 40 percent of
income has been picking up. Real growth in wages and the lowest
unemployment rate in 30 years have spread the shopping spree into
every corner of American society.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL SALES ROSE 3 PERCENT IN APRIL
</P>
<P>
   Sales at retail stores open at least a year rose 3 percent in
April as shoppers snapped up spring fashions at clothing chains
such as Ann Taylor and department stores. But sales at some of the
biggest retailers may start to slow, analysts and investors said.
That could hurt stocks like Gap and Wal-Mart that have surged.
Thursday, shares of Wal-Mart fell $2.1875, to $42.875, even though
its sales met expectations.
</P>
<P>
   INSURERS AGREE ON HOLOCAUST CLAIMS
</P>
<P>
   Several large European insurance companies agreed for the first
time to pay claims on prewar policies of Holocaust victims. The
settlement could potentially result in billions of dollars in
payments.
</P>
<P>
   NO BREAK IN TRADE GROUP'S DEADLOCK
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations over a new leader for the World Trade Organization
are likely to remain deadlocked at least until next week, envoys
said, amid speculation that neither of the two finalists would get
the job.
</P>
<P>
   HONDA TO BUILD FACTORY IN ALABAMA
</P>
<P>
   Honda announced that it would build a $400 million factory in
Lincoln, Ala., to assemble sport utility vehicles and minivans.
</P>
<P>
   PRICES OF STOCKS AND BONDS SLIDE
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell after Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman,
said the ``spectacular rise in equity prices'' might be ``beyond
the justifiable.'' The Dow Jones industrial average slid 8.59
points, to 10,946.82. The Nasdaq composite index skidded 62.17
points, or 2.45 percent, to 2,472.28, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index fell 15.26 points, or 1.13 percent, to 1,332.05.
Treasury prices tumbled, driving the yield on the 30-year Treasury
bond up to 5.78 percent from 5.70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   DATA-SCRAMBLING LIMITS REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government's restrictions on the export of
data-scrambling software are unconstitutional, a federal appeals
court in California ruled.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISA GETS MEXICAN CAPITAL
</P>
<P>
   Months of rumors that Rupert Murdoch would buy into Televisa,
Mexico's largest television network, were laid to rest. Instead,
the Mexican venture capital firm of Sinca Inbursa, which is part of
the empire of Carlos Slim Helu purchased a 24 percent stake in
Grupo Televicentro, the holding company that controls Televisa.
</P>
<P>
   BOARD TURMOIL IN SOUTH AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Two board members of South Africa's most prominent black
empowerment company, New Africa Investments, resigned in the face
of outrage over a plan to award themselves and two other board
members stock options worth more than $20 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
