<HEADER>
A7503 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-IRWINDALE-SAFETY-     05-06 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-IRWINDALE-SAFETY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWINDALE OFFICIAL SAYS FANS ARE SAFE HERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ A crash similar to the one at Lowe's Motor
Speedway near Charlotte, N.C., last weekend is not likely to happen
at Irwindale Speedway, track promoter and vice president Ray
Wilkings said this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, three died and eight were injured when a tire and
suspension parts flew into the grandstand after a crash in the
VisionAire 500 Indy Racing League event. The accident happened less
than a year after a similar crash at Michigan Speedway in Brooklyn,
Mich., killed three. They too were hit by flying tires and
suspension debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fences are more updated than Charlotte's,'' Wilkings said.
``We have the same type of fence that was put in after the Michigan
(incident). We have a superspeedway fence on a short track. Most
tracks don't have this type of fence.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the IRL raced at the 1.5-mile high-banked Charlotte oval
in 1997, the track fence's height was increased to 15 feet. After
the Michigan race last July, the catch fence was raised to 17{ feet
and more webbing was added.
</P>
<P>
   Irwindale's catch fence is also 17{ feet with the additional
webbing. The outer wall on the outside half-mile track is about 20
feet away from the first row in the 6,500-seat grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have the safest fence you can have,'' Wilkings
said.
</P>
<P>
   Irwindale also has an advantage in that most of its events are
for NASCAR vehicles, which means the wheels do not protrude from
the car. However, there are 11 open-wheel races at the track this
season. Two have already been run with one on-track incident, the
death of sprint car driver Casey Diemert of Roseburg, Ore., who
clipped the wheel of another car, went airborne and then slammed
into a wall during the opening-night practice. A U.S. Auto Club
show, featuring sprints and midgets, is scheduled for Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Open-wheel cars' parts are designed to break away from the car
in an accident, hopefully sparing the driver serious injury.
Frequently, it's the tires and suspension that are tossed first.
Formula One organizing body FIA this year began requiring teams to
install a tether to keep wheels and suspensions from breaking away
from the car.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is the speed of the cars. At Charlotte and
Michigan, the accidents happened when the cars were doing at least
200 mph. The lap record at Irwindale is 114.979, set by Davey
Hamilton in a WSMRA Super Modifieds event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of types of race cars here, but the type of cars
that do race here do not get to superspeedway speeds,'' Wilkings
said.
</P>
<P>
   There had been no deaths at Charlotte or Michigan until the past
two incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about having something like this happen and you try
to think of everything you can do to prevent it,'' Lowe's track
president H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler said. ``It's a violent sport. You
never know what's going to happen next and you have to take the
known things that have happened and quantify them and learn from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several drivers say Charlotte's 25-degree banking is the source
of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those high-banked tracks are impossible, the speeds too
incredible,'' former CART driver Mario Andretti told the Charlotte
Observer. ``We have to do silly things, crazy things, stupid things
just to slow the cars down. The speeds are just unreasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Gappens, a speedway vice president, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the Indy cars have run on banked tracks for many
years. I think the (IRL) has been very responsible in their
research,'' he said. ``If you look at the history, up until
Saturday night, there hasn't been a problem'' at Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   No spectators have been hurt or killed by flying debris at
either California Speedway, site of NASCAR and CART 500-mile races,
nor on the street circuit of Long Beach, site of the CART Toyota
Grand Prix of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Parts from exploding dragsters _ usually the blowers _ have
occasionally been thrown into the grandstand at Pomona Raceway
during the Winternationals and Winston Finals. Fans have been taken
to area hospitals after being hit by debris, but none for serious
injuries. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
