u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-JACKSON-NYT &LR;      05-06 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-JACKSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHIL JACKSON, TRAVELING CAMPAIGN TRAIL, POSTPONES MEETING WITH
NETS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Four weeks after pulling off a trade for
the spectacular Stephon Marbury in mid-March, the New Jersey Nets'
principal owner, Lewis Katz, was scheduled to meet with another
prominent basketball personality about joining his team.
</P>
<P>
   The date with Phil Jackson never took place, though, because
Todd Musberger, Jackson's agent, called to postpone.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was busy traveling the presidential campaign trail for
Bill Bradley, the former senator and former basketball player for
the New York Knicks. An agreement to meet later was set, Musberger
told Katz.
</P>
<P>
   With the Nets' tumultuous season having ended Wednesday, Katz
and Jackson are likely to have that meeting within the next week or
two.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the universally coveted coach who led Michael Jordan's
Chicago Bulls to six league championships, appears to be at the top
of a slate that is probably shorter than the list of playoff teams
the Nets beat this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' owners and department heads met Thursday to discuss
their coaching search and other possible moves in what could be an
active off season. In addition to hiring a head coach, the Nets
will look to strengthen themselves at the center position via free
agency or a trade, find a small forward to back up Keith Van Horn
or Kendall Gill, re-sign Jamie Feick and extend Van Horn's
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, settling their coaching situation is the top
priority, and that could be as simple as receiving a yes or a no
from Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The interim coach, Don Casey, and his assistants _ Eddie Jordan,
Jim Lynam, Mike O'Koran and Hal Wissel _ did an excellent job in
achieving a 13-17 record despite losing Jayson Williams, Jim
McIlvaine, Scott Burrell, Eric Murdock and Van Horn to
season-ending injuries. Casey and company would seem to be the
Nets' second choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This coaching staff has already received a favorable
evaluation,'' Michael Rowe, the Nets' president, said. ``They will
receive serious consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of the players, including the co-captains Gill and
Williams, along with Van Horn, think that Casey, who replaced the
ousted John Calipari, should get the job regardless of the
availability of Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to play for anybody else,'' Gill said. ``Case,
Jimmy Lynam, Eddie Jordan _ since I've been in the league this is
the best coaching staff that I've played for. All of the guys love
them. Phil Jackson is a great coach. I can't take anything away
from him. But when you take away a coach that the players love, it
kind of puts bad salt in their wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who reported Thursday that he is ahead of schedule in
the rehabilitation of his broken right leg, said, said: ``Let's
keep what everybody likes. I hate change. The ship was going toward
that big iceberg, and Case righted the ship. So let's stay with
Case. He's my No. 1 pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Marbury, who in March strongly expressed his desire to play
for Jackson, has taken to Casey. When asked if he would be bothered
if Casey and his staff are retained, Marbury said: ``I would have
no problem with that. I love Case. Case is the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has received offers from four other clubs and will
certainly be pursued by the Knicks and the Los Angeles Lakers if
both teams falter in the playoffs. He could also choose to continue
working with Bradley's presidential campaign and suspend his return
to coaching for another year. Two Eastern Conference officials said
they believe that Jackson will either stick with Bradley or go to
Los Angeles, assuming the Lakers replace their interim coach, Kurt
Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, the path would seem clear for Casey. The only
hitch could be if Jordan and Lynam, both head-coaching candidates
in their own right, did not return as assistants. The feeling
throughout the Nets' management is that one or both of those
assistants must return for Casey to get the job.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said he definitely wants to rejoin Casey's staff in New
Jersey, and would leave only if he received an offer to be a head
coach elsewhere. Lynam said he is unsure of what he will do.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Silas, who did an exceptional job as the Charlotte Hornets'
interim coach, is a possible coaching candidate for the Nets in the
unlikely event that the Hornets do not make him a satisfactory
offer.
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks fire Jeff Van Gundy, he would probably be
considered. The Cleveland Cavaliers' coach, Mike Fratello, also has
been mentioned, but many within the Nets' organization believe that
his personality and coaching style are too similar to Calipari's.
There is little chance of the Nets hiring a coach directly out of
college.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
