<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOLL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Rivalry Comes to Toll Calls
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Starting today, California consumers have a new way to get cheaper
phone bills.
</P>
<P>
   That's because customers now can choose any phone company as
their local toll carrier and are no longer required to use Pacific
Bell. Local toll calls are calls made to regional numbers that are
more than 12 miles away but are not long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   So get ready for more dinnertime calls from phone companies
hawking their service. Already, competitors are slashing prices and
aggressively marketing their ability to carry these calls.
</P>
<P>
   Mark C. Brucker, a telecommunications consultant in Berkeley,
said customers need to review their phone bills to figure out if
they would save with a carrier other than Pac Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making the switch makes the most sense for those who have
large bills for toll calls,'' Brucker said.
</P>
<P>
   You may want to switch to a new local toll provider if you:
</P>
<P>
   _Make calls during weekday business hours, when Pac Bell's rates
are the highest.
</P>
<P>
   _Make short calls, since Pac Bell charges more for the first
minute than for additional minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _Tend to call locations more than 40 miles away, where Pac
Bell's rates run the highest.
</P>
<P>
   Those who should stick with Pac Bell include people who make few
toll calls or who have one of the company's savings plans, Brucker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Californians make a lot of local toll calls _ about 25
percent of all local toll calls are made within the state _
consumers stand to save a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom estimates that Californians will save more than
$150 million with local toll competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be easier for people to save money,'' said
Regina Costa, a telecommunications analyst with The Utility Reform
Network, a consumer group. ``Everybody in the state makes one of
these calls at some point. They could save $5 or $10 a month; it
just depends on the volume of calls they make.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, San Francisco customers who called someone in San
Jose by dialing 1 plus 408 and the number would pay Pac Bell a
toll. If such customers wanted to use another company, such as
AT&AMP;T, they had to dial a special seven-digit access code to get
around Pac Bell's network.
</P>
<P>
   Customers now can select AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom or another carrier
as their local toll provider, much as they choose a long-distance
company.
</P>
<P>
   But don't grab the phone just yet.
</P>
<P>
   The prices being offered by alternate carriers are competitive,
but not all customers are candidates for switching. Those who want
to switch should be aware of monthly fees and other requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the discounts on local toll calls will come to customers
who choose the same company for their local toll and long-distance
service.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T just lowered its local toll rates to 5 cents per minute,
down from 7 cents, but the rate applies only to customers on an
AT&AMP;T long-distance plan. MCI and Sprint also give preferential toll
rates to their long-distance customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really encourage customers to give us all their business in
order to get the best benefits,'' said Joyce Dorris, director of
brand marketing for MCI.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell offers cheaper rates to customers who buy lots of local
toll minutes, but unless you use all the included minutes, consumer
advocates say, customers can wind up paying more than the
advertised rates.
</P>
<P>
   To help decide whether to switch carriers, consumers can check
out the WebPricer, a service on the World Wide Web provided by
consumer advocates that calculates the cost of each local toll
call. The site is located at &LR;  http://ora.ca.gov &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   To determine whether a call is classified as a local toll or
long-distance call, customers can call a Pac Bell operator or check
the front of the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   Today has been long anticipated by both consumers and phone
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Californians have been waiting for the savings promised by the
1996 Telecommunications Act. Until now, only customers in GTE
territory in Southern California have had a choice of local toll
providers. Bay Area consumers have had to ``dial around'' Pac Bell
to get better rates.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell's competitors have been eager to get into California's
local toll market, which is estimated to be worth $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the phone company and its competitors have spent several
years arguing over entry. Competitors said Pac Bell was unfairly
keeping them out, and Pac Bell said it was following the rules
spelled out in the Telecommunications Act.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell argued that it did not have to open the market to
competitors until the company was allowed to offer long-distance
service. So far, Pac Bell has been denied entry to that lucrative
market.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, state regulators ordered Pac Bell to open the local
toll market after the Federal Communications Commission issued a
similar ruling. Pac Bell asked the FCC to postpone the start date
to June 15 so it could prepare for the change but was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   John Britton, a Pac Bell spokesman, said the company has spent
the past few weeks reprogramming 774 switches across the state and
training over 8,000 service representatives.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months, switching from Pac Bell to another
local toll provider will be free. After November 7, it will cost
$5.26 to make the change. However, some long-distance companies may
pick up that tab.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
