<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH MEETS RELATIVES OF JASPER SLAYING VICTIM AS HATE CRIMES BILL
DEBATED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush met for the first time
Thursday with relatives of the Jasper man who was dragged to death
last year, assuring them he would take ``a serious look'' at the
hate crimes bill if the Senate passes it, but refusing to try to
sway senators on how to vote, the victim's family said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, in so many words, that next to God he is the man
holding my dad's fate. And I said, `It's up to you if my dad died
in vain,''' said Francis Renee Mullins, the 28-year-old daughter of
James Byrd Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he told me that no matter what the (outcome), my dad did
not die in vain,'' Mullins added. ``I think I moved him a little
bit, but not as much as I would have liked to.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullins and her cousin, 27-year-old Darrell Verrett, met with
Bush for about 10 minutes in the governor's office, pleading with
him the importance of passage of the James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes
Act. The measure, House Bill 938 by Rep. Senfronia Thompson,
D-Houston, passed the House last week but has met strong opposition
in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said the governor had offered to
meet with the Byrd family shortly after his murder but the family
had declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor told them (Thursday) that he was pleased that the
real murderer in the terrible, brutal murder received the death
penalty,'' McClellan added.
</P>
<P>
   One of three white men charged in the killing of Byrd, an
African-American, has been convicted. The two other men will be
tried later.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Senate Criminal Justice Committee took testimony
for more than four hours Thursday on the hate crimes bill, Sen.
Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, who is carrying the bill in the Upper
Chamber, left the matter pending because he was one vote shy of
being able to move it to the Senate floor. He said he would try to
schedule a vote for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is made up of four Republicans and three
Democrats, and votes at this point are falling along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   And on the National Day of Prayer, Mullins _ breaking down in
tears as she described how her father died as his head and arm were
ripped from his body as it was dragged along a logging road _ told
the committee she was praying that they would vote the bill out of
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hanging on to the grace of God that you and your peers
will do what's right,'' Mullins said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston state Sen. John Whitmire, meanwhile, was so incensed by
the stalemate in the Senate committee that he was hoping to muster
votes from fellow Democrats to block all bills from floor debate
until the hate crimes bill is heard there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would be remiss if we didn't raise the stakes a
little,'' Whitmire said. ``I don't think you'd have to do it (block
all bills) but a day or two.''
</P>
<P>
   He admits, though, that the support isn't there for that drastic
of a tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am optimistic we will come up with the one additional vote
... but we need the governor, the lieutenant governor and the
speaker,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``as important as tax reform, but this does not have the
bully pulpit of the governor's office, but, hey, it's picking up
steam,'' Ellis added.
</P>
<P>
   As passed by the House, the bill would enhance penalties for
those convicted of crimes against a person because of the victim's
race, gender, sexual preference or any of seven other categories of
individuals. It would not, however, increase penalties for those
convicted of murder or capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   It also would allow victims of hate crimes to seek civil
remedies against their attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Most proponents of the proposal contend that the current statute
is so vague it is unusable and likely unconstitutional. Indeed,
Ellis said, it has been used only twice since it was passed in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue that the bill would set up preferential
categories of victims, giving criminals tougher penalties for
attacking one of the protected group than for someone who is not in
a protected group.
</P>
<P>
   But Ellis and other Democrats insist the real ``hot button
issue'' is its inclusion of gays and lesbians in the protected
categories.
</P>
<P>
   But at least, Ellis said, ``the debate this session has matured
to the point that even if it is their concern, they're too ashamed
to say it.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Mayor Lee Brown told the committee that the hate crimes
legislation is sorely needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The James Byrd Hate Crimes Act is an important piece of
legislation ... because it will send a strong message to those who
commit crimes against an individual or group because of their
prejudice, bias or hatred,'' Brown said. ``The hate crimes bill
will assist in stopping a cycle of violence, a cycle that starts
with small maybe subtle acts of hatred but eventually builds into
cruel acts of bigotry as well as brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   Yvette Cantu of the Family Research Group of Washington, D.C.,
said she believes that any bill or law that sets up distinctions
should not be passed, or should be repealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will a man who rapes me because I'm a lesbian be convicted
differently than if he raped me because I'm 5-foot-4-inches,'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
