<SLUG> BC-BKN-PLAYOFFS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UGLY SEASON IN THE PAST: NOW PAYOFF IS PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Used to be you followed your team until it was knocked out,
caught a few highlights from the later rounds and eventually tuned
in for the coronation. The playoffs were replete with fun and
flair, but ultimately the drama boiled down to whether the Chicago
Bulls would win in five games or six, whether Michael Jordan would
hit the game-winner with 1.2 seconds left or at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Used to be Celtics, Lakers, Bulls; you knew who was going to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people tell me they never felt like they had a
chance,'' said Heat coach Pat Riley, referring to the reign of the
Los Angeles Lakers. ``And I'm sure it was the same way in the
Eastern Conference when Boston was running the show.''
</P>
<P>
   As the National Basketball Association postseason opens
Saturday, six teams have a legitimate chance to win the
championship. And that's not counting the Houston Rockets or the
Lakers, who meet in the most compelling Western Conference
first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that a dynasty has been broken up and the playing
field somewhat has been equaled, I do think everybody feels hungry
and feels they have a chance,'' Riley said. ``There's nothing
looming down there in the specter of a Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   The lockout-ruptured regular season is over. The payoff for all
those pulled hamstrings and 56-point eyesores begins Saturday when
Riley's Heat and the Knicks begin Act III of their basketball
morality play in Miami. Larry Bird's third-seeded Indiana Pacers,
maybe the East's best hope to win the post-Michael/Scottie crown,
play host to Milwaukee in Game 1 on Sunday. Also on Sunday, the
Orlando Magic will try to corral Allen Iverson and the Philadelphia
76ers.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the veteran, savvy Utah Jazz is a lock. Karl Malone and
John Stockton may have to go through San Antonio to advance to the
finals for a third consecutive season. The Spurs and the Jazz
finished with identical 37-13 records, but Tim Duncan, David
Robinson and the Spurs won the home-court tie breaker, and a
remarkable 31 of their last 36 games.
</P>
<P>
   Portland may have peaked, but it still has enough rebounders and
young legs to match up well against either San Antonio or Utah.
Indicative of the parity, the Jazz opens against Sacramento, a
matchup that has presented three overtimes in three games this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Jordan's retirement and the Bulls' disbanding may
not be the commercial downfall of the NBA after all. At least they
were nice enough to leave the league's other 28 teams with a nice
going-away present: a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody out there who scares you,'' said Avery Johnson,
the San Antonio point guard. ``You respect all the better teams,
but you don't fear them like maybe teams feared the Bulls in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the parity, Riley said: ``More so in the East. I do think
there are a few teams over there that have the experience and the
size. I mean, Utah has been there. They sort of remind me of what
happened in 1983 with Dr. J,'' he added, referring to
Philadelphia's breakthrough year for a title after so many years of
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that they weren't a great, great, great team,'' Riley
said, ``but it's like the heavyweight champion of the world. If the
next one in line has been there twice already, you're going to have
to really beat them. They have the experience and they're going to
be a tough handle out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee and Philadelphia make their return to the playoffs for
the first time since 1991. Postseason neophytes like Iverson will
be forced to match up with veterans like Anfernee Hardaway for at
least a week. Glenn Robinson and Ray Allen make their postseason
debuts against the battle-tested Reggie Miller, Dale Davis, Chris
Mullin and Mark Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Old-school teams like the Jazz and Pacers have an inside track
on the title, but youth is about to be served early in the first
round. If it's not Jason Williams going by Stockton or Alonzo
Mourning dunking over Patrick Ewing, it may be Kobe Bryant and
Shaquille O'Neal helping usher Charles Barkley into retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, meanwhile, continues his development into the league's
most valuable player. It may not happen this season, but as Malone
found out last Sunday in a Spurs victory, Duncan is closing in on
that designation. By the end of the conference finals, the
second-year center may have sealed it.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the first title of the post-Michael era will take more
than all-stars. San Antonio's Mario Elie, Utah's Bryon Russell,
Indiana's Jalen Rose, Miami's Terry Porter and Portland's Stacey
Augmon are the type of selfless contributors who can either knock
down a big shot or move their feet quick enough to pick up a key
offensive foul in the final minutes _ the kind of players that add
fire to this seat-of-the-pants season.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson's 76ers could knock off Orlando in the first round. If
the eighth-seeded Knicks find a way to get past Miami for the
second straight season, they would meet the imminently beatable
Pistons or Hawks in the second round, and be on their way to their
first conference finals in five seasons. And no telling what
Bryant, O'Neal and Glen Rice can do if they keep jelling
offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Wild. From a labor-pained season of mediocrity, a postseason of
intriguing possibility has emerged. Just thank Jordan and the Bulls
for their going-away present.
</P>
</TEXT>
