<HEADLINE>
WEST POINT DECIDES IT SHOULD SEEK PRIVATE FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forced to compete with increasingly wealthy universities while
making do on a tight post-Cold War defense budget, the U.S.
Military Academy at West Point, N.Y., is announcing Friday the
first major private fund-raising campaign in the history of the
service academies.
</P>
<P>
   West Point, which gets nearly all its money from the Defense
Department and gives full scholarships to every one of its 4,100
cadets, hopes to raise $150 million to endow professorships and to
pay for amenities like improved athletic buildings and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure that West Point maintains itself as a
tier-one quality institution,'' said Lt. Gen. Daniel Christman,
West Point's superintendent. He said that while the budget has
remained roughly constant after inflation over many years,
competition for the most desirable students has intensified.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other tier-one schools we compete with are in the middle
of what I describe to alumni as a war with each other _ for
faculty, for modernization, for technology,'' he said. ``We felt we
could not go to Congress to ask for all of this. The reality _ and
I've been around the Army 34 years _ is that we have rarely seen
the fiscal constraints as tight as they have been.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army pays basic operating costs of about $175 million a
year. But fund-raisers are quick to distinguish between ``core
needs'' _ like the classes, military training and barracks
essential for students working toward a bachelor's degree and
military commission _ and the extras that new money will pay for,
like internships, expanded student recruitment and stadium viewing
stands.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years of the quiet phase of the campaign, the period
during which an institution approaches its best donors before
announcing its campaign, West Point has already raised nearly $100
million, including 19 gifts of $1 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the fund-raising effort, formally named the
Bicentennial Campaign because of West Point's 200th anniversary in
2002, is like any other university campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It has the requisite wealthy alumni as co-chairmen, in this case
Peter Dawkins (West Point '59), a Heisman Trophy winner and Rhodes
scholar who is vice chairman of Citigroup's Travelers Insurance
Co., and Dana Mead (West Point '57), a former White House fellow
and West Point professor who is now chairman and chief executive of
Tenneco Corp.
</P>
<P>
   And it has the requisite contribution from an Internet baron: $7
million from Jim Kimsey (West Point '62), who led the first company
of the 82nd Airborne into the Dominican Republic in 1965 and 20
years later founded America Online.
</P>
<P>
   But in critical ways, the campaign is unlike any other. For one
thing, federal employees are legally barred from asking for money
from private donors, so the campaign is being run by West Point's
alumni group, the Association of Graduates, with academy officials
playing a supporting role.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raisers must also be cautious about corporate donations.
Defense contractors would seem an obvious source of money, but
alumni association officials are wary that such contributions could
create a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been very careful _ and the defense contractors
have been very careful _ not to create a real or imagined quid pro
quo, though we're not eliminating anyone,'' Mead said.
</P>
<P>
   All contributions must be reviewed by Army lawyers either at
West Point or in Washington, said Lt. Col. Michael Mahan, the
alumni association's vice president for development. ``It is
sometimes an impediment to fund raising,'' he added, ``but the
point is that there could be room for impropriety here and we have
to take the time and effort to make sure that there isn't any.''
</P>
<P>
   Six companies, including Rockwell International, Lucent
Technologies Microelectronics, and CAE Electronics, are on the
preliminary list of 71 ``leadership'' donors to the campaign. Mahan
said the biggest corporate gift so far is $1 million from MBNA
America for a military ethics center.
</P>
<P>
   The college must also be careful about how it attaches donor
names to campus facilities, a standard perquisite for large
contributors. ``As with most public schools, we are trying to come
up with tasteful naming opportunities,'' Christman said. ``But we
do not put them in the main cadet areas so we don't modify the
military ethos of the place.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that West Point needs private money to supplement its
public budget surprised Christman when he signed on as
superintendent three years ago after serving as assistant to the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   West Point, like the other service academies, has routinely
accepted donations from its 45,000 alumni, but it had not
cultivated them in the systematic way that other leading
universities do. A good year meant about $5 million in donations,
except when the alumni were raising money for a project, like a new
alumni hall. Some private universities much larger than West Point
take in hundreds of millions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have sent out a mailing once a year and had a few
focused efforts to fund specific projects,'' Mead said.
</P>
<P>
   Other service academies are either contemplating or planning
similar campaigns. The Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md., said
recently that it intended to begin a campaign but had not announced
any specific goal of how much to raise. Richard Coppock, president
of the alumni association at the Air Force Academy in Colorado,
said Thursday that he expects it to do something similar.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   West Point officials and alumni spent about a year discussing
the possibility of a major fund-raising drive, how the money might
be used and how much to seek. But it took time to convince alumni
of the need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys who have been to Vietnam feel, `Hey, I gave at the
office,''' Kimsey said. ``This really is a sea change for them.''
</P>
<P>
   William McGoldrick, a former college development officer whose
firm, Washburn &AMP; McGoldrick, was a consultant to West Point as it
planned its campaign, said that the alumni are as passionate about
their academy as those from colleges with the highest rates of
giving, like Dartmouth and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The unique experience of attending West Point, including the
first-year hazing program known as Beast Barracks, appears to have
created a loyal alumni corps. In interviews with West Point alumni,
McGoldrick said, many expressed strong affection for the
institution. He recalled one who said, ``Next to my wife, I love
nothing more than West Point.''
</P>
<P>
   McGoldrick was also not expecting so many of the alumni to be
wealthy. ``In hindsight, we shouldn't have been surprised,'' he
said, noting that while many West Point graduates stay in the
military for 20 years or more, many others leave for careers in
business. (In exchange for their free education, graduates must
spend five years on active duty and three years in reserve.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 52 individuals we interviewed, a third were chief
executives, chief operating officers or chief financial officers at
major U.S. corporations,'' McGoldrick said.
</P>
<P>
   As in most college fund-raising, donors are giving money to
projects that appeal to them. Mead, who holds a Ph.D. in political
science and economics from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, said he was paying for four ``Mead scholars'' to work
each summer in organizations like NATO, the United Nations or the
Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   Dawkins, who was captain of cadets, senior class president and
captain of the football team, is contributing $1 million toward a
``vastly improved strength development center'' for exercising.
</P>
<P>
   ``A steel bar and two coffee cans filled with cement is where I
began,'' he said. But in his view, the academy needs the latest
equipment, especially if it is to compete against heavily endowed
football powerhouses.
</P>
<P>
   He and others contend that such extras are important to lure the
strongest students possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us feel in our bones that the world is not going to
get any less dangerous, and is not going to be any less in need of
good leadership for the Army,'' Dawkins said. ``So we should
literally leave no stone unturned in trying to provide the very
best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
