<HEADLINE>
NBC MINESERIES FOLLOWS THE TRAIL OF A KILLER FUGITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any memories of Kevin Anderson as the kindly Father Ray of
``Nothing Sacred'' will vanish upon viewing ``The Hunt for the
Unicorn Killer.''
</P>
<P>
   In a well-made NBC miniseries that's as good as ``Noah's Ark''
was bad, Anderson is outstanding as the consummate slimeball _ a
brilliant, manipulative narcissist who seduces women with his
``I's.'' Indeed, one reason why this film spans Sunday and Monday
nights is that Ira Einhorn's ego surely couldn't have been
contained in one evening.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn is the wily fugitive you may have read about over the
years. In the '60s and '70s, he was a prominent anti-war and civil
rights activist in Philadelphia. His Svengali-like personality
attracted many disciples,
</P>
<P>
   some of them wealthy and prominent. He used these connections in
1977 to jump bail after being charged with the murder of his
girlfriend, Holly Maddux. A Philadelphia jury convicted him in
absentia, but even though a diligent investigator traced him to
Ireland, then Sweden and finally France, Einhorn is not in jail
today. A French court initially refused to send him back, then said
he could be returned only if he were retried. Pennsylvania has
enacted legislation allowing a new trial, but Einhorn is appealing
the French ruling and remains a free man, 22 years after Maddux's
body was found stuffed in a steamer trunk in his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Einhorn says he was framed by the CIA. ``The Hunt for the
Unicorn Killer'' makes note of this defense, but the film's
position is unmistakable: Ira Einhorn is a killer, he has been
convicted in a court of law, and he deserves to pay dearly for
murdering Holly Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   Supported by strong evidence, including the testimony of
acquaintances and Einhorn's own journals, Anderson studiously
creates a classic villain: intelligent and charming, scheming and
mean.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Maddux, a Bryn Mawr graduate from Tyler, Texas, fell in
love with the intelligent/charming side. It was the start of a
relationship she tried to end more than once, but to which she
always returned. Except the last time Maddux said she was leaving,
she disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux's father, Fred, suspected Einhorn from the start, but
Philadelphia police were reluctant to investigate a celebrity. Only
after a private investigator pieced together enough evidence to
implicate Einhorn did police join the case and ultimately find
Maddux's body _ 18 months after her disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   It's every father's nightmare, and Tom Skerritt effectively
conveys the anguish, uncertainty, confusion and dread that dogged
Fred Maddux for years. ``My job was to protect her,'' he says in
the film, quietly convincing himself that he failed as a father.
It's a dramatic demonstration of how much Einhorn had insinuated
himself into other people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one was more affected than Holly Maddux, who died
from a horrible beating. Australian actress Naomi Watts gives a
delicate performance, subtly finding the strength and vulnerability
of the impressionable young woman. Laurels, too, to Kellie Overbey,
who plays Meg, one of three Maddux sisters who continue the
campaign to bring the Unicorn _ Einhorn is German for ``one horn''
_ back home for a little ego reduction.
</P>
<P>
   The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer. Four-hour miniseries about the
true story of fugitive Ira Einhorn. Starring Kevin Anderson, Tom
Skerritt and Naomi Watts. Sunday and Monday on NBC. Parental
guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
