<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7533 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-CHINA-REPORT-N     05-06 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-CHINA-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL FINDS U.S. MISTAKES LED TO CHINA IMPROVING MISSILE
FLEET 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate investigators have concluded that lax
monitoring of the launching of American satellites in China and
shortfalls in U. S. intelligence assessments contributed to
Beijing's enhancing its ballistic missile fleet using American
expertise.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators have also found that China sought to influence
the 1996 elections in the United States but say it is unclear
whether specific political donations known to have been made by
Chinese officials were a part of that overall plan.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were included in a 45-page unclassified report that
the Senate Select Committee on Intelligence issued Thursday night.
The report was approved with virtual unanimity by the 17-member
committee. Only Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., dissented, committee aides
said, for reasons that could not be learned Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   China's ballistic missile advances and its efforts to influence
the 1996 elections were addressed in separate sections of the
committee's report. This was done, committee aides said, at the
insistence of an influential Democrat, Sen. Carl Levin of Michigan,
to underscore that no link between the two matters had been found.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not address recent news accounts of China's theft
of some of this country's most sensitive nuclear secrets. Those
accounts surfaced largely after the committee had completed its
formal inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the report have the scope or detail of a still
classified report compiled by a special House investigative
committee on technology transfers to China.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it focused on the impact to U.S. national security of
the launching of American satellites in China, and on China's
efforts to influence the elections three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the committee's conclusions affirmed findings by
American military and intelligence analysts, among them that
national security had been harmed by the satellite launchings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee concludes that the technical information
transferred during satellite launch campaigns'' has enabled China
``to improve its present and future space launch vehicles and
ICBM's,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel focused on two instances in particular where sensitive
information was divulged to the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   One case involved information that the Hughes Electronics Corp.,
a General Motors subsidiary, and Loral Space and Communications
shared with Chinese engineers after a failed launching of a Loral
satellite in February 1996. The other instance involved information
that Hughes shared with Chinese officials after the failed
launching of a Hughes satellite in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   These transfers of information came at a time, investigators
said, when China was aggressively trying to obtain sensitive
military technology. Although American intelligence analysts filed
reports at the time describing this Beijing priority, the committee
found that intelligence warnings had not highlighted the risk to
national security associated with specific technology exports.
</P>
<P>
   The committee found no evidence that China had yet incorporated
what it learned into its long-range nuclear missile fleet, and
acknowledged that China had improved its missile program more with
help from other countries than from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the panel offered several recommendations to
strengthen the monitoring of the launching of American satellites
in China, including detailed reports by the Pentagon to Congress
and pay increases for American monitors of those launchings.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also recommended that senior American intelligence
officials be closely consulted during the process of export
licensing of commercial satellites. In addition, Congress should be
notified when satellite companies are under suspicion of violating
export laws, the senators said.
</P>
<P>
   One major change already enacted into law at Congress'
insistence is the shift in control of American satellite exporting,
back to the State Department from the Commerce Department. The
Clinton administration transferred jurisdiction to the Commerce
Department in 1996, and the department was later accused of putting
commercial interests ahead of national security.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Security Council, David C. Leavy,
said Thursday night that the administration concurred with most of
the committee's recommendations regarding satellite exports.
</P>
<P>
   As for China's efforts to influence American elections in 1996 _
the subject of extensive hearings by House and Senate committees in
1997 _ the investigators found that the focus of China's plan was
the Congress, although there was no evidence of any attempt to
influence a specific lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   In this part of the report, investigators noted that Johnny
Chung, a Democratic fund-raiser, had told them that he had been
given $300,000 by a senior Chinese official to help President
Clinton's re-election campaign. But, the report said, the FBI has
been able to trace only $20,000 of that sum to the Democratic
National Committee, from a contribution by Chung. Most of the rest,
the report says, went to Chung's personal use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
