<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT &LR;      05-06 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIDE TAKES OUT KNOBLAUCH, BUT NOT FOR THE YEAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Chuck Knoblauch limped slowly into the Yankees'
clubhouse late Thursday afternoon, like a miracle at a religious
revival. His teammates, who had expected Knoblauch to be rolled,
carried or pushed to his locker with his left leg in a cast or
splint, gawked in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, you're walking,'' said Scott Brosius, grinning in
amazement, for he and the others had witnessed the frightening
collision initiated by the Minnesota rookie Corey Koskie and
expected the worst after seeing Knoblauch writhing on the ground in
agony near second base. If Knoblauch, hitting .333 as the leadoff
batter, had been lost for the year, none of them would have been
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch may miss only a few days or maybe a little longer
with a severely bruised lower left leg _ ``I was very lucky,'' he
said _ and the Yankees finished their 10-game road trip happily,
pleased about their 6-4 record. Given the hard humor of
ballplayers, a few of them may have even thanked Knoblauch for
sacrificing his body on the play that proved pivotal to their 4-3,
10-inning victory over the Twins Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (18-9) returned to New York and will begin a
nine-game homestand on Friday against the Seattle Mariners. Hideki
Irabu is scheduled to start against the Mariners' Mac Suzuki in
what is believed to be the first major league match-up between
pitchers of Japanese descent. Luis Sojo will most likely start at
second base for the Yankees in place of Knoblauch, who will undergo
further evaluation Friday and may or may not be placed on the
15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch will gladly suffer the pain and the time lost,
considering what might have been after the frightening play in the
eighth inning. The Yankees and Twins were tied, 3-3. David Cone
allowed three runs in the first inning and gamely battled through
the middle innings, throwing 115 pitches in the first seven
innings. When the Yankees tied the game in the top of the eighth on
Brosius' two-out run-scoring triple, Cone asked to pitch the bottom
of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone walked Brent Gates, and with one out, allowed a
ground-ball single to Terry Steinbach, Gates taking third. Cone
walked Koskie to load the bases, prompting Don Zimmer, the Yankees'
interim manager, to insert the sinkerballer Jason Grimsley, hoping
he might prompt pinch-hitter Ron Coomer to hit the ball on the
ground and get a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Coomer obliged, hitting a chopper toward shortstop Derek Jeter.
Jeter thought the ball was hit too slowly to turn a double play, so
he decided to flip to second base quickly for a force on Koskie and
get one sure out. Gates raced home with the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, however, still wanted to try a double play. With his
left foot on the base, his right foot on the dirt to the left-field
side of the bag, and Koskie bearing down on him, Knoblauch received
Jeter's throw and intended to pivot and fire to first. Willie
Randolph, a former second baseman and now the Yankees' infield
coach, watched Knoblauch plant himself for the throw and cringed.
``Get out of there,'' Randolph said to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's body began turning so that he could throw to first,
and he was facing third base when Koskie, 6 feet 3 inches and 217
pounds and intent on destroying any chance for a double play,
launched himself at Knoblauch. Without touching the ground, he
crashed into the side of Knoblauch's left leg. From third base,
Brosius saw Knoblauch's knee and leg fold in a way the body is not
supposed to bend, and he was sure Knoblauch was seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch went down and immediately tried to rise. He is
accustomed to pain: he usually ranks among the league leaders in
getting hit by pitches, and almost never moves, often taking
fastballs off his ribs and left arm without flinching.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch could not shrug off this injury. He rolled on the
dirt and grimaced, eyes closed, and he could hear the shouting of
the second-base umpire, Jim Joyce. Joyce dramatically pointed at
Koskie, saying he had gone over the bag to hit Knoblauch and
interfered with his attempt at a double play. Coomer was called
out, ending the rally without any runs, and later, Twins Manager
Tom Kelly said Joyce's ruling was ``the right call, no question
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was carried off the field, leaning on the shoulders of
teammates, and he said to others in the dugout that his left foot
was numb. Unlike his teammates watching silently as trainers tended
to him, Knoblauch already figured his knee was all right. ``I could
bend it,'' he said. But Knoblauch was not sure if his leg was
broken, and he was taken to Hennepin County Medical Center for
X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees went about the business of winning the game. Bernie
Williams led off the 10th inning with a single to left, stole
second, and with one out, Ricky Ledee _ batting .162 _ fell behind
in the count to Rick Aguilera, no balls and two strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we go again,'' Ledee thought, but he punched a line drive
to left field and Williams scored the decisive run.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees returned to their clubhouse, already certain
Knoblauch was hurt and would be sidelined extensively. ``It's very
unfortunate for us,'' catcher Joe Girardi said. ``From the looks of
it, we're not going to have him for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   From Girardi to Zimmer to Cone to Brosius to Randolph, they said
Koskie's play was reckless, not dirty, a result of rookie
exuberance and inexperience that is understandable and
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just leaves a bad taste in your mouth when you see your
second baseman get roll-blocked and hurt,'' Cone said. ``He's a
young player and I'm sure he's just trying to play the game hard,
but you can't roll-block that late when the second baseman is in a
vulnerable position. His career is on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Koskie, who knew Knoblauch _ a former Twin _ and chatted with
him on Tuesday and Wednesday, went to Kelly immediately after the
game and apologized for the play, and Kelly called Zimmer to check
on Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   At the hospital, doctors X-rayed Knoblauch's leg and found no
fractures; same with his ankle. Knoblauch's leg was wrapped and,
still wearing his baseball pants and T-shirt, he limped gingerly
into the clubhouse, much to the stunned relief of teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he was just trying to play the game hard,'' Knoblauch
said, cheerfully. ``I can deal with these bruises, and I'll get
back out there as soon as I can.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
