</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENCRYPTION-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT CALLS LIMITS ON DATA-SCRAMBLING SOFTWARE UNCONSTITUTIONAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)  (rk) 
 By PETER WAYNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. government's restrictions on the export of
data-scrambling software are unconstitutional, a federal appeals
court in California ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by a three-judge panel of the 9th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in San Francisco affirmed a lower court ruling in
the case of an Illinois mathematics professor who had sought to
distribute information about encryption on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three judges concluded that the federal export
regulations ``operate as a prepublication licensing scheme that
burdens scientific expression'' and thus were a prohibited form of
prior restraint under the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The government has long argued that encryption software used to
scramble messages is a ``munition.'' Indeed, military history is
rife with examples of battles that have turned on intercepted
messages.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, many businesses and computer software companies
have lobbied the government to relax those regulations, arguing
that protection of sensitive financial and other private data is
essential to growth of Internet commerce. Moreover, they have
argued that because encryption software is common overseas, the
laws merely prevent American companies from competing.
</P>
<P>
   The case began when Daniel Bernstein, who now teaches
mathematics at the University of Illinois at Chicago, was a
doctoral student at the University of California at Berkeley.
Bernstein developed an encryption program he called Snuffle and
wanted to publish it for review.
</P>
<P>
   When Bernstein was denied an export license by the Commerce
Department, he sued with the backing of the Electronic Frontier
Foundation, a civil liberties group.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's decision, written by Judge Betty B. Fletcher and
joined by Judge Myron H. Bright, found that the regulations vested
``boundless discretion in government officials.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the Supreme Court has held that prior restraint, or
blocking something from being published, is legal only in extreme
cases. Thursday's opinion said that the Commerce Department's
license requirements for exporting encryption software ``run the
twin risks of encouraging self-censorship and concealing
illegitimate abuses of censorial power.''
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Judge T.G. Nelson argued that
distributing encryption software was a form of conduct, not speech,
and thus could be regulated.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher and Bright disagreed, stating, ``The source code at
issue here is text intended for human understanding, albeit in a
specialized language.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Department of Justice, which brought the case, and the
Department of Commerce declined to comment until they had reviewed
the decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
