<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-COLLEGE-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NET DIFFERENCE IN GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You wouldn't know it from looking at her stats,
but UCLA goalie Erin Golaboski hates her position. Not so USC
keeper Bernice Orwig.
</P>
<P>
   For each of Golaboski's 186 saves and 4.6 goals-allowed average,
she would trade it for playing in the field, maybe as a two-meter
or driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to play in the goal as a kid, but now she can't stand
it,'' UCLA interim water polo coach Adam Krikorian said.
</P>
<P>
   Orwig thrives in goal, making 212 saves and earning her
conference's Player of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   Their paths have crossed several times this season, with USC and
Orwig thriving each time. They might meet again this weekend in the
NCAA women's national tournament in Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The roles have switched. UCLA (21-9), which has won the past
three titles, finds itself seeded fourth. The Bruins begin today at
10:45 a.m. against 13th-seeded Maryland. USC (26-2) is No.1 after
never finishing better than fifth.The Trojans meet No.16 Indiana at
9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterfinals are later today (USC would face either UC
Santa Barbara or San Jose State at 3 p.m., UCLA would get Hawaii or
UC San Diego at 5:30). The two could meet in Saturday's semifinal
at 5:15 p.m., with the winner advancing to Sunday's national
championship game at 3:30 p.m. Stanford and Cal are seeded second
and third.
</P>
<P>
   Both goalies have national tournament experience, but Golaboski
played in the field last year and scored 65 goals, second-best on
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played goalie in high school (in Maryland), and I was
recruited to play goal,'' Golaboski said. ``But they didn't need
me, so I played in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't needed because UCLA had All-American Nicolle Payne.
Payne graduated, so Krikorian asked Golaboski to return.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``ask'' isn't the right word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize I didn't have a choice,'' Golaboski said, ``so I
worked at it and got better.''
</P>
<P>
   Orwig comes to play every day (she has 80 saves in her previous
national tournaments) and has watched the Trojans attitude change
of late. The players respond differently to coach Jovan Vavic's
shouting. They're practicing harder, she said, because the main
goal is in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practice hard because we want to,'' she said, ``not because
Jovan was yelling at us. In meetings, Jovan asks a question and
everyone knows the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the team's role has switched to favorite, Orwig doesn't
think the pressure will overwhelm the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me more confidence,'' she said. ``Everyone has a
greater sense of what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you know?: Traditionally, the Mountain Pacific Sports
Federation volleyball runner-up receives the at-large berth into
the NCAA Final Four, which began Thursday and concludes Saturday.
This season, USC was passed over in favor of Long Beach State, a
team the Trojans beat in the first round of the MPSF tournament. It
made sense, since Long Beach had beaten USC three times this season
and the 49ers are ranked higher.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the runner-up didn't receive the NCAA at-large
berth was 1990. UCLA finished second but USC got the berth and went
on to win its fourth national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Roumain repeats: Pepperdine volleyball player George Roumain
repeated as the American Volleyball Coaches Association's Player of
the Year. The 6-foot-6 outside hitter is only the second player
(UCLA's Jeff Nygaard is the other) to be named national player of
the year twice.
</P>
<P>
   Roumain led the nation with an 8.55-kills-per-game average and
was third with 2.47 digs per game.
</P>
<P>
   Also making the All-America team were Highland graduate Ryan
Millar of BYU, who became one of only five players to earn
first-team honors three times; UCLA's Adam Naeve and Brandon
Taliaferro and Pepperdine's Scott Wong.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine golf notes: The women qualified for the NCAA West
Regional Championships for the first time and will be one of 20
teams competing at the Pine Forest Country Club in Houston this
weekend. The top 11 teams and two individuals will advance to the
NCAA Championships, May 19-22, in Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Tamie Durdin leads the Waves with a 74.71 stroke
average.
</P>
<P>
   The men finish the regular season with this weekend's
Stanford-U.S. Intercollegiate. Freshmen Michael Beard leads wit a
73.28 stroke average.
</P>
<P>
   On the tennis court: The UCLA men earned the No. 1 seed for the
NCAA championships that begin May 14. The Bruins (21-2) will host
Western Michigan. Also playing at UCLA are Tulsa and San Diego
State.
</P>
<P>
   USC is seeded 12th and will face Missouri-Kansas City in Fresno.
Fresno State and Nevada-Las Vegas complete the bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine's men also made the tournament and will play New
Mexico in Tempe, Ariz. Fourteenth-seeded Arizona State is the host
and will play Hofstra.
</P>
<P>
   The final four rounds are May 20-23 at Florida.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, UCLA, Pepperdine and USC earned the eighth,
ninth and 10th seeds and will play at home. UCLA gets Western
Michigan (with South Alabama and Colorado), Pepperdine has Boston
University (with Lousiana State and Ohio State) and USC faces Drake
(with Minnesota and San Diego).
</P>
<P>
   The final four rounds are May 20-23 at Georgia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
