<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN HEIR KEEPS REINS AT TELEVISA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The young heir who took over Televisa, Mexico's
largest television network, has survived family feuds and
management crises to finish refinancing his hold on the company
without yielding control outside his family.
</P>
<P>
   Months of rumors that Rupert Murdoch, the worldwide media
executive, who has been on a television shopping spree in the
United States and Europe, would buy in to the Mexican broadcaster,
were laid to rest for the time being Thursday. Grupo Televicentro,
the holding company that controls Televisa, announced that the
Mexican venture capital firm Sinca Inbursa had purchased a 24
percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Inbursa is part of the empire of Carlos Slim Helu, one of the
wealthiest men in Latin America, who is also chairman of Telefonos
de Mexico, the telecommunications conglomerate. Slim agreed that
his investment in Televicentro would be placed in a neutral trust
fund that will always vote with the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Emilio Azcarraga Jean, 31, the chairman of Grupo Televisa SA,
retained 51 percent of the holding company while his first cousin
Alejandro Burillo increased his stake to 25 percent from 11
percent. That ensures Azcarraga's control over the huge media
concern created by his father, since Televicentro holds a
controlling stake of 26.5 percent of the voting shares of Televisa.
</P>
<P>
   In comments last week, Slim said he was not interested in
running Televisa, the largest media company in the Spanish-speaking
world. He called it ``an excellent company with very good
management'' which he regarded as a solid investment, and he said
Inbursa had made a favorable deal, as well. No details were
released on the price Slim paid. But analysts said it was probably
in the $100 million range.
</P>
<P>
   Televisa shares soared by nearly 14 percent on the stock market
here Thursday, in part reflecting Slim's reputation as a savvy
investor whose stock choices are widely emulated. In New York,
Televisa's American depository receipts rose $5, or 11.7 percent,
to $47.75.
</P>
</TEXT>
