<SLUG> BC-WTO-DEADLOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE ENVOYS AGAIN FAIL TO CHOOSE LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ Negotiations over a new leader for the
World Trade Organization are likely to remain deadlocked until at
least next week, envoys to the group said Thursday, and there was
increasing speculation that neither of the two finalists would get
the job.
</P>
<P>
   The rising pessimism came after another meeting failed to make
progress toward a choice between the New Zealand and Thai
candidates for director- general of the trade organization, the
134-nation group that determines the rules and mediates disputes in
global commerce. It has been leaderless for nearly a week.
</P>
<P>
   With each day the deadlock persists, the possibility increases
that the organization will have to postpone a ministerial meeting
on Nov. 30 in Seattle, where it had been expected to begin
important talks on lowering remaining trade barriers in goods in
services.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff between the supporters of Mike Moore, New Zealand's
former prime minister, and Supachai Panitchpakdi, Thailand's deputy
premier and commerce minister, has come to symbolize the
organization's difficulty in reaching agreements easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, the members, should be ashamed of the spectacle,''
Mexico's trade envoy, Alejandro de la Pena, said after the failed
round of negotiations Thursday. He said the group had not learned
from the wrangling over the selection of its first
director-general, Renato Ruggiero of Italy, whose four-year term
expired May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Envoys said they were unlikely to reconvene until late next
week, diminishing the chances of a breakthrough before then. Last
week, Moore was named as the candidate with the most likely chance
of getting consensus by the member nations. But Supachai's
supporters have insisted that the organization's governing body,
the general council, try to build a consensus around the Thai
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Repercussions from the standoff in Geneva have rippled out to
Asia, where Thailand's government has blamed the United States for
trying to derail Supachai.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials, who strongly back Moore, have made it clear that
they are against efforts to revive Supachai's chances.
</P>
<P>
   As the deadlock stretched on, diplomats began raising the idea
of scotching both candidates and starting over. ``I don't think
we're there yet,'' one European envoy said, ``but it is a real
possibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
