<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DIDDLEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BO DIDDLEY AGAIN FEELS LIKE A MAN AMONGST THIEVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the fans he has made and the awards he has won as one of
the pioneers of rock 'n' roll, Bo Diddley feels like a two-time
loser.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, '60s and '70s, it was unscrupulous lawyers, agents
and label executives that conned him out of money he was rightly
owed from the sales of his records.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's bootleggers, pirates and the Internet that are
depriving him of a better living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said about 30 years ago that these computers were going to
be the death of us,'' Diddley said in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Awakened from a nap, Diddley was admittedly cranky when he
picked up the phone at his home in Levy County, Fla. From there, he
launched into a laundry list of complaints about the music business
and American society in general. But there were flashes of humor,
too, as he acknowledged the absurdities inherent in a decades-long
music career.
</P>
<P>
   Diddley's last album, the Grammy-nominated ``A Man Amongst
Men,'' was released in 1996 on the Code Blue label, an Atlantic
Records subsidiary. The label has since folded, leaving Diddley
with...well, diddly.
</P>
<P>
   Fans tape his shows because his records are hard to find. Others
download his music for free on the Internet. And every once in a
while, he comes across a CD he knows nothing about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just played a benefit show here in Levy County and a kid
came up to me with a CD he wanted autographed,'' Diddley said with
dismay. ``I asked him where he got it from. It turned out to be a
bootleg. Some label I'd never heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   Diddley, 71, said it is deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost out one time, got slapped in the face and kicked in the
butt and shoved aside. Never got the recognition I deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got these computers and all this garbage going on
with people downloading music for free, so I'm losing again.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his frustrations, Diddley will always be remembered for
his distinctive ``Bo Diddley beat,'' a chunky, syncopated rhythm
featured in many of his classic rock 'n' roll songs _ ``I'm a
Man,'' ``Diddy Wah Diddy,'' ``Diddley Daddy'' (a Chris Isaak
favorite), ``Crackin' Up,'' ``Before You Accuse Me'' (covered in
the 1990s by Eric Clapton), ``Sweet Little Rock 'n' Roller,'' ``Say
Man'' and ``Who Do You Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Diddley's career took off in the mid-'50s when he and Chuck
Berry joined Chess Records. In 1963, he toured Britain for the
first time and discovered that white artists were adopting his
style and making it pay. But within a couple of years, Diddley also
was selling lots of records in Britain, more than he was in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, Diddley went to England to record ``The London
Bo Diddley Sessions.'' As the '70s drew to a close, The Clash
invited the rock veteran to open its British and American tours.
</P>
<P>
   Diddley was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in
1987. Recent honors include Lifetime Achievement Awards from the
National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences (1998) and the
Rhythm and Blues Foundation (1996).
</P>
<P>
   Diddley said he is honored by the awards but otherwise
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderful awards on the wall do not put money in your bank
account,'' he said. ``It does not make my pockets look like
footballs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi native said he makes enough from his live shows
to get by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in poverty. But I could use a couple or more bucks. It
would be so much better if I was paid for these recordings. I
should be a millionaire by now and workin'
</P>
<P>
   if I felt like it. But I gotta work because I have to. And
that's screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that grouses Diddley is the media's view of rock
'n' roll history. Diddley was incensed by a recent TV special that
portrayed Elvis Presley as the creator of rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me sick what they're feeding all these kids on
television,'' Diddley said. ``Elvis was great and he did a hell of
a thing. But he did not start rock 'n' roll and I'm tired of the
lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Diddley travels with one guitar, a custom-built copy of the
box-shaped guitar he made famous in the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to give people something for their money,'' he said.
``We don't run off the stage after 15 minutes like some
entertainers.''
</P>
<P>
   Diddley is currently without a record label. ``I'm not looking
for anybody, but if someone comes along with the right deal and
they really do what they promise they're going to do, sure I'm
interested,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2247EDT &QL; 
