</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEMOCRATS SURVEY UPHILL FIGHT  
 NATIONAL DEMOCRATS RESIST STATE INITIATIVES  
 CALIFORNIA DEVISES `OPEN' PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democrats have always figured that the fight to regain control
of the United States Senate would be all uphill in 2000, given that
Republicans came out of the 1998 election with a 55-45 edge. And
ever since three party stalwarts _ Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New
York, Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey and Richard Bryan of Nevada _
announced this year that they would not seek re-election, the hill
has seemed even steeper.
</P>
<P>
   The job of directing the Democratic comeback effort has fallen
to Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, chairman of the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee, who calculates that the committee
will have to raise at least $60 million for a credible comeback
effort. But Torricelli says, the party must recruit good
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he says the party must be willing in its candidate
search to take a look at ``progressive people, despite their
previous affiliation'' _ independents and fallen-away Republicans,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in Minnesota, where the Republican incumbent, Sen. Rod
Grams, has been considered vulnerable almost since the day he
narrowly won election in 1994, some top Democrats are encouraging
the state's widely popular auditor, Judy Dutcher, a Republican, to
switch parties and challenge Grams.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dutcher might well fit in as a Democrat, being a supporter
of abortion rights and gay rights and a friend of labor. But she
says she will wait a bit before deciding, in part, she adds,
because she also is being courted by the newly resurgent Reform
Party.
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, where another Republican incumbent, James Jeffords,
also seems vulnerable because of a narrow victory in 1994,
Democrats are urging Rep. Bernard Sanders, the only Independent in
the House, to mount a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, one of the state's most popular politicians (he runs at
large because Vermont's population is so small), mostly casts his
lot with Democrats in House votes. So if he ran for the Senate, and
won, he could presumably remain an independent and Senate Democrats
could usually depend on getting his vote.
</P>
<P>
   Will he go for it?
</P>
<P>
   Top House Democrats have told him that if he remains in the
House _ he seems assured of re-election _ they would honor his
seniority and give him a subcommittee chairmanship should the party
regain control next year. But Senate Democrats have made similar
promises, leading their House counterparts to counter that the
House is considerably more likely to end up in Democratic hands in
2000 than the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   National Democrats Resist State Initiatives
</P>
<P>
   Still another state Democratic Party is at odds with the
Democratic National Committee over the scheduling of an event
leading up to next year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   First, Oregon Democrats, then South Carolina Democrats,
squabbled with the committee over primary voting dates, leading the
committee to threaten sanctions if they did not toe the party line.
</P>
<P>
   Now come Massachusetts Democrats with a plan to hold a straw
poll at their state convention this month that will provide an
informal reading on how Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley are faring.
</P>
<P>
   As Gus Bickford, the executive director of the Massachusetts
Democratic State Committee, sees it, the poll, scheduled for May
15, will also ``add a little bit more spice to a convention that
might otherwise not have been as exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   But national party officials see such straw polls otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really don't prove anything,'' Peter Kauffman, a national
committee spokesman, argues.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the committee has yet to threaten Massachusetts Democrats
with any punishment should the vote take place.
</P>
<P>
   The poll will certainly provide a bit of spice if Gore, already
faltering a bit in some other states, shows poorly and Bradley runs
better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no recent Massachusetts newspaper or television
polls that pitted Gore against Bradley in a theoretical primary.
But there are polls, one taken in late April, that show Gore with
much higher ``unfavorable'' ratings than Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Further, in recent Massachusetts newspaper and television polls,
as in polls in other states, Gore has been running well behind the
current Republican leader, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   California Devises `Open' Primary
</P>
<P>
   California officials believe they have finally found a way to
hold an ``open'' presidential primary next year as required by a
new state law and at the same time not violate long-standing
national party rules that forbid such primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The solution is in still another new law, just signed by Gov.
Gray Davis:
</P>
<P>
   Next year's primary will be open as state law mandates _ that
is, voters may cross party lines, supporting whomever they choose
on the ballot, regardless of registration. The results will be
tallied and forwarded to party headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But the ballots will be coded so that separate tallies can be
kept in all instances in which Democrats vote Democratic,
Republicans vote Republican, and so forth. Those tallies will also
be forwarded to party headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials, who helped legislators draw up the newly signed
law, plan to ignore the tallies resulting from the open voting.
While that tallying will satisfy the mandate resulting from a
recently passed citizens' ballot initiative, the parties are
confident that they can legally choose their own rules for counting
votes and thus are under no obligation to accept the open primary
results.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they say they intend to rely on the results from the
coded ballots to pick primary winners. If they do not follow that
carefully plotted course, they warn, the state's delegations to the
national nominating convention will almost certainly not be seated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
