<HEADLINE>
JONES QUESTIONABLE FOR GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calf. _ Los Angeles Galaxy midfielder/forward Cobi
Jones missed practice Wednesday with an injured left big toe and is
questionable for Saturday's match at Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Jones injured himself in the waning moments of Saturday's 1-0
shootout victory over New York/New Jersey at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's day-to-day at this point,'' Galaxy trainer Ivan Pierra
said. ``He's able to jog, but it's a little painful. It's one of
those situations where he could be fine in the next couple days, or
it could take as long as a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Time's up?: Ecuadorian midfielder Jaime Caidedo became the
Galaxy's fourth and final foreign allocation just before the start
of preseason training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old signed a six-month contract which ends later
this month. He was coveted by former Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano,
but likely will be waived when his contract expires. He has not
played in any of the previous seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy assistant coach Ralph Perez said it is tough to keep a
foreign player if he is not contributing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look throughout the league, it's very important you
have four foreign players and that can be an asset,'' Perez said.
``Jaime's a great kid and he works hard, but that's not all you
need from your foreign player. Your foreign player is supposed to
bring an element that is missing or can add something. This year,
we've played seven games and we haven't started more than two
foreigners at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Offense wanted: Despite the Galaxy's four goals in seven games,
no one seems to be panicking or worrying about the team's 4-3
start.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy midfielder/defender Danny Pena says the goals will come,
but the Galaxy needs to get off to a quick start after the kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, our defense created most of our offense,'' Pena
said. ``When we are creating opportunities early in the game, it
forces teams to come at us. When that happens, the game opens up
and we can counter and put more goals in the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that hasn't happened this season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
