<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ELECTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REESE WITHERSPOON GETS WINNING VOTE IN `ELECTION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paramount has been very reluctant to release its
``Rushmore''-like high school comedy, ``Election'' _ possibly
because it's crude and adolescent in ways that could turn off a
mainstream audience (and in at least one way that probably should
have earned it an NC-17 rating).
</P>
<P>
   But after it opened to all favorable reviews in a tiny New York
release two weeks ago, the studio appears to have had a sudden
change of heart. And with little fanfare, it has held its breath
and tossed it into this weekend's release schedule.
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of Jim McAlister (Matthew Broderick), the most
dedicated and popular teacher of Omaha's George Washington Carver
High, whose happy life goes straight to hell when his most annoying
student, Tracy Flick (Reese Witherspoon), launches a campaign to
become student body president.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Tracy conniving, ruthlessly ambitious and sweet on
him, she also recently had an affair with Jim's best friend, who
lost his teaching job and almost went to prison as a consequence.
And if she wins, part of her job will involve working side-by-side
with Jim.
</P>
<P>
   So he inspires the school jock (Chris Klein) to run against her,
and the jock's lesbian sister (Jessica Campbell) also throws her
hat in the ring, and Jim becomes so determined that Tracy not win
the election that he begins a moral slide that snowballs out of
control.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by Alexander Payne, whose first film was the so-so
1996 comedy, ``Citizen Ruth,'' it's often distastefully juvenile,
and has one scene in which a teacher gleefully describes a sex act
with an underage teenager that the MPAA rating board seems not to
have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's mostly funny. Broderick gives a wonderfully deadpan
and long-suffering performance, much of it is very cleverly written
and staged, and its off-beat structure (with narration from all
four principal characters) somehow gives a brilliant cross-section
of the particular horror that is high-school life.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, ``Election'' features a career-best performance
from Witherspoon. By wholeheartedly embracing a character who is
self-deluded, unattractive and totally unsympathetic, she steals
the movie and takes another big step toward becoming what she has
long threatened to be: the Gen X Bette Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Election. Directed by Alexander Payne. Screenplay by Payne &AMP; Jim
Taylor, from the novel by Tom Perrotta. Cast: Matthew Broderick,
Reese Witherspoon, Chris Klein, Jessica Campbell. Paramount. 104
minutes. Rated R for sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7551 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-POLICE-SHOOTING     05-06 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLICE-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA OFFICERS CLEARED IN KILLING OF YOUNG WOMAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A county prosecutor said Thursday that four white
police officers in Riverside, Calif., who shot and killed a black
teen-ager as she sat apparently unconscious in a car with a gun in
her lap, had probably made an error in judgment, but had committed
no crime.
</P>
<P>
   In clearing the officers in the death of the woman, Tyisha
Miller, the Riverside County district attorney, Grover Trask, said
her death was ``a terrible, terrible tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights advocates and relatives of Ms. Miller have
protested the slaying, calling the officers murderers and the
incident the latest in a series of acts of police brutality across
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Ms. Miller's family and supporters, including the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, denounced Trask's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a shameful day in America,'' said the Rev. Bernel
Butler, Ms. Miller's cousin and a spokesman for the family. ``I
served in Desert Storm, but this makes me almost ashamed to say I
served in the military. We go abroad to protect people, but we
don't protect our own people here at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident began early Dec. 28, when the police were called to
a service station where Ms. Miller, 19, was slumped in her locked
car with a gun in her lap. The officers said that when they tried
to break a window to get her out of the car, she reached for the
gun. They then fired 23 shots into the car, striking her 12 times.
</P>
<P>
   Butler said that all he and the family have wanted was that the
officers be made to answer to a judge and jury, ``like anyone else
who shot a defenseless girl 12 times while she sat unconscious in
her car.''
</P>
<P>
   The police began to back off from their original version of the
events soon after the shooting, and a deputy district attorney,
Mike Soccio, said Thursday that Ms. Miller's gun had not been
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Trask said at a crowded news conference that the officers had
been called to the service station at about 2 a.m. by Ms. Miller's
cousin, who said Ms. Miller was unconscious in her car with a gun
on her lap. The car had a flat tire and the cousin had come to
help. But when she arrived, she was unable to rouse Ms. Miller.
</P>
<P>
   When the police arrived, Trask said, they too tried to wake Ms.
Miller, banging on the car windows, shouting and shining
flashlights in her face.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes, fearing that Ms. Miller was seriously ill,
the officers decided to break the window and grab the gun, Trask
said. The first try failed, but Ms. Miller suddenly sat up and
stared at her beeper, apparently unaware of her surroundings, he
said. Then officer Daniel Hotard, 23, a policeman for 11 months ,
broke the window and leaned inside to grab the gun.
</P>
<P>
   With his head inside, ``a shot went off towards my right ear,''
Hotard told investigators.
</P>
<P>
   That shot came from a fellow officer, who thought he saw Ms.
Miller reach for a gun, Trask said. Hotard fell to the ground as
his three partners, Paul Bugar, 24; Wayne Stewart, 25, and Michael
Alagna, 27, continued firing. Hotard, still on the ground, fired
several rounds into the driver's side door.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have concluded,'' Trask said, ``that the plan to break out
the window was probably a mistake in judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the officers had to weigh the risk of getting Ms. Miller
the medical attention she apparently needed with getting the gun
out of her lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a judgment call,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller had a small amount of alcohol in her system, but in
two autopsies, one commissioned by her family, there was nothing to
indicate any illness, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Butler and Earl Ofari Hutchinson, a civil rights advocate,
author and radio talk show host, said that an independent federal
prosecutor should be brought in to investigate. In the meantime a
rally and march to protest Trask's decision have been scheduled for
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
