<SLUG> BC-FILM-WINSLOW-BOY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAKE OF `THE WINSLOW BOY' FAILS TO BE A COMPELLING MORALITY
TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Based on the evidence of his past work, a new, G-rated film
version of Terence Rattigan's 1946 play, ``The Winslow Boy,'' would
seem just about the least likely project imaginable for Chicago
playwright-turned-filmmaker David Mamet.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it's very British. For another, it already has
been made into a successful film in 1948, directed by Anthony
Asquith, and starring Sir Cedric Hardwicke and Robert Donat. (And
wasn't it Mamet who once said that ``a remake of a good film is a
waste of everyone's time''?)
</P>
<P>
   Still, here it is, and despite some polished performances and
stronger production values than the original, it's not nearly as
good a film. And even though it follows Rattigan's play quite
closely, it fails to be a compelling morality tale.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1910 and based on a true incident, it's the story of the
Winslows: a recently retired London banker named Arthur (Nigel
Hawthorne) and his affluent, close-knit family, who get a nasty
surprise when his 12-year-old son is expelled from the Osbourne
Naval College _ accused of stealing a five-shilling postal order.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to six months later, and the case of ``The Winslow Boy'' is
suddenly an Edwardian media event. At great personal sacrifice, the
family has rallied around the accused, fought his expulsion and
gathered supporters who see the case as a symbol of an injustice at
the heart of the British legal system.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the film follows their fortunes as the case is taken
on by famed barrister Sir Robert Morton (Jeremy Northam), who also
believes in the boy's innocence and fights it in the halls of
Parliament, while becoming romantically attracted to the Winslow
daughter (Rebecca Pidgeon).
</P>
<P>
   It's a handsome production, and generally well-cast _ though
Hawthorne can't give the senior Winslow half the moral authority
that Hardwicke did; and Northam, while copying every gesture of
Donat's turn as Morton, doesn't have half that great screen actor's
star power.
</P>
<P>
   And Mamet makes some fatal mistakes, not the least of which is
skipping the dramatization of the family's series of rebuffs and
frustrations that dominated Asquith's first act, showing us why the
family came to devote itself so utterly to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   In this version, in which so much of the drama and action takes
place off screen or is merely implied in flashback references, it's
never clear what moral principle is involved, or why, 90 years
after the incident, we should be interested in it.
</P>
<P>
   The Winslow Boy. Directed and written by David Mamet, from the
play by Terence Rattigan. Produced by Sarah Green. Cast: Nigel
Hawthorne, Jeremy Northam, Rebecca Pidgeon, Gemma Jones. Sony
Pictures Classics. 110 minutes. Rated G, suitable for all
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
