<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7674 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-ROBINSON-AZR     05-06 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-ROBINSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON PLANS TO OVERCOME POSTSEASON FAILURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The NBA is a league full of labels and tattoos. Nobody
has to tell Clifford Robinson which of the two is easier to erase.
</P>
<P>
   The label is always there, no matter what Robinson does or
doesn't do.
</P>
<P>
   By appearance, at least, it looks to be even more permanent than
the portrayal of a warrior in a red-headband that is tattooed on
Robinson's right arm. The warrior is poised to strike. Robinson
likes to say that the tattoo represents the warrior within him.
</P>
<P>
   But from afar, it is impossible to see.
</P>
<P>
   From afar, there is only the label. And it says Robinson is
poised to fail.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to come under review at the eve of the NBA playoffs
every spring. The media arrives, waving cameras and tape recorders
like a surgical team with scalpels. Nothing about the intent is
cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has been tagged with one of basketball's cruelest
combinations. His great accomplishments in regular-season are not
duplicated in the playoffs, the real season. The lion in winter is
the lamb in spring. That, at least, is the reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Unfair, said Suns coach Danny Ainge, who Thursday expressed
exasperation at the way in which Robinson almost had become prey
for the media on the opening day of the playoff hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Knee-jerk reaction, said some of Robinson's teammates, whose
emphasis on jerk was neither misplaced nor mis-interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, himself?
</P>
<P>
   Been there. Done that.
</P>
<P>
   He knew the questions were coming. He dealt with them in a
reasonable, straight-forward fashion. He was fulfilling his end of
the business. It's part of being a pro, and, these days, Robinson
has been been every bit of that and more. After a decade in the
NBA, Robinson knows as well as any veteran that labels are always
misunderstood and seldom beaten. All he can do is try to help the
Suns beat the Portland Trail Blazers in a first-round playoff
series that opens Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He is coming off one of his best regular-seasons, ever. Even he
has said as much. But there's an argument that the season is only
as good as his playoff performance. Does he need a great playoff
performance to validate all the exceptional performance that came
before it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' said Robinson, who says he is more weary than
frustrated by the repeated questions. ``I wouldn't say I have to
have an exceptional one (playoffs). I just think I have to continue
to play as well as I have all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have to go out carry us. I don't think I have
to do anything super. I just think I have to go out and maintain
what I've done all year.''
</P>
<P>
   If Robinson continues to play at the same level, some
prognosticators believe there's a good chance that the Suns can
upset the Blazers in the best-of-five series. From scouting report
to scouting report, there is consensus on at least one element:
Robinson is a key.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's first-round elimination of the Suns by the San
Antonio Spurs, Robinson drew a lot of the blame. On the balance
sheet, a comparison of his regular-season to playoff numbers is not
favorable. His scoring average fell to 6.3 points from 14.2. His
shooting percentage fell from a career-high .479 to .273.
</P>
<P>
   For his career, Robinson is averaging 15.9 points in regular
season and 10.1 in the playoffs. He's shotting 44.9 percent in
regular-season and 40.4 in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But Ainge bristles at the suggestion that the numbers add up to
a playoff failure. That stats, he says, do not retell the story of
a series in which Rex Chapman and Danny Manning were sidelined by
injuries. The numbers, he says, do not explain the dilemma of
asking the 6-foot-10 Robinson to play center against David Robinson
and sometimes Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Clifford Robinson was asked to take the last stand
in the Alamo city, which is built on a monument to a final, futile
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cliff was the best player in the only game we won,'' Ainge
said of the Spurs 3-1 victory. ``Nobody played well.''
</P>
<P>
   With center Luc Longley in the lineup this time around, Robinson
is able to play small forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``His skills are more suited for small forward,'' said Ainge,
who expects Robinson will be matched by against Rasheed Wallace
through much of the Portland series. ``He's more comfortable at
that spot.''
</P>
<P>
   For Robinson, an irony in this series is his return to a city
where he played eight years. It's a place he still calls home. His
three children live in Portland. It's the site of his greatest
moments. He was an All-Star with the Blazers in 1994. He was the
NBA's Sixth Man of the Year in 1993. Yet, it is also a city with
the roots of his reputation for playoff futility. The Portland
``Oregonia''n's web site Thursday was filling up with knocks at
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   One Portland fan wrote that the Blazers best chance was a player
he still calls ``Uncle Cliffy.'' Another fan remembered a muffed
pass in an NBA Finals game against the Chicago Bulls. On and on, it
went.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistakes in the playoffs always seem to be magnified,'' Suns
playmaker Jason Kidd said. ``It becomes a label, and it's hard to
shake. But I'm sure Clifford is looking forward to this series.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it.
</P>
<P>
   But Robinson almost makes it sound as though he's headed for a
reunion with some old friends who might be a little estranged these
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my best years were in Portland,'' Robinson said.
``I've put those days behind me. The fans will say a lot of things.
I understand that. That's their prerogative. I'm just looking
forward to this series.''
</P>
<P>
   In large part, Robinson is because he says he understands _
enjoys _ basketball more than he ever has.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a short series, and now is the time of year when you
can't concern yourself with individual gratification,'' Robinson
said. ``What is said is put out of my mind. I've had some great
things happen to me an individual player. But as I get older, I
enjoy the experience of having good things happen to the team at
large. It's part of growing up. In 10 years, you learn a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   And most of it can't be found on a label. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-06-99 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
