<DOCNO> NYT19990506.0468 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-06 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7678 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-FINLEY-AZR     05-06 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-FINLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY FINDS SUPPORT DURING SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There are reasons to believe that Steve Finley will
not perform this poorly all season. There also might be reasons to
worry.
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks into the season, the Diamondbacks insist all is well
with the player they have signed to be their center fielder through
2002. No matter that he is batting .232 after 112 at-bats, which
ties him for the third-highest at-bat total in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, people such as Manager Buck Showalter, hitting
coach Jim Presley and even a former teammate say that starting slow
is nothing new for Finley, who traditionally has had his worst
months at the start of a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, he's hot right now compared to what he usually is,''
said Cincinnati's Greg Vaughn, who played with Finley each of the
past two years in San Diego. ``Like me, he's a thinker. Anytime you
think in baseball, you get in trouble. He needs to get to the point
where he's, `See the ball, hit the ball.'
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about Steve, he's a gamer. You can pencil his name
into the lineup and he'll play his butt off.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley has only four hits in 23 at-bats (.174) with runners in
scoring position. ``Terrible,'' he said about that particular
statistic. Only two of his groundouts have been to the left side of
the infield, an indication that he is trying to pull the ball too
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I want to do better,'' said Finley, who led off
Wednesday's victory with a ground-rule double and scored the game's
first run. ``I feel I'm going to get a hit every time I step into
the batter's box. I believe I can hit .400. It's not a goal, but
that's my mind-set.''
</P>
<P>
   One part of Finley's game that remains unrivaled is his defense.
A two-time Gold Glove Award winner in center field, Finley remains
one of the best defensive players in the game, catching almost
everything hit from gap to gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best center fielders I've ever had,'' said
Showalter, who has managed Bernie Williams and Devon White. ``When
I put my head on the pillow at night to sleep, Steve Finley is one
thing I do not worry about. I look at it like someone's going to
pay down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter called Finley into his office before Wednesday's game
in Cincinnati for a quick pep talk. He wanted to make sure that
Finley knew he wasn't about to be benched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to know how happy we are with him,'' Showalter
said. ``Steve Finley is a winner. There's a reason he's been around
winning clubs throughout his career. He's just frustrated now
because he's not clicking on all eight cylinders.''
</P>
<P>
   Watch Finley's eyes and body language inside the clubhouse and
he looks like someone who still does not feel he's pulling his
weight, which is common with a struggling player in his first year
with a new club.
</P>
<P>
   Another point that may be dragging Finley down is his contract.
He signed a four-year deal worth $21.33 million. The next-largest
offer was a three-year deal for $12 million from San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed,'' Finley insisted. ``I feel like I know
I could be doing better, but that's baseball. If I was in my first
few years in the game, I'd be worried like hell. As long as we're
winning, I honestly don't care what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   In his best seasons, 1995 and '96, Finley sprayed the ball
around the park with regularity. He also slammed 30 and 28 home
runs, the highest totals of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the game believe Finley fell in love with the home run
after those two seasons, the second of which saw him finish 10th in
the Most Valuable Player voting and help lead the Padres to their
first playoff appearance in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a timing guy,'' Presley said. ``Sometimes all it takes is
one swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Was it that ground-rule double Wednesday night? The Diamondbacks
and Finley certainly hope so. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
