<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expect presidential gridlockBy Debbie Hiott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ President Clinton's coming to town today, but
the closest many Austin residents will get to him will be as
they're stalled in traffic while the presidential motorcade goes by
in the middle of rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One is scheduled to arrive shortly after 5 p.m. at
Austin-Bergstrom International Airport in Southeast Austin. The
president will spend an undetermined amount of time there before
his motorcade winds its way through the streets of Austin to a
fund-raiser in the West Austin home of his longtime friend Roy
Spence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will stay overnight at the Driskill Hotel at Sixth and
Brazos streets, and he'll arrive there late in the evening, just as
the night life on Sixth Street kicks into gear.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Wilkinson, Austin's resident agent in charge for the Secret
Service, said Brazos from Sixth to Seventh will be closed while the
president is at the Driskill, and police barricades will be erected
around the hotel's perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service has been working for days with Austin police,
Travis County sheriff's office and the Texas Department of Public
Safety on safety and traffic preparations. Secret Service officials
won't release the route of the presidential motorcade, but delays
are likely as police escorts barricade streets.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic disruptions usually last no more than five to 10
minutes, Wilkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
