<HEADER>
A7682 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT-FE     05-06 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SETTLEMENT-FEES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    $260 million claim for tobacco suit fees dropped
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEXARKANA, Texas _ Embattled Houston attorney Marc Murr dropped
a claim for $260 million in legal fees Wednesday for work he said
he did on the state's landmark settlement with the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected move was hailed by Attorney General John Cornyn
as a ``complete victory for taxpayers of Texas.'' But questions
remain about what Cornyn will do next about allegations he made
that Murr and former Attorney General Dan Morales committed fraud
by creating bogus contracts used as the basis for the legal claim.
</P>
<P>
   And sources have told The Associated Press that the FBI has
begun an investigation, although many principals in the contract
dispute, including Morales, say they have not been questioned by
federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said Cornyn was a liar motivated by politics. Cornyn
said Thursday he stood by every word.
</P>
<P>
   Murr's move to drop his claim also masks the fact that Murr will
still get $1 million in fees for work that many said he did not do.
That is because two arbitration panels _ at the national and state
levels _ set fees for Murr. The state recommended $260 million; the
national panel said Murr should get $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Murr gave up in the face of what we believe was
overwhelming evidence,'' Cornyn said after the hearing in federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   But Murr's attorney, Roy Minton of Austin, said Murr would
probably make another claim for legal fees. U.S. District Judge
David Folsom said Murr has 60 days to make a new claim by
requesting another arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move, if Murr made it, could revive Cornyn's stinging
allegations that Morales fabricated two contracts Murr used to
establish his arbitration case. He originally sought 3 percent of
Texas' tobacco settlement, or $520 million, based on a contract
Cornyn said was a fake in court papers he filed Wednesday. But
asked to show the proof of his claims, the attorney general
declined. ``We are continuing our investigation into other aspects
of the tobacco attorneys' fees arrangement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said Morales ``gave us no choice'' but to reveal in court
papers the allegations that Morales fabricated contracts because
the former attorney general refused to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Was it done to intimidate Murr? ``I'm not in the intimidation
business,'' Cornyn replied.
</P>
<P>
   Murr was ordered to appear before U.S. District Judge David
Folsom to answer questions about how the state arbitration was
handled. Folsom had ordered the arbitration and stated in the order
that he would appoint one of the three members to the panel.
</P>
<P>
   But Morales and Murr chose all three members without waiting for
Folsom, a move that Cornyn said completely violated the judge's
order and, therefore, made the $260 million award worthless. Cornyn
has said that he feared Texas taxpayers may have been liable for
the money, instead of the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Murr, once called the ``stealth lawyer'' by attorneys for the
tobacco industry, slipped out of the courtroom without comment as
reporters huddled around Minton.
</P>
<P>
   In a carpeted, ornate Texarkana courtroom that served as the
ring for a legion of lawyers who fought in the 3-year-old tobacco
case, Murr's offer to vacate his arbitration award brought the
latest contest to an anticlimactic close. Ten minutes after the
hearing began, Minton and his son, David, his law partner, packed
up their briefcases to leave.
</P>
<P>
   They had huddled with Cornyn and Cornyn's first assistant, Andy
Taylor, in Folsom's chambers for little more than a quarter-hour
before Folsom called the hearing to begin. Cornyn said later that
he cut no deals. In the pleading filed Wednesday, Cornyn alleged
that Morales faked a contract with Murr, a friend and onetime
colleague in a Houston law firm, to set up Murr's separate
arbitration of his legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Arbitrators awarded Murr $260 million after Morales and Murr
presented them with a second, earlier contract that said Murr would
get 3 percent of whatever Texas recovered from the cigarette
makers.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said that second contract, dated Oct. 17, 1996, had
actually been created last year, weeks before Murr's September
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
