<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-LINES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CRUISE LINES WILL BASE VESSELS IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ARTHUR C. GORLICK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For years, the Port of Seattle and the region's
business leaders battled futilely to get a cruise ship line to
operate from the city's waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two cruise ship lines say they will base vessels here.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean International announced Thursday that next year
it will become the second cruise ship line to operate at the Port
of Seattle's Bell Street Pier facilities at Pier 66.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami-based cruise line said it will base its
2,000-passenger Vision of the Seas in Seattle for voyages through
Puget Sound, the Strait of Juan de Fuca, the San Juan Islands and
Canada's Inside Passage to Vancouver and Victoria, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Cruise Line announced last year that it will operate
21 seven-day summer cruises to Alaska aboard its 2,000-passenger
Norwegian Sky from Seattle's Bell Street Pier terminal beginning
May 7, 2000, under a four-year agreement with the port.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that cruising is an ideal way to really experience
this part of the country, which boasts spectacular scenery and
wonderful ports of call,'' said Jack Williams, president of Royal
Caribbean International.
</P>
<P>
   Port of Seattle officials said that each vessel call will pump
nearly $1 million into the community. The two cruise lines are
expected to create 400 new jobs, produce $74 million in business
revenues and generate $8.4 million in state and local taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides longshore and stevedore jobs, the cruise ships directly
create jobs for ticketing and reservations agents and business for
provisioners of bunker fuel, food and a range of items and services
that include flowers and piano tuners.
</P>
<P>
   Port of Seattle commissioners have authorized construction of a
$12.9 million cruise terminal at the Bell Street Pier facility,
which contained only a shell for a cruise terminal when the $110
million, 11-acre pier opened in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Royal Caribbean is using the seven cruises next year as a test
of the itineraries in the new market,'' said port spokesman Imbert
Matthee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this works out well, we assume they will go for a longer
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean will launch its Port of Seattle operations with
a one-night cruise for travel agents on May 14, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   On May 15, 22 and 29, 2000, it will have four-night cruises into
British Columbia. On May 19 and 26, it will have three-night
cruises and on June 2, 2000, a two-night cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Cruise Line's lease gives it exclusive use of the
port's cruise ship terminal on Sundays, a preferred day for
departure.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean will operate its Vision of the Seas voyages on
Mondays and Fridays, Matthee said.
</P>
<P>
   Large vessel cruising from the Port of Seattle had been stymied
for years by the 1886 Passenger Service Act, which bars
foreign-registered cruise ships from stopping at more than one U.S.
port per voyage to pick up or drop off passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the law's restrictions, cruise lines have operated
extensively from Vancouver, B.C., with many cruise ship passengers
arriving at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport and being bused to
Vancouver. Vancouver's harbor has become increasingly crowded with
cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   The Port of Seattle and Greater Seattle Chamber of Commerce
unsuccessfully backed efforts to get Congress to change the law,
but the two cruise lines that will operate here have found ways
around the limitations.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Caribbean cruises will stop at two Canadian ports
before completing a round-trip voyage to Seattle, complying with
the 113-year-old law.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian Cruise Line voyages will stop at Alaskan ports,
but won't drop off passengers before heading back to Seattle with a
stop in Vancouver, B.C., also under the law's provisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
