<HEADLINE>
THREE DIE IN OKLAHOMA HOSPITALS AS DEATH TOLL CLIMBS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KEVIN MORAN 
and DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Scores of families rejoiced Thursday as loved
ones were found safe after Monday's tornadoes, but officials said
more than a dozen people still missing are likely dead.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of missing fell dramatically in Oklahoma, from
more than 100 to just 14, hopes for those faded as search teams
brought in dogs trained to sniff out bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Three people died in hospitals overnight Wednesday, bringing the
confirmed Oklahoma death toll to 41. Five died in Kansas and one in
Texas in the initial storms. Four more people were killed Wednesday
as bad weather continued to roll eastward across the southern
states.
</P>
<P>
   The dead identified Thursday included two people from the rural
community of Bridge Creek. Asheton Darnell, a 3-week-old boy, had
been ripped from his mother's arms and found in a ravine.
</P>
<P>
   Kara Wiese, a 26-year-old single mom who had been clinging to
her son as well, also perished while her 6-year-old child survived.
</P>
<P>
   At Children's Hospital, the father of three injured children
told a remarkable story of survival. Sean York of Midwest City said
he and the children were huddled in the family bathtub, covered by
a mattress, when the house exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It threw us up out of the tub,'' York said. ``I landed on the
ground, and the house was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The children were tossed up to 50 yards in the darkness, and
York found them only when the roar of the twister faded and he
could hear their cries. He first reached 6-year-old Dustin, who was
sitting in the middle of the back yard near two small neighbor
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I found my neighbors' little 4-month-old boy, and he was
already passed,'' York said. He was referring to Jeffery Yonnes Jr.
</P>
<P>
   York's wife, Susan, was at a friend's home when the tornado
struck. Now, she tends to her husband and three children, all of
whom are hospitalized. Daughter Tierra, 8, remained unconscious in
intensive care after suffering the worst injuries: a bruised brain,
dislocated left arm and punctured right eye.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the stormy weather moved across the south, killing
four people in Tennessee on Wednesday and tearing off roofs and
knocking out power in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton on Thursday ordered federal disaster aid for
Bowie County to help clean up the damage after twisters touched
down in Texas on Tuesday, killing one person.
</P>
<P>
   Across Oklahoma City and its battered suburbs, as residents
scoured the rubble they once called home, local and state officials
again increased their estimates of the number of damaged buildings.
An official tally could take weeks, but some had feared the total
could approach $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma County officials Thursday upped the number of homes
destroyed or heavily damaged from 1,700 to 2,500 as they began the
painstaking task of counting lots.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate does not include what are known to be high totals
in nearby Moore and portions of Oklahoma City within Cleveland
County, which had not yet assessed the number of homes and
businesses destroyed. In the heavily hit municipality of Del City
alone _ damage assessment teams began their work there _ 560 homes
were on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma County Tax Assessor Mike Means said the bulk of the
homes will be removed from the tax rolls. ``There's nothing
salvageable at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that cleanup efforts were threatened by
camera-clicking crowds that were clogging streets of the wrecked
subdivisions eager for a glimpse of destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been having many, many sightseers coming into these
communities, and we're particularly concerned with the weekend
coming up,'' said Oklahoma County Emergency Management Director
David Van Nostrand said. ``All the traffic in the area is hindering
the cleanup.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem was the huge amount of debris, estimated at 220
million cubic yards, left to be cleared away. Leaders from Oklahoma
City and its Midwest City, Del City, and Choctaw suburbs were
discussing the problem Thursday with the Federal Emergency
Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Storm sewers are full of debris, and concern was growing
Thursday about hazardous chemicals and rodents in the growing heaps
of rubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rats and mice, that's a developing problem,'' Van Nostrand
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of most pressing concern, however, were those still unaccounted
for three days into one of the worst tornado disasters to strike
the Oklahoma plains. While law enforcement authorities have
searched the rubble at least three times for victims, FEMA said
special dog-handler teams, including two from Texas, were arriving
late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials became convinced that the 14 people still listed as
missing probably died in the tornado rampage. Searchers focused on
areas in Bridge Creek, south Oklahoma City, Moore, Del City and
Midwest City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have identified either where the people were supposed to
live, or where they might have been, and those are the areas that
will be searched,'' said Ray Blakeney, director of operations for
the state Medical Examiner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Examiner Dr. Fred Jordan said identification of the last
10 or so victims was slowed because of the severity of their
injuries. And he said that unlike victims of the 1995 federal
building bombing in the city _ which included many federal
employees _ most of the tornado victims had no fingerprints on
file.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan said that as of late Thursday almost all of the 41
bodies had been released to various funeral homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we're very close to the end of this process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
