<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCKET TO 'EM: CHAPMAN GIVES BOOT TO HIS GOGGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Apparently, the great goggle debate is over.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rex Chapman hasn't said much about his dislike for the goggles
he was required to wear in the last few games as protection for a
broken bone at the base of his right eye socket.
</P>
<P>
   But Chapman's actions said plenty Thursday after the Suns' final
practice before departing for Portland, where they will work out
today and open the NBA playoffs against the Trail Blazers on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When assistant coach  &UR; Frank Johnson handed Chapman the goggles
after a workout, he dropped them to the floor, stomped on them,
kicked them across the court and continued his conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The $300 goggles remained on the floor, in two pieces, long
after Chapman was gone. Guess he won't be taking them to Portland,
unless somebody applies a &UR; Kurt Rambis tape job. &QL; 
Roster &QL; 
The Suns submitted their 12-man playoff roster, and there were few
surprises. Guard  &UR; Gerald Brown, who finished the regular season on
the injured list, was placed on the playoff roster. Rookie &UR; Toby
Bailey, who finished the regular season on the active roster, was
not included.
</P>
<P>
   Guard  &UR; Randy Livingston, who scored 12 points and handed out
three assists in his debut Wednesday night, was impressive enough
in the season finale against Minnesota to earn a spot on the
playoff roster.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston was in the playoffs as a rookie with Houston three
years ago. He had just helped Sioux Falls win the Continental
Basketball Association title when the Suns called _ in the nick of
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying to you if I said the last couple of years hasn't
been frustrating,'' he said. ``I had to be patient. Matter of fact,
I was on my way to Venezuela when I got the call from the Suns.'' &QL; 
Bulletin board &QL; 
Portland's &UR; Isaiah Rider provided the first salvo in the war of
words that goes with every playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix can't guard us, but they can put the ball in the
basket,'' Rider said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Suns center  &UR; Joe Kleine replied, ``That's kind of funny that
Isaiah Rider is talking about defense. Instead of worrying about
our defense, he should worry about what time their shoot-around
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Rider has a long history of being late for
or missing shoot-arounds and workouts. He missed one this week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
