</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RAMBIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMBIS FATE LIKELY HINGES ON LAKERS' PLAYOFF SHOWING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Now is when it really begins. That wild ride
of a regular season that served as Kurt Rambis' introduction as an
NBA head coach will be left as so much melodramatic preamble.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers will be judged by what they do in the
playoffs, and similarly, so will Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   If they make a deep run into the playoffs, it could prove the
beginning of a lengthy Lakers coaching career for Rambis. Get
bumped out in the first round, it could well make for a quick
coaching exit.
</P>
<P>
   If Rambis longs for a coaching marathon, it's a maddening and
unpredictable sprint that awaits. This is big-time, career-turning
pressure, yet Rambis shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't put that pressure on myself, so I don't worry
about it,'' Rambis said. ``I try and control the things I can and
not worry about the things that I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers open a difficult first-round matchup Sunday with the
veteran Houston Rockets, who are led by veteran coach Rudy
Tomjanovich.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis has had to cut his coaching teeth during a chaotic
regular season. He took over for fired Del Harris 12 games into the
season. Dennis Rodman came, Dennis Rodman went. Eddie Jones and
Elden Campbell were traded to the Charlotte Hornets for Glen Rice,
J.R. Reid and B.J. Armstrong, who was then waived. Jerry West
retreated to the shadows. The Lakers struggled.
</P>
<P>
   And Rambis was told to go coach.
</P>
<P>
   As others wait to pass judgment on Rambis based on the Lakers'
postseason performance, several players believe it already should
be a dead issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think by now, he's passed with flying colors,'' guard Kobe
Bryant said. ``It has to be (difficult), with everything he's been
through. Are you serious? Having to put up with all this stuff?
</P>
<P>
   ``He shouldn't be thinking about what people are going to say
about him. People will criticize him. Who cares? As long as he
keeps improving as a head coach, it's going to pay off in the long
run anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as that run doesn't come to a sudden stop against
Houston. He has no contract beyond this season. His fate awaits in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't necessarily be fair, but it probably will go down
like that,'' guard Derek Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   As a player, Rambis was the Lakers' ultimate role player _
crashing the boards, diving for loose balls, taking the charge,
playing tough defense. The counter-culture forward with the
lunch-pail work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis, 41, believes having to work harder to become an NBA
player is serving him well in becoming an NBA coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still learning, I'm still developing,'' Rambis said.
``Like the team, I still have a lot of things to learn. As a
player, I never felt I knew everything. I never felt I could sit
back and say, `I'm satisfied with how I am as a player.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Having only ended his 14-year NBA career in 1995, Rambis
remained close to the players the last two years as a Lakers
assistant coach. At the end of a practice or before a game, he
would tutor all who were willing to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a players' coach,'' Bryant said. ``He talks to the
players, he listens to the players, lets the players make a lot of
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rambis has felt his relationship with the players slowly
evolve down a different path.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I would like to think of myself as a buddy to all
these guys, you just don't have that type of relationship as a head
coach anymore,'' he said. ``Because if you're a player who's not
playing, it's my fault now and the buddyness just kind of goes out
the window because they're ticked off.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been far from a smooth ride, but the Lakers have won four
consecutive games heading into the playoffs, and Rambis said they
are playing their best basketball of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers management is not saying whether that will lead to
another season for Rambis. West, their executive vice president,
remains in the background. General manager Mitch Kupchak would
rather Rambis not be an issue heading into the playoffs, and his
comments are guarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get into it,'' Kupchak said. ``This is really
not the time to start talking about it, because it will lead to
other questions. But he's done a wonderful job and we're very happy
with what he's done to date. I don't think myself or Jerry would
have done anything differently than what he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of his first, and perhaps most significant,
postseason as a head coach, Rambis said his approach to the
pressure is working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still sleep at night, so I guess it can't be that bad,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
