(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
REFINED BASE STEALING
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rangers center fielder Tom Goodwin worked extensively
this spring to become a more dangerous threat on the bases.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers continue to reap the fruits of that labor.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin entered last night's game with an American League-best
14 stolen bases in 17 attempts for a gaudy 82.4 success rate.
Goodwin stole 38 bases during 1998, but was caught a league-high 20
times, a 65.5 percent success rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what I'm seeing right now _ good leads, good
acceleration and good slides,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
``He's also doing a good job of picking the right pitches and right
counts to run. He's also healthier than he was at any time last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin worked daily this spring with first-base coach Ed
Napoleon and minor-league instructor Dick McLaughlin to ensure
improvement in those areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those little things mean a lot on bang-bang plays,'' Napoleon
said. ``It's a game of inches, and you've got take to as many of
those inches as you can get.'' PITCHING DECISION WANTED
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Blue Jays, the Rangers' next opponent, feature a
bullpen in transition.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays traded struggling closer Robert Person to the
Philadelphia Phillies for left-hander Paul Spoljaric on Wednesday.
Blue Jays manager Jim Fregosi plans to implement a
closer-by-committee with left-handers Graeme Lloyd and Dan Plesac
expected to appear during most save opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Kelvim Escobar, a member of the Blue Jays'
rotation, likely will become the closer when right-hander Joey
Hamilton returns from the 15-day disabled list. Hamilton is
scheduled to start Monday for Triple-A Syracuse while on his
medical rehabilitation assignment and could rejoin the Blue Jays'
rotation for a start May 15 against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get my mind ready to do one or the other,'' Escobar
told reporters Wednesday. ``They have to make a decision. Right
now, I don't know what is going on.'' AVOIDING THE RED SOX ACE
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers last night concluded the first of their five
two-game series scheduled this season.
</P>
<P>
   Players dread two-game series because of the inconvenience and
wear-and-tear that the resulting travel causes. However, the
Rangers' two-game series with the Red Sox worked to their favor.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will miss facing Red Sox right-hander Pedro
Martinez, the American League's pitcher of the month for April. The
Red Sox plan to start Martinez (5-1, 2.06 earned-run average)
tonight against AL West-rival Anaheim. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Jeff Zimmerman, who provided the Rangers two
scoreless innings of no-hit relief during Wednesday's 8-3 victory
against Boston, entered yesterday's games leading the league's
relievers in ERA (0.93) and opponents' batting average (.109).
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' organization promoted right-hander Chris Tynan and
infielder Frank Marciante to Class-A Savannah from their extended
spring program and demoted outfielder Ernies Baez and right-hander
Douglas Silva from Savannah to their extended spring program.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
