<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CANSECO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CAM-DO KID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Jose Canseco has been through two divorces,
three major surgeries and a number of incidents involving police.
</P>
<P>
   He has been the American League's most valuable player, and he
has suffered a major arm injury in a frivolous pitching appearance.
He was once called the best player on the planet. Other times he
has been considered washed up, over the hill and simply finished.
</P>
<P>
   He is with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, his fifth team in six
years. His remarkable career has taken more twists and turns than a
Robert Ludlum spy novel. Yet through it all, Canseco keeps smiling
and whacking, hitting .279 with 10 home runs and 23 runs batted in
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Every time you start shaking your head and wondering what might
have been, Canseco comes roaring back, thumbing his nose at his
many former employers and bashing as many home runs as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about feeling sorry for this guy. He might get that
plaque in Cooperstown, N.Y., before it's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know every player who has ever hit 500 home runs is in the
Hall of Fame,'' Canseco said. ``I don't know if the criterion has
changed, because a lot of guys in this era could hit 500 home runs.
But that's still a lot of home runs, and if that's still the
criterion, then I hope I do get voted into the Hall of Fame. It
would be a great thrill for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco expressed those hopes during a telephone interview
Wednesday. Later that night he had to leave the Devil Rays' game in
the third inning with a bruised left knee, a reminder that
injuries, not personal problems, are what's kept him from achieving
the full greatness once expected.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Canseco has learned to take conditioning more
seriously than in his younger days. Remember, this is a guy who
showed up for spring training with the Rangers saying he didn't
care what kind of town Port Charlotte, Fla., was as long as he
could get a pizza delivered.
</P>
<P>
   He was half-joking, but he has learned. Canseco said he hired a
personal trainer this off-season, is on a strict diet and hits the
weight room harder than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 21 or 22 years old, you take your health for
granted,'' Canseco said. ``My first years with Oakland I averaged
159-160 games a year. I could pop out of bed and run sprints any
time. But when the injuries come and you're missing ballgames and
you know you could be hitting 40-50 homers and helping the
ballclub, it becomes more frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you realize you need to do everything you can to stay
healthy and help the ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild: ``I think he's come to
terms with who he is and what his career means to him and what,
probably, life is all about in a lot of ways. A lot was thrown at
Jose in a short period of time. That doesn't mean his behavior is
acceptable, but there are reasons for it at times. Like I said, I
think he's come to terms with a lot of it and gotten past a lot of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco still hits for power when he's healthy. He showed that
last season when he hit a career-high 46 home runs with 107 RBI for
the Toronto Blue Jays. He also had 583 at-bats, the first time
since 1991 he has had more than 439 at-bats in a single season.
</P>
<P>
   After signing with the Devil Rays in the winter, Canseco began
this season averaging one home run every 15.2 at-bats. If he had
stayed injury-free, he would have more than 500 home runs by now.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his 10 homers give him 407 for his career. But he's
thinking beyond 500 home runs. Canseco, 34, said he has a chance
for at least 600, a level reached only by Hank Aaron (755), Babe
Ruth (714) and Willie Mays (660).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of setbacks, three surgeries, \Rnine\S times on
the disabled list,'' Canseco said. ``There was a time when 500 home
runs didn't seem a possibility. I also know one more injury could
be career ending. But I hit 46 home runs last year and drove in 107
runs. If I stay injury-free, 500 home runs is a definite
possibility. After that, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco said there were times the past few years when he thought
about retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``But being a competitor, you've always got to give yourself
that last chance,'' Canseco said. ``You don't want to retire at 34,
35 years old and then say, well what if I could have stuck with it
a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still the love of the game and the feeling you get
when you go up there with the perfect swing and hit the ball
perfect and smack it 500 feet. I've got a lot of time to make up,
and I've got a lot of good years left in me, if my health lets me
have them.''  &LR; tagtop:T.R. Sullivan, (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
