<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LeBRETON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS LAMENT PASSING OF TEAMMATE, ``OLDER BROTHER''
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he talked Thursday about the sudden death of his friend, his
teammate, the man he said was like his ``older brother,'' Daryl
Johnston's voice trembled with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   It dawned on those who listened that of all the episodes and
misfortunes that the Cowboys have endured, tragedy had not been one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   It hadn't been like the Detroit Lions, on whom fate seems to
have laid an unremitting curse. Three Lions have died while they
were active players. And in 1974, coach Don McCafferty suffered a
fatal heart attack during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   It hadn't been like the Kansas City Chiefs, who lost a promising
running back named Joe Delaney, who drowned while trying to save
the life of a boy. Another Chiefs running back, Mack Lee Hill, hurt
his knee in a 1965 game and died of a stroke on the operating
table.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Chargers lost David Griggs in a fatal auto
accident in 1995. A year later, the Chargers' Rodney Culver was
killed in the ValuJet plane crash in the Florida Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a day that impacted a tremendous amount of lives,''
Johnston said Thursday as he mourned the sudden death of Mark
Tuinei.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that is going to take a long time to get
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Because, at 6-foot-5 and 320 pounds, he often seemed larger than
life, and because he so often had a smile to match, Tuinei left
those who met him with an indelible impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I can ever find a person who spoke negatively of
Mark Tuinei,'' said Bill Bates, his former teammate.
</P>
<P>
   And so they called off practice Thursday and the Cowboys,
unaccustomed to tragedy's cold slap, swiftly departed Valley Ranch.
They had dodged cameras before, but this time was different.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a veteran Cowboy who hadn't laughed at one of Tui's
practical jokes or wasn't hardened by Tui's courage. Tuinei retired
after the 1997 season. His knees had deserted him months before
that.
</P>
<P>
   To Tuinei, the ongoing knee problems had been merely another
challenge. It had been a challenge just growing up in his tough
neighborhood on Oahu. It had been a challenge after he had gotten
booted out of UCLA for fighting and then found that his fists had
caused him more trouble back in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Getting into the university's ROTC program turned his angry
world around, Tuinei felt. Years later, after he had become a star
on a Super Bowl championship team, Tuinei flew the man who got him
into the program to Dallas. At a charity golf tournament, Tui
introduced him as ``the man who turned around my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was never one that looked for attention for himself,'' said
Tex Schramm, who was club president when Tuinei was signed as free
agent in 1983. ``He was a self-made man who had a lot to be proud
of, yet never called attention to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't until the end of his career that people started
realizing that he had become one of the best offensive linemen in
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei, along with Bates, was a free agent at the Cowboys' 1983
camp in Thousand Oaks, Calif. Almost from the start, coaches were
impressed with Tuinei's mobility.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought he'd be a great center,'' recalled Gil Brandt,
the former personnel chief.
</P>
<P>
   But for Tuinei, it was still a challenge. After the 1988 season,
the Cowboys placed him on their Plan B free-agent list. No other
NFL team claimed him.
</P>
<P>
   Eight seasons later, he was still playing. Still quietly doing
his job.
</P>
<P>
   To those of us who wrote about him for a living, Tui was the
amiable giant who answered questions, win or lose. We remember the
way he beamed when he learned that he had been selected to his
first Pro Bowl, a homecoming that the kid from the islands had
always only dreamed about.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Pono, a college athlete herself, defended him
fiercely, and we media people joked that we were more afraid of her
than we were of him.
</P>
<P>
   They had no children, but Mark Tuinei's Cowboys family was
large.
</P>
<P>
   As Bates and Johnston addressed the cameras and notepads
Thursday, it was a sobering scene. In so many ways, the Cowboys
have spent four decades on the edge. Why tragedy picked Mark Tuinei
is unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones must realize that the autopsy and toxicology
reports could reopen a maelstrom of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the Cowboys mourn. A good man, one of their own,
died young. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
