<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW OWNERS WON'T LIKELY HELP A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The financially bloody battle for San
Francisco Bay approaches a crucial moment. Two syndicates are
competing to buy the Oakland Athletics, and a decision is expected
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The winner could be the luckiest bunch since Custer's troops won
a free trip to Montana.
</P>
<P>
   The fight for baseball supremacy in the Bay Area has been
on-going for 31 years, ever since Charlie Finley was stupidly
allowed to move the Athletics from Kansas City in 1968. But the
Giants, who arrived in San Francisco 10 years earlier, might have
struck the decisive blow by building Pac-Bell Park, which is
scheduled to open next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are expected to cut off season-ticket sales at 28,000
some time this summer, a mind-boggling figure for a team averaging
18,139 per game now. But the Athletics are drawing only 14,241 per
game across the bay and have no chance of getting a new stadium any
time soon.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Athletics are the only team whose facility was
deliberately made worse. The Coliseum was ruined for baseball when
the Raiders returned and underwent substantial football renovations
to appease Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   But two groups are still willing to pay $122.4 million to
current owners Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann and keep the team in
the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Former A's vice president Andy Dolich heads one group, which
includes Hall of Fame second baseman Joe Morgan and George ``I
Guarantee It'' Zimmer, owner of The Men's Wearhouse. The rest of
the group is also from the Bay Area and is the sentimental
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The other group is headed by San Francisco-area lawyer Michael
Lazurus and Arizona banker Lyle Campbell, and also includes Bob
Watson, the former Astros and Yankees general manager, and Cubs
announcer Steve Stone, who started his pitching career with the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   That group is considering making Watson chief operating officer,
which would make him the first black owner in baseball history.
Morgan's role with the other group is undefined, but Dolich would
likely be the main man.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for both groups is making something work in
Oakland, especially now that the Giants are finally getting out of
3Com Park and into their plush downtown digs.
</P>
<P>
   Both are also forced by contract to stay in Oakland at least
through 2004, so escaping to Las Vegas, Sacramento, Calif., or even
Mexico is out for now.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics wanted desperately to move to San Jose, Calif.,
but the Giants claimed that lucrative territory as their own and
major-league baseball backed them. The East Bay, the Athletics'
defined territory, has more than 2 million people but can't stand
alone as a market without help from San Francisco or San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics have an admirable collection of young talent _ Ben
Grieve, Eric Chavez, Miguel Tejada and A.J. Hinch _ but they could
end up eligible for arbitration or free agency before the new
owners can assemble the proper supporting cast to produce a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our window of opportunity is small,'' manager Art Howe
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   The sad part is, if the Bay Area had one team, it would be a
financial power. But the Giants could end up that way anyway with
their new ballpark, leaving the Athletics begging for scraps, as if
they aren't already.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing aspect of all of the whole situation is there are
two groups willing to buy into such a dreary business proposition.
But nobody ever made intelligence a prerequiste for owning a
baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   That was proved a long time ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
