<HEADLINE>
LEAVE KENTUCKY DERBY ALONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The first torn-up ``win'' ticket had barely
hit the floor when the cry went up to reduce the Kentucky Derby's
20-horse limit.
</P>
<P>
   If ever a Derby provided an argument for such a drastic break
with tradition, it was Saturday's 125th running at Churchill Downs
in Louisville, Ky., in which a first-turn traffic jam seemed to
cost more than half of the 19 horses any chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   So inconclusive was Charismatic's victory at 31-1 odds, in the
eyes of the handlers of most Derby losers, that as many as a dozen
of them are expected to test him again at the May 15 Preakness
Stakes in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who think the solution is to shrink the race next
year are Bob Baffert, who trained three of the losers; Daily Racing
Form columnist Mike Watchmaker (``It's Time to Limit Derby Field to
14''); and Washington Post columnist Andy Beyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``(With 14) it would become a competition rather than a
crapshoot,'' Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   Is there an argument for keeping the Derby as it is? Well, yes.
</P>
<P>
   A good argument.
</P>
<P>
   People forget the Derby isn't meant to be a definitive,
championship race. It's an event all its own, and the luck factor
so despised by fat-cat trainers and frustrated bettors is one of
its enduring charms.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fun is the knowledge that you and I could go halves
on a cheap 2-year-old this summer and have a lottery player's
chance of winning the Derby _ if our little gelding gets good at
the right time and the contenders run into the hind end of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that the winner must be kissed by the Fates is woven
through Derby lore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's one of the unique things about the Derby,''
Churchill Downs president and CEO Thomas Meeker said on the
backstretch the morning after the race. ``The Derby has a way of
giving back to people at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is one way of saying: How bad a winner can Charismatic be
when he's owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis (affable spokesmen for the
sport), trained by D. Wayne Lukas (elected to the Hall of Fame four
days earlier) and ridden by Chris Antley (whose comeback from
weight trouble was the human-interest story of the race)?
</P>
<P>
   If Churchill Downs wanted the Derby to identify the best horse
in the country, it would follow the advice to shrink the field, and
it wouldn't stop there.
</P>
<P>
   It would adopt Baffert's other idea to allow trainers to select
their post positions in a ``draft'' order determined by horses'
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Then it would shorten the race from 1\ miles to the more common
1[ miles.
</P>
<P>
   Then it would push the race back from the first Saturday in May
to the first Saturday in July to allow time to weed out more
pretenders.
</P>
<P>
   Then it would move the race from the quirky running surface and
unpredictable climate of Churchill Downs to, say, Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   And it would open the race to 3-year-olds and up so all of the
best horses in the country could take part.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that although it would become the strongest,
fairest race of the year, it would cease to be the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The jockeys said this was the roughest Derby they've seen. Yet
nobody got seriously injured. And the winner, though overlooked by
most fundamentals-minded bettors (he qualified under only four of
this column's ``Ten Commandments for Derby Handicapping''), was a
horse whose previous race tied for the best in the field according
to no less an authority than the Beyer speed ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Big field or not, there might have been little traffic if not
for the fact so many horses had the same stalking style.
</P>
<P>
   A year before the 2000 Kentucky Derby, racehorse owners already
are dreaming of glory, fans are trying to spot the winner among
precocious 2-year-olds, and Churchill Downs is preparing for
another crowd of 150,000.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't sound like a race that needs to be changed.
</P>
<P>
   Good point: Trainers have been talking about how they almost
claimed Charismatic when he ran for a $62,500 price at Santa Anita
in February. Mike Mitchell, in particular, said he would have
claimed the colt if not for the fact the Lewises were nice enough
to give him drag-racing tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Said hard-bitten realist Bobby Frankel: ``Yeah, well, why didn't
they claim him? And another thing: Wayne Lukas is the only trainer
who could have won with that horse. He's the only one who would
have taken the horse to Kentucky.''
</P>
<P>
   This week: The best action takes place out of town Saturday,
with 1998 Kentucky Derby winner Real Quiet (Gary Stevens) and '99
Santa Anita Handicap winner Free House (Chris McCarron) heading a
five-horse field in the Pimlico Special, and Arkansas Derby
winner-by-disqualification Certain (Kent Desormeaux) and Tampa Bay
Derby winner Pineaff (Sid LeJeune Jr.) among 10 in the Illinois
Derby. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL; 
Hollywood Park leaders: Jockeys (through Wednesday): Laffit Pincay,
9 wins; Alex Solis, 8; Garrett Gomez, 7; Brice Blanc, Chris
McCarron, Emile Ramsammy and Gary Stevens, 4. Trainers: Ron
McAnally and John Shirreffs, 4; Jack Carava, Vladimir Cerin, Jerry
Dutton, Bill Spawr and Darrell Vienna, 3.Handicapper helper: The
old-school way to pick the Preakness winner: Add each horse's early
running position to his finish in the Kentucky Derby; lowest number
is the choice. This year it's Cat Thief, who ran second for the
first three-quarters of a mile and finished third; 2 plus 3 equals
5. Next best are Charismatic (7 plus 1 equals 8) and Worldly Manner
(3 plus 7 equals 10). The theory is that Pimlico is kinder than
Churchill Downs to speed horses.
</P>
<P>
   On the stakes schedule: At Hollywood Park: Saturday, $100,000
Will Rogers Handicap, 3-year-olds, 1 mile on turf; Sunday, $100,000
Wilshire Handicap, fillies and mares 3 and up, 1 mile on turf. At
Golden Gate Fields: Saturday, $150,000 Yerba Buena Breeders' Cup
Handicap, fillies and mares 3 and up, 1] miles on turf. At
Sportsmans Park: Saturday, $500,000 Illinois Derby, 3-year-olds, 1[
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Mileposts: The owners of Event of the Year plan to X-ray the
Strub Stakes winner's left front knee again in 10 days before
deciding whether to retire the colt. Trainer Richard Mandella said
there are signs of weakness in the bone _ ``a warning that we might
have a problem if we don't stop. They (owners John and Betty Mabee)
might want to give him four months off and keep racing him.'' The
weakness was discovered after Event of the Year's disappointing
fourth-place finish in the Mervyn LeRoy Handicap at Hollywood Park
on Saturday. Chips in the other front knee kept the horse out of
the 1998 Kentucky Derby.... Laffit Pincay completes a three-day
suspension today for interference in an April 25 race at Golden
Gate Fields. Pincay's nine wins in the first full week at Hollywood
Park put him within 93 of Bill Shoemaker's career-record 8,833....
Artax, who broke Dr. Fager's 30-year-old Aqueduct record for 7
furlongs by winning the Carter Handicap in 1:20.04 Sunday, is
scheduled to run next in the May 27 Metropolitan Mile at Belmont
Park.... R Far Out Star's maiden victory Wednesday was jockey Randy
Valdez's first since his apprenticeship expired.... Hollywood Park
wagering on Kentucky Derby Day set a record for the spring-summer
season _ $24.5 million.... Baseball's Joe Adcock, who died this
week at 71, was Louisiana's leading thoroughbred breeder 10
times.... Pat Valenzuela, recently cleared of robbery charges, met
with Hollywood Park stewards Sunday, beginning what figures to be a
long process of trying to get his jockey's license back. The
decision ultimately rests with the California Horse Racing Board.
Valenzuela hasn't ridden since 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
