<HEADLINE>
DRAKE EXPECTED AT CAMP AFTER DOING TIME FOR DUI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Even though defensive lineman  &UR; Jerry Drake has
nearly two months left on his prison term, the Cardinals still are
including him in their plans for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin said after Thursday's voluntary camp workout
that he still plans to have Drake back for training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Drake is to be released from a state prison on July 3, three
weeks before training camp opens.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded no contest in December to two aggravated counts of
driving under the influence and was sentenced to concurrent prison
terms of six and four months. He was arrested twice in 1997, only a
month apart, for driving while under the influence.
</P>
<P>
   Drake, 29, played only one game last season because of a back
injury and was placed on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to see how his back is,'' Tobin said. &QL; 
Job offer &QL; 
The Cleveland Browns have offered free agent linebacker  &UR; Jamir
Miller a one-year contract worth $1.2 million. The deal could be
worth as much as $1.5 million with incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Miller hasn't accepted the deal, however, and reportedly would
like a one-year contract worth $1.5 million that could grow to $2
million with incentives.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns are the second team to make Miller a contract offer.
</P>
<P>
   He turned down a two-year, $6 million deal from the Cardinals
two months ago. They talked to him again after he switched agents
about a one-year deal worth under $1 million. &QL; 
Complete recovery &QL; 
Tobin said backup quarterback  &UR; Dave Brown is throwing the ball much
better than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a lot more comfortable with what we're doing,''
Tobin said of Brown, who signed with the team as an unrestricted
free agent last summer. ``He's more familiar with our receivers. I
think he's throwing the ball well.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he's also much healthier. He had a partially torn
rotator cuff a year ago. ``I tore my pec muscle with the Giants,''
he said. ``The rehab made my shoulder tight. All last year I didn't
throw well. It was frustrating.'' &QL; 
Bug's world &QL; 
Defensive lineman  &UR; Brad Ottis missed Thursday's workout because of
a spider bite on his right leg. He is expected back today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we call him, `Spiderman,' '' trainer  &UR; John Omohundro
said.
</P>
<P>
   The spider was a Brown Recluse and the injury occurred at the
team's Tempe training facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we have a bunch (of spiders), but I know
there's one,'' Omohundro said.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin was reminded that players in New York likely don't have to
worry about spider bites.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they might slip on the ice,'' Tobin said. &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
Running back  &UR; Mario Bates (ankle) and wide receiver  &UR; Ronnie
Anderson (strained quadriceps) also missed Thursday's practice.
Anderson could return next week while Bates likely won't be able to
run full speed for a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Center  &UR; Mike Devlin also worked at guard at Thursday's practice.
It was the first time he has played the position since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end  &UR; Andre Wadsworth, the team's first-round draft
pick a year ago, returned to school at Florida State in the
off-season and is only two classes away from getting his master's
degree in sports administration. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
