<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES PLAYERS STAND BEHIND SCHOENFELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, ARIZ. - While Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld enjoyed a
rare day off with 18 holes of golf, his disheartened hockey team
spent Thursday going through year-ending physicals and defending
their coach.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld is the center of speculation. Will owner Richard
Burke and General Manager Bobby Smith will let him honor the final
year of a three-year contract and coach next year? Or, will he
become the sacrificial lamb for the team's failure to reach the
second round of the NHL Stanley Cup playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Wednesday, in the wake of Tuesday's night 1-0
overtime ouster by St. Louis, that a decision on Schoenfeld's
future will be made within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   While Schoenfeld was unavailable to the media Thursday, he said
during the playoffs that he is at peace with the job he has done,
adding he knows he has given his best efforts to his job and if
that isn't good enough, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   If the reaction of the team's players is any indication, Smith
has a slam-dunk decision upcoming. Schoenfeld will be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year there are changes made,'' assistant captain Teppo
Numminen said. ``It's part of the game and why management is there.
They'll do what they think best.
</P>
<P>
   ``But sometimes the changes you make don't work out, and you
basically have to rebuild. It's the same thing with Shoney. I hope
the whole coaching staff is back. For two years they've done a
great job of giving us the information we need going into games. I
can't see any fault of theirs. They've done a great job here.''
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic that Schoenfeld finds himself under fire,
considering the Coyotes' 39-31-12 record and 90 points ranks as his
best statistical season as an NHL coach.
</P>
<P>
   The team's 90 points were second most in franchise history,
trailing only the 96 points in the 1984-85 season. That team beat
Calgary in the first round, only to be swept in the second round in
four straight by Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent ouster was the eighth straight time the franchise
has failed to escape the first round _ the third time it blew a 3-1
series lead _ and a trip to the conference semis was a not so
private mandate.
</P>
<P>
   The forechecking system Schoenfeld employs has also been
criticized by some as being too defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' captain Keith Tkachuk said. ``We're an
aggressive team. I know some people think we sit back, but
sometimes you just can't get there. Coach gives us the green light
to go out and do it offensively. Obviously, when you're missing a
lot of guys in the playoffs you have to play more defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to get into a shootout when you're missing key
guys. But we get the green light to go and that's what I like. When
you don't win, the first guy they look at is the coach, which is
unfair. I hope he comes back because I know we can do better next
year under him.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Rick Tocchet, whose playoff performance was hampered by
an unreported cartilege tear in his rib cage prior to Game 6,
praises the coach's value as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made big strides with Shoney,'' he said. ``Everybody in
the room likes him. He's a good coach. A good tactical coach. He's
a good motivator. Those are good qualities in this era of sport.
Athletes make a lot of money and there are egos involved. It's
tough to find coaches to come in and be that type, and he has done
it for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got all he could out of every player we have, including the
kids who were called up. We just ran out of bullets (injuries) and
St. Louis had more depth at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Adams, a 14-year NHL veteran who was limited to just three
games in the series because of a badly strained groin, said he
played in pain Tuesday was in part due to his coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy playing for him,'' he said. ``He's the type of guy you
want to play for and guys want to do what they can for him. He's an
honest guy and hopefully he'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Goaltender Nikolai Khabibulin, who become a restricted Group II
free agent in July, pointed out he has played for four coaches
(John Paddock, Terry Simpson, Don Hay and Schoenfeld) in the five
years he has played for the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a good thing when you have the same coach,'' he
said. ``In the five years I've been here we've had quite a few
coaches. It's gives you more stability when you come back and see.
You know what he wants from you and he knows the player. But it's
hard to say what will happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
