<HEADLINE>
COYOTES LOCKERROOM RESEMBLES EMERGENCY ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Jeremy Roenick's decision to play in the
Coyotes' 1-0 overtime loss to St. Louis Tuesday night just 19 days
after surgery to repair a jaw broken in three places was an amazing
story, but it turns out there were a number of amazing stories.
</P>
<P>
   Winger Dallas Drake will undergo surgery today to repair a nose
that lists severely to port after it was broken midway through the
third period. He didn't miss a shift.
</P>
<P>
   Fans saw defenseman Gerald Diduck helped from the ice with an
injured knee in the third period after being submarined by the
Blues Geoff Courtnall.
</P>
<P>
   What they didn't know was that Diduck, playing in only his third
playoff game after missing 25 games with a broken foot, broke a
different area of his foot in the first period after blocking an Al
MacInnis slapshot and played superbly until the knee injury ended
his night.
</P>
<P>
   He reported for the team's year-end physical Thursday wearing a
walking cast on one leg and a knee splint to protect strained
ligaments on the other. The unrestricted free agent walked like a
robot.
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Greg Adams, already playing with a strained groin,
matched his uniform number by taking 17 stitches in his right cheek
after it was sliced by MacInnis' skate. He returned to action.
</P>
<P>
   And defenseman Jyrki Lumme was playing with a shoulder still so
badly injured that he requires off-season surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Center Robert Reichel missed Thursday night's team party because
he left Phoenix Wednesday morning to see his family in New York. &QL; 
Corkum's future? &QL; 
One decision GM Bobby Smith must make concerns third-line center
Bob Corkum, who becomes an unrestricted free agent on July 1.
Corkum is believed to be seeking at least $1 million a year, and
some believe the team's recent signing of center Juha Ylonen to a
three-year contract means it won't re-sign Corkum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like very much to be back in a Coyotes uniform, but that
will be worked out this summer,'' Corkum said. ``I'll take it day
by day and see what happens. My family loves it here. I love it
here. I'd like to see this team through the second and third rounds
and eventually to a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids have a lot of roots planted here and enjoy their
schools a lot. But you do what you have to do and kids will
adapt.'' &QL; 
Niki's fate &QL; 
Goaltender Nikolai Khabibulin becomes a restricted Group II free
agent on July 1, but doesn't expect to draw an offer because, he
says, the compensation a team would have to pay for signing him
would be too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody is going to give me an offer,'' he said.
``I haven't talked to my agent yet, either. It's hard to say what
is going to happen because I don't know what Bobby Smith is
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would like to get his contract done as soon as
possible, Khabibulin said, ``As long as I get the right deal, I
don't care when I get it. I like the guys, city and fans here. I'd
like to stay here.'' &QL; 
Oleg disappointed &QL; 
The Coyotes decision to make Oleg Tverdovsky and healthy scratch
for Tuesday's Game 7 after playing in all 82 regular season games
and the first six playoff games left him a frustrated man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed,'' he said. ``I wanted to play and
thought I could help and bring something to the team. It was tough
to watch because you can't do anything about it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
