<SLUG> BC-RAC-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCHILL ADDS HOLLYWOOD PARK TO ITS COLLECTION 
TVG MEETS RESISTANCE 
VALHOL'S DECLINING BANKROLL 
PREAKNESS PREPARATIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Churchill Downs, where the Kentucky Derby was run last Saturday
before a crowd of 151,051, announced Thursday that it had signed an
agreement to buy Hollywood Park race track in Inglewood, 11 miles
southwest of downtown Los Angeles, for $140 million in cash in the
latest and longest step toward extending its racing and gambling
operations coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which will be closed later this year, will include 240
acres of land and the Hollywood Park Casino, a card club situated
at the track, which will be leased to Hollywood Park Inc. for $3
million a year. In January, Churchill Downs bought Calder Race
Course near Miami for $86 million, and declared its intention of
acquiring other tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the acquisition of Calder in Miami and now Hollywood Park
in Southern California, Churchill Downs will be positioned to be
the premier race track operator and simulcast broadcaster in the
United States,'' said Thomas Meeker, president of Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   R.D. Hubbard, chairman of Hollywood Park Inc., hailed the sale
as ``a major step toward our corporate objective of focusing on the
growth of our gaming businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   TVG Meets Resistance
</P>
<P>
   Control over betting at home has apparently created a rebellion
in the ranks of the National Thoroughbred Racing Association.
</P>
<P>
   Ten tracks in the mid-Atlantic region, including Pimlico, the
Meadowlands and Monmouth Park, joined Thursday to protest the
recent decision of the NTRA to become a national wagering hub for
the Television Games Network as ``threatening the viability of the
racing industry in our states.''
</P>
<P>
   The tracks said in a letter to Tim Smith, commissioner of the
NTRA, that ``the details of the TVG partnership have been reviewed
only by representatives of five or six large tracks, and this
venture now is being forced down the throat of the rest of the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Valhol's Declining Bankroll
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas Racing Commission's decision Wednesday to
disqualify Valhol from the purse money he won in finishing first in
the Arkansas Derby subtracts $300,000 from the colt's bankroll,
leaving him with only $44,000 and a much reduced chance of making
the list of 14 horses allowed in the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   The commission concluded that Valhol's jockey, Billy Patin, used
an electrical buzzer on Valhol, fined the rider $2,500 and
suspended him for the rest of the year. In the Kentucky Derby last
week, Valhol was allowed to run after his owner, James Jackson, won
a court ruling ordering the purse to be paid to him. The colt ran
with a new jockey, Willie Martinez, and finished 15th in a field of
19.
</P>
<P>
   But the racing commission still had to hear arguments and make
its own ruling in the case. It did, and Patin was the main target
although the colt's winnings were taken away.
</P>
<P>
   Preakness Preparations
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Preakness candidates were staying at Churchill Downs
rather than shipping to Pimlico in Baltimore, where the Preakness
will be run one week from Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid, ninth in the Derby, was withdrawn from the
Preakness by his trainer, Scotty Schulhofer. But K One King
(eighth) was declared back in the Preakness a day after he was
withdrawn to undergo surgery for an ankle chip. ``We decided that,
as long as he is not hurting it's best for him to run,'' said his
trainer, Akiko Gothard.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, who missed his chance to become the first trainer
to win the Derby three years in a row when all three of his
candidates ran out of the money, planned to send his favored entry
_ Excellent Meeting (fifth) and General Challenge (11th) _ home to
California. He also said that Prime Timber, who ran fourth, would
probably not go on to the Preakness either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a light horse,'' Baffert said. ``He came out of the Derby
pretty tired. He's telling me he needs more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does that leave Silverbulletday, the sensational filly who
won the Kentucky Oaks for her 10th victory in 11 starts?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll see how she draws next week, and then decide,'' Baffert
said from Churchill Downs. ``I don't want to run unless I think she
can win.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, he said, Silverbulletday would remain in
Louisville, Ky., until next Wednesday. He was keeping open the
possibility that he would enter her in the Black-Eyed Susan Stakes
for fillies, which is run the day before the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas, who won the Derby with his 31-1 former claimer,
Charismatic, said he would also wait until Wednesday to ship
Charismatic and Cat Thief (third) to Pimlico. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
