<HEADER>
A7714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELL-NASHVILLE07-COX     05-06 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-NASHVILLE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell moving some manufacturing to Nashville
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ With its eye on making speedier deliveries to
East Coast customers, Dell Computer Corp. is transferring all
production of its consumer and small business computers to
Nashville, Tenn., beginning this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The move into Nashville with a regional campus is Dell's first
U.S. expansion outside of Central Texas and a major strategy shift
designed to increase the company's share of the consumer PC market
_ a segment it only got serious about within the past three years.
Dell is expected to spend some $200 million on office and
manufacturing space in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   At an announcement in Tennessee's state Capitol on Thursday
morning, Dell officials said they immediately will begin hiring the
first of at least 600 assembly and 400 technical-support workers it
expects to employ in Tennessee by year end. The company said the
number may grow to 3,000 over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   But executives at the Round Rock-based company were quick to
point out that transfer of the operations wouldn't have a major
impact in North Austin, where its Dimension PCs aimed at consumers
and small businesses are made now. The estimated 3,000 workers
involved in assembly, technical support and service of the
Dimension will be offered training for new positions in the Austin
area, said spokesman Peter Scacco.
</P>
<P>
   The Dimension assembly operations in North Austin will be
converted to manufacture other products, such as Dell's two
notebook lines and its OptiPlex PC for corporate customers, Scacco
said.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 18,000 workers in Central Texas, Dell is the
region's largest private employer.
</P>
<P>
   In Nashville, Dell Vice Chairman Kevin Rollins estimated that
about 15 Dell executives and managers who are intimately familiar
with Dimension production will be asked to move to Tennessee. The
remaining jobs will be filled locally.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its strong work force, a quality of life similar
to Austin's and at least $40 million in government incentives,
Nashville was attractive because its location allows Dell to ship
computers within a day to the Eastern half of United States, where
the majority of the country's population lives, said Paul Bell,
Dell's senior executive for the home and small business group.
</P>
<P>
   With a Federal Express hub in nearby Memphis and a UPS hub in
Louisville, Ky., Dell will be able to manufacture Dimension PCs
later in the day and still guarantee overnight delivery, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our entire business model is about taking hours out,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Customer service is key to Dell's goal of being the No. 1
supplier to consumers and small business, segments that grew more
than 50 percent last year for Dell, Rollins said.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement that wasn't completed until Thursday
afternoon, Dell will get $20 million in property tax exemptions for
40 years and other incentives from Nashville and surrounding
Davidson County.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which still has to be approved by Nashville's
44-member Metro Council, calls for the joint city-county government
to give Dell free use of up to 700 acres of land next to Nashville
International Airport and to demolish a dozen aging structures on
one parcel that once housed the region's mental health hospital.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the state of Tennessee has pledged about $20
million for road, sewer and other such improvements and for
training area workers for Dell jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins said Dell hopes the first Dimension will roll off the
assembly line by August from a nearly completed building east of
Nashville. That structure, which developers started without knowing
who their tenant would be, will house Dimension manufacturing
operations even while Dell moves into its first buildings on the
former hospital grounds early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Briefing officials of Nashville's Metro Council Thursday
afternoon, Mayor Phil Bredesen said Dell's expansion ``represents a
minimum'' of 3,000 jobs in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it works, well it could be many times that,'' he said in
answer to one of several questions from the curious but generally
supportive council.
</P>
<P>
   And while he declined to comment on speculation that Dell might
grow to 10,000 employees here, Rollins voiced confidence in the
company's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at our trajectories and our growth rate, you're
going to see that we are going to need a lot of people and a lot of
help,'' Rollins said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
