</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALIAN-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DYNAMIC WILLIAMS SISTERS ROLL ALONG AT ITALIAN OPEN 
 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The scene is the same this spring at the Foro Italico _
the clay just as red, the cypresses just as green _ but the women's
roles are changing. The Williams sisters are walking tall and
making big strides, and the vast majority of their competitors are
not keeping up.
</P>
<P>
   Together, which is the way they still prefer to be, Venus and
her younger sibling, Serena, have already combined to win five
singles titles this year: three for Venus and two for Serena.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday at the Italian Open, against opponents who once
gave them trouble, the sisters took turns underscoring their
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Serena was the first Williams to make her point by defeating
Irina Spirlea, 6-2, 6-3. Then, with Serena watching from the
stands, Venus handled Anna Kournikova, 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier match, second-seeded Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario, now
underpowered and still searching for good form after a hand injury,
was upset in straight sets by Sylvia Plischke of Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Spirlea, a tall, straight-talking Romanian, exchanged a chest
bump and harsh words with Venus at the 1997 U.S. Open. The tension
between her and America's first tennis family has since dissipated,
but at last year's U. S. Open, Spirlea put an end to Serena's
tournament when she defeated her in the third round in three sets.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Serena won her first tour event in Paris and then
won again at Indian Wells in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's not giving you anymore the chance,'' Spirlea
said. ``She's not missing as much as she was missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena, ranked 10th, is also creeping inside the baseline with
increasing regularity, hitting her ground strokes and service
returns earlier and getting into the net with some frequency on a
surface that is not always forgiving of net-rushers. Her body
language is different, too; her movement during and between points
is more economical and cocksure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the thing that has really moved up is my mental,'' she
said. ``I know how to work the game more and play points better.
It's just something that's grown. At the U.S. Open, I hadn't won a
tournament, but now I know what to do playing people like her in
her game.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus already knew what to do against Kournikova when they first
played in the final in Key Biscayne, Fla., last year. She won in
three sets, but at the time, it was uncertain which of the
teen-agers was heading to the top the fastest.
</P>
<P>
   With Williams at a career-high No. 5 in this week's ranking and
Kournikova, who has yet to win a tour event, at No. 13, the sport
now has the answer. And though Kournikova has split with coach
Pavel Slozil and stopped double-faulting at an embarrassing clip,
she could not find a way to keep Venus from firing service winners
and pulling her uncomfortably wide with big ground strokes.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's quarterfinals, Serena should have the trickier test.
While Venus will face 11th-seeded Dominique Van Roost, Serena will
face No. 1 Martina Hingis, the only player not named Williams who
has won more tournaments than Serena this year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that meant Hingis, Venus and Serena were now the
world's top three, Serena did not hesitate. ``Definitely,'' she
said. ``Of course. The statistics show it. It's just a fact for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the WTA computer does not yet reflect it, Hingis concurs,
and now she wants revenge for her 6-4, 7-6 loss to Serena in the
semifinals last month in Key Biscayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is this is on clay, and I'm a more confident
player, and I take her more seriously than last time,'' Hingis said
Thursday night after her straight-set defeat of Corina Morariu.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was kind of cocky on the court, and that kind of ticked me
off in a way. But this time, it's going to be different.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
